<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-16 00:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1857 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-ASTROS-BAGWELL-HN     03-16 0841
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ASTROS-BAGWELL-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Time News Service clients)  
 By JOSEPH DUARTE  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
KISSIMMEE, Fla. _ Considering what time o year it is, Jeff Bagwell
has been noticeably quiet.
<TEXT>
<P>
   His bat has been doing all the talking instead.
</P>
<P>
   Spring training is generally the worst six weeks of the year for
Bagwell, a habitually slow starter who annually proclaims himself
``the worst player in camp.'' But through the early portion of this
season's exhibition schedule, he would have trouble selling that
story.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's on hold. Don't count me out yet,'' said Bagwell, who hit
a two-run homer Monday against the Los Angeles Dodgers to raise his
spring batting average to .500. ``It's still early.''
</P>
<P>
   Just why is Bagwell putting up numbers normally reserved for the
year's hotter months?
</P>
<P>
   Bagwell, set to turn 31 in May, said maturity has given him a
better understanding of hitting. The added experience, a lack of
consistency last season and the realization that his crouching,
wide-open, hands-low trademark batting stance is, well, difficult,
led him to the idea of slightly altering his swing.
</P>
<P>
   As the regular season draws nearer, he says it's still a work in
progress.
</P>
<P>
   ``I worked a lot harder than I have in a long time at my swing _
not that I didn't work hard before, but I never tried to make a
change, try and do something a little different,'' Bagwell said.
``So I put more time into it. Maybe that's part of the reason (it's
working). Another part is maturity. I'm getting a little older, so
hopefully I understand how to hit a little better each year.''
</P>
<P>
   The stance has been slightly modified, but it remains vintage
Bagwell.
</P>
<P>
   He still squats low in a crouch and holds the bat straight up.
The difference is in the location of his hands, which are now held
at about shoulder level rather than around his belt.
</P>
<P>
   But he is still sending baseballs over fences. To wit: his
crushing opposite-field blast off Darren Dreifort during the third
inning Monday, his second homer of the spring. In six spring games,
Bagwell leads the Astros in average, home runs and RBIs (seven). He
has yet to strike out.
</P>
<P>
   Bagwell said the change is something he talked about with
hitting instructor Tom McCraw and decided to implement during the
offseason.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anybody that looks at my swing knows it's difficult,'' Bagwell
said. ``Most people stride forward, and their hands go back. I
stride backward, and my hands go down. I understand my swing. I
understand what you're supposed to do when you hit. As I'm getting
older, it's harder and harder to have that same quickness and being
able to get your bat from around your belt up into a hitting
position. The only way to fix that is try and fix your hands a
little bit.''
</P>
<P>
   Few would suggest Bagwell needed to tinker with anything after
finishing 1998 with a .304 batting average, 34 home runs and 111
RBIs. But being a perfectionist, Bagwell saw reason to work harder.
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea is for me to become a better hitter,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   More than anything, Bagwell's emphasis is on consistency. Last
season, the first baseman got off to one of the slowest starts of
his career, hitting .236 with only seven home runs during the first
two months of the season. He rebounded to hit .337 in June but
dipped to .240 in July before ending the season on a tear.
</P>
<P>
   ``He didn't panic when things weren't going well,'' McCraw said.
``He stayed after it. He's not allergic to work. He realized that
was going to get him out of it, and he worked his behind off.''
</P>
<P>
   During the early part of spring training, Bagwell went high-tech
in his crusade to make an adjustment. Second baseman Craig Biggio
filmed Bagwell hitting against live pitching in the batting cage
and during soft-toss. Bagwell then viewed the tape carefully to
pinpoint any adjustments that needed to be made.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing that did for me was it showed me I can do what I set
out to do,'' Bagwell said. ``I can control my hands a little bit,
try and keep them above my belt. That gives me confidence that the
things I'm doing are going to help me succeed. That's the reason
I'm taking so much extra soft-toss. I've never taken soft-toss in
my life. I need that muscle memory.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Biggio: ``Basically, you want to be swinging the bat well
and get your swing right in the last week of (camp). As long as
you're making solid contact and hitting the ball, the last week is
when you want to be finding your groove and fine-tuning things for
the season.''
</P>
<P>
   The loss of outfielder Moises Alou to a torn anterior cruciate
ligament and the resultant pressure to carry a greater load
offensively played no role in his change, Bagwell said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously we're going to have to step it up a little bit,'' he
said. ``I'm doing this for no other reason than my sanity. I'm sure
there are a lot of people that would love to have the problems I
have. That's not good enough for me. I'm always trying to get
better.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether the calendar reads February or July.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
