<HEADLINE>
AFRICANIZED BEES FOUND IN SAN FERNANDO VALLEY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY DAVE McNARY  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The killer bees are here.
</P>
<P>
   The discovery of a swarm of Africanized honeybees in an oak tree
in Calabasas west of Los Angeles makes it official: The San
Fernando Valley is now officially colonized by the killer bees, Los
Angeles County agriculture officials said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement means that 40 percent of Los Angeles County _
1,668 miles _ is now colonized by the fierce hybrid bee responsible
for five deaths in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Agriculture Commissioner Cato Fiksdal said there is no cause for
alarm.
</P>
<P>
   ``Individual bees are not a problem,'' he said. ``It's only the
hive. They only attack when they've established a hive and you
disturb their home.''
</P>
<P>
   Officials said the best defense when attacked by a swarm of
killer bees is a good set of legs. Cover your head, mouth and eyes
and run to the nearest enclosed area where the bees can be locked
out. If there is no cover, be prepared to run for up to a
quarter-mile before the killer bees relent.
</P>
<P>
   African honeybees escaped from a Brazilian agriculture research
station in 1957 and began breeding with more docile European
honeybees. The result: Africanized honeybees, a fierce hybrid that
aggressively defends its territory and spawns new colonies at up to
four times the rate of its European cousins.
</P>
<P>
   The bees were discovered in the south Los Angeles community of
Lawndale on Nov. 28. Since then, agriculture officials have tracked
their rapid advance across the county. Their arrival in the San
Fernando Valley was expected.
</P>
<P>
   On March 5, a gardener found a swarm of bees in an oak tree in
Calabasas and called the Los Angeles County West Vector Control
District. A DNA test confirmed the colony was Africanized
honeybees.
</P>
<P>
   The discovery added an additional 658 miles to the areas of the
county already colonized by killer bees. Fiksdal said he made an
official announcement Monday ``to put residents on a little bit of
heightened awareness.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
