<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-BUCKS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KNICKS DEFEAT BUCKS, 108-102 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By SELINA ROBERTS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MILWAUKEE _ Latrell Sprewell is the new guy. He doesn't have
enough history with Jeff Van Gundy to pour out his soul for his
coach nor enough time with his teammates to understand their bond
with him.
</P>
<P>
   But Sprewell knew the New York Knicks needed this game on Monday
night. They needed it to feel better about themselves after their
image was smeared by a debacle in Chicago on Friday and to rid
themselves of a five-game losing streak on the road.
</P>
<P>
   So Sprewell had the solution. He treated this like a home game.
He woke up in his hometown on Monday and felt comfortable in his
surroundings. Setting out on his smoothest performance yet, he
found partners for his jitterbug style as the Knicks followed his
season-high 28-point lead on their way to a 108-102 victory over
the Milwaukee Bucks at the Bradley Center.
</P>
<P>
   ``Spree got to sleep in his own bed; that's what it was,'' Chris
Childs said. ``I just want to know when he's going to invite us to
his house to eat.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever home cooking Sprewell received, it was nourishment for
the whole team. He finally looked to be fitting in.
</P>
<P>
   ``We came out with the mental intensity, the drive and fire,''
said Larry Johnson, who scored 21 points and hit two clinching free
throws. ``It's something to build on. To be honest, it was the
Chicago game that pushed us. We understand that if we don't come
ready to play what can happen.''
</P>
<P>
   The aftermath of the Knicks' franchise-low effort in Chicago
included a televised report that Van Gundy's job was on the line.
But Van Gundy did not seem the slightest bit ruffled, worn or
sleep-deprived from his long Sunday. He had weathered another
unstable day in a market titillated by the drama of a coach's head
on the line.
</P>
<P>
   The same coach who had struggled to motivate his players on the
road looked on as the inspired Knicks responded. There would be no
giving in, giving out or giving up the loose ball. Allan Houston
took to driving toward the basket and found 22 points. Chris Dudley
took over the paint and grabbed 11 rebounds and came up with a tap
or two to keep the ball alive for the Knicks (13-9) as the Bucks
(12-8) were drawing close in the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks led, 84-73, at the end of the third quarter. But then
Ray Allen began to take charge and barge through the Knicks'
interior defense, drawing fouls and picking up points. With Allen
leading a 6-0 run, the Knicks' lead was just 84-79 with 9 minutes
56 seconds left in the game. A couple of forceful moves by Houston
and Sprewell, and the Knicks built a 10-point lead again with six
minutes left.
</P>
<P>
   The road issues were behind Van Gundy for a night, and so was
any talk of his imminent doom. It did not matter whether the Knicks
had issued Van Gundy an ultimatum of win or else before the team
played Charlotte on Sunday night. Although team executives
vehemently denied that the report, which was on NBC, had any basis,
the story was out there. And when a coach is coming off the shame
of losing in franchise-low fashion to the dismantled Chicago Bulls,
once the speculation is dangled, it might as well be true.
</P>
<P>
   But on Monday, Van Gundy was still on the job. Those close to
him, however, wondered privately if there will come a time when he
grows weary of the market and the Knicks' corporate team structure
and decides to depart on his own terms.
</P>
<P>
   This is not a decision Van Gundy is said to be contemplating
now. But he does wonder about the perils of working in New York.
Only there, after three years as the head coach, can a horrific
loss on Friday and an 11-9 record entering Sunday's game become
fodder for his firing. Is it worth it to coach in New York?
</P>
<P>
   ``You know what, that's a great question,'' Van Gundy said
before Monday tonight's game. ``I've thought about that. But you
know what, in some ways, you can always point out the bad in a big
market, in the New York market. Scrutiny is going to be there. But
there are so many more good things about it. I do believe I was
given a lot of credit the last three years. If I'm going to accept
that, then I have to accept the criticism when it's not going as
well. I deserved that and the team deserved criticism after that
Chicago game, and rightfully so. Now, you could then ask yourself
whether that meant my job should be on the line.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
