<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LA-VALLEY-SECEDE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CITYHOOD STUDY A GO FOR L.A.'S SAN FERNANDO VALLEY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY MICHAEL COIT and DEBORAH SULLIVAN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The San Fernando Valley cityhood push reached a
major milestone when election officials certified petitions calling
for an unprecedented study of breaking up Los Angeles and creating
an independent Valley city.
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles County officials reported Monday that Valley Voters
Organized Toward Empowerment's signature tally topped the required
25 percent of registered Valley voters by just 719 votes. Valley
VOTE turned in 202,514 signatures and needed 131,771 to be valid,
said county Registrar-Recorder Conny McCormack.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement marks a critical victory for the group that has
gotten state laws changed and overcome other obstacles to get the
Local Agency Formation Commission to conduct the study that could
lead to a citywide vote by November 2000 at the earliest.
</P>
<P>
   Many obstacles remain, particularly whether the city, county and
state will fund the $1.8 million to $2.6 million study to determine
how secession would work and what the assets and liabilities would
be of a Valley city, potentially the nation's sixth-largest with
1.3 million residents.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was probably the hardest part. Certainly the vote is
going to be difficult too, but this was monstrous,'' said Jeff
Brain, Valley VOTE president. ``To get 25 percent of the voting
public to sign a petition is incredible.''
</P>
<P>
   The group fell short in a sample count because of 24 duplicate
signatures that penalized it more than 25,000 under election rules.
It was still short when the full count was completed comparing
petition signatures with voter registration records. But a final
review validated enough signatures, although 15,807 duplicates were
found, McCormack said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We spent a tremendous amount of extra effort on it, as we do
whenever it's close. That's not unusual,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   County Supervisor Zev Yaroslavsky, chairman of the LAFCO
committee leading the study, said the signature drive's success
goes far beyond the work needed to place a regular initiative, or
even a state constitutional amendment, on the ballot.
</P>
<P>
   Yaroslavsky declined to speculate on the fate of secession, but
said the petition drive validates a widespread desire to bring the
distant workings of government to a neighborhood level.
</P>
<P>
   ``People want safer streets, they want control of parks, of
schools. People are looking for local control, and the secession
movement in the Valley is an answer to this legitimate goal.''
</P>
<P>
   Valley VOTE leaders took a moment to celebrate during the
group's board meeting Monday and then resumed planning for the
study of city finances and potential obstacles that remain.
</P>
<P>
   LAFCO still has to find the money to pay consultants to complete
the study. Valley VOTE and city representatives are expected to
contest many issues used to determine the impact of secession.
</P>
<P>
   ``The work has only just begun,'' said Richard Close, Valley
VOTE board chairman. ``We're going to work with LAFCO to make sure
that it's comprehensive and fair and to make sure the Valley gets
its fair share.''
</P>
<P>
   Now that the signatures have qualified, public officials are
bound to proceed seriously with the study, Yaroslavsky said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the dynamic changed as of this morning,'' he said.
``Everyone involved in this process has to step back and make this
process work. It would be folly for any of us, the city, county or
state, to surreptitiously or otherwise try to frustrate the public
will.''
</P>
<P>
   State law requires that the comprehensive analysis identify the
new city's costs of providing public services and facilities, and
its revenues during the three fiscal years following incorporation.
</P>
<P>
   The law grants the commission substantial powers in deciding how
to divide or transfer the city of Los Angeles' assets, bonded
indebtedness, resource rights and employees. The commission might
require that a new city raise additional tax revenues, issue bonds
and make lump-sum payments.
</P>
<P>
   LAFCO officials contend that state law gives little guidance.
They noted that municipal secession has not occurred in California
since Coronado split from San Diego nearly a century ago and said
there is no precedent for such a study.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's never been done before. Once we decide what process we
use, then we can go forward,'' said Larry Calemine, LAFCO's
executive officer.
</P>
<P>
   The agency first needs a formal application for detaching the
Valley from Los Angeles and incorporating it as a separate city.
Brain said the application will be submitted within a week by one
or more of Valley VOTE's three ``chief petitioners.''
</P>
<P>
   Yaroslavsky's committee, however, started preparing for the
study in February. When the committee meets again, likely in April,
it expects Valley VOTE to identify what information from the city
they want analyzed and reviewed.
</P>
<P>
   A critical goal for Yaroslavsky is to get as much cooperation
from the city as possible.
</P>
<P>
   ``A stonewalling strategy by any of us will result in
litigation, which may be inevitable anyway,'' he said. ``Maybe the
public will be best served by having a court, or the Supreme Court,
resolve this.''
</P>
<P>
   Yaroslavsky said any effort to withhold information also would
further exacerbate the frustrations that led to the secession drive
in the first place.
</P>
<P>
   ``The more resistance there is, the more it accelerates the
feeling of disenfranchisement that led to this,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   A majority of voters both in the Valley and the entire city
would have to vote in favor of secession.
</P>
<P>
   Despite widespread support in the Valley for a cityhood study,
Mayor Richard Riordan remains opposed to secession, said Jessica
Copen, the mayor's senior press deputy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Secession is not the answer. He believes the city can work
together, we can work with the Valley. He's very committed to that,
he feels passionate that the city should remain together,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Valley VOTE leaders remain optimistic that the study can be
completed within about a year, giving LAFCO an opportunity to place
the secession question on the November 2000 ballot.
</P>
<P>
   Calemine cautioned that it likely will take years. ``I think
it's beyond optimism to think it will be on the 2000 ballot.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
