<HEADER>
A1867 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-LOPEZ-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      03-16 0847
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-LOPEZ-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   John P.Lopez
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
PHOENIX _ Bob McNair suddenly is making NFL owners think twice.
</P>
<P>
   But NFL commissioner Paul Tagliabue continues to think only
about the West Coast aura, no doubt dreaming of
television-negotiation leverage that would be like a barefoot
frolic on the beach hand-in-hand with Rupert Murdoch.
</P>
<P>
   McNair continues to chug forward purposefully and deliberately.
</P>
<P>
   But Tagliabue continues to be wooed by the bright lights and
mega-market value of Los Angeles, bursting his double-breasted coat
with big plans.
</P>
<P>
   McNair continues to hope and impress. Tagliabue and his cronies
continue to try to quash those Houston hopes and move on.
</P>
<P>
   The expansion drama continued Monday, with Tagliabue and a
strong contingent of NFL leaders and owners trying to take that
drama to Hollywood.
</P>
<P>
   But just as it seemed McNair met his Black Monday when Tagliabue
shot down Houston hopes during a news conference, a glimmer of
light later shined through when some owners refused to fall in line
with the commissioner.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're still alive,'' McNair said.
</P>
<P>
   But if Tagliabue keeps pushing _ and he should as the calls
arrive from Murdoch, the czar of the LA-based Fox network _ it
might be a stay of execution.
</P>
<P>
   When Tagliabue predicted after a noon meeting with the expansion
committee that a recommendation for expansion would be made by
Monday evening, the Houston bid seemed dead. Tagliabue also said
that, no, there would be no such ``win-win'' concession made for
McNair and Houston. There would be no guarantees of a future
franchise relocation to Houston.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our policy is to keep teams where they are,'' Tagliabue said.
``I think we would continue to adhere to that policy.''
</P>
<P>
   McNair and Steve Patterson, who also leads the Houston effort,
were numbed by the words.
</P>
<P>
   ``We pretty much knew what that recommendation was going to
be,'' McNair said. ``It was going to Los Angeles.''
</P>
<P>
   But shortly after, the owners gathered and debated. Many owners
fell in line with Tagliabue's cause despite the still-unsettled
ownership fight in LA and still-vague support from Los Angeles
civic leaders.
</P>
<P>
   Some owners defended McNair and the sure thing, including
Pittsburgh Steelers owner Dan Rooney, who previously was considered
an LA proponent but delivered a plea for Houston's cause.
</P>
<P>
   The day ended with questions, uncertainty and no recommendation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We weren't even close,'' said Carolina owner Jerry Richardson,
who co-chairs the expansion committee with New England's Bob Kraft.
``We were split as owners, and we were split on the committee. We
have a difficult situation. We have two good cities, but there's
only one team. We're looking for something that makes sense.''
</P>
<P>
   They should look to the future and look hard again at McNair's
win-win proposal.
</P>
<P>
   ``They found out there was a lot more support for Houston than
they thought,'' McNair said. ``If our support stays with us, it's
going to be difficult (for Los Angeles) to get the votes.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps a faction of the owners began to realize the potential
damaging consequences of being blinded by LA's glitz: Not only
could there not be a win-win result for the NFL, but it could be
lose-lose.
</P>
<P>
   Award the expansion franchise now to Los Angeles, and there
indeed would be a brilliant marketplace at the league's disposal.
But what if the obvious fears about Los Angeles are realized?
</P>
<P>
   What if the community reacts to the NFL the way it has in the
past, by going surfing or roller-blading and catching the final
score on the news? What if the public money never comes? What if
the stadium is consistently half-empty and that marvelous TV
audience is repeatedly blacked out?
</P>
<P>
   The NFL loses.
</P>
<P>
   The second loss might be even more damaging. Award the expansion
franchise now to Los Angeles without some sort of promise to
relocate an existing team to Houston _ the win-win idea _ and the
Houston market would be gutted.
</P>
<P>
   McNair's stadium would not be built. McNair, a popular man among
NFL owners, would move on. The $195 million allocated by the city
and county would be used to refurbish the Astrodome and for other
projects, making Houston an undesirable NFL destination for years
to come.
</P>
<P>
   Tagliabue clearly has strung McNair and Houston along for
months, probably only to establish a lucrative standard for LA's
franchise fee. While McNair has done everything asked of him,
Tagliabue and those behind him have been as disingenuous as the
city of angels to which they have sold their votes.
</P>
<P>
   This fight is reeking of Holyfield-Lewis. Only in Tagliabue's
America.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've put a lot of trust in (Tagliabue),'' McNair said. ``I'll
be very disappointed if we don't get some sort of positive
message.''
</P>
<P>
   There is at least one more day to wait and ponder. The owners no
doubt should ponder hard, too.
</P>
<P>
   After all, an expansion team in Los Angeles might be a lot of
things, but it probably will not be Tagliabue's much-hoped-for day
at the beach.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
