<SLUG> BC-FBN-MEETINGS-SUPER-BOWL-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUPER BOWL PROMISED IF STADIUM BUILT  
 NFL DENIES PLEDGE MEANT TO INFLUENCE VOTE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE SCHOENFELD  
 and ROBBIE SHERWOOD  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - If the Rio Salado Crossing stadium project is built,
the Super Bowl will come.
</P>
<P>
   The NFL owners voted unanimously Monday to award Mesa a Super
Bowl in 2004, 2005 or 2006 if voters in Mesa, Gilbert and Queen
Creek approve the $497 million stadium and convention center
project.
</P>
<P>
   Mesa's sales tax would go up a quarter-cent to help pay for the
facility, but backers are promising $1.3 billion in private
investment in the project and a yearly $1.6 billion boost to the
local economy. Now the NFL is promising the Super Bowl, which
supporters say could bring at least $300 million.
</P>
<P>
   Some might consider the league's action as an attempt to
influence the May 18 election, but Jim Steeg, NFL vice president of
special events, said, ``This is not an ultimatum.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an offer. The (proposed) facility is so good, we want to
play a Super Bowl there.''
</P>
<P>
   The last time the league got involved in Arizona politics,
voters rejected a Martin Luther King Jr. holiday referendum in
November 1990 after the league hinted that the 1993 Super Bowl
would be pulled from the Valley if the holiday were defeated.
</P>
<P>
   Voters passed the King holiday in 1992, and Super Bowl XXX was
played in the Valley in January 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think this is pressure on the voters,'' said Cardinals
owner Bill Bidwill, whose team would play in the proposed stadium.
``They're voting on an entire package. This is just part of it.''
</P>
<P>
   NFL Commissioner Paul Tagliabue said the Super Bowl awarded by
the owners on Monday likely will be ``the first of many'' if the
Rio Salado Crossing is built.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd expect to be in the (Super Bowl) rotation,'' Mesa Mayor
Wayne Brown said. ``We'd expect to have one every five or six
years.''
</P>
<P>
   Pittsburgh Steelers owner Dan Rooney, whose team played Dallas
in the 1996 Super Bowl, said there was no opposition to the
proposal to bring a conditional game in 2004, 2005 or 2006 to Rio
Salado Crossing.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a great time here,'' Rooney said. ``I couldn't say
enough good things about it. It was perfect for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Cardinals Vice President Michael Bidwill, spearheading the
stadium drive for the team, described the league's action as a
``huge economic carrot.''
</P>
<P>
   A study by the Arizona State Business School for the Arizona
Department of Commerice found that hosting the 1996 Super Bowl
provided a $306 million economic boost for the Valley.
</P>
<P>
   ``Presumably, it'll be higher than that the next time,'' Michael
Bidwill said.
</P>
<P>
   Vince Fantozzi, a member of both citizens groups dedicated to
defeating the project, used Michael Bidwill's dangling carrot
analogy, but with a different spin. If voters approve the project,
Fantozzi said his neighborhood south of the site will be ruined by
traffic while taxpayers subsidize a wealthy, privately owned
football team.
</P>
<P>
   ``This further cements the idea that this election is being
bought by the Cardinals and the NFL,'' Fantozzi said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Cardinals are already paying for the (pro-stadium)
campaign, so they are just dangling another big carrot with the
Super Bowl. It's old-fashioned politics at work.''
</P>
<P>
   Tagliabue said the only reason the league hasn't awarded the
Valley a Super Bowl since the 1996 game is because of problems with
Sun Devil Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   The team bid for the 2000 and 2001 Super Bowls at Sun Devil
Stadium, but the games were awarded to Atlanta and Tampa.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we did the play the game here, it was outstanding,''
Tagliabue said. ``We've said many times the community-based events
were precedent-setting. It was the venue that was outmoded.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sun Devil Stadium is a good college stadium. It's not up to
the standards our members expect for a Super Bowl going into the
next decade. The new stadium is. The bar has been set higher and
higher. We know what our fans expect from a Super Bowl, and this
new facility here will have it.''
</P>
<P>
   NFL officials have frequently said the problems with Sun Devil
Stadium as a Super Bowl site include power capacity at the stadium;
access to the locker rooms; and concession and locker room
facilities.
</P>
<P>
   League spokesman Joe Browne said the owners didn't specify the
year Mesa would get the game to give the league flexibility and
because of considerations to other cities.
</P>
<P>
   Detroit has been promised a Super Bowl after voters approved a
downtown stadium, which won't be completed until at least 2002.
</P>
<P>
   Quentin Smith, vice chairman of the Valley's Super Bowl
Committee, said the league also wasn't specific about the Super
Bowl date because of ``maximum flexibility with the construction
process.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether he preferred to have a Super Bowl in 2004, 2005 or
2006 in Mesa, Bill Bidwill said, ``I'll take any of them.''
</P>
<P>
   However, project backers are focusing campaign efforts on
highlighting the 650-acre project's other aspects, chiefly the
convention center, parks, golf courses and public spaces, said Brad
Wright, executive director of the Yes! on Rio Salado Crossing
political action committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's great, but we are still much more excited about the 240
to 260 days a year that we will use the facility for things other
than football,'' Wright said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
