<SLUG> BC-CAR-PRIX-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GRAND PRIX COURSE COMES TO PASS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By STEVE IRVINE  
 c.1999 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONG BEACH, Calif. _ The Toyota Grand Prix of Long Beach turns
25 next month and to celebrate, the organizers have given the race
course a face-lift. For the first time since 1992, the course will
take on a new look that organizers hope will make the April 18
event the most exciting yet.
</P>
<P>
   Dario Franchitti, last year's runner-up to Alex Zanardi, took a
break from his preparations for the start of the CART season opener
this weekend in Miami, to come to Long Beach and test the new
configuration. He came away impressed after taking a slow-speed
tour _ for him _ at the wheel of the Toyota pace car.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has a better flow to it,'' said Franchitti, who arrived
Sunday night and left town a couple of hours after his drive.
``Hopefully, there's more passing and certainly there's more
character. I think it's a very positive change.''
</P>
<P>
   The course begins with the Shoreline Drive straightaway as
before, but now the drivers will take a left at the conclusion of
the straight instead of the traditional right turn.
</P>
<P>
   ``Turn 1 is definitely a passing zone,'' Franchitti said.
</P>
<P>
   The drivers then circle the Dolphin Fountain in front of the
Aquarium of the Pacific and the adjacent parking structure before
rejoining Shoreline Drive for a short time. After a left turn at
the previous Turn 1, the remainder of the track will be almost the
same.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had to work closely with many city entities to decide what
the most challenging, exciting and safest course would be for
all,'' said Chris Pook, president and CEO for the Grand Prix
Association of Long Beach.
</P>
<P>
   There is plenty of work left to be done before race weekend
begins on April 16. By the time the 11-turn, 1.85 mile course is
complete, there will be 1,800 concrete blocks, each weighing 8,100
pounds and measuring 12 feet in length, plus 250 tire crash
barriers. Not to mention 21 spectator grandstands, 12
television/photo towers, eight vision boards and 61 viewing suites.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we're finished, we will have built a city within a
city,'' said Dwight Tanaka, vice president of operations for the
Grand Prix Association.
</P>
<P>
   Franchitti said he hopes there's one thing that doesn't change.
</P>
<P>
   ``The stands were alive when we finished the race and were going
around (last year),'' Franchitti said. ``I could hear them cheering
(while) in the car, which is very unusual. The fans were just
incredible. I thought, `I like this.' ''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-16-99 0036EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
