<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-16 00:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1870 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-ROCKETS-HNS &LR;      03-16 0911
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-ROCKETS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JONATHAN FEIGEN  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
The 40-point loss didn't really happen, or at least it didn't
matter. The Rockets have dismissed the disaster in Portland as an
anomaly, the inevitable result of back-to-back games mixed with
travel problems and a rested opponent on a roll.
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``That was a situation where we had a lot of problems with the
flight,'' forward Charles Barkley said. ``We didn't have a
chance.''
</P>
<P>
   That game nine days ago, at least its blowout score, was labeled
a fluke. Tonight, the Rockets get a chance to prove it. The Trail
Blazers come to Houston for the second of back-to-back road games,
though traveling only from Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   If the Rockets' 111-71 crash was the result of mitigating
circumstances, most of them have changed. New circumstances and
problems, however, have cropped up in their place, starting with
Scottie Pippen's public disclosure of his frustrations with the
Rockets' offense.
</P>
<P>
   The Rockets insist they are not as poor a team as they appeared
March 7 in Portland. But Pippen left little question that he
believes there are real problems with the team's offense.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Rudy Tomjanovich would not publicly discuss Pippen's
complaints but said they would be addressed.
</P>
<P>
   ``The main thing I would say is I'm going to do my work in the
locker room,'' Tomjanovich said. ``That's just my way. I'm not
going to publicly debate the things that have to be ironed out.''
</P>
<P>
   He did say, however, that the problems could be solved.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll always be confident unless guys give up,'' Tomjanovich
said.
</P>
<P>
   All season long, Pippen has described himself as frustrated. He
said Sunday that considering his role in the offense, he didn't
know why the Rockets even wanted him.
</P>
<P>
   But even before Pippen made his frustration public, Tomjanovich
warned that teams could not let 1999's grueling, rushed schedule
cloud their perspective.
</P>
<P>
   ``Understanding what a different deal this year is is
important,'' Tomjanovich said. ``The regular season is tough. You
cram all these things together, the extra game a week and travel,
and you've got to be mentally tough to keep a positive attitude and
not say this team is 40 points better than us.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we have veterans that will get that message across.''
</P>
<P>
   The message the Rockets seem most intent on delivering is that
the 111-71 final was misleading and that they are a better team
since then anyway.
</P>
<P>
   ``I personally don't put a lot of stock in our last game
(against Portland) because of what happened with our travel,'' said
forward Matt Bullard, referring to an overnight delay in Vancouver.
``With the plane broken down, we had to stay in Vancouver an extra
night. Nobody got any sleep. If we would have beaten them out
there, it would have been quite an accomplishment to overcome all
those situations.
</P>
<P>
   ``This game will be a more accurate test. I think it will be
more indicative of what our team is like. I guess it could be a
measuring stick, not because of the way last game was but just
where we are now.''
</P>
<P>
   Although they come in off a loss in Phoenix in which Tomjanovich
said they were ``out-energied'' down the stretch, the Rockets used
last week's three home games and two practices to shore up areas
that had been shortcomings.
</P>
<P>
   ``It helped,'' Tomjanovich said. ``This thing is like the guy at
the dike. You fix this (hole), and all of a sudden there's another
one there. As a coach, that's how you live your life during the
year.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rockets' problems have not come in torrents. But the time at
home allowed them to address problems large (turnovers and
free-throw shooting) and small (sideline inbounds plays and
pick-and-roll defensive support).
</P>
<P>
   ``Any time you get to spend a few days in the gym together,
review things, watch video, it helps,'' guard Brent Price said.
``It wasn't like we went at it two hours full-speed. We went short.
But we had certain things we wanted to work on. From a learning
standpoint, it was very valuable.''
</P>
<P>
   But while the Rockets made those improvements and beat each of
the teams to come into Compaq Center, none could be considered an
especially difficult test. They have beaten just two teams with
winning records: the Suns on Feb. 16 and the SuperSonics on Feb.
23. And other than Utah, nobody has a better record than Portland's
17-4.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a test for us,'' Rockets forward Othella Harrington said.
``They do have a good team. They have great starters and great
backups. They are one of the top teams in the West and in the
league.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not more meaningful because of the loss. We did lose by
40 points, but a loss is a loss. But playing them again, we want to
have a better showing than last time.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rockets have enough reasons to need a better performance
without having to reconsider the night in Portland. Pippen's
dissatisfaction is only the most recent sore, or even open wound, a
victory can heal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think the way we lost has any effect on the game and
playing them again,'' Price said. ``We're a much better team than
we showed. A lot had to do with our schedule. There's no question
we were fatigued and road-weary, and it showed. There's no question
we look forward to playing them on our court and in a fresh
setting. We'll have a day off. But I don't think the blowout puts
any extra eagerness to the game.''
</P>
<P>
   There's enough eagerness there already.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-16-99 0036EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
