<HEADER>
A1871 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOX-HERSKOWITZ-COLUMN     03-16 0496
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-HERSKOWITZ-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MickeyHerskowitz
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
For the first time in quite a while, I really, really missed Howard
Cosell this week. I find myself mentally reaching for the earplugs,
trying to imagine how the man who considered himself the conscience
of sport would have reacted to the latest atrocity in boxing.
</P>
<P>
   True, Jim Lampley fairly well summed up the mood of those at the
scene, and those who paid to watch at home, when he denounced the
decision that gave Evander Holyfield a draw with Lennox Lewis on
Saturday as ``fraudulent.'' His reference to boxing as a
``cesspool'' was a nice touch of color, as well.
</P>
<P>
   Manny Steward, the trainer for the British import, even went a
step beyond that judgment. ``It looked,'' he said, in a hopeless
tone of voice, ``as if (the outcome) was rigged.''
</P>
<P>
   The only opinion that could have overshadowed those would have
been Cosell's, who used words like a dagger. At the least, Howard
would have thrown an entire thesaurus at them. He would have
labeled the verdict ``a sham of a mockery of a fraud'' and demanded
an investigation by Kenneth Starr or the FBI or the Supreme Court _
or, barring that, a Certified Public Accountant.
</P>
<P>
   Just when you think boxing can't sink any lower, the sport
plunges to another depth. It is down there now where only Jacques
Cousteau and Capt. Nemo dared to go.
</P>
<P>
   Some laughed, and some cheered, when Cosell walked away from the
microphone after Larry Holmes turned the face of Tex Cobb into
grade-A ground beef in a fiasco at the Astrodome. Howard never
called another fight, an action Cobb would later proudly claim as
``my gift to mankind.''
</P>
<P>
   So let us say this as delicately as we can. Evander Holyfield is
a fine fellow, who was driven by a sincere desire to prove himself
one of the great heavyweights of all time. But on Saturday night in
New York, he was beaten by Lennox Lewis, over 12 rounds, as
decisively as the loser of any title fight in memory. Lewis
dominated him, at times toyed with him, and in punches thrown and
landed held a more than 2-1 advantage.
</P>
<P>
   At the finish, there seemed little doubt Holyfield knew he lost
the fight. To the extent that his bruised and swollen face
permitted, his expression and his body language gave it away. He
put an arm lightly around Lewis' shoulder and congratulated him,
the act of a gentleman. Later, he would say that he couldn't
comment on the judges' cards ``because I was fighting it, not
scoring it. I gave my best, but it wasn't my best fight.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, one could hardly have expected even the decent and
usually straight-talking Holyfield to yelp, ``Hey, I can't accept
this decision. I got stomped. Who were the judges _ Ray Charles,
Jose Feliciano and Helen Keller?''
</P>
<P>
   But the pain, shock and disbelief of Lewis were unmistakable,
packed into two words you could not hear but clearly saw his lips
form: ``Oh, mann
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-16-99 0037EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990316.0011 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-16 00:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1872 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-WEST-TICKETS-AZR &LR;      03-16 0746
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-WEST-TICKETS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEST REGIONAL: THAT'S THE TICKET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By LES POLK  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - March Madness is coming to town this week.
</P>
<P>
   Will ticket madness follow?
</P>
<P>
   The NCAA West Regional at America West Arena featuring Gonzaga,
Florida, Connecticut and Iowa has been sold out since January. Word
among ticket brokers is that demand for tickets to the doubleheader
on Thursday and the regional championship Saturday is steady but
not spectacular.
</P>
<P>
   NCAA officials advise the best way to get tickets is through the
universities that reached the regional round.
</P>
<P>
   Each school must purchase 500 seats to the Thursday and Saturday
sessions and has the option of buying 750 more. If any of those are
returned, they would then be offered to the other schools, and only
if they aren't bought then would any more be available to the
general public.
</P>
<P>
   Iowa, with a large contingent of transplants, vacationers and
snowbirds in the Valley, could have the biggest local fan base.
</P>
<P>
   And at the Iowa Cafe in Mesa, excitement is building.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, you betcha it is,'' said Ruth Cavender, who runs the
restaurant with her sister, Shirley Woolums.
</P>
<P>
   Cavender, who ran a cafe in Mount Ayr, Iowa, for 35 years, would
like to go herself but doubts she will.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're so darned busy at this time of year I don't have time to
do anything else, but I'd like to,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Bernard Muir, a director of the NCAA men's tournament, said that
tickets in Phoenix had sold out quickly and that he expected teams
such as Iowa and Connecticut with long basketball traditions and
loyal fans to heighten demand.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's definitely going to be a tough ticket,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Muir said the NCAA did not condone fans buying tickets from
brokers. But brokers will have them available.
</P>
<P>
   The face value of a ticket to the three games _ two Thursday and
the regional championship Saturday _ is $90. They are originally
sold that way, as a three-game package.
</P>
<P>
   Brokers on Monday said prices ranged from $225-$275 for the
three-game package in the lower bowl at the arena to $125-$150 in
the upper deck.
</P>
<P>
   And they said that although there was a steady stream of callers
both buying and selling tickets, it was far from the hottest ticket
ever to hit town. It's not a Super Bowl, for example.
</P>
<P>
   But that could change, especially if enough fans can find their
way to Phoenix, a hot ticket itself in the month of March.
</P>
<P>
   Because it's spring break for many students in the Valley and
elsewhere in the Southwest, there could be a run on tickets from
people who just want to see an NCAA tournament in person and be a
part of the scene.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a huge interest, but it's a little tough to arrange,''
said Geno Bronchetti of All World Travel in Spokane, Wash., home of
Gonzaga (that's Gone-ZAG-uh), which plays Florida in Thursday's
first game.
</P>
<P>
   At Hawkeye World Travel in Iowa City, Iowa, Annette Reed agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a huge demand, but not much availability,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   And short-notice flights to Phoenix are averaging about $1,500
round-trip, she said.
</P>
<P>
   The regional is being run by Arizona State University, which is
the host school.
</P>
<P>
   Capacity for the event is being listed at 18,500, rather than
the usual 19,023 for basketball at America West Arena, because of
the large media contingent.
</P>
<P>
   And once tickets were distributed to the teams, the NCAA, CBS,
ESPN, the NCAA's corporate sponsors, officials and other working
parties, there wasn't a tremendous number left for the general
public.
</P>
<P>
   As the host school, ASU first offers tickets to Sun Devil
basketball season-ticket holders, said Tom Sadler, ASU assistant
athletic director and tournament manager at America West.
</P>
<P>
   ``The NCAA really wants to make sure that college basketball
fans are in attendance,'' Sadler said.
</P>
<P>
   America West Arena also received tickets for some of its
constituents, he said.
</P>
<P>
   If you can't track down those relatives in Iowa with tickets, or
if you're unfamiliar with the Phoenix ticket scene, scalping is
legal. Phoenix cordones off the downtown scalpers in a specific
area and has been regularly moving the location around.
</P>
<P>
   If you want to give it a shot, the current scalping area is on
the north side of Jackson Street between Third and Fourth streets.
</P>
<P>
   The price will depend on demand and supply _ and, of course, on
the level of Madness reaching the Valley.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
