<SLUG> BC-BKC-WEST-UCONN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FINAL FOUR FAITH  
 UCONN COACH KNOWS IT'LL HAPPEN _ SOMEDAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By KENT SOMERS  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Whenever a Connecticut basketball fan reminds him the
Huskies have never played in the NCAA Tournament's Final Four,
Coach Jim Calhoun has a pat answer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Someday,'' Calhoun says, ``we'll get Connecticut back to where
it used to be.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's always kind of a stopper to the question.''
</P>
<P>
   Thirteen years ago, Calhoun took over a Connecticut program that
hadn't been to the NCAA Tournament since the late 1970s and was
unknown to most people outside the Northeast.
</P>
<P>
   He has built it into a national power. Since 1989-90, the
Huskies have won 30 or more games four times, including this
season's 30-2 mark. They have won more games in the 1990s than all
but six other Division I teams.
</P>
<P>
   They are a No. 1 seed for the third time in the 1990s, and their
game Thursday against Iowa in the semifinals of the West Region at
America West Arena marks their seventh Sweet 16 appearance this
decade.
</P>
<P>
   All wonderful accomplishments. Still, the question that dogs
Calhoun and the Huskies is about what they haven't accomplished.
Calhoun handles the issue well, although he thinks it's unfair to
define his program by its lack of a Final Four appearance.
</P>
<P>
   ``The coach wants to go to a Final Four and win a national
championship, too,'' he said. ``If you look what we've done over
the past 13 years, we've done OK.''
</P>
<P>
   Things appear to be set up perfectly this season for UConn, the
No. 1 seed in the West Region of the tournament.
</P>
<P>
   To advance to the Final Four in St. Petersburg, Fla., all the
Huskies have to do is win Thursday over fifth-seeded Iowa and
Saturday over either 10th-seeded Gonzaga or sixth-seeded Florida in
the region finals.
</P>
<P>
   Calhoun knows there are inherent dangers in that logic. The
first two rounds of the tournament were filled with upsets.
</P>
<P>
   Of the top four seeds in the West, only UConn made it out of the
second round.
</P>
<P>
   ``You just have to make sure you don't have a poor or bad game,
or the other team doesn't throw an `A' game at you,'' Calhoun said.
``It's not much more complicated than that.''
</P>
<P>
   This is the sixth time since 1990 that Connecticut has been
seeded first or second. The Huskies have advanced to the region
finals three times with the first coming in 1990, when Duke's
Christian Laettner hit a jump shot with one second left to win it
for the Blue Devils.
</P>
<P>
   Duke is the overwhelming favorite to win this year's title, with
UConn perhaps having the best chance of upsetting the Blue Devils.
</P>
<P>
   Calhoun will have none of that, and he does his best to keep
Duke out of his players' minds.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference last week, point guard Khalid El-Amin was
asked whether the 22-point victory over New Mexico in the second
round was meant to send Duke a message.
</P>
<P>
   Before El-Amin could answer, Calhoun whispered a word of
caution. El-Amin then provided a stock response, saying the Huskies
weren't thinking of the Blue Devils at all.
</P>
<P>
   Connecticut's players have been constantly reminded of the
school's failure to get to the Final Four, but they seem unaffected
by it and by the pressure of being a No. 1 seed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we like being the No. 1 seed,'' El-Amin said. ``We
worked so hard all year to get it.''
</P>
<P>
   That the program's success is defined by making the Final Four
is testament to the job Calhoun had done in his 13 years. Before
arriving at Connecticut, Calhoun was successful at Northeastern
University in Boston, and he turned down a couple of offers before
accepting the Huskies' job.
</P>
<P>
   Indiana Coach Bobby Knight gave Calhoun some pointed advice when
the Connecticut job opened.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said, `If you don't take this one, I'll give you a really
good kick in the ass,' '' Calhoun said. ``One thing about Bob is
he's usually true to his word, and I didn't feel like a kick in the
ass. He knew that things were lined up (at UConn).''
</P>
<P>
   Calhoun initially struggled to recruit players to Connecticut,
but as the program improved, so did the quality of recruits. The
Huskies will go anywhere for players. Forward Richard Hamilton is
from Pennsylvania. El-Amin is from Minneapolis. Center Jake Voskuhl
is from Texas. Former Husky Brian Fair was from Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   By Calhoun's second year, the Huskies were playing in the NIT.
By his third season, they were a No. 1 seed in the NCAA tournament.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw a place that really loved basketball,'' he said. ``It's
gone from a good regional program to a national program. We've had
good players, and we're at a place that cares about basketball.
That helps.''
</P>
<P>
   Their problems this season, however small, were caused primarily
by injuries. Hamilton struggled through a thigh injury, and Voskuhl
was hampered by a sore left foot.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's pretty evident we went into a lull toward the end of the
season,'' Voskuhl said. ``We're starting to get our rhythm back.''
</P>
<P>
   They are healthy now and, like Duke, they are deep and talented.
Hamilton and El-Amin can not only score, but along with guard Ricky
Moore, can defend the perimeter as well as any trio in the country.
Voskuhl is an effective rebounder and defender, as is forward Kevin
Freeman.
</P>
<P>
   The Huskies love to use pressure defense and to play up-tempo.
The press makes it difficult for teams to get into their offensive
sets, and it forces turnovers. With El-Amin and Hamilton, UConn
usually converts those turnovers into points and impressive runs.
</P>
<P>
   In their past four games, the Huskies have enjoyed streaks in
which they've outscored opponents, 22-5, 13-0, 11-0, 20-7, 17-0 and
11-0. They've won each game by at least 19 points.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're on a mission,'' Hamilton said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, UConn is vulnerable. The Huskies were nearly upset by
Seton Hall in the Big East Tournament, and Calhoun has emphasized
to his team just how fragile tournament success is.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've said it all along,'' Calhoun said. ``We are good enough
to make a ride, and at 30-2, I think we have made a pretty good
ride already.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
