<HEADLINE>
PREGNANT PAUSE ISN'T IN CARDS YET FOR HURST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL HUFFMAN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Excuse Pat Hurst if her mind is not fully focused on
this week's Standard Register PING golf tournament at Moon Valley
Country Club. Distractions such as defending a major championship,
which Hurst will do next week at the Dinah Shore, can do that to
you.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, yes, there is one other. The Phoenix pro is six months
pregnant. She is one of three LPGA players who live in the Valley _
along with Barb Whitehead and Caroline McMillan _ who are expecting
their first child.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being pregnant really doesn't affect my swing that much,''
said Hurst, who has established herself over the past four years as
one of the better players in women's golf.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess, if anything, I have to pace myself a little bit more
because I tend to get tired. But mostly, it's the usual things you
would expect when you're pregnant: I go through cravings, and my
body reminds me of that. I definitely eat breakfast, lunch and
dinner now, whereas I never ate breakfast before.''
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, Hurst is taking pretty good care of herself and her
baby boy, Jackson Jeffrey, who is projected to arrive on June 28.
She has not missed a cut in six tournaments this season, with her
best effort being a tie for fifth in the Hawaiian Open.
</P>
<P>
   That Hurst has been so consistent is no surprise, really. Her
five-year career on the LPGA has been a steady growth process. It
began in 1995, when she captured Rookie of the Year honors, and was
cemented last year with a victory in the Dinah Shore. She has one
other victory _ the 1997 Oldsmobile Classic.
</P>
<P>
   Last year she finished eighth on the money list, finished fourth
at the U.S. Open, and helped fuel the U.S. team's victory in the
Solheim Cup with a 3-1 individual record.
</P>
<P>
   But what most people don't know about Hurst, whose earlier
accolades include two U.S. Golf Association titles and an NCAA
crown, is that from 1992 to '94, she actually gave up her childhood
dream of playing on the LPGA.
</P>
<P>
   ``I missed two years in a row at (LPGA Qualifying School), and I
decided to quit and take a job as a teaching pro at LaQuinta
(Calif.),'' said Hurst, 29.
</P>
<P>
   ``Believe it or not, I enjoyed teaching, and I didn't think
about playing (professionally), because I hadn't been enjoying golf
for a while. I had never taken a break from golf since I started
playing (at age 11). I just thought to myself, `Hey, it's OK to
take some time off.' ''
</P>
<P>
   To fully understand Hurst's sabbatical, it is important to go
back to her childhood. She spent nearly every day at a course
called Skywood near San Leandro, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   ``My dad passed away when I was 4, and my mom's boyfriend of 20
years, Frank _ I call him my `common-law stepdad' _ got me
interested in the game. I'd spend every day at the golf course
until my mom would pick me up in the evening.''
</P>
<P>
   There never was a doubt in Hurst's mind what she wanted to do
when she grew up.
</P>
<P>
   ``Playing professionally was my dream,'' she confessed. ``Every
time the LPGA came around to play in the San Jose Classic, my mom
would let me take the whole week off from school. I'd stay out
there all day long, and I loved it.''
</P>
<P>
   As a top junior player, Hurst captured the 1986 U.S. Junior
Championship. As an All-American at San Jose State, she added the
1989 NCAA and U.S. Women's Amateur Championships to her re sume.
</P>
<P>
   So it was somewhat, well, shocking that Hurst's career path took
a detour after two unsuccessful bids to get her LPGA card. Then
again, maybe not considering Hurst is known as gracious,
introspective woman by her peers.
</P>
<P>
   ``At times, I guess I'm mellow, but there are other times when
the game can get to you,'' Hurst conceded. ``I just always make it
a point to tell the other person `good shot' because that's what
I'd hope they would do towards me.''
</P>
<P>
   Which is not to say that Hurst is a mamby-pamby. Just ask her
husband, Jeff Heitt, who caddied for Hurst for three seasons before
they ended up at the altar.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's very competitive, like at the Solheim Cup last year,''
Heitt said. ``Some were comparing her to Dottie Pepper, but she
just doesn't wear it on the outside like Dottie does.''
</P>
<P>
   Heitt, who is the LPGA Tour representative for PING, said he
knows his wife is looking forward to the baby, ``but I think Pat
will really miss not playing.''
</P>
<P>
   ``She's planning on taking four months off (after the baby), and
that will be a long time for Pat,'' Heitt added.
</P>
<P>
   Hurst admits that juggling her career and motherhood will be
challenging, ``but fortunately the LPGA now has a great day-care
program.''
</P>
<P>
   Hurst said she plans to play until the Titleholders (May 6-9),
and will take maternity leave until sometime in September. But in
the meantime, there is her defense in the Dinah Shore to deal with.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't say I'm at a disadvantage (being pregnant),'' she
said of her chances in the first major of 1999. ``But I'm not
practicing as much. Sometimes that's a good thing. If you don't put
pressure on yourself, you tend to play better, at least I do.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
