<HEADLINE>
SABRES BEAT ISLANDERS, 2-1 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By TARIK EL-BASHIR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUFFALO, N.Y. _ Since Bill Stewart took over behind the New York
Islanders' bench nearly two months ago, an uninspiring performance
by his team had become so rare that it was difficult to remember a
time when it did not work hard in a game.
</P>
<P>
   Let Monday night's game against the Buffalo Sabres, a 2-1 loss,
serve as a refresher. One day after they were stung by an overtime
loss to the New York Rangers, the drained Islanders appeared to
avoid physical contact and rarely mustered an even-strength scoring
chance.
</P>
<P>
   The Islanders went down quietly to the Sabres before 18,105 fans
at Marine Midland Arena. The loss extended the Islanders' streak to
eight games without a victory (0-6-2), and it prompted Stewart to
conduct a 15-minute team meeting afterward.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's getting very discouraging,'' said Stewart, referring to
his team's inability to finish off good scoring chances around the
net. ``I'm getting a little annoyed. I'm very disappointed.''
</P>
<P>
   Zigmund Palffy, the Islanders' sniper, finished without a shot
on goal. His linemate Robert Reichel had four shots but could not
put the puck in the net, not even on a first-period breakaway.
</P>
<P>
   The Islanders fell behind by 2-0 on goals by Miroslav Satan in
the first and third periods. Bryan Smolinski scored late in the
game, and Wade Flaherty made 22 saves to keep the Islanders close.
But close was not enough to end the team's dry spell.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had our opportunities,'' Flaherty said. ``I made some big
saves but we didn't score enough goals.''
</P>
<P>
   Flaherty made his first start in the Islanders' net since Dec.
28. He was the Islanders' most consistent player, making several
important saves. Flaherty's counterpart, Dwayne Roloson, stopped 21
shots.
</P>
<P>
   In the first period on Monday night, the Islanders witnessed a
fight, something they had not seen since Feb. 4. Defenseman Eric
Cairns, whom the Islanders recently recalled, squared off with Paul
Kruse, whom the Islanders traded last season.
</P>
<P>
   The fight momentarily invigorated the Islanders, who were behind
by 1-0 because of a Cairns turnover on a Sabres power play. After
Cairns lost control of the puck in front of the Islanders' net, it
landed on the stick of Michael Peca, who made a cross-ice pass to
Satan. He buried the puck behind Flaherty, who was leaning the
wrong way.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we just started slow,'' said Trevor Linden, the
Islanders' captain. ``We came on there at the end. It's too bad we
couldn't score another goal or two.''
</P>
<P>
   Satan tallied his second goal of the game, and 31st of the
season, while his team was short-handed. It came at 7:40 of the
third period on a two-on-one rush. Thirty-one seconds later,
Smolinski banged in a rebound of Eric Brewer's shot from the point
on the same power play. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
