<HEADLINE>
LIONS AIM TO KEEP TURKEY DAY GAME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE SCHOENFELD  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Here's how serious the Detroit Lions are to keep their
annual Thanksgiving Day game:
</P>
<P>
   The chief executive officers of Ford, General Motors, Chrysler
and Kmart sent NFL owners a letter in which they strongly urged
them not to change a 65-year tradition.
</P>
<P>
   It helps the cause of the Lions and the Dallas Cowboys, the
other team that hosts a Thanksgiving Day game each season, that
those companies are among the league's biggest advertisers.
</P>
<P>
   The issue of rotating the Thanksgiving Day game among all
franchises is expected to be discussed today at the NFL meetings.
</P>
<P>
   Lions Vice Chairman Bill Ford Jr. is hopeful that the issue will
come to a vote.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't want to do this year after year,'' Ford said. ``It's
becoming an annual event.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, Kansas City Chiefs owner Lamar Hunt proposed the
Thanksgiving games rotate, maintaining the Lions and Cowboys have
competitive advantages by hosting the Thanksgiving games each year.
A vote wasn't taken.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think there should be a situation where one team has
an every-year advantage,'' Hunt said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Expansion update &QL; 
The NFL'S expansion committee met with the general membership for
about an hour Monday but did not make a recommendation on a 32nd
team.
</P>
<P>
   The owners are expected to again address the issue today with a
recommendation likely to come.
</P>
<P>
   Houston and Los Angeles are the contending cities.
</P>
<P>
   Sign of the times
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Tom Donahoe, director of football operations for the Pittsburgh
Steelers, doesn't think the Cardinals' plan to possibly play a
rookie left tackle is surprising.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're probably forced to do it now,'' he said of teams losing
players in free agency. ``It helps when you have a pretty high
draft pick, which they do (eighth overall). Sometimes needs dictate
what you do in the draft. You can't answer every problem in free
agency.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals lost starting left tackle &UR; Lomas Brown to the
expansion Cleveland Browns in free agency. Instead of going after a
replacement in free agency, they said they would take an offensive
pick early in next month's draft.
</P>
<P>
   ``Years ago I would have agreed with the notion that you don't
want a rookie protecting the quarterback's backside,'' Donahoe
said. ``Today, you're seeing teams play rookie linemen all the
time. It's not an ideal situation. It's probably not your best
option, but you do what you have to do.'' &QL; 
Negotiations on hold &QL; 
 &UR; Gary Wichard, agent for Cardinals wide receiver  &UR; Rob Moore, said he
didn't expect to resume talks with the Cardinals until summer.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals placed the franchise tag on Moore after not being
able to sign him to a multi-year deal.
</P>
<P>
   Moore was upset with the designation, but Wichard said he was
confident the two sides could reach an agreement.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's OK with me that nothing is going on,'' Wichard said.
``There's no sense having aggravation in March, April and May.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it will all work out. We'll get it done. He wants to
play with the Cardinals. They want him.''
</P>
<P>
   If the Cardinals sign Moore after July 15, they will get their
franchise designation back.
</P>
<P>
   Risky proposition &QL; 
Dallas Cowboys Coach &UR; Chan Gailey said he opposed changing the
touchback rule following kickoffs to the 25-yard line from the 20.
</P>
<P>
   ``It penalizes somebody who works hardest at being good at
something,'' Gailey said.
</P>
<P>
   Some coaches think the proposed rule would reward teams with
poor kickoff-return teams and penalizes teams with strong-legged
kickers. &QL; 
DeBartolo punishment &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Edward DeBartolo Jr., already barred from running the San
Francisco 49ers for his part in a gambling scandal, is expected to
be fined $1 million and be suspended from the NFL for a year.
</P>
<P>
   DeBartolo pleaded guilty last year to one felony charge of
failing to report an alleged extortion attempt by former Louisiana
Gov.  &UR; Edwin
 &UR; Edwards in connection with DeBartolo's bid for a riverboat gambling
license.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
