<SLUG> BC-FBN-CARDS-DRAFT-PICKS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CARDS GET 4 EXTRA PICKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE SCHOENFELD  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - The Cardinals have been awarded four compensatory
picks in next month's NFL draft, giving them 11 choices overall.
</P>
<P>
   Only the Green Bay Packers were awarded as many picks.
</P>
<P>
   None of the picks is in the first day of the draft, which
disappointed team officials when the announcement was made at the
NFL meetings Monday in Phoenix. The Cardinals thought they would
get higher compensatory picks after losing five players to free
agency before the 1998 season: middle linebacker Eric Hill (St.
Louis), wide receiver Kevin Williams (Buffalo), defensive end
Michael Bankston (Cincinnati), free safety Brent Alexander
(Carolina) and punter Jeff Feagles (Seattle).
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals were given a pick in the fifth round (No. 170
overall), two in the sixth (Nos. 204 and 207) and one in the
seventh (No. 241).
</P>
<P>
   They will have two first-round picks, one pick in the second,
third, fourth and seventh rounds, two picks in the fifth round and
three in the sixth.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals earlier forfeited their own seventh-round pick in
an August trade with Pittsburgh for cornerback J.B. Brown.
</P>
<P>
   Only two teams were given compensatory picks on the first day of
the draft. Green Bay and Pittsburgh were given third-round
choices. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
