<HEADLINE>
WOMACK'S RECOVERY ON SCHEDULE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DON KETCHUM  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TUCSON _ Diamondbacks officials breathed a sigh of relief Monday
regarding a couple of medical fronts they had been monitoring and a
new one that had surfaced.
</P>
<P>
   X-rays of outfielder  &UR; Tony Womack's &UR; fractured right wrist
revealed that the healing process was on schedule.
</P>
<P>
   He had a full-length cast removed for the evaluation, and
another was put on after. That will remain for another week, when a
smaller one will replace it. He continues to have a target date of
mid-April for his return and likely would begin the season on the
15-day disabled list.
</P>
<P>
   Right-hander  &UR; Amaury Telemaco had a magnetic resonance imaging
test on his ailing shoulder, but no damage was found. There appears
to be slight evidence of tendinitis, which will be treated with
rest and anti-inflammatory medication. He likely will be sidelined
for a minimum of three to five days.
</P>
<P>
   The new medical case involves outfielder  &UR; David Dellucci. He
experienced pain in his left wrist during Sunday's game against the
San Francisco Giants in Scottsdale and had an X-ray on Monday. The
results were negative.
</P>
<P>
   One theory was that a cyst had formed on the back of his hand
and that it had some dissipation, causing the soreness.
</P>
<P>
   ``That (cyst) is something that's been with me for a while, but
this is the first time it's really bothered me,'' Dellucci said.
``It's not that big of a deal. I just had it checked. It's
something I'll deal with. I want to play, and I'll play with the
pain.'' &QL; 
Kim on the way &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Korean right-hander  &UR; Byung-Hyun Kim, who on Feb. 19 signed a
four-year deal for about $2 million, will arrive in camp later this
week or early next week and will be placed on the 40-man roster.
</P>
<P>
   To make room for Kim, the club is scheduled to remove a player
from the 40-man roster either today or Wednesday. &QL; 
Standing tall in left &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Desi Wilson continues to impress club officials, although he
has an uphill battle for a roster spot because of the sheer numbers
at his two positions.
</P>
<P>
   The 6-foot-7 former Phoenix Firebird came into camp as a first
baseman but also can play the outfield. Manager  &UR; Buck Showalter put
him in left in the late stages of Arizona's 11-2 victory over San
Diego on Monday. Wilson had two hits to raise his spring average to
.285.
</P>
<P>
   ``I played right, left and even center last year in Japan, and
I've been taking fly balls during practice out there,'' Wilson
said. ``It's actually fun out there. I think I'm a versatile
player, and I hope they think the same way.''
</P>
<P>
   The Diamondbacks have  &UR; Travis Lee at first base and  &UR; Greg
Colbrunn as the backup. Utility men  &UR; Andy Fox and  &UR; Dale Sveum also
can play first, and the club is overloaded in the outfield at the
moment.
</P>
<P>
   In all likelihood, Wilson will start the season at first base
for Triple-A Tucson. &QL; 
Short stops &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Right-hander  &UR; Armando Reynoso continued to make steady progress,
earning the victory Monday. In four innings, he gave up four hits
and struck out three. One of the hits was a second-inning solo
homer by third baseman  &UR; George Arias, who played at Tucson Pueblo
High, Pima Community College and the University of Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   Showalter said Reynoso's command of his pitches wasn't as sharp
as it had been, but he doesn't appear concerned. Reynoso's next
start is expected to be when the Diamondbacks play the Milwaukee
Brewers on Saturday in his native Mexico, at Hector Espino Stadium
in Hermosillo.
</P>
<P>
   Outfielder  &UR; Pete Incaviglia was hit in the left forearm by a
pitch from San Diego's  &UR; Salvador Rodriguez, but he did not appear
to have any damage.
</P>
<P>
   The club is expected to bring up 11 players from its
minor-league camp today to play in the two split-squad games at Hi
Corbett Field and Tucson Electric Park. Among them are outfielder
 &UR; Garry Maddox, infielder  &UR; Scott Coolbaugh and pitchers  &UR; Don Peters,
Ben
 &UR; Norris and  &UR; Jason Crews. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
