r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-SUNS-BAILEY-AZR &LR;      03-16 0733
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-SUNS-BAILEY-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BAILEY ANSWERS AINGE'S CALL FOR ENERGY  
 ROOKIE APPRECIATES CHANCE TO START 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By NORM FRAUENHEIM  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sacramento's Jason Williams, Boston's Paul Pierce, Toronto's
Vince Carter and Vancouver's Mike Bibby are the best-known. They
are the contenders. One figures to be NBA Rookie of the Year.
</P>
<P>
   No surprises there.
</P>
<P>
   But every draft class has at least one surprise. There's no
award for the player who springs it. But if there were a Rookie
Surprise of the Year, Toby Bailey of the Suns would be an early
leader in the race.
</P>
<P>
   As he prepares to make his third straight start tonight in
Milwaukee, Bailey is the latest draft pick, No. 45 overall, with a
starting job.
</P>
<P>
   Bailey is one of eight active rookies with starting jobs. In
addition to Williams, Pierce, Carter and Bibby, the starters are
Robert Traylor of Milwaukee and Houston's backcourt of Michael
Dickerson and Cuttino Mobley. A ninth rookie starter, Denver center
Raef LaFrentz, was lost for the season a few weeks ago because of a
knee injury.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a great opportunity,'' Bailey said. ``I'm just there
to do whatever I can. I want to keep the ball alive, dive for loose
balls, play defense. That kind of thing. Mostly, I'm just trying to
learn.''
</P>
<P>
   The starting lineup is a complete reversal from the situation in
which Bailey found himself a couple of weeks ago. He had been
placed on the injured list, which is a common NBA dumping ground
for mid- to late second-round picks who spend most of their
apprentice seasons as practice players.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was frustrating at the time,'' Bailey said. ``But it also
was an opportunity. I was still learning in practice.''
</P>
<P>
   But Bailey and undrafted playmaker Gerald Brown came off the
list at about the time that Coach Danny Ainge was struggling to
overcome inconsistent, sluggish play. With Rex Chapman sidelined
because of a calf injury, Ainge gave Bailey a chance.
</P>
<P>
   The result? Instant energy.
</P>
<P>
   The Suns are 1-1 with Bailey starting at shooting guard. There
was a narrow loss to San Antonio and Sunday's 14-point victory over
Houston.
</P>
<P>
   For now, Ainge said he plans to continue with Bailey as the
starter. Chapman is back, but his jump shot is not. After missing
three straight games, Chapman come off the bench against Houston
and shot 1 for 10.
</P>
<P>
   Soon, Ainge will face a dilemma. Chapman appears uncomfortable
as a reserve. He has yet to find his range. Over 16 games, he's
shooting 31.3 percent. In a compressed season, he might be able to
find it only by playing. There isn't much much practice time.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, it's beginning to look as if Ainge has found
much-needed youth and athletic talent in Bailey, a 6-foot-5
swingman from UCLA. He's a good defender and he has been an active
rebounder. Against Houston, he grabbed five of his six rebounds in
the first seven minutes. His presence helped jump-start a team that
has been a slow starter.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a lot of veterans who tend to take those first 12
minutes off,'' Ainge said. ``I think Rex would rather start. But
Toby has started in the last two, and we've played a lot better. So
that's the way we're going to continue, for now at least.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look, we have a lot of big game players on this team. But
there are times when it just seems harder to light the fire with
Tom Gugliotta, Danny Manning, Jason Kidd and Rex. They've all
talked about it. And we all know that these guys compete,
especially with their backs to the wall. But as a team, we don't
have enough athletic ability to go on cruise control.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's why we inserted Toby in the starting lineup. He won't
take those minutes for granted.''
</P>
<P>
   Last summer, Ainge lobbied hard and long for a deal that allowed
the Suns to acquire Bailey. The Suns gave the Los Angles Lakers
cash and the option to purchase second-round picks in 1999 and 2000
for the rights to Bailey.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, Bailey was an uncertain quantity among scouts. He
was a sensational UCLA freshman. But during the next three years,
there was no apparent development as he struggled with position
changes and through a program that was rocked by a coaching change.
But Ainge remembered the dynamic skills of a freshman.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always loved his athleticism,'' said Ainge, who never could
have guessed that he would see so much of it so soon. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
