<HEADLINE>
`MOON' SCAPE GETTING THUMBS DOWN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL HUFFMAN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PH0ENIX - One of the hottest topics of conversation at the LPGA
tournament in Tucson last week was the abysmal condition of the
greens at Moon Valley Country Club, which this week will host the
$850,000 Standard Register PING.
</P>
<P>
   But not all the pros were complaining, especially one who has
had a major impact on the Phoenix tournament.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone is moaning, and I'm thinking secretly, `That's good
for me,' '' said  &UR; Laura Davies, who had her string of Standard
Register PING titles snapped at four in a row last year by
 &UR; Liselotte Neumann.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm hitting it so well, but I'm just not putting that good, as
always. So I think it's only going to help me if it doesn't turn
into a putting contest.''
</P>
<P>
   Most players who attended last week's Welch's/Circle K
Championship conceded that the Standard Register PING could be
settled by the tour's big hitters. One of those was  &UR; Wendy Ward,
the former All-American at Arizona State who finished third at the
1995 tournament as an amateur.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, I heard (the greens) were not very good,'' Ward said.
``At the same time, I really enjoy Moon Valley. I've had some good
experiences there in the past, so I'm looking forward to it.''
</P>
<P>
   At the moment, 15 greens are in average to below-average shape,
while three new ones _ Nos. 14, 15 and 18 _ are young and a little
bumpy from being redone this past year by Tempe architect  &UR; Bill
Phillips.
</P>
<P>
   Problems with the surface of ``the Moon'' should clear up for
future tournaments. The Solheim family, which owns PING as well as
the golf course, is committed to a multimillion renovation, with
Atlanta architect  &UR; Bob Cupp redoing the other 15 greens.
</P>
<P>
   The project will move the tournament to new course next year,
before it returns to Moon Valley in 2001. An announcement regarding
the site for the 2000 tournament may come this week. &QL; 
Star gazing &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Some of the LPGA's biggest names will show up this afternoon for
pre-tournament activities that include the Hewlett-Packard Putting
Contest, the LPGA Long-Drive Competition and the ``Golf Southwest''
``Magazine'' Celebrity Skills Challenge.
</P>
<P>
   The putting contest kicks things off at 2:30 p.m. on the
practice green near the clubhouse. Among the pros competing are
 &UR; Patty Sheehan,
 &UR; Nancy Harvey, Danielle Ammaccapane, Amy Fruwirth, Jenny Lidback,
 &UR; Shirley Furlong, Jody Anschutz, Pam Wright and  &UR; Robin Walton. The
winner already has been determined, as Hewlett-Packard will present
a check for $10,000 to officials from the Joanne Winter/Silver
Belle Championship.
</P>
<P>
   The long-drive competition, which is just for fun, follows at 3
p.m. on the 10th hole. It matches three LPGA pros _ Rookie of the
Year  &UR; Se
 &UR; Ri Pak, Michelle McGann and Davies _ with three top junior players
_
 &UR; Kristi Larson of Scottsdale Chaparral High School,  &UR; Erin Tone of
Gilbert High and Xavier's  &UR; Alissa Kuczka.
</P>
<P>
   The skills challenge starts at 3:30 p.m. on the 18th green. The
$12,000 event matches eight pros with seven local media types.
Clearly the better players are defending champ Neumann, Pak,
Davies, McGann,
 &UR; Meg Mallon, Beth Daniel and  &UR; Juli Inkster, the winner of last
week's Welch's/Circle K Championship. The winning team earns
$5,000, with the money split between the pro and a charity
represented by the media member. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
