<SLUG> BC-HKN-COYOTES-SCHOENFELD-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SMITH ENDORSES SCHOENFELD, RIPS COACHING CHANGE RUMORS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By TIM TYERS  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - On a day when Coyotes Coach Jim Schoenfeld broke his
silence regarding his job security, General Manager Bobby Smith
snuffed a week of speculation with a declarative statement before
Monday night's game with Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   ``These things (rumors of a coaching change) take on a life of
their own and undermine the coach and the team,'' Smith said. ``Jim
Schoenfeld is our coach. There will be no coaching change.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's why I'm so irate and embarrassed. If I knew there was
someone in our organization who played a role in what I think was
pure fabrication and rumor, they would be ex-Coyotes today. It's
not how I run shop.''
</P>
<P>
   A reason the rumors gained momentum is that management didn't
squelch them from the start, which led to ``sourced reports'' that
the 1-0 victory over Anaheim, saved Schoenfeld's job. It was
thought that Schoenfeld would receive an extension of his contract
that has one year remaining after the team bolted to the league's
best start at 17-3-3, but it has not been offered.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're all judged every day, myself included, but I'm telling
you we're not changing coaches,'' Smith said. ``If we continued not
playing well, there were all sorts of things I would have had to
consider.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know what I want and that's to play well and be one of eight
teams playing in the second round of the playoffs. One of the teams
grouped in there trying to win it all.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's something we haven't done since 1987 and it's where our
focus is.''
</P>
<P>
   Schoenfeld laughed at the theory that one game saved him, as did
Smith, who said, ``You don't make a major change based on something
like that.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's look at that logically,'' Schoenfeld said Monday morning
before Smith's announcement. ``If the coach is good, you don't say,
`Oh boy, if you lose this one, you're toast.' If a coach is bad and
wins three in a row, you should still replace him. To me, the whole
thing about one game is moronic, really.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I'm wrong for the job and the team has won five in a row,
get the guy who's right. Have the guts to make a decision. Change
the coach, or change the tune, because I'm tired of hearing the
same old song.''
</P>
<P>
   Schoenfeld said he doesn't think a member of the organization is
the source of such speculation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a hard time believing a responsible member of our
organization, who would be privy to that stuff, would be that
irresponsible _ actually, hockey-ignorant _ because it can only
hurt our team.
</P>
<P>
   ``What if I win? Does that mean I get two games? What does that
do to the players as far as their responsibility goes? It gives
them an out. Even if they don't want it, it's there subconsciously.
That's the battle we face: `Guys, you've been given an out, it's up
to you whether you want to take it or not.' Hey, it might be the
kiss of death after all, who knows?''
</P>
<P>
   Schoenfeld said he saw no need to apologize for his team's
owning the third-best record in the West.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm completely satisfied because my best is given for the team
every day,'' he said. ``Frankly, that's all that matters. Where I
get my joy is when I'm on the ice with the players and when I'm
behind the bench with those guys. That's why I can take all this
other nonsense, put it where it belongs and do my job.''
</P>
<P>
   The players say they are solidly in Schoenfeld's camp. Smith
said the performance in the win over Anaheim demonstrated those
feelings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our play impressed me,'' Smith said. ``With the rumors out
there, the players screamed out that they wanted to play for Jim
Schoenfeld. It was a good effort in a very emotional game.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
