<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-RANGERS-CAPITALS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RANGERS TIE CAPITALS, 1-1 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By JOE LAPOINTE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ All things considered, the Rangers probably got about
what they deserved on Monday night at Madison Square Garden when
they tied the Washington Capitals, 1-1. Weary from a busy schedule,
New York failed to hold a lead, but survived to gain 1 point in the
standings in the race for the final playoff berth in the Eastern
Conference.
</P>
<P>
   Over all, it was a forgettable game with a frantic overtime
period and a few memorable moments before it. One was the first
National Hockey League goal for Rumun Ndur, a Ranger rookie
defenseman. Another was what might be the final Garden appearance
for Washington's Dale Hunter, a veteran bully-boy who played the
villain's role as usual in a scrappy performance. And the Rangers
got another sharp performance from goalie Mike Richter, who stopped
33 of 34 shots.
</P>
<P>
   With 14 games remaining in their 82-game regular season
schedule, the Rangers have 67 points, tying them with Florida for
ninth place. Both teams trail Boston by 1 point in the battle for
the final playoff berth. But the Rangers have played two more games
than both the Bruins and the Panthers.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers, who were playing their sixth game in nine days,
won't have to play again until Friday night, when they host
Buffalo. Coach John Muckler is happy for the break.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is probably the worst schedule I've ever seen in my
life,'' Muckler said. ``Not only six games in nine nights, you're
playing twice back-to-back games. That's impossible. The team was
just dog tired. It's not fair to anybody.''
</P>
<P>
   Ndur was not complaining. His goal came in the first period, at
14 minutes and 33 seconds, when he slapped the puck past goalie
Olaf Kolzig. Ndur then went into a victory dance that deserves
inclusion on the season highlight reel. In his energetic jumping,
he almost landed on top of Gerard Gautheir, the linesman, who
avoided most contact by ducking out of the way.
</P>
<P>
   ``He couldn't see me, he was so excited,'' Gauthier said. ``I
told him `I don't know if you will remember your first goal, but I
sure will.' No way I was going to stay there. He's a big guy.''
Ndur is 6 feet 2 inches and 222 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   Hunter, who has been playing for 19 seasons, sparked his team by
roughing up various Rangers. He exchanged shoves with Niklas
Sundstrom, a clean player. Later, he started a ruckus by coming to
an abrupt stop in front of Richter and spraying him with ice chips.
When other players joined the confrontation, Hunter located Brian
Leetch, the Ranger captain, and shoved a glove in his face.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've played against him for 12 years,'' Leetch said of Hunter,
``and, at least once a game, I've eaten his glove at some point.''
At the end of the period, Hunter roughed with Adam Graves but
declined an invitation to fight Darren Langdon. This led to an
exchange of angry words between the coaches behind the benches and
down the corridor they share at intermission.
</P>
<P>
   It also seemed to spark the Capitals. They tied the game at 1-1
at 11:44 of the third period on a goal by Enrico Ciccone, who shot
through traffic from the blue line to beat Richter after Washington
won a faceoff in the Ranger end.
</P>
<P>
   The Capitals made it to the Stanley Cup finals last spring, but
lost four consecutive games to the Detroit Red Wings. Washington
has been in a slump ever since, and is unlikely to make even the
first round of the tournament this season. Coming into the game,
the Capitals were nine points behind Boston. Several of their
players could be traded by next Tuesday's deadline.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers are undefeated in their last two games, 4-2-1 in
their last seven and 9-4-2 in their last 15. Richter said the best
might be yet to come.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're just going to keep getting better,'' he said. As for
losing the lead, he was not discouraged. ``We were good enough to
re-group and not let that beat us,'' Richter said. ``One point is
better than none. We'll take the tie.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-16-99 0050EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
