<DOCNO> NYT19990316.0023 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-16 01:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1888 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-BLAZERS-HNS &LR;      03-16 0925
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-BLAZERS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MURPHY  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
DALLAS _ They've pretty much heard all the names.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Portland Jail Blazers. The Trial Blazers. The Bail Raisers.
</P>
<P>
   Most anything negative that can be written or said about a team
of precocious young NBA players with problems, both off the court
and on, had been written and said about the Portland Trail Blazers.
</P>
<P>
   These post-Clyde Drexler Blazers were the gangstas of the NBA,
the traveling road show of Hoodstock, and they seemed to enjoy that
image.
</P>
<P>
   But the Blazers are now being described another way _ the best
team in the NBA.
</P>
<P>
   Well, maybe.
</P>
<P>
   Most point to the Utah Jazz as the league's top team, but an
argument could easily be made for Portland. And you wouldn't _ or
couldn't _ get much of argument on that point from the Rockets, who
were flogged 111-71 by the Blazers on March 7 and are seeking
revenge in tonight's rematch at Compaq Center.
</P>
<P>
   But these Blazers aren't dwelling on that game as any indication
of what will happen tonight.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, man, the one thing I've learned in my little short stint
in the league is that you have Scottie Pippen, you have Charles
Barkley, you have Dream (Hakeem Olajuwon), and you have a coach in
Rudy T who are up there (among the best in the league),'' said
Portland point guard Damon Stoudamire. ``All that psyching and
stuff, that won't work. I know they're probably sitting at home
getting ready to play. They're going to be ready.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be a dogfight, because they haven't forgotten
what happened. We're going to have to be ready to play, because
they're going to come at us with all they've got.''
</P>
<P>
   OK, so the Blazers are maturing. But what makes them so good?
</P>
<P>
   Depth, versatility and a willingness to sacrifice.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't say that it's easy, and the bottom line is that it's
not over, but for the first 20 games, we've done a good job of
(juggling lineups and egos),'' said Portland coach Mike Dunleavy.
``Our guys have embraced the idea of winning. And the fact is that
because we have a lot of depth on our team, there are going to be
given nights, because guys are playing well, (somebody) may get
more minutes than usual.
</P>
<P>
   ``And if it happens to be at your position, you just have to
check your ego at the door and be satisfied with the fact that we
are winning, and that's what it takes to win. So far, it's worked
for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed.
</P>
<P>
   After letting Dallas hang around awhile, the Blazers
steamrollered the hapless Mavericks 106-91 Monday night for their
17th win in 21 games. Only Utah at 18-4 has a better record.
</P>
<P>
   It's how the Blazers are doing it that has teams around the
league casting a wary eye toward the Pacific Northwest. In a year
when teams are scrambling to find enough legitimate talent to stock
the roster, the Blazers come at you 11 deep. The members of their
second team _ Walt Williams, Jim Jackson, Greg Anthony, Stacey
Augmon and Kelvin Cato _ could all start most anywhere else in the
league.
</P>
<P>
   Not only do the Blazers have a lot of talent, but they have
lotto talent as well. Even though general manager Bob Whitsitt has
not had a lottery pick of his own to use in the draft, the Blazers
have either traded for or signed as free agents 10 players who were
taken in the lottery by other teams: Stoudamire, Isaiah Rider,
Brian Grant, Rasheed Wallace, Williams, Jackson, Augmon, Anthony,
Carlos Rogers and Bonzi Wells.
</P>
<P>
   And while that kind of depth is rare, the versatility the
Blazers possess is even more so. They can go big, running out a
front line that averages almost 7 feet across, or they can go small
and quick. That means a fast-breaking team, or a bunch that can
hammer you in the half-court set. Pick your poison.
</P>
<P>
   Wallace, who sprained his ankle against the Mavericks on Monday,
can play all three frontcourt positions, and Jackson and Williams
can play point guard, shooting guard or small forward. Rider can
play small forward in a pinch, and Augmon can play shooting guard,
small forward or power forward.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Portland's strengths are) the chemistry and the different
combinations we can use,'' said Grant, the league's fifth-best
rebounder at 10.9 boards per game. ``Maybe one or two combinations
aren't working, but we can go with so many.''
</P>
<P>
   Depth like that can create problems, especially in this
stat-conscious, I-need-my-minutes NBA. But Dunleavy has managed to
defuse any problems, like when he sat down Stoudamire during the
fourth quarter in a recent string of games. Stoudamire, however,
said nothing, content that Portland was winning all those games
while Anthony ran the team.
</P>
<P>
   ``That, to me, is a very big step for us,'' Dunleavy said. ``It
doesn't matter who plays as long as we're winning, and I think that
is starting to sink in with our guys.''
</P>
<P>
   The only other real problem facing the Blazers is the same one
that plagues most young teams _ complacency. They know they're
better than most teams and wind up playing at something less than
full effort.
</P>
<P>
   Like against Dallas on Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not a good attitude to have, because we're not that
good,'' Stoudamire said. ``We're not the old (Chicago) Bulls. But
we're human, and you tend to think that way.''
</P>
<P>
   They may not be the old Bulls, but they sure look like the
league's newest young bucks.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're winning, and our losses have all been close (with the
exception of a 14-point setback to the Jazz),'' Wallace said. ``I
love the way we're playing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
