<HEADER>
A1889 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SALMON-PROTECTION-1ST     03-16 1107
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SALMON-PROTECTION-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SALMON TO GO ON THREATENED LIST IN NORTHWEST
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Subs for rewriting throughout)   (sw) 
 By SAM HOWE VERHOVEK   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Federal officials will formally declare on Tuesday
that nine wild salmon species in the Pacific Northwest are
threatened with extinction, the first listing under the 26-year-old
Endangered Species Act that affects an entire urban region, a
government official said.
</P>
<P>
   But while that announcement deals with fish, it is people _
especially the three million in the greater Seattle area _ who will
have to face the consequences of halting the decline of these once
mighty salmon runs.
</P>
<P>
   They will almost surely pay more in taxes, to acquire land
around waterways and to buy out floodplains so rivers can reclaim
areas where the salmon once spawned. They are already being urged
by their local leaders to stop using fertilizers and pesticides,
voluntary efforts that may eventually become mandatory, county
officials said on Monday. They will probably face sharp new
restrictions on building, especially near streams and other
waterways.
</P>
<P>
   And at the heart of all these measures will be these questions:
Will people decide that these are all steps toward a better quality
of life in a region already consumed with worry that its lavish
natural splendor is under attack? Will they find, as Mayor Paul
Schell of Seattle likes to put it, that ``in working together to
save the salmon, it may turn out that the salmon saves us''? Or
will listing the salmon as threatened species, which in many ways
dwarfs the impact of the 1990 listing of the northern spotted owl
that set off its own environmental controversy, provoke a backlash
against the Endangered Species Act?
</P>
<P>
   The law allows officials more time to develop protections for
species listed as ``threatened'' than it does for those with the
even more serious classification of ``endangered.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Officials from Gov. Gary Locke on down have been formulating
plans for months in anticipation of the announcement, and they will
now be forthcoming.
</P>
<P>
   Under the Endangered Species Act, unless steps are taken to
protect the affected species, governments and even private citizens
can face criminal penalties. But so far, unlike the spotted owl
fight, in which many leaders in logging and timber towns bitterly
opposed the listing and even mocked the owl, there has been little
opposition to the proposed listing. And no one is belittling the
salmon, a symbol of the region.
</P>
<P>
   The salmon species, including the Puget Sound chinook, or king
salmon, have been hurt in all ways by human development in recent
decades, by pollution and runoff that includes sewage and chemicals
from fertilizers and by construction that in many cases has simply
closed off waterways. Farther inland, their runs have been
significantly reduced by the huge dams that provide the region's
famously cheap and abundant hydropower.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our goal is recovery of the salmon,'' said Ron Sims, the King
County executive, who oversees an area that includes the city of
Seattle and who has repeatedly said that he believed residents here
were willing to pay more and take other steps to protect the fish.
``However, our ultimate purpose is to restore our environment so
that we may provide for the coexistence of people and fish in the
Pacific Northwest.''
</P>
<P>
   The announcement on Tuesday, by the National Marine Fisheries
Service, will extend Endangered Species Act protections on wild
salmon found in nearly every watershed in Washington state, as well
as in parts of the Willamette Valley in Oregon. The fish include
the Puget Sound chinook, the Lower Columbia River chinook, Upper
Columbia spring chinook, Lake Ozette sockeye, Hood Canal summer
chum, Lower Columbia chum and the mid-Columbia steelhead. Decisions
were delayed for six months on four other salmon runs in California
and Oregon.
</P>
<P>
   Federal officials said on Monday that they believed that salmon
restoration could amount to ``life by a thousand stitches instead
of death by a thousand cuts.'' But the devil will be in the
details, and some political and business leaders have said some
contemplated steps were far too Draconian to pass public muster.
</P>
<P>
   The state agriculture commissioner, Jim Jesernig, said recently
that state officials were already getting ``beaten up by all
sides,'' by Indian leaders and environmental groups who believe
that the most likely measures will not do enough to protect the
salmon and by homebuilders and farmers, some of whom, Jesernig
said, were already calling state officials ``jack-booted Nazis.''
</P>
<P>
   For now, many local officials here said they were convinced that
there was a way to help the salmon and help people at the same
time, especially since many people here list ``runaway growth'' or
``sprawl'' as one of their dominant concerns. And the officials
think there is a way to do it without the legal rancor that has
attended species listings.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've looked very hard at many of those cases,'' Tim Ceis,
director of the Endangered Species Act policy coordination office
for King County, said on Monday. ``The lawyers were the ones making
the money. Nobody was spending any money on the fish.''
</P>
<P>
   But lawsuits may be inevitable, from both sides. The state's
Building Industry Association, representing developers, says the
salmon issue is being used to stop growth and that the most likely
proposals for building restrictions show that local regulators have
``lost all common sense.'' With the Seattle metropolitan area
projected to add as many as one million people in the next 25
years, some skeptics say the fish do not stand a chance.
</P>
<P>
   Environmental groups, on the other hand, say the issue can be a
winner for both sides.
</P>
<P>
   ``Special-interest defenders of the status quo who oppose real
action to save salmon would have you believe the listings will
produce a shattered economy, a Cuba-on-the-Sound,'' said Tim
Stearns, executive director of Save our Wild Salmon, an
environmental group. ``That kind of thinking is laughable, and in
fact, the opposite is true. If our governor and state Legislature
get serious about salmon restoration, we would see enormous gains
in our quality of life and real economic benefits.''
</P>
<P>
   While the restrictions are likely to place new limits on fish
catches in many Washington rivers, they are not likely to change
the diets of Pacific Northwesterners or anyone else in the United
States who fancies the taste of salmon: most salmon eaten in this
country is flown in from Alaska, or raised in domestic pens here,
or in Canada and South America.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
