<SLUG> BC-LA-DEMS-CONVENTION-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S NOW OFFICIAL _ L.A. WILL HOST Y2K CONVENTION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY RICK ORLOV  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ With four simple words _ ``the Democrats are
coming'' _ Los Angeles won the competition to host the Democratic
National Convention in August 2000 when the party's presidential
ticket will be picked.
</P>
<P>
   Democratic National Committee chairman-designate Joe Andrew made
the announcement Monday at a politically star-studded ceremony at
the Convention Center where he used the city's unique bid, which
was put together by private groups rather than government, as a
campaign issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unlike the Republicans, the 2000 Democratic convention will be
sponsored by the private sector with the cooperation of the public
sector, not the other way around,'' Andrew said from beneath an
arch of red, white and blue balloons.
</P>
<P>
   ``The citizens of California will get the benefit and not the
burden.''
</P>
<P>
   Final action is expected Friday when the City Council meets to
approve the contracts. City approval is needed because Los Angeles
will be responsible for traffic and security at the event _
estimated at about $6 million of the $34.5 million contract.
</P>
<P>
   For Mayor Richard Riordan, virtually the only Republican in a
sea of Democrats in local politics, winning the convention
competition over Boston and Denver made him ``the proudest mayor in
California.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are the gateway to the world and the world's gateway to
America,'' Riordan said. ``Los Angeles is not just back, it's
better.''
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Gray Davis, whose election in November was credited with
being one of the points cited in the selection of Los Angeles,
praised the choice and offered his own vision of how to begin the
event.
</P>
<P>
   ``In choosing this city, the DNC has affirmed that Los Angeles
is back,'' Davis said. ``Having weathered riots and recessions,
floods and fires, Los Angeles is prepared to resume its role as one
of the world's great urban centers.
</P>
<P>
   ``During the 1984 Olympics, there was a torch relay across the
country. I would like to see the nominee do the same thing as we
prepare to open this convention. The nominee should campaign in
Arizona and Nevada, Washington and Oregon. He or she should go to
Northern California, the Silicon Valley to the San Fernando Valley,
to make this a convention that involves people.''
</P>
<P>
   The Los Angeles bid was unique for a political convention in
that most of the cost is being borne by the LA Convention 2000
committee of business and civic leaders.
</P>
<P>
   The committee is co-chaired by billionaire Eli Broad, Democratic
activist Bill Wardlaw, grocery magnate Ron Burkle and DreamWorks
SKG executive David Geffen. Burkle recently joined the committee in
its efforts. All four are major contributors to Democratic
candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Broad said the DNC decision reaffirms the role Los Angeles plays
in the nation as it prepares for the future.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are the millennium city,'' Broad said. ``We are in the
middle of a renaissance and we can't wait to showcase the city and
its people.''
</P>
<P>
   Broad cited the work on the Staples Center, which will be the
main site of the convention, as well as the other projects under
way in downtown, such as the Disney Concert Hall, the new Cathedral
of Our Lady of Angels and possibly on the Coliseum for a new
professional football team he is seeking.
</P>
<P>
   The return on the investment is expected to be between $137
million and $150 million in tax revenues from the 30,000 visitors
the convention will draw and neighboring areas also are expected to
benefit from increased tourism.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew said the dates of the convention have yet to be set, but
that he is looking at either the week of Aug. 14 or Aug. 21, 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew had served as head of the site selection committee that
visited Los Angeles last year and recently was named to become the
party's next chairman.
</P>
<P>
   ``I found it odd to be making recommendations to myself,''
Andrew said. ``But I was convinced early on that the convention
should come here.''
</P>
<P>
   There had been some speculation in recent months the city's bid
was in trouble because of the way it was being financed as well as
the arrogance many DNC members perceived from Californians _
particularly over their emphasis on the state's political power
with its 54 electoral votes.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew dismissed some of those concerns as ``mere speculation
and rumor'' that occurs around every convention bid.
</P>
<P>
   It has been a long time since Los Angeles served as a host city.
Its first, and last, political convention was in 1960 when
Democrats nominated John F. Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   Four years ago, the city had been asked by both parties to bid
for their 1996 conventions. However, Riordan declined, saying the
city had not fully recovered from the Northridge Earthquake.
</P>
<P>
   Both Democrats and Republicans have fared poorly in carrying the
state when conventions were held here.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats nominated James Cox in San Francisco in 1920 but he
lost to Republican Warren G. Harding. In 1960, Kennedy won the
nomination in Los Angeles but lost the state to Richard Nixon. In
1984, Walter Mondale was nominated in San Francisco but lost
California to Ronald Reagan.
</P>
<P>
   Dwight Eisenhower carried California in 1956 after being
nominated in San Francisco. Barry Goldwater, also nominated in San
Francisco, lost the state to Lyndon Johnson in 1964 and Bob Dole
lost California in 1996 after being nominated in San Diego.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-16-99 0118EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
