<HEADER>
A1895 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-NFL-LADN     03-16 0922
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NFL-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO ANSWERS FROM PHOENIX
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BOB KEISSER  
 c.1999 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR; PHOENIX _ The NFL might someday expand to Los Angeles or
Houston, but it is becoming increasingly clear that a decision here
at the league's winter meetings this week is unlikely.
</P>
<P>
   The combination of a late rally of support for Houston and owner
trepidation over the league's suggested L.A. solution has created a
stalemate. The expansion committee adjourned again Monday without
recommending membership. It will convene again this morning in
search of a consensus.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have 24 votes for Los Angeles, We don't have 24 votes
for Houston. We don't have 24 votes to expand,'' said Carolina
owner Jerry Richardson, the co-chair of the expansion committee.
``What we've got are problems.''
</P>
<P>
   The 12-member expansion committee can recommend a franchise be
granted to either city, but a 24-vote majority of the league owners
is required before the franchise is awarded.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have a consensus,'' said Buffalo owner Ralph Wilson.
``We go round and round. Houston has a stadium. L.A. is a key
market, but its bids are nebulous. I don't think we'll even take a
vote on it before these meetings are done.
</P>
<P>
   ``But who knows? Things can happen fast around here. Nothing
ever surprises me.''
</P>
<P>
   With good reason. A few weeks ago, key players at the highest
level of the NFL had devised a scenario to give L.A. a tenuous bid
that would attract other bidders besides Michael Ovitz (Carson) and
Ed Roski (New Coliseum) and keep Houston as a backup.
</P>
<P>
   That idea is still being advanced. But its backers didn't count
on the reticence of several owners to expansion in general and
Houston businessman Robert McNair's aggressive campaign.
</P>
<P>
   McNair's campaign had the advantage of a face, plus a committed
wallet, to go with the name. While the league kept the Ovitz and
Roski bids somewhat at bay, McNair rounded up support, so much so
that he believes he has a majority of the 12 votes on the expansion
committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one ever comes up and says, `We'll vote for you,' '' said
McNair. ``But based on what they say, I think I have a majority.
Someone said the committee took a straw vote Sunday and it was 12-0
in favor of L.A. I think that was the vote to adjourn.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a difficult issue to begin with. Owners come knowing
they have a decision to make on expansion, but they really don't
get the chance to look at the proposals until they get here.''
</P>
<P>
   Now that they have, some owners favor Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Pittsburgh owner Dan Rooney spoke on Houston's behalf Monday
during the general session, Kansas City owner Lamar Hunt said he
personally favors Houston, and Dallas owner Jerry Jones conceded
Houston has a good case.
</P>
<P>
   San Diego owner Alex Spanos emphatically supported Houston, in
part because it has a firm commitment from local politicians.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tell me what Los Angeles has got?'' asked Spanos. ``I've said
100 times that I want a team in L.A., but they have to want it,
too. I want L.A. (politicians) to come to me and say, `Here's what
we'll do,' just as Houston has.
</P>
<P>
   ``It unfortunately took Bud Adams leaving to get Houston where
it is today. It took Baltimore 10 years and St. Louis seven to
learn the lesson. It took Cleveland six months.''
</P>
<P>
   Carson mayor Peter Fajardo, whose city is committed to a $180
million investment, said, ``We're still hopeful,'' despite Monday's
lack of a decision. A spokesman for Ovitz did not return phone
calls.
</P>
<P>
   Roski, the Kings owner and industrial real estate baron, took
the news in stride and thinks L.A. is in the lead of this race. ``I
don't think they ever promised us a decision (here). Their intent
was to find some direction,'' he said. He said no one from the
league has handed him a list of conditions he has to meet or even
mentioned what the franchise fee will be. But he's prepared to
follow through if needed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We probably would respond like we have from the start,'' he
said. ``They suggested we redesign the stadium; we did. They
suggested we add to the ownership group, and we did. We're open to
anything they might say.''
</P>
<P>
   That would include a private response to any league request for
more public money, as Spanos indicated. The New Coliseum proposal
includes more than $300 million in public investment, but most of
it is in the form of already completed infrastructure.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been very clear on this,'' Roski said. ``Los Angeles
does not have the ability to do any (more public financing) than it
has. And what they've done is significant. If there's something
else they want, we can deal with it privately.''
</P>
<P>
   Commissioner Paul Tagliabue said he is hopeful that the meeting
will produce some kind of decision. He said the best possible
situation in L.A. would be for all interested parties to unify
themselves. At this stage of things, something like that might have
to take place before the owners are ready to return to L.A.
</P>
<P>
   Pat Bowlen, who is pro-L.A., said the league might need to look
at this as a two-part process _ give one city an expansion team and
work with the other as a future home for an existing team with
stadium concerns.
</P>
<P>
   McNair wrote letters to eight owners saying he'd like to buy
their teams and move them to Houston if he doesn't get an expansion
team.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, we can wait forever,'' Roski said. `` Our facility isn't
going away.''
</P>
<P>
   The league meetings adjourn Wednesday and the owners will meet
again in May.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-16-99 0122EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990316.0027 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-16 01:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1896 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-REEVESCOLUMN-TEX     03-16 0871
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-REEVES </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TCU, NIT MAKING GOOD OL' PARDNERS
</HEADLINE>
 COLUMN-TEX (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM REEVES 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Fort Worth tilted its Stetson back, propped
its boots on the back of a purple seat and sent the NIT a message
at Daniel-Meyer Coliseum Monday night _ ``Y'all come on back now,
ya' hear?''
</P>
<P>
   It was an offer a tournament desperate for dynamic energy and
attention couldn't refuse.
</P>
<P>
   TCU and Fort Worth put on an impressive and powerful show for
the NIT folks. The Frogs rocked Nebraska, 101-89, in a second-round
game and a boisterous sellout crowd rocked the roof at
Daniel-Meyer.
</P>
<P>
   The victory earned the Frogs a third-round home game against
Oregon on Wednesday night. Tipoff will be at 8:30 as the second
half of an ESPN doubleheader.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a great win for us and the crowd was awesome,'' TCU
coach Billy Tubbs said. ``We've had great crowds before, but I
don't know that we've had a better one than the one that was here
tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   To borrow a slogan Milwaukee once used during a World Series,
``What a time, what a team, what a town!''
</P>
<P>
   OK, it is just the National Invitation Tournament, not the Big
Dance, and maybe you had to be there to appreciate the excitement
Monday night. But by the look and the sound of the crowd, you
probably were. They said 7,166 fans were in the place. It sounded
more like 71,166.
</P>
<P>
   This, on a night when TCU students were on spring break.
</P>
<P>
   The 21-10 Frogs, who bounced the Cornhuskers out of the
tournament despite playing without star center Lee Nailon for most
of the second half, looked more like the Purple Horde of the first
half of the season than the team that lost six of its last 10 games
in the regular season and totally collapsed against BYU in the
opening round of the WAC tournament.
</P>
<P>
   ``We probably played better in the second half tonight,'' Tubbs
said, ``than we have all season.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet, Tubbs had his best player _ Nailon _ sitting beside him on
the bench for a 12-minute stretch while the Frogs were taking
control of the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was nervous about the team keeping it up when I came out,''
admitted Nailon, who picked up his fourth foul with 15:03 to play
and left with the scored tied at 55. ``But they stayed into it. At
first I was anxious to get back in, but after a while I just said,
`Hey, they've got it going good. I'll just stay right where I'm
at.'''
</P>
<P>
   Marquise Gainous, who elected not to play in that critical loss
to BYU because of a hand bruise (doctors had cleared him), was
magnificent, pounding home a game-high 30 points, pulling down nine
rebounds and stepping in to defend against Big 12 player of the
year Venson Hamilton when Nailon sat down.
</P>
<P>
   When Nailon checked back into the game with 3:25 to play, the
Frogs led by 11, 88-77.
</P>
<P>
   All five Frogs starters hit double figures, including 20 for
Nailon, who played only 28 minutes but hit seven of nine from the
field.
</P>
<P>
   It was TCU's second NIT victory, following Wednesday night's
72-71 win at Kansas State, and the first time the Frogs have broken
the 80-point barrier in their past seven games.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've tweaked things a little bit,'' Tubbs admitted.
</P>
<P>
   Tubbs may have finally understood that he couldn't will this
team to be something it's not. From his playbook of 24 defensive
schemes, Tubbs threw out all but two: the man-to-man and a tricky
1-3-1 zone ``we're just now beginning to understand.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead of asking his players to operate 10 different offensive
attacks, they now use two or three.
</P>
<P>
   He has gone to a six-man rotation, using Shannon Long as his
only sub whenever possible. He lets Nailon slip out on the
perimeter now and then and the big man has responded with some
surprising 3-pointers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're having fun again,'' Tubbs said. ``We're having fun at
practice and carrying that over into the games. The loss to BYU
took a lot of pressure off.''
</P>
<P>
   It certainly took the Frogs, who began the season ranked 24th in
the country, right out of the NCAA Tournament, which might not be
so bad after all. Instead of a soundly squashed toad in the NCAA
sea, they're suddenly beginning to look like a mighty big Frog in
the NIT pond.
</P>
<P>
   ``We could have been in Milwaukee \Rfor an NCAA subregional\S,''
Tubbs sniffed, ``talking about getting our butts beat.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, they're one victory away from a trip to the NIT final
four in New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Lee Nailon would be great \Rfor the NIT\S in New
York,'' Tubbs said, turning politician. ``Heck, I think we'd be
great in New York.''
</P>
<P>
   The NIT could certainly use the personality and Tubbs' array of
one-liners.
</P>
<P>
   ``Beating Nebraska is a lot like beating Southern Cal,'' Tubbs
said. ``They both have great football programs.''
</P>
<P>
   There was a message in there somewhere, I think.
</P>
<P>
   ``The NIT does want it wants to,'' Tubbs said before learning
that TCU would be awarded the home court Wednesday. ``They can send
us to Afghanistan if they want to.''
</P>
<P>
   No way. Fort Worth and the Frogs made a point Monday night, and
they made it loud and clear. The NIT, to its credit, was too smart
and too desperate for a little pizzazz to ignore it.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, Afghanistan lost in the first round. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
