<SLUG> BC-HKN-KINGS-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PULSE REMAINS STRONG FOR KINGS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROGER PHILLIPS  
 c.1999 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD, Calif. _ It has gone from a flicker to a flame.
</P>
<P>
   Given up for dead a week ago, the Kings suddenly are very much
alive.
</P>
<P>
   With their third consecutive strong effort, this one against one
of the best teams in the National Hockey League, the Kings took
another big step in their late-season bid to get back in the
playoff race. They defeated the Eastern Conference-leading Ottawa
Senators on Monday night by a 4-0 margin before a Forum crowd of
12,640.
</P>
<P>
   Rob Blake and Philippe Boucher scored late in the second period
to break up a scoreless tie, and Donald Audette and Sean O'Donnell
provided third-period insurance goals. It paved the way for the
Kings to put together a three-game winning streak, their longest
since they won five straight in late December and early January.
</P>
<P>
   Stephane Fiset stopped 29 shots to record his second shutout
this season and the 14th of his career. Fiset has allowed only
three goals during the winning streak, stopping 87 of 89 shots on
goal.
</P>
<P>
   With 15 games remaining, the Kings (26-36-5) moved to within
three points of idle Calgary and Edmonton, which share the final
Western Conference playoff berth.
</P>
<P>
   The Senators (38-20-8) lost their second straight following a
five-game winning streak, and fell to 0-6 at the Forum, an arena
they will not be visiting again.
</P>
<P>
   In the first period, the Kings outshot Ottawa by a meager 5-4
margin.
</P>
<P>
   ``They play the trap so well,'' Audette said. ``Everything is
clogged up in the middle and it is so hard to get something going,
so that is why you have to get your speed from down low and come
with speed and one guy late. If we do that, we have a good chance
to enter the zone pretty easy.''
</P>
<P>
   In the second period, the Kings heeded Audette's game plan and
outshot the Senators 17-10. Again and again, a King would join the
play late to receive a pass and take a shot. But for most of the
second period, the outstanding play of Senators goalie Ron Tugnutt
_ who began the night with a microscopic 1.60 goals-against average
_ negated the Kings' opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   Then, with 6:07 to play in the period, Ian Laperriere drew a
roughing penalty from Senators defenseman Lance Pitlick, giving the
Kings their second power play of the game. They wasted little time
capitalizing. The Kings gained control of the puck, moving it
around until it finally landed on Blake's stick at the left boards.
With Ray Ferraro in front of the net, Blake fired a slap shot that
beat Tugnutt to the short side at 14:38. It was Blake's ninth goal
this season, his fifth in the last nine games, and the 100th of his
nine-year NHL career.
</P>
<P>
   Less than three minutes later, Boucher scored his second goal of
the season, a shot off a pass from Ferraro that banked off two
Senators in front, then off the right goal post, and finally past
Tugnutt.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings broke the game open early in the third, Audette and
O'Donnell scoring 44 seconds apart. Audette scored when he got
behind the Senators' defense and held off Pitlick with one arm
while knocking the puck in with the other. O'Donnell's goal was
just his second this season.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
