<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-16 02:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1918 &Cx1f; tth-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-THIEL-COLUMN-SPI &LR;      03-16 0903
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-THIEL-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE GEORGE KARL SAGA CONTINUES, BUT AT A NEW VENUE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ART THIEL  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Think of it this way, Milwaukee Bucks: The $25,000
fine that you must pay on behalf of George Karl is merely a down
payment on trouble.
</P>
<P>
   Hard to know when the full bill will come due. But it will be as
big as it is unavoidable. Someday, Karl will fit your franchise
like underwear on a porcupine.
</P>
<P>
   Don't get me wrong. I enjoy George. Upon his departure from the
Sonics, I wrote that he was the most colorful, intriguing character
in Seattle's modern pro sports history, and our corner of the world
will not be quite as entertaining.
</P>
<P>
   Then again:
</P>
<P>
   The circus has to leave town sometime.
</P>
<P>
   No one can watch ``Silence of the Lambs'' seven days a week.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-four hours in the woodshop over a table saw is hard on
the ears.
</P>
<P>
   Karl will wear out the Bucks, as he did the Sonics, as he did
the Warriors, as he did the Cavaliers. It's his nature.
</P>
<P>
   Because he's a good coach, he will rack up W's. He just can't do
it without a hard price. He's not alone in that _ see Billy Martin,
Jimmy Johnson, Red Auerbach, Vince Lombardi, Pat Riley.
</P>
<P>
   The difference is that Karl doesn't burn out his players; he
blows himself up. And over such stupid stuff.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's whopper fine from the NBA is a good example. Karl was
nailed for something that had nothing to do with a game, a bad
call, a league ruling or a civil or criminal action.
</P>
<P>
   The fine was because Karl, who had been warned by the NBA to
stop, continued his petty selfishness toward another franchise in
an embarrassing, public way. In other professions, it falls into
the category of ``conduct unbecoming ... ''
</P>
<P>
   Karl's words certainly weren't a firable offense, but players
and coaches are bound by NBA contracts to refrain from excessive
disparagement of teams and the league.
</P>
<P>
   I guarantee he won't get it.
</P>
<P>
   Even if what Karl said was accurate _ and a lot of it isn't _
his day and his rhetoric as Sonic coach are so over in Seattle that
he might as well be peddling 1962 World's Fair programs.
</P>
<P>
   He is, however, still a good coach with a good team and a
Seattle newsmaker when his new club meets his old club. That's why
the P-I sent reporter Ronald Tillery to Milwaukee ahead of last
Wednesday's Sonics-Bucks contest.
</P>
<P>
   The story plan was to go easy on the stale Walker-bashing and
heavy on the good start with the new team. Instead, Karl directed
the interview back to his vendetta, which was cited as the basis
for the fine.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wally totally discontinued the communication,'' Karl was
quoted as saying. ``He said it's because I talk too much. I say
it's because he's incompetent.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were very few negative things about Seattle outside of
Wally. I believe in doing the right things and I don't think he
does. He's a politician. He's a trickster. And that's the opposite
of how I handle my life.''
</P>
<P>
   That, in brief, is the kind of rhetoric that ended Karl's tenure
in Seattle. It's not so much that Karl was leaking sensitive
information; it's the unrelenting criticism he was passing about
his bosses.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the degree of truth in Karl's diatribes, and whatever
protections are offered by the First Amendment, anyone who's ever
had to work for a living knows that one publicly trashes a boss at
some peril to one's continued employment.
</P>
<P>
   Not exactly a scoop, eh?
</P>
<P>
   Yet nearly everyone around Karl during his tenure, including his
assistants, felt compelled to make the point again and again,
because he equated stifling his criticism with the despised word
``politics.''
</P>
<P>
   They begged him to shut up, not because they didn't necessarily
agree with him, but because the campaign helped no one but the
newspapers. The truth of that contention was right in front of
Karl: Shawn Kemp's pouts over money helped put an end to the
1996-97 Sonic season.
</P>
<P>
   The Karl-Walker tiff wasn't merely the inevitable basketball
disagreements between ownership and staff. Karl disliked Walker
from his roots (a Virginia Cavalier instead of a Carolina Tar Heel)
to his suits (Armani instead of sweats).
</P>
<P>
   He also never liked Walker's style: A by-the-book operation that
conflicted with Karl's stretch-the-rules methodology. Which makes
even more hilarious Karl's claim that Walker is a trickster. If
Karl were unleashed, he would make Rick Neuheisel and the
University of Minnesota's academic support staff look papal.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond the hypocrisy, Karl's ultimate betrayal of his allies and
his own words _ never mind his bosses _ is that he could never
subsume his visceral dislike for the greater good of the team and
franchise.
</P>
<P>
   I'm almost always a fan of those who question authority. But in
the context of team sports where the primary goal of all employees
is to win championships, the boat-rocker can go only so far before
all rowers get wet.
</P>
<P>
   The option always exists to leave the boat, but Karl found 3
million reasons to stay to the end of his Seattle contract.
</P>
<P>
   Now he has a better deal in what he claims is a better
situation. But that situation finds itself $25,000 lighter for no
valid reason whatsoever other than Karl's lack of maturity.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, for an NBA franchise, $25,000 is chump change. Just as
assuredly for Milwaukee, it's only the beginning.
</P>
<P>
   Art Thiel is a P-I columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
