<SLUG> BC-BBA-VECSEY-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARINERS CAN COUNT ON ALEX RODRIGUEZ _ FOR NOW 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LAURA VECSEY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PEORIA, Ariz. _ His team was still over at the ballpark, putting
together a comeback win over the Brewers on Monday. Alex Rodriguez
was in the clubhouse, changing from his uniform into his workout
clothes.
</P>
<P>
   That's what an 0-for-3 day in the Cactus League will do for you.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez left the game in the sixth inning, but instead of
hitting the showers, Rodriguez the major league shortstop
transformed himself into Rodriguez the 23-year-old in need of extra
batting practice.
</P>
<P>
   He picked up one of his signature black bats, the kind he has
specially made for him _ just like Ken Griffey Jr. does. Then
Rodriguez picked up another, far less glamorous number _ a
big-barreled piece of hickory all yucked up with pine tar, dirt and
goodness knows what else.
</P>
<P>
   With his choice weapons in hand, Rodriguez strode deliberately
out of the clubhouse and headed toward a bay of batting cages about
100 yards in back of the Mariners' spring training facility.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was horse(expletive) today,'' Rodriguez said in an
exaggerated monotone, just to make sure no one missed the point
that he was fabulously unhappy with his day's work at the plate.
``Can't swing the bat.''
</P>
<P>
   When a lone passerby suggested that things would probably come
around for the former American League batting champion who plays as
if he refuses to be anything less than MVP material, Rodriguez
nodded.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hope so,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   And there he stood, in a cutoff T-shirt and dark blue
compression shorts with a rip across the back of one leg, swinging
again and again at balls sent flying toward him by the pitching
machine.
</P>
<P>
   In the shaded cage, with not a soul around except a buddy
feeding the balls into the chute, the whirring sound of the
pitching-machine motor was broken only by the crack of Rodriguez's
bat.
</P>
<P>
   He smacked about 50 or 60 pitches into the netting. Then, his
arms tiring, Rodriguez declared the count to be at 3-2. He then
proceeded to ``foul off'' three more pitches before declaring the
final ball he hit to be, you got it, a home run.
</P>
<P>
   Not a single. Not a double. Not a foul ball, but a homer,
meaning that the pride of the Mariners _ or at least one of them _
had turned a negative situation into a positive.
</P>
<P>
   ``Spring is for work,'' Rodriguez said later, after he was
satisfied his timing and bat speed were now sufficiently up to
snuff.
</P>
<P>
   There is something intensely deliberate and determined about
Rodriguez, traits that have not wavered in his four seasons with
the Mariners, and already have led him to AL Player of the Year,
the 40/40 club and batting champ honors.
</P>
<P>
   What has wavered, however, is Rodriguez's faith in his future
with the M's _ a topic that has been, and will be, beaten to death
from now until the day Rodriguez, like Griffey, is either signed,
traded or whatever by the sticker-shocked Mariners.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, in the middle of spring training for a season Rodriguez
said the M's will have to overachieve in to succeed (``But, hey,
we're definitely due to overachieve. We've underachieved so much
the past couple of years.''), Rodriguez was again asked about his
future.
</P>
<P>
   Waves of TV, radio and print reporters feel obliged to ask it
and, frankly, Rodriguez is not at all shy about answering.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll see. We're still some players away from where we want to
be,'' Rodriguez said about Topic No. 1, which still eclipses talk
about where the M's will finish in the AL West.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just want to win. I'll be better able to answer that
question in about 18 months,'' said Rodriguez, whose four-year deal
(a steal considering the Nomar Garciaparra and Derek Jeter
contracts) expires after the 2000 season.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez signed that deal two years ago for security, since he
wanted to ensure that his mother and family would never be without
money. But at the time he signed his extension, Rodriguez did joke
that the next deal he signs will not be for security.
</P>
<P>
   One thing is certain: Rodriguez said Monday he is completely
open-minded about remaining a Mariner.
</P>
<P>
   He is not automatically out of here, he said. He still loves the
fans and city of Seattle, which is a good endorsement from a very
poised, slick Miami native who would certainly thrive in the bright
lights of New York or Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   But Rodriguez still is not far enough removed _ time-wise,
emotionally or competitively _ from the magic of '95. There seems a
part of him that still hopes Mariner ownership and the front office
again can put a winner on the field and restore that level of
competitiveness to the franchise.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course, we had Randy Johnson, Jeff Nelson and Norm Charlton
that year,'' Rodriguez said.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez also gave some indication that his situation, no
matter what happens, will never get as ugly as what happened with
Johnson _ though with a shark of an agent like Scott Boras, it is
tough to imagine hardball not being played on Rodriguez's behalf.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, Rodriguez is not shying away from opportunities to
gently remind the Mariners that he is definitely looking for them
to make a commitment to fielding a winner. Like Griffey said this
winter, the ball is in their hand.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, Rodriguez likes the new kid playing second base
next to him. Carlos Guillen, who arrived from Houston in the
Johnson trade, should make a difference, and not just defensively,
where the M's were miserable last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I say he's going to have a very productive offensive year. I
say he hits .280, 15 homers and 60 RBIs. Write that down and you'll
be a genius, I guarantee,'' Rodriguez said.
</P>
<P>
   Which was about one of the only things Rodriguez would
guarantee.
</P>
<P>
   Laura Vecsey is a P-I columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
