<HEADLINE>
OFFEAT OR BASIC: 10 NYC GUIDES  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MARCH 21) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By BETSY WADE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The only thing spinning faster than the machines turning out New
York guidebooks is the city itself. Publishers cannot possibly keep
up with the construction crews and busy chefs, but they sure try.
</P>
<P>
   I have been accumulating paperbacks, and in just a few weeks
gathered a stack of 23, not counting ones for people who live in
the city, like ``Short Bicycle Rides.''
</P>
<P>
   For this column, I've winnowed the list to those that appear of
widest use to Americans who are going to visit New York, and three
guides for specialized audiences: parents with young children and
nature lovers.
</P>
<P>
   But here's a word of advice: When shopping for a guide, do not
be persuaded by the 1999 on the cover, or copyright date. Most
guides are researched more than a year in advance. The easiest way
to carbon-date an edition is to check entries on the American
Museum of Natural History. If it does not say that the Hayden
Planetarium is shut, in renovation or otherwise inaccessible, it
was written before January 1997, or, worse, in ignorance of an
important change in a major attraction.
</P>
<P>
   Do not select a guidebook for maps: the free subway, bus and
combination transit maps are constantly updated, and there are
commercial maps, like Zagat's restaurant map, for special purposes.
</P>
<P>
   The two standard guidebooks first.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fodor's 99 New York City'' credits a list of 14 authors and is
$14.50. There is lots of condensed information organized for
walking and sightseeing by area, with restaurants by type. Although
the restaurant listings identify the cross streets for addresses,
an essential, the copious bar listings do not. Two pages in the
back with books and videos may not belong in a guidebook, but they
are eclectic fun: the city sits for its portrait in ``The Invisible
Man'' by Ralph Ellison as well as ``The Thin Man'' by Dashiell
Hammett, and lots of others. A Rand McNally map can be detached;
others are in the text.
</P>
<P>
   ``Frommer's 99 New York City'' by David Doty with Cynthia S.
Baker (Macmillan U.S.A., $14.95) contains many odd things; for
example, that the subway ``stinks,'' which is not normally the
case, and is ``scary.'' Doty is an authority on Paris, and it may
be that New York runs a poor second in his affections. The book is
strong on ``cultural icons'' like Grand Central Terminal, and other
architecture. Hotels and restaurants are organized by area. I noted
errors in the ``medical requirement'' section for foreigners, but
this may not have wide implications. A Frommer's map may be
detached, and there are two-color maps.
</P>
<P>
   Next come two with a slightly oblique approach.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Unofficial Guide to New York City'' by Eve Zibart and Bob
Sehlinger with Jim Leff (Macmillan U.S.A., $15.95) is the first try
at New York for the ``unofficial'' writers, who began their travels
in Orlando at least 13 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   This one must have taken a long time because the book flunks the
Planetarium test, saying it will be shut ``until at least 1998''
(it is due to reopen in 2000). But the book has a nice outspoken
tone; for example, ``learn the New York street walk: fast and
confident ... avoid the telltale clenched, fearful rush.''
</P>
<P>
   Full restaurant reviews rate the food quality on a scale of 0 to
100; the attractions get stars, and pointers to important parts of
the attraction. The safety chapter is tops, both for information
and attitude. No pictures, no maps.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Complete Idiot's Travel Guide to New York City'' by Bruce
Murphy and Alessandra de Rosa (Macmillan U.S.A., $15.95) is one of
10 cities in the Complete Idiot series, but I still cannot picture
myself in the street reading one.
</P>
<P>
   Otherwise, a good job. It uses icons to point up important or
curious facts. It includes the usual features: safety, getting
around, hotels, restaurants, major sights. The list of bars and
clubs is short enough to show that this is not a major fixation.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Despite niggling errors, the authors have it right on a number
of things, such as tipping in restaurants _ double the tax _ and
how to get a good Sunday brunch _ go early. Lots of graphics and
maps.
</P>
<P>
   Here are three that are useful as supplements to more basic
texts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Time Out New York,'' published by Penguin Books, was produced
in its sixth edition by a cast of hundreds ($14.95). Replete with
ads, pictures and a lorryful of attitude, this is the
British-derived guide to hipness. A picture of people gazing at
fish displays in Chinatown bears this caption: ``Chinese
checker-outers: Local residents shop for raw deals.''
</P>
<P>
   Not strong on architecture, but with lots of scene, this guide
is popular with young people. Older travelers might find the
typefaces minuscule.
</P>
<P>
   ``Frommer's Irreverent Guide to Manhattan'' by Ian McMahan and
Jordan Simon is in its second edition (Macmillan U.S.A., $12.95).
The sections start out with ``The Lowdown,'' but the slapdash
snobbery does not always work. ``Must-sees for second-time visitors
from Peoria'' is a sample. The research needs updating, too:
Brendan Byrne Arena is now Continental Airlines Arena.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Mad Monks' Guide to New York City'' by James Crotty and
Michael Lane (the Monks), published by Macmillan U.S.A. ($15.95),
will probably offend everyone, but has moments of high hilarity. In
a list of ``What We Hate About New York 1999'' is the following:
``Frat boy cum stockbroker cum bridge-and-tunnel weekend hangouts
that line the Upper East Side.''
</P>
<P>
   It includes interviews, photographs with a Weegee squint and a
list of songs about New York. The information is up to date, but
this is not a basic guidebook, and it is not for the kids.
</P>
<P>
   And the three narrow-focus guides.
</P>
<P>
   ``Frommer's New York City With Kids,'' sixth edition, by Holly
Hughes (Macmillan U.S.A., $15.95) had its origins in ``The Candy
Apple: New York With Kids'' by Bubbles Fisher. Ms. Hughes, a worth
successor, has three young children and, as would be expected from
a West Sider, knows that the word to apply to the Hayden
Planetarium is ``razed.''
</P>
<P>
   She has a wonderful ``treasure hunt'' for the American Museum of
Natural History and a list of books to prepare children of almost
any age. Restaurants with more than one branch are listed under
``The Chain Gang.''
</P>
<P>
   ``New York's 50 Best Places to Go Birding in and Around the Big
Apple'' by John Thaxton (City &AMP; Company, $15). The first 82 pages
in this pocket guide concern places in the city. Thaxton's paean to
the Jamaica Wildlife Refuge will guide out-of-towners to pure joy:
``And in winter, owls roost in the woodland gardens and hawks and
falcons cruise over the ponds, sometimes scaring thousands of ducks
into flight.'' It includes pen-and-ink sketches.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nature Walks in and Around New York City'' by Sheila Buff
(Appalachian Mountain Club, $12.95). A hundred of this book's 350
pages concern New York City. It is complete with maps, trail
guides, phone numbers, distances, some small photographs and other
data usually found in a.m.C. guides.
</P>
<P>
   This is not poetry, but it's packed with facts. The entry on
Inwood Hill Park has geological information, though the book
virtually bypasses the Reservoir in Central Park, saying it's for
joggers. Clay Pits Pond State Park on Staten Island, one of the few
state parks in the city, gets a good entry, including how to get
there by mass transit.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-16-99 0206EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
