<HEADLINE>
VISITING CARNAC  
 DUBLIN LITERARY TOURS  
 JAPANESE RAIL PASSES  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MARCH 21) 
</HEADLINE>
   By SUZANNE MacNEILLE (af)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. (italics)Can you tell me when Carnac, the French
archeological park, is open to the public? I have heard that access
is restricted. _ Lionel P. Herd, Seattle(end italics) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. In recent years, the trampling of vegetation caused by the
sheer volume of visitors has prompted French park officials to
limit access to Carnac to the summer. But this year there are plans
to open the prehistoric site during the 1999-2000 off-season as
well.
</P>
<P>
   Carnac, near the Breton coast, and just north of the town of
Carnac, is the name given to the barren countryside that is strewn
with thousands of enigmatically placed stones dating from Neolithic
times. Many of these huge stones are arranged in parallel rows;
some mark dolmens, or ancient burial sites.
</P>
<P>
   The meaning of the menhirs, or standing stones _ some as high as
60 feet _ has been endlessly debated. The most popular theories
assign them religious or astronomical significance.
</P>
<P>
   Until 1991, the site attracted 800,000 visitors a year. But then
the ministry of culture, which oversees the site, discovered that
the damage caused by thousands of tourists walking on the heather,
prickly juniper and other delicate vegetation that helped anchor
the stones to the ground was causing some of the menhirs to be
displaced. As a result, visits to the site were limited to small
groups during the summer.
</P>
<P>
   Plans now call for opening the park to individual, unguided
visits in the off-season from Oct. 1 to April 1, 2000. Admission
will be free.
</P>
<P>
   During the busier summer months, the park will continue to be
open to groups of 25 for guided tours only, with a limit of 180
people a day. The tours, which are offered by the site's visitor
center, cost $5.50, and last an hour and a half.
</P>
<P>
   By calling the center in advance, it is possible to find out
when a group visit is scheduled for the day you're visiting and if
the quota of visitors has been filled. The number is (33-2)
97.52.89.99.
</P>
<P>
   BLB Tourisme, based in nearby Auray, offers tours to the site,
including a half-day trip. The total cost is $150, regardless of
group size. Information: (33-2) 97.56.60.86.
</P>
<P>
   You may also be interested in stopping at the Prehistoric
Museum, in the center of the town of Carnac, near the mayor's
office. The museum contains numerous Carnac artifacts, including
pottery, tools and weapons. It is open Wednesdays to Mondays, from
10 a.m. to noon and from 2 to 5 p.m. In July and August, the museum
is open daily, from 10 a.m. to 6 p.m. Admission is $5.50.
Information: (33-2) 97.52.22.04. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. (italics)Can you give me some suggestions for guided literary
tours in Dublin? I'm especially interested in James Joyce. _ Mary
Lynn Mercer, Tampa, Fla.(end italics)
</P>
<P>
   A. You won't have a hard time finding literary tours in Dublin,
a city linked to such writers as Bram Stoker, Jonathan Swift, J. M.
Synge, William Butler Yeats, Sean O'Casey, Samuel Beckett, Oscar
Wilde and James Joyce, among many others.
</P>
<P>
   Here are a few possibilities:
</P>
<P>
   The Literary Pub Crawl is a two-and-a-half hour tour led by
professional actors who perform work by some of Dublin's writers
while guiding you around the city's most famous literary haunts. It
starts on Duke Street, where that street's many connections with
Joyce and his novel ``Ulysses'' are discussed.
</P>
<P>
   The route passes by Trinity College, associated with writers
such as Synge, Bram Stoker and Swift, and includes stops such as
The Old Stand, a former haunt of Brendan Behan's. Among the works
performed and discussed are excerpts from Beckett's ``Waiting for
Godot'' and O'Casey's ``Juno and the Paycock.''
</P>
<P>
   Tours, which cost $9, are conducted Thursday to Sunday at 7:30
p.m., with an additional tour on Sunday at noon; from April 5 to
Oct. 31, tours are at 7:30 p.m. daily. Information: (353-1) 670
5602, fax (353-1) 4545 680.
</P>
<P>
   A tour that focuses solely on James Joyce is offered by the
James Joyce Center at 35 Great George's Street North. Among the
places visited are the Jesuit-run Belvedere College, where Joyce
was a student; 5 Parnell Square, former home of Oliver St. John
Gogarty, the poet, politician, athlete, surgeon and writer who was
the model for Buck Mulligan in ``Ulysses;'' and 44 Fontenoy Street,
the last home in which the Joyce family lived in Dublin.
</P>
<P>
   The 90-minute tour, which starts at 2:30 and costs $9 is offered
on Mondays to Fridays until June. From June through September it is
offered daily. Information: (353-1) 8788 547.
</P>
<P>
   Dara Nolan, who represents the Association of Approved Tour
Guides, can put you in touch with guides who specialize in private
literary tours. A half-day tour costs $72. Her telephone and fax
number is (353-1) 278 1626.
</P>
<P>
   If you want to explore independently, the Dublin Tourism Center
on Suffolk Street publishes a number of booklets, maps and leaflets
that include information about the city's literary sites. For more
information call the Irish Tourist Board in New York (800)
742-6765. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. (italics)Do you have information on Japan Rail Passes? _
Ingrid Salzmann, New York, N.Y.(end italics)
</P>
<P>
   A. Foreign tourists visiting Japan may purchase special passes
that can be used on most of Japan Rail trains (exceptions include
the Nozomi Super Express), as well as on many buses and ferries.
The pass must be purchased through travel agents before arriving in
Japan. The Japan Rail West passes for travel in the Sanyo and
Kansai areas are the only passes that can be purchased in Japan.
</P>
<P>
   The standard, countrywide passes allow unlimited travel for 7,
14 and 21 days. While the prices are set by Japan Rail, authorized
travel companies that sell the passes in the United States (either
directly to the traveler, or through your personal travel agent)
may use different exchange rates.
</P>
<P>
   For example, earlier this month, Kinetsu International Express,
(800) 422-3481, sold the passes at a rate of 118 yen to the dollar,
resulting in these coach fares: $240 (28,300 yen) for 7 days, $382
(45,100) yen for 14 days and $489 (57,700 yen) for 21 days.
First-class rates, student and children's fares are also available.
</P>
<P>
   Among the regional passes are the JR East Pass (includes Tokyo
and Nagano ski areas), the JR Kyushu Pass (in and around Kyushu
Island) and the JR West passes mentioned above.
</P>
<P>
   For a brochure contact the Japan National Tourist Board, 1
Rockefeller Plaza, Suite 1250, New York, N.Y. 10020; (212)
757-5640, fax (212) 307-6754.
</P>
<P>
   Suzanne MacNeille
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
