<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-BRIEFS-$ADV21-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHORT NOTES ON TRAVEL  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MARCH 21) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Win One, Lose One: Michelin Unveils 3-Stars &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The 90th edition of the Michelin Red Guide to France was
released March 3, bestowing one new three-star rating, on the chef
Michel Bras, for the restaurant that bears his name in Laguiole
(pronounced Lie-OLE) in the Auvergne region of south-central
France.
</P>
<P>
   One restaurant, Marc Meneau's Esperance in the Burgundian
village of Vezelay, was demoted from three stars to two. Thus the
number of three-star restaurants remains unchanged at 21, with 6 in
Paris and 15 in the provinces. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The French guide was particularly generous this year, adding
nine restaurants to the two-star roster. Frederic Anton, who
studied under Joel Robuchon, won two stars at the Pre Catelan in
the Bois de Boulogne, in Paris, and Eric Lecerf was elevated from
one star to two at the Astor in the Hotel Astor in Paris.
</P>
<P>
   Christian Le Squer, who has been at the restaurant Ledoyen in
Paris only six months, managed to retain the two stars won by
Ledoyen's former chef, Ghislaine Arabian. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Other new two-stars include Christian Constant's Violon d'Ingres
in Paris, Clos de la Violette in Aix-en-Provence, and Moulin de
Lourmarin in Lourmarin, in the Luberon.
</P>
<P>
   With guides published earlier this year elsewhere in Europe,
there were no changes in three-star lineups. Italy now boasts two
new two-stars: Da Caino in Montemerano and Dolada in Pieve
D'Alpago.
</P>
<P>
   Significant changes took place in Britain, with three new
two-stars, including the Gidleigh Park in Chagford, Devon, and 14
new one-stars, including the Fat Duck in Bray on Thames.
</P>
<P>
   In Portugal, the Vila Joya in Albufeira has been upgraded to two
stars, and in Spain, the popular Madrid restaurant Viridiana lost
its single star. New two-stars in Germany include La Table in
Dortmund-Syburg and Steinheuers Restaurant Zur Alten Post in
Neuenahr-Ahrweiler.
</P>
<P>
   Switzerland claims two new two-stars: Cerf in Cossonay and Haus
Paradies in Ftan. The longtime traditional Swiss restaurant
Bruderholz (formerly known as Stucki) in Basel lost one of its two
stars. In the Benelux countries, new two-stars include De
Bellefleur in Antwerp, Belgium; and in the Netherlands, Oud Sluis
in Sluis and De Librije in Zwolle.
</P>
<P>
   Patricia Wells &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Jamaica Takes Steps To Protect Tourists &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Jamaica is putting soldiers in tourist areas to prevent thefts
and harassment of visitors. The new policy of using members of the
country's military, mostly in plainclothes and some armed with
pistols, to augment police protection was announced in January by
Francis Tulloch, the minister of tourism, with the strong support
of the island's hotel association. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Jamaican officials say crimes against tourists have dropped 50
percent in the last 10 years, but harassment of visitors from
cruise ships received extensive publicity last winter, as did three
recent armed attacks.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Martin, a spokesman for the Jamaica Tourist Board in New
York, said that although the tourist total had risen substantially
over 10 years _ the level is now 1.9 million a year, including
nearly 700,000 cruise passengers, Martin said _ the police force
had not grown commensurately. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``This reinforcing presence is unobtrusive,'' Martin said, ``but
obvious to those that count.'' These include local hawkers, he
said, ``and other antisocial elements.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Rooms and Tickets For Sydney Olympics &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The next Olympic Summer Games, to be held in Sydney, are a
little less than 18 months away, but it's not too early to order
hotel accommodations and tickets. Cartan Tours, the company chosen
by the organizers of the Sydney games as the official United States
sales agent for Olympics tickets and tours, began taking orders
last week for the Games, scheduled for Sept. 15 to Oct. 1, 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Don Williams, Cartan's vice president, said that Olympic tickets
will range from $8 for early-round soccer games to $1,054 for top
seats at the opening and closing ceremonies.
</P>
<P>
   Basketball preliminaries are $42, the finals $248 to $347;
gymnastics start at $65 for opening rounds and go up to $217 to
$271 for finals. Customers will know by Sept. 30 if their orders
can be filled for the events they requested.
</P>
<P>
   Cartan has a choice of hotels in Sydney or in the Blue
Mountains, a region of spectacular natural beauty about 90 minutes
from the city, or the Central Coast, an area just north of the city
that is famous for its beaches and headlands.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Train service _ free to Olympic ticket holders on the day of the
event they attend _ is available to the Blue Mountains and Central
Coast. Cartan's packages will include transportation to the events,
most of which will take place in Homebush Bay, nine miles west of
downtown Sydney.
</P>
<P>
   Six-night accommodation packages _ including round-trip air fare
from Los Angeles, airport transfers and full breakfast daily _
start at $4,990 a person, double occupancy, for rooms with private
homeowners. For rooms in pubs (the equivalent of a small hotel in
the United States), rates start at $5,190; the hotel packages start
at $5,490. Olympic tickets are extra.
</P>
<P>
   Top-category hotels include the Avillion and the Radisson Plaza.
For families, the Metro Inn and Apartments or Pacific International
are recommended. Suburban hotels include the Hawkesbury Lodge in
Windsor, a resort not far from the rowing events.
</P>
<P>
   Cartan is also selling pre- or post-Olympic visits to the Hunter
Valley wine-growing region, two hours north of Sydney. For a
48-page brochure, call (800) 841-1994 or www.cartan.com on the Web.
</P>
<P>
   Joseph Siano &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In Atlanta, a Case of Impressionist Fever &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The High Museum of Art in Atlanta is destined to be a popular
place for the next few months: Not one, but two exhibitions of
Impressionism _ the museum world's biggest crowd-pleaser _ have
taken over its fourth floor until May 16.
</P>
<P>
   ``Impressionism: Paintings Collected by European Museums,''
which retells the story of Impressionism's development and initial
rejection by the establishment, brings together 60 works by
Cezanne, van Gogh, Manet, Renoir, Cassatt, Sisley and others.
</P>
<P>
   They are drawn from 39 collections in 13 countries, including
those of the Musee d'Orsay in Paris, the National Gallery in London
and the National Gallery of Scotland.
</P>
<P>
   Such renowned works as Monet's ``Port at Argenteuil,''
Pissarro's ``Avenue de l'Opera: Sunshine, Winter Morning'' and van
Gogh's ``Portrait of Armand Roulin'' are on view; and so are works
by several lesser-known Impressionists like Marie Bracquemond,
Jean-Baptiste Armand Guillaumin and Jean-Francois Raffaelli.
</P>
<P>
   The High's other show, ``Monet and Bazille: A Collaboration'' is
the first exhibition to examine the relationship between two
founding members of Impressionism. The duo met as art students in
1863, shared a succession of studios and traveled together to paint
the coast of Normandy and the countryside near Fontainebleau.
</P>
<P>
   Bazille's career ended tragically when he died in 1870, at the
age of 28, in the Franco-Prussian War. He did many figure paintings
and landscapes, but is perhaps best known for his series of
paintings of his friends' studios, with identifiable paintings in
view, such as the two in this exhibition.
</P>
<P>
   Among the 20 paintings in ``Monet and Bazille'' are Monet's
``Strollers,'' Bazille's ``View of the Village'' and, for direct
comparison, scenes of the seaside at Ste.-Adresse by each artist.
</P>
<P>
   Other Atlanta institutions have also caught Impressionist fever.
The Atlanta Botanical Garden is offering self-guided tours
highlighting ``Plants of Monet's Garden.'' The Atlanta Ballet, the
Atlanta Symphony and two theaters are offering discounts to museum
ticket-holders.
</P>
<P>
   Eleven hotels have one-night package deals that include two
tickets to the museum and breakfast for two. Prices range from $125
at the Georgian Terrace Hotel to $195 at the Four Seasons Hotel.
Information: the Atlanta Convention and Visitors Bureau, (800)
285-2682.
</P>
<P>
   ``Impressionism: Paintings Collected by European Museums'' will
travel to the Seattle Art Museum (June 12 through Aug. 29) and to
the Denver Art Museum (Oct. 2 through Dec. 12). ``Monet and
Bazille'' will not travel.
</P>
<P>
   The High Museum, at 1280 Peachtree Street, N.E., is open daily
during these exhibitions. (It is normally closed on Mondays.)
Tickets, which are dated and timed, cost $13 for adults on weekdays
and $15 on weekends and are available at the museum box office,
(404) 733-5000, or through Ticketmaster, (404) 817-8700. Judith H.
Dobrzynski
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
