<BODY>
<HEADLINE>
EAGLES BOW TO VOLUNTEERS 
</HEADLINE>
 BKW-BOSTON COLLEGE-TENNESSEE-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUSAN BICKELHAUPT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   KNOXVILLE, Tenn. _ The Boston College women's basketball team,
coming off of its best season, tried to prove to itself and to a
national television audience that it could play with the best. It
wanted to prove that it could do battle with the Tennessee Lady
Vols. And it did _ for half a game.
</P>
<P>
   But in the end, Tennessee showed why it is ranked second in the
country, seeded first in the region, and a three-time defending
NCAA champion. The Lady Vols rolled over the Eagles, 89-62, before
9,907 at Thompson-Boling Arena Monday night in the second round of
the NCAA Tournament. Tennessee (30-2) will go on to face Virginia
Tech in Saturday's East Regional semifinals in Greensboro, N.C.
</P>
<P>
   BC freshman guard Brianne Stepherson said, ``We did show people
in the first half that we have the ability to play with a team like
that.''
</P>
<P>
   But, she added, ``A game's not 20 minutes, it's a full 40
minutes.''
</P>
<P>
   It didn't seem to affect Tennessee to be playing without guard
Semeka Randall, who sprained her ankle Saturday. Forward Chamique
Holdsclaw, one of three Lady Vols named All-American last week,
almost singlehandedly destroyed the Eagles with 39 points, tying
her career high. Sophomore forward Tamika Catchings scored 13
points, and center Michelle Snow added 12.
</P>
<P>
   The eighth-seeded Eagles (22-8) seemed ready to stand up to
Tennessee and write another chapter in their history book. After
Tennessee missed its first two shots, BC freshman Nicole Conway
fired up a 3-pointer, and the Eagles were on their way. Holdsclaw
hit a basket, but Stepherson sank another 3-pointer, and BC had a
6-2 lead.
</P>
<P>
   BC led for the first eight minutes, until Tennessee tied it at
14-14. Even when the Lady Vols took a 25-19 lead, BC refused to get
rattled. The Eagles came back behind two 3-pointers by Alissa
Murphy and regained the lead at 29-27.
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee kept trying to establish its dominance, as Holdsclaw
hit on 9 of 12 field goal attempts and finished the half with 23
points.
</P>
<P>
   But 6-foot-3-inch BC center Jamie Cournoyer, who had been
averaging only 4.5 points per game, had a perfect half, going 5 for
5 on field goals and hitting all three free throws.
</P>
<P>
   The Eagles, looking nothing like the underdogs they were
supposed to be, trailed by only 1 at the half, 42-41.
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee coach Pat Summitt let her team know that she was not
happy with the first-half performance. So when the second half
began, the Lady Vols starting putting pressure on BC, starting with
a 6-0 run and holding both Stepherson and Murphy scoreless the rest
of the way.
</P>
<P>
   ``We made sure Murphy didn't get the basketball,'' said Summitt.
``We made other people handle the ball.''
</P>
<P>
   Murphy was held to 12 points, while Stepherson's scoring was
limited to her one 3-pointer. Tennessee also started pulling down
rebounds, grabbing 35 in the game to BC's 23.
</P>
<P>
   As the Eagles ran into foul trouble, Stepherson, then Becky
Gottstein, then Murphy took seats on the bench. The brightest spot
for the Eagles was Cournoyer, who had a career-high 16 points.
Conway added another 16 and grabbed 8 rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   A somber BC coach Cathy Inglese said, ``I was pleased with our
first-half efforts, but Tennessee did a great job defensively in
the second half, and our fouls got us into trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   As the Eagles head back home after their first NCAA appearance,
Inglese said she was proud of them.
</P>
<P>
   ``This showed a heck of a lot of character,'' she said. ``I
can't have been more proud of our freshman class.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
