<HEADER>
A1928 &Cx1f; tth-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-MARINERS-TAYLOR-S     03-16 1276
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-TAYLOR-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORMER `NATURAL' BRIEN TAYLOR WORKING TO REGAIN HIS FORM, THIS TIME
WITH M'S 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TYLER KEPNER  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PEORIA, Ariz. _ The 3,000 fans and several dozen players at Fort
Lauderdale Stadium thought they were seeing the future. The energy
of March 4, 1993 still reverberates within Brien Taylor, who can
call it up on command. It is proof, in a way, of who he once was.
</P>
<P>
   It was a New York Yankees intrasquad game, and the 21-year-old
Taylor was facing major league hitters for the first time. He would
no doubt be doing so for many years, and was ticketed to start for
real sometime in '94.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor heard it all: This kid throws bullets. How can he pitch
in the mid-90s with a motion so easy and smooth? With that
fastball, he can be as dominant as anyone.
</P>
<P>
   The last endorsement came from Bernie Williams. Taylor retired
him that day, he remembers, with fastballs at the knees. Two
shutout innings, and the quiet, proud kid from rural North Carolina
was the toast of New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember a guy asking me, Don't you think you're better than
everybody here?'' Taylor said the other day, shaking his head.
``Out of the blue, first question. I said, no chance.''
</P>
<P>
   But the question was not so unreasonable. Taylor had been the
No. 1 pick in the country in 1991, four years after Ken Griffey
Jr., two years before Alex Rodriguez. His first two minor league
seasons, he averaged more than a strikeout per inning. Greatness
was all but guaranteed.
</P>
<P>
   And then he nearly lost it all.
</P>
<P>
   These days, the 27-year-old Taylor rises at 6:30 a.m. from his
room at the local Comfort Inn. He catches the early bus to the
Peoria Sports Complex, and arrives before 7 every morning. Griffey
and Rodriguez have lockers in the same building, but in a very
different room.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor is a Mariner farmhand, signed by Seattle as a minor
league free agent in January. He spent seven years with the
Yankees, but never made it past Class A after injuring his shoulder
defending his brother in a fight in December 1993. No other player
picked No. 1 overall from 1967-95 has failed to make the majors.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners have a year to see if Taylor can. He signed a
one-year contract, and must be put on the 40-man roster after this
season or he becomes a free agent. If Taylor's arm strength is
where it was last year, when the M's clocked him at 94 mph, he
could be a starter someday.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's not the 98-99 mph fastball guy (anymore), but he doesn't
need to apologize for his fastball, either,'' said Bryan Price, the
Mariners' minor league pitching coordinator. ``He still throws the
ball pretty darn good. Maybe he's not going to be the overpowering
No. 1 starter for the New York Yankees, but he could very easily be
maybe a No. 4 or 5 starter or a top left-handed relief pitcher with
the Seattle Mariners. And that I think would be probably just fine
with him. It certainly would be fine with us.''
</P>
<P>
   For Taylor, it is less a chance to start over than a chance to
continue his progress. But that progress has not been evident in
his statistics. After missing all of 1994, Taylor has gone 3-15
with a 10.85 earned run average. In 1082/3 innings, he has walked
175 and struck out 86.
</P>
<P>
   Much of that time has been spent simply building back strength
or working on mechanics in extended spring training. Taylor has
pitched only 21 games the past two years, but he said he hasn't
been hurt. His problem has been control, not velocity, but Taylor
said he has seen subtle improvements each year.
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as getting a feel for the game, going there every day,
getting into a rhythm, that's never happened,'' he said. ``But now
I feel confident because my arm strength's there and I've got an
idea of where the zone is again. But still, from there, I've got to
pitch.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners are giving Taylor extra attention. One of the main
reasons they've brought former St. Louis Cardinals pitching coach
Hub Kittle to camp is to tutor Taylor. Farm director Benny Looper
considers Kittle an expert on correcting control problems of young
pitchers, pointing to Ken Hill and Todd Worrell as examples.
</P>
<P>
   Kittle traces Taylor's control problems to ``long-arming'' the
ball and striding too far toward first base in his delivery. Price
has detected a hitch in Taylor's arm swing in which he pauses for
an instant, throwing off his timing and making it hard to find a
consistent release point.
</P>
<P>
   There are bound to be more suggestions, and Taylor also is
trying to develop a slider. It's a lot to digest, and the Mariners
acknowledge they might need to put Taylor in extended spring
training as they introduce new ideas to him. If those ideas take,
Taylor likely will start at Class AA New Haven or Class AAA Tacoma.
</P>
<P>
   ``We certainly didn't sign him to bring him along step by step,
A-ball to double-A to triple-A,'' Price said. ``We want to put him
in a situation where we can start thinking about him as a major
league pitcher. If we're doing that down here, fine. But if he's
throwing the ball the way he's capable of, I don't think he'll be
pitching in A-ball.''
</P>
<P>
   The most important thing for Taylor, Looper said, is re-gaining
his confidence. He will pitch consistently when he's ready, he
said, and it doesn't matter if that comes at the lowest level or
Class AAA.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor said he's never lacked confidence. When the Yankees tried
to wow the small-town kid with a $300,000 bonus, he and his family
called their bluff and got a record $1.55 million. When Yankees
manager Buck Showalter asked if he was nervous before that
intrasquad game in '93, Taylor replied, ``Why should I be? They
should be nervous.'' It's no different now.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would never have thrown that hard forever anyway,'' Taylor
said. ``I look at it as, I've still got a great arm, throw with
good velocity, get them out. I can still be a great pitcher.''
</P>
<P>
   If he was going to quit, Taylor said, he would have done it his
first year after shoulder surgery, when he realized he would never
again be a natural. He would feel fine one day, then be unable to
lift his arm the next two or three days. He was physically
incapable of being who he was supposed to be, yet unable to escape
his own shadow.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me,'' Taylor said, ``it was more like, OK, this is Brien
Taylor, good is not good. You've got to be awesome. So then you're
so far away in your mind from where you had been, but you've got to
go back there. But I loved it, and I didn't want to walk away.''
</P>
<P>
   If he weren't playing, Taylor said, he probably would go to
college and become an electrician. For Sunday dinners, he would do
what he does now in the offseason, driving from his home in
Raleigh, N.C., to his parents' home in Beaufort, the one his bonus
money helped build.
</P>
<P>
   But the part about fading away and becoming a regular guy? That
happened long ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the bigger cities, it's like nobody knows you,'' Taylor
said. ``Once you're not a great pitcher, a lot of people don't have
a clue who you are. You can disappear just that fast.
</P>
<P>
   ``Honestly, I'm glad all the other stuff went away, like the
fame and the people around me all the time. That was the external
stuff that comes with it when you're great, but it can be a burden.
When it disappeared, it really didn't bother me. But losing my
talent bothered me. You can't have it two ways.''
</P>
<P>
   Taylor paused. Yes, the talent he once had is gone. But to him,
and the Mariners, the story isn't over.
</P>
<P>
   ``You got a (bad) break, but the most important thing is, Can
you get it back again?'' Taylor said. ``I'm still here.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
