<HEADER>
A1938 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKW-UCLA-LADN-(SLANG)     03-16 0329
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKW-UCLA-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UCLA ADVANCES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LEE BARNATHAN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ This time, there were no last-second shot-clock
problems, no eight-tenths of a second that lasted forever.
</P>
<P>
   This time, there was time for the UCLA players to savor a 87-63
run-away second-round victory over the Kentucky Wildcats on Monday
night in an NCAA Women's Tournament game at Pauley Pavilion.
</P>
<P>
   UCLA advances to the West Regional Saturday at the Sports Arena
against second-seeded Colorado State.
</P>
<P>
   In last year's second round at Alabama, UCLA fell victim to a
scorekeeper who failed to restart the clock on time, giving Alabama
more than the .8 that remained to sink its winning jumper.
</P>
<P>
   There would be nothing to worry about this time in the second
meeting this season between the two teams. UCLA won 64-54 on Nov.
29 in the finals of the Rainbow Wahine Classic in Hawaii.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins led 34-24 at the half, but Kentucky came out strongly
from the opening tip, going on a 12-2 run in the first 6{ minutes,
helped by Hubbard and Gomez, who each picked up two fouls in that
span. Hubbard never returned in the half, and Gomez didn't come
back until there were about six minutes left.
</P>
<P>
   Foul trouble usually means big trouble for UCLA, but the Bruins
slowly came back, thanks in part to Kentucky's similar predicament.
The Wildcats had 15 fouls, compared to UCLA's eight.
</P>
<P>
   UCLA only made seven field goals, failing to sink even one for a
stretch of 4:55 at one point but converted 17 of 18 free throws.
Martin made 10 by herself, which came in handy because she didn't
attempt a field goal until 10:13 remained in the half. She was just
1 of 3.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins went on a 16-3 run in 3:36 to turn the 12-2 deficit
into an 18-15 lead with 7:26 to play in the half.
</P>
<P>
   Then, after the Wildcats scored four straight points, UCLA
scored 14 in a row in 3:32 to build its lead to 32-19.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
