A1950 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-KINGS2-LADN-(SLAN     03-16 0679
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-KINGS2-LADN-(SLANG)_WRITETHROUGH </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KINGS' PULSE REMAINS STRONG
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROGER PHILLIPS  
 c.1999 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR; INGLEWOOD, Calif. _ It has gone from a flicker to a flame.
</P>
<P>
   Given up for dead a week ago, the Los Angeles Kings suddenly are
very much alive.
</P>
<P>
   With their third consecutive strong effort, this one against one
of the best teams in the National Hockey League, the Kings took
another big step in their late-season bid to get back in the
playoff race. They defeated the Eastern Conference-leading Ottawa
Senators on Monday night by a 4-0 margin before a Forum crowd of
12,640.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we play like that,'' center Ian Laperriere said, ``we're
going to win more games than we lose.''
</P>
<P>
   Rob Blake and Philippe Boucher scored late in the second period
to break up a scoreless tie, and Donald Audette and Glen Murray
provided third-period insurance goals. That paved the way for the
Kings to put together a three-game winning streak, their longest
since they won five straight in late December and early January.
</P>
<P>
   Stephane Fiset stopped 29 shots to record his second shutout
this season and the 14th of his career. Fiset has allowed only
three goals during the winning streak, stopping 87 of 89 shots on
goal.
</P>
<P>
   With 15 games remaining, the Kings (26-36-5) moved to within
three points of idle Calgary and Edmonton, which share the final
Western Conference playoff berth.
</P>
<P>
   The Senators (38-20-8) lost their second straight following a
five-game winning streak, and fell to 0-6 at the Forum, an arena
they will not be visiting again.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted to play patient,'' coach Larry Robinson said. ``They
are in some ways a very frustrating team to play against. They've
got a lot of speed and they come at you in waves and finish their
checks. If you stray from your game plan, you give them chances and
they are very scary team to play against.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the Kings stuck with their game plan.
</P>
<P>
   In the first period, the Kings outshot Ottawa by a meager 5-4
margin, but in the second, they stepped up their forechecking and
outshot the Senators 17-10. Again and again, Kings players would
join the play late to receive a pass and take a shot.
</P>
<P>
   But for most of the second period, the outstanding play of
Senators goalie Ron Tugnutt _ who began the night with a
microscopic 1.60 goals-against average _ negated the Kings'
opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   Then, with 6:07 to play in the period, Laperriere drew a
roughing penalty from Senators defenseman Lance Pitlick, giving the
Kings their second power play of the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had punched him before,'' Laperriere said. ``(The referee)
never calls the first punch. He always calls the second, and
(Pitlick) punched me back.''
</P>
<P>
   The Kings wasted little time capitalizing on their power play.
They gained control of the puck, moving it around until it finally
landed on Blake's stick at the left boards.
</P>
<P>
   With Ray Ferraro in front of the net, Blake fired a slap shot
that beat Tugnutt to the short side at 14:38. It was Blake's ninth
goal this season, his fifth in the last nine games, and the 100th
of his nine-year NHL career.
</P>
<P>
   Less than three minutes later, Boucher scored his second goal of
the season, a shot off a pass from Ferraro that banked off two
Senators in front, then off the right goal post and finally past
Tugnutt.
</P>
<P>
   ``We must be in a vacation mode or something out here, losing
these last two games,'' Tugnutt said. ``The first 10 minutes in San
Jose and most of the night tonight, we really weren't there. We let
them control the game all night long. It's not so much losing
back-to-back as it is how you lose them.''
</P>
<P>
   The Kings broke the game open early in the third, Audette and
Murray scoring 44 seconds apart. It was the first goal since Dec.
30 for Murray, who missed 19 games with a knee injury.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, the Kings are doing all the things they hadn't been
doing all season. Suddenly, a playoff berth is in sight.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can control one thing,'' Blake said, ``and that's how we
play.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
