<HEADER>
A1953 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKW-UCLA2-LADN-(SLANG     03-16 0629
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKW-UCLA2-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SWEET 16 FOR BRUINS THIS TIME
</HEADLINE>
 ...WRITETHRU (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LEE BARNATHAN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ There was no last-second shot-clock glitches or
any second-half defensive letdowns.
</P>
<P>
   Just the kind of game the UCLA women's basketball team needed to
play to beat Kentucky and reach the the NCAA Tournament's Sweet 16
for the first time since 1992.
</P>
<P>
   The third-seeded Bruins overcame early foul trouble, made 32 of
35 free throws and didn't let up defensively and forced Kentucky
into a 33-percent shooting night in securing an 87-63 rout of the
sixth-seeded Wildcats Monday night before 2,604 at Pauley Pavilion.
</P>
<P>
   Maylana Martin scored 21 points, including 15 of 15 free throws,
and grabbed 12 rebounds as the Bruins (25-7) advanced to the West
Regional Saturday at the Sports Arena against second-seeded
Colorado State. Kentucky finished 21-11.
</P>
<P>
   Marie Philman scored 16 points and had 10 rebounds for the
Bruins, and Janae Hubbard scored all 13 of her points in the second
half.
</P>
<P>
   In last year's second round at Alabama, a slow-to-start shot
clock gave Alabama more than eight-tenths of a second left to get
off the final shot and steal a victory. Monday night, UCLA never
let Kentucky get that close.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year was on our mind,'' said Melanie Pearson, who scored
13 points. ``We know we can go farther.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin, as often is the case, was a main reason why. She usually
doesn't play the entire first half but had to when Hubbard picked
up her second foul with just two and a half minutes gone.
</P>
<P>
   She also usually gets more than three shots in the first half,
but Kentucky keyed on her defensively. She didn't get her first
attempt until there was 10:13 left in the first half. Her one field
goal came with 3:29 to play.
</P>
<P>
   So Martin hurt the Wildcats in other ways. She sank 11 of 11
free throws and took six rebounds in the first half.
</P>
<P>
   ``Her back was bothering her (Sunday), so we told her, `For 10
minutes, you go work on free throws while the team does other
stuff,' '' UCLA coach Kathy Olivier said. ``It paid off.''
</P>
<P>
   This was the second meeting between the two teams. UCLA won
64-54 on Nov. 29 in the final of the Rainbow Wahine Classic in
Hawaii. In that game, Martin had 11 points and 14 rebounds, and
Philman had 19 points but just three rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``My shot hasn't been on for the past 10 games,'' Philman said.
``I had to pick it up defensively, and I could do that by
rebounding.''
</P>
<P>
   Kentucky came out strongly, going on a 12-2 run in the first 6{
minutes, helped by Hubbard and Erica Gomez each picking up two
fouls in that span. Hubbard never returned in the half and Gomez
didn't come back until there were about six minutes left.
</P>
<P>
   Usually, foul trouble means big trouble for UCLA, but the Bruins
slowly came back, thanks in part to Kentucky's similar foul
troubles. The Wildcats committed 15 fouls, compared to UCLA's
eight.
</P>
<P>
   UCLA only made seven field goals (and didn't sink one for one
stretch of 4:55) but converted 17 of 18 free throws. The Bruins
also went on a 16-3 run in 3:36 to turn the 12-2 deficit into an
18-15 lead with 7:26 to play in the half. Then, after the Wildcats
scored four straight points, UCLA scored 14 in a row in 3:32 to
build its lead to 32-19.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins led 34-24 at the half, but Kentucky cut it to six
points early on. It appeared another defensive lapse was imminent,
similar to the one Saturday, when Wisconsin-Green Bay ran off 22 of
31 points.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, it was the Bruins who turned it up. A 19-8 run in 5:41
put UCLA ahead 63-40. Everybody got involved in that run; five
players scored.
</P>
<P>
   Forward LaTonya NcDole led the Wildcats with 16 points and for
Laura Meadows.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-16-99 0306EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
