A1962 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FORBES-CANDIDACY-SFCH     03-16 0673
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FORBES-CANDIDACY-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 REPUBLICAN TAKES LEAP WITH HIGH-TECH PRESIDENTIAL BID  &HT;     By MARC SANDALOW 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
WASHINGTON _ Steve Forbes, whose family made millions of dollars
with the printed word, will announce his candidacy for the
Republican presidential nomination Tuesday in cyberspace.
<P>
   ``You and I are entering the information age _ and the
Washington politicians are stuck in the Stone Age,'' Forbes said in
a statement to be posted on his Web site (www.forbes2000.com) by 5
a.m. PST.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is going to be a new, information-age campaign about
great ideas and enduring values,'' Forbes said. ``Today marks the
beginning of a national crusade to restore Ronald Reagan's vision
of hope and prosperity for all Americans.''
</P>
<P>
   Forbes joins a growing field of Republican hopefuls, currently
led by Texas Governor George W. Bush and former Cabinet secretary
Elizabeth Dole. In hundreds of appearances over the past several
years, Forbes has tried to win over fiscal and social conservatives
by championing both tax reform and the rights of the unborn.
</P>
<P>
   It may be harder for him to assume the mantle of darling of the
high-tech community. Bush already has the support of many
Republicans in Silicon Valley, and Vice President Al Gore is
counting on high-tech Democrats to help finance his campaign. Gore
is so comfortable with his cutting-edge credentials that he even
claimed during a television interview last week to have helped
invent the Internet, prompting former Vice President Dan Quayle to
quip Monday that ``If Gore invented the Internet, I invented
spell-check.''
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, the heir to the Forbes publishing fortune says he
will ``run the first full-scale presidential campaign in American
history on the Internet _ because I want you to be involved every
step of the way.''
</P>
<P>
   Every major presidential candidate boasts a Web site, although
their value has been largely confined to providing information to
volunteers, curiosity seekers and news reporters. Rep. John Kasich,
an Ohio Republican running for president, even sent reporters a
printed news release when his web site (www.k2k.org) was named
``Political Web Site of the Day'' by one reviewer.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes, who spent about $35 million of his own money on his
failed 1996 presidential bid, is expected to spend most of his
money on a more traditional form of communication _ television. His
advertisements in the last election focused on his plan to replace
the current tax code with a flat-tax plan, which he said would
permit most Americans to fill out their returns in less than three
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The 51-year-old New Jersey native, who has never held elective
office, still talks about ``driving a stake'' through the tax code
and offering ``job retraining'' for laid-off workers at the
Internal Revenue Service. But he has also broadened his message,
speaking out against legal abortions and on other issues that
appeal to the religious right.
</P>
<P>
   A text of his Internet announcement released to reporters makes
clear that he will continue to run as a nonpolitician, and try to
draw Gore into the Clinton administration's ethical morass.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you trust other politicians to clean out the corruption and
sleaze of the Clinton-Gore administration?'' he asks.
</P>
<P>
   After his message is distributed through cyberspace, Forbes will
take a more traditional route to announce his candidacy. He plans
campaign events Tuesday and Wednesday in New Hampshire and Thursday
in Iowa, the sites of the nation's first primary and caucus.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes joins Quayle, former Tennessee Gov. Lamar Alexander, Sen.
Bob Smith, R-N.H., journalists Pat Buchanan and Family Research
Council president Gary Bauer among Republicans who have announced
their candidacy.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, Dole, Kasich and Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., have all
announced the formation of exploratory committees and are expected
to make final decisions by the summer. Gore and former Sen. Bill
Bradley, D-N.J., are the only announced Democratic candidates.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
