<SLUG> BC-JOEMURRAY-COLUMN17-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   DISPATCHES FROM DREAMSVILLE: Big night at the honky-tonk
</P>
<P>
   (''Dispatches from Dreamsville'' is an occasional series in
which readers share with Cox Newspapers senior writer Joe Murray
their memories of growing up in small-town America. Back then, or
at least the way we remember it, life was like a dream.)
</P>
<P>
   By Jane Brooking
</P>
<P>
   Special to Cox News Service
</P>
<P>
   Of all the ``Dreamsvilles'' of my youth, the one I remember most
clearly is Paris, Texas, the summer I was 14.
</P>
<P>
   My favorite job that summer was babysitting with the children of
the owners of Paris's most popular honky-tonk. It wasn't your
average summer job.
</P>
<P>
   The Saturday night I'll never forget started like any other,
with the children and me, noses pressed to the window, watching the
cars and pickup trucks arrive.
</P>
<P>
   Even before the music started, we could sense the happy mood of
the couples coming to hear (and, of course, dance to) the music of
that week's headliner.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes we could see, tucked into a corner behind the dance
hall, a shiny silver-colored tour bus with the performer's name in
big bright letters splashed across the sides and front.
</P>
<P>
   Each Saturday night, as the children's parents left to walk
across the wide parking lot that separated home from business, they
would remind me to lock the door and not to unlock it until one of
them called to say they were on their way to the house.
</P>
<P>
   This night when the phone rang, it was different.
</P>
<P>
   It seems Bob Wills, this week's star, wasn't feeling well and
needed a glass of milk. Would I let him in and pour him a glass of
cold milk?
</P>
<P>
   Bob Wills! My favorite of favorites, and I was going to pour him
a glass of cold milk.
</P>
<P>
   I would have gladly run out and milked a cow if they had asked
me to.
</P>
<P>
   Gathering all the poise and charm of my 14 years, I opened the
door and invited my hero into the living room.
</P>
<P>
   I remember perching on the edge of my chair, trying to act very
sophisticated but not having the vaguest idea of what sophisticated
was.
</P>
<P>
   He sat on the sofa, sipping his milk and talking to me as if I
were an adult.
</P>
<P>
   Fourteen-year-olds of that time, at least in Paris, Texas,
weren't as worldly as they are in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   It didn't occur to me to wonder about the cause of his upset
stomach or to connect it with stories in the fan magazines.
</P>
<P>
   I don't remember a word he said, just how grown up I felt to be
in the same room with this famous man and how kind he was to me.
</P>
<P>
   I've lived through many years of Saturday nights, but not one
can compare to the night I met Bob Wills.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Jane Brooking lives in Gladewater, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (If you have a story to share, send it to ``Dispatches from
Dreamsville,'' c/o Joe Murray, Cox Newspapers, P.O. Box 151108,
Lufkin, Texas, 75915. A photo of the writer is optional. If your
article is used, you will receive $25.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
