r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ROSENFELD-SHORTTAKES1     03-16 0235
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROSENFELD-SHORTTAKES17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SHORTTAKES: Enter, the Tepid War
 &HT;    By Arnold Rosenfeld
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   There was a time in America when it was easy to tell good from
bad. World War II is the best example. Allies good. Axis bad.
Events were to prove the labels were on the mark. Then we segued
into the Cold War. Despite some confusion, you could still tell the
good guys from the bad.
</P>
<P>
   Then the Cold War ended. Communism cratered. Americans became
fretful, peevish. Someone had a brilliant idea. We could hate each
other. Conservatives. Liberals. Americans went for the gusto. It
was suddenly OK to hate democracy, your own government, the woman
next door who didn't use the precise words you would use to
denounce something or someone.
</P>
<P>
   So it felt comfy the other day to hear the Cold War is back,
sort of. The Tepid War. Espionage. Stolen atomic secrets. Perhaps
even _ two cheers _ a whiff of treason. Republicans demanding
investigation. Democrats saying what's the big deal, everyone
spies.
</P>
<P>
   So, here we are. The Chinese have stolen nuclear secrets, a
hideously dangerous thing to do. What will probably count most in
the longest run is what that will make of us as a people.
</P>
<P>
   Arnold Rosenfeld is editor-in-chief of the Cox Newspapers.
E-mail: arnold.rosenfeld(at)cox.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
