<HEADLINE>
EDITORS:
</HEADLINE>
  
 Tuesday, March 16, 1999      The Hearst News Service will file the following stories for
Wednesday. If you have questions, please call Tim Spence at
202-298-6920.  
    (Slugline includes the ``HNS'' tag.)
   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   AFFIRMATIVE-ACTION (San Francisco) _ The number of blacks and
Latinos accepted to prestigious Lowell High School next fall has
plummeted by 50 percent, raising questions about how to maintain
diversity without using race in admissions. At the same time,
offers to Chinese American and white students has jumped
considerably at Lowell, one of the top public schools in
California. By JULIAN GUTHRIE.
</P>
<P>
   MARINES-CITIES (Alaeda, Calif.) _ The Marines, computers and
high-tech weapons at the ready, landed in the East Bay amid a war
of words and not much else. The troops who came ashore in the
Marines' urban warfare rehearsal were greeted by about 100
protesters. There were sharp words but no incidents. By ERIC BRAZIL
and LARRY D. HATFIELD.
</P>
<P>
   FEATURES/LIFESTYLE
</P>
<P>
   CIRCUMCISION (Albany, N.Y.) _ Deyva Arthur's decision not to
circumcise her newborn boy last month created quite a stir among
her relatives. But she feels better about defying family tradition
since the American Academy of Pediatrics stated in a new policy on
March 1 that the potential medical benefits of circumcision are not
sufficient to recommend it as a routine medical procedure. By
SYLVIA WOOD.
</P>
<P>
   COLON-CANCER (Albany, N.Y.) _ It is an irony of our times that
the second-largest cancer killer _ colon cancer _ has a 90 percent
survival rate if detected early, yet almost two-thirds of new cases
aren't discovered until the cancer has headed out to other parts of
the body. By BRUCE A. SCRUTON.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL NEWS (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   ROBERTSON-STEPHENS (San Francisco) _ It's been a wild ride for
Robertson Stephens, the San Francisco investment bank that helped
build the high-tech economy. Two years ago, the firm was bought by
BankAmerica Corp. for $540 million. Then last year, BankAmerica
sold Robertson Stephens for $800 million to BankBoston Corp. Now
BankBoston has been snapped up by Fleet Financial Group Inc. By
EDWARD IWATA.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET-PORN (Austin, Texas) _ When these executives talk
e-commerce, they're not discussing best-selling books and CDs. At
Monday's standing-room-only ``XXX Files'' panel at Austin's South
By Southwest (SXSW) Interactive Conference, electronic retailers
were talking about pornography, the one commercial activity on the
Web that does make money. By MATT BEER.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   SALTER-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ Probably it's just a coincidence
that I got the worst flu I've had in at least a decade at the very
same time I was murdering mice. After all, what tangible
correlation could there be between some flu virus that invaded my
body (even though I had a flu shot) and the murder of a bunch of
mice who've been living in my walls? By STEPHANIE SALTER.
</P>
<P>
   LYNCH-COLUMN (Albany, N.Y.) _ The fight between Evander
Holyfield and Lennox Lewis raises questions. In the modern era,
nobody can fix a big boxing match by paying off the fighters. How
do you bribe a guy to take a dive when he's already getting 40
million bucks? But referees and judges? By DAN LYNCH.
</P>
</TEXT>
