<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990316.0056 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-16 12:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2161 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EZZARD-COLUMN17-COX     03-16 0621
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EZZARD-COLUMN17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Women's groups join forces for clearer voice on issues
 &HT;    By Martha Ezzard
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Maybe the new organization Women Leaders Online
(http://www.wlo.org) will help destroy the notion _ and the
reality, according to recent studies _ that women have been slow to
pick up on the advantages of high tech. I hope the ``leaders'' part
of the title isn't a signal that it's only for women with
high-powered careers.
</P>
<P>
   The new group is one of 120 women's organizations sponsoring
this week's `` Women's Equality Summit'' in Washington. Other
groups include the bipartisan Women's Campaign Fund and the Women's
Political Caucus, which has chapters in every state. Altogether the
summit sponsors represent 5 million women voters.
</P>
<P>
   Though women's groups have agitated too much about the ``glass
ceiling'' issues for women at the top and too little about housing
and child care for working women, the summit agenda sounds
down-to-earth enough. Women will talk to lawmakers about Social
Security reform and about ridding it of some of its built-in
disadvantages for women. They'll suggest ways to make quality child
care and family health care more affordable.
</P>
<P>
   Too often such one-shot Washington gatherings turn out to be
little more than single-interest sound and fury that soon
evaporates. But the national political backdrop for the women's
foray and the alliances women's groups are forming at the state
level may mean it's something more.
</P>
<P>
   Central to that backdrop are two women _ cast for decades as
political wives standing by their men. In 2000, Elizabeth Dole will
seek the presidential nomination; Hillary Clinton, perhaps, a U.S.
Senate seat. The political message of the post-impeachment era is
that extremism is out and moderation in. That gives women,
especially pragmatic ones such as Dole and Clinton, an advantage.
</P>
<P>
   If GOP candidates for the presidency, especially George W. Bush
and Elizabeth Dole, can move the party back to the mainstream,
where most women voters are, the country and the two-party system
will be better off. The early signs are good.
</P>
<P>
   Indications that this week's Washington summit is more than a
simplistic tribute to ``Women's History Month'' are reinforced by
the grassroots activities of coalition building that are bubbling
up at the state level among women's groups. Those efforts may
signal the disintegration of the backlash to the women's movement
that started in the 1980s. I hope so.
</P>
<P>
   As the hard-core right wing of the GOP embraced the backlash,
pushing its socially conservative agenda, women's organizations
lurched to the left. That has to change if feminism is to retrieve
its original focus on mainstream issues such as equal pay,
education and legal rights.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia women's groups have also formed a coalition, the Georgia
Women's Alliance, made up of 30 organizations across the state.
That group will soon suggest to Gov. Roy Barnes some strong women
candidates for appointment to several key posts _ the Public
Service Commission, the state board of education and the governor's
powerful new regional transportation authority. If any governor in
the country understands the significance of the women's vote,
Barnes does. Women accounted for much of his margin of victory last
year.
</P>
<P>
   Let's hope Barnes' lesson will be the lesson for all politicians
in 2000, when women will turn out in record numbers to vote. Groups
such as Women Online can contact a million women in a heartbeat.
The suffragettes would be proud.
</P>
<P>
   Martha Ezzard is a member of the editorial board of The Atlanta
Journal.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
