<HEADER>
A2164 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-YOUNG-COLUMN17-COX     03-16 0653
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YOUNG-COLUMN17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bush-Clinton in '00: For candidate trying to please all, this is
the ticket
 &HT;    By John Young
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ George W. Bush went out on a limb last week and
may have blown a calculated quest to please everyone. He aligned
himself with a noted Republican who, though a war hawk, was squishy
soft on social issues.
</P>
<P>
   It happened when, announcing a presidential exploratory
committee, Bush gave an apparent blanket endorsement of Abraham
Lincoln.
</P>
<P>
   The extent to which this has damaged him remains to be seen.
Strategists differ. Bush's invoking the image of a tall
Midwesterner is seen by some as infuriating small Northeasterners.
Aligning himself with Lincoln makes him persona non grata with
certain influential southern PACs, including the Committee to
Deconstruct Reconstruction.
</P>
<P>
   Can a campaign so wounded survive?
</P>
<P>
   Strategists differ. But clearly, if Bush is serious about
pleasing enough people to become president, and I think he is, he
has but one choice now: announce tomorrow his running mate, William
Jefferson Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   If he doesn't, Elizabeth Dole will.
</P>
<P>
   What's in a name? The names Dole and Bush are to politics what
Hellman's and Kraft are to sandwich spread. But in packaging and
poll numbers, Clinton has established himself as a bona fide
Miracle Whip.
</P>
<P>
   Out-Dukakising the field
</P>
<P>
   You don't need to see poll numbers to know who the front-runners
are anymore in presidential races. They are the candidates being
the most vague.
</P>
<P>
   In that regard, Dole and Bush already are in a death struggle.
When asked for specific issue stances, they cover their ears and
hum loudly.
</P>
<P>
   Dole thus far has put the fear of the Lord into Bush with her
oblique tenacity. She's taken care to distance herself from all
telling allegiances. Not only has she left husband Bob at home to
show that he wouldn't call the shots in her presidency, but to
avoid being seen as beholden to former employer American Red Cross,
she has yet to state definitively whether she's for disaster or
against it.
</P>
<P>
   You might say these two front-runners are following in the
footsteps of the vague campaigners whose last names they share.
Wrong. Actually they are applying the lessons learned from the
nominating-process success of a one-time Bush campaign foe, Michael
Dukakis.
</P>
<P>
   After 1984 Democratic nominee Walter Mondale was faulted for
being too specific and honest _ even promising to raise taxes _
Dukakis survived a crowded 1988 field of Democrats by being the
most squat _ as in not telling us squat. Only when he won the
nomination did voters realize that he wasn't too tall, either.
</P>
<P>
   No-tell, do-tell
</P>
<P>
   Of course, there's a difference between not telling the voters
anything and telling them everything they want to hear, campaign
promise-wise. That, of course, is where Bush knows Clinton would be
most valuable on his ticket.
</P>
<P>
   Bush shouldn't need the help. He comes off a governor's race in
which he came close to promising everything to everyone _ monster
tax cuts, teacher pay hikes, name it. State budget writers are now
coming to grips with the impossibility of it all.
</P>
<P>
   But this is a run for president, not for Texas' weak
governorship. With Clinton aboard, Bush could stay vague. He could
leave the campaign promises to his running mate.
</P>
<P>
   Not only that, Bush could deflect questions about his ``young
and foolish'' days by directing all sundry questions to his No. 2
man, who would keep the hounds at bay with plates and plates of raw
fleshy matter. Spiro Agnew was the crooked Nixon's
``law-and-order'' mouthpiece. Bill Clinton could be the blemished
Bush's ``sworn-off-sin'' distraction.
</P>
<P>
   Bush-Clinton. Come on, George. How badly do you want it?
</P>
<P>
   John Young writes for The Waco Tribune-Herald, Waco, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
