<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-16 12:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2166 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BABBITT-GRANDJURY-AZR     03-16 1187
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BABBITT-GRANDJURY-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GRAND JURY PROBES BABBITT ROLE IN 1995 CASINO PROPOSAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JEFF BARKER  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A federal grand jury is investigating the rejection
of a Wisconsin Indian casino by the staff of Interior Secretary
Bruce Babbitt, including whether the White House improperly
influenced the decision in exchange for campaign donations, ``The
Republic'' has learned.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the grand jury secretly heard for more than four
hours from Loretta Avent, a former deputy assistant to the
president. Avent, who left the White House in 1996 and now lives
with her family in Phoenix, is not personally a subject of the
investigation, said her attorney, John Frank.
</P>
<P>
   Avent served as the White House liaison to the nation's Indian
tribes in 1995, when lobbyists, backed by large campaign donations,
sought to pressure the Clinton administration to reject a proposed
Indian casino in Hudson, Wis.
</P>
<P>
   Avent counseled her colleagues not to succumb to the lobbyists'
requests, and an independent counsel is now investigating, among
other things, whether the White House took her advice and steered
clear of the lobbyists' influence.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Republic'' has learned that the grand jury also has issued
a subpoena for Interior Department records of a Midwestern tribe,
the Shakopee Sioux, that opposed the casino application that's at
the heart of the Babbitt probe.
</P>
<P>
   Avent's appearance is the first signal that independent counsel
Carol Elder Bruce, in resolving allegations against Babbitt, is
exercising her broad authority to investigate not only the Interior
Department but also whether the White House and possibly the
Democratic National Committee improperly sought to involve
themselves in the casino decision.
</P>
<P>
   Many congressional Republicans consider Bruce's probe a final
opportunity to hold Democrats accountable for what they believe
were widespread campaign fund-raising abuses in the 1996
presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   In January, Attorney General Janet Reno rejected an independent
counsel investigation of former White House deputy chief of staff
Harold Ickes, who was accused of lying to a Senate committee
looking into campaign finances.
</P>
<P>
   Bruce was appointed one year ago to find out whether Babbitt, a
former governor of Arizona, lied to Congress in his account of the
Interior Department's rejection of an application by three bands of
the Chippewa tribe for the Wisconsin casino. Babbitt's
congressional critics allege that the Interior Department denied
the application because of pressure generated by rival tribes that
were donating heavily to the Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   Babbitt has said that his staff based its decision on the merits
of the application and that he was not personally involved.
</P>
<P>
   After House committee hearings in January 1998, some GOP
lawmakers privately conceded that the evidence against Babbitt was
so thin that they would not be disappointed if the investigation
focused less on Babbitt than on his political appointees at
Interior and on the White House.
</P>
<P>
   The federal court that appointed Bruce last year gave her wide
latitude, saying she might want to explore not only whether Babbitt
lied but also ``any potential criminal violations in connection
with the underlying casino decision.''
</P>
<P>
   Bruce's spokesman, Cary Feldman, declined comment Monday, as did
Babbitt's lawyers. Prosecutors use grand juries as a method of
collecting documents and testimony. The jury's existence does not,
by itself, mean indictments are forthcoming.
</P>
<P>
   Avent became embroiled in the casino controversy because Patrick
O'Connor, a lobbyist opposed to the proposed casino, was trying to
call her at the White House in 1995 _ presumably to discuss the
application to use a 55-acre parcel of land for gaming.
</P>
<P>
   Avent was reluctant to speak to a lobbyist and believed the
administration should also be wary, she wrote in an April 1995
memorandum to Ickes.
</P>
<P>
   Her memo suggested that it would be a dangerous precedent to
appear to accede to well-connected lobbyists who might promise
campaign donations later on.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is such a hot potato,'' Avent wrote. ``The legal and
political implications of our involvement would be disastrous.''
</P>
<P>
   Avent said the administration owed it to tribes to treat all
Indians the same, regardless of how much money they had or who
their lobbyists were. O'Connor was considered well connected
because he was a former official with the DNC.
</P>
<P>
   Several Republican lawmakers quoted from Avent's memo during the
hearings on Capitol Hill last year.
</P>
<P>
   They said they wanted to know who saw the memo and whether Ickes
and others at the White House took her advice to not get involved
with the casino application.
</P>
<P>
   Those questions were not answered at the Capitol Hill hearings,
which is probably why Bruce and her staff of 10 attorneys were
interested in calling her as a witness.
</P>
<P>
   Avent referred inquiries to her Phoenix attorney, Frank.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it was governmental abuse to call her into this at
all,'' Frank said in an interview. ``She has had nothing to do with
Babbitt in any matter, nor with Paul Eckstein.''
</P>
<P>
   Eckstein, a Phoenix attorney and former Harvard Law School
classmate of Babbitt's, was a lobbyist for the proposed casino at
the time of the decision.
</P>
<P>
   Eckstein testified on Capitol Hill that Babbitt told him during
a July 1995 meeting that Ickes had ``directed'' that a decision on
the Chippewa casino be issued ``that day.''
</P>
<P>
   Babbitt said he may have invoked Ickes' name in the context that
Ickes ``expected'' or ``wanted'' a decision. But Babbitt said
Ickes, in fact, never demanded a decision, and that Babbitt made
the statement simply as an excuse to end the meeting with Eckstein.
</P>
<P>
   The independent counsel was appointed to determine which version
of the conversation _ Eckstein's or Babbitt's _ is true.
</P>
<P>
   If Eckstein's version is true, then Babbitt lied to Congress,
according to the Justice Department. But Babbitt's aides say that
even if he said what he is accused of, it doesn't prove that the
casino decision was improper, or that Babbitt was a major player.
</P>
<P>
   Neither the independent counsel nor the Interior Department
would offer an explanation of why the grand jury is seeking
department records pertaining to the membership of the Shakopee
Sioux.
</P>
<P>
   However, the Shakopee Sioux attracted attention during the
congressional hearings because they opposed the casino application
and because two of Babbitt's former Interior aides represented the
Shakopees after leaving the department.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Dan Burton, R-Ind., said last year that the independent
counsel should review why aides John Duffy and Tom Collier ``took
lucrative law jobs representing the tribe that contributed the
largest amount in the effort to stop the casino proposal.''
</P>
<P>
   Duffy and Collier didn't violate any ethics rules, and the law
firm, Steptoe and Johnson, says they didn't handle issues related
to the casino application. &QL; 
 &QL; 
(Jeff Barker can be reached at (202) 662-7264 or at
jeff.barker &LR; pni.com via e-mail.) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
