<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    E-mail from an old friend
 &HT;    By Elizabeth Schuett
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GIBSONBURG, Ohio _ Only children are not necessarily lonely
children, but every once in a while they need a little culture
shock to remind them that life at their house is not the norm. My
mother figured a few weeks each summer at Doweezy?s house in the
country would do the trick.
</P>
<P>
   Doweezy Bito was my age, and the oldest of five daughters in a
lively, loving Bohemian family. Life at the Bito's was a melodrama
with Mama directing the entire production from the kitchen sink.
Papa worked on the railroad.
</P>
<P>
   Summers at Doweezy's were an impromptu performance with a
six-star cast, although the baby Rita didn't have much of a part
when we played cowboys and rustlers in the woods behind the
abandoned chicken coop. She was too little to ride the range on a
broom-handle horse with the rest of us. On rainy days
</P>
<P>
   though, when we played house on the front porch, Rita was our
baby. She loved it and Mama said it was okay, as long as we didn't
make her cry.
</P>
<P>
   The Bito girls and I got along well. We argued only over whose
turn it was to be Roy Rogers or Dale Evans. Nobody wanted to be
Gabby but it took all of us to be the Sons of the Pioneers, sitting
around the campfire at night singing, ``Cool Water.''
</P>
<P>
   Late afternoons, when potatoes were on the supper menu, Mama
Bito would holler Doweezy and me in to peel. We'd spread
yesterday's paper on the kitchen floor and sit cross-legged as Mama
shook enough potatoes out of a bag to fill the dented, wire-handled
boiling pot. She kept a close eye on my peels so I
</P>
<P>
   wouldn't waste.
</P>
<P>
   Mornings came early at the Bito's. Seven days a week, all of the
girls who were old enough were expected to show up dressed, hatted,
and ready to pedal off to Mass at the little Catholic church three
blocks away. There were two bicycles for the four of us. We took
turns on the handlebars. What a sight we must have been _ three
Bitos and one southern Baptist, clutching prayer books, skirts
billowing in the wind, pedaling toward redemption.
</P>
<P>
   Since my mother had no inkling of my impending conversion, I'd
come without a church hat. Mama Bito whipped up one for me in an
afternoon _ a little Dutch boy thing in white dotted swiss. Each
morning I'd anchor it with a couple of bobby pins and off we'd go.
One day, when my summer stay had lengthened from a couple of weeks
to over a month, the nun asked if I would like to sing in the choir
with Doweezy and her next sister, Marianna. I checked with Mama
Bito and she said God wouldn't mind a Baptist in the Catholic
choir. She even helped me with the Latin.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after supper, the inevitable march to the bathtub began.
Baby Rita and the next one, Cecee, would already be down for the
night when the rest of us hit the bubbles _ two at a time.
Barefoot, in seersucker nighties, we'd line up for our hugs and
goodnight kisses from Mama and Papa. Doweezy, Marianna,
</P>
<P>
   and I shared a room upstairs, under the eaves.
</P>
<P>
   Each year I cried when summer ended and I had to leave my
warm-weather family. There was just so much life being lived at the
Bito's that I didn't want to give up my place in it.
</P>
<P>
   As so often happens, folks drift apart and get out of touch.
That happened to us. It's been over half-a-century since the girls
and I put our make-believe horses in the barn for the last time. I
had no idea what had become of the Bitos, until this morning
anyway, when I pulled up an email from a reader. ``I read your
column in my local paper. Are you the skinny kid who used to spend
summers at our house?'' It was signed, Louise (Doweezy) Bito.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure am,'' I emailed right back. I hope she asks what I'm
doing this summer.
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Schuett writes for Cox News Service. Address mail to
320 West Madison, Gibsonburg, Ohio 43431 or email to:
eschuett(AT)nwonline.com)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
