r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MONEYTALK17-COX     03-16 0612
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONEYTALK17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    MONEY TALK: Do the Couch Potato
 &HT;    By Hank Ezell
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Couch Potato portfolio had another wonderful year.
</P>
<P>
   It was up 19.6 percent during 1998, which beats the 12.1 percent
average return for 726 comparable mutual funds.
</P>
<P>
   The Couch Potato is one of those too-good-to-be-true investment
formulas, seemingly in the same class with consulting an
astrologer, checking hemlines or woofing with the Dogs of the Dow.
The difference is the Couch Potato seems to work more years than
not.
</P>
<P>
   It's called the Couch Potato because it is simple to execute,
easy to maintain and dull as dirt. You put half your money into an
S&AMP;P 500 index fund and half into a government bond fund. Then you
go away and leave it alone. Maybe once a year you come back and
shift money from one to the other, to maintain a 50-50 balance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Good investment returns come from being simple, cheap and
virtually inert,'' argues Scott Burns, the Dallas Morning News
columnist who invented the Couch Potato.
</P>
<P>
   The chart tells the story. The Couch Potato has given better
returns in four of the last seven years, compared with the average
for hybrid mutual funds. Hybrid funds have a similar mix of stocks
and bonds.
</P>
<P>
   If you invested $10,000 over those seven years, the Couch Potato
would have made about $24,600, or $2,500 more than the hybrid
funds.
</P>
<P>
   One reason is Burns chose low-cost Vanguard funds for his
portfolio. The stock investment is in the Index 500 fund; the bonds
are in the Intermediate Term U.S. Treasury fund.
</P>
<P>
   I am not saying the Couch Potato is suitable for everyone.
</P>
<P>
   There are two kinds of investors: Those who know they can beat
the market, and those who know the market can beat them. This gets
down to the basic urges of the marketplace, greed and fear.
</P>
<P>
   More daring investors _ including the market beaters _ won't be
satisfied with the Couch Potato. That's because it hasn't kept up
with the stock market and probably never will.
</P>
<P>
   The Couch Potato returned 19.6 percent in 1998, but the Standard
and Poors' 500 index was up 26.7 percent. The Couch Potato was held
back by those stodgy bonds, which returned 10.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Young people, especially those with investments in tax-deferred
retirement accounts, may also go for more aggressive investments.
They have the time to coast past any stock market retreats.
</P>
<P>
   Those are the fearless investors, more or less. The Couch Potato
appeals more to the fearful.
</P>
<P>
   If you are willing to accept an average return on your stock
investments, rather than taking a chance on hot-hands investment
managers, then the S&AMP;P 500 index fund will appeal.
</P>
<P>
   If you fear the volatility of the stock market, then government
bonds in the Couch Potato will comfort you.
</P>
<P>
   If you are frozen by the number of mutual funds to choose from _
more than 10,000 now _ the simplicity of Burns' approach will be a
relief.
</P>
<P>
   If you are afraid of making mistakes _ buying too high, selling
too soon, holding on too long and all that _ the passive, even
somnolent technique of the Couch Potato is rewarding.
</P>
<P>
   You are not stuck with those two funds from the Vanguard family.
You can find mutual funds with similar aims in the USAA, Fidelity,
T. Rowe Price, Dreyfus and Schwab groups.
</P>
<P>
   Nor must you stick to a 50-50 allocation. Burns also tracks a
racier formula: 75 percent stocks, 25 percent bonds. Its return
last year was 24.1 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Here's one more comforting thought: Burns himself is a couch
potato. His own 401(k) retirement account practices what he
preaches.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
