<SLUG> BC-THE-MECHANIC17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Batteries can fall into short-trip death cycle
 &HT;    By Nora Carter
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: While living in Florida, I drove my car 20 miles to and from
work without experiencing any battery problems. When I moved to
Cumberland, my commute was shortened to two miles. Coincidentally,
I have had a succession of batteries installed ranging from
expensive, top-of-the-line models to (a discount store's) best.
None of them has lasted. They work fine in warm weather but fall
flat when the temperature turns cold.
</P>
<P>
   One dealer replaced my ignition switch and another my starter,
with no results. I bought a voltmeter that allows me to monitor the
charging voltage while driving and determined the charging rate was
indeed low when all of the accessories were operating. I have since
installed a new aftermarket voltage regulator and am now charging
15-16 volts, yet on really cold mornings the battery voltage still
reads lower than normal. I bought a battery charger, but it is
really inconvenient to run an extension cord from my condo's
bedroom window, so I have resorted to carrying one of those
portable battery jump-start packs in the trunk of my car.
</P>
<P>
   Am I forever doomed to this kind of existence? Is there a better
brand of battery for my short trips? Any suggestions are welcome. _
Cal Calhoun
</P>
<P>
   A: It was not coincidental that your battery saga corresponded
with your two-mile commute pattern. A battery needs about 20
minutes of continuous, high engine rpm to completely recharge after
the starter has drained it. Your Florida commute provided that.
What your battery is being subjected to is a constant cycle of
discharge from the starter motor and partial recharge, with the
battery getting weaker each time.
</P>
<P>
   The weather is also a player here. A marginal battery may
perform satisfactorily in warm weather but even a good, fully
charged battery loses some of its capacity when the temperature
drops.
</P>
<P>
   Your ``15-16 volt'' regulator also has me concerned. Although it
may appear to be a solution, you are more likely compounding your
problem and creating an explosive situation. The charging voltage
to the battery should be about 2 volts more than battery voltage
with accessories off and about 0.5 to 1 volt above with all of them
on. If the battery is being overcharged, it begins to boil out the
electrolyte solution, ultimately uncovering part of the active lead
plate material and rendering it useless. Battery capacity
diminishes. Worse yet, as the electrolyte level gets lower, more
hydrogen gas collects inside the vacated area of the battery. A
good zap with that battery pack of yours and BOOM!
</P>
<P>
   I suspect your particular problem may also be related to a
partial electrical blockage between the alternator and the battery
and needs to be diagnosed by a good electrical mechanic. The
short-trip death cycle of batteries might be solved by using a
different type of battery.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the batteries are the sealed, maintenance-free type. The
good news is that these batteries have a long shelf life and really
are maintenance-free, with no periodic service required. However,
maintenance-free batteries have a downside. They are harder to
recharge and do not tolerate deep discharge.
</P>
<P>
   Low-maintenance batteries, on the other hand, are not sealed
(they have little caps on top) and require periodic service. The
trade-off is that these batteries can be discharged and recharged
easier. Low-maintenance batteries are usually sold at independent
repair shops.
</P>
<P>
   After you have repaired your charging system and replaced your
battery (again), take it out and drive it a long distance at least
once a week.
</P>
<P>
   Nora Carter, who has 26 years of experience in the auto repair
industry, is an automotive instructor at DeKalb Technical Institute
and an ASE master automobile technician/L-1.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
