<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Toyota serious about reviving full-size pickup
 &HT;    By Linda Sharp
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Toyota is making a second stab in the full-size truck segment,
and this time the company has taken the gloves off.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone, including Toyota, knows that its first attempt, the
T100, missed the mark. It wasn't that it was a bad truck; it just
had two major flaws. It didn't offer a V-8 engine, and it was
priced too high. Harnessed with the 25 percent import duty, a buyer
really had to want a Toyota to justify the T100's cost.
</P>
<P>
   Things are about to change. Scheduled to go on sale in June, but
with order models expected in Toyota stores late this month, Toyota
has made a concentrated effort to ensure the new half-ton Tundra
not only meets but exceeds buyers' expectations.
</P>
<P>
   Simply put, Toyota realizes the Tundra needs to be better in key
areas that define what a full-sized truck is all about:
acceleration, towing, payload hauling and braking.
</P>
<P>
   Based on tests by AMCI, an independent testing organization, the
Indiana-built Tundra appears to have hit paydirt. It went
zero-to-60 in 7.87 seconds. That's more than a second better than a
comparable Chevrolet Silverado or Ford F-150.
</P>
<P>
   On average, the Tundra has 20 percent better acceleration
performance, comparing base engine against base engine.
</P>
<P>
   AMCI also conducted the tests pitting the Tundra's new
245-horsepower, 4.7-liter, dual-overhead-cam V-8 against the
competition's larger optional engines. Tundra beat the 5.9-liter
Dodge Ram, tied the 5.3-liter Chevy and trailed the 5.4-liter Ford
by 0.003 of a second.
</P>
<P>
   All Tundras will have standard anti-lock brakes. Loaded with a
1,200-pound payload, AMCI found Tundra stopped shorter and surer
than competitors.
</P>
<P>
   But make no mistake, the new Tundra is not a copy of an American
truck; it is still uniquely Toyota. Equipped with rack-and-pinion
steering, the feel is like that of an upscale passenger car, a
sensation confirmed by an exceptionally quiet cab.
</P>
<P>
   Little wind or road noise can be heard in an interior where you
really have to remind yourself that you are driving a pickup. And
with Toyota's attention to ergonomics, the Tundra's new extended
cab will be the first in the segment in which there are handles
inside and outside the body.
</P>
<P>
   A test drive of a pre-production Tundra gave all indications
that Toyota has handled the performance barrier. And just to get
the consumers' and competition's attention, the company is baring
its knuckles on pricing. A well-equipped truck with the extended
Access Cab will carry a manufacturer's suggested retail price of
$22,250.
</P>
<P>
   It includes a four-speed automatic, air conditioning,
radio/cassette, tachometer, cruise control and 16-inch styled
wheels. A standard cab V-6 with a manual transmission will carry an
MSRP of $14,995.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
