<SLUG> BC-SUVS17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SUVs: How big is too big?
 &HT;    By Matt Reed
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Just what we need: one more guilt-trip
about living in the 'burbs.
</P>
<P>
   Bad enough already that our sport-utility vehicles burn gas by
the tanker and can squash Geo Metros like raisins. Now, here comes
Ford trying to sell us the biggest ``sport ute'' on earth _ one the
pundits and tree-huggers and safety nabobs can't stop howling
about.
</P>
<P>
   And, well... it looks pretty nice.
</P>
<P>
   They call it the Ford Excursion, 19 feet and 4 1/4 tons of
stroller-haulin', Honda-stompin' machinery. It seats nine, gets a
shameful 12 mpg and stretches almost a foot longer than the
previous champ, the Chevrolet Suburban. (Chevy has already vowed to
one-up the monster Ford.)
</P>
<P>
   All of which begs the question: Honey, how big is our garage?
</P>
<P>
   Actually, that's not the question serious people want you to
ask. Pretend you're thinking: My God in heaven! How big is too big?
</P>
<P>
   Seems we really have reached the point where someone needs to do
something about the mass quantities of fuel SUVs burn, the exhaust
they emit and the waste they lay to cars that stray into their
paths.
</P>
<P>
   The Sierra Club nicknamed the Excursion (which sells for
$45,000) the ``Ford Valdez,'' evoking the notorious Exxon
supertanker disaster. And the EPA fears a rise in greenhouse gasses
because, as light trucks, all sport utilities are allowed to
produce more fumes than cars.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, something must be done. But it must be done in Washington
or Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   It certainly won't start in Omaha or Fort Lauderdale or
Poughkeepsie. And a case could be made that it shouldn't.
</P>
<P>
   ``This thing is like an 18-wheeler,'' says Angela Farazi, a
mother of two, praising her hulking (but now second-tier) Ford
Expedition. ``I have no use for another foot of space ... but if I
had another child, I'd go for the new, bigger
whatever-you-call-it.''
</P>
<P>
   Key word there: child.
</P>
<P>
   See, it's a car-eat-car world out there on interstates and
six-lane boulevards _ what with all the crazies running red lights
and hurtling across town at 70 mph. And no one will ever convince
suburbanites it's smarter to wrap less protective metal around
their precious kids and spouses, even if a Camry produces less
smog.
</P>
<P>
   As fate would have it, the Farazis and their Expedition had a
nearly head-on collision with a sedan in October. Both cars were
doing 30 mph _ the same speed you see in government crash tests.
</P>
<P>
   ``We practically drove over them,'' Farazi says of the wreck
that demolished the other car but, miraculously, spared its
passengers serious injury. ``We still did $10,000 in damage to our
truck, but inside you couldn't even tell there was an accident.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, it costs $30 to fill an Expedition or Suburban's tank.
And SUV owners say they'd happily buy a more efficient,
cleaner-burning SUV _ if only somebody sold one.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not driving this thing because I want to guzzle gas or
pollute the environment,'' Ferazi says. ``I'm driving it to protect
my family.''
</P>
<P>
   Critics need look no further than the soccer fields to see that
any change in vehicle size and efficiency will have to be driven
from the ``supply side.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We thought about the Expedition for carrying extra kids,''
says Cindy Woolf, a soccer mom now driving her third Ford Explorer.
Why the Explorer? ``It's mostly a safety thing. Also, it has space
in the back for the kids' junk ... And it's not a minivan.'' Big or
too big?
</P>
<P>
   So, how big is too big for SUV buyers?
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a line,'' Woolf says.
</P>
<P>
   Like when it slugs down $60 a week in gas? Or when the exhaust
from a planet-sized Suburban forms its own atmospheric weather
systems?
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's when it just becomes too hard to maneuver, hard
to park,'' Woolf speculates.
</P>
<P>
   Tsk, tsk.
</P>
<P>
   (Wink, wink.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
