<SLUG> BC-TESTDRIVE17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    For Neon, it's already 2000
 &HT;    By Russ DeVault
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bring on 2000 _ that's the message DaimlerChrysler wants to
convey with its all-new Neon sedan, but, unfortunately, that's not
all you'll hear from the frisky compact.
</P>
<P>
   It's true, as DaimlerChrysler reiterates, that the Neon,
available in near-identical versions with your choice of Plymouth
or Dodge badging, is getting quieter as it matures. It's decibels
quieter than when introduced in 1994, but the 2000 Neon does have
echoes of the noise problems that hounded those first-generation
models.
</P>
<P>
   It's no big loser, however. The Neon is basically a smart
compact with some decent standard features and a sound ride and
decent performance and fuel mileage from its four-cylinder engine.
By adding insulation and making other refinements, DaimlerChrysler
now offers a Neon that's a tad bigger, a bit smoother and clearly
coming up to speed in the race for entry-level/budget-conscious
buyers.
</P>
<P>
   Some things haven't changed, however, although the pricing isn't
one of them. The base prices for the Plymouth and Dodge versions _
differentiated only by their badging and steering-wheel insignia _
have crept up about $600 this year and now start at $12,890 in base
form with similarly upgraded Plymouth LX and Dodge ES trim levels
available for about $14,600.
</P>
<P>
   The test Neon Plymouth LX came with a list price of $12,390 but
had enough individual and packaged options to push the bottom line
to $17,700 before discounts pulled it down to $16,680. The add-ons
included air conditioning, power anti-lock disc brakes, a CD
player, tilt wheel, cruise control and power windows and locks.
Suffice it to say that the list of standard equipment really isn't
a long read.
</P>
<P>
   It doesn't take long to navigate the powertrain possibilities,
either. Missing this year is the 150-horsepower engine option,
meaning the only powerplant is the 132-hp four-cylinder with either
a three-speed automatic or five-speed manual transmission. Frequent
stirring of the test Neon's manual were smoothly accomplished and
doubtlessly made for better starts and merges than the automatic is
going to deliver.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, pushing it along contributes to the engine and road noise,
but maybe that's why Neons can be equipped with a nice stereo
system that includes a CD player for a modest $125. Add that, and
the cabin, which has good visibility and simple instrumentation
with white-face gauges, becomes quite habitable. Attractively
finished and comfortably designed seats adjust easily, and drink
holders are said to be specially designed to be capable of taking
on Big Gulp beverages _ another sign that the Neon is aimed at the
youth market.
</P>
<P>
   But make that the upper end of the youth market, those buyers
mature enough to be willing to trade the sportiness of a coupe for
the convenience of four doors (and to pay extra for air
conditioning and some other create comforts). The nifty coupe is
gone, leaving the Neon Plymouth/Dodge sedan to motor on despite
unanswered questions about its reliability and the future of the
Plymouth line itself.
</P>
<P>
   But, hey, the Neon is the first 2000 model to come to market,
and while it's not a radical way of entering the next millennium,
it's a practical possibility even if it won't go there all that
quietly.
</P>
<P>
   Test vehicle: 2000 Neon Plymouth/Dodge front-drive sedan
</P>
<P>
   Price as tested: $16,680 (includes discounts not always
available, base price: $12,390)
</P>
<P>
   Drivetrain: 2.0-liter four-cylinder engine (132 horsepower),
optional three-speed automatic transmission ($600)
</P>
<P>
   Safety features: dual front air bags, side-impact beams,
optional power anti-lock disc brakes with traction control ($740)
</P>
<P>
   Other options on test vehicle: package with air conditioning,
power front windows and locks, heated mirrors, keyless entry,
tachometer, assist handles, fog lamps, tilt steering wheel and
185/60R15 touring tires, $2,365; cruise control, $225; AM/FM radio
with CD player, $125; 15-inch aluminum wheels, $355; package with
lights for mirrors, engine compartment and interior, $130
</P>
<P>
   EPA figures: 25 mpg regular unleaded city, 31 mpg highway
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
