<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-16 12:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2178 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WWII-PILOTS17-COX     03-16 0816
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WWII-PILOTS17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Group unites Allied, German pilots
 &HT;    By Eliot Kleinberg
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Once, they sneered at one another
through cross hairs, each bracing for the kill.
</P>
<P>
   Now they want to get past that.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the 60 veterans in the U.S. Military Pilots Association,
based in suburban Boynton Beach, are American. One is Canadian.
</P>
<P>
   And two flew for the Third Reich.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can get past that they were enemies,'' said association
member George Boone. ``The war is over.''
</P>
<P>
   It was during a card game several years ago that Wolf Abler, a
retired consulting engineer from Dusseldorf who's wintered at Quail
Ridge for 18 years, mentioned his flying past. An association
member at the game invited Abler to attend a function.
</P>
<P>
   ``From the beginning it was very friendly coming together,''
Abler said. ``No animosity.''
</P>
<P>
   Abler said he joined the Luftwaffe at 17 and rose to the rank of
lieutenant. He was never shot down but mechanical problems led to
two emergency landings in Germany. And he shot down one British
pilot, believed killed as his plane plunged into the North Sea off
of Norway.
</P>
<P>
   ``I must confess I didn't like the Nazi regime,'' Abler, 77,
said. ``But you have parents. You have relatives. You have other
people. I was always thinking, `I do it for my country.' But if you
are in the air, you are in combat, you have no choice. Shoot or be
shot.''
</P>
<P>
   The other German, Rudy Ploederl, was shot down during the battle
of Stalingrad and spent 3 1/2 years in a Russian prisoner-of-war
camp. He declined to be interviewed, citing his poor English.
</P>
<P>
   Some can't forgive, forget
</P>
<P>
   This is not the first case of former World War II foes getting
together. But it's a sensitive issue with no right answers, said
Phil Bodahn, spokesman for the 2.8 million-member American Legion,
the largest group of American veterans.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many of our veterans have gone through things that we not only
don't talk about, we can't talk about,'' Bodahn said from
Washington. ``I know World War II veterans today who can not, who
would not talk to a Japanese or a German veteran. At the same time
I know people, World War II veterans, who feel a sense of kinship
with them.''
</P>
<P>
   Group welcomed Germans
</P>
<P>
   In World War I movies, chivalrous pilots saluted their worthy
foes while their scarves flapped in the wind. That romantic
stereotype tailed off in the next war, said Roger Cirillo, project
historian for the planned World War II memorial in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   But pilots of that era do seem less contemptuous of the enemy
than do veterans who fought on the ground, he said. Although pilots
committed atrocities, he said, aerial warfare drew less personal
hatred because it was more machine-versus-machine.
</P>
<P>
   And, he said, ``The real issue with the Germans is over the
Holocaust. And that wasn't the Luftwaffe.''
</P>
<P>
   American members of the local pilots' group said they had no
reservations about admitting the Germans.
</P>
<P>
   Ralph Bogart, one of the group's founders, said he distinguishes
between ``the Germans who hated everybody and the professional
types; they didn't participate in the atrocities.''
</P>
<P>
   Keeping it going
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Military Pilots Association started a decade ago with
World War II pilots at Quail Ridge, said Ben Claus, one of the
leaders. As veterans succumbed to age, it expanded to three other
nearby country clubs _ Delray Dunes Golf and Country Club, Pine
Tree Golf Club, and Country Club of Florida.
</P>
<P>
   The group meets for golf outings and get-togethers and had its
10th annual banquet March 5 at Quail Ridge Country Club.
</P>
<P>
   The group recently brought in about a half-dozen pilots from the
Korean and Vietnam wars, said Claus, himself a Korean War veteran.
</P>
<P>
   ``Somebody's got to keep it going, and we're the next in line,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Seeing enemies as humans
</P>
<P>
   Leaders of the pilots group said they don't believe it has any
Jewish members.
</P>
<P>
   Ralph L. Shear of suburban Boca Raton, commander for 16 Jewish
War Veterans posts with 2,400 members in Broward and Palm Beach
counties, has for years fought to bring former SS members to
justice.
</P>
<P>
   But he said he has no problem with the pilots' group inviting
the Germans. ``If it's just a couple of them left, how can you say
there's anything wrong?'' Shear said.
</P>
<P>
   Said Boone, who was shot down in the raid over the critical
German refineries at Ploesti, Romania: ``Probably some time ago we
would have had a difficult time with it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now we just look on them as human beings and people who didn't
want to kill and be killed any more than we did.''
</P>
<P>
   Boone, meanwhile, is heading to Bucharest, Romania this summer _
to meet the man who shot him down over Ploesti.
</P>
<P>
   Eliot Kleinberg writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
