NYT-03-16-99 1207EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990316.0072 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-16 12:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2179 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ASSISTED-LIVING-CENTE     03-16 1828
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ASSISTED-LIVING-CENTERS17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Managing freedom in assisted living centers
 &HT;    By Douglas Kalajian
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Josephine Megna is all dolled up with no
place to go. She was awake before dawn, as always, slipping into
her short, brown wig and white-framed sunglasses.
</P>
<P>
   Josephine insists on looking just-so before making her 5 a.m.
appearance each day in the retirement home lobby, though there's no
one to see her except a sleepy attendant.
</P>
<P>
   Today brought swift fortune: a blue gift-wrap ribbon someone
tossed into a waste basket. Josephine plucked it out and stuck it
bow-tie high on her black-knit sweater, right above the floral
cluster.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think a woman looks better if she has something bright to
set off her blouse,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   At 96, on a day like most others when she won't leave the
grounds, looking her best is as important as it was during the
years she was married and working.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to keep going,'' she says. ``Never give up. Never
say, `I'm done for.'''
</P>
<P>
   It's a philosophy she shares freely, sometimes insistently, with
her mates at the Palm Beach Assisted Living Facility in downtown
West Palm Beach.
</P>
<P>
   ``Get up and dance,'' she exhorts. ``Move. Move. If I can do it,
you can do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Some listen; most don't. Josephine says she isn't discouraged
and won't quit trying. She knows she isn't trying alone.
</P>
<P>
   The monthly activity board is full of things to do: Board games,
card games, exercise, bingo, prayer services. And yes, dancing. But
it isn't easy to get people excited about another day in a place
none of them expected to end up in.
</P>
<P>
   The path to 534 Datura Street is as wide as America and as long
as a lifetime. This is an unplanned destination for working people
who never had the luck of a corporate pension or the luxury of an
individual retirement account.
</P>
<P>
   There are younger people here with handicaps, and some former
down-and-outers who qualify for state aid to the elderly homeless.
But most of the 165 residents are ``private pay'' retirees who
don't need the constant care of a nursing home but do need a
watchful eye.
</P>
<P>
   It's a broad and forgiving designation. The federal government
considers them poor, but they have some income: Social Security,
veterans benefits. With luck, they get a little help from family,
and a little more from Joseph Glucksman.
</P>
<P>
   Glucksman is a former assistant county administrator who heads
the nonprofit company that runs the place. After years in
government and nonprofit work, he knows where to look for
additional benefits, and he's a wizard at getting grants and
private donations.
</P>
<P>
   So residents pay an average of about $700 a month for room and
care that costs about $1,100. Many get single rooms with private
baths. Everyone gets a room key laced to a coiled plastic bracelet.
They also get three meals a day plus snacks, and someone to clean
up, do the laundry and make the bed.
</P>
<P>
   They even get a taste of Old Florida's boom times. A 1996
renovation honors the building's origins as the Alma Hotel, built
to catch the 1920s overflow from The Breakers. There are
pink-and-teal accents on the walls, fireplaces on each floor. The
dining room is almost elegant, with white stucco, red tile and
heavy wood chairs covered in brocade.
</P>
<P>
   A new boom is happening all around. The foundations of CityPlace
are being laid just blocks away, and the cafes of Clematis are even
closer. Everyone gets a chance to see the sights.
</P>
<P>
   There are exercise walks every few days plus occasional trips to
festivals along Flagler Drive or to The Kravis Center. Most
residents are free to leave any time if they sign out at the front
desk. Emma Peinhardt McMurray heads out first thing every morning.
</P>
<P>
   She's gone just long enough to walk down the block and buy the
newspaper. She reads the feature stories first and then checks for
news of Cullman, Ala., where she was born 78 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Emma is so happy with the home where she's lived these past two
years that she wrote a letter to the editor suggesting a story
about the ``beautiful, graceful'' people who run it. She is
irritated by the suggestion that she might be an equally
interesting subject.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was raised on a farm, attended the University of Alabama,
went to the Rose Bowl twice,'' she says. ``That's all there is.''
</P>
<P>
   She might say more, but she's pressed for time. They're
expecting her in the tailor room to help sort and hang donated
clothes. Then she's due in the dining room to clear tables before
the second lunch seating. Like Josephine, Emma tries to keep
moving.
</P>
<P>
   ``I worked all my life,'' she says. ``I'm not going to stop
now.''
</P>
<P>
   She worked hard enough as a kid to earn a scholarship. That's
when she moved in with Aunt Edith in Birmingham. Emma studied
physical education for two years, which was enough in those days to
start teaching. Good thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``My father said that was enough and I had to come home,'' she
says. ``I had to do what he said. We were strict Lutheran.''
</P>
<P>
   Emma taught in a private school, then a public school. She was
married once, a long time ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``You just print what I put in my letter about how nice they
keep this place,'' she says, leading her guest from the sitting
room to the kitchen to the outdoor patio. ``It's immaculate, isn't
it?''
</P>
<P>
   There's scrubbing going on as she speaks; even the fish tank's
water is crystalline. Emma detours briefly to help a blind woman
round a corner. Then she spots a woman walking in circles.
</P>
<P>
   ``Your room is on the fourth floor,'' Emma reminds her, pointing
toward the elevator.
</P>
<P>
   Emma tries to help as many people as she can. Not everyone does.
Being old or sick doesn't make someone nice or honest. Emma points
out a smiling woman. ``She steals clothes,'' Emma says.
</P>
<P>
   It's good to have someone watching out for you. ``Like Ed, my
neighbor across the hall,'' she says. ``He's a good man.''
</P>
<P>
   When Emma spots Ed Smith in the snack room, she gives him a hug
and a kiss on the cheek. If they'd met back home as kids, she
wouldn't have spoken to him. ``I was taught to hate blacks,'' she
says. ``I've come a long way.''
</P>
<P>
   Ed's childhood in Eastman, Georgia, had this in common with
Emma's: Long days in the hot fields on the family farm. ``Both were
poor states,'' he says. ``Most people just had a little bit.''
</P>
<P>
   When the Depression hit, they had a little bit less.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got tired of working and working for nothing,'' he says. ``A
bunch of my buddy boys and me loaded up a truck and left town on a
Sunday night. That was 1934 or '35.''
</P>
<P>
   Ed landed in Belle Glade, cutting sugar cane. Then he moved to
Dania for the tomato harvest. The pay wasn't better, but at least
you could eat what you picked.
</P>
<P>
   He picked whatever he could until he had enough money to buy a
car. For the next 40 years, Ed was an independent taxi driver.
``Nobody knows a place like a taxi driver,'' he says. ``I knew
everybody in West Palm Beach, and everybody knew me.''
</P>
<P>
   He never retired. He just stopped driving when the arthritis in
his legs got too bad. That was 1988. He wound up in a nursing home
in Lake Worth, but he didn't like that. Too many people, most of
them nasty.
</P>
<P>
   He likes the people here much better, and it's close to his old
haunts. Ed's 83 now and he walks well enough to get out most every
day and visit friends in the neighborhood. His idea of keeping busy
does not include volunteering the way Emma does.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I worked, I got paid,'' he says. ``I'm not going to start
working for nothing now.''
</P>
<P>
   Peter Gratten envies anyone who can.
</P>
<P>
   ``I used to volunteer, but I had to take a leave of absence,''
he says. ``I have pains. The doctors can't figure out what's
causing them. They go up my neck. I'm not living anymore. I'm just
existing.''
</P>
<P>
   Peter's family owned a nightclub in Fall River, Mass. His wife
died 30 years ago. He lived with his younger daughter for a while,
but she has three children to care for. He's been here about six
months, liked it until the pain hit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I used to help the ladies,'' says Peter, 84. ``I'd see them in
the hallways, lost. Sometimes they'd open the fire exit door and
the alarm would go off. You hear things all night.''
</P>
<P>
   He couldn't sleep, but he found the perfect night-shift job:
Tending the front desk. He could count on a visitor every day at 5
a.m.
</P>
<P>
   ``Josephine would come down, ready to dance,'' he says. ``A
couple of times she got me up to dance with her. I can't do that
now.''
</P>
<P>
   Josephine, who is sitting nearby, cuts him off.
</P>
<P>
   ``Never let yourself down, damnit,'' she says. ``I'm older than
all of you.'' With that, she's out of her seat, her arms waving
hula style.
</P>
<P>
   ``I used to dance at the Hawaiian room on 59th Street in a
little grass skirt my brother bought for me,'' she says. ``I danced
at the Hotel Taft and won $5,000 with my partner. We won $10,000 at
Madison Square Garden.''
</P>
<P>
   Sure enough, copies of old news clips and pictures of the dance
sensation from Mamaroneck, N.Y., line the wall near the big-screen
TV in the sitting room. Josephine danced her way through the
Depression and World War II. She danced through jobs as a meat
cutter, nurse's aide and waitress.
</P>
<P>
   ``I used to come out carrying the trays like this,'' she says
with a dip and sway. ``They gave me a big raise.''
</P>
<P>
   She was younger then, but not much. Josephine retired at 91. She
was living on her own in the Poconos when she fainted, fell and
cracked her head. ``That was more blood than I donated all during
the war,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   She came to Florida and stayed with her brother for several
years, but he worried she could fall again. She's been here since
August. (She insists it's only been a few weeks, even as she shows
pictures of herself at the Halloween party.)
</P>
<P>
   ``What's the difference?'' she asks. ``Whatever day it is, you
go ahead with things.''
</P>
<P>
   What she'd like to do is move on. Like many others, this was not
Josephine's first stop after leaving home. Almost everyone talks
about ``the other place.'' The other place was bigger or smaller.
It was noisier or quieter. It wasn't nearly as nice; it was much
nicer.
</P>
<P>
   Josephine liked the other place better. ``I feel like I'm in
jail here,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   She could go for a walk if she signed out at the desk, but she's
not so eager. She loved the outdoors back home. ``I love to do yard
work. I loved to play with my dogs. I used to have rabbits and
bears come right up to me.''
</P>
<P>
   There's nothing like that here. Besides, signing out is too much
like asking permission and she's too independent for that. She
doesn't even like the idea of people coming into her room to clean.
</P>
<P>
   ``I make my own bed,'' she says. ``I don't wait for anyone to do
anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Except, maybe, to get up and dance.
</P>
<P>
   Douglas Kalajian writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm
Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
