</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PARK-ARIZONA-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEIGHBORS COOL TO ARIZONA PARK PLAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By SETH LANDAU  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   AJO, Ariz. _ Most small-town residents in southwestern Arizona
can appreciate the Sonoran Desert's natural beauty. To a point,
they even want to preserve it.
</P>
<P>
   But the desire to preserve stops short of losing the way of life
they enjoy now, some Ajo and Gila Bend residents say. And that,
they fear, would be the result of a proposed Sonoran Desert
National Park.
</P>
<P>
   A group of 40 people, most of them from Tucson and Phoenix,
announced last week that it wants to create the park out of more
than 3 million acres of desert in southwestern Arizona. It's ``the
last big piece you can save'' in the lower 48 states, said Charles
Bowden, who backs the proposal.
</P>
<P>
   But Ajo resident and activist Bud Klinefelter sees it
differently.
</P>
<P>
   ``If (park advocates) get through with this, it's going to
destroy the community,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   With a population of 2,500 in the summer and 4,500 in the
winter, Ajo is a sleepy town surrounded by dormant copper mines,
Indian reservations and other federal land.
</P>
<P>
   Wayne Ivey, who was born and raised in Ajo, agreed that the park
would mean new restrictions for people who live in the tiny town.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only thing there is to do there is run around in the
desert: four-wheeling and motorcycling,'' he said by e-mail.
``Right now, Ajo is blocked on all sides, leaving only a small area
for recreation.''
</P>
<P>
   The national park would unify Organ Pipe Cactus National
Monument, Cabeza Prieta National Wildlife Refuge and the Barry M.
Goldwater Air Force Range. That marriage, Klinefelter said, would
put even tighter restrictions on Ajo's neighboring land.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't even go into Cabeza Prieta (now) without a permit,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   In Gila Bend, population 1,700, resident Ron Henry said a
national park would limit the use of the land just south of town.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have farmers that use (military range land) for grazing,''
he said. Civilians are permitted to use military land if they first
receive permission from a base commander.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have that much to do in this area and this (national
park) would curtail it that much more.''
</P>
<P>
   Bill Broyles, who has helped create the plan for the park, said
there already are many camping, hunting and driving restrictions
placed upon the three areas.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not out to restrict anybody's access,'' said Broyles, a
Tucson writer. Rather, his group wants to ``best sustain our uses
of the land,'' although he acknowledged that the National Park
Service does have a few more rules.
</P>
<P>
   Broyles and his colleagues are calling for the park to be formed
within five years. Daniel Arreola, an Arizona State University
geography professor, said there would be no further restrictions
for people who want to go into Cabeza Prieta and Organ Pipe because
those sites already are protected by the federal government.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only part that isn't already a park is the gunnery
range,'' said Arreola, who specializes in Mexican-American
borderlands.
</P>
<P>
   Not all Ajo residents oppose the park.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Crawford, program coordinator for the International Sonoran
Desert Alliance, said he is ``much in favor'' of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's probably the only way to preserve one of the few precious
places we have left on the planet,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Organ Pipe, Cabeza Prieta and the Goldwater range are managed by
the National Park Service, U.S. Fish and Wildlife Service and the
Defense Department, respectively. Representatives from the three
agencies have said they cannot comment about the initiative now.
</P>
<P>
   All three zones are owned by the Bureau of Land Management.
Interior Secretary Bruce Babbitt has no position on the proposal.
</P>
<P>
   To achieve national park status, the Sonoran Desert proposal
would need congressional approval and the president's signature. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
