<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-16 12:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2195 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MONUMENT-ARIZONA-AZR &LR;      03-16 0739
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONUMENT-ARIZONA-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ENVIRONMENTALISTS: PROPOSED MONUMENT SHOULD BE LARGER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE YOZWIAK  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   FLAGSTAFF, Ariz. _ A national monument proposed northwest of the
Grand Canyon should be twice as large as originally envisioned by
Interior Secretary Bruce Babbitt, the head of a prominent Flagstaff
environmental group said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The Grand Canyon Trust wants to make the proposed Shivwits
Plateau National Monument on the Arizona Strip nearly 1 million
acres, almost the size of adjacent Grand Canyon National Park.
</P>
<P>
   Geoff Barnard, president of the trust, said the larger area is
needed to protect wildlife migration corridors, prevent mining of
uranium and other minerals, stop abuse from off-road vehicles and
halt encroaching development from the booming populations of St.
George, Utah, and Las Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   Advocates contend that the monument would protect the last
remaining portions of the Grand Canyon that are not included within
the 1.1 million-acre Grand Canyon National Park.
</P>
<P>
   But opponents, including People for the USA, call the proposal
``Clinton Land Grab II.''
</P>
<P>
   The group, which advocates recreation, mining, ranching, logging
and oil drilling on public lands, still is steamed by President
Clinton's 1996 designation of the 1.7 million-acre Grand
Staircase-Escalante National Monument in southern Utah.
</P>
<P>
   Environmentalists and advocates of public-lands extraction
sparred Monday night at a town hall attended by nearly 500 people
at the auditorium of Northern Arizona University's Cline Library.
</P>
<P>
   Brent Mackelprang, a former mayor and lifelong resident of
Fredonia, said Babbitt was lying about grazing and hunting
continuing if a monument were established.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pretty soon, they lock you out,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Sylvia Allen of People for the USA told students in the crowd,
``Good luck to all of you in finding jobs.''
</P>
<P>
   Carmen Bradley, chairwoman of the Kaibab band of Paiute Indians,
said she supports the monument to ``preserve and protect the
pristine nature of the (Arizona) Strip.''
</P>
<P>
   Robert Euler, a Prescott anthropologist, also backed the
monument's establishment to prevent the destruction of
``irreplaceable cultural resources.''
</P>
<P>
   Even the venue for the town hall spurred complaints from People
for the USA. The group's executive director, Jeff Harris, told
members in an e-mail alert last week that NAU ``is not neutral
ground.''
</P>
<P>
   Harris described the campus as ``a place full of college
`activists' with nothing better to do.'' He urged his members in
Utah and Arizona to ``pack the joint,'' and bring signs reading
``Babbitt locks up our future'' and ``Yesterday Utah, today
Arizona, tomorrow the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Babbitt, in making the proposal in November, said he wanted to
protect the grazing rights of existing ranchers, many of them the
descendants of pioneer Mormon families who moved to the Arizona
Strip, north of the canyon, nearly a century ago.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the Escalante designation, made in the heat of the '96
presidential campaign, Babbitt has moved to enlist the approval of
Congress, especially the Arizona delegation, in creating the
Shivwits monument.
</P>
<P>
   However, Babbitt said that he is pledged to establishing the
monument before his term ends in 2001.
</P>
<P>
   The Shivwits Plateau _ named for a band of Paiute _ is managed
by the Lake Mead National Recreation Area and the Bureau of Land
Management. Much of the area was proposed in the 1970s as an
addition to Grand Canyon National Park. But the Senate balked at
the idea because cattle ranching and hunting are not allowed within
federal parks. They are allowed at national monuments.
</P>
<P>
   Barnard said motorcycles and other all-terrain vehicles have
turned the land south of St. George and north of the proposed
monument into ``a free-fire zone for ATVs.''
</P>
<P>
   Babbitt also said he is concerned that the area, only a few
hours' drive from Las Vegas, eventually could be overrun by miners
and developers.
</P>
<P>
   Babbitt's proposal covers 550,000 acres. But the Grand Canyon
Trust proposal would nearly double that, connecting Grand Canyon
National Park to wilderness areas in the Virgin Mountains.
</P>
<P>
   That would create a giant loop of national parks, monuments,
recreational areas and wilderness lands across northern Arizona and
southern Utah. &QL; 
 &QL; 
(Steve Yozwiak can be reached at steve.yozwiak(at)pni.com via
e-mail.) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-16-99 1217EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
