<DOCNO> NYT19990316.0075 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-16 13:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2227 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LYNCH-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      03-16 0678
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LYNCH-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STATES SHOULD STAND UP TO SLEAZY BOXING OPERATIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN LYNCH  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ I'm a uniquely gentle and sensitive soul. I was
joined in my family room Saturday night by a few other gentle and
sensitive souls who share my artistic affection for watching guys
in satin shorts beat each other bloody.
</P>
<P>
   My friend Gregg had picked Evander Holyfield to win. Holyfield,
however, had gotten his butt kicked. Lennox Lewis had landed more
jabs than Holyfield had landed punches. Then the decision was
announced _ a draw.
</P>
<P>
   One judge scored the fight for Lewis by 116-113. Another scored
it 115-115. The third gave the fight to Holyfield, 115-113. The
judges then left Madison Square Garden accompanied by their seeing
eye dogs.
</P>
<P>
   Gregg is a betting man. This charade saved him major bucks. He
reacted to this wonderful and totally unexpected news by jumping up
and shouting, ``This is an outrage! It's a total outrage!''
</P>
<P>
   OK, his money was still his own; Gregg was horrified
nonetheless. So was anybody who cares about honest athletic
competition. But this fight was a Don King Promotion, so what's the
surprise?
</P>
<P>
   In the modern era, nobody can fix a big boxing match by paying
off the fighters. How do you bribe a guy to take a dive when he's
already getting 40 million bucks? But referees and judges? They're
right downstairs, in the bargain basement. Don King fights
routinely reek.
</P>
<P>
   An agreeable stiff named Bruce Seldon once was rendered
unconscious by the breeze from a missed Mike Tyson right hand. As
heavyweight champ, Larry Holmes once took a tuneup bout against
journeyman Renaldo Snipes. Sensing that this was his life's
defining moment, Snipes fought way over his head.
</P>
<P>
   In a middle round, Snipes caught Holmes with a terrific shot and
decked him. Holmes got up, clutched and grabbed and, miraculously,
survived the round. He was in such pitiful shape that any
responsible referee would have stopped the bout.
</P>
<P>
   Not in a Don King Production, though. King had a fortune riding
on Holmes' next fight with Gerry Cooney. It was crucial that Holmes
win this one. So, a few rounds later, when a battered Holmes in got
a rather ordinary shot in against Snipes, that same referee stopped
the bout instantly, proclaiming Holmes the winner.
</P>
<P>
   What happened in the Holyfield-Lewis fight seems obvious. King
has a promotional contract with Holyfield but not with Lewis. The
bout had sold out the Garden, and in only days. It had attracted a
staggering pay-for-view audience.
</P>
<P>
   Barring a contest so one-sided that nobody would pay to see a
repeat, it was clear from the start that a rematch would be staged.
If Lewis had gotten the decision in the first fight, the new
champion would have used another promoter for the second. That
provided Don King with a strong rooting interest in Saturday
night's outcome.
</P>
<P>
   This sport is dirty because there's no national regulation. King
is a former Cleveland numbers guy who did a decade in the can for
kicking a business rival to death. The New York State Athletic
Commission should bar him. It won't because New Jersey and Nevada
won't. Since Don King can always find some state in which to
operate, every state lets him do business rather than see a big
fight go elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   The fees from this fight for the promoter and the sleazy
sanctioning bodies should be impounded while New York Attorney
General Eliot Spitzer launches a serious criminal probe into
consumer fraud. The New York State Athletic Commission also should
revise New York boxing rules.
</P>
<P>
   Immediately, New York _ and every other state, too, now that I
think of it _ should require the posting of judges' scores after
each round. That way, if the fix seems in, fans would have the
option early on of hanging the judges and the promoter from the
ring mike.
</P>
<P>
   In a gentle and sensitive fashion, of course.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Dan Lynch is a columnist for the Albany Times Union, P.O. Box
15000, Albany, NY 12212.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
