 PageExpress budget for the week of March 15, 1999 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PageExpress, a new service from The New York Times Syndicate,
consists of paginated pages built with content from Cox Newspapers
and The New York Times News Service. The pages are easy to retrieve
from a web site. You can use them just as they are or customize any
or all of the elements _ text, fonts, photos and graphics _ to suit
your needs.
</P>
<P>
   For more information on these pages, or to view a sample, use
your web browser to visit http://nytsyn.com/pageexpress.
</P>
<P>
   For the password to download and use the pages, call Bob Farnell
at The New York Times Syndicate: 800-972-3550 or e-mail him at
farnellb &LR; nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   Unless otherwise noted, pages are available after 2 p.m. Tue.,
March 16.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FOCUS: HAITI (Available by 2 p.m., Fri., March 19):
</P>
<P>
   (PAGE WILL INCLUDE SEVERAL COLOR PHOTOGRAPHS OF HAITI)
</P>
<P>
   In the fall of 1994, President Bill Clinton confounded his
critics by successfully using 20,000 U.S.-led forces to overthrow a
brutal military regime here and give democracy a second chance.
Almost no blood was shed. A triumph in foreign policy was declared.
But today, after nearly five years of pouring more than $2.2
billion of American taxpayers' money into this tiny island nation,
there is little to feel triumphant about.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: HAITI-FLOPS: The history of U.S. aid in Haiti is peppered
with some pretty big flops.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: HAITI-FUTURE: With American taxpayers more than $2 billion
in the hole when it comes to Haiti, a growing number of Congressmen
are increasingly concerned about the effectiveness of U.S. aid to
the hemisphere's poorest country.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ENTERTAINMENT: OSCAR PREDICTIONS (Available by 2 p.m., Thu., March
18):
</P>
<P>
   (PAGE WILL INCLUDE AT LEAST 3 COLOR PHOTOS, 1 COLOR
ILLUSTRATION, 1 GRAPHIC)
</P>
<P>
   Film critics Eleanor Ringel and Steve Murray predict Oscar
winners in all the major categories, indicating not only who will
win but who they personally think was best. (Will include color
illustration showing five nominees for best picture)
</P>
<P>
   WITH: OSCAR TELEVISION: A rundown on all Oscar-related
programming for Sunday, including pre-shows.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: OSCAR TRENDS: Story will detail what might happen Oscar
night that would be a first. For instance, Tom Hanks might become
the only actor to ever win three best actor trophies. Judi Dench
might win an Oscar for one of the shortest performances ever.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: PHANTOM MENACE COUNTDOWN: A two-column graphic,
``Countdown to `Star Wars,''' outlining the number of days
remaining until ``The Phantom Menace'' opens.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: VIDEO REVIEWS: ``One True Thing,'' ``The Waterboy''
``Bulworth.'' (Will include 2-column color studio photograph from
one of the reviewed films)
</P>
<P>
   WITH: CD REVIEWS: Beth Orton's ``Central Reservation,'' Elton
John and others on ``Aida'' soundtrack.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NASCAR (Available by 5 p.m., Thu., March 18) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   To be determined.
</P>
<P>
   (PAGE WILL INCLUDE AT LEAST 3 COLOR PHOTOGRAPHS AND 1 COLOR
ILLUSTRATION)
</P>
<P>
   WITH: WINSTON CUP NOTES: Odds and ends column on Winston Cup
</P>
<P>
   WITH: BUSCH SERIES NOTES
</P>
<P>
   WITH: TRACK GRAPHIC: A 2-column color illustration of Darlington
Raceway
</P>
<P>
   WITH: WINSTON CUP STANDINGS
</P>
<P>
   WITH: BUSCH GRAND NATIONAL STANDINGS
</P>
<P>
   WITH: SUNDAY'S RACE AT A GLANCE: A fact box previewing Sunday's
TranSouth Financial 400 at Darlington Raceway.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FOOD: CUMIN: TRENDY SPICE &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (PAGE INCLUDES 1 COLOR PHOTO)
</P>
<P>
   If you don't have a jar of cumin nestled between the salt and
pepper, you are definitely out of step with the times. Sales of
cumin skyrocketed 62 percent between 1995 and 1997, according to
McCormick &AMP; Co., the country's major spice purveyor. That makes it
the fastest-growing spice in this country, outpacing other spices,
which grew a more modest 17 percent. (Includes 3-column color photo
of different-colored cumin seeds.)
</P>
<P>
   WITH: CUMIN BOX: How do you pronounce Cumin?
</P>
<P>
   WITH: RECIPES: Moroccan Spiced Steaks, Cumin Cheese Toast,
Orange Avacado Salad.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: CYBERSPICE: There is such a wealth of knowledge about
herbs and spices that one could make a lifetime study of these
fascinating plants. And for eons, people have done just that. In
ancient times in many societies, knowledge of herbs and their uses
both in medicine and in cooking set a person apart as a wise and
valued member of the group. Today, these people are on the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: FOOD NOTES: Food fanatics who read the New York Times or
magazines such as Gourmet and Saveur have heard of Piquilla
Peppers, the sweet, slightly piquant beak-shaped peppers from the
Spanish Pyrenees. Given that trendy chefs are so eager to feature
them, it's surprising to learn that the fire-roasted pimientos are
a canned product.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHEELS: PONTIAC GRAND AM &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (PAGE INCLUDES 1 COLOR PHOTO, 1 COLOR MUG SHOT)
</P>
<P>
   The folks at Pontiac could have left well enough alone with the
Grand Am. Since its 1992 redesign, the nameplate has ranked as one
of the 10 most popular cars in the United States. And with annual
sales in excess of 200,000, the Pontiac has led the compact class
in retail registrations for the past five years. Yet the automaker
unveiled a new design for 1999. (Includes 3-column color photo of
Grand Am)
</P>
<P>
   WITH: AT A GLANCE: Fact box on the Pontiac Grand Am.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: THE MECHANIC: Getting your car repaired? Pick any two:
good, fast or cheap. (Includes 1-column color mug shot of
columnist)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PERSONAL TECHNOLOGY: SHOULD YOU BUY A PC WITH PENTIUM III? &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (PAGE INCLUDES 2 COLOR PHOTOS)
</P>
<P>
   PCs with the new Pentium III chip from Intel are on shelves now.
These new machines are the fastest yet, reasonably priced and _
based on early reports _ relatively bug-free. Just don't buy one.
(Includes 3-column color photo of chip)
</P>
<P>
   WITH: FACT BOX: Facts about the new Pentium III chip.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: TECH BRIEFS: Sports teams have had their own Web sites
since the Internet became popular. Now individual players are
taking the cue. For example, there's The Official Tim Duncan
Website of the San Antonio Spurs second-year power forward.
(Includes 2-column color photo of web site)
</P>
<P>
   WITH: TECHNOBUDDY: As soon as they're available in your
neighborhood _ and if you have the money to spare _ get a cable
modem and use it to connect to the Internet. That's what I did a
week ago. It made a big difference, but maybe not in the ways you'd
expect.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: ON-LINE LIFE: This year's hot technology trend is
compelling content from media players such as newspapers,
magazines, television networks and cable companies.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: INTERNET NOTES: One of the most popular instruments for
amateur musicians is the guitar. As it turns out, the Web is a
terrific resource for would-be guitar players.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TRAVEL: EUROPE'S MOST ROMANTIC CITIES &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (PAGE INCLUDES 4 COLOR PHOTOS)
</P>
<P>
   Columnist offers picks for the most romantic cities in Europe
plus advice for those planning a honeymoon: First, stay in one
place in Europe. Don't go driving all over the continent in an
effort to see everything. You'll just get tired and cranky. Stay in
one city, and it will become ``your'' city, the one that will be
foremost in your photo album. (Includes main art of couple riding a
gondola in Venice plus secondary art of gondolier; color photo of
Paris cafe, color photo of The Louvre)
</P>
<P>
   WITH: LIABILITY: Issues of hotel liability may come as unwelcome
news to travelers.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: TRAVEL BRIEFS: A New York tour operator and airline-ticket
consolidator has opened a Web site to accept bids on domestic and
overseas tickets, and the owner says that no bid _ not even $1 _ is
too small to start.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BOOKS: `VISIONS OF TECHNOLOGY' &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (PAGE INCLUDES 1 B&AMP;W ILLUSTRATION, 3 COLOR PICS OF BOOKS, 1
COLOR MUG SHOT OF COLUMNIST)
</P>
<P>
   In ``Visions of Technology,'' Richard Rhodes has compiled an
anthology of more than 200 selections tracing the development of
technology through the 20th century. It begins with the birth of
radio, movies and airplanes, moves through the era of television
and satellites, and concludes with the development of the Internet
and artificial intelligence as the century closes. (Includes
3-column B&AMP;W illustration of old man looking at computer)
</P>
<P>
   WITH: REVIEW: There is a point in some books when satire gives
way to outright meanness. Which means readers will recognize that
``Me: By Jimmy (Big Boy) Valente,'' Garrison Keillor's supposed
``just having a little fun'' mock-book about Jesse Ventura, the
pro-wrestler-turned-governor of Keillor's beloved home state of
Minnesota, is, frankly, nasty. (Includes color photo of book cover)
</P>
<P>
   WITH: REVIEW: You read a novel like ``Dreamland'' because you
want to get lost in the past. And where better to get lost than New
York City in 1910, with its millionaires and immigrants, factory
girls and gamblers, politicos and cops, outcasts and reformers?
(Includes color photo of book cover)
</P>
<P>
   WITH: SKUBE ON BOOKS: Who isn't impressed by a two-ton sentence?
You wouldn't want to diagram it, and you certainly couldn't sing
it. Either would ruin it. You only behold its profundity, whatever
its meaning. (Includes 1-column color mug shot of columnist)
</P>
<P>
   WITH: N.Y. TIMES BEST SELLERS LIST
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SCIENCE &AMP; HEALTH: RECOVERING FROM EATING DISORDERS &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (PAGE INCLUDES 3 COLOR PHOTOGRAPHS)
</P>
<P>
   A young woman faces the formidable task of beating bulimia and
anorexia nervosa after six years. But she wants her personal
suffering to help others recover from eating disorders. ``I want to
go around to high schools and talk,'' she says. She's also
establishing a foundation to help people pay for the expensive
treatment that health plans rarely cover. (Includes 3-column color
photo of woman holding a picture of herself and 1-column photo of
dancer sitting at table.)
</P>
<P>
   WITH: WEB SITES: A list of Web sites dealing with eating
disorders.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: SCANNER: Besides decreasing the drugs and increasing the
comfort for fidgety children, the Aquilion scanner will enable the
radiation department to streamline its schedule and sooner
accommodate people without emergencies. (Includes 2-column color
photo of child entering scanning device.)
</P>
<P>
   WITH: ARTHRITIS DRUGS: Thousands of arthritis patients
nationwide are being prescribed Enbrel and two other new medicines
to control pain and swelling with fewer side effects, such as
stomach and kidney distress.
</P>
