<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LANGUAGE-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DISCONCERTED BY `DISCONNECT' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAN FREEMAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you hate it, blame it on Washington. The word has been
marching northward for more than two decades, but it's only in the
past few months that disconnect, in its new noun form, has been
drawing queries _ and complaints _ from readers and colleagues.
</P>
<P>
   ``Vile,'' one copy editor calls it. ``I came across it three
times today in one (long) article,'' writes Nancy Shohet West of
Framingham. ``Is this the flip side of impact as a verb?'' And
recently, it's been appearing in the Globe with quotation marks _
``a major `disconnect' between the Beltway media and the rest of
the populace'' _ which is the punctuational equivalent of holding
our editorial nose. Apparently some editors, having just noticed
the arrival of disconnect, want to make it clear they don't yet
consider it respectable, everyday usage.
</P>
<P>
   It can only be Boston's resistance to fashion that has kept
disconnect at a distance so long. Back in 1990, William Safire had
already collected enough examples of the word, mostly from
Washington sources, to report on it in his New York Times column.
At the time, the earliest citation he could find was a 1984
quotation from Pat Caddell, the political consultant and pollster
to President Carter.
</P>
<P>
   But a more recent search finds disconnect in a 1976 issue of
Aviation Week and Space Technology, again in a Washington context:
A spokesman blames the cancellation of Minuteman funding on ``a
disconnect between the research and development community, the
Defense Dept. comptroller, program analysis and evaluation, and the
Office of Management and Budget.'' (Sounds like three or four
disconnects, but who's counting?)
</P>
<P>
   Disconnect as a noun was in Webster's unabridged dictionary in
1976, as the short form of ``disconnecting switch,'' a safety
switch to cut off an electrical circuit. The noun was also current
within phone and power companies, who referred to the customers
they'd cut off as disconnects. It's a short figurative leap from a
gap in the power supply to the notion of a disconnect between the
American people and the politicians, for example, or between a
friend's words and her deeds.
</P>
<P>
   This new disconnect is not just a gap or a gulf. It comes only
between people, or phenomena, with the potential to make a
connection; it implies a broken circuit, not a distant separation.
We wouldn't say there was a disconnect between Mars and Venus
(except in the pop-psychology universe), or between plants and
animals.
</P>
<P>
   As for disconnect's origins, there's no law against making verbs
into nouns in English. Unless you object to a laugh and a scratch,
both derived from verbs, you've got no theoretical reason to
despise disconnect.
</P>
<P>
   It's too soon to tell whether disconnect will prove ``the flip
side of impact as a verb'' _ that is, whether it will have to fight
its way toward respectability against a tide of disapproval. But
disconnect has already hung around for more than 20 years without
attracting much hostility, and it fits right into the techspeak
that's spreading, for better or worse, through our vocabulary. For
instance, in a Times interview last week, novelist Sue Miller spoke
of domestic fiction as her ``default mode.'' In the wired world she
shares with most of us, disconnect isn't likely to be banned from
the lexicon.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Calling all Beantowners &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The monumental Oxford English Dictionary is an ongoing project,
and ordinary readers can play a role in the revisions now (and
forever) underway. OED entries list the first written citation of
each English word, but many such dates are revised as earlier
evidence turns up. And among the items on the OED's latest
``appeals list'' _ words they're hoping to learn more about _ is
Beantowner, meaning, of course, someone from Boston. The editors
are looking for a citation before 1961, so any Beantowner who has
such evidence is invited to send it along to OED3(at)oup.co.uk.
</P>
<P>
   Sci-fi buffs may be able to help with a couple of other
requests: There's probably a space junk citation from before 1979
(how could Heinlein not have used that phrase?), and the OED is
also seeking pre-1979 examples of men in black _ ``people believed
to visit those who claim to have had an alien encounter,'' as they
delicately put it. The truth is out there . . . .
</P>
<P>
   (What's the word? Write or e-mail yours to Jan Freeman at The
Boston Globe, Box 2378, Boston, MA 02107-2378;
freeman(at)globe.com. Please include a hometown and phone number.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
