<SLUG> BC-NHAMP-IDENTITY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GRANITE STATE VOTE TAXES N.H. LEGACY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By THOMAS FARRAGHER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DERRY, N.H. _ The stingy image may have been only caricature.
Still, New Hampshire reveled in it. This was a flinty place where
money did not come easy and frugality was a time-tested virtue.
</P>
<P>
   This was not Taxachusetts. And for generations, neighbors sent
neighbors to the State House in Concord with firm orders to keep it
that way.
</P>
<P>
   ``Live free or die. We lived that, you know?'' said Roland
Routhier, 73, who for 32 years ran Shamrock Cleaners on Railroad
Avenue here before retiring in 1980. ``I never hesitate to tell
people when we went out of state that we are the only place in the
union that doesn't have a sales or an income tax. We're proud of
that.''
</P>
<P>
   But earlier this month, that solid symbol of parsimoniousness
was jolted. In a seismic vote, state lawmakers in the House of
Representatives voted to approve the state's first-ever income tax.
</P>
<P>
   For New Hampshire, which for decades has paid its bills with a
patchwork quilt of levies and fees that helped preserve its status
as the only state never to have enacted a broad-based sales or
income tax, it was a watershed.
</P>
<P>
   And in it, some see a symbol of what the Granite State has
become.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we're consciously aware of the fact that we are being
invaded by America,'' said R. Stuart Wallace, an adjunct history
professor at Plymouth State College.
</P>
<P>
   Said Donald Hall, the award-winning Wilmot poet and author: ``I
may lament the decline of the old culture. But that decline is
real.''
</P>
<P>
   But for people like Peg Lipin, a Massachusetts native who moved
here in 1977, the income tax is the tool to break the chains of a
financing system that has meant absurd property taxes and painfully
unequal school systems.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tradition is fine,'' Lipin said. ``But there's always a time
for new traditions. We're working with a system that worked a long
time ago, but it doesn't fit the state's needs anymore. Something
needs to be done.''
</P>
<P>
   The fate of the income tax is uncertain. It was narrowly
approved by the Republican-controlled House. The state Senate,
controlled by Democrats for the first time in 86 years, could
approve it. But Governor Jeanne Shaheen, a Democrat, is promising
to veto it.
</P>
<P>
   Still, observers agree, the state Supreme Court's 1997 ruling
that the current system of raising money for education with local
property taxes created unconstitutional inequities between rich and
poor towns, is the greatest-ever threat to New Hampshire's
antipathy for sales and income taxes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a seminal event,'' said Thomas Rath, a Concord attorney
and a former state attorney general. ``We've had a series of
elections here where would-be governors have been defined by what
they would not do rather than what they would do.''
</P>
<P>
   When the income tax bill was approved by the House March 4 in a
194-190 vote with support of almost every Democrat and many
Republicans representing poor school districts, Representative
Elizabeth Hager, a Republican from Concord and the bill's chief
sponsor, clenched her fist in victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was its last great hope,'' Hager said. ``If we lost, it
would have been another 20 years before we got another chance. It
still might be.''
</P>
<P>
   Like the larger issue itself, public support for the income tax
is in dispute. Proponents cite a Becker Institute survey showing 52
percent support the income tax. Opponents point to a survey by the
American Research Group of Manchester last December, indicating
that two-thirds of the public opposes it.
</P>
<P>
   But with 400 members, the New Hampshire House is arguably one of
the most representative legislative bodies in the Western world _
intimate political terrain where the elected are never too far from
those who elected them.
</P>
<P>
   As state lawmakers struggle to reach a court-imposed deadline of
April 1 to enact a new education finance plan, what hangs in the
balance is not only how New Hampshire pays for its classrooms, but
whether its decades-old litmus test on taxes lives or finally dies.
</P>
<P>
   The end of what is known here as ``The Pledge'' would be the
curtain on a post-war era.
</P>
<P>
   Before he became a chief aide to President Dwight D. Eisenhower,
Sherman Adams was New Hampshire's Republican governor. Faced with a
yawning budget gap in 1949, Adams proposed the adoption of an
income tax.
</P>
<P>
   When state lawmakers rejected the proposal by 17 votes, the
state's arch-conservative newspaper, the Union Leader of
Manchester, cheered. ``The only way to save is not to spend,'' a
Union Leader editorial declared.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly thereafter the newspaper's publisher, William Loeb, made
sure gubernatorial candidates publicly promised to be savers, not
spenders.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's sort of a check on the public sector,'' said Will
McEachern, a Portsmouth native and an economics professor at the
University of Connecticut. ``We don't have to mind the store if we
know they don't have access to the cash register.''
</P>
<P>
   A buoyant economy, creative financing, and Loeb's dominance of
the state's media kept the issue at bay for another generation.
</P>
<P>
   In 1971, Governor Walter R. Peterson's proposal for a 3 percent
income tax was rejected 219-157 in a House vote. When Peterson
sought a third term running on a pro-tax platform, he was opposed
by two-time primary loser Meldrim Thomson Jr., whose winning
campaign slogan appeared on his car's license plate: ``AX TAX.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a sense that we were sort of headed for an income
tax back then, but when Thomson got elected, that was the end of
that,'' said Hank Nichols, an assistant professor of journalism at
New England College in Henniker.
</P>
<P>
   Those who dared flaunt The Pledge did so at their peril. With a
proposed income tax designed by his economist brother, Will, Paul
McEachern ran for governor in 1984 and lost in the primary. He
became the Democratic gubernatorial nominee in 1986 and 1988,
losing to Pledge-takers John Sununu and Judd Gregg despite having
sworn off income taxes.
</P>
<P>
   ``At some point, if you're going to choose to lead, it doesn't
do any good to run and lose just to make a point,'' said McEachern.
``New Hampshire is a little bit ornery _ always has been.''
</P>
<P>
   If that orneriness has abated in this year's tax debate,
students of New Hampshire said, it is because of shifting political
realities: Loeb died in 1981 and the influence of his Union Leader
has been waning. Now, a majority of the state's residents _ 60
percent by one estimate _ are not New Hampshire natives.
</P>
<P>
   There is also a simpler explanation. Faced with the estimated
$900 million needed every year to fund schools, state taxpayers are
out of more unconventional options.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, they must consider the kinds of big-ticket levies used
by other states _ if not the income tax, then higher taxes on
business, or even casino-style video gambling.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's going on now is that New Hampshire is becoming more
like the rest of the states in the country that have had to work
out the process of providing more equal funding for education,''
said Jere Daniell, a history professor at Dartmouth College.
</P>
<P>
   But in such pragmatism, say many residents, is the dilemma: How
to find the money without becoming more like the other states. And
with a deadline looming, nobody yet seems to have put forward a
convincing answer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
