u t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRAVEL-COLLINS-COLUMN     03-16 1077
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-COLLINS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A WATERY `BATTLE' IN NEW ZEALAND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BUD COLLINS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAPE REINGA, New Zealand _ The battlefield is wet and windy,
fumingly ferocious, and relentlessly fascinating. As oceans collide
like two white buffalo butting horns, your unobstructed ringside
seat is on the grassy rise beside the Cape Reinga lighthouse. An
ivory cinder block tower, it sits, beamingly, at the uppermost tip
of New Zealand's North Island, the storm-bitten nail of a slender,
sandy digit pointed into endless expanses of sea.
</P>
<P>
   A lonely, gale-pounded end-of-the-line, this is known to the
Maoris as ``Te hika o te ika'' _ tail of the fish. They say it's
the terminus of their earthly line, too, sacred ground, the
jumping-off point for spirits headed to the next world.
</P>
<P>
   Neither the Tasman Sea, charging from the left, nor the South
Pacific, roiling and rolling from the right, is of a mind to give
an inch as they meet head-on in their unceasing territorial war,
trying to total each other. It doesn't work, of course. No
surrender. Both will survive contentiously forever. But as watery
sparks noisily fly in the form of waves crunching and leaping
whitecappingly as high as 30 and 40 feet, they define the words
``maelstrom'' and ``turmoil.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Mesmerizing,'' says my friend Aurelio as we spectate on this
rock-faced bluff above the eternal clash that seems a gigantic
briny tossing salad of many greens. ``I give the Tasman the edge
today, but I suspect the Pacific will retaliate.''
</P>
<P>
   This is also the end of one of the better bus lines that runs
from Kaitaia along Ninety Mile Beach to the Cape.
</P>
<P>
   ``Better take the bus trip,'' Ian McPhee had advised. ``Forget
driving your rental for the day. You need a 4-wheel-drive to even
get onto the beach, and some of them have been known to sink in a
soft spot and get inundated by the tide. Instant junk. Great only
for the guy that owns the tow truck. But you don't need explaining
something like that to the rental agency, and also maybe walk 20
miles or so back to town. Leave it to the bus drivers at Harrison's
Tours. They know the way.''
</P>
<P>
   Ian is the proprietor of the Kauri Lodge motel in Kaitaia, a
refuge where his wife, Sally, bountifully greets those checking in
with hot, fresh-baked scones. She also wisely suggested dinner at
the Kaitaia Hotel because of Patricia Wakefield's cooking.
</P>
<P>
   Ninety Mile Beach is ``actually 62 miles long,'' said a laughing
bus driver Pat Heta, a Maori. ``But it probably seemed endless to
the first Europeans to see it, and I guess Ninety Mile had a nice
sound to it, so . . . maybe the old tourism hype?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Aw, who's counting?'' said Aurelio. ``It's so beautiful,
whatever the mileage. Just beaches-and-cream,'' she said, alluding
to the surf constantly foaming and frothing on the left as the bus
wheeled along the broad sand flat. High-rising as ivory and khaki
ramparts on the right were dunes patrolled by green-coated scrub.
We were locked into in a corridor of blues and beige: sea, sky, and
sand.
</P>
<P>
   Heta, the driver, said, ``In the old days when nobody much was
around, they would hold speed tests for racing cars here. Kingsford
Smith, an Australian driver and pilot _ the Sydney Airport is named
for him _ did 120 m.p.h. in 1932. I don't know what the bus record
is, but I have no intention of threatening it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nowadays there are annual surfing carnivals and a 36-mile
footrace. A marathon-plus, and you can't get lost. No turnings or
hills, but you might have to watch out for wild horses.''
</P>
<P>
   Or errant fishing lines at the Bluff, a rocky platform that
suddenly appeared at water's edge. We stopped to watch a gang of
Maori fishermen up on the black outcropping where waves splattered
and showered on three sides. Men and women, they furiously wielded
15-foot bamboo poles, rearing back and then casting their lines
into the agitated waters, somehow skilfully managing not to hook
each other or kibitzers.
</P>
<P>
   They were pulling in sizable snapper and trevally, a good day at
black rock. As one of the polesters, Henry Nathan, happily
observed, ``We'll never starve around here.''
</P>
<P>
   After departing the anglers, Heta announced, ``Now, for all of
you who may be missing winter in your Northern Hemisphere home,
we'll have some toboggan rides.''
</P>
<P>
   New Zealand seaside style, that is. Stopping beside a snow-white
monster dune, altitude over 100 feet, he produced from the baggage
compartment plastic two-man sleds. ``Just climb to the top and
slide down. I promise you won't get frostbite (in 85- degree
temperature) or luge bruise.''
</P>
<P>
   No idle promise. But he didn't add that an uphill slog in hot
knee-deep sand will make you feel dune-in pretty fast. The reward
is not pretty fast _ in fact a slo-mo slide as breathtaking as
skateboarding in mud. One walk up to the summit in blazing sunshine
is sufficient. Oh, well. The concept sounds good.
</P>
<P>
   ``A singular novelty, right?'' rationalized Aurelio. ``Probably
not a potential Olympic event, but you don't have to wear a crash
helmet, either.''
</P>
<P>
   A detour took us to the Wagener Museum for lunch. The museum
itself is an eclectic melange of such items as a 1928 American Easy
Spin Dry washing machine, a 1906 Edison Gramophone, player pianos,
an 1897 typewriter, Maori art and crafts, stuffed animals _ ``a
collection of collections,'' in the words of curator Owen Wagener,
a descendant of the founder.
</P>
<P>
   Even an incredible assemblage of about 500 chamber pots and
bedpans. Most of these chinaware, glass, and metal conveniences are
imaginatively shaped, colored, and decorated, many hand-painted.
Certainly state of a lost art.
</P>
<P>
   ``The largest such collection in the Southern Hemisphere _ and,
we believe, second in the world only to one in Germany,'' modestly
stated Wagener. ``There is something for every taste.''
</P>
<P>
   And every waste? Aurelio wondered, ``Are there any in Limoges,
Waterford, or Steuben?''
</P>
<P>
   Most stylish was a 1903 model billed as a ``non-splash thunder
bowl,'' and with a built-in music box that plays ``Oft in a Stilly
Night.'' But a 1940 number from England was timely and satisfying,
bottomed with a portrait of Adolf Hitler. Its music box plays ``In
the Fuhrer's Face.''
</P>
<P>
   Back to the beach, the bus soon pulled up at the Cape Reinga
lighthouse, in time for the big game: Tasman vs. South Pacific.
You're never late, and it's always a tie.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
