<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-16 13:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2283 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MUSIC-ALI-ART-BOS &LR;      03-16 1712
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-ALI-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TATYANA ALI JUGGLES HARVARD, HOLLYWOOD AND A RECORDING CAREER 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUZANNE C. RYAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- It's a rainy Thursday night in Cambridge,
</P>
<P>
   and the House of Blues is packed. ``I'm so excited, I'm going to
scream!'' says Keri Palmer, 19. Hovering expectantly in front of
the stage with a posse of fans, she says, ``I really want to meet
her.'' The ``her'' that's eliciting so much enthusiasm is Tatyana
Ali, actress, Harvard freshman, and pop singer.
</P>
<P>
   Standing in a waiting room overlooking the stage, dressed in
shiny blue pants and a Karl Kani tank top, the 5-foot-4 Ali looks
every bit the star as she gears up to perform live at her first
Boston performance. Still, you'd never guess what she's thinking
about: ``All of my friends have a quantitative reasoning test
tonight at 8!'' groans Ali, 20, glancing at a clock (It's 7:25.)
Cupping a mug of steaming hot water, the college student paces the
room, adding, ``Some of them ditched it. But some couldn't.''
</P>
<P>
   Talk about extracurricular activities. Best known as Ashley
Banks, a character from the TV series ``The Fresh Prince of
Bel-Air,'' (1990-1996), Ali is managing to combine the unthinkable:
the music industry, Hollywood, and Harvard.
</P>
<P>
   Many a famous name has launched a career after Harvard. But not
many entertainers maintain jet-setting careers while toiling in the
Ivy League. It's a heavy load. So heavy that Ali has taken four
months off to tour nationally in 50 cities with the group 'N Sync
and promote her debut CD ``Kiss the Sky.''
</P>
<P>
   But Ali swears she'll be back for Harvard's summer session. ``I
want to finish on time,'' she says. ``I'll do five classes my
sophomore year and summer school this summer.''
</P>
<P>
   Does Ali ever waver about school? With recognition, momentum,
and youth on her side, why not save Harvard for later, for when
Hollywood turns to the next young starlet?
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always wanted to go to college,'' says Ali. ``Forty
percent of my reasoning is brainwashing from when I was little. On
my father's side of the family, they are all educators. And on my
mother's side, not going to college is not considered an option.''
</P>
<P>
   A native of Long Island who has lived in Los Angeles since
landing the part on ``Fresh Prince'' at age 11, Ali could easily
have attended school in California. But she says, ``I know a lot of
people who did that. You're so close to the business. Every
audition and every meeting seems so important that you just leave
school. I figured if I was far away, I can only do the really
important things.''
</P>
<P>
   What's more, she says, growing up on the East Coast, she recalls
lots of road trips with her parents and two younger sisters. ``We
went to all the colleges. I have this picture in my mind of ivy and
cobblestone streets and students sitting on the grass. In
California, everything is so new. It's not the same.''
</P>
<P>
   Ali arrived in Cambridge with no fanfare. Like every other
freshman, she was convinced she needed new clothes. ``My dad said,
`I don't understand why you have to go shopping,' '' she recalls.
``I have a ton of clothes, but not for everyday school stuff.
They're either dressy clothes or sweats. I needed jeans.''
</P>
<P>
   While Ali could have selected a luxury apartment overlooking the
Charles, she opted for a dorm and a suite of rooms with five
roommates and no cable TV. ``An apartment?'' she says. ``That's no
fun. That's totally missing the point.'' Since Ali arrived at
school a day late (she was in London working), she got stuck with
the smallest bedroom and the top bunk of a bunk bed.
</P>
<P>
   In the beginning, Ali's fellow students were curious about the
celebrity, often approaching her in the dining hall. ``People would
say, `I used to watch you when I was little.' Or they'd say, `I
have your album,' '' says Ali. But only one student made a real
fuss, asking to take a picture with her. ``I said, `You do realize
that I'm graduating with you, right? You'll see me every day for
the next four years' . . . It was weird for me because in LA no one
cares. It's such a factory town.''
</P>
<P>
   It didn't take long for down-to-earth Ali to settle in around
Harvard Square, although admittedly she has a somewhat surreal
student lifestyle. A good friend and mentor is superstar Will
Smith, who also starred on ``Fresh Prince.''
</P>
<P>
   ``My roommates will say `Will Smith just left a message. Do you
think that's normal?''' laughs Ali, who talks to Smith at least
twice a month.
</P>
<P>
   When Ali went clubbing with her friends recently, a DJ was
playing her hit song ``Daydreamin' '' when the group walked in. ``I
was like, `Oh God. I'll go to the bathroom now,' '' she recalls.
</P>
<P>
   And when radio station JAM'N 94.5 agreed to sponsor a show of
hers at the House of Blues Feb. 4 (giving away tickets to callers),
classmates like George Reed, Ali's boyfriend, got to see a
different side of her. Ali executed choreographed steps with four
dancers and confidently shouted in the microphone: ``Put your hands
in the air!. . .What's up, everybody? I feel so much love. You know
this is my home town, right?''
</P>
<P>
   Said Reed last month, ``Tonight is the first time I saw her
perform live. It was amazing.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ali says getting up on stage in Boston was a relief. ``When I
saw my friends there I thought, `Good, now they know me.' This is
such a big part of my life.''
</P>
<P>
   Moments of glamour aside, Ali's life qualifies as ordinary on
most days. Rather than limousines, she'll take the MBTA through the
city _ with a group, not alone. ``I told my mom I took the bus to
the Cheesecake Factory. She just pursed her lips,'' Ali says. ``I'm
in college. No one wants to spend money on a cab when they can
spend 85 cents for a token.''
</P>
<P>
   On campus Ali typically wears no makeup _ just lip balm. Her
hair? ``I might streak my hair blue or braid my whole head,'' she
says. Her uniform is normally jeans, T-shirts, and sweaters. ``I
still think I'm in California. I keep wearing tank tops under
sweaters as if I can take off the sweaters at some point. The cold
is hard to get used to.''
</P>
<P>
   Like many students, Ali sometimes borrows clothes from her
roommates. ``They wear my clothes, too. It's no big deal.''
</P>
<P>
   Ali, an African-American studies major, finished her first
semester in January. She took classes in the morning and studied in
the evening. And the afternoons? ``There was a lot of
procrastination going on,'' she admits. ``Hanging out with
girlfriends.'' To show her school spirit, Ali joined a choir. But
in rehearsals with 300 singers from 7 to 10 p.m., she found herself
falling asleep. ``I couldn't do it.''
</P>
<P>
   She was traveling every weekend to radio stations from Chicago
to San Francisco to promote her CD, which was released last summer.
She was also juggling offers to appear in TV specials and award
shows; she has presented at the MTV Video Music Awards, the
American Music Awards, the Billboard Music Awards, and the NAACP
Image Awards.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things come up, and I get excited,'' she says. ``I'm a pretty
ambitious person. But then I think `What will I miss in school?'
It's all about priorities and not being greedy. You have to keep
yourself in mind and what you want.''
</P>
<P>
   So when Disney called asking her to host a Christmas TV special,
she said no. ``I would have missed a class where you can only miss
two sessions,'' she says. Then Ali changed her mind. ``I talked to
the professor and he said OK. But I'm not into going to a professor
and saying, `I have a special situation.' That's lame. Everybody
has a story.''
</P>
<P>
   In the cynical world of show business, Ali has managed to keep
it real, perhaps because her family is a huge part of her life and
they keep her grounded. ``I'm very proud of her,'' says her mother,
Sonia Ali. ``Of course, the school thing is the biggest thing for
me. Nobody can take a degree away from you.''
</P>
<P>
   Sonia accompanies Ali on all of her business trips and
appearances or ensures that some other relative is present. ``You
have to be very careful,'' she says. Indeed, during a recent photo
shoot in Boston for the cover of Touch, a British pop culture and
music magazine, Sonia paused while talking on two cellular phones
at once. Staring at her daughter, who was lying on the floor,
posing for the camera, Sonia asked an observer, ``Is her top very
open?'' Ali laughed, replying: ``No, Mom.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ali has been acting since she was 3 and saw ``E.T.'' on the big
screen. ``I saw all those kids, and I said, `I want to do that,' ''
she says. ``I liked auditioning . . . You sing. You dance. I never
cared if I got the part.'' She sang on ``Star Search'' twice when
she was 7, winning both times. Later, she appeared in the Broadway
version of ``Fences.''
</P>
<P>
   When Ali landed the part on ``Fresh Prince,'' Sonia, who is
originally from Panama, sacrificed her career as a registered nurse
to move Ali and her two younger daughters (now 13 and 16) to Los
Angeles while her husband, Sheriff Ali, who is from Trinidad,
continued working in New York as a police officer. ``We did the
bicoastal thing,'' says Sonia. ``We came home twice a year and my
husband would come to LA sometimes twice a month.''
</P>
<P>
   When the show went off the air three years ago, Ali spent her
senior year in high school doing all the things she could never do
in the classroom trailer on the set. ``I was part of every
committee and club,'' she says. ``I went to all the parties.''
</P>
<P>
   Ali deferred her Harvard admittance for one year to record her
first album. She's on tour now, she says, because she wants to give
the album everything she can.
</P>
<P>
   She plans to continue recording albums while at Harvard. ``I'm
already itching to get back in the recording studio,'' she says.
``I feel a lot stronger than when I first started.''
</P>
<P>
   But Ali would also like to act. ``I don't think I have to make a
choice,'' she says. In the summer of 2000, she hopes to do a movie
or another US tour promoting a second album. ``I'm working on new
songs now,'' she says. ``I can record this summer.''
</P>
<P>
   After her Harvard classes, of course.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
