<DOCNO> NYT19990316.0095 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-16 13:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2288 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RAC-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      03-16 1185
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAME AWAITS SELECT FEW AS BALLOTS ARRIVE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON INDRISANO  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Hall of Fame ballot has arrived. There are 130 voters
nationwide, and ballots are due Friday. The winners will be
announced during Kentucky Derby week.
</P>
<P>
   Here's how one turf writer voted:
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
JOCKEY &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The nominees: Russell Baze, Earlie Fires, Jackie Westrope.
</P>
<P>
   The vote: (1) Baze. (2) Fires. (3) Westrope.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Baze rode 400 winners for the seventh consecutive
time. He has been the leading rider on the Northern California
circuit annually since 1980. He is the 12th rider to achieve 6,000
victories and has won at a 21 percent clip during his career. From
1992-96, he led the country in wins, a record run.
</P>
<P>
   Because he is based at Bay Meadows and Golden Gate Fields, Baze
doesn't get much publicity. However, his Hall of Fame credentials
speak for themselvs.
</P>
<P>
   Fires was the leading apprentice of 1965 and is still riding. He
also has won 6,000 races and has done a lot, but not as much as
Baze. Westrope was the leading rider in the nation in 1933 as a
15-year-old apprentice. He was killed in a racing accident at Santa
Anita in 1958. Frankly, this voter is in no position to properly
evaluate a man who was a star 66 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
TRAINER &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The nominees: Neil Drysdale, D. Wayne Lukas, Richard Mandella.
</P>
<P>
   The vote: (1) Lukas. (2) Mandella. (3) Drysdale.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1974, Lukas has won 927 stakes races with 351 horses. In
1990, he became the first trainer to reach $100 million in total
earnings, and in 1988 he set the one-year mark of $17.8 million. He
has led the purse-money list 14 of the last 16 years.
</P>
<P>
   Lukas has saddled 19 Eclipse winners, a record, including two
who were Horse of the Year (Lady's Secret and Criminal Type). He
has won 13 Breeders' Cup races, the most of any trainer, and 10
Triple Crown races (three Kentucky Derbys, four Preakness Stakes,
three Belmont Stakes). Lukas accomplished what arguably is the
greatest training feat ever by winning six consecutive Triple Crown
races from 1994-96. The only comparable acomplishment was by the
late Woody Stephens, who saddled six consecutive Belmont Stakes
winners from 1981-86.
</P>
<P>
   Lukas doesn't treat his horses like pets, and some people
understandably object to his assembly-line tactics. But this isn't
a popularity contest. It's about career accomplishment, and, on
that basis, Lukas stands out.
</P>
<P>
   Mandella is a terrific conditioner, one who will soon be voted
into the Hall, and Drysdale is a major talent, as well. Their only
problem is being nominated in the wrong year.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
CONTEMPORARY MALE HORSE &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The nominees: A.P. Indy, Exceller, Precisionist.
</P>
<P>
   The vote: (1) A.P. Indy. (2) Exceller. (3) Precisionist.
</P>
<P>
   A.P. Indy, a son of Seattle Slew, ran only 11 times. But if you
saw him race, you know he was a great horse. He cost $2.9 million
as a yearling in 1990 and actually earned that back in his brief
career. Racing only at ages 2 and 3, he won the Hollywood Futurity,
Santa Anita Derby, Belmont Stakes, and Breeders' Cup Classic. The
only thing that kept A.P. Indy off the radar screen of the casual
fan is that he injured his hoof the day before the 1992 Kentucky
Derby and had to be scratched the morning of the race. That was the
year that Arazi flopped and long shot Li'l E. Tee captured the Run
for the Roses. A.P. Indy would have been a cinch had he started.
The injury also kept him out of the Preakness.
</P>
<P>
   A.P. Indy had soundness problems that limited his career, but he
was a monster on the racetrack, and that's what counts.
</P>
<P>
   Exceller won 15 of 33 starts. In 1978, he took the Jockey Club
Gold Cup at Belmont, beating Seattle Slew and Affirmed. He is the
only horse to have defeated two Triple Crown winners in the same
race. This voter saw Exceller on television, and he was tough to
pass on. But A.P. Indy was brilliant. Precisionist also was a top
horse, winning the Woodward, Swaps, and 1985 Breeders' Cup Sprint
in a carreer that saw him take 20 of 46 starts. However, he was not
quite in the class of A.P. Indy and Exceller.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
CONTEMPORARY FEMALE HORSE &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The nominees: Dance Smartly, Miesque, Winning Colors.
</P>
<P>
   The vote: (1) Miesque. (2) Winning Colors. (3) Dance Smartly.
</P>
<P>
   Miesque, who was based in France, ran twice in the United
States, winning the Breeders' Cup Mile in 1987 and '88, and won two
Eclipse Awards. That's how impressive she was. At age 3, she scored
at Hollywood Park on a firm course. The following year, she won at
Churchill Downs in deep going. Miesque won 12 of 16 career starts,
always racing against males, and was never worse than third. She
captured nine Group I races in Europe. Miesque was as fast as a
rocket. She turned her foot quicker than any other horse this turf
writer has ever seen and, as with A.P. Indy, is worthy of the Hall
despite being lightly raced, in the European tradition.
</P>
<P>
   In 1988, Winning Colors became only the third filly (after
Regret and Genuine Risk) to triumph in the Kentucky Derby. She also
won the Santa Anita Derby against males, and, that fall just missed
winning the Breeders' Cup Distaff at Churchill against undefeated
Personal Ensign, in what many consider the greatest of all
Breeders' Cup races. She was past her peak at age 4, and finished
with a career mark of eight wins in 19 starts. It was tough to vote
against a Derby winner, but Miesque was simply more dominating.
</P>
<P>
   Dance Smartly, a Canadian-bred, was sensational as a 3-year-old
in 1991, going 8 for 8, with her wins including the Canadian Triple
Crown and the Molson Million, against males, and the Breeders' Cup
Distaff. She took 12 of 17 starts in her career, and is worthy of
the Hall, but not over this competition.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
HORSE OF YESTERYEAR &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The nominees: Bald Eagle, Bowl of Flowers, Gun Bow.
</P>
<P>
   The vote: (1) Gun Bow. (2) Bald Eagle. (3) Bowl of Flowers.
</P>
<P>
   Since horses must be retired for 25 years to qualify, this
category requires a careful reading of the resumes. If you're known
by your enemies, then this vote has to go to Gun Bow, since his No.
1 foe was the mighty Kelso, the five-time Horse of the Year
recently voted the fourth-best thoroughbred of the century. Gun Bow
beat Kelso by 12 lengths, while setting a then-track record of 1:59
3/5 for 10 furlongs, in the Brooklyn at Belmont in 1964. Kelso beat
him in the Aqueduct Stakes, but Gun Bow came back to nip Kelso in
the Woodward. Kelso evened the series by beating Gun Bow on the
turf in the Washington, D.C., International. Gun Bow won 17 of 42
starts, and his split decison with Kelso is eye-catching.
</P>
<P>
   Bald Eagle, champion handicap horse of 1960, was outstanding on
both grass and dirt and defeated Sword Dancer in the Metropolitan
Handicap. His final record showed 12 tallies from 29 races. He was
great, but Gun Bow appears to have been a little bit greater. Bowl
Of Flowers, champion filly at age 2 and 3 in 1960 and '61, won 10
of 16 starts and was a tremendous female. But she's no match for
Gun Bow and Bald Eagle.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-16-99 1350EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
