u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-TEMPLE-BARNES-BOS     03-16 0902
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-TEMPLE-BARNES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BARNES THREW THE BOOK AT THE BEARCATS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL VEGA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- Lamont Barnes stood in a corner of Temple's locker
room in the FleetCenter, a white towel wrapped around his waist and
another draped over his shoulder and across his torso like a toga.
He was all smiles. Some were coaxed by reporters, others came
naturally when the 6-foot-10-inch junior forward was asked to
recount the pivotal moments of a 64-54 victory over No. 3 seed
Cincinnati Sunday in the second round of the NCAA East Regional.
</P>
<P>
   Barnes's smiles reflected his impact in guiding the sixth-seeded
Owls to their first Sweet 16 appearance in six years. He led Temple
to a regional semifinal matchup against No. 10 seed Purdue in East
Rutherford, N.J., by scoring a team-high 15 points against the
rough-and-tumble Bearcats.
</P>
<P>
   Still, given the many tragedies that have pockmarked his life,
it seems a minor miracle that Barnes can find anything to smile
about. He was 8 years old when his mother was beaten to death
during a robbery of their home in Lexington, Ky.; he was a high
school senior in Hopkinsville, Ky., when his father was shot to
death; and he was just beginning his freshman year at Temple when
his grandmother called with the news of the death of a close
cousin.
</P>
<P>
   And yet, with 32 seconds remaining in the Owls' triumph over
Cincinnati, a toothy grin creased Barnes's face as Temple fans
filled the FleetCenter with chants of ``Sweet 16! Sweet 16! Sweet
16!''
</P>
<P>
   How sweet it was, indeed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just happy for our team,'' Barnes said. ``I just looked
up and heard the crowd cheering and it was nice, because I don't
normally hear them cheering during the game.''
</P>
<P>
   In this game, however, Barnes had other priorities. If Temple
was going to succeed against Cincinnati's muscular and heavily
tattooed frontcourt, Barnes knew he would have to set the tone with
physical play in the low post. That was evident to him during
pregame warmups when players from both sides exchanged hard stares.
From that moment, Barnes knew it was imperative that he, 6-9,
240-pound freshman center Kevin Lyde, and 6-10, 290-pound freshman
reserve Ron Rollerson do one thing. ``Go at 'em,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was very important that we got established, because
defensively they're a very strong team,'' Rollerson said. ``They've
got one guy pushing on you low and another guy coming at you
weak-side to block the shot. But, yeah, they're one of the stronger
teams in the country and, by looking at us, we're not. For us to be
pushing with them, tug for tug, played a huge role in that game.
And Lamont did a great job in there for us. He's been one of our
go-to guys all year.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Lyde, ``Lamont played good, he played good. He wanted to
show that we wasn't a pushover, because they were talking some talk
to us, saying that we were scared. But he wanted to show them that
he wasn't scared.''
</P>
<P>
   That much was evident when Barnes backed in Kenyon Martin,
Cincinnati's menacing 6-8, 230-pound junior center, and hit a
turnaround jumper that gave Temple a 6-0 lead. Then, after Temple's
tough matchup zone forced Cincinnati to commit a 35-second shot
clock violation, Barnes stuffed home an offensive rebound. In all,
Temple outrebounded the Bearcats, 32-31, getting 19 defensive
boards.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew they were going to be physical and we know we didn't
want them to come out and get the upper hand on us, so we wanted to
get physical right back with them,'' Barnes said. ``If the ref was
going to allow that to go on, then we figured we should play
physical with them.''
</P>
<P>
   If there was one sequence that illustrated Temple's tenacity on
the boards, it was late in the first half when Barnes helped keep
the ball alive for a third-chance 3-pointer by Quincy Wadley that
lifted the Owls to a whopping 16-point lead, 29-13.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, I believe it kind of hurt them the way we were
rebounding the ball,'' Barnes said. ``They probably weren't
expecting it, but it helped that our rebounding was good for us.''
</P>
<P>
   It also helped that Barnes, Temple's second-leading scorer (12.8
points per game) and leading rebounder (7.0 per game), found the
mark with his shot. He hit 5 of 8 field goal attempts, including a
towering baseline skyhook over Martin's hand that expanded Temple's
lead to 31-18 in the second half.
</P>
<P>
   Did the Bearcats underestimate Barnes?
</P>
<P>
   ``Naw, I knew what he could do,'' Martin sniffed. ``He wasn't a
surprise to us. He made a couple of shots. Everyone's going to make
a couple of shots. They were tough shots where I had my hand up,
but they went in.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Cincinnati assistant Rod Baker, ``Barnes got more touches
than he had been getting. He really got a lot more touches and they
really went to him and they felt like he was a guy who was going to
get something done for them.''
</P>
<P>
   Sunday in the FleetCenter, Barnes did just that. He got it done
for his team _ with a smile on his face _ and because he did, the
Owls are in the Sweet 16.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is great for us,'' Barnes said, smiling again. ``There
was a point in time where we hit a little slide and we lost a
couple of games, but to be able to be where we are right now is a
great feeling. It's great for us as a team, it's great for our
program, and it's great for our school. I just hope everybody
enjoys it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-16-99 1352EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
