<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-REMATCH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A SNAG IN A REMATCH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It was 6 a.m., the sky over Manhattan just starting
to lighten on the morning after The Indecision, and Don King sat in
front of a plate of spaghetti arrabiati at Bravo Johnnie's trying
to figure out how to make the stink of what had just happened go
away.
</P>
<P>
   With him sat HBO Sports president Seth Abraham. Both men had
only one thing on their mind: ironing out a rematch between Evander
Holyfield and Lennox Lewis as fast as possible.
</P>
<P>
   Within hours after that meeting the three sanctioning bodies _
the World Boxing Council, World Boxing Association, and
International Boxing Federation _ announced that they would not
block such a fight by insisting that their No. 1 contenders get
title shots first, a decision that surprised Abraham and showed
that once in a while common sense rules over uncommon greed, even
in prizefighting. Yet hurdling that stumbling block did not assure
a late summer or early September rematch.
</P>
<P>
   A little-known clause in Lewis's contract may prove to be the
real problem.
</P>
<P>
   When Lewis first agreed to take $9.5 million to Holyfield's $20
million for the unification bout that ended in a draw Saturday
night, he granted a rematch clause if Holyfield lost. In return,
Lewis was given an unusual ``draw clause'' that said he would be
paid $15 million for a rematch if the first fight was a draw.
</P>
<P>
   Now that clause hangs over the proposed promotion like a
guillotine blade despite last weekend's financial success. Although
the draw was considered unsatisfactory by most people and unsavory
by some, pay-per-view sales of Holyfield-Lewis have been estimated
between 1.1 million and 1.4 million, which would put it in the top
five all-time pay-per-view fights and net King $10 million.
</P>
<P>
   But the economics of a rematch could prove overwhelming if Lewis
sticks to his $15 million clause because it is unlikely that
Holyfield, who retained the IBF and WBA titles with the draw, will
agree to have his own purse reduced. With fears that a rematch may
not sell as well, King and HBO will have to scramble to put
together a financial package that works or the cable network's
parent company, Time-Warner, would have to accept the likelihood of
losing money to make the match happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``The second fight isn't bigger than the first,'' a source close
to the negotiations said. ``It's smaller. But I don't think Evander
will take one cent less, and Lewis's purse is to go up
significantly. If Holyfield refuses to come down to $15 million or
so, why should HBO do it and lose money?''
</P>
<P>
   Those are decisions neither Holyfield, Lewis, nor HBO is ready
to make, but the much-maligned sanctioning bodies wasted no time
announcing they would do nothing to block the fight.
</P>
<P>
   ``The three of us were milling around after the fight talking
about the decision,'' IBF president Bob Lee said. ``After (WBA
president Gilberto) Mendoza, (WBC president Jose) Sulaiman and I
talked for a few minutes, it was clear what we all wanted was a
unified title-holder. That's what's best for the sport. So we all
said we'd relax the rules for mandatory defenses and I released it
to the papers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The sanctioning bodies have opened the door. We want it done.
But we can't promote it. That's up to King and Duva. But if money
is an issue, that's a major stumbling block.''
</P>
<P>
   King, Holyfield, Lewis, and Abraham were all at HBO Monday to
tape the replay show that will run Friday night. Holyfield and
Lewis will break down from their perspectives what went on, and
Lewis certainly will reiterate his claim that he was robbed.
</P>
<P>
   Just as Holyfield's physical wounds remain raw, so do Lewis's
emotional ones. Abraham knows he will have to deal with that, but
he also knows deals like this must be done quickly, before they are
slowed by the weight of the warring parties' demands and egos.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don wants the rematch because he knew what would happen,''
Abraham said. ``He knew everyone would blame him. Tempers are very
hot right now. Lennox's people are outraged, so we have to let
things cool down.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope after that we'll do the practical thing. What happened
happened. It can't be changed. If you wallow in self-pity, no deals
get made. I'm saddened for the sport for what happened but we have
to move quickly on a rematch. We'd like one by July or August.''
</P>
<P>
   If Holyfield, Lewis, and perhaps Time-Warner are willing to pay
the price, they just may get it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
