<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-16 13:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2299 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOX-JUDGE-BOS &LR;      03-16 0539
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-JUDGE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUDGE SPEAKS UP, SAYS VIEW WAS BLOCKED IN KEY ROUND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Jean Williams has judged at least a dozen title
fights and never once had a scorecard questioned. That's how she
got the assignment that has led people to bellow that she is blind,
incompetent, a co-conspirator in Lennox Lewis's demise, in the
pocket of Don King, or all of the above.
</P>
<P>
   Williams is the Atlantic City municipal accountant who Saturday
night tallied up her scorecard and concluded that Evander Holyfield
had defeated Lewis in the heavyweight unification fight at Madison
Square Garden. Based on that, you might not want her doing your
income tax, but boxing insiders said Monday that there was no
reason to suspect her honesty or competence.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't have a problem with her when we heard her name,''
said Carl Moretti, matchmaker for Main Events, Dino Duva's
promotional company that represents Lewis. ``We had seen her a lot
in Atlantic City because she's from New Jersey and works a lot of
fights here. She's done 10 or 12 world title fights. She did (Ivan)
Robinson-(Arturo) Gatti. We had no reason to raise a red flag.''
</P>
<P>
   Not until her card said 115-113 for Holyfield. Then her fitness
to work such a fight came under assault, especially after she
somehow concluded that Holyfield had won the fifth round even
though Lewis battered him for much of the three minutes and nearly
knocked him down.
</P>
<P>
   Williams stood by her card, saying after the fight, ``That's
what I saw round by round.'' Monday she still stood by her scoring
and claimed she couldn't see Lewis's fifth-round assault on
Holyfield because his back was to her most of the time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't see the blows that I later saw on TV,'' Williams
said. ``If I couldn't see it, I can't score it. That's what we're
told (by the International Boxing Federation and the New Jersey
Athletic Commission). I'm taking a lot of heat but I can't score
what I can't see. I scored what I saw.''
</P>
<P>
   What she saw is something very few others saw, because she saw
Holyfield a winner. But IBF president Bob Lee continued to back
her.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's a good official,'' Lee said. ``I had no reason not to
support her. She saw what she saw. She's earned her wings. People
are dumping on her, but look at the Englishman's card.''
</P>
<P>
   British judge Larry O'Connell scored the fight a draw, and both
Moretti and HBO Sports president Seth Abraham said they had Lewis
winning only 7-5 in rounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's odd for me to defend (promoter) Don King, but Eugenia
Williams is not his baggage,'' Abraham said. ``She's the IBF's
baggage. Frankly, I had the fight 7-5 myself.
</P>
<P>
   ``Judging a fight is subjective. In a big fight, the tenser
things get, the more extra subjective it can become. We can all
make a list of decisions that were abysmal. Although I believe
Lennox won, I wouldn't put this decision in that category.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, New York Attorney General Eliot Spitzer, the New York
Athletic Commission, and the state's Senate Committee on
Investigations each announced that they had begun investigations
into Saturday's fight, according to the Associated Press.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
