<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-16 13:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2301 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JUVENILE-JUSTICE-BOS &LR;      03-16 1132
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JUVENILE-JUSTICE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOVE TO TRY JUVENILES AS ADULTS UNDER SCRUTINY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (w and a coding)  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LOUISE D. PALMER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The criminal case against 15-year-old Anthony
Laster was clear-cut in the eyes of Florida prosecutors: He
demanded lunch money from a schoolmate in a threatening manner and
took $2 out of the schoolmate's pocket.
</P>
<P>
   The youth, who is mentally retarded, was charged as an adult
with strong-arm robbery, battery and extortion. He was locked up
for nearly two months _ one month spent in an adult jail. Last
week, prosecutors in Palm Beach County dropped the charges after
the schoolmate testified that he was not threatened.
</P>
<P>
   ``This isn't an isolated case,'' said Marsha Levick of the
Juvenile Law Center, a children's legal rights organization in
Philadelphia. ``That prosecutors could do this without a judge
reviewing it . . . is enough for us to be concerned about the kinds
of abuses prosecutors can commit when they have discretion.''
</P>
<P>
   Juvenile justice advocates are pointing to this Florida case as
a cautionary tale of what can happen when prosecutors have the
power to charge and try minors as adults for serious offenses
without having a judge review the case. Florida is the only state
that gives such broad powers to prosecutors, but the idea is
gaining ground in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate is considering a bill that would overhaul the
juvenile justice system, including a measure that would allow
prosecutors to try minors 14 and older as adults without the right
to appeal the decision to a judge. The House Judiciary Committee is
conducting hearings on the matter.
</P>
<P>
   The White House approves of granting federal prosecutors similar
discretion, as long as juveniles have some form of appeal.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation has been attacked on different fronts in and out
of Congress. Legal groups, including the National Association of
District Attorneys, have protested the bill's federal reach into
state jurisdiction.
</P>
<P>
   And youth advocates say that even though the federal courts
handle only a small number of juvenile cases, they fear the
legislation could become a standard used by states.
</P>
<P>
   These advocates also say putting more youths into the adult
system means they could be exposed to violent adult behavior while
losing out on counseling and other rehabilitation services provided
through the juvenile court system.
</P>
<P>
   Laster was not physically harmed during his time in the county
jail. But community groups criticized Barry E. Krischer, the Palm
Beach County state attorney, for misusing the Florida law.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Edmondson, a spokesman for Krischer, said Florida law
requires that juveniles be sent directly into adult court for
certain felonies.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't pick and choose charges,'' said Edmondson. ``A crime
had been committed, and you don't select who you are going to apply
the law to.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Krischer's court filing, the charges were dropped
after Laster's schoolmate said in a deposition that he was not
threatened, making ``further prosecution of the robbery charge no
longer viable.''
</P>
<P>
   Edmondson added that the state attorney is ``very aggressive
with juveniles,'' and he believes the only way to lower crime is to
send juveniles a ``wake-up call'' by sending them to adult court.
``He wants to scare them straight,'' Edmondson said.
</P>
<P>
   But children's advocates say the state had no business charging
Laster, who has an IQ of 58, with a felony and as an adult and
sending him to jail for taking $2 in lunch money.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is like hitting an ant with a hatchet,'' said Levick of the
Juvenile Law Center. ``It is even more troublesome in 1999, a time
when juvenile crime has been declining for the past six years, to
suggest that we need to try more kids in adult courts.''
</P>
<P>
   Some argue that expanding the power of federal prosecutors to
easily charge juveniles as adults could undermine public safety, as
well as the rehabilitative goals of the juvenile justice system.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of the evidence shows you are going in the wrong direction
and will in fact increase, not decrease, crime,'' said
Representative Robert C. Scott, a Virginia Democrat on the House
Judiciary Committee. ``When people say kids should get adult time
for an adult crime, they don't realize they have been misled.''
</P>
<P>
   Scott said minors tried in adult court often do not receive
sentences as long as they might receive in juvenile court,
particularly for nonviolent offenses. As an example, Scott said a
first-time adult offender in Virginia convicted of burglary
typically receives a suspended sentence.
</P>
<P>
   ``This guarantees that juveniles won't be punished, or they will
be punished for a short amount of time in an adult jail, where they
can count among their associates and role models armed robbers,
drug dealers, rapists and murderers,'' Scott said.
</P>
<P>
   A recent report by the Justice Policy Institute, a Washington
legal research and education organization, said: ``Studies about
juveniles prosecuted as adults consistently report that those
juveniles have higher reoffense rates, more serious reoffenses, and
reoffend sooner upon release from confinement'' than those
prosecuted in juvenile court.
</P>
<P>
   Vincent Schiraldi, director of the institute, said other studies
show juveniles in adult facilities also are more likely to be
physically and sexually abused.
</P>
<P>
   But Senator Orrin G. Hatch, Republican of Utah and chairman of
the Senate Judiciary Committee, said he believes ``our juvenile
crime problem has taken a new and sinister direction.''
</P>
<P>
   Hatch, speaking on the Senate floor last month while introducing
the juvenile crime bill, noted that minors commit 21 percent of all
violent crimes and said the number of murder cases involving
15-year-olds increased 207 percent between 1985 and 1993.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is our intent to ensure that when there is a federal crime
warranting the federal prosecution of a juvenile, the federal
government assumes its responsibility to deal with it, rather than
saddling the states with that burden,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Justice Department spokesman Brian Steel said, ``The White House
favors shifting the responsibility from the judges to the
prosecutors to decide whether or not a juvenile should be tried in
adult court.''
</P>
<P>
   While the Association of District Attorneys does not support the
bill because it involves the federal government in state affairs,
Gary Walker, cochairman of the association's juvenile justice
committee, said, ``It is necessary to be able to directly file
juvenile cases to adult court to provide for the safety of the
public. It gives you the ability to incarcerate and remove from
society those people who are exceptionally dangerous for a longer
period of time.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-16-99 1357EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
