<HEADLINE>
IMPORTANCE OF FACING CLIPPERS NOT LOST ON CELTICS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL HOLLEY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- They know it, they think it, and maybe they even
whisper it among themselves. But they never would speak publicly
about what they know. Especially not now. Why? They just can't.
</P>
<P>
   That is the advantage you have over the Celtics. You can see a
bad basketball team and say, ``That team is terrible.'' The
Celtics? Their candor is blunted by extreme diplomacy. So they look
at a team with a 1-19 record and say something like, ``Those guys
have a lot of talent. They have Maurice Taylor, Rodney Rogers and
Lorenzen Wright. If you're not careful, that team can beat you . .
. ''
</P>
<P>
   But Rick Pitino and his Celtics know the truth, even if we don't
have the opportunity to print or broadcast their uncensored words.
And the truth is that they cannot lose to the Los Angeles Clippers
wednesday night at the FleetCenter. Never mind that the Clippers
beat the Kings and the Celtics didn't. Never mind that the Clippers
have won more recently than the Celtics, who have a five-game
losing streak.
</P>
<P>
   They cannot lose to Chris Ford's team. Not at home. If a home
loss to the Lakers extends your losing streak to six, that's
acceptable. But the Clippers are 0-9 on the road. This is the team
that lost its first 17 games, a mark that ties the worst start in
league history. This is also the team that still would not have a
winning record if it won its next 17. Lose to a team like that at
home and you'll never forget it. Just in case you do, your fans
will remind you forever.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's our record at home?'' Kenny Anderson asked after the
Celtics lost to the Pacers Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   He was told 4-2.
</P>
<P>
   ``And what's our record on the road?''
</P>
<P>
   He was told 3-10.
</P>
<P>
   The Celtics point guard thought about those numbers for a while
and came to a conclusion: ``We've got to take care of the crib,
man. We've got to take care of our home court. We can't lose too
many more games at home.''
</P>
<P>
   Anderson knew what team was next on the schedule when he made
those remarks. The Celtics haven't heard boos since Opening Night,
when they were thumped by the Raptors. They know they will hear
boos if they lose.
</P>
<P>
   And then there is Pitino. If his team were to lose, the loss
probably would end his honeymoon with Boston fans. When most fans
vent online and on radio stations, their complaints are directed at
the players. But a six-game losing streak and a defeat to the LA
junior varsity _ as the late agent Ron Grinker once called them _
would shift the focus from the players to the man who coaches them.
</P>
<P>
   The Celtics had the day off Monday. You can be sure they ran
errands in Greater Boston. You also can be sure a few of them
paused for a moment and said, ``We cannot lose to the Clippers
(Wednesday).''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're a little bit of a strange team sometimes,'' Dana Barros
said. ``If we play a team that is perceived to be good _ a team
that is on TV a lot or something _ we'll play very well. If it's a
team that is not supposed to be real great, we'll struggle.''
</P>
<P>
   So, Barros was asked, how do you even out your performances?
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the million-dollar question,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Pitino has said that his team would have to make an
``incredible'' run simply to make the playoffs. He also has
maintained that the Celtics will be a definite playoff team in his
third season, not his second.
</P>
<P>
   But the players know that the coach takes losing hard. After the
Celtics lost to the Pistons Friday night, people outside the team's
locker room could hear the coach's raised voice. He was not happy.
A reporter approached him afterward and extended a microphone.
``Don't put that in my face,'' he snapped. And that was after a
defeat to the seminal Grant Hill and his Pistons. A loss to the
Clippers probably would cause the coach to snap the mike itself if
someone pushed it toward his noggin.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't matter who we play, we just need a win,'' Anderson
said. And they need it Wednesday.
</P>
</TEXT>
