   SCI-SLEEP-ELDERLY (Undated) _ About 25 percent to 35 percent of
older Americans have troubles sleeping, but their fitful nights are
often viewed as a normal part of aging and go untreated by their
doctors or caretakers. Now, researchers report that insomnia in
older adults can be effectively treated with cognitive-behavior
therapy, with sleeping medication, or with a combination of the
two. The therapy proved longer lasting than drug treatment, the
researchers report Wednesday in the Journal of the American Medical
Association. By Erica Goode. (1400 words)
