<HEADER>
A2306 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VENNOCHI-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      03-16 0748
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VENNOCHI-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MY SON, THE RACER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOAN VENNOCHI  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``This time, ski as fast as I do. I want you to see what it
feels like.''
</P>
<P>
   With that challenge, he was off. The snow sparkled off the
mountainside, the brightness swallowing up his sandy-colored head.
Thank goodness for his Chicago Bulls jacket. The silly oversized
black and red coat stood out against the whiteness, keeping him in
focus a hundred yards down the trail.
</P>
<P>
   This was no expert skier. This was just a typically reckless,
just-turned-10-year-old boy, thrilling to everything his mother
fears: body-hurtling speed, sharp turns, and hard falls, especially
in public places.
</P>
<P>
   We were celebrating his breakthrough into double digits with a
midweek ski adventure, an escape from work and school encouraged by
the month's surge of almost-spring snowstorms.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mom's a nice, easy skier, right?'' the ski rental guy asked
with polite contempt and depressing accuracy. Hearing no protest,
he handed over a pair of short, balloon-tipped skis, all the rage
for aging baby boomers who never mastered the art of swift edging
on steep slopes.
</P>
<P>
   But for some reason, Mom didn't feel like skiing as nice and
easy as usual. How could she, when her companion was taking so much
delight in doing the opposite?
</P>
<P>
   Her carefully carved turns guaranteed she would never go fast
enough to lose control.
</P>
<P>
   But they also meant she would never feel the furious rush of
frigid air that he did when he bolted forward, caring nothing about
form and everything about fun.
</P>
<P>
   At first, he jumped over ridges and she skied around them. But
then, she planted her poles, dug in, and lifted up. She was just
the merest fraction off the ground, but, waiting below, he saw the
gap between earth and skis and grinned a thumb's up.
</P>
<P>
   When he tucked along narrow, relatively flat passages, so did
she _ no more cautious snowplow, designed to hedge off disasters
like awkward, face-losing skids off icy patches. The knees creaked
a little on the way down, but the crouch felt good. Getting up felt
even better.
</P>
<P>
   When he bombed down the final stretch to the bottom, landing in
a ridiculous heap in front of the base lodge, she fought back the
impulse to tell him to get back up and act his age. After all, he
was doing just that. Instead, she headed to the lift line and
waited for him to gather himself and his goggles together to take
another run.
</P>
<P>
   No one, not even a mother, should over-romanticize a quick trip
up Interstate 93. But there was something very special about this
moment, stolen from our regular routine.
</P>
<P>
   Parenting so often means managing a schedule of chores and
assignments. It's time to read. Time to practice piano. Time to
play soccer. Have you finished your homework? Brushed your teeth?
Grabbed your lunch money?
</P>
<P>
   And then there's the constant limit-setting. No more Nintendo.
No more fighting with your sister. No more flip answers,
eye-rolling looks of disgust, or embarrassing noises designed to
imitate bodily functions. No more chips or Coke.
</P>
<P>
   In everyday life, getting too loud or wild is never welcome. It
starts a chain reaction that affects siblings, spouses, and pets,
never in a positive way. It intrudes on obligations. It ends with
arguments, time-outs and the worst threat of all: no sleep-overs.
</P>
<P>
   But on the mountain, getting slightly but not unsafely out of
control is acceptable. Let's get chili nachos for brunch and forget
about the calories. Let's hop into the outdoor hot tub even though
the air is so cold, your hair nearly freezes on the way in and out.
</P>
<P>
   There is also time for conversation beyond the ``did you?'' and
the ``don'ts!''
</P>
<P>
   Yes, the ski lift attendant looks a little like the actor in
``Free Willy.'' No, it's not always disgusting to kiss someone in a
hot tub, although doing it in front of strangers as avidly as the
teenagers across from us are doing it is not highly recommended by
mothers. Of course, your test score on the upcoming MCAS will not
define you for the rest of your life; but doing your absolute best
on this newest form of fourth-grade torture is the preferred
option.
</P>
<P>
   And finally, it is OK to ski and live harder and faster than
your mother.
</P>
<P>
   But please, Nicholas. Don't go too fast, too soon. I am far from
ready to let you out of my sight. And already, I am having trouble
keeping up.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Joan Vennochi is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
