<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-NOTES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SNUGGLING AT SEA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD P. CARPENTER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here's some advice from Dr. Ruth Westheimer, writing in Porthole
magazine: ``If you take a cruise and book a cabin with a veranda,
it's OK to make love on the veranda _ providing no one can see you,
you have the cabin door to the hallway locked from the inside and _
above all _ don't get sunburned!''
</P>
<P>
   Good advice no doubt, yet getting intimate on the veranda rates
only number eight in a Porthole Web site survey of the best places
on a ship to . . . well, you know. Here, in order, are the top 10:
in the cabin, by the pool, in a lifeboat, at the disco, in the
casino, in a hot tub, by the smokestack, on that veranda, in the
spa/gym, and in the galley.
</P>
<P>
   But if you're merely talking romance, here, in order, is
Porthole's list of the top 10 romantic activities on board:
strolling in the moonlight, kissing, dancing, sharing a romantic
dinner, stargazing, watching the sunset, drinking champagne, giving
each other a massage, having breakfast in bed, and indulging in
aphrodisiacs.
</P>
<P>
   And if you're looking for love, look in all the right places.
The magazine says that if you want to meet people in their 40s and
up, consider a more upscale line like Holland America or Crystal
Cruises. Meanwhile, moderately-priced lines with shorter
itineraries, such as Carnival or Norwegian, are more likely to
attract people in their 20s and 30s.
</P>
<P>
   (For more information about Porthole, a glossy magazine devoted
to cruises, call 800-776-PORT or visit www.porthole.com.) &QL; 
 &QL; 
And speaking of romance: Couples aboard Celebrity ships report
enjoying AquaSpa treatments called Rasul (on the Century, Galaxy,
and Mercury) and Seraglio Bath (on the Horizon). The treatments
start with a seaweed-soap shower, followed by the application of
medicinal muds to each other's bodies, followed by an herbal
steambath, followed by . . . who knows? &QL; 
 &QL; 
Travel Trivia: Which two lakes does the Niagara River connect?
(Answer at end of column.) &QL; 
 &QL; 
In a name: ``Nausea'' is derived from the Greek word for ``ship.''
But that was long ago. Today's sailings can be smooth indeed. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Quotable: ``You never enjoy the world aright till the sea itself
floweth in your veins.'' _ Thomas Traherne. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Cruise-ship joke: ``As you leave the ship for the final time,
you'll see two boxes. One is marked ``Towels'' and the other is
marked ``Ashtrays.'' _ Keith Cox, cruise director of the Grand
Princess. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Virtual cruisegoing: Phil Beach, editor of the popular Shipboard
Cruiser newsletter, has set up a Web site that can link you to
cruise lines, itineraries, ports, and even airports. Visit
www.shipboardcruiser.com. Meanwhile, www.cruise-news.com is an
Internet newsletter about ships 'n' such. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Burning to travel: The Queen Elizabeth II moves just 6 inches for
each gallon of diesel it burns. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Advice to go: If you love cruisegoing, you might consider a
repositioning cruise, in which the ship moves from one geographical
area to another for the season. ``The itineraries usually call for
more days at sea than a typical cruise, so passengers have more
leisure time,'' says James G. Godsman, president of Cruise Lines
International Association. ``The cruise lines also use this
occasion to schedule extensive onboard programs, special
entertainment, and theme cruises.'' This spring, at least 12 major
lines will be sailing across the Atlantic to reposition in Europe.
Others will have ships transiting the Panama Canal before heading
for other waters. And a couple plan not-to-be repeated routes. For
more information, see a CLIA-affiliated travel agent or visit
www.cruising.org. For a copy of CLIA's 1999 Cruise Vacation
Planner, a 68-page guide, visit the Web site or call 888-Y-CRUISE
(888-927-8473). &QL; 
 &QL; 
Advice to (not) go: If a woman is seven or more months pregnant,
many cruise lines will recommend that she not sail, lest she give
birth at sea. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Opera afloat: The Sydney Opera House is one of the world's most
distinctive buildings, so it's fitting that a distinctive
Australian dinner ship features opera on selected evenings. The new
MV Sydney 2000, which proclaims itself the world's biggest and most
beautiful floating restaurant, conducts sails with four-course
dinners accompanied by a program of the world's most popular arias
performed live by principal Australian opera singers. And the ship,
which departs from historic Circular Quay, also provides
magnificent views of the opera house from the sea. The cost is
about $60 US. For more information on this or other sailings, call
888-292-2775 or visit www.captcookcrus.com.au. For information
about Australia cruises, flights, lodging, and tour packages, call
800-633-3404. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Taking no chances: The Grand Princess cruise ship has 23,000 rolls
of toilet paper aboard. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Did you guess it? The Niagara River connects Lake Erie and Lake
Ontario. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Send comments and questions to Travel Tidbits, Boston Globe,
Boston, MA 02107. Send e-mail to carpen(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
