<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-GALAPAGOS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXPLORING THE WONDERS OF THE GALAPAGOS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PATTI DOTEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   GALAPAGOS ISLANDS, Ecuador _ It's a strange place _ this
archipelago 570 miles off the coast of Ecuador.
</P>
<P>
   Cormorants don't fly, they swim. Mockingbirds fly, but don't
mock. Penguins sit on black volcanic rock, not ice. Iguanas glide
with great ease in the sea. And sea lions sunbathe alongside
members of the island's only transient species _ homo sapiens.
</P>
<P>
   Fear doesn't exist here. The harmonious coexistence among the
animals, unknown in the rest of the world, began centuries ago when
the islands' inhabitants found themselves marooned here and without
enemies.
</P>
<P>
   Until, that is, the arrival of man.
</P>
<P>
   His introduction of goats, pigs, rats, and donkeys upset the
islands' delicate ecological balance. And although the islands were
declared a national park in 1959 and various programs have helped
contain the goat and donkey population, many naturalists believe
the only way to restore and preserve the ecology of the archipelago
is to ban tourism entirely.
</P>
<P>
   So this archipelago is a fitting place for the
turn-of-the-century traveler. Not only because it may be off-limits
in the near future but because it's a millennium-esque type of
place _ dark, stark, mysterious, and otherworldly. Early navigators
called the islands ``Las Encantadas'' or the ``bewitched ones''
because they appeared and then quickly vanished within swirling
mists and cloud formations. Yet this bleak landscape can also be
set afire with dazzling sunrises and sunsets.
</P>
<P>
   On a recent five-day/four night excursion (there are weeklong
cruises as well) aboard the luxurious ship Explorer II, the 90
passengers, predominantly American, all took advantage of the daily
hikes, snorkeling, and sunbathing plus the on-board buffets,
four-course dinners, and free drinks.
</P>
<P>
   Two islands are visited daily, with the ship traveling the
longest distances at night. The Galapagos is made up of 13 large
and six smaller islands and 42 islets stretching over 30,000 square
miles of ocean. Humans inhabit four of these islands. The rest
remain relatively unchanged since their accidental discovery by a
Spanish bishop in 1535 who noted in his journal: ``found nothing
but seals and tortoises, and such big tortoises that each could
carry a man on top of itself'' and birds ``so silly that they do
not know to flee.''
</P>
<P>
   Three hundred years later, Charles Darwin spent 35 days here and
used the islands' animals as the basis for his 1859 book on
evolution, ``The Origin of Species.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, the islands draw 45,000 visitors annually.
</P>
<P>
   All guides working aboard the Explorer II speak English and have
trained at the Charles Darwin Research Station on Santa Cruz, the
area's second-largest island. They lead groups of 12 to 15
passengers onto the islands where they act as island police. They
keep visitors from wandering freely, leaving or taking anything or
touching the animals. The latter is perhaps the most difficult for
visitors since baby sea lions waddle over and look up at island
guests with huge, imploring brown eyes.
</P>
<P>
   The daily routine is camplike: 6:45 a.m.: wake-up call; 7:15
a.m.: buffet breakfast; 8 a.m.: Groups gather in the lounge and
prepare to disembark in ``pangas,'' small motor boats, for the
morning's hike. At noon, a buffet lunch is served onboard around
the pool, and then another journey to another island begins at 3
p.m. Dinner is served at 7:30 followed by a briefing on the next
day's activities.
</P>
<P>
   One warning _ cruising the Galapagos is not like cruising the
Caribbean or Greek Isles. Although the Explorer is luxurious, with
gleaming wood paneling, wall-to-wall carpeting, and marble baths in
the staterooms, it is more a means of transportation than an entity
unto itself. Passengers must be agile enough to get in and out of
the pangas, climb to the summit of Pinnacle Rock on Bartolome
Island (a steep stairway of 370 steps), and walk across rugged lava
terrain. Also, elementary school children can become bored on the
hikes _ this is not an action trip or a Disney World but an
educational natural zoo.
</P>
<P>
   Composed entirely of basalt, the islands are the tips of
gigantic volcanoes poking up some 30,000 feet from the ocean floor.
The earliest islands are believed to have formed 4- to 5 million
years ago with Fernandina and Isabela relative youngsters at 1
million years old. Some of the islands are still active (Isabela
erupted last fall) and were never connected to the mainland.
Therefore, all living things had to cross hundreds of miles of
water.
</P>
<P>
   This explains the predominance of sea birds, mammals, and
reptiles, which, it is thought, floated to the islands on organic
debris. Seeds and insects arrived either stuck to the wings of
birds or in the contents of animal stomachs. To survive, the
animals had to adapt to their new environment.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, the iguanas grew long tails for swimming, fed on algae,
and developed glands to expel the salt from ingested sea water. The
flightless cormorants became good fishermen. And Darwin's finches
either grew thick beaks for splitting seeds or long thin bills for
catching insects, depending on the particular island on which they
took up residence. It is believed that the 13 species on the
islands came from one original species.
</P>
<P>
   Adding color to these parts are the pink flamingoes, frigate
birds with their boastful red chests, blue-footed boobies who strut
their stuff during elaborate mating rituals, and the highly
polished, red-orange Sally Lightfoot crabs.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the islands are virtual deserts, while others are more
lush with large mangrove forests.
</P>
<P>
   Bartolome Island is lunarlike, with brackish-colored lava dried
into huge mud cakes, deep craters, and the honeycombed Pinnacle
Rock _ perhaps the best viewing stage in the islands. But there's
also plant life here in the soil-less crevices _ hardy lava cactus
with long spiny fingers.
</P>
<P>
   On James Island, abandoned shacks and water tanks are testimony
to man's effort to start a salt business. It failed. Other signs of
man's presence exist in Tagus Cove where graffiti was carved on
rocks by pirates and buccaneers who roamed these parts in search of
fresh water and tortoise meat.
</P>
<P>
   Fernandina Island, a flat island with black lava covered with
emerald algae, has many lava pools where female sea lions watch
their young practice their swimming prowess while huge bulls fend
off intruders with loud barking. Cormorants dry their stubby wings
in the sun while hawks sit motionless on leafless branches.
Visitors must walk gingerly here to avoid stepping on the hundreds
of iguanas piled on top of one another as they take in the
afternoon sun _ warming their bodies for the cool nights.
</P>
<P>
   Rabida Island, with its dark red beaches (due to high iron oxide
content), is the best place to photograph, sunbathe, and swim with
sea lions.
</P>
<P>
   Although ``Galapagos'' is Spanish for giant land tortoise, these
creatures are in short supply today. Thousands were killed for
their meat by whalers during the 18th and 19th centuries. The only
tortoises seen on our trip were those being bred at the Charles
Darwin Research Center on Santa Cruz.
</P>
<P>
   One of the tortoises, the 185-pound George from the island of
Pinta, is the last of his species. He shares his large bachelor pad
with two females brought in for romance. So far, George prefers his
own company, living up to his nickname, Lonesome George.
</P>
<P>
   As for weather, the Galapagos are an all-year destination with
two seasons. The hot or wet season lasts from January to early May
with an average temperature of 82 degrees (we encountered only one
rainstorm). The cool or dry season is from May to December, when
the average temperature is 64. Although the islands straddle the
equator, the days are comfortable and the evenings are cool.
</P>
<P>
   And a trip to the islands should also include a visit to the
mainland. Ecuador is a stunningly rugged, beautiful, and varied
country with the Andes running up its spine. Quito, the highest
capital in the world, is well worth a visit. Then go south along
the Avenue of the Volcanos to Banos and stay at the Swiss-managed
hotel, Luna Runtun, high up in the mountains overlooking the city.
Or go north from Quito and stay at one of the comfortable haciendas
and shop at the famous Otavalo market. Further north is Cotacachi _
a small town lined with leather shops. The two yellow Pompeii shops
have the highest quality goods.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
