<HEADLINE>
A BIG VOTE OF CONFIDENCE IN THE CRUISE MARKET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY MORRIS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   America is getting into cruising in a big way.
</P>
<P>
   But Americans are already into cruising, you say. So what's the
deal?
</P>
<P>
   Simply put, American Classic Voyages, the company that runs
American-Hawaii Cruises and the Delta Queen Steamboat Co., has just
placed orders for two of the largest ships ever built in America.
Yes, America. There hasn't been a large cruise ship built in this
country in 40 years.
</P>
<P>
   This is pure confidence in a growing market for cruise
vacations. The high cost to build and operate an American-flagged
vessel is cited as the main reason no one has undertaken a project
this big. As it is, American Hawaii presently operates the largest
American-flagged cruise ship _ the Independence (20,221 tons,
682-feet-long, 1,021 passengers), built in Quincy in 1951 for
transatlantic voyages.
</P>
<P>
   Cruising, simply put, is getting bigger in vacation plans with
each year. Later this year Carnival Cruises will introduce the
Triumph, a slightly larger version of the Carnival Destiny, which
only two years ago ruled the seas as the largest cruise ship at
100,000 tons. Since then, Princess came along with the Grand
Princess at 109,000 tons, and this fall, Royal Caribbean will top
them all with the Voyager of the Seas at 138,000 tons.
</P>
<P>
   The reasons for this growth are simple. Cruises offer one of the
most relaxing ways to travel, provide good value for the travel
dollar, appeal to all ages, and can provide vacation experiences to
suit most travelers.
</P>
<P>
   While cruises are relaxing, these vacations are not just for the
sedate. Cruising is also for the active with many vessels offering
lavish spas and fitness centers; others are designed for adventure
cruising, and all can offer active land tours in port. Simply put,
cruise travelers can be as active as they want, relax when they
want.
</P>
<P>
   Last week American Classic Voyages Co. signed an agreement with
Litton Industries' Ingalls Shipbuilding for a Project America
contract that calls for the building of the largest US cruises
ships ever built. . Ingalls initially will build two 1,900
passenger US flag cruise ships at its Pascagoula, Miss., shipyard
for service in the Hawaiian Islands. There is an option for a third
vessel. The base price for the first two vessels is $880 million
with the first vessel set to enter service in early 2003.
</P>
<P>
   Ingalls built the last American-built large cruise ships, the
Brasil and the Argentina, for Moore McCormack Lines in 1958.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our goal at American Classic is to provide passengers a great
Hawaiian vacation experience aboard modern US-owned, US-built, and
US-crewed cruise ships,'' said Phil Calian, president of American
Classic.
</P>
<P>
   Calian said the first two ships will be about 72,000 gross tons
and 840 feet long (by comparison, the United States launched in
1952 was 50,924 tons), with a design that blends the best of Hawaii
with the modern luxuries of cruising. Of the ship's 950 cabins, 77
percent will be ``outside'' (64 percent of which will have private
balconies). Calian added the ships will be designed to maximize the
sense of spaciousness on board and provide panoramic views of the
Hawaiian Islands and the Pacific.
</P>
<P>
   Giving a boost to the project was Congress' passage of the
US-Flag Cruise Ship Project Statute in 1997 with the goal of
revitalizing the US-flag oceangoing cruise ship fleet. Senator
Trent Lott of Mississippi said the project also should lower
overhead costs of building military ships. Interestingly, the
Independence was built with two engine rooms, so that if it were
called into military service it could operate should one engine go
down.
</P>
<P>
   American Classic isn't just building megaliners, it also
announced last year its Delta Queen Steamboat Co. will build a new
line of five small coastal cruise ships that will operate along
America's Eastern Seaboard, the Pacific Northwest, and Northern
California. The first of these $35 million, 300-foot, 226-passenger
vessels is scheduled to be launched in spring of 2001.
</P>
<P>
   The confidence in the growth potential of the cruise market is
``tremendous'' according to Micky Arison, chairman of Carnival
Corp. And, when Arison says tremendous, he backs it up with
investments of billions of dollars in new ship construction.
Carnival is now the largest cruise company in the world, owning not
only Carnival Cruises but also Holland America, Windstar, Cunard,
and a major share of Costa Cruises.
</P>
<P>
   This summer Carnival's second 100,000-ton plus ship, the
Carnival Triumph will debut with a series of four- and five-day
cruises from New York to Canadian ports of Saint John in New
Brunswick and Halifax in Nova Scotia. The cruises will operate July
19 through Oct. 11.
</P>
<P>
   In the fall, the world's largest cruise ship debuts. Royal
Caribbean International's Voyage of the Seas. The Voyager will sail
the Caribbean from Miami and will offer many new innovations in
cruising including Promenade View staterooms that overlook the
interior ``boulevard of shops and restaurants.'' Royal Caribbean's
trademark Viking Crown lounges that sit atop their vessels, will
have a new touch on the Voyager, a wedding chapel atop the lounge.
The ship also will have an indoor ice-skating rink, rock-climbing
walls and an in-line skating track _ who said cruising was for the
sedate?
</P>
<P>
   Princess Cruises just introduced its Sea Princess, one of its
Grand Class of 77,000-ton vessels.
</P>
<P>
   Holland America will introduce two 65,000-ton vessels this year
_ the Volendam in August and the Zaandam in November. The Volendam
will offer a series of cruises from New York through eastern
Canada.
</P>
<P>
   Even Disney is into the cruise business. Its Magic is currently
sailing on three- and four-day sails to the Bahamas and Disney's
fantastic private isle. These cruise vacations also include a
three- or four-day stay at Disney World. The line's second ship,
the Wonder is scheduled to enter service this year.
</P>
<P>
   Norwegian Cruise Line will have the maiden voyage of its
76,000-ton Norwegian Sky in August.
</P>
<P>
   Smaller vessels are also in: Radisson Seven Seas Cruises will
offer the Seven Seas Navigator, a 30,000-ton vessel, this August;
Mediterranean Shipping Cruises launches the 47,900 ton Mistral in
June (the line boasts it will be the most beautiful ship of the
decade), and Star Clippers will introduce its largest sailing
vessel, the Royal Clipper in November.
</P>
<P>
   And, that's just the list of new ships coming on line this year.
Even more are now under construction in European shipyards for
delivery beginning next year.
</P>
<P>
   Also new this year will be some major changes at Cunard. Cunard,
now owned by Carnival, will see a major updating of the Queen
Elizabeth 2, the renaming of the Vistafjord as the Coronia. The new
Cunard company will also operate Seabourn Cruises and is rebranding
the Sea Goddess I and the Royal Viking Sun as the Seabourn Goddess
and the Seabourn Sun. ``We are rebuilding the Golden Age of sea
travel for those who missed it the first time around,'' said Larry
Pimentel, president of Cunard. For this, Cunard is reintroducing
much of the transatlantic service it offered in the golden days of
ship travel with service between Southampton and New York and
European ports and Boston and Miami.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
