<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ONBUSINESS-COLUMN-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SMALL BANKS AWAIT THEIR SLICE OF THE ACQUISITION PIE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN SYRE AND CHARLES STEIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The big banks weren't talking Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Major national players such as First Union Corp. and KeyCorp and
BankAmerica Corp. had no comment when asked whether they might be
interested in bidding for the banking business that will be sold
off when Fleet Financial Group and BankBoston Corp. get together.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a matter of policy we never speak about our acquisition
plans,'' said a spokesman for KeyCorp, an $80 billion bank based in
Cleveland.
</P>
<P>
   But smaller local banks were more than happy to talk Monday. And
a number of them were positively gushing about the prospect of
getting a chance to acquire some of the $13 billion in deposits
that will have to be divested to meet antitrust concerns.
</P>
<P>
   Deposits, branches, and loans probably will be sold around
Boston, Hartford, and Providence, places where the two banks
overlap the most. Fleet will have a say in who gets the prizes, but
federal regulators will have a big say in the matter as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will be some real competition for these deposits because
a lot of people will view this as a one-shot opportunity,'' said
William Ryan, chief executive at Peoples Heritage Financial Group
in Portland, Maine. Ryan said his $10 billion bank would be very
interested in anything that came up for sale in Massachusetts or
Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   At USTrust in Boston, chief executive Neal Finnegan was already
plotting his strategy. By Monday morning he was on the phone with
his investment banker wondering how he might raise the money he
would need to put in a bid.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a responsibility to our shareholders to look at this
as an opportunity to build a more valuable franchise,'' said
Finnegan.
</P>
<P>
   Finnegan's $6.5 billion bank got a lot bigger in 1996 when it
bought a series of branches that came up for sale when BankBoston
bought BayBanks. Finnegan clearly would love to be able to pick up
some crumbs a second time.
</P>
<P>
   Who else might be interested? Eastern Bank for one.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are ready, willing, and able,'' said Mark Primeau, the
bank's executive vice president. Eastern, based in Lynn, is a $2.7
billion bank that has grown rapidly in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   Citizens Financial Group also has to be added to the list. The
Providence bank was a bit circumspect Monday, saying only it would
take a look at whatever came up for sale. But given its past
appetite for acquisitions, Citizens is likely to take a bite at the
apple. At $18 billion, Citizens is currently the third-largest bank
in New England, soon to be the second-largest. The new
Fleet-BankBoston combination will have $178 billion in assets.
</P>
<P>
   For some people, that gaping disparity is a problem. They argue
that a series of small to medium-size banks will never pose serious
competition for a giant. Their proposed solution: bring in another
giant.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to be aggressive in getting another major lender to
come into this market,'' said Secretary of the Commonwealth William
Galvin. Galvin's concern is the economy. He says local businesses
need at least two big banks they can go to for loans. Without that
second big player, the newly enlarged Fleet could have too much
clout here, said Galvin.
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Marks agrees. The community activist, who has forced a
number of banks to make loans available to poor and working-class
citizens, says he too will be urging regulators to recruit a second
giant to come into the region. Like Galvin, Marks believes only a
major competitive threat will be able to keep Fleet in check.
</P>
<P>
   The smart money says it isn't going to happen. Bank analysts say
there is very little precedent for the sale of deposits and loans
to big competitors. The selling banks obviously don't want the
competition and regulators have not forced them to go that route.
</P>
<P>
   There's another problem with the ``two giant'' strategy. While
$13 billion may sound like a lot of money, in big-time banking
circles it amounts to chump change. For major national banks, some
of whom are closing in on $500 billion in assets, the opportunity
to pick up $13 billion in New England may not be that exciting.
</P>
<P>
   Finally there is an argument to be made that smaller banks may
be able to provide real competition for Fleet.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of this consolidation has opened a window for well-run
community banks,'' said James Moynihan, an analyst with Advest in
Boston. Customers turned off by the megabanks, said Moynihan, often
prefer the service and personal touch the smaller banks can offer.
</P>
<P>
   Business executives say the small banks have been beating the
bushes recently, competing aggressively to make business loans.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't hear anyone complaining about the lack of credit,''
said Brian Gilmore, executive vice president at Associated
Industries of Massachusetts, a business trade group.
</P>
<P>
   It will be some time before the winner is crowned in this
competition. But don't be surprised if the victor is somebody who
already lives in the neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Steven Syre and Charles Stein can be reached by e-mail at
boscap(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
