<HEADLINE>
MISSING THE SHIP CAN BE COSTLY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY MORRIS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   What happens if you miss the ship? It can and does happen,
sometimes for unusual reasons. And, you could lose hundreds if not
thousands of dollars.
</P>
<P>
   Generally the most common reason for missing the ship is
weather, especially for Northeastern travelers in winter.
</P>
<P>
   Most cruise lines will do their best to get you to the ship,
even if it is at the next port of call. Norwegian Cruise Lines says
it will work with passengers who have purchased an air/sea package
in the event they miss the ship for weather problems. If for some
reason they cannot sail, the line, said they have offered to apply
the costs toward a future cruise within a year.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, however, many travelers missed their sailing because
of the Allied Pilot's Association ``sick out.''
</P>
<P>
   One way to at least save the cruise is to purchase travel
insurance that provides for trip cancellation or trip interruption
insurance. But even with this insurance, you could miss the boat if
the policy doesn't cover an incident such as this.
</P>
<P>
   Those who purchased Travel Guard insurance policies were covered
because the company decided to make an exception and reimburse
policyholders for trip cancellation and trip interruption losses.
``We just thought it was the right thing to do,'' said John Noel,
Travel Guard International chief executive officer.
</P>
<P>
   Losses caused by incidents such as the airline sick-out are
typically not covered in travel insurance policies. If it were a
strike, it would have been covered.
</P>
<P>
   For travelers booking a cruise which can cost thousands of
dollars, travel insurance that covers cancellation and other
circumstances makes good sense. However, before buying a policy, it
pays to read the fine print. Find out what is covered and what is
not.
</P>
<P>
   Travel Guard, for example, covers any unforeseen circumstances
other than those specifically excluded. Some policies cover only
specific circumstances. Some policies may cover just the cost of
the cruise, and not the air fare. Other policies may offer
graduated coverage with a full refund of the cost of the trip if it
is cancelled a month or more in advance, and only a portion
otherwise. The policy also may offer no coverage if cancelled
within 24 hours of the sail.
</P>
<P>
   Travel Guard said it has covered people who experienced a flat
tire on the way to the airport, a couple who two days before the
trip were told the baby they were seeking to adopt was suddenly
available in just a couple of days, and even a groom left at the
altar when his bride-to-be never showed up. He at least got the
cost of the honeymoon back.
</P>
<P>
   Deciding on how much insurance to take on a vacation trip
depends on how much you're willing to lose on any nonrefundable
portion of the trip. If you can't afford to lose anything, full
coverage is worthwhile. On a $3,000 cruise, Travel Guard said the
cost would be $275.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Great Lakes cruising
</P>
<P>
   Once, ships regularly cruised the Great Lakes. This summer
cruising returns with two nine-day sails planned for Aug. 24 and
Sept. 14. The Columbus, a 418-passenger ship operated by
Hapag-Lloyd, a European company, will sail the lakes providing
calls to both American and Canadian ports. The cruises are being
offered by a Cambridge, Ontario firm, Cruising the Great Lakes.
Rates begin at $1,350 a person. For information, write Box 1758;
Cambridge, Ontario N1R 7G8 or call, 800-319-9997.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Good deals
</P>
<P>
   It's your choice: Paris &AMP; Burgundy or Paris &AMP; Champagne. The
packages, which begin at $749 and $789, provide a week in France
combining Paris with either the Burgundy or Champagne regions. Both
packages are good through Oct. 31 and offer round-trip air fare
from New York, accommodations, a gourmet dinner, rental car, museum
pass, and more. Or, perhaps you'd rather sample Scotland on a Lochs
&AMP; Whisky Tour. The tour includes a nine-day car rental, full
Scottish breakfasts, accommodations and air fare beginning at
$1,049. For information, call New Frontiers at 800-366-6387.
</P>
<P>
   AirTran is offering travelers a Business Class upgrade for just
$25 over any fare until May 31. Seats are subject to availability
as there are just 16 of that class on the DC-9s and eight on the
737s. For information, call 800-247-8726.
</P>
<P>
   How old do you have to be to qualify for senior discounts?
Consider these senior deals:
</P>
<P>
   Novotel is offering senior travel discounts of up to 50 percent
off published rates at nine Novotel hotels in the United States and
Canada. For details, call 800-668-6835. The rates are for those 55
and older, except in New York where you must be 60 or older and in
Montreal where the requirements call for 65 and older.
</P>
<P>
   The Sanibel Inn on Sanibel Island on the southwest coast of
Florida is offering Boomer Plus, which offers travelers 50 and
older a 20 percent discount April 18-May 31 and a 25 percent
discount from June 1 through Dec. 23. The package includes
breakfast and a gift. For information, call 800-237-1491.
</P>
<P>
   The Equinox in Manchester Village, Vt. Is offering a spring
escape through March 27 and April 10 through April 29. The
$109-a-person rate includes accommodations, breakfast and dinner,
and the use of the Fitness Spa. Skiing, off-road driving, and spa
services are available. For information, call 800-362-4747.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Inn scene
</P>
<P>
   If you're interested in discovering great New England hotels,
inns, bed and breakfasts, or motor lodges, the New England
Innkeepers Fine Food and Lodging Show April 18 is the place to be.
The show, noon to 5 p.m. at the Sheraton Framingham in Framingham,
will have representatives from 350 lodging establishments. Chefs
from these lodgings also will be on hand creating culinary
demonstrations. Admission is $7. For information, call
603-964-6689.
</P>
<P>
   If you have a bed and breakfast, you might want to catch the
1999 Conference of Northeast Bed &AMP; Breakfasts March 21-24 at the
Sheraton Waterbury Hotel in Connecticut. Featured will be seminars
on Make the Best Better and Bernice Chesler, whose guides to bed
and breakfasts are known throughout the country. For information,
call 203-597-9527.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Literary tour
</P>
<P>
   Through March, Boston offers a trolley tour of the Literary
Trail of Greater Boston. The tour, developed by the Boston History
Collaborative, includes sites in Boston, Cambridge, and Concord
featuring famed writers homes, and places they gathered. Many
Boston hotels are offering weekend packages that include two adult
tickets for the Literary Trail along with accommodations and
breakfasts. Packages range from $169 to $595 a night (taxes and
gratuity extra). The Colonnade offers a choice of package including
one in a custom-designed Author's Suite thatfeatures a collection
of signed first-edition books ($595). For details, call
800-962-3030. Among other hotels offering packages are the Fairmont
Copley Plaza (800-527-4727), Swissotel (888-73-SWISS) beginning at
$169 a night; The Lenox (800-225-7676). For more information on the
trail or accommodations, call 888-SEE BOSTON.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Making plans
</P>
<P>
   Massachusetts isn't the only place that celebrates Patriot's
Weekend in April. Maine, once part of the commonwealth, also marks
the holiday, especially in Ogunquit where the 9th annual Patriot's
Weekend Celebration runs April 16 through 18. Many events will be
staged under the big top on Qgunquit Beach. Also planned is a
public supper Friday evening, the famous fireman's cook-out, a
beach bazaar throughout the weekend, a taste-of-the-town Saturday
with each taste from area restaurants just 75 cents, Saturday is
casino night on the beach, and on Sunday, Elvis will be there to
sing ``On the Beach.'' Ogunquit is just over an hour from Boston
and is one of Maine's most picturesque villages. For information,
call the Chamber of Commerce at 207-646-2939.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Women's history
</P>
<P>
   Throughout March, Colonial Williamsburg is celebrating National
Women's History Month with programs that explore the intricacies of
relationships and connections between 18th-century African,
British, and Native American women, free and enslaved. Particular
emphasis is given to the mistress and slave relationships that were
forged for sheer survival on the eve of the American Revolution.
For information, call 800-HISTORY.
</P>
</TEXT>
