<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-16 14:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2329 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WARSH-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      03-16 0755
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WARSH-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NATE PUSEY REG Q AND ALL THAT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID WARSH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; If you think for a minute that there was anything coincidental
about the fact that it was just an hour before the traditional St.
Patrick's Day breakfast in South Boston when the news that Fleet
Financial Group would acquire BankBoston Corp. began to seep out to
the best informed, then you don't know anything about Boston.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, if you think that simply being Irish is going
to get you a job working for Terrence Murray in the banking
behemoth that is the new Fleet Boston Corp., then you don't know
anything about modern times.
</P>
<P>
   The picturesque developments whereby the 215-year-old bank that
was Boston's proudest old Yankee institution as recently as the
1980s soon would be absorbed into an upstart Rhode Island bank run
by an Irishman of humble origins have many antecedents.
</P>
<P>
   For example, the merger's unseen stars no doubt include Senator
Edward M. Kennedy and Representative Joe Moakley, who plumped for
it behind the scenes. Why let a gang of high-rollers from New York,
Charlotte, N.C., or San Francisco take control of New England's
biggest banks if it could be avoided?
</P>
<P>
   Yet the regulator whose say-so surely counted for more than any
other in the deal was Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin. Federal
Reserve Board chairman Alan Greenspan shares reponsibility for
banking oversight, but Treasury's view counts for more in the
administration's policy toward mergers.
</P>
<P>
   That means the man who, more than any other, unleashed the
social forces that led to Monday's combination is a plain
Midwestern clergyman named Nathan Pusey, who was president of
Harvard University during the 1950s and 1960s.
</P>
<P>
   It was Pusey who in the mid-1950s presided over the effort
ordained by its governing corporation to transform Harvard College
from a regional college _ and sometimes little more than a
finishing school for the children of the upper classes of New
England _ into an institution of national standing and scope.
</P>
<P>
   Under Pusey _ and especially under admissions director Wilbur
Bender _ the decision had been made to seek out promising
applicants nationally, from all walks of life, and to admit
students on the basis of character, not standardized tests alone.
Harvard (and the Massachusetts Institute of Technology) also
invested heavily in the sciences in those days, especially the
infant field of molecular biology.
</P>
<P>
   The effects of this opening-up of the university could scarcely
have been more far-reaching, for New England in particular. Class
restrictions continued to chafe, but putting bright kids close to
one another immediately began to erode old barriers. Social
deregulation had begun in earnest.
</P>
<P>
   Rubin arrived at Harvard in 1956 from New York; Murray, two
years later from Woonsocket, R.I. Neither would have made it into
the Harvard of a dozen years before, when social and economic
standing counted for more than smarts and drive. Both men lived for
a time in Winthrop House, an undergraduate dormitory, and if they
didn't know each other then, they would have become aware of each
other's existence soon thereafter.
</P>
<P>
   Murray made his way to Industrial National Bank in Providence.
Rubin went to the London School of Economics, Yale Law School, and
then to work for the investment banking house of Goldman Sachs.
Both men rose rapidly to the top.
</P>
<P>
   By the 1980s, the enthusiasm for deregulation had spread to
finance. Traditional barriers separating financial institutions
functionally and geographically _ the Glass-Steagall and McFadden
acts, and Regulation Q _ had begun to fall. A great financial
merger movement was under way.
</P>
<P>
   Little Industrial National was quicker out of the blocks than
venerable Bank of Boston. It was not that the Yankees didn't try.
It was simply that the smaller bank was quicker, bolder, luckier:
Murray bought Albany's Norstar Bancorp in 1987, Boston's Bank of
New England in 1991, and Shawmut National Corp. in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Monday it was BankBoston's turn, and though the ``social
arrangements'' _ as the measures designed to maintain the losers'
wealth and self-esteem are known _ were as generous as in any other
deal of similar size, there could be no doubt whatsoever as to who
had won. Hence the announcement so close to St. Patrick's Day.
Boston would remain a financial center _ Boston go bragh!
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(David Warsh writes about economics for The Boston Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
