<HEADLINE>
SOME BURNING ISSUES AND HOT TOPICS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN SHAUGHNESSY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT MYERS, Fla. _ Picked-up pieces while counting the cars on
the Florida Turnpike . . .
</P>
<P>
   --How many days before the Patriots-to-Hartford deal collapses
under the weight of greed and ego?
</P>
<P>
   --Despicable baseball story of the day comes from Vero Beach,
where Gary Sheffield says he's considering retirement. Shef has
five years left on a six-year, $61 million contract and doesn't
like the Dodgers' new dress codes and personal-grooming guidelines.
He told the Los Angeles Times, ``I'm tired of every decision always
being around me. I just want to wear my facial hair and earrings
and just play the game.'' Go home, Gary, you nitwit.
</P>
<P>
   --John Calipari no doubt someday will tell folks that he made
Stephon Marbury the player he is  &UR; today &LR; . Coach Cal, after all, did
coach Marbury for one whole game. It was clear from the start that
Caliparis boola-boola stuff wasn't going to work in the pro game.
But weep not for the fired coach. He's got a pile of dough in the
bank and will get plenty of job offers. Maybe he can clean things
up at the University of Minnesota. Maybe he can clean up our state
treasury, or put UMass back on the map. Can he steal a slogan from
the Clippers and copyright, ``Refuse to Win''?
</P>
<P>
   --If Jim Calhoun can't make the Final Four this time, then he's
truly jinxed. Top West seeds (2-3-4) Stanford, North Carolina, and
Arkansas are bounced and the Huskies have to beat Iowa and either
Florida or Gonzaga to make it to St. Pete. It's never easy, but it
could have been a lot tougher.
</P>
<P>
   --If you're feeling ripped off from Saturday night's boxing
debacle, tell it to somebody else. The sport, as known by our
fathers and grandfathers, is dead. Anyone who bets hard-earned
money or buys pay-per-view expecting legitimate competition is a
sucker. And the suckers keep coming back. The boxing game is a
quagmire of sleaze. It's WWF without the good acting. Ears are
bitten, landslides are ruled draws, and we're supposed to wait
breathlessly for the rematch.
</P>
<P>
   --Boxing judge Eugenia Williams just awarded the 1998 World
Series to the San Diego Padres.
</P>
<P>
   --Red Sox first base hopeful Brian Daubach is from Belleville,
Ill. If you remember that Jimmy Connors also hails from Belleville,
pass Go and collect $200.
</P>
<P>
   --You say you want more positive stuff from the Boston sporting
press. So I show up and write a glowing column on the Celtics.
They've been pummeled almost daily since the column ran. That's it.
No more Mr. Nice Guy.
</P>
<P>
   --Teddy Dupay, the 5-10 reserve guard who helped Florida beat
Penn and Weber State, is the same kid Jimy Williams watched twice a
week last year as a Florida high school senior.
</P>
<P>
   --Driving on I-4 near Orlando I saw a truck advertising Dot
Richardson's softball training center.
</P>
<P>
   --The Darryl Strawberry situation could get testy. George
Steinbrenner renewed Darryl's contract but doesn't want to pay the
$850,000 in luxury tax he'll face if Straw is on the Opening Day
roster. Straw wants to be in the majors, but the Yankees have three
left fielders and a DH (Chili Davis) ahead of him. Stay tuned.
</P>
<P>
   --Seen ``Affliction''? The murder suspect/deer hunter says he
was as good a pitcher as Roger Clemens.
</P>
<P>
   --The harmony didn't last long in Fort Lauderdale, where Uncle
Albert Belle pulled a nutty, blamed the media, and had the rules of
coverage changed to suit his style.
</P>
<P>
   --WBZ Radio's Jon Miller says Mike Gimbel is the Dick Morris of
the Dan Duquette administration. Great line. And something tells me
old Statman is still having his way with the Sox front office.
</P>
<P>
   --Cameron Diaz or Gwyneth Paltrow? You make the call. Just don't
call it a draw.
</P>
<P>
   --Patriots? Houston? Too close to New Orleans.
</P>
<P>
   --The Sweet 16 features Dr. Tom Davis, Gary Williams, and Jimmy
O'Brien. Why can't BC get coaches like that?
</P>
<P>
   --Dennis Rodman and Los Angeles were made for one another. In
LA, Dennis can let his freak flag fly and still get to Vegas in an
hour.
</P>
<P>
   --Eugenia Williams awards the Oscar for best picture to ``The
Postman.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Dan Shaughnessy is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
