<HEADLINE>
ON-LINE RETAILERS DANGLE THEIR PROFITABLE GOODS: PORN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MATT BEER  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ When these executives talk electronic commerce,
they're not discussing best-selling books and CDs.
</P>
<P>
   During the ``XXX Files'' discussion Monday at the South By
Southwest (SXSW) Interactive Conference, electronic retailers were
talking about photographs of ``mummification bondage,'' a practice
that involves the creative use of duct tape.
</P>
<P>
   SXSW offers plenty of opportunities to discuss high culture on
the Internet, but this year's conference has been dominated by the
Internet's pursuit of money _ and pornography is the one commercial
activity on the Web that does make money.
</P>
<P>
   So while some executives pondered when such retail giants as
Seattle-based Amazon.com would turn a profit, money-making
pornographers merrily chatted away to a captive audience.
</P>
<P>
   ``A 14-foot-by-14-foot garden plot'' crowded with a ``giant
handful of seeds'' was how panelist Content Love Knowles of Austin
described the Internet porn economy.
</P>
<P>
   Knowles, a former brothel manager who runs Babalon.com, a Web
site that specializes in sadomasochistic content, said customers
overwhelming demand quality on-line porn. Quality, in this case,
refers to reputable companies that provide customer service rather
than just click-here-and-order credit card processors.
</P>
<P>
   Although most Internet analysts don't break out statistics on
on-line pornography purchases, Forrester Research, an Internet
market research firm in Massachusetts, estimated in February that
consumers spend about $1 billion annually to purchase naughty
pictures, videos and sex toys through the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Besides the occasional mention of unusual sex practices, the
panel of on-line pornographers spent most of their meeting
discussing the usual retailing concerns of any Internet company:
dealing with troublesome middlemen, preventing theft and
maintaining inventory.
</P>
<P>
   Christophe Pettus, founder of San Francisco-based Blowfish, one
of the first Web sites to sell sex products, said the absence of a
central warehouse for sex toys and other paraphernalia has hindered
the industry from meeting demand. Centralized distribution has been
key to keeping inventories moving at Amazon.com and other massive
Web retailing sites.
</P>
<P>
   Pettus said that kind of infrastructure ``just isn't there yet''
for the porn trade.
</P>
<P>
   George Hunt, founder of the Thursday Night Videos Web site,
which makes on-order fetish videos, raised the question of how to
handle the on-line version of shoplifting: other Web site operators
who illegally copy original explicit content onto their own sites.
</P>
<P>
   ``If someone steals from me, I'm going to make a business deal
(out of it),'' said Knowles, who said she either threatens the
offender with a lawsuit or makes them link to her site. Panelists
agreed that the problem was widespread and perhaps plagues
pornographers more than other retailers.
</P>
<P>
   Panelists also complained that sites without sexual content have
been luring away potential customers by using explicit words in
their metatags, the keywords that a Web site gives to search
engines so they can be identified. This causes the search engines
to call up vast lists of Web sites that are not necessarily
sex-related.
</P>
<P>
   This practice, panelists agreed, threatens the on-line
pornography industry.
</P>
<P>
   Those attending the meeting agreed that the next frontier in
on-line pornography is attracting women customers. Knowles
estimated that upwards of 30 percent of her customers are women.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-16-99 1429EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
