<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-16 14:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2339 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ROBERTSON-STEPHENS-HN     03-16 0465
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROBERTSON-STEPHENS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INVESTMENT BANK FINDS ITSELF FACING NEW BOSSES ... AGAIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By EDWARD IWATA  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Robertson Stephens, the San Francisco investment
bank that helped build the high-tech economy, has had a wild ride
of its own.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, BankAmerica Corp. bought the company for $540
million. Then last year, BankAmerica sold Robertson Stephens for
$800 million to BankBoston Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Now Fleet Financial Group Inc. plans to acquire BankBoston for
$16 billion, creating the eighth largest bank in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Fleet has $104 billion in assets and the Quick &AMP; Reilly discount
brokerage. BankBoston has $74 billion in assets and Robertson
Stephens, the nation's leading underwriter of initial public stock
offerings since 1995, with 282, according to Securities Data Corp.
</P>
<P>
   ``Robertson Stephens has been through a fair amount,'' said
Michael Flanagan of Financial Service Analytics in Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the short term, the deal spells another round of identity
crisis. But for the long term, Robertson Stephens gains great
potential for an expanded marketplace.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael McCaffery, chief executive of Robertson Stephens, said
the acquisition was another big plus for his investment bank.
Profits for Robertson Stephens were up 35 percent the first year
with BankBoston, he said, and income will hit a record high for the
first quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our business is in great shape, and we're extremely
successful,'' McCaffery said. ``This is a big positive for our
organization. We're ecstatic.''
</P>
<P>
   The marriage with Fleet's Quick &AMP; Reilly discount brokerage will
give Robertson Stephens popular retail outlets for its investment
products, including equity research and initial public offerings.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Quick &AMP; Reilly's electronic brokerage, SureTrade,
will let Robertson Stephens jump into the electronic investment
banking field.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll tap into every aspect of their retail channels,'' said
Camille Lepre, a Robertson Stephens spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
   The deal between the two Boston banks, announced Monday, may
save $600 million in operating costs and lead to 5,000 lost jobs.
Robertson Stephens, however, plans to hire this year, McCaffery
said.
</P>
<P>
   Robertson Stephens was founded in 1978 by Sanford Robertson, who
left the company last year to start his own investment outfit.
</P>
<P>
   Robertson built the company into a leading investment bank
specializing in financing for high-tech startups. Since its
founding, the company has raised $49 billion in initial public
stock offerings, or IPOs, and other financing.
</P>
<P>
   The Fleet-BankBoston deal, which must be approved by regulators
and shareholders, is expected to close late this year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
