<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-16 14:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2344 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ULTIMATE-MESSAGE-NYTS     03-16 0727
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ULTIMATE-MESSAGE-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AND NOW FOR A MESSAGE FROM THE ULTIMATE CEO 
</HEADLINE>
   (Religion Commentary)
 &HT;    
 &HT;    (Mike McManus is a syndicated columnist whose ``Ethics &AMP;
Religion'' appears in almost 100 newspapers)
 &HT;    
 &HT;    (To purchase this ``separate buy'' article from the New York
Times Syndicate please contact syndicate sales representative DEBRA
WEYDERT at 732-390-4480)
 &HT;    
 By MIKE McMANUS  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Drivers caught in a snarl of freeway traffic leading into Dallas
looked up last week at that tall skyline and saw a huge new black
billboard with a few stark words in white:
 &HT;    ``Keep Using My Name In Vain, I'll Make Rush Hour Longer. GOD''
 &HT;    Those driving in from different directions saw other billboards
with equally arresting messages from the Creator:
 &HT;    ``Don't Make Me Come Down There. GOD''
 &HT;    ``What Part of `Thou Shalt Not...' Didn't You Understand? GOD''
 &HT;    ``Will the Road You Are on Get You to My Place? GOD''
 &HT;    The God Ad Campaign is being donated by local billboard
companies as a public service. There will soon be 10,000 billboards
like these all across America as billboard firms donate the space.
 &HT;    ''It is a gift to the community,'' says Nancy Fletcher,
president of the Outdoor Advertising Association of America. ''It
is a positive way to get people thinking about spirituality, and
increasing the numbers who are going to church. It makes you
believe in divine interventin!''
 &HT;    The campaign began in Broward County, Florida, in and around
Fort Lauderdale last fall. It was football season, of course. So
two of the first billboards to go up tartly said:
 &HT;    ``Let's Meet at My House Sunday Before the Game. GOD''
 &HT;    ``C'mon Over and Bring the Kids. GOD''
 &HT;    The ads were developed by The Smith Agency after an anonymous
client came in one day and told owner Andy Smith, ''I have one
goal. I need to have people start thinking about God. Things are
getting out of control. People are not obeying the rules any more.
Every day you read about murder, robbery, adultery everything that
God said, `Don't do.'
 &HT;    ''If we can get to one person before he robs a bank, to think
about God first, maybe we can stop him. If so, it will be worth
it.''
 &HT;    I tried to find out who the anonymous benefactor was even to
learn whether he was a pastor or businessman, but could learn
nothing. Oprah Winfrey offered to put the guy on her show, but he
declined: ''If people focus on me or the money I spent, they will
forget the message of the ads. Forget about me. I am looking for
nothing. The message is much more important than who I am.''
 &HT;    So let's go back to the message. This summer you may be driving
along some hot day and look up to see these billboard that ought to
get your attention:
 &HT;    ``You Think It's Hot Here? GOD''
 &HT;    ``Need a Marriage Counselor? I'm Available. GOD''
 &HT;    Some of the messages were written by the anonymous donor. They
are more gentle:
 &HT;    ``I Love You...I Love You...I Love You. GOD''
 &HT;    ``Tell the Kids That I Love Them. GOD''
 &HT;    But most were written by Charlie Robb, who describes himself as
''being in the target audience of people who used to go to church,
but who don't any more.''
 &HT;    ``I'm a former altar boy,'' he told me. To reach such people,
Scripture would not work, he says. ''We had to make the message
contemporary, slightly irreverent, reminding people that they are
dealing with the ultimate CEO.''
 &HT;    ``Need Directions? GOD''
 &HT;    ``Do You Have Any Idea Where You're Going? GOD''
 &HT;    ``Follow Me. GOD''
 &HT;    ``Have You Read My Number 1 Bestseller? There Will Be a Test. --
GOD''
 &HT;    How has the God Ad Campaign worked? The Miami Herald surveyed
churches in he area and reported that attendance rates were up.
Even Charlie has been to church a few times. A woman in Fort
Lauderdale sent an E-mail to the Smith Agency, thanking it for the
ads which are ''such a breath of fresh air.'' She said her niece
was married to a man who would never go to church with her. While
driving along, they both saw this ad:
 &HT;    ``I Loved the Wedding. Invite Me To The Marriage. GOD''
 &HT;    The man went to church with his wife for the first time the next
Sunday, and has been going ever since.
 &HT;    ``We Need To Talk. GOD''
 &HT;    
 &HT;    ----
 &HT;    c.1999 Mike McManus
