<HEADER>
A2353 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOCCER-ZIDANE-NYTSF &LR;      03-16 2561
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOCCER-ZIDANE-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUST A SOCCER STAR, AFTER ALL 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (This article has already moved to Centerpiece clients. To
publish as a ``separate buy'' article, it must be purchased _ the
rate is not prohibitive _ from one of these New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives: 
 &HT;    (--U.S. and Canada: DEBRA WEYDERT in New Jersey at
1-732-390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697. 
 &HT;    (--Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942. 
 &HT;    (--Latin America: OLIVIA VASQUEZ in Los Angeles, 310-996-0075;
fax, 310-996-0089. 
 &HT;    
 By JOHN VINOCUR  
 FROM: The New York Times Magazine  
 &HT;    Way back when Jacques Chirac didn't know Zinedine Zidane from ZZ
Top, before he scored the goals that won France the World Cup in
1998, before French kids voted him more popular than Michael Jordan
and French women called him sexier than Brad Pitt or Antonio
Banderas, before his face was painted in street murals big enough
for Stalin or Mobutu, Zinedine Zidane did something brutal and
dumb.
 &HT;    That was last June, in the second match of the World Cup,
soccer's world championship, when Zidane raked his studs across the
stomach of a fallen South African player and was suspended for the
next two games. It was not a smart thing to do, crudeness bordering
on disgrace for someone who would subsequently be voted the best
player in the world _ and whose game illuminates soccer in its
finest shadings, all virtuosity, elegance, intellect.
 &HT;    In the stands and in the streets in France, the talk descended
from ``what a shame'' to ``what did you expect?'' Zidane, they
said, the Algerian kid, the one from the worst slum in Marseille,
reacted as if he was back on the street with his homies.
 &HT;    The simple explanation, that he overreacted in a fit of stress
and frustration, dissolved in a rush of national discomfort. In the
Arab bars and cafes in St. Denis near Le Stade de France, the
stadium France had built for the 1998 World Cup, Zidane's expulsion
was all about prejudice and politics and plots.
 &HT;    In the white French working world of diminished expectations, of
train strikes and broken stamp dispensers and kids beating up bus
drivers, it was about a French team that more resembled a group
picture from the housing projects, with their Arabs and blacks.
Zidane, uh, you know, what else could you expect?
 &HT;    The French coach, Aime Jacquet, refused to look at him when he
walked off the field in disgrace. Smail and Malika Zidane's
youngest son, a 26-year-old from Building 7 in La Castellane
projects, was a goal or two away from being blamed for France's
elimination from the World Cup. He went back to the team's training
facility to shut up and wait out his suspension.
 &HT;    When Zidane came back to the lineup, France won its next three
games and the World Cup. His two goals in the final, both
magnificent headers, beat Brazil, soccer's pre-eminent national
team. A country that had never romanticized or intellectualized
sports found itself marveling at what it decided it wanted its
triumph to mean: the first happy signs of its transformation into a
multicultural society of underestimated vigor.
 &HT;    Suddenly, la France universelle, the cultural pressing machine
that remodels every difference into standard-issue Frenchness,
conceded, at least for the moment, that it was richer through all
its Zidanes. The victory, with a team composed of white, brown and
black players, had said something enormously encouraging about what
kind of country France could be.
 &HT;    In the dismal hierarchy of French racism, light-years from the
notions of tolerance that attracted the Richard Wrights and James
Baldwins and Bud Powells to Paris, the country's millions of North
Africans _ Arabs in the French mind, regardless of their
citizenship _ people exactly like Zidane's family, are easy targets
for daily scorn. They are automatically suspect, reflexively and
indiscriminately linked to growing street violence or _ like
Arab-Americans _ to any terrorist bombing.
 &HT;    In winning the World Cup, however, France lived through a burst
of generosity and good intentions unlike anything it had
experienced since the liberation of World War II. And it put in the
middle a soccer player whose brilliance was too quickly taken as a
metaphor for a change in national political temperament.
 &HT;    Wishfully, France persuaded itself to read into Zidane's
wondrous creativity the beginning of an end to its problems of race
and class, a too facile symbol of victory for a job nowhere near
done. Zidane became the emblematic figure of a social phenomenon of
which politicians and marketers and instant sociologists all wanted
a piece.
 &HT;    President Chirac, no soccer fan, pinned Legion of Honor ribbons
on Zidane and his teammates; the president's approval rating
soared. Marketing people pronounced Zidane ``stable, virile and
serious'' _ complimentary, yes, but not quite their usual
vocabulary when talking about French athletes of European origin.
 &HT;    Zidane took all this in very quietly, with an air of distance
that later looked like wisdom. With a million people on the
Champs-Elysees, he saw blue lasers spell out his name on the Arc de
Triomphe: ``Zidane for President,'' the giant letters said, and
``Merci, Zizou.'' The French press took to calling him Zizou, which
sounds very French and cute.
 &HT;    It was only months later that one of his brothers, with ever so
mild reproach, said that his family and friends actually call him
Yaz, short for Yazid, not a terribly unusual name in Kabylia, the
region in Algeria from which their parents had come. Months later,
too, when Zidane talked about the experience, it was pointedly
about his buddies from the projects (Malek, Baba, Richard, Nordine,
Nasser), not the moment's groundswell of good feeling and
fraternity.
 &HT;    In the autumn, perhaps with the special egalitarian moment
withering, Christian Jelen, writing in Le Figaro magazine, said
that ``the immigrant has become the new vector of revolution. The
immigrant is the new pariah, the new symbol of oppression and
waste. He has replaced the worker as the Christ figure in the mind
of the left-wing intellectual.''
 &HT;    At just about the same time, a stand-up comic named Guy Bedos,
much loved in France for his precisely targeted cynicism, caught
the evolution in the national mood from summer to winter. ``Hey,''
he shouted at his audience, ``a couple of kicks from some
(epithet), two head shots from an Arab and France starts going
around like it's in some kind of Benetton one-world commercial.
What is this?''
 GROWING UP IN THE PROJECTS  
 &HT;    Zidane looked at me as if I were out of my mind. I had come to
Turin, where he plays for Juventus, the great and superrich Italian
team built by Gianni Agnelli, and I was talking to him about his
old housing project, La Castellane.
 &HT;    We went over the obvious: Social workers said that in some
buildings the unemployment rate ran at about 60 percent, that Arab
families were disintegrating and that the only people seemingly up
in the morning were kids going to school. The cops feared the
place, doctors refused to make house calls there for a while last
year and when the Grand Mufti of Marseille, the city's Islamic
spiritual leader, came by on a kind of official pastoral visit,
somebody stole his car.
 &HT;    Still, I said, set on the scale of projects and mean streets in
the United States, Marseille North seemed a lot less forbidding:
whitewashed apartment houses built into the side of a deep ridge, a
view out to the Mediterranean, an arc of beiges, rusts, opalescent
blues and eucalyptus trees.
 &HT;    Zidane stared back, amazed at this proposition. He has kind
green eyes. He tried hard not to make me into a fool and searched
for something judicious to smooth away the embarrassment.
 &HT;    ``It's not like the projects are horrible, disgusting,'' he
explained, ``but things happen there. It was a pretty rough place.
There were 6,000 people at La Castellane when I lived there. If it
wasn't happening at the bottom of the hill, it was happening at the
top. Rough.''
 &HT;    At La Castellane, soccer happened in confined spaces, under
building eaves, in driveways, in parking lots. In the Marseille
projects, the game is played the way basketball is in inner-city
America. When you get the ball, you do what you can fast. Project
soccer is moves, ball control, amazing your homeboys, bidding up,
working the ball _ tricks that are every La Castellane's equivalent
of slam-dunks.
 &HT;    An old club team coach remembered Yaz at 11 or 12. ``The kid was
Zorro,'' he said. ``He made the law.''
 &HT;    If he had not combined schoolyard flash with the skills of a
master architect, Zidane might have wound up among the 43 percent
of young men in France with foreign parents who are out of work. As
it was, a recruiter saw Zidane at 13 dribble through the legs of an
opponent in front of his own goal, a display of dazzling soccer
gall.
 &HT;    Nervously, and after a check of his French citizenship, Zidane
was brought into the training program of the professional club at
Cannes. His mastery developed from there, a mixture of hot street
moves and a very much colder sense of space that lets his passing
control the game in the subtlest of geometric patterns.
 &HT;    On the field he's slightly hunched, not wildly fast, not buffed
and muscular, but remarkably supple. Unlike other players,
according to Enzo Francescoli, the former Marseille midfielder
Zidane idolized as a kid, he takes control of the ball with the
outside rather than the inside of his foot. Uniquely, the ball
seems to sit not so much in front of his feet but tucked
protectively between them. When Zidane is on, he does for soccer
what the most brilliant point guards do for basketball: He creates
the continuously unexpected.
 &HT;    Zidane lacks Michael Jordan's transcendent physical grace, but
his moves, like Michael's, make true believers. Zidane, says Pierre
Labat, who coached him at Bordeaux, has two characteristics. ``He
does things that nobody has ever seen before, and when he does the
same thing others do, he does it differently.''
 &HT;    Pele, the Brazilian who is widely considered the greatest soccer
player ever, brought a joy and athletic fluidity to the game in the
1960s. Maradona, the stumpy Argentine of the 1980s, was all heat
and percussion, looking as if he would score every time he got the
ball.
 &HT;    Zidane has been described as the player of the year 2000 _ the
first model for the next generation, an athlete whose draftsman's
sense of space, line and invention, mixed with moments of wild
schoolyard jive, seems cooler, more modern, a step beyond.
 &HT;    Told he had outpolled Jordan in France as the world's best
athlete, Zidane said: ``I'm not even on the same planet with
Michael Jordan. Get serious.''
 &HT;    No one has imposed new loyalties, new emotions on him. His
friends truly are his buddies from the projects. During his first
two years in Italy, Zidane had at least one of them living at all
times in his house with his family.
 &HT;    He tried to explain what it was like to be a North African kid
in the projects, with your father stacking boxes in a supermarket
chain's warehouse. When he watched the French national team on TV
with his brothers, it was like: ``You know, they're over there, and
we can only be here. You've got to be twice as strong as the other
guy. When you start off, the two of us, we've got something less
than the French guy.''
 &HT;    This soft-spoken resentment also marks Zidane. He doesn't say
quite what would soothe the French status quo, and he subtly but
steadfastly resists efforts to make him into the symbol of a new
multicultural movement. He didn't like the subject when I put it to
him, and he pushed it back. He limited talking about his doubts to
soccer and acknowledged them as ``more the fact that I'm never
fully happy with what I do.''
 &HT;    For someone who may be the world's most popular Frenchman, it is
not always easy going home, and Zidane expresses no great interest
in playing again for a French club team. The reason is unstated but
clear enough. After the marketing man who condescendingly
pronounced him stable and serious, a television critic for the
sports newspaper L'Equipe watching a recent appearance gave him
good marks for alertness and passion. But, as if he were grading
Zidane on his Frenchness, the critic felt compelled to add that he
was also ``inhibited and hesitant in his phrasing.''
 ENCOURAGING SIGNS  
 &HT;    Winter finds Zidane back at Juventus, playing for a salary
estimated at more than $3 million a year and getting thrown out of
a match and suspended again after a nasty tackle. The event makes
next to no news in France, and this time the what-did-you-expects
are missing.
 &HT;    There are other encouraging signs. Loubna Meliane, a young woman
with a North African background, emerges as the spokeswoman for a
student movement that actually talks the government into making
some reforms. French rap, from groups in the projects, dominates
pop music, while Le Figaro, often an almost comic advocate of
cultural conservatism, offers an article on the popularity of rai,
a form of Algerian pop music.
 &HT;    Even the sacred French language seems to be moving toward a
wider idea of pluralism. Bourgeois parents tell of their kids
developing housing-project accents that reflect the intonation and
sentence structure of Algerian immigrants. And all of France savors
the story about Germany, disgraced in the World Cup, changing
soccer managers and thinking about how to get more non-100-percent
Germans onto the national team.
 &HT;    But not everyone believes that Zidane's face on giant wall
murals in Marseille and on the highway to Charles de Gaulle Airport
signals conclusive change. A report from the traditionally ignored
High Commission on Integration, established some years before,
lists profound inequalities in education, housing and the justice
system and warns about ``the rise and seriousness of discrimination
that victimizes foreigners and French citizens of foreign origin.''
 &HT;    With the nation focused on the crime issue with its
not-so-subtle undercurrents of racism, notions of France's
brilliant multicultural future look a bit overdrawn. The best that
can be confidently said about Zidane and the French World Cup
victory is that they may have given a different sense of what
France might be. For now, what there is of transformation stops
there.
 &HT;    French television recently carried a report on a 19-year-old
named Nicolas Anelka, a black man from a mean Paris suburb who is
playing soccer for Arsenal in London. He's described as possibly
the next Zidane, but faster, stronger.
 &HT;    On camera from London, Anelka waves the crew off, saying at
first that he doesn't like to talk to the press. Maybe, a voice in
the background suggests, he'd just like to say hello to France.
 &HT;    ``Yeah,'' says Anelka, perking up. ``Hello Djamel, Karim, Akim
and Sami.''
 &HT;     c.1999 John Vinocur  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (John Vinocur is the senior correspondent of The International
Herald Tribune, where he was the executive editor from 1987 to
1996.) &LR;
</P>
