<HEADER>
A2365 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIRCUMCISION-HNS &LR;      03-16 0731
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIRCUMCISION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CIRCUMCISION A DIFFICULT CHOICE FOR SOME PARENTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By SYLVIA WOOD  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Deyva Arthur's decision not to circumcise her
newborn boy last month created quite a stir among her relatives.
</P>
<P>
   But she feels better about defying family tradition since the
American Academy of Pediatrics stated in a new policy on March 1
that the potential medical benefits of circumcision are not
sufficient to recommend it as a routine medical procedure.
</P>
<P>
   ``It kind of vindicates me a little bit,'' said Arthur, who
lives in Troy, N.Y., with her husband and her son, Julian Sam Foy,
who was born Feb. 17.
</P>
<P>
   The debate over whether to circumcise, however, isn't expected
to die soon, as parents wrangle with cultural, religious and ethnic
traditions, as well as medical factors in making the decision.
</P>
<P>
   The American Academy of Pediatrics stopped short of giving any
specific advice: ``We encourage parents to discuss the benefits and
risks of circumcision with their pediatrician, and then make an
informed decision about what is in the best interest of their
child,'' said Dr. Carole Lannon, chairwoman of the academy's task
force on circumcision.
</P>
<P>
   As Arthur attests: ``It wasn't an easy decision.''
</P>
<P>
   Each year, an estimated 1.2 million newborn males are
circumcised in the United States, at a cost of between $150 million
and $270 million. Circumcision surgically removes the foreskin, or
the skin that covers the end of the penis.
</P>
<P>
   In revising its policy, the academy also stated for the first
time that if newborn males are circumcised, they should be given
local anesthesia for pain relief _ something that's not usually
done now, in part because of some concern about the risk of
complications, including allergies and swelling.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Robert Rosenblatt, a obstetrician and gynecologist, is
already anticipating questions from parents, who may feel even more
confused.
</P>
<P>
   ``There never really has been a lot of medical evidence that
circumcision was necessary,'' said Rosenblatt, who practices in
Delmar, N.Y. ``Some parents go on the basis that if everybody else
is doing it, maybe we should too.''
</P>
<P>
   Circumcision is the widespread tradition in the United States.
Some doctors have long believed it decreases the risk of
infections, sexually transmitted diseases and the risk of penile
cancer.
</P>
<P>
   But there are cultural reasons too. For Jews and Muslims,
circumcision is a religious ritual. For many Americans, it's
considered more socially acceptable, even though in Europe and
Latin America, circumcised males are a minority.
</P>
<P>
   It remains controversial, however, whether circumcision affects
penile sensation and sexual satisfaction.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Michael Horgan, the head of neonatal medicine at Albany
Medical Center, believes the academy did a good job of distilling
all the available medical literature on circumcision. But he
acknowledged that parents rarely talk about risk factors.
</P>
<P>
   ``How do you get that information out so parents can make an
informed decision?'' Horgan said.
</P>
<P>
   On urinary tract infections, the academy concluded that
uncircumcised infants are four to 10 times more likely to acquire
one in the first year of life than circumcised boys, but the
absolute risk is very low _ about seven to 14 cases in every 1,000
uncircumcised infants, compared with one to two out of every 1,000
circumcised infants.
</P>
<P>
   With penile cancer, their findings were similar. Although
uncircumcised males have a threefold increase in risk, they
concluded that the disease is so rare that the absolute risk is
very low _ about nine to 10 cases for every million men.
</P>
<P>
   Arthur and her husband discussed circumcision at length before
their son was born.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had done some research and read Dr. Spock and a variety of
articles. None of them said there was much medical reason,'' Arthur
said.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, she acknowledged she and her husband had trouble
reaching an agreement. ``He couldn't decide,'' she said. ``Once the
baby was born, he didn't want anything to cause him pain.''
</P>
<P>
   Arthur is optimistic that as more parents learn about the issue,
they will choose not to have their children circumcised.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of the world isn't circumcised,'' she said. ``By the time
my son is that age, half of the boys won't be circumcised either.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
