<HEADER>
A2399 &Cx1f; tad-z
r w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BLIND-$ADV21-COX     03-16 1959
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BLIND-$ADV21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TECHNOLOGY A MIXED BLESSING FOR BLIND CONSUMERS
 &HT;    With BLIND-DATA. For release Sunday, March 21.
 &HT;    1380&AMP;add.
 &HT;    By ANDREW MOLLISON
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ As technology races into the future, many blind and
visually impaired consumers are having trouble keeping up.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're kind of in the middle between rather costly, but fairly
good, access in the computer environment, and increasingly bad
access in portable telecommunications and home appliances,'' said
Paul Schroeder of Chicago, director of the national technology
program of the New York-based American Foundation for the Blind.
</P>
<P>
   On balance, technology has been a boon for the 10 million
Americans whose vision can't be corrected with glasses or contact
lenses alone. That is especially true for the 3 million with the
most severe visual handicaps _ those who can't read newsprint or
recognize a friend at arm's length, or are blind in both eyes.
</P>
<P>
   Using special software, they can use computers. Telephones can
receive e-mail or voice-mail messages. In some cities, blind people
can phone a 24-hour ``Newsline'' number to hear stories from their
local newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   But the rapid development of technology often leaves people with
bad sight behind:
</P>
<P>
   _ The computer programs most popular in homes or offices seldom
include features that will help visually impaired users.
</P>
<P>
   _ As makers of home appliances and electronic gadgets focus on
sleek exteriors, some of their products have become harder to use.
</P>
<P>
   Computer users with bad eyesight must buy, install, customize
and frequently upgrade the software that lets them use
graphics-oriented programs designed for people who can see well.
That assistive technology can cost more than the computer itself.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had some vision for most of my life,'' said Linda Jacobson
of Orange Park, Fla. At first she used software that enlarged the
print and icons on her screen. But as her sight deteriorated, she
went shopping for a program that would read the computer screen to
her aloud.
</P>
<P>
   ``The screen-reader Linda bought cost $550,'' said her husband,
Eric, a software developer. ``It didn't work, and we called the
company for support, and their reply was, 'It works here.' ``
</P>
<P>
   Even the best special software ``doesn't work on some modern Web
pages because of the graphics, and when it does work it downloads
very slowly,'' said Shawn Martin of Alamogordo, N.M., who is blind.
``It's new, and it's just not as reliable as the old low-tech
stuff, like talking thermometers and talking scales.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You can get to the point where maybe you can fill out the
order form to buy a book on line, but you can't find the 'submit'
button, and there's no keyboard equivalent to activate it,'' said
Scott Marshall, a blind lawyer and advocate in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   A test by Cox Newspapers of the home pages of the 25 busiest Web
sites showed that all but five had graphic elements that could not
be read by assistive programs for the visually impaired.
</P>
<P>
   The job market offers an even bigger challenge, because many
businesses develop their own computer networks in-house. It's not
always easy to plug assistive software into such a system.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are just a few techies in the field who can do it,''
said LaDella Holmes-Reddick of the Center for the Visually Impaired
in Atlanta, ``and if an Atlanta company offers a job to one of our
blind clients, we might have to fly in someone from Texas to write
the code.''
</P>
<P>
   The shortage of specialized technicians is nationwide, said
Curtis Chong, director of technology at the Baltimore headquarters
of the 50,000-member National Federation of the Blind.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't learn this stuff in Silicon Valley. The few of us
who do it pick it up on our own with a whole lot of assistance from
talking to other blind people,'' Chong said. ``Second, if
somebody's really good at technology you have to pay them a lot of
money to keep them from being hired away, and rehabilitation
agencies just haven't had that kind of money.''
</P>
<P>
   Strikingly, however, many blind people find everyday appliances
even more annoying than computers. At least computers have
keyboards they can become familiar with.
</P>
<P>
   But today's top-of-the-line microwave ovens, radios, TVs, VCRs,
cell phones and ATM machines often operate with touchpads and video
displays that ask written questions or use up-and-down arrows.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can twirl knobs by feel, but that doesn't work with visual
displays,'' said Michael Fischer of New York, director of
low-vision services for Lighthouse International.
</P>
<P>
   The other day, Audley(cq) Blackburn's TV set stopped responding
to his remote.
</P>
<P>
   ``It talks to you to tell you what to do next, but it doesn't
give you feedback to tell you whether you did it right,'' the
Austin, Texas, small business owner said. ``I accidentally pushed
the wrong button and somehow deprogrammed the thing. So I had to
call a sighted friend to come over and ask him to look at my set
and read me the screen.''
</P>
<P>
   William Schiavo, a young programmer studying technology in
Baltimore at the National Center for the Blind, said, ``The average
guy can run down to the ATM and stuff their card in and get out
some money, but unless we have previously visited and memorized the
sequence of ATM commands, we can't use it.''
</P>
<P>
   On an out-of-town trip, he met a woman who proudly told him that
her bank's ATM was braille-equipped ``so us blind guys could use
it.'' Pawing the machine, he finally found a little braille tag
that read, ``For assistance, pick up the nearest telephone.''
</P>
<P>
   Linda Ward of Jacksonville, Fla., who enjoys infomercials on TV,
jokes that she saves money by being unable to respond to those that
end, ``please call the number on your screen.''
</P>
<P>
   But she gets genuinely upset during hurricane season when she
hears the beep on her TV set that means a weather warning is
scrolling across the screen.
</P>
<P>
   ``I called the TV station once and told her that blind people
didn't know what the message was, and her response was like, 'what
are blind people doing watching TV?' That was nasty,'' Ward
recalled. An audio option that could be used for such purposes
without disturbing sighted viewers has been required in all stereo
TV sets for several years.
</P>
<P>
   ``My wife went shopping for an electric range,'' said Al
Pietrolungo of Baltimore, who is blind. ``She called the library
and asked them to look up the top five recommendations from
Consumer Reports. She went to the appliance store, and all five of
them were unusable by blind people, because they had digital
displays or touchpads.''
</P>
<P>
   How do these things happen?
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't test things for blind people,'' said spokeswoman Rana
Silver of Consumer Reports magazine. ``There are consumers with
disabilities who use mainstream products, but unfortunately, when
you are blind, it's a very specialized subset of the population.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked about the complaints, the Electronics Industry
Association, which includes major appliance and electronics
companies, referred all questions to two blind experts: disability
consultant Mike Paciello of Nashua, N.H., and Lawrence Scadden at
the National Science Foundation's program for persons with
disabilities.
</P>
<P>
   ``Manufacturers don't consider or use or test their devices or
appliances with people with disabilities,'' Paciello said. One big
reason, he said: ``There are no national or international standards
that mandate accessibility.''
</P>
<P>
   While their numbers are increasing as baby boomers age, market
forces still work against the blind. Appliance makers don't think
that 1 million legally blind consumers and 9 million visually
impaired consumers are a big enough niche to target in a country of
more than 270 million people, Paciello said.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, the visually impaired aren't as prosperous as the
population in general. Half are retired, and only three in 10 of
working age have jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Scadden said that Whirlpool and Sharp Electronics are the only
big U.S. suppliers that will give braille overlays to any consumer
who buys products with touchpads. But in today's mega-stores, many
clerks and customers don't even know that the option exists, or
which company makes which brands.
</P>
<P>
   ``No designer would deliberately make something inaccessible,
but they just go ahead and design products for fully able-bodied
young people,'' Scadden said. ``They don't even save any money by
doing it that way. ``
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   He once asked the engineers at one computer manufacturer to make
a cost-free change: A higher contrast between the letters and
background on a new model's keyboard.
</P>
<P>
   ``Although I can't see keys myself, I know a lot of people with
low vision who wanted the keys labeled in high contrast,'' Scadden
said. ``But I was told by the engineers that that wasn't their
department, that was marketing, which was more concerned about
appearance than usability.''
</P>
<P>
   Even learning what kind of technology could help is a mystery to
many people who start losing their vision after a lifetime of
normal sight.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no Consumer Reports magazine for the blind or partly
blind,'' said William Paul, whose central vision in each eye
deteriorated steadily during the decade before his retirement as
executive vice president of United Technologies in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no one-stop shop where the average person can check
out all the electronic software and hardware to find out what will
help with your particular kind of eye disease,'' Paul said.
``Almost no one, including eye doctors, knows much about the
closest thing we have to it today _ the low-vision clinics the
Lions Clubs are starting at several universities, and the little
stores where some gutsy entrepreneurs are aiming at this marketing
niche.''
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton and Congress have approved three federal laws
that could help deal with inaccessible technology.
</P>
<P>
   But the question of how well the laws will be enforced is still
up in the air:
</P>
<P>
   _ The Department of Education was empowered last fall to create
a central Web site containing a big, national inventory of
technology and devices usable by people with disabilities,
including visual problems. ``We have to do something, but we don't
know yet what we will do,'' a departmental spokeswoman said.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Telecommunications Act of 1996 authorized the Federal
Communications Commission to study how to make the next generation
of telecommunications devices usable for the blind. For three years
now, the commission has been studying the question of whether to
issue regulations or voluntary guidelines.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Assistive Technology Act of 1998 required that no later
than August 2000, the federal government try to make its agencies
stop buying electronic information technology that cannot be used
by employees or citizens with disabilities. Federal advisory panels
are hard at work on the first drafts of such rules.
</P>
<P>
   ``After that, if any consumers buy software off the shelf,
chances are it will have accessibility built right into it,'' said
William Paul, who serves on one of the advisory panels. ``Suppliers
will have already folded accessibility features into their product
in order to sell it to the federal government, because it is by far
their biggest customer.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What we have to do is make sure the regulations that enforce
those laws are efficient, effective and in line with the spirit of
the laws,'' said Paul Edwards, a disability expert at Miami-Dade
Community College who heads the nation's second largest
organization of blind consumers, the American Council of the Blind.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
