<SLUG> BC-MARINES-CITIES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOCK INVASION PITS MARINES AGAINST PROTESTERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ERIC BRAZIL and LARRY D. HATFIELD  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALAMEDA, Calif. _ The Marines, computers and high-tech weapons
at the ready, landed on the eastern shore of the San Francisco Bay
amid a war of words and not much else.
</P>
<P>
   A half-hour behind schedule, the first of 550 battle-dressed
Marines were ferried ashore at the old naval base here Monday
aboard husky CH-53 Super Stallions, helicopters that carry 37
soldiers in full combat gear, and the smaller 22-person CH-46 Sea
Knights.
</P>
<P>
   The soldiers who came ashore in the Marines' urban warfare
rehearsal were equipped with laptop computers, tiny digital radios
_ the first major change in combat radio communications since 1938
_ and ``acoustical anti-sniper weapons'' that react to the sound of
gunfire and automatically pound the source with .50-caliber
bullets.
</P>
<P>
   Waiting on shore were about 100 protesters representing an array
of causes, including peace, tree and bicycle activists. There were
sharp words but no incidents and the police were on hand.
</P>
<P>
   After helicopters had deposited most of the Marines ashore, four
LCAC hovercraft, 88-foot heavy-duty landing vessels, rumbled
noisily across the Bay and onto the tarmac at Alameda Point, where
they disgorged about 200 troops and a quantity of equipment,
including trucks and light armored vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is just a dress rehearsal for war,'' said veteran San
Francisco leftist Gloria La Riva. ``We think they're just planning
for an invasion of Iraq.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's absolutely untrue,'' Lt. Col. Gary Shenkel, a Marine
spokesman, said in the sharpest exchange of the exercise. Noting
that 300 civilians were working with the operation, he added,
``This is not a preparation for war. There will be tremendous
technology transferred to civilian uses.''
</P>
<P>
   The Marines already know how to make landings, attack and
bombard, added Marine Col. Mark Thiffault.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we don't know how to do is to fight and survive in an
urban area,'' he said. ``We don't believe we're going to have
another large Saddam Hussein-type operation. They (Iraqis) are not
stupid. They're not suicidal.''
</P>
<P>
   The combined Navy-Marine exercise included overflights of the
Bay area by the Sea Shadow, the Navy equivalent of the stealth
bomber, in what Thiffault called a major test of combat
communications capability.
</P>
<P>
   The communications gear centered on the USS Coronado was
essential to new types of warfare, he said. ``It lifts the fog of
war,'' he said of the high-tech hardware.
</P>
<P>
   The exercises were a follow-up to similar urban warfare
practices in Monterey over the weekend.
</P>
</TEXT>
