<P>
   AMISH-COOKING (New York) _ Amish. For centuries, the word has
been associated with devout religious belief, barn raisings and
Kelly McGillis churning butter for Harrison Ford. Now it has a new
connotation. Just listen to Mark Spangenthal, the chef at the
Screening Room, explaining why he brought his Amish chicken dish
from The Markham, his old restaurant, to the Screening Room:
``There is nothing more American than the word Amish,'' he said.
``I don't want to say sexy. Sexy isn't the right word. But it looks
real nice on the menu.'' By Rick Marin.
</P>
<P>
   WINE-TALK (Las Vegas, Nev.) _ The scene is Aureole, the desert
branch of Charlie Palmer's highly regarded restaurant in New York.
While the original Aureole is elegant and understated, the version
here in the new Mandalay Bay Hotel is, well, pure Las Vegas. Take
the wine tower. Four stories of stainless steel, glass and
plexiglass, it is a wine cellar in reverse, soaring 42 feet over
the bar. Clearly the centerpiece of the restaurant, it holds _ and
dramatically displays _ some 9,000 bottles of wine. Move over,
Paris. Move over, New York. When it comes to wine, at this moment,
Las Vegas is the place to be. By Frank J. Prial.
</P>
<P>
   With
</P>
<P>
   WINE-TASTING (Undated) _ A capsule wine review.
