<DOCNO> NYT19990316.0134 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-16 15:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2423 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JOURNAL-RUSSIA-0317-C     03-16 0801
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JOURNAL-RUSSIA-0317-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    JOURNAL: SOME THINGS STILL WORK, EVEN IF RUSSIA DOESN'T
 &HT;    With Photo Mug of Holmes.
 &HT;    Moving in both the International and Commentary categories.
 &HT;    By CHARLES W. HOLMES 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Since the economy crashed and burned last August, it
has not been easy to find good news to report from Russia's
capital.
</P>
<P>
   But as winter delivers its last punches in the next few weeks,
now let us praise a few things that -- well, let's be blunt here --
that actually WORK WELL in Russia.
</P>
<P>
   Operating in a market economy may give Russians a fit, but
operating in a blizzard is ``byez problemah'' -- without a care.
Russia has to struggle to find its way in the post-Cold War world;
there is no such identity crisis in the everyday routine of coping
with winter.
</P>
<P>
   Armies of snow removal trucks deploy on the roads day and night
to clean the streets while the extensive Moscow subway system
handles millions of riders a day.
</P>
<P>
   And the centralized heating system works so well that on some
winter days it may be sub-zero outside while it is
shorts-and-t-shirt weather inside your apartment.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the United States, where snowstorms are tracked by armies
of meteorologists and television bulletins offering alarming
updates of snowfall amounts and school closings, there is no such
panic in Russia.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the weather rarely makes the news here. Beginning in
late October or early November, the weather outlook goes something
like this: Today, it is definitely going to be cold and will
probably snow. Tomorrow, ditto. And on and on until April.
</P>
<P>
   Here's the good news: This city of 12 million is never really
paralyzed by winter. Sure, urban traffic crawls, as it does most
all the time, summer or winter. But snowfall rarely brings school
closings and flight delays.
</P>
<P>
   History attests to Russia's proficiency at dealing with winter.
It helped Moscow repel the armies of Napoleon and Hitler. Winter is
an old friend, the subject of affection and only a few complaints.
It never keeps a Russian from getting to work, school, the
unemployment office.
</P>
<P>
   This harmony with winter is as old as Russia itself and an
integral part of the national character. But the systems in Moscow
for coping are thanks in large part to Soviets.
</P>
<P>
   The 1917 Bolshevik Revolution and the Communist regimes that
followed industrialized what had been a country of peasant farmers.
Many of these new factory workers came to live in the cities. And
happy workers needed a way to get to work, and a warm apartment at
the end of the day.
</P>
<P>
   The Soviets built an impressive, efficient subway system and a
network of central heating stations that provide hot water and
steam heat to every apartment building.
</P>
<P>
   They also made sure the roads were clean, for the party
hierarchy zipping around in their black limousines -- and also for
the bread trucks to make their deliveries to keep those workers
happy.
</P>
<P>
   All these systems still work today, heavily subsidized by the
local and federal governments. Then, as now, they remain important
to maintaining the social order in difficult times.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our budget is bad,'' explained Gennady Krapivny, a senior city
official, ``but we keep everything normal.''
</P>
<P>
   This winter, it has snowed more days than not. Every 24 hours,
more than 6,800 snowplows, trucks and other machines are operated
by more than 15,000 workers to remove snow from Moscow streets.
</P>
<P>
   There are also about 40,000 men and women under the direction of
local councils who are given shovels and dispatched to clear
streets, sidewalks and trolley-bus rails. Between Nov. 1 and April
15, the city will have spread nearly 300,000 tons of salt on the
icy streets and moved mountains of snow, which it trucks away to
deposit in the Moscow River.
</P>
<P>
   Today, there are 2.5 million cars in Moscow, a more than 10-fold
increase in 10 years. But of course, most people in this city are
not driving to work. Nine million people a day are riding the
subway.
</P>
<P>
   The people in charge of the Moscow Metro, its 160 stations and
163 miles of track, view their system as the lifeblood of the city.
</P>
<P>
   The Bolsheviks directed metro builders to remove ornate tiles
and artwork from the homes of the imperial-era upper classes to
decorate the ``people's houses'' -- the subway stations. They
remain places of grandeur, and a one-way fare remains at a level
the proletariat would like -- about 17 cents.
</P>
<P>
   The system is rundown and operates at a huge deficit, but
between 6 a.m. and 1 a.m., it remains the swiftest and most
reliable way around the city.
</P>
<P>
   Even if, after the economic crisis last August, more Muscovites
today have no job to go to.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
