A2448 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRIVIA-Q&AMP;A-TEX     03-16 0435
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRIVIA-Q&AMP;A-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO FOOTBALL PLAYERS HAVE BEEN OPEN ABOUT BEING GAY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROGERS CADENHEAD 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: Are there any self-described gay people on a pro football
team?
</P>
<P>
   _ D.M., Fort Worth
</P>
<P>
   A: No gay NFL players have discussed the subject publicly.
``Dave Kopay is the only former NFL player to be open about his
sexuality,'' said Dan Woog, author of ``Jocks: True Stories of
America's Gay Male Athletes.''
</P>
<P>
   Agent Leigh Steinberg told New Republic in 1998, ``Frankly, it
would be easier for someone convicted of bank robbery to get a job
in the NFL than an overtly gay player.''
</P>
<P>
   The late Glenn Burke, Major League Baseball's first openly gay
player, believed that teams were unwilling to sign him because of
it.
</P>
<P>
   Kopay openly discussed his sexuality after retiring in 1975.
``The David Kopay Story,'' a book he wrote with Perry Deane Young,
describes the experiences of several gay players in the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think most people don't give the public _ even the sporting
public _ enough credit for being fair and open-minded, even about
something as controversial as homosexuality,'' Woog said.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Where can I write to have a birthday card or greeting from
the president sent to a senior citizen celebrating a 100th
birthday?
</P>
<P>
   _ J.K., Fort Worth
</P>
<P>
   A: The White House Greeting Office sends out cards recognizing
birthdays 80 and up, and wedding anniversaries 50 and up.
</P>
<P>
   Send requests to The White House, Attn: Greeting Office, Room
39, Washington, D.C. 20502; or fax a request to (202) 395-1232.
</P>
<P>
   You should request a card at least six weeks before the event.
The Greeting Office mails cards 10 days prior to the occasion.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How can a person become a contestant on ``Hollywood
Squares''?
</P>
<P>
   _ F.H., Fort Worth
</P>
<P>
   A: If you're going to be in Los Angeles, call the ``Hollywood
Squares'' Contestant Department at (323) 850-0707 to arrange an
interview.
</P>
<P>
   ``Squares'' is open to anyone 18 and up who has not appeared on
a game show in the past year and isn't affiliated with CBS or other
companies involved in the production. The show does not pay any
travel or hotel expenses for contestants.
</P>
<P>
   To request tickets to see a taping, write to Guest Relations,
CBS Television City, 7800 Beverly Blvd., Los Angeles, CA 90036.
</P>
<P>
   (Rogers Cadenhead writes a trivia column for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. He can be reached at the Star-Telegram, Box 1870,
Fort Worth, Texas 76101; or by E-mail at trivia(at)prefect.com.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
