<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-MEDICARE (Washington) _ The national commission weighing
ways to overhaul the Medicare system prepares to adjourn without
reaching a consensus on ways to bolster the health program for the
elderly. President Clinton rejects one proposal supported by both
the Democratic and Republicans leaders of the commission. By GREG
McDONALD.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-RICHARDSON (Washington) _ Energy Secretary Bill Richardson
tells a Senate panel the administration has taken numerous steps to
tighten security in the wake of allegations that a U.S. weapons
scientist gave nuclear secrets to China. The extent of the damage
from the spying won't be known until the CIA completes its probe
next month, he says. By ERIC ROSENBERG.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-AFRICA (Washington) _ Calling for a new partnership with
Africa to promote economic development, President Clinton urges
widespread debt-relief for African nations. In a speech opening a
U.S.-Africa ministerial meeting in Washington, Clinton urged the
international community to forgive an estimated $70 billion loaned
mostly to poverty-stricken African countries. By JOHN C. HENRY.
</P>
<P>
   CHILD-CARE (Washington)_ House Democrats push for a boost in
federal funding for day care and higher tax credits for
moderate-income families with children. By JENNIFER CORBETT DOOREN.
</P>
<P>
   INS-BUDGET (Washington) _ Sen. Kay Bailey Hutchison, R-Texas,
criticizes an Immigration and Naturalization Service plan not to
hire more Border Patrol agents as the Senate Appropriations
Committee reviews budget requests for next year. By STEVE LASH.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   FORBES-2000 (Concord, N.H.) _ Already running in cyberspace,
Steve Forbes appears in person at a New Hampshire rally to announce
his campaign for the Republican presidential nomination in 2000.
The magazine publisher had used his Internet site to kick off his
second bid for the nomination. By BENNETT ROTH.
</P>
<P>
   BUDGET-TEXAS (Austin, Texas) _ Texas lawmakers writing the state
budget and another group contemplating tax-relief proposals are on
a collision course over how to divvy up a projected surplus of at
least $2.5 billion, key legislators said. Gov. George W. Bush is
waiting anxiously for the outcome. By JOHN GONZALEZ.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MEANS-COLUMN (Washington) _ Lamar Alexander, who has been
campaigning for two years, made it official last week that he is
running for the 2000 Republican presidential nomination. He's just
a blip in the polls, and his anti-Washington message is stale. So
why is he running? By MARIANNE MEANS.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BKN-ROCKETS (Houston) _ The Houston Rockets play host to the
Portland Trail Blazers, a team that beat them by 40 points nine
days ago. By JONATHAN FEIGEN.
</P>
<P>
   With: BKN-ROBERTSON-COLUMN
</P>
<P>
   BKC-KENTUCKY (Undated) _ Kentucky is two victories away from its
fourth consecutive Final Four, and senior guard Wayne Turner has a
chance to become the first non-Duke player ever to reach four
straight NCAA tournaments. By TERRY BLOUNT.
</P>
<P>
   FBN-NFL-OWNERS (Phoenix) _ NFL owners are expected to grant an
expansion team to either Houston or Los Angeles. Reports indicate
that Los Angeles may be granted a six-month deadline to come up
with an acceptable bid. If it fails to do so, then Houston will be
awarded the expansion team. By JOHN WILLIAMS.
</P>
<P>
   With: FBN-LOPEZ-COLUMN
</P>
<P>
   BBN-ASTROS (Kissimmee, Fla.) _ Sean Bergman came out of nowhere
to emerge as a solid starter and 12-game winner for the Houston
Astros last season, yet this spring he keeps hearing that he is on
trading block. By JOSEPH DUARTE.
</P>
