<HEADER>
A2469 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AFFIRMATIVE-ACTION-HN     03-16 0574
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AFFIRMATIVE-ACTION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MINORITY ADMISSIONS PLUMMET AT SAN FRANCISCO SCHOOL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JULIAN GUTHRIE  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The number of blacks and Hispanics accepted into
San Francisco's most prestigious public high school for the coming
year plummeted 50 percent from fall 1998, raising serious questions
about how to maintain diversity without using race in admissions.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, offers to Chinese-American and white students
has jumped considerably at Lowell High, one of the top public
schools in California.
</P>
<P>
   The changing demographics of the school are the result of a
settlement reached in February that bars the city's public schools
from using race as a factor in admissions. The Lowell numbers show
the formidable challenge the district faces as it wades tentatively
into an era of color-blind admissions.
</P>
<P>
   Prevented from considering race or ethnicity, the district hoped
to maintain diversity at Lowell by awarding extra points to
students from low-income and otherwise disadvantaged families.
Lowell is the only high school in the district to require an
admissions test.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time, the school district gave bonus points to
Lowell applicants who come from single-parent families, augmenting
a system of points already in place taking economic hardship into
account.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of helping blacks and Hispanics, however, the points
system made more Chinese-American and white students eligible.
</P>
<P>
   Lowell makes between 825 and 850 offers for freshman admission
every year, and 600 to 625 students generally accept.
</P>
<P>
   Of the offers made to students for fall 1999, 65.3 percent went
to Asian-Americans, 26.97 percent to whites, 5.4 percent to
Hispanics and 1.97 percent to blacks.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Asian-Americans received 58.8 percent of the offers,
whites received 23.57 percent, Hispanics received 11.41 percent and
blacks received 5.57 percent.
</P>
<P>
   According to the terms of the February settlement, the
62,000-student district has until Sept. 20 to craft a new
enrollment plan that will govern all schools beginning in the fall
of 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are working on finding ways to continue diversity in our
schools,'' said Jennie Horn, who oversees Lowell admissions. ``It's
very tricky. We're doing number crunching and simulations and
studies. With Lowell, we tried every which angle, incorporating
every factor other than race.''
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco PTA President Carol Kocivar, a member of the
Lowell admissions committee, said relying on social and economic
factors to increase enrollment of blacks and Hispanics wasn't
enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``The district and the community must work very hard to help
youngsters become eligible,'' Kocivar said. ``That means starting
from the beginning. If we don't have these kids in the 50th
percentile by the third grade, we can't expect them to be
Lowell-eligible by the eighth grade.''
</P>
<P>
   From 1983 until last month, San Francisco's public schools were
governed by a federal consent decree requiring them to enroll
students through a rigid racial formula: No more than 45 percent of
students at any school could be of one race, and at least four
ethnic groups had to be represented at each school.
</P>
<P>
   Chinese-American families filed suit to overturn the 1983
formula because their children were being kept out of prized
schools, notably Lowell, due to the racial quota system.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-16-99 1613EST &QL; 
