A2473 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-TEX     03-16 0727
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AND NEXT: AL GORE'S PLAN TO MAKE LIVER TASTE LIKE CHOCOLATE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BILL THOMPSON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Isn't Al Gore the guy who was supposed to reinvent government?
The guy who was supposed to take a hatchet to the federal
bureaucracy? The guy who inspired one of President Clinton's
boldest declarations: ``The era of big government has ended''?
</P>
<P>
   The very same.
</P>
<P>
   OK, then. Why on earth is Vice President Albert ``Slash the
Government'' Gore popping up on television every day to tout some
new government program that is guaranteed to spur the economy,
promote world peace, cure cancer and eliminate tooth decay?
</P>
<P>
   Because he's running for president, that's why.
</P>
<P>
   Look, folks. Gore has spent the last six years laboring in the
shadow of the most controversial president in memory. He may not
want to admit it, but the vice president is desperate to raise his
profile.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't feel like I'm in a shadow,'' Gore told some TV
interviewer the other day. But that sounded about as sincere as his
claim that there was ``no controlling legal authority'' prohibiting
his use of White House telephones for political fund-raising.
</P>
<P>
   Of course Gore labors in the president's shadow; that's what
vice presidents are supposed to do.
</P>
<P>
   Gore has been loyal to a fault, defending Clinton in the face of
allegation after allegation, scandal after scandal. The former
Tennessee senator went so far as to predict at the president's
post-impeachment pep rally in December that William Jefferson
Clinton would be remembered as one of America's greatest
presidents.
</P>
<P>
   He said it with a straight face, too. But then, Gore says
everything with a straight face. ``Expressiveness'' is not the
first word that comes to mind when making an inventory of Gore's
political assets.
</P>
<P>
   Heck, it's not one of the first 50 words that come to mind.
</P>
<P>
   Gore won his reputation as a humorless stiff the first time he
ran for president, way back in 1988. It's a reputation that has
followed him through two more national campaigns and his entire
tour of duty as Clinton's right-hand man.
</P>
<P>
   Gore will never be able to dazzle voters with his charisma, so
he is hoping to delight them with his ability to get things done.
</P>
<P>
   Which is why he seems to be on CNN every time we turn around:
going to bat for frustrated air travelers one day, announcing new
labeling requirements for over-the-counter medicines the next _ and
all the while assuring the electorate that his vision for America
is superior to the visions being espoused by the one other Democrat
and the herd of Republicans who covet Clinton's job.
</P>
<P>
   This program-a-day business used to be the president's domain,
most news junkies recall, but that was when he needed a daily
diversion to get the public's collective mind off impeachment. If
the scandal started heating up, Clinton would concoct some new
government initiative, step in front of the cameras to announce it,
and then boast that he was focusing on the people's business while
his enemies engaged in the politics of personal destruction.
</P>
<P>
   You don't keep those 60 to 70 percent job-approval ratings by
staring out the window all day long.
</P>
<P>
   With impeachment behind him, Clinton now can afford to fly
around on Air Force One and leave the daily unveiling of new
programs to Gore _ who has been hard pressed to get his name in the
paper lately except as a projected loser to Republicans George W.
Bush and Elizabeth Dole in those 2000 presidential preference
polls.
</P>
<P>
   The 2000 election is a long way off, needless to say, and there
are any number of scenarios that might transform Gore from underdog
to winner by the time voters go to the polls. To his credit, the
vice president is steady as a rock _ which figures, since he has
the personality of a rock _ and thus isn't likely to make any
catastrophic, self-destructive mistakes.
</P>
<P>
   He has a problem, though: If Gore keeps inventing government
programs to get himself on television, the Republican who takes him
on will rip him to shreds for wiping out the budget surplus that he
and Clinton have been bragging about.
</P>
<P>
   (Bill Thompson is a columnist for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can contact him at (817) 390-7787. Visit the Star-Telegram's
online services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
