<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TASTE-CHAI-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>


</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  EDITORS NOTE: Each week, The San Francisco Chronicle's panel of
professional tasters tries a different product available in
supermarkets.  
 
 
 TASTER'S CHOICE: Too Many Spices Spoil the Chai 
 &HT;       
 By Robin Davis  
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; SAN FRANCISCO _  &LR; Once Starbucks started serving it, chai tea
officially became mainstream. So it's no wonder the Indian spiced
tea has been showing up on grocery shelves.
<P>
   But just where it shows up is a mystery, unique to every store.
Some place it beside soft drinks and bottled water; others put it
in the coffee-and-tea aisle. Still others keep it in the
refrigerator case, even though some of the teas are shelf-stable.
</P>
<P>
   Equally as varied are the tastes. Today's panel tasted seven
brands of chai tea, and the results were mixed.
</P>
<P>
   Each brand was made according to package directions. All but one
recommend being heated and mixed with different amounts of steamed
milk, though the drink also may be served cold.
</P>
<P>
   The top scorer was &UR; Oregon Chai &LR;  (32 ounces, $4.49-$6.39 at many
supermarkets). One panelist described it as ``very restorative and
comforting.'' Most panelists liked the combination of spices, but
one dissenter thought too many spices created a medicinal flavor.
Four would buy it; one would not.
</P>
<P>
   Second place went to  &UR; Tazo  &LR; (32 ounces, $5.29 at Andronico's).
Two panelists thought is was mild _ one referred to it as ``sort of
a Wonder bread approach.'' But all but one panelist liked the blend
of spices. Four would buy it; one would not.
</P>
<P>
   Scores on the remaining brands dropped significantly. The best
of the rest was  &UR; Toddy &LR;  (12 ounces, $3.99 at Trader Joe's), though
panelists were divided. Two panelists thought it had good tea
flavor, another thought it tasted too strongly of tea. Others were
put off by the gray color. One would buy it, two might buy it and
two would not.
</P>
<P>
   Fourth place went to  &UR; Sattwa Chai &LR;  (32 ounces, $4.39 at Rainbow
Grocery). Three panelists disliked the overly sweet flavor and the
heavy use of spice, but another panelist thought the drink was
nicely spiced. Two might buy it; three would not.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Celestial Seasonings &LR;  (32 ounces, $5.99 at Andronico's) scored
just one point lower than Sattwa. Two panelists complained about
the bitter taste, and others thought it was too heavily spiced. One
panelist compared the flavor to pumpkin pie. One would buy it; four
would not.
</P>
<P>
   Honest Tea Kashmiri Chai and Masala Chai Co. scored too low to
rate.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Panelists were Dan Bowe, associate culinary director, Center for
Culinary Development; Jon P. Carroll, cookbook author; Donna Katzl,
chef-owner, Cafe For All Seasons, San Francisco; Roland Passot,
chef-owner, La Folie in San Francisco and Left Bank in Larkspur and
Menlo Park; and Kirk Webber, chef-owner, Cafe Kati, San Francisco.
All products are tasted blind.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-16-99 1623EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
