<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOURCE-RADIS-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>


</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
 
EDITORS NOTE: This column profiles Northern California growers,
anglers and artisans who make the region such a culinary
wonderland. Over the next few months, we'll take you from field to
forest to factory to look at the wealth of ingredients stocking our
larders. As a bonus, ``Georgeanne Brennan will offer tips for using
the bounty in fresh, innovative ways.  AT THE SOURCE: Radishes Make Organic Grower's World Go 'Round  
   
   
 By Karola Saekel  
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
   
   
 SAN FRANCISCO _  Quick mental association with the word radish:
cute little red sphere decorating deli trays; may or may not be
eaten.
 &HT;    Well, think again. There is the granddaddy of them all _ sturdy
white daikon, a mainstay of Japanese cuisine, which can grow to a
foot and a half; black Spanish radish (black on the outside, creamy
white inside), much favored by Eastern Europeans; mild icicles,
both white and red, or white French breakfast radishes that are
particularly favored alongside soft-ripened cheeses.
 &HT;    How about a radish weighing a full pound? Watermelon radishes
can get that big without turning woody. These roots (the word
radish comes from radix, the Latin word for root) have greenish
skin and crimson- and white-ringed interiors that make them real
lookers when sliced. Their taste goes from sweet to spicy, says
Andy Martin, sales manager at Lakeside Organic Gardens in
Watsonville, a major supplier to local markets and restaurants.
 &HT;    Lakeside is the organic spin-off of a major conventional grower,
Dick Peixoto Co., and cultivates 600 acres of certified organic
produce. The farm adds 100 acres a year, so by the end of 1999, 700
acres will be planted. (Certification comes after three years and a
long paper trail of organic practice.)
 &HT;    Radishes are a secondary crop (lettuces, broccoli and
cauliflower are main crops), says Lakeside manager Terence Welch,
but one or the other kind of radish is harvested year-round. Trucks
loaded with hundreds of boxes of radishes roll out of the farm
three times a week, destined for such stores as Draeger's,
Cosentino's, Whole Foods and the Santa Cruz area's New Leaf
markets. Even with this heavy local consumption, Welsh says, more
than half the crop travels east of the Rockies.
 &HT;    Watsonville, home to several radish growers, boasts ideal
conditions for radishes _ sandy loam and lots of water. The climate
also allows weekly planting throughout the year.
 &HT;    Martin, a former chef in Aptos, says many restaurants have
discovered that radishes are far more than a spot of color for the
crudite tray. Chefs are serving them with butter and sea salt for
an appetizer, incorporating them into stir-fries or making them the
main ingredient of salads.
 &HT;    Radishes have been staples in European, Middle Eastern and Asian
cuisines for centuries (their cultivation is believed to have
started thousands of years ago in China, from where they traveled
to Egypt and Greece). Now, it seems, the pungent subterranean
treasures are finding their place in the sun of American menus.
 &HT;     
(BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIMS) 
 
 
 GEORGEANNE'S KITCHEN  _ Cool Ways to Use Crisp Radishes &HT;     
 
By Georgeanne Brennan 
c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Radishes of all kinds, and even their greens, may be used in
numerous ways. Here are just a few ideas:
<P>
   &UR; Tunisian-Style Roasted Pepper and Radish Salad.  &LR; Roast, peel
and seed 1 or 2 poblano chile peppers, then slice into very fine
strips. Cut 5 or 6 French breakfast or round red radishes into very
thin slices.
</P>
<P>
   Toss the peppers with olive oil, vinegar, salt, pepper and a bit
of cayenne pepper. Arrange on a plate and top with a mixture of
chopped cilantro and parsley. Top with the radishes and drizzle
with a little olive oil.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; French Radish Plate &LR; . Choose tender young radishes, such as
French Breakfast, round red, purple, Easter Egg. Leave the young,
bright green leaves attached. Arrange them on a plate, along with a
ramekin of kosher salt and a small pot of unsalted butter. Serve
with slices of country-style bread for an appetizer.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Watermelon Radish and Pork Stir-Fry &LR; . Make a mixture of about 1
tablespoon cornstarch with an equal amount of water, a little soy
sauce and some dry sherry.
</P>
<P>
   Put cubed pork in a bowl and pour in the cornstarch mixture,
gently turning to coat. Let stand for 1 hour.
</P>
<P>
   Cut watermelon radishes into 1/2-inch cubes. Clean and coarsely
chop some spinach. Mince 2 or 3 garlic cloves.
</P>
<P>
   Heat a little oil in a wok. Add the garlic and radishes;
stir-fry until the radishes are tender, about 3 or 4 minutes.
Remove and set aside.
</P>
<P>
   Using a slotted spoon, transfer the pork to the wok and stir-fry
1 to 2 minutes. Return the radishes and garlic, add the spinach and
stir-fry until the spinach is just limp. Pour in any remaining
cornstarch mixture, and add a heaping spoonful of black bean and
garlic sauce; stirring to combine.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Black Radish Appetizer &LR; . Peel and grate a black radish or two.
Spread thin slices of chewy, dark bread with butter. Top with the
grated radish. Serve with iced vodka or slivovitz.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Spring Rolls with Radishes &LR; . Crush 5 or 6 garlic cloves and put
them in a bowl with red wine vinegar. Let stand for at least 1 hour
and up to overnight.
</P>
<P>
   Grate red, purple or daikon radishes. Grate carrots. Sliver
green onions.
</P>
<P>
   Saute minced garlic and ginger in oil, then stir in the radishes
and carrots, cooking only a moment or two. Sprinkle with a little
salt.
</P>
<P>
   Spread open a spring roll wrapper and fill with the
radish-carrot mixture. Add slivers of green onion and roll up
according to package directions. Fry in oil until crisp and golden,
about 2 minutes on each side. Remove to paper towels to drain.
</P>
<P>
   To serve, cut a slit lengthwise in each roll and spoon in a
little of the garlic vinegar.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Georgeanne Brennan, a food and garden writer who lives in Yolo
County, is the author of ``Aperitif'' and ``The Food and Flavors of
Haute Provence.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
THE LOWDOWN ON RADISHES &QL; 
 &QL; 
Radishes are part of the family of cruciferous vegetables (which
includes broccoli), which are believed to have cancer-inhibiting
properties. They are extremely low in calories (17 for one cup of
sliced radishes, which supplies about one-third the daily
requirement of vitamin C).
</P>
<P>
   Radishes keep up to a week in the refrigerator if you remove the
greens (use those as a salad ingredient if they are fresh). If a
radish such as the black Spanish is too pungent for your liking,
peeling it will leave you with only the much milder interior.
</P>
<P>
   Large, long white radishes are a staple in Bavarian beer
gardens, where regulars compete in carving them into paper-thin
spirals. The layers are liberally sprinkled with salt and pressed
back together to be eaten in big bites as a companion to a stein of
ice-cold beer.
</P>
<P>
   Andy Martin of Lakeside Organic Gardens, a Watsonville grower of
radishes, says radishes of all kinds make a pleasantly crunchy
addition to stir-fries. A former restaurant chef, Martin also
recommends a salad in which sliced or shredded radishes are dressed
with sesame oil and rice vinegar, seasoned with salt and pepper to
taste and sprinkled with toasted sesame seeds.
</P>
<P>
   _ Karola Saekel
</P>
</TEXT>
