<HEADLINE>
IT WASN'T THAT HARD TO SEE THAT NCAA REQUIREMENTS WERE A PROBLEM
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CECIL JOHNSON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Some people have a devil of a time with their ``I-told-you-so''
reflex.
</P>
<P>
   When something happens that validates some position they once
took or some prediction they made, they can't resist crowing about
it.
</P>
<P>
   I'm not that kind of person. But it's clear that I was right all
along about the NCAA's Proposition 48 and its misbegotten
offspring, Proposition 16.
</P>
<P>
   Now comes U.S. District Judge Ronald L. Buckwalter and gives
that elitist, discriminatory and hypocritical baggage the legal
heave-ho. The case against the National Collegiate Athletic
Association was so overwhelming that Buckwalter didn't even see the
necessity for a trial. He just ruled ``no.'' He said, in effect,
that the eligibility standards for freshmen should not remain in
effect because they are grossly unfair to African-American athletes
and athletes from low-income families.
</P>
<P>
   Nor did Buckwalter mince his words. In fact, he used the NCAA's
own words and data to condemn its freshmen eligibility policy. He
cited a July 27, 1998, memo dispatched by NCAA officials to
Division I member schools, documenting the fact that
``African-American and low-income student-athletes are
disproportionately impacted'' by the grade point and standardized
test score requirements.
</P>
<P>
   In plain English, he means that those categories of student
athletes are getting the short end of the stick.
</P>
<P>
   Well, if that isn't a kick in the old elitist keister. The judge
sees in a flash that the standards are unfair. The NCAA has known
it for some time. And some people, most notably members of the
Black Coaches Association, tried to tell the NCAA that before
Proposition 48 became unholy writ in 1986.
</P>
<P>
   But no one had any data before the fact with which to counter
the powers that be in the NCAA, who were infernally bent on
pursuing that folly. And it took a boycott by Georgetown University
basketball coach John Thompson in 1989 to persuade the NCAA to
jettison the infamous Proposition 42.
</P>
<P>
   That proposition would have denied financial aid to athletes
forced to sit out their freshman year because they failed to meet
Proposition 48 standards.
</P>
<P>
   In 1992, the NCAA proceeded to make matters worse by racheting
up the standards with the overlay of Proposition 16. Proposition 48
imposed a minimum 2.0 grade point average and a 700 SAT score or a
17 ACT score. Proposition 16 imposed a sliding scale that would be
based upon a 2.5 GPA combined with either a 700 SAT or a 17 ACT. An
athlete with a 2.0 GPA would need a 900 SAT or a 21 ACT to be
eligible.
</P>
<P>
   Proposition 16 went into effect in 1996. In 1997, four
Philadelphia high school athletes sued the NCAA, asserting that
NCAA rules that effectively prevented them from getting athletic
scholarships were discriminatory.
</P>
<P>
   It is on the basis of that lawsuit that Buckwalter has issued
his historic ruling. If there is any justice in this matter, his
ruling will provide appropriate relief to others besides those
plaintiffs.
</P>
<P>
   This case should be given class-action status. And every athlete
still in college who was among those ``disproportionately
impacted'' by the NCAA's discriminatory rules should at the very
least have a year of eligibility restored.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the final outcome of this case, the NCAA's way of
determining initial eligibility will have to change. That will be
the case, even if the NCAA prevails on appeal. The statistical
evidence of unfairness is too overwhelming.
</P>
<P>
   Some prominent nonblack coaches already have been saying as
much. Among them is Mike Krzyzewski, Duke University basketball
coach and president of the National Association of Basketball
Coaches.
</P>
<P>
   Krzyzewski said in reaction to Buckwalter's ruling that the NABC
has long been concerned about how the minimum test score would
affect youths from lower socioeconomic backgrounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``This court ruling will certainly open a new discussion for
creating better legislation for all youngsters,'' Krzyzewski said.
</P>
<P>
   Giving credit where it's due, the NCAA appeared to have had good
intentions in installing Propositions 48 and 16. There was a lot of
genuine concern about unacceptably high numbers of collegiate
athletes failing to graduate.
</P>
<P>
   Some, however, suggested that another objective of the standards
was to increase the percentage of white athletes participating in
NCAA programs and decrease the numbers of African-Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Although I never subscribed to that school of thought, I can
understand why such suspicions arose. It was obvious even then that
the eligibility standards favored white athletes from affluent
backgrounds. The standardized tests on which they rely too heavily
are culturally and class biased.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than fight Buckwalter's ruling, the NCAA needs to move as
quickly as possible to enact fair initial eligibility criteria. The
appeal is a waste of time and money and an insult to the student
athletes and former student athletes who were injured by the bogus
rules.
</P>
<P>
   (Cecil Johnson is a columnist and editorial writer for the Fort
Worth Star-Telegram. You can e-mail him at
cecil(at)star-telegram.com or call him at (817) 390-7663. Visit the
Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
