<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CUSTARD-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON   Not Your Grandmother's Custard  
 Bay Area chefs dress up a homespun favorite in jazzy new guises 
 &HT;       
   
 By Karola Saekel  
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; SAN FRANCISCO _ &LR;  Call it a new indulgence, a craving for comforting
food or maybe a backlash against one too many plates artfully
adorned with two al dente baby carrots.
<P>
   Whatever the reason, chefs and their customers are succumbing to
the soothing, silky _ even sexy _ seduction of custards, flans,
timbales or whatever name you care to attach to a baked concoction
of eggs and milk (or cream), enhanced with whatever strikes a
cook's fancy.
</P>
<P>
   Whereas in the early '90s, it was cr &LR; e &LR; me brul &LR; e &LR; e, that
seductively silky dessert chefs flavored with the likes of designer
chocolate, mango puree, lavender blossoms and more, that took
custard out of the nursery-food category, now savory custards are
in the spotlight.
</P>
<P>
   If the trend was slowly simmering for a couple of years, it came
to a spectacular boil when Ron Siegel, the talented 32-year-old
chef of Charles Nob Hill restaurant in San Francisco, stunned his
culinary cohorts by becoming the first American chef to score a
knockout victory (unanimous decision by all four judges) in Japan's
glitz-for-gluttons Iron Chef television competition last fall
(televised here in mid-January).
</P>
<P>
   Faced with the formidable task of creating _ in 60 minutes _ a
complete meal based on a secret theme ingredient revealed to the
competitors at the start of the show (live lobster, in this case),
Siegel started his menu with a lobster custard _ and wowed the
judges.
</P>
<P>
   He has prepared that international attention-getter for his Nob
Hill customers a few times since, but it's not his only custard
caper. As a bouche amus &LR; e &LR; e _ the complimentary appetizer top
restaurants present to tease guests' gustatory expectations _ he
sometimes bakes a simple mushroom custard in empty eggshells. As
delicious as they are fetching, these are great starters for an
Easter brunch or dinner, and it's not a project of Iron Chef
complexity. If a home cook doesn't have the time to prepare the
eggshells, he/she can always cheat a tad and bake the custards in
paper-lined muffin tins.
</P>
<P>
   At San Francisco's Grand Cafe, Denis Soriano also has made room
on his menu for savory custards. He gives a crispy,
mahogany-colored roasted chicken breast taste and color contrast
with beet-red molded basmati rice and a smooth little mound of
spinach custard. Venison's complementary companion is a woodsy
chestnut custard.
</P>
<P>
   At Oakland's Bay Wolf, chef/owner Michael Wild, the master of
duck cookery, features an appetizer of duck liver flan with pickled
onions and grilled bread.
</P>
<P>
   Ten or 15 years ago, these items would not have been found on
American restaurant menus. Eighty years ago, they would have been
commonplace. Leaf through the ``Hotel St. Francis Cook Book''
(published in 1919), in which Victor Hirtzler, San Francisco's
first celebrity chef, gives a year's worth of his menus, and you'll
find savory egg-cream dishes almost daily at lunch or dinner _ or
both.
</P>
<P>
   In 19th century American and British cookbooks, savory puddings
were staples. ``The American Frugal Housewife,'' by a Mrs. Child,
published in 1832, amusingly distinguishes between country and city
dwellers in its recipe for batter pudding. Country folk are told to
``beat up five or six eggs with a quart of milk, and a little salt,
with flour enough to make it just thick enough to pour without
difficulty. Those who live in the city, and are obliged to buy
eggs, can do with three eggs to a quart, and more flour in
proportion. Boil about three quarters of an hour.''
</P>
<P>
   This was meant to be a filling starch dish. Some modern chefs
use savory puddings much the same way, if with a bit more
sophistication than boiling a flour-egg-milk gruel on the stove.
</P>
<P>
   At One Market in San Francisco, chef Rabah Abusbaitan says the
revival of savory custards is a natural outgrowth of the new
popularity of old-fashioned dessert custards like cr &LR; e &LR; me brul &LR; e &LR; e
and cr &LR; e &LR; me caramel. The latter was his favorite sweet his mother
cooked when he was a boy in Jerusalem. Now he heightens the
richness of lobster bisque with an aromatic basil flan. He also
favors the rich smoothness of custard with such robust dishes as
roasted lamb, which he pairs with a white bean custard.
</P>
<P>
   Philippe Striffeler of Anzu in the Nikko Hotel in San Francisco
is fond of a custardy mushroom bread pudding to accompany the
restaurant's signature prime steaks. The custard works equally well
with veal, chicken and pork, he says _ ``anything except fish.''
</P>
<P>
   Custards fit into the trend of home-style foods gaining on
supertrendy concoctions, Striffeler says.
</P>
<P>
   He would not get an argument from Elka Gilmore of San
Francisco's Oodles, who serves a subtle roasted garlic flan with
Western-style food and an intricate steamed chawan mushi as part of
her fusion tasting menu. A free-form interpretation of the
traditional Japanese dish, chawan mushi is made of duck consomme,
eggs, chicken confit, scallops, gingko nuts and shiso leaves, with
dashi (Japanese stock) adding a smoky note.
</P>
<P>
   Not your grandmother's custard, Gilmore would readily admit. But
she feels these dishes fit the zeitgeist of the late '90s _ a
peculiar mix of comfort and sophistication to which diners respond.
Gone, she says, are the days, a dozen or so years ago, when people
came to upscale restaurants to be seen rather than nourished.
</P>
<P>
   Today's savvy restaurant patron, she says, wants to go beyond
``something grilled with mango/chile.'' The new diner appreciates
nuances of cuisine and isn't afraid of the occasional indulgence,
including, she says, a ``divinely rich'' savory custard.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
(BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIMS) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Tips for Making Perfect Custard &QL; 
 &QL; 
Savory custards and their cousins, bread puddings and timbales, are
not difficult or labor-intensive to make (Irma Rombauer in ``The
Joy of Cooking'' called timbales the more even-tempered cousins of
souffles). But there are a few simple facts to bear in mind for
optimum results:
</P>
<P>
   _ Having all ingredients at warm room temperature ensures even
cooking. If eggs are refrigerator cold, place them in a large bowl
of lukewarm water for 10 minutes before cracking them. This is also
important if a recipe calls for whipping egg whites; they will
reach their maximum volume when they are about 75 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   _ Straining uncooked egg-milk mixtures through a fine sieve is
not strictly necessary but does promote a smooth, silky texture.
</P>
<P>
   _ Never cook custard concoctions at more than medium heat.
Temperatures over 350 degrees will toughen the albumin (protein) of
eggs, resulting in tough curds and a watery texture, since the
protein can no longer absorb liquids.
</P>
<P>
   _ For the same reasons, custards are baked in a bath of hot but
not boiling water (hot tap water is safe) which helps diffuse heat.
</P>
<P>
   _ Another way to avoid watery custards is to blanch or cook
vegetables before adding them to the basic egg-milk (or cream)
mixture. Uncooked vegetables exude too much moisture during baking.
</P>
<P>
   _ When testing for doneness, insert a sharp knife or skewer near
the edge of the dish. If it's done there, residual heat will finish
cooking the center as the dish cools. If you have let the custard
bake a little too long and the center is completely set when you
test, remove it from the oven, let stand about 1 minute, then place
the dish in a shallow pan of ice water to stop further cooking.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &LR;   &LR; _ Karola Saekel
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CHARLES NOB HILL MUSHROOM CUSTARDS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   At the restaurant, chef Ron Siegel serves these as an amus &LR; e &LR; e
bouches (complimentary appetizer). They would be a fun addition to
an Easter brunch.
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   12 eggs
</P>
<P>
   1 cup milk
</P>
<P>
   1 cup cream
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup chopped mushrooms, sauteed in 1 tablespoon butter
</P>
<P>
   Salt and white pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Preheat the oven to 275.
</P>
<P>
   Working over a bowl to catch any spills, remove the top quarter
of each eggshell, either with small, sharp shears or by
decapitating the eggs with a determined whack of a chef's knife.
Put the contents of 3 eggshells into a small bowl, whisk to mix;
set aside. Reserve the remaining egg yolks and whites for an omelet
or other use.
</P>
<P>
   Trim the tops of the shells as neatly as possible. Rinse the
shells with hot tap water and carefully remove any membrane. Place
the shells upside down on a drainer tray to dry.
</P>
<P>
   Combine the milk and cream in a saucepan and bring to a boil.
Add the mushrooms and return to a boil. Pour into a blender and
puree on high speed until liquefied. Pour back into the rinsed
saucepan and bring to a boil once more.
</P>
<P>
   Whisk the hot mixture slowly into the 3 beaten eggs. Strain
through a fine sieve. Season the egg mixture with salt and pepper.
</P>
<P>
   Set the cleaned egg shells into the depressions in the bottom
half of a cardboard egg carton; divide the custard mixture among
them. Place the carton in a large baking pan; add enough hot water
to reach the bottom of the eggshells.
</P>
<P>
   Cover loosely with foil and bake for 40 to 45 minutes, until
just set. Remove and cool to room temperature.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR;  Serve in individual egg cups. Garnish with sprigs of
watercress, parsley or dill. You may also carefully crack the
bottom of the shells with a teaspoon, so the shells will stand
upright on a plate.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Note:  &LR; If cooking in the eggshells seems too time consuming,
line 12 small muffin tins with paper liners, divide the custard
mixture among them, place in a shallow pan with 1 inch of hot water
and bake as above. Cool and unmold onto small plates; garnish as
desired.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 12.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 100 calories, &LR;   &LR; 3 g protein, 2 g &LR;   &LR; carbohydrate,
9 g fat (5 g saturated), 80 mg cholesterol, 42 mg &LR;   &LR; sodium, 0 g
fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; ASPARAGUS CUSTARD &QL;  &LR; 
This is a classic custard adapted from Julia Child's original
``Mastering the Art of French Cooking.'' It may be made with other
chopped cooked vegetables such as cauliflower, Brussels sprouts,
broccoli or spinach.
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   1 cup panko or other dry white breadcrumbs
</P>
<P>
   5 tablespoons butter
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup finely minced onion
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   Pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   A few gratings nutmeg
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup grated Swiss or medium-sharp cheddar cheese
</P>
<P>
   5 eggs
</P>
<P>
   1 cup reduced-fat or whole milk, brought to a boil
</P>
<P>
   3 pounds asparagus, tough parts removed, blanched
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 325 degrees. Coat a 6-cup souffle mold or
oven-proof casserole with cooking spray. Coat the inside of the
mold with 1/3 cup of the breadcrumbs, shaking out excess.
</P>
<P>
   Melt 1 tablespoon of the butter in a small saucepan over medium
heat. Add the onions, cover and cook for about 10 minutes, until
translucent but not browned.
</P>
<P>
   Transfer the onions to a large mixing bowl. Add salt, pepper,
nutmeg, the cheese and remaining breadcrumbs. Beat in the eggs, 1
at a time.
</P>
<P>
   Melt the remaining 4 tablespoons butter in the hot milk; add to
the onion mixture.
</P>
<P>
   Cut the asparagus into 1/2-inch pieces and add to the custard.
</P>
<P>
   Pour the custard into the prepared mold. Place the mold in a
baking pan. Pour enough very hot water into the pan to come about
halfway up the sides of the mold.
</P>
<P>
   Bake for 35 to 40 minutes, until until a knife inserted into the
center of the custard comes out clean.
</P>
<P>
   Let cool at least 5 minutes. Run a knife around the rim of mold
and invert the custard onto a serving plate. Or serve directly from
the mold.
</P>
<P>
   Surround with a bechamel sauce seasoned with chopped fresh
herbs, Mornay sauce or other cheese sauce, if desired.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 6.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Note:  &LR; The custard may be baked in individual souffle molds or
custard cups. Reduce the cooking time to 25-30 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 310 calories, &LR;   &LR; 17 g protein, 22 g &LR; 
 &LR; carbohydrate, 19 g fat (10 g saturated), 215 mg cholesterol, &LR;   &LR; 396
mg sodium, 3 g fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; OODLES ROASTED GARLIC FLAN &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon canola oil
</P>
<P>
   1 medium onion, thinly sliced
</P>
<P>
   2 cups veal or chicken stock
</P>
<P>
   2 cups heavy cream
</P>
<P>
   1 sprig fresh rosemary
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons pureed roasted garlic (see note)
</P>
<P>
   Salt and pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   7 egg yolks
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Heat the oil in a small skillet; add the onion and cook over
medium heat until caramelized, stirring frequently.
</P>
<P>
   Combine the caramelized onion and stock in a small saucepan;
bring to a boil and cook until reduced to 8 tablespoons. (Measure 8
tablespoons water into the pan beforehand, so you know at which
level the stock should be when it is sufficiently reduced.) Strain,
discarding the onion.
</P>
<P>
   Coat 8 small (3-inch) ramekins with nonstick cooking spray.
Divide the stock among them. Refrigerate until the stock has
solidified.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, combine the cream, rosemary and garlic in a
heavy-bottomed saucepan. Bring to a boil, remove from heat and let
cool. Discard the rosemary. Season with salt and pepper.
</P>
<P>
   Preheat the oven to 400 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Beat the egg yolks in a medium bowl until blended, then add the
cream, beating until well mixed. Strain through a fine sieve.
Divide the mixture among the ramekins.
</P>
<P>
   Place the ramekins in a shallow baking pan. Pour enough hot
water into the pan to come two-thirds of the way up the sides of
the ramekins. Bake for 20 minutes, or until the flans are set.
</P>
<P>
   Let the flans cool, then unmold onto serving plates and garnish
as desired.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 8 as an appetizer.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Note:  &LR; Many delis sell heads of roasted garlic; pureed roasted
garlic also is available in jars. To roast your own, cut off the
top quarter from a whole head of garlic, drizzle with a scant
teaspoon of olive oil, wrap in foil and bake in a 325 oven until
very soft, about 1 hour. Squeeze out the soft garlic pulp into a
small bowl, discarding skins. A medium head yields about 2
tablespoons.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 345 calories, &LR;   &LR; 11 g protein, 9 g &LR; 
 &LR; carbohydrate, 31 g fat (17 g saturated), 273 mg cholesterol, 51 &LR; 
 &LR; mg sodium, 2 g fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; ONE MARKET BASIL FLAN &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   1 bunch basil
</P>
<P>
   11/2 cups heavy cream
</P>
<P>
   Pinch nutmeg
</P>
<P>
   Pinch ground cardamom
</P>
<P>
   Pinch ground ginger
</P>
<P>
   Salt and pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   1 handful spinach leaves
</P>
<P>
   2 eggs
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 300 degrees. Coat 4 small (3-inch) ramekins with
nonstick cooking spray.
</P>
<P>
   Separate basil leaves from stems. Place the stems in a
heavy-bottomed saucepan. Add the cream, nutmeg, cardamom, ginger,
salt and pepper; bring to a boil.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, blanch the basil and spinach leaves in boiling salted
water for just a moment; drain and shock with cold water. Squeeze
dry.
</P>
<P>
   Combine the basil and spinach leaves with the hot cream in a
blender or processor; process until pureed. Strain through
cheesecloth or a fine sieve. Let cool.
</P>
<P>
   Lightly beat the eggs, then stir them into the cooled cream
mixture. Divide among the ramekins. Place the ramekins in a shallow
baking pan; pour enough hot water into the pan to come a third of
the way up the sides of the ramekins. Cover loosely with foil.
</P>
<P>
   Bake for 30 minutes, or until the flans are set. Let cool to
room temperature.
</P>
<P>
   Serve as an appetizer or side dish.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 350 calories, &LR;   &LR; 6 g protein, 4 g carbohydrate, &LR; 
 &LR; 36 g fat (21 g saturated), 228 mg cholesterol, 82 mg sodium, 1 &LR;   &LR; g
fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
ANZU WILD MUSHROOM BREAD PUDDING
</P>
<P>
   Philippe Striffeler, chef in the Nikko Hotel's new restaurant,
Anzu, serves this with steak, pork, veal and chicken.
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup butter
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup minced shallots
</P>
<P>
   1 pint assorted mushrooms, cleaned and cut into medium dice
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup Madeira
</P>
<P>
   1 cup milk
</P>
<P>
   1 cup cream
</P>
<P>
   6 egg yolks, beaten
</P>
<P>
   1/4 bunch Italian parsley, finely chopped
</P>
<P>
   11/2 teaspoons chopped thyme
</P>
<P>
   Salt and pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   11/2 teaspoons porcini powder (optional)
</P>
<P>
   6 ounces brioche loaf, cut into 1/2-inch-thick slices, crusts
removed
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Melt the butter in a large saute pan. Add the shallots and
``sweat'' for 1 minute. Add the mushrooms and cook over medium-high
heat until softened and dry. Add the Madeira and cook until it
evaporates. Add the milk and cream and heat to near boiling.
</P>
<P>
   Whisk the mixture into the egg yolks. Add the herbs, salt,
pepper and optional porcini powder.
</P>
<P>
   Coat a large, shallow casserole with nonstick cooking spray or
butter. Layer one third of the bread slices into the casserole.
Pour in half of the mushroom custard. Layer half of the remaining
bread over the custard; pour in the remaining custard. Top with the
remaining bread.
</P>
<P>
   Let stand for 10 to 15 minutes. Moisten with additional cream if
the top of the pudding seems dry.
</P>
<P>
   Place the casserole in a large baking pan. Pour in enough hot
water to come a third of the way up the sides of the casserole.
</P>
<P>
   Bake in a 300-degree oven until firm, about 1 hour.
</P>
<P>
   Let cool for 10 to 15 minutes before cutting into squares.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 6.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 425 calories, &LR;   &LR; 8 g protein, 25 g &LR; 
 &LR; carbohydrate, 31 g fat (16 g saturated), 317 mg cholesterol, &LR;   &LR; 224
mg sodium, 1 g fiber. &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
