r d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOODNEWS-SFCHRON &LR;      03-16 1338
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOODNEWS-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>


</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  EDITORS NOTE: Food, nutrition and health studies bombard us, but
the seemingly endless information is often as confusing as it is
enlightening. With Food in the News, The Chronicle's Food staff
aims to change that. This regular roundup column will make
practical sense of the latest nutrition-related studies, as well as
offering offbeat but tantalizing snippets of other food news to put
on your plate. &HT;     
   
   
 FOOD IN THE NEWS: Consumers Puzzle Over Antibiotic-Free Meat  
   
   
 By Kim Severson  
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; SAN FRANCISCO _  &LR; Consumer interest in antibiotic-free meat and
poultry is growing. But butchers say people are still confused
about the decades-old antibiotics debate.
<P>
   Sales of meat and poultry labeled ``antibiotic free'' spiked at
Andronico's Market in San Francisco last week after the Food and
Drug Administration announced plans to tighten its guidelines
regarding antibiotics and livestock.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whenever something like this comes out on television or in
stories or whatever, it will go full force for a couple of weeks
and then it dies down,'' says Alex Castro, a 14-year veteran of the
Andronico's meat department on Irving Street in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1989, interest in antibiotic-free meat and poultry has
increased slowly. Sales of those products now make up about 20
percent of the store's meat department sales, he says. Prices of
beef sold as antibiotic-free can be $1 or more per pound higher
than the market's standard beef, and the price can keep some people
from putting the meat in their carts, he says.
</P>
<P>
   At Magnani Poultry in Berkeley, which sells only antibiotic-free
meat and chicken, business is good. And consumers are asking more
questions about how their meat and chicken are raised, co-owner Tim
McCormick says.
</P>
<P>
   That means butchers in turn must ask their purveyors tougher
questions. But with few regulations in place, knowing exactly how
an animal has been treated is tough _ even for meat sellers well
versed in antibiotic use.
</P>
<P>
   Butchers can rely only on wholesalers' promises that animals
have either not eaten antibiotics or were taken off the drugs a
week or two before slaughter, allowing antibiotics to pass from
their bodies, McCormick says.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 50 million pounds of antibiotics produced annually in
America, about 40 percent are given to animals. Most of that goes
into feed to promote growth.
</P>
<P>
   The FDA is expected to tighten its system for approving new
antibiotics for animals and for monitoring the effects of drugs
already in use. The concern is that antibiotic use in animals can
lead to drug-resistant strains of bacteria. People in the United
States increasingly have fallen victim to drug-resistant bacterial
infections _ a problem some researchers attribute to the overuse of
antibiotics in humans and animals.
</P>
<P>
   The new FDA guidelines aren't expected for two years.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Pity the Pyramid &LR;
</P>
<P>
   In case you weren't confused enough about what the government
wants you to eat, note that a new version of the mother of all
federal food guidelines comes your way this fall.
</P>
<P>
   Every five years, the U.S. departments of Agriculture and Health
and Human Services revise the nation's dietary guidelines, which
serve as the cornerstone of federal nutrition policies and are used
to design school lunch menus and build the nation's food pyramid.
</P>
<P>
   The current pyramid is based on grains, suggesting a daily
intake of six to 11 servings for a healthy adult. Fruits and
vegetables come next, followed by high-protein food, such as meats,
nuts and legumes. Dairy follows. Fats and sweets top the pyramid.
</P>
<P>
   A number of groups want to influence the outcome of the
nutrition guideline committee's work, which is set for release in
September. In a series of press conferences and testimony at last
week's public hearing on the guidelines in Washington, D.C.,
various nutrition agendas were pushed. Among them:
</P>
<P>
   _ A coalition of more than 20 groups, including the American
Heart Association and the American Cancer Society, want the pyramid
to center on vegetables and fruits rather than grains. Elizabeth
Pivonka, a registered dietitian and president of Produce for Better
Health Foundation, says America suffers from a growing ``vegetable
deficit.'' Her organization has found only 17 percent of foods most
Americans eat at lunch are fruits, vegetables or 100 percent juice.
</P>
<P>
   _ Nutritionists and advocates for the elderly suggest a new
pyramid to reflect the dietary needs of people over 70. That
pyramid, say nutritionists at Tufts University, should be based on
eight glasses of water to compensate for a reduced thirst
mechanism. It also suggests more fiber, special attention to
calcium to prevent bone loss and smaller portion sizes to reflect
the elderly's reduced energy needs.
</P>
<P>
   A prototype of the pyramid, published in the March issue of The
Journal of Nutrition, shows a small flag waving from the top. The
flag represents supplements of calcium and vitamins D and B-12,
three nutrients in which the elderly are often deficient.
</P>
<P>
   _ The pyramid should incorporate the needs and habits of a
broader range of ethnic groups, some advocates say. Physicians for
Responsible Medicine argues that the inclusion of three servings of
dairy products ignores the fact that many people with African,
Asian, Native American or Latino roots are lactose-intolerant.
Other nutritionists have created various ethnically customized food
pyramids, and argue the new guidelines should better reflect the
way non-whites eat.
</P>
<P>
   _ Food safety tips should be included in the dietary guidelines,
representatives of the Clinton administration say. The guidelines
should teach Americans not only what to eat, but also how to handle
food. Medical expenses and lost productivity while people recover
from food-borne illness cost the country between $6.6 billion and
$37 billion annually, Catherine Woteki, Clinton's undersecretary
for food safety, told the panel.
</P>
<P>
   How all this will affect the panel's recommendations is
anybody's guess. So is whether Americans will respond at all to the
intricate new set of guidelines.
</P>
<P>
   Says Janet King, director of the USDA Western Human Nutrition
Research Center in San Francisco: ``Eventually, in perhaps a
decade, we will have customized food pyramids.'' Until then, she
says, Americans who can't keep up with all the suggested changes in
the guidelines could follow a simple formula. Start by eating at
least five servings of fruit and vegetables a day, eat some sort of
calcium-rich food with every meal and lay off the fat.
</P>
<P>
   People who want to comment on changes in the nation's nutrition
guidelines can submit written comments to Shanthy Bowman,
Department of Agriculture Nutrient Data Laboratory, 4700 River
Road, Unit 89, Riverdale, MD 20737.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &UR; Don't Quit Your Day Job &LR;
</P>
<P>
   If the stream of reports about food and health have you
terrified of eating anything, you might want to zip over to the
FoodSafe Web site, produced by the Department of Food Science and
Technology at the University of California at Davis.
</P>
<P>
   Not only can you find out about food safety and read a flurry of
food research, you also can discover the song stylings of the
program's director.
</P>
<P>
   Carl Winter, who makes his living as a food toxicologist,
rewrites rock lyrics to reflect the nation's food fears and make
food safety a little more palatable.
</P>
<P>
   The Beatles' ``I Wanna Hold Your Hand'' becomes ``You Better
Wash Your Hands.'' The BeeGees' ``Stayin' Alive'' becomes an ode to
food poisoning: ``You can tell by the way I chose my food/I'm a
worried guy, in a cautious mood.'' And how about this Village
People hit? ``It's fun to work with the USDA.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Bay Area classrooms now playing the CDs, you can
catch Winter's act next week at the Hard Rock Cafe in Baltimore,
where he is the headliner for an Institute of Food Technologists
conference.
</P>
<P>
   Find the UC-Davis Web site at  &LR; www.foodsafe.ucdavis.edu.  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
