<SLUG> BC-SECRET-MUSSE-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>


</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  EDITORS NOTE: Each week, The Chronicle offers readers the recipe
for an outstanding dish at a Bay Area restaurant, plus the chef's
secrets for making it a success. 
   
   
 SECRETS OF SUCCESS: Aperto Bathes Mussels in a Vibrant Sea  
   
   
 By Michael Bauer  
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
   
   
 SAN FRANCISCO _  Few dishes are better _ and easier to prepare _
than mussels. In most cases, they are steamed, but at Aperto they
are baked, which produces a vibrantly flavored dish that looks as
good as it tastes.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The seafood is flavored with fennel, bright dots of cherry
tomatoes and arugula. The wine and butter that are used as a sauce
become even better when mingled with the natural juices from the
mussels and vegetables.
</P>
<P>
   At Aperto, the mussels are cooked in the oven and transferred to
the stove top simply to reduce the juices and concentrate the
flavors.
</P>
<P>
   These can make an impressive starter to any meal, or for an
informal get-together they can become the main course. They're
especially good accompanied by crisp roasted or fried potatoes.
</P>
<P>
   It's this casual type of dish, crafted by Chris Shepherd, that
has made Aperto on Potrero Hill a popular hangout. The storefront
space, with an open kitchen carved out of one corner, is always
crowded and has a comfortable homelike quality.
</P>
<P>
   At Aperto, you'll find several signature dishes, including an
excellent roast chicken with preserved lemons, warm prawns with
cannellini beans and more than a half dozen pastas. It's this type
of vibrant food that you'll find all over Italy but with a lighter
California twist.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  Aperto, 1434 18th St. (at Connecticut), San Francisco; (415) &LR; 
 &LR; 252-1625. Lunch and dinner daily. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; THE SECRETS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; Roasting.  &LR; This no-muss method is actually easier than cooking on
the stove top and creates a more intense flavor.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; The arugula.  &LR; The arugula roasted on top at the last minute
adds a distinctive aroma and flavor to the mussels.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; APERTO'S BAKED MUSSELS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   4 tablespoons olive oil
</P>
<P>
   1 fennel bulb, thinly sliced
</P>
<P>
   2 pounds Prince Edward Island (black) mussels, scrubbed and
debearded
</P>
<P>
   1 cup cherry tomatoes, halved
</P>
<P>
   4 tablespoons dry white wine
</P>
<P>
   6 ounces arugula (2 cups loosely packed), washed and dried
</P>
<P>
   1 stick (4 ounces) unsalted butter, cut into small cubes
</P>
<P>
   Salt and pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 450 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Heat the olive oil in a large, oven-safe saute pan. Add the
fennel and saute until it turns translucent and begins to
caramelize. Add the mussels, cherry tomatoes and wine; bring to a
quick boil. Remove from heat. Spread the arugula over the mussels,
dot with butter and season with salt and pepper.
</P>
<P>
   Place the pan in the oven and bake for 5 to 7 minutes, until the
mussels open. Remove pan from the oven and place over medium heat.
Boil until the liquid has reduced slightly, about 2 minutes.
Discard any mussels that have not opened.
</P>
<P>
   Arrange the mussels in a circle in each serving bowl and pour
the arugula/tomato mixture into the center.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 465 calories, &LR;   &LR; 16 g protein, 11 g
carbohydrate, &LR;   &LR; 40 g fat (17 g saturated), 138 mg cholesterol, 387
mg sodium, 7 &LR;   &LR; g fiber. &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
