<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-16 16:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2503 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AMISH-COOKING-ART-NYT     03-16 1049
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AMISH-COOKING-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FROM GRAVY TO JUS, NOW `AMISH' IS TRENDY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Pa., N.J., Ind.)   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (af)  
 By RICK MARIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   For centuries, the word ``Amish'' has been associated with
devout religious belief, barn raisings and Kelly McGillis churning
butter for Harrison Ford. Now it has a new connotation.
</P>
<P>
   Just listen to Mark Spangenthal, the chef at the Screening Room,
explaining why he brought his Amish chicken dish from the Markham,
his old restaurant, to his new restaurant: ``There is nothing more
American than the word `Amish,''' he said. ``I don't want to say
`sexy.' Sexy isn't the right word. But it looks real nice on the
menu.''
</P>
<P>
   He's not the only chef turned on by Amishness. At Follonico,
Amish chicken for two is a recurring special, either pan-roasted in
the wood-burning oven with fresh herbs or _ in a strangely
cross-cultural locution _ fricasseo.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've caught a little flak when we've run it on the menu,''
Follonico's chef and owner, Alan Tardi, said. ``People say: `You're
supposed to be an Italian restaurant. What are you doing with Amish
chicken?'''
</P>
<P>
   A valid question. It appears that New York foodies have come to
see ``Amish'' as the ultimate simple-chic approbation, the
gustatory equivalent of antiquing in Lancaster County, Pa. They may
have picked it up from high-end meat purveyors, who like to
advertise the Amish origins of their fowl.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Complete Meat Cookbook'' (Houghton Mifflin, $35) notes the
new popularity of Amish pork. And the Amish Manhattan Farmers
Market, which opened its second store a year ago at 240 East 45th
Street, will hang its third horse-and-buggy shingle at the World
Trade Center in May.
</P>
<P>
   Never mind that the Amish market's owners are from Turkey or
that the store is stocked with non-Amish staples like balsamic
vinager, Froot Loops and Perrier. Never mind that many Amish
chickens are raised no better than Frank Perdue's, or that even if
the menu says ``Amish,'' the birds can come from almost any farm in
Lancaster County. For all that diners know, they could be eating
Shaker-bake.
</P>
<P>
   So what exactly does ``Amish'' mean, in a culinary context?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a marketing ploy,'' said Ariane Daguin, co-owner of
D'Artagnan, a Newark-based supplier of Amish chicken to New York
restaurants and markets. ``It doesn't mean anything.''
</P>
<P>
   The mystique of the Amish label, Ms. Daguin said, comes from its
``aura of naturalness,'' though chickens raised on Amish farms do
not always eat vegetarian feed. Nor are they free-range or free
roaming.
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Aidells, co-author with Denis Kelly of the ``Complete Meat
Cookbook,'' is a devotee of Amish meat products. ``I don't know if
it has more fat in it or what,'' he said of Amish pork he ate in
Bern, Ind. ``But it has a wonderful taste, a real nice pork
flavor.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked to describe that flavor, Aidells offered the word
``porkiness.'' He also recalls fondly the Amish chicken at the
now-closed David Ruggerio restaurant, which had a taste that he
called ``chickeny.''
</P>
<P>
   Tardi of Follonico agrees that the virtues of Amish chickens are
hard to pin down. ``There's all this talk about free-range and
organic, and this isn't that,'' he said. ``But it is minimally
processed, with no hormones. It's a chicken with morals.''
</P>
<P>
   Not necessarily. Phyllis Pellman Good, the author of ``The Best
of Amish Cooking'' (Good Books, 1988), who is a Mennonite (the sect
from which the Amish broke in the 17th century), says that Amish
chickens, contrary to popular belief, are not free-range.
</P>
<P>
   ``They lead pretty confined lives,'' she said. How about hormone
injections? ``There's a range from quite cautious to full
participation in that type of technology,'' she said. ``They're way
beyond little nests in quaint barns.''
</P>
<P>
   Regarding the origin of Follonico's ``Amish'' chicken, Tardi
acknowledged, ``I can't vouch for the fact that it was produced by
Amish people in black hats and no buttons.''
</P>
<P>
   At the River Cafe, Amish chicken is served with Yukon Gold
whipped potatoes, Blue Lake green beans and button mushrooms in a
chicken jus. Peter Demers, the restaurant's steward, said that, of
the Amish chickens he buys, ``the majority are from Amish
farmers,'' but that ``some might be Mennonites, too.'' Such
distinctions apparently fall off the trucks from Pennsylvania. And
``Mennonite chicken'' (italics)is(end italics) a bit of a mouthful.
</P>
<P>
   But the River Cafe's Amish chicken is a distant city cousin to
the simple country dish served in Lancaster County. Ms. Good
approved of the potatoes and greens as side dishes, but not the
mushrooms, which are not grown by the Amish. ``If you have them,
they come out of the can,'' she said. ``And we would never say
`jus.' It's gravy. Thick, not that watery stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   Few Amish people, restricted by their religion and cultural
inclination from straying far from Pennsylvania Dutch country, make
the trek to New York to sell their wares. One exception is David
Wengerd, an Amish farmer who has been commuting here from central
Pennsylvania since 1985.
</P>
<P>
   He and his 11 children operate stands at Columbus Circle,
Federal Plaza and the Union Square Greenmarket. Five years ago,
Wengerd said, he gave up a store on the west side of Union Square
when the rent went from $12,000 to $18,000 a month.
</P>
<P>
   In his straw hat and black corduroy jacket with hooks in place
of buttons, Wengerd certainly looked like the real thing. He had a
gray goatee and fantastic set of teeth. ``It doesn't bother me,''
he said of the casual way in which the adjective ``Amish'' is
thrown around. ``The Amish philosophy is live and let live. People
would like us to do something about it. But it would be completely
against our religion. We don't believe in fighting against
anyone.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Good said that these quiet, pacifist people just don't take
their food seriously enough to get upset about the use and abuse of
their good name.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here in Amish country,'' she said, ``the emphasis is on lots
of food mildly seasoned. Presentation is way down in the order of
importance.''
</P>
<P>
   Here in Amex country, it's the other way around.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
