<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-16 16:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2511 &Cx1f; taf-z
s t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRAVEL-FRANCE-DINING-     03-16 1061
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-FRANCE-DINING-2TAKES-$ADV21-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN FRENCH WINE COUNTRY, GOOD EATING, TOO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, March 21)  
 (bl)  
 By ERIC ASIMOV   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Vineyards command the horizon along the Rhone River from Avignon
to Lyons and, farther north, in Burgundy. In winter, of course,
there are no grapes, or even vines. They've been pruned back,
leaving only thick, gnarled stalks, rising a twisted foot or so
above the ground.
</P>
<P>
   Like their vines, the French of the wine country seem to pass
the cold weather in a state of dormancy. Aside from a wispy fire to
burn cuttings or a lone worker trudging the fields, the land
appears deserted. But look closer and you see light dancing through
the cracks of the farmhouse shutters, smoke pouring from the
chimneys. Though hidden away, pots continue to be stirred.
</P>
<P>
   On a midwinter trip with three friends to visit wineries in the
Rhone Valley and Burgundy, many of the more celebrated restaurants
_ those with Michelin stars _ had cut back their hours or were
closed for vacation. Yet, it's also a season of great eating, with
lots of game, hearty stews and, of course, truffles. (In spring,
menus change to offer lighter fare.)
</P>
<P>
   Where to go? We asked the winemakers for recommendations, and
they were happy to oblige. They suggested some unpretentious
restaurants that don't require a lot of time or cost a lot of
money, where workers in jeans are as welcome as executives in ties.
These restaurants serve robust, unfussy food, and, as a bonus,
almost always have excellent wine lists. Here are five, moving
south to north.
</P>
<P>
   Restaurant St.-Hubert
</P>
<P>
   This friendly, pleasant restaurant in Entrechaux, northeast of
Gigondas, focuses on fresh game in winter. Heads of wild boar, stag
and mountain goat dominate the bright dining room, where a
fireplace warms the cold marble floor. Unlike many places that
serve frozen game, in which the flavor has been dulled and the
texture toughened, St.-Hubert uses only fresh game from various
parts of France, which it dresses itself.
</P>
<P>
   To get properly in the spirit, you might start with a seasonal
specialty, assiette de la foret, a huge portion of game charcuterie
that includes an earthy terrine of wild hare, leathery smoked ham
of baby wild boar, rich smoked breast of wild duck and a dish of
lactaires delicieux mushrooms in a light vinaigrette (or, in fall,
cepes). Alternatives to game include excellent foie gras de canard
or a truly luxurious dish, brioche aux truffes and foie gras. You
are served what looks like an ordinary brioche, but the top is
hinged. Open it up and dig out a soft-cooked egg with truffles and
strips of luscious duck liver. As you eat, the egg is absorbed by
the bread until it becomes extraordinarily soft, like baby food for
grown-ups.
</P>
<P>
   Main courses in winter include a selection of civets, or game
stews, made with deep, hearty sauces of red wine and the blood of
the animal. The wild boar civet is tender and mellow, with a warm,
lingering aftertaste, while venison _ from a biche, or doe, to be
precise _ has a stronger, more pronounced flavor. Selle de
chevreuil, or saddle of venison, in a creamy grand veneur sauce is
gamier than the farm-raised American version, while the meat of the
perdreau, or partridge, is wonderfully flavored underneath its
brittle skin. The bird is split for two people, and served with
bacon, bay leaves and roasted garlic. As good as the partridge was,
it was also a little dry.
</P>
<P>
   The dessert selection is not memorable. Instead finish the meal
with a cheese course, which might include a pungent Roquefort, a
wedge of nutty Reblochon, and three different chevres: a soft,
fresh disk, a slightly more flavorful semiripened sample and a
gloriously well-aged slice, hardened and subtly yet powerfully
flavored.
</P>
<P>
   While most of these places have great wine lists, St.-Hubert is
the inexplicable exception. The restaurant has the wines of the
southern Rhone at its fingertips, but its list is sadly mediocre.
</P>
<P>
   La Beaugraviere
</P>
<P>
   With salmon-colored walls and tablecloths and a floor of beige
industrial tile, this resolutely plain restaurant near Bollene has
all the charm of a car rental office. The dining room's sole
enticing feature, a big fireplace, is blocked from view by a table
right in front of it. What draws people to La Beaugraviere is not
its looks but its specialty: truffles, and lots of them.
</P>
<P>
   The restaurant not only offers three special truffle menus from
December through March, it also offers 18 truffle dishes a la carte
in winter (dropping to five the rest of the year), including
truffle ice cream, which, at $17 or so a scoop, I decided to
forego. I didn't want to overdo it, after all.
</P>
<P>
   Not that the truffle menus are paragons of restraint. The least
expensive of the truffle menus, about $67, offers three truffle
courses, plus cheese and dessert. The starters include either
pumpkin veloute with truffle shavings, which give the creamy soup a
decadent edge, or eggs softly scrambled with truffles, my choice
for swooning over their rich, intoxicating flavor.
</P>
<P>
   The menu comes with a mid-course of chicken cannelloni in a
Parmesan-and-cream sauce, with truffles, of course, which elevate
this prosaic dish to unexpected heights. The main course, a thick
hunk of broiled veal under a shroud of truffles, is a sensuous
blend, while a side dish of tiny round potatoes with truffles is a
glorious expression of the humble tuber and fungus, adorned with a
little olive oil and coarse salt.
</P>
<P>
   The nontruffle choices are even more interesting. A $34 menu
centers around lievre a la royale, magnificently gamy wild hare
stuffed with ground liver and herbs, tasting of the forest and the
earth. For just $23, the meal might include lamb's feet wrapped in
tripe, a wonderfully mellow, homey dish that I loved.
</P>
<P>
   La Beaugraviere offers a huge selection of Rhone wines,
including, on the moderate side, a silky berry-scented 1995
St.-Joseph from J.L. Grippat for about $42.
</P>
<P>
   After a cheese course comes dessert, a delicate apple tart or
the ubiquitous molten chocolate cake, crisp outside and liquidy
inside. Both are fine and, I think, more than a match for truffle
ice cream. Then the correct yet friendly waiter brings a little
treat, dense chocolate pot-au-creme in little glass cups. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
