<HEADER>
A2513 &Cx1f; taf-z
s t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRAVEL-FRANCE-DINING-     03-16 1197
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-FRANCE-DINING-$ADV21-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: glass cups.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Restaurant Le Chaudron
</P>
<P>
   Chaudron means kettle, and a bubbling pot is the perfect image
for this boisterous, lively restaurant in Tournon, a prime meeting
spot for local winemakers, who love to share old jokes at full
volume from across the room. At this, they are aided by the owners,
Marc and Dominique Grillon, who welcome everybody with a smile and
leap right into the teasing themselves.
</P>
<P>
   This is no temple of haute cuisine. It is a moderately priced
gathering spot for sampling the local culture with an excellent
wine list specializing, naturally, in the wines of the northern
Rhone. You might find some bargains on the list, like a beautifully
balanced 1992 Hermitage from Alain Graillot for about $37. Or you
might splurge on a more extravagant wine, a lovely, complex 1991
Cornas from A. Clape for about $53.
</P>
<P>
   The menu itself requires more careful navigation. Crepinette de
sanglier, a kind of wild boar sausage that has been wrapped in
caul, was extremely dry and was served without the red wine sauce
promised on the menu, but the foie gras de canard was smooth and
creamy. The best main course was a fricassee de pintade, guinea hen
with bacon and braised cabbage, a delicious combination. Magret
with caramelized pear was tender and flavorful, but a civet de
lapin, or rabbit stew, was tough and unexpectedly dry.
</P>
<P>
   A nice plate of local cheeses served with a basket of good bread
is a satisfying ending, perfect with the last sip of wine. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Les Tontons
</P>
<P>
   There is no shortage of restaurants or winemakers in Beaune, the
beautiful little walled city in the heart of Burgundy. Les Tontons,
an inviting restaurant in the center of the city, is a favorite of
the wine trade. Its beige stucco walls are unadorned except for a
big painting of the proprietors, Pepita and Richard Grocat,
superimposed over a background of the city and bearing a basket of
eggs, a plump chicken and bountiful produce. We were greeted warmly
as we stepped in out of a driving rain, feeling as if we had found
a refuge.
</P>
<P>
   The husband-and-wife owners are hands-on. Mrs. Grocat, smiling
and jovial, is unobtrusively attentive, while her husband comes out
of his kitchen every so often to bring out food and help clear
plates. His $26 lunch menu is full of alluring choices,
meticulously prepared with exceptional ingredients. The flavors are
complex yet unrefined, the antithesis of fussy.
</P>
<P>
   A layered loaf of foie gras and Mulard duck confit is a
luxuriously delicious appetizer, sweetened just enough with figs,
while risotto with shrimp and slivers of Parmesan is superb,
animated by a judicious few drops of truffle oil, the texture at
that precise point between dry and creamy. For a $4 supplement
comes another excellent starter, small, sweet scallops,
cross-sectioned and sauteed with a little pile of caramelized
endive.
</P>
<P>
   Main courses included what I regarded as the perfect rainy day
dish, parmentier de boeuf Bourguignon, which is really no more than
a Gallic shepherd's pie, a circular terrine of the beef sandwiched
by pureed potatoes that is marvelously soothing. Ris et mignon de
veau is a more forceful dish of veal and sweetbreads, moistened by
their own juices and complemented by a sweet ragout of salsify.
Pigeonneau, or roasted squab (for a $5 supplement), is the most
powerfully flavored main course. The rich, livery meat is as red as
beef, with a thin layer of glistening fat, and goes beautifully
with sauteed cabbage.
</P>
<P>
   By Burgundian standards, the wine list is reasonably priced. We
drank a fresh 1996 Savigny-les-Beaune Les Narbantons from Ecard for
$31, although there are also many wines for which you can pay much
more.
</P>
<P>
   We skipped the gorgeous cheese plate and indulged in desserts,
including a refreshing baked pear with exceptional nougat ice
cream, and a classic, floating island, that was surprisingly light
and pleasant.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Aux Vendanges De Bourgogne
</P>
<P>
   This bright restaurant in Gevrey-Chambertin, on the main road
through the Cote de Nuits is a winemaker's haven. Not only is the
front room decorated with grapevine wallpaper, but the Art Nouveau
ceiling lamps are wrapped in vines. The lamps themselves look like
nothing so much as generous breasts, as if wine were mother's milk.
</P>
<P>
   Aux Vendanges offers a special wine feature as well. Each Monday
it selects three Gevrey-Chambertin wines to sell at cost. We pulled
in for lunch on a Wednesday, but were still able to find some
excellent values on the list, like a simple, spicy 1995 Bourgogne
from Leroy for $21 and a 1993 Marsannay from Bruno Clair for $23.
Even a more expensive choice, like a supple, perfumed 1994
Charmes-Chambertin from Geantet-Pansiot is a terrific buy at $54.
</P>
<P>
   The brief $19 lunch menu is a great deal as well, with a starter
like a sensational galette de pied de porc, a brown buckwheat crepe
wrapped around the incredibly rich, almost gelatinous meat from the
pig's foot. It comes with a small salad and is almost a meal in
itself. The other appetizer selection, a large green salad with
marinated mushrooms, is neither as rich nor as distinctive.
</P>
<P>
   Main courses include tender chicken baked in cream sauce with a
heaping portion of preserved morels and a firm, white-fleshed
Mediterranean fish called rascasse, moist and well-cooked, but
again not particularly distinctive. Perhaps the restaurant is
reluctant to upstage its wines.
</P>
<P>
   The menu offers a choice of cheese _ including some hard-to-find
Burgundy specialties such as a lush Soumaintrain fermier _ or
dessert, a terrific pain perdu, a sweet crisp-but-airy slice of
bread. It's proof that French toast really does come from France.
</P>
<P>
   Bill of Fare
</P>
<P>
   These restaurants all accept Visa but not American Express.
Prices are based on a meal for two with a moderately priced bottle
of wine and the 12.5 percent service that is customary in France.
Unless otherwise noted, smoking is permitted and there is no
nonsmoking section.
</P>
<P>
   Prices have been calculated at 5.9 francs to the dollar.
</P>
<P>
   Restaurant St.-Hubert, Entrechaux, D938 and D54, (33-4)
90.46.00.05. Closed Tuesday and Wednesday. One room is set aside
for nonsmokers. Dinner menus about $13, $23, $31 and $46. About
$110 for two.
</P>
<P>
   La Beaugraviere, N 7, Mondragon, about four miles southwest of
Bollene, (33-4) 90.40.82.54. Closed Sunday and Monday evenings
(open for Sunday lunch). Lunch and dinner menus about $23, $34,
$67, and, in winter, special truffle menus at $67, $93 and $117.
About $140 for two.
</P>
<P>
   Restaurant Le Chaudron, 7 Rue St.-Antoine, Tournon, (33-4)
75.08.17.90. Closed all day Sunday and Thursday evening. Dinner
menus about $20, $27. About $90 for two.
</P>
<P>
   Les Tontons, 22 Faubourg Madeleine, Beaune, (33-3) 80.24.19.64.
Closed all day Sunday and Monday lunch. Lunch menus about $16 and
$26 (with supplements, around $32). About $90 for two.
</P>
<P>
   Aux Vendanges de Bourgogne, 47 Route de Beaune,
Gevrey-Chambertin, (33-3) 80.34.30.24. Closed Sunday. One room is
set aside for nonsmokers. Lunch and dinner menus about $19 and $26;
weekday market menu, $13. About $70 for two.
</P>
