A2515 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COLON-CANCER-HNS &LR;      03-16 1091
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLON-CANCER-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REGULAR CHECK-UPS SEEN AS KEY IN FIGHT AGAINST COLON CANCER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By BRUCE A. SCRUTON  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ The second-largest cancer killer _ colon cancer _
has a 90 percent survival rate if detected early, yet almost
two-thirds of new cases aren't discovered until the cancer has
invaded other parts of the body.
</P>
<P>
   American Cancer Society figures present an unsettling snapshot
of colon cancer in 1999. At Stage 2, where the cancer has spread to
the area around the colon, the survival rate (defined as living
five years after diagnosis) declines to roughly 2 in 3.
Thirty-seven percent of the cases are discovered at this point.
</P>
<P>
   When the cancer has moved to other parts of the body _ and 1 in
5 cases are discovered at this advanced stage _ the chances of
living five more years is less than 10 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The bright spot is a survival rate of more than 90 percent when
the cancer is discovered at the local phase, or stage 1. Only 37
percent of the cases are diagnosed at that time.
</P>
<P>
   Being pushed this year, however, is an educational program aimed
at both doctors and the general population.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't recommend testing enough,'' said Dr. Gabe Feldman,
director of colon and prostate cancer for the American Cancer
Society. ``Everyone needs this screening at age 50.''
</P>
<P>
   Of cancers that strike both sexes, lung cancer is the biggest
killer, followed by cancer of the colon.
</P>
<P>
   Incidence and mortality rates for African-Americans is higher in
both men and women, with about half that difference being
attributed to diagnosis at a later stage of the cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Without another step in research, Feldman notes, doctors can
save 20,000 to 30,000 lives with earlier colon cancer screening.
``We can stop most of this development, just by using what we know
today,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Such early screening can detect polyps, the growths on the
inside of the bowel which are often the precursors to cancer and
which, if removed, ``means the patient won't even get (colon)
cancer,'' he stressed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't know what causes these growths yet,'' said Dr. George
Boyar with Saratoga-Schenectady Gastroenterology Associates in
upstate New York. ``But polyps are very common, especially as you
get older.''
</P>
<P>
   According to the American Cancer Society, there is a 1-in-1,708
probability of developing colon cancer for those up to age 39. In
the next two decades of life, however, the odds drop to about 1 in
125. Between ages 60 and 79, there is a 1-in-25 chance of a man
developing cancer in the large intestine. For women, the chance is
1 in 32.
</P>
<P>
   What makes colon cancer such an insidious killer is that in its
early stages there are often no symptoms, Feldman said.
</P>
<P>
   Boyar, whose practice does about 1,000 colonoscopys a year, said
colon cancer ``is not detected because there are no active signs. A
lot of the symptoms (for gastrointestinal problems) are the same
and you can have a lot of disease in the colon with no symptoms.''
</P>
<P>
   The results of recent studies, however, show there is a good
chance of diagnosis before there are active symptoms. A diagnostic
test, coupled with high survivability when detected in early
stages, is the basis for the new educational push on colon cancer.
</P>
<P>
   The tool is a simple fecal occult blood test for everyone age 50
and older. Stool samples are collected at home over the course of
three days and taken to the doctor's office. A few drops of a
chemical onto the test strips can show the presence of blood _ one
of the earliest warning signs.
</P>
<P>
   Polyps can get irritated and bleed. Of course, the doctors
noted, blood can also point to other problems.
</P>
<P>
   But the study of 46,000 people in Minnesota over a 20-year
period showed 33 percent fewer deaths from colon cancer in those
who had a yearly fecal occult blood test. Testing just every other
year showed a 21 percent reduction in the death rate.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Dr. John H. Bond, co-author of the study, said there is a 35
percent chance of finding a growth in the colon of someone with a
positive test. About 10 percent of those people will have cancer
with the others having precancerous polyps.
</P>
<P>
   Should blood be found, or if there are other indications of
cancer possibility, such as a family history, the doctor will order
a close look. In younger (under 40) people, the No. 1 cause of
bleeding is hemorrhoids, noted Feldman, but a doctor should be
consulted to be sure.
</P>
<P>
   Boyar said the quickest and easiest exam is a sigmoidoscopy,
done in the office. Using a flexible tube with a built-in camera
and lights, the doctor looks at the lower third of the large
intestine. ``If we find something there, the odds are there are
problems further up,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The other procedure is a colonoscopy, usually done in a hospital
setting, in which a longer tube travels the entire six-foot length
of the large intestine. For this procedure, the patient is in a
drug-induced, relaxed state.
</P>
<P>
   Should any polyps be discovered, a thin wire can be passed
through the instrument, looped over the growth to cut it off. A
later biopsy determines if there is, or was, cancer.
</P>
<P>
   More advanced stages of cancer, which can also be seen with the
colonoscope, require more radical treatment, such as surgery,
chemotherapy or radiation.
</P>
<P>
   While the exact reason for polyp development, and cancer, is
unclear, Feldman noted there are some general trends to note, such
as being overweight, inactivity and ``a typical Western diet.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't mean chili peppers,'' he laughed, noting that diets
rich in fruits and vegetables seem more protective than those with
plenty of red meat.
</P>
<P>
   And family history, he said, is extremely important in colon
cancer. People with a parent or sibling who has colon cancer should
not wait until age 50 to be checked. While non-hereditary colon
cancer rarely occurs before age 40, hereditary colon cancers often
occur in younger people.
</P>
<P>
   Regular examinations can detect polyp growths. Remove the polyp
and remove most chances of cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Regular exams for everyone over 50 can also detect polyp
growths, the doctors stressed. ``If you're a man and concerned
about prostate cancer, you should be concerned about colon
cancer,'' Feldman said. ``And for women, to be checked for breast
cancer, get checked for colon cancer.
</P>
<P>
   ``You need this,'' he said. ``Talk to your doctor. Go see him.
This simple test can save lives.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
