<HEADLINE>
GENTLE RIVALRY PACKS BIGGER PUNCH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MONICA ANDERSON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Before last weekend, I had planned to do a comparative analysis
using two very unusual rivalries: Matisse and Picasso dueling it
out at the Kimbell Art Museum in Fort Worth while Holyfield and
Lewis duked it out at Madison Square Garden in New York City.
</P>
<P>
   I know, it's a big leap _ but I was feeling froggy.
</P>
<P>
   The media hype for the Lewis-Holyfield match raised the level of
boxing fans' anticipation as high as Don King's Afro. In one
corner, the American, Evander Holyfield, who at age 36, was older,
balder, shorter and 31 pounds lighter than his opponent. Yet,
Holyfield was the favorite going into the fight. After all,
Holyfield was a proven warrior. He beat George Foreman and ``Iron''
Mike Tyson.
</P>
<P>
   Holyfield's opponent, Lennox Lewis of Britain, was young and
cocky, and he appeared in the ring with his dreadlocks pinned up
with bobby pins. I have nothing against dreads, but a French roll
on a fighter is just so ... so unwarriorlike.
</P>
<P>
   So you've got a proven champion who enters the ring singing
hymns vs. a guy with hairpins. Of course, Holyfield was the
favorite.
</P>
<P>
   However, despite the cornucopia of famous faces encasing King's
canvas like a human frame, the better match was in Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   Henri Matisse, the great French artist best known for his bold,
colorful paintings, also excelled in sculpture and illustration.
Matisse pursued a career in law before he discovered his talent for
painting at the age of 20. For the next 60 years, he pursued his
passion. The results are so magnificent that people still stand in
long lines to see his works.
</P>
<P>
   Pablo Picasso, Matisse's contemporary, began studying art at a
very young age. He is best known by the general public for his
uncanny ability to transform geometric shapes into colorful,
sensuous women with large hips. He was versatile and prolific like
Matisse. He was also a critic and admirer of Matisse.
</P>
<P>
   Matisse and Picasso engaged in a match of skills that involved
more structure and strategy than strength, yet it was an intense
battle nonetheless. Their one-upmanship left the art world reeling
in its brilliant aftermath.
</P>
<P>
   What is the point of all this? Nothing really. I just liked the
exhibit a lot, and I'm really hoping that big hips become vogue
again. However, I should point out that Lewis, bobby pins and all,
beat up Holyfield as if Holyfield had stolen his mother's purse on
Christmas Eve. I have rarely seen so decisive a fight. Although it
ended in a controversial draw, Lennox was the winner, in my eyes.
</P>
<P>
   The boxing world is still reeling from the uppercut to its
credibility. No one would stand in line to see that fight again. I
wouldn't even stand up to see that fight again.
</P>
<P>
   The only real draw was at the Kimbell, where the exhibit billed
as ``A Gentle Rivalry'' left the audience awestruck; unable, and
unwilling, to choose a winner.
</P>
<P>
   The moral of this story is: It costs $8 to see Matisse and
Picasso; it cost between $60 and $10,000 to see Don King's circus.
</P>
<P>
   And the winner by unanimous decision is ...
</P>
<P>
   (Monica Frazier Anderson is a wife, mother and dentist in
Arlington, Texas. You can call her at (817) 548-5564, or write in
care of the Arlington Star-Telegram at 1111 W. Abram St.,
Arlington, TX 76013. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on
the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
