A2534 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LABBE-COLUMN-TEX     03-16 0813
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LABBE-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OUT OF CONTROL WHEN IT COMES TO GUN SAFETY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By J.R. LABBE 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   At first it looked like a photograph of Ma Barker somehow got on
the inside pages of The New York Times last week. But even the
infamous mom of a brood of gangsters would have known better.
</P>
<P>
   There stood Dianne Feinstein, the anti-gun senator from
California, posing for all the nation's media to capture on
Kodachrome, holding an AK-47 with her finger firmly planted on the
trigger.
</P>
<P>
   Here's a woman so concerned about the supposed recklessness of
gun manufacturers that she's calling for a ban on high-capacity
ammunition magazines _ the justification being little more than
anecdotal evidence _ who wouldn't know firearm safety if it bit her
on the end of her upturned San Franciscan nose.
</P>
<P>
   Any 8-year-old who's ever taken the Eddie Eagle Gun Safety
Program offered by the National Rifle Association knows that one of
the first rules of firearm safety is to never put your finger
inside the trigger guard and on the trigger of a gun unless you
mean to shoot it. Never. Ever.
</P>
<P>
   And there stood one of the poster children for gun control,
exhibiting to the whole world exactly how accidental shootings
happen. The result? The gun manufacturers get blamed for producing
an unsafe product when the responsibility lies with the careless _
or in some cases deliberate _ person who doesn't respect firearms.
</P>
<P>
   It's a safe bet that Feinstein was also violating another rule
of gun safety, but I can't say for sure because of the way that the
photograph was cropped. Judging by the crowd of people gathered
round the senator, it's likely that she had that dreaded assault
rifle pointed at someone.
</P>
<P>
   Never, ever point a firearm, even an unloaded firearm, at
anything you're not willing to shoot.
</P>
<P>
   One of my colleagues overheard my rant about the photograph _
frankly, it would have been nigh onto impossible to ignore me in
our small office, the flames shooting out of my ears were so hot _
and interjected that I might be overreacting just a tad. After all,
he said, the gun was undoubtedly unloaded.
</P>
<P>
   Thereby prompting a lesson on the first and most important rule
of firearm safety: Treat all guns as if they are loaded.
</P>
<P>
   Feinstein's demonstrated ignorance of how to safely handle a
firearm is proof that state Rep. Suzanna Gratia Hupp is on the
right track with her proposed resolution to encourage Texas schools
to use the Eddie Eagle program to teach youngsters what to do if
they find themselves around a firearm.
</P>
<P>
   The Lampasas Republican is asking her colleagues in the
Legislature to declare Oct. 18-22 as Childrens' Firearm Safety Week
and to encourage schools statewide to use the tested and successful
program to instruct youngsters about the fundamentals of gun
safety.
</P>
<P>
   The Eddie Eagle program teaches children what to do if they see
a gun: Stop, immediately leave the area and tell an adult.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, if the adult they tell about the firearm is clueless
about how to safely handle it, we still have a problem. But the NRA
has an answer for that scenario as well.
</P>
<P>
   The organization produces an informative booklet called ``Smart
&AMP; Safe: Handling Your New Gun.'' It's designed especially for teens
and for adults with little or no firearm experience. There's also a
10-minute video on the fundamentals of gun safety that's targeted
toward teens and adults, and a brochure that explains parental
responsibilities regarding gun safety for children. All are
produced by the NRA's safety and educational division and can be
ordered by calling (800) 336-7402.
</P>
<P>
   I've been accused of being a shill for the NRA. I make no
apologies for being a member of an organization that fights as hard
for Second Amendment rights as the media fights for the First. I
don't always agree with its tactics _ there's room for negotiation
and compromise on some issues _ but I support the basic mission of
protecting the right of private gun ownership.
</P>
<P>
   It's the individual choice of adult Americans as to whether they
want firearms in their homes. You may not want one in your house,
and that's fine. But parents should not be blind to the reality
that their children may come across a firearm somewhere else. Teach
your children to understand that the danger is not the gun but what
can happen if the gun is mishandled.
</P>
<P>
   Accidental shootings would never occur if people would follow
basic, common-sense procedures on how to handle firearms. So,
Dianne, take your finger off the trigger before someone gets hurt.
</P>
<P>
   (Jill ``J.R.'' Labbe is senior editorial writer and columnist
for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram. Her e-mail address is
jrlabbe &LR; star-telegram.com, and her phone number is (817) 390-7599.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
