u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OVEN-BARBECUE-NYT &LR;      03-16 1265
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OVEN-BARBECUE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAN'T WAIT TILL SUMMER TO BARBECUE? READ ON 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By JOHN WILLOUGHBY and CHRIS SCHLESINGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   There are many charms to late winter, but right about now, they
are definitely fading. For one thing, it seems like years, rather
than months, since we enjoyed the foods of summer. And for us, that
means barbecue.
</P>
<P>
   We miss the time-honored ritual of hovering around a smoky fire
all night, drinking beer and trading stories. Even more than that,
though, we miss the taste. Crusty outside and tender inside, imbued
with the rich, deep flavor of hickory smoke, barbecue is an
unbeatable treat.
</P>
<P>
   But when the snow is on the woodpile, there's just no way to
barbecue.
</P>
<P>
   Or maybe there is.
</P>
<P>
   While it is rank heresy even to suggest this among true
aficionados, it is possible to approximate the taste of real
barbecue in the oven.
</P>
<P>
   Notice that word ``approximate,'' because, of course, you can't
duplicate the flavor of meat that has spent eight or 10 hours
sitting over a smoldering hickory fire. But with patience and the
help of bottled flavor, it is possible to produce a reasonable _
and tasty _ facsimile.
</P>
<P>
   This culinary sleight of hand requires that the cook abandon any
desire for efficiency, in favor of the time-honored motto of the
great pit masters of the South: ``Slow and low is the way to go.''
The heart of the process is cooking over low heat for a long time.
</P>
<P>
   Barbecuing essentially consists of placing a large, tough cut of
meat in an enclosed space like a pit or a cast-iron smoker, with
the fire on one side and the grid holding the meat on the other.
The meat is cooked through the indirect heat and smoke of the fire.
The temperature is kept just below the boiling point, 212 degrees,
and over many hours the meat's stringy connective tissues, called
collagen, dissolve into gelatin. This transforms the tough meat
into a tender delicacy.
</P>
<P>
   To cooks who are not used to the method, its very slowness seems
daunting, but barbecue cannot be hurried.
</P>
<P>
   In this respect, there is actually an advantage to using an
oven, rather than a live fire. With a fire, you have to guess at
the temperature: place one too many logs on, and you get meat that
will cook too fast. An oven can maintain the required low, even
heat for an indefinite time: Just set the dial.
</P>
<P>
   What the oven cannot do is to provide the dominant flavor of
smoke. To mimic that, you have to add a step untraditional to
barbecuing: a dunk in brine.
</P>
<P>
   A classic brine combines water and salt, sometimes with sugar
added. Both salt and sugar are hygroscopic, which means that they
attract and absorb water.
</P>
<P>
   This quality lets the brining solution work its way into the
meat, seasoning the meat throughout and enhancing its flavor.
</P>
<P>
   We decided to take advantage of the phenomenon by adding a good
dose of liquid smoke to the brine, so that its flavor is carried
right into the meat.
</P>
<P>
   Some cooks may balk at using liquid smoke, suspecting that it is
a witch's brew of chemicals and additives, like many potions that
have been designed to mimic flavors. Not so. It is made by simply
burning hickory wood, condensing the resulting smoke, dissolving it
in water and filtering it to remove impurities. With no added
chemicals or coloring, it has been designated as a ``natural''
product by the Food and Drug Administration.
</P>
<P>
   Since the amount of brine required depends on the size and shape
of the container that is used for brining, it may not always be
necessary to make as much brine as is called for in the recipe
presented here.
</P>
<P>
   As with most unfamiliar dishes, you will have to go by trial and
error the first time, but after that you will know what you need
before you begin.
</P>
<P>
   The spice rub and the tomato-based barbecue sauce recipes
offered here are multipurpose, suitable not only for ribs but also
for barbecued beef brisket, grilled chicken or even strong-flavored
fish.
</P>
<P>
   Just remember that the sauce should be passed as an addition
after the cooking; if you put it on the food while it is cooking,
the sauce will burn.
</P>
<P>
   As for the meat, there is no point in aiming for an exact
cooking time. After all, this is a cooking method so casual that
the interval at which more fuel is added to the fire is
traditionally measured in the time it takes the cook to consume a
beer.
</P>
<P>
   The best way to determine when the meat is done is not by time,
temperature or even appearance, but by sticking a large fork into
the meat and trying to lift it up. If the fork will not hold the
meat because the meat starts to fall apart, then it is ``fork
tender'' and ready to eat.
</P>
<P>
   So, while you will miss the experience of hunkering down next to
smoldering logs in a dirt pit, this oven method lets you enjoy
results that are as close to real barbecue as you are likely to get
without digging a hole in your back yard.
</P>
<P>
   But there is nothing to prevent you from sitting up all night
next to the oven, if you wish, telling tall tales and drinking
beer.
</P>
<P>
   SMOKY BRINE
</P>
<P>
   Time: 5 minutes
</P>
<P>
   4 ounces (1/2 cup) liquid smoke
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 cups kosher salt
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup brown sugar.
</P>
<P>
   In a large bucket, very large roasting pan or other container
that can easily hold the meat to be brined, combine a gallon of
water, liquid smoke, salt and brown sugar. Stir to dissolve salt
and sugar.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: about a gallon.
</P>
<P>
   BARBECUE SPICE RUB
</P>
<P>
   Time: 5 minutes
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon kosher salt
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup sugar
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons cumin
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons freshly ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons chili powder
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup paprika.
</P>
<P>
   In a small bowl, combine all ingredients, and mix well. This rub
will keep for months when covered and stored in a cool, dark place.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 1 scant cup.
</P>
<P>
   BASIC BARBECUE SAUCE
</P>
<P>
   Time: 1 hour 15 minutes
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons vegetable oil
</P>
<P>
   1 onion, minced
</P>
<P>
   6 ounces tomato puree
</P>
<P>
   2 16-ounce cans of tomatoes with juice
</P>
<P>
   2/3 cup white vinegar
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup orange juice
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup dark brown sugar, packed
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon each, paprika and chili powder
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons each, kosher salt and freshly ground black pepper.
</P>
<P>
   1. In a large, heavy-bottomed saucepan, heat the oil over medium
heat until hot but not smoking. Add the onion, and saute, stirring
frequently, until golden brown, about 7 to 10 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   2. Add the tomato puree, tomatoes, vinegar, orange juice, brown
sugar, paprika, chili powder and salt and pepper, and bring to
boil. Reduce heat to very low, and simmer, uncovered, at lowest
possible heat for 1 hour, stirring every once in a while to prevent
scorching.
</P>
<P>
   3. In a food processor or blender, puree the sauce, in batches
if necessary.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: about 2 pints.
</P>
<P>
   CHEATER-STYLE BARBECUED RIBS
</P>
<P>
   Time: 4 1/2 hours, plus 24 hours' brining
</P>
<P>
   2 full racks of pork spareribs, about 3 pounds to a rack
</P>
<P>
   Smoky brine (see recipe)
</P>
<P>
   Barbecue spice rub (see recipe)
</P>
<P>
   Basic barbecue sauce (see recipe).
</P>
<P>
   1. Place the ribs in the bucket, very large roasting pan or
other container holding the brine. Make sure the ribs are
completely covered. Refrigerate them for 24 hours, turning them
once after 12 hours.
</P>
<P>
   2. Heat oven to 200 degrees. Remove ribs from brine, dry with
paper towels, and rub all over with the spice rub, pressing
slightly to be sure it adheres. Put ribs on baking sheets, place in
oven, and cook for 4 1/2 hours or until ribs are very tender.
Remove, and serve, passing the basic barbecue sauce for diners to
apply as they wish.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 6 servings.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
