<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Wednesday, March 17, sent to computer graphics clients of The New
York Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
(mk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST
</P>
<P>
   Air heated on descent from the Rocky Mountains enveloped the
west-central Plains Tuesday, boosting temperatures to near 80
degrees in western Nebraska. On Wednesday, breezes from the West
will direct the unseasonable warmth into much of the Eastern
states. Indeed, beneath plenty of sunshine, daytime readings will
approach 70 degrees as far north as Washington, D.C. Farther north,
snow cover will temper the warmth a bit over the interior Northeast
and eastern Great Lakes where readings will average in the 50s.
</P>
<P>
   A slow-moving, high-altitude low pressure system will bring
inclement weather to portions of the Southwest and Texas on
Wednesday. A pocket of cold air associated with the low will cause
snow to fall in sections of northern New Mexico and extreme
southern Colorado. Several inches of new snow is likely by evening
in the Sandia and Sangre de Cristo Mountain ranges.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, scattered rain showers will dampen the lower
elevations of New Mexico and the Texas panhandle as moist breezes
from the Gulf of Mexico develop. As the upper low center encounters
the moistened air, rain will turn heavy later Wednesday night and
Thursday across Texas and the lower Mississippi Valley. Local
flooding is possible.
</P>
<P>
   Light snow will accompany another low pressure system near the
Minnesota-Canada border with spotty rain showers occurring farther
east over northern Michigan. Elsewhere, rain will arrive near the
Pacific Northwest coast by evening while mild and dry conditions
cover California and Nevada.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Beginning of the End
</P>
<P>
   March marks the beginning of the end of the rainy season in
Southern California as the jet stream, which carries
precipitation-producing disturbances, begins an inexorable
northward migration. Time for rain is running out. By April,
chances will decrease dramatically. Most of Southern California's
precipitation falls during late autumn and winter, but this season
has been dry. On Monday, 0.45 inches fell at Los Angeles, bringing
the city's seasonal total to only 4.78 inches. Normal-to-date
rainfall is 12.35 inches. By March 15, 1998, 23.59 inches of rain
had fallen at Los Angeles.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
