<SLUG> BC-WINE-TASTINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A WARM PORT 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Rozes Port, 40 Years Old, Oporto, Portugal. About $120.
</P>
<P>
   For reasons known best to the tradition-bound port trade, there
is absolutely no mention on the bottle of this wine that it is, in
fact, an aged tawny. The label says only that it is 40 years old.
And that isn't entirely true.
</P>
<P>
   The average age of all the wines in the blend is more than 40
years but some are quite young. Tawnies can be ``refreshed'' with
younger wines as they mature in casks. Younger wines can also be
blended in shortly before bottling. The name tawny comes from the
brownish color the wine acquires as it ages in barrels. This wine
is warm and rich with a distinctive nutty flavor.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
