<DOCNO> NYT19990316.0172 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-16 17:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2577 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AFRICA-BOOK-REVIEW-NY     03-16 0625
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AFRICA-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.Y.)  
 TO AFRICA, THROUGH ITS FOOD 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By FLORENCE FABRICANT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Jessica Harris' first trip to Africa, when she was 24, was a
``going home'' to the West Africa of her roots. It was her
introduction to a continent of vast geographic and ethnic
diversity, which she has revisited many times since that first trip
in 1972. Those trips, and the foods she sampled in her travels, are
recounted in her new book, ``The Africa Cookbook: Tastes of a
Continent'' (Simon &AMP; Schuster, $25).
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Harris, a historian and professor of English at Queens
College in New York, who has written other cookbooks, dares the
reader to confront preconceptions about the continent. Her chapter
on the history of African food, for example, is called ``Beyond
Bare-Breasted Maidens and Cannibal Cooks.''
</P>
<P>
   As for food history, she points out that Egypt had Africa's
first high-class cuisine, as ancient wall paintings showing ducks
being force-fed seem to prove. But don't look for foie gras recipes
in this book. Despite a few production numbers calling for multiple
meats and every vegetable on the produce stand, the clearly written
recipes are mainly for simple preparations, with garlic and chilies
the dominant seasonings.
</P>
<P>
   The North African recipes show their basis in refined Islamic
traditions, and are complex and sophisticated. Adding orange flower
water to fresh orange juice, for example, is an inspired Moroccan
notion. To my palate, the recipes from other parts of Africa seemed
to cry out for finishing touches, like the chopped cilantro I could
not resist adding, for color and flavor, to the jagacida, a meat
and bean stew with rice from the Cape Verde Islands, and to the
delicious Kenyan curried corn with coconut. Many vegetable recipes,
like kale with chili and garlic, were more appealing than the
starchy porridge dishes and fritters.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Harris writes about ingredients like okra and black-eyed
peas, which came to the Americas in the holds of slave ships and
influenced cooking here.
</P>
<P>
   And she does not shy away from the influence that contact with
Europeans had on Africa's cuisine over the centuries, identifying
it in dishes like baked crab: though it is from the Nigerian
province of Benin, it is European in style.
</P>
<P>
   Though Ms. Harris didn't set out to present only authentic
non-Europeanized dishes, she observes that an appreciation for
native cuisines grew after countries achieved independence. Because
she examines Africa mainly on a regional basis, a reader wanting to
understand how, for example, the cooking of Senegal differs from
that of Ghana, will not get much help here.
</P>
<P>
   A glossary of ingredients and utensils, and an excellent list of
sources for exotica like bitter leaf (a spinach-like herb), make
the book extremely user-friendly.
</P>
<P>
   BENIN-STYLE BAKED CRAB
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from ``The Africa Cookbook''
</P>
<P>
   Time: 45 minutes
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon unsalted butter
</P>
<P>
   2 pounds fresh lump crab meat
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup minced scallions
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup minced parsley
</P>
<P>
   1 cup chopped tomato
</P>
<P>
   2 eggs
</P>
<P>
   2 cloves garlic, minced
</P>
<P>
   1 stalk celery, minced
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon tomato-based hot sauce, or to taste
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup stale crumbs from French bread.
</P>
<P>
   1. Preheat oven to 350 degrees. Lightly butter 6 6-ounce
ramekins or empty, well-washed crab shells.
</P>
<P>
   2. Combine crab meat, scallions, parsley, tomato, eggs, garlic,
celery and hot sauce in a bowl, and mix. Season to taste with salt
and pepper. Stir in half the bread crumbs. Divide mixture among
ramekins, and sprinkle with remaining bread crumbs. Bake about 25
minutes, until lightly browned on top.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 6 servings.
</P>
</TEXT>
