<HEADLINE>
TRACKING DOWN THE ARTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, March 21)  
 (bl)  
 By L.R. SHANNON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   www.culturefinder.com
</P>
<P>
   Culturefinder is an online directory of mostly live
entertainment _ theater, classical music, opera, dance and jazz _
as well as museums. You can find events practically anywhere in the
United States and, for a $4.50 fee, buy a ticket to them. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The numbers claimed, 300,000 events in more than 1,000 cities in
the United States, are so impressive that they are difficult to
believe. I didn't know there were 1,000 ``cities'' in the United
States, so I looked up the town of about 11,000 people I live in
and found it, with an event listed but no further information. At
any rate, Culturefinder has full listings and ticket services,
including discounts, for seven cities: New York, Los Angeles,
Chicago, Boston, San Francisco, Philadelphia and Washington. (Five
more cities are scheduled to be added in March: Atlanta,
Dallas-Fort Worth, Houston, Miami and Minneapolis.)
</P>
<P>
   I requested arts events in New York City from March 21 to 28.
After a few minutes _ minutes, not seconds _ a calendar with 1,784
events appeared: ``The Great Hollywood Studios,'' a musical revue
at the 92nd Street Y; a graduation recital by Erin Elstner, a
percussionist, at the Mannes College of Music; Marcel Marceau at
the Sylvia and Danny Kaye Playhouse at Hunter College; ``Lewis
Wickes Hine: the Final Years,'' a photography exhibit at the
Brooklyn Museum of Art, and ``Macbeth'' at the American Place
Theater, a full and varied list indeed.
</P>
<P>
   ZOOMING INTO THE PARK
</P>
<P>
   The first day of spring is a perfect time to start thinking
about national parks, and Maptech's National Park Digital Guide on
CD-ROMs provides a lot of information to ponder on all 54 of them. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The CDs are loaded with maps, both 1:24,000-scale and
1:100,000-scale topographic maps from the U.S. Geological Survey
and the official National Park Service maps. As you move across a
map with the cursor, the coordinates change on the screen, and you
can zoom in for more detail or zoom out for the big picture. The
maps are sharp and colorful _ how sharp and colorful depends on
your computer and display _ and they pop up fairly swiftly for a
CD-based program. The computer should be a 486 or better running
Windows 95, 98 or NT, with at least 16 megabytes of RAM and,
obviously, a CD-ROM drive. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Besides the maps, the disks contain a wealth of information
about the parks _ activities, plants and animals, trails, history,
reservation information, among other things, including such
services as restaurants and accommodations outside each park. The
trails section, for example, lists each trail by length and level
of difficulty, and you can trace each one on the screen to get a
sense of how tough it is. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Much of this information is also offered at Parknet, the
National Parks Web site at www.nps.gov, but not, for instance, the
Geological Survey maps. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A CD for one park is $29.50. There are six regional sets at
$69.50 each, and you can get all 54 parks for $179.50. The parks
can be sampled, and disks ordered, at the Web site,
www.maptech.com/topo; Maptech's phone number is (800) 627-7236.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
