</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STUDENT-OSCAR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOVE AFTER 60 COULD LEAD TO AN OSCAR AT 32 
</HEADLINE>
  
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.) (dal) 
 By FELICIA R. LEE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   They talked about wanting love and sex and the need just to have
someone to hold them. They talked about what the world looks like
for someone who is 75 or 80 and alone. When a group of elderly
members of a Lower East Side theater group shared the most intimate
details of their lives, their stories were powerful enough to
persuade a student filmmaker, Keiko Ibi, to turn her senior thesis
into a documentary, and it has been nominated for an Oscar.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Ibi is a 32-year-old native of Tokyo who received a Master
of Fine Arts from New York University last year and is married to
another filmmaker, Greg Pak. ``The Personals: Improvisations on
Romance in the Golden Years,'' Ms. Ibi's first documentary, is
nominated in the documentary short subject category.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really surreal,'' Ms. Ibi said of her nomination and the
flurry of telephone calls, e-mail media interviews and inquiries
about what she would wear to the Sunday night Academy Awards
ceremony in Los Angeles. (A designer dress, ``simple, purple, with
an Oriental flair.'')
</P>
<P>
   A thin woman with thick black hair and an open, relaxed manner,
Ms. Ibi seems giddy these days, as well she might. It is rare for a
student thesis to win an Oscar nomination, and ``The Personals''
has been shown at some 15 film and video festivals and has won six
awards.
</P>
<P>
   The project started in 1996 when Ms. Ibi took a basic acting
class with Seth Glassman, then the director of the Alliance Stage
Co. He invited the class to a party at his home, where Ms. Ibi met
the actors from his theater company.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were really funny,'' Ms. Ibi said. ``They wanted my
attention. They took my hand and said, `Oh, I met this girl.' One
talked about his open-heart surgery. I was intrigued right away.''
</P>
<P>
   Every Wednesday Ms. Ibi went to the Educational Alliance, a
settlement house, community center and social service agency on the
Lower East Side. She would spend about two hours filming the men
and women as they rehearsed an original play about looking for love
in the personal advertising columns. She also went home with them
and started hearing their stories about the role of love and sex in
their real lives.
</P>
<P>
   ``As I saw them on the stage,'' she said, ``I started to wonder:
`How are they at home? Are they alone?' I think fundamentally they
really liked me. I didn't ask, `How's your sex life?' I started
with where were you born, tell me about your parents. As they
became more relaxed, they opened up to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Ibi added: ``They were at the time of their lives they just
wanted to be happy. They just wanted to be themselves and find an
outlet to express themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   They did. The 37-minute film captures one man putting in his
dentures and another talking about his impotence. The women talk
about going into marriage as virgins and their disappointments in
lovemaking. Another man with neither a wife nor children wonders
what his life has meant and if he will die lonely. A couple, both
disabled, talk about how they met.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Ibi has stayed in touch with her new friends and says they
all liked the film. One of them, Fred Schecter, died recently, and
his family told Ms. Ibi the film was a comfort to them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love her,'' Rose Straub, one of the women in the film, said
of Ms. Ibi. ``I wish to God she was my daughter.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The film is excellent,'' she said. ``What you saw in the film
was me. We were really very honest and frank in that film. I'm not
ashamed; what I put in that film was my life. I was brought up very
strict. We were not taught how to handle a man.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Straub, who is 80 and has a 43-year-old son and two
grandchildren, said she has had suitors since ``Personals'' was
released but is becoming tired of the whole business.
</P>
<P>
   ``At our age there's not the respect they gave their wives,''
she said. ``They're offering you nothing. This last man I'm going
with, all he talks about is his wife, his wife, his wife. She's
dead already six years.''
</P>
<P>
   Selma Wernick, who is seen in the film talking about her former
husband's impotence and her affair with a married man, said she was
pleased with ``The Personals'' and wanted her children to see it.
Ms. Wernick is 74, and her son and daughter are in the their 50s.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the film is wonderful,'' she said. ``I think it gives
out two messages. Seniors are like everyone else. The other message
is, there is life after retirement.''
</P>
<P>
   Like any good filmmaker, Ms. Ibi has her own story to tell. It
starts in Tokyo where she was the only child of a couple, now
divorced, who worked in real estate. She had always found delight
in American films. Some of her favorites were ``The Godfather,''
``Gone With the Wind'' and ``Chinatown.''
</P>
<P>
   She studied literature at Japan Women's University and won the
title of Miss Japan Grand Prix as a 19-year-old beauty contestant.
She also took acting class, directed school plays and finally
begged her mother for permission to go to New York to study film.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Ibi enrolled at Syracuse University in 1991 and became a
film major. ``I was learning the language, learning the culture,''
she recalled.
</P>
<P>
   She transferred to N.Y.U. in 1993 in part because of its film
program's reputation. Its graduates include Spike Lee, Martin
Scorsese and Oliver Stone. In no time, Ms. Ibi recalled, she had
stopped wearing full makeup each day, had stashed away her pink
sweaters and become a true downtown New Yorker.
</P>
<P>
   No matter what happens at the Academy Awards ceremonies ``The
Personals'' will have its television premiere on HBO in June. Ms.
Ibi said the network editors helped her cut her original 79-minute
version of the film, which came from 70 hours of tape.
</P>
<P>
   Her mother, who put up most of the money for the film, is now
convinced that sending her daughter to the United States was not a
bad thing. Meantime Ms. Ibi is completing a feature-length
screenplay and is about to begin a new documentary.
</P>
<P>
   ``Keiko is destined to do wonderful things,'' said David K.
Irving, chairman of the undergraduate film and television program
at the Tisch School of the Arts at N.Y.U. He was acting graduate
chairman of the department when Ms. Ibi presented several cuts of
her film. ``She is so unassuming, she is so pleasant,'' Irving
said. ``Her persona is such that you can tell her anything.''
</P>
</TEXT>
