<HEADLINE>
KGIL PICKS UP ADULT BLEND OF '50S_'70S HITS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRED SHUSTER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The adult standards format produced by Westwood
One and featured on KLAC-AM (570) from 1994 through 1998 will
resurface on KGIL-AM (1260) for a two-station simulcast.
</P>
<P>
   The format, which propelled KLAC from a .5 to a 2.6 share, will
be exclusive to KGIL. The program director is Chick Watkins, who
will also helm the midday shift, spinning the music of the '50s,
'60s and '70s.
</P>
<P>
   KGIL will feature the music of Nat King Cole through March 29,
when the new format kicks off on two frequencies _ 1260-AM and
1650-AM (replacing all-traffic KKTR).
</P>
<P>
   Mornings on KGIL will be hosted by Jeff Rollins, who has worked
in radio on both coasts and was once evening traffic anchor at
all-news KFWB-AM (980).
</P>
<P>
   After the Westwood One format left KLAC late last year, the
station switched to a music mix it calls ``standards, swing and big
band,'' anchored by Charlie Tuna in morning drive. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Around the dial: Modern-rock programmer Mike Halloran, formerly of
KROQ-FM (106.7) and San Diego's 91X, takes over the afternoon shift
and the assistant program director desk at KLYY-FM (107.1) _ Y107 _
on Monday. ... San Diego radio executive Michael Steele succeeds
Tracy Austin at KIIS-FM (102.7) as assistant program director and
music director. Austin moved to a Hartford, Conn., station as
program director. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
