<DOCNO> NYT19990316.0183 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-16 17:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2619 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEMECULA-WINERIES-LAD     03-16 2050
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEMECULA-WINERIES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE FINE IS WINE IN TEMECULA VALLEY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Has sidebar slugged TEMECULA-DRIVING) 
By ERIC NOLAND  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMECULA _ Go on a weekend _ but only if you must.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike its cousins to the north in Napa and Sonoma counties, the
Temecula Valley wine country is bracketed by two major metropolitan
areas _ Los Angeles and San Diego. Thus, some 18 million people
live within 100 miles of this narrow swath of vineyards in
southwestern Riverside County, and on most weekends it seems as if
a good percentage of them have crammed into the tasting rooms of
the 12 wineries here.
</P>
<P>
   If your schedule can be juggled to allow for a weekday visit,
that is a much more advisable course. Tasting rooms tend to be much
less crowded, and winery personnel have more time to relax, visit
and enlighten you on the history and traits of the wines they've
slaved to bottle.
</P>
<P>
   But even on busy weekends, this region has its charms. Most of
the wineries _ gargantuan Callaway the notable exception _ are
small, mom-and-pop operations, bottling only a few thousand cases
of wine per year. These micro wineries may dabble in a few sales in
nearby San Diego, but they don't even bother trying to crack the
daunting Los Angeles market.
</P>
<P>
   So the Temecula Valley is the only place to find some of these
wines. And several of them will reward you for your drive (about 90
miles from downtown L.A.).
</P>
<P>
   ``Most varietals do very well down there because of the long
growing period during the summer,'' said Tim Bekins, senior wine
buyer for the Trader Joe's chain of gourmet markets. ``The weather
is constant. They don't have to worry about rain destroying or
watering down the vineyards. It stays sunny so long down there. It
raises the sugar tremendously. That way, they have these fully ripe
fruits when they harvest. I think they do very well with cabs and
chars (cabernets and chardonnays).''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps because most visitors from Los Angeles and San Diego
treat this wine region as a day trip, Temecula has plenty of room
for improvement in lodging and dining experiences. That was evident
during a three-day visit last month.
</P>
<P>
   Following is a guide to select wineries, lodgings and
restaurants. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
WINERIES
</P>
<P>
   Callaway: This is Temecula's behemoth, bottling an estimated
260,000 cases annually (a winery spokeswoman said she wasn't at
liberty to divulge the actual figure; the only one of 12 Temecula
wineries unwilling to do so). Since its wines are on the shelves of
neighborhood Ralphs and on the menus of California-cuisine grills
throughout the state, name recognition is extreme, and Callaway
often fills every square foot of its cavernous tasting room.
</P>
<P>
   The wines here are outstanding, laden with high ranks by wine
magazines and silver and bronze medals from various county fairs
(including Los Angeles'). But the high quality of the wines is
about the only inducement to visit this winery.
</P>
<P>
   On a Sunday, the tasting room was crowded and impersonal. On a
return visit the next day, it was empty and impersonal. Employees
seemed infinitely more interested in arranging a collection of
bottles and chattering over their plans for the evening than
engaging four visitors in conversation about their product.
</P>
<P>
   And when one visitor used up her allotted four tastes on
Callaway's superb array of white wines, she was rebuffed when she
offered to pay another tasting fee to sample a couple of the reds.
``Only one tasting per person,'' came the curt recitation of
company policy.
</P>
<P>
   Cilurzo: The antithesis of the Callaway experience.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1960s, when Vince Cilurzo was a senior lighting director
for the ABC television network in Los Angeles, he and wife Audrey
sought an escape from the urban madness and found it here in a
parcel of the former Vail cattle ranch. In the spring of 1968, they
planted several rows of petite sirah grapes, and Temecula's first
commercial vineyard was born. (Eli Callaway, now of golf-club fame,
followed shortly with the region's first winery.)
</P>
<P>
   On the recent visit, Audrey herself conducted a tour of the
winemaking operation, looking as if she had just put aside her
work, wiped the grape juice off her hands and emerged from the
cellar to meet guests.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, the tasting experience on both a Sunday and a Monday
was like walking into someone's kitchen, as Cilurzo employees
enthused over each bottle like doting parents.
</P>
<P>
   Audrey indicated a bottle of Cilurzo's 1997 Merlot Reserve. ``We
sent a barrel sample to Orange County (for last year's fair),'' she
said, ``and they called back and said, `When are you going to
bottle this?' Vince said, `Not for a while.' And they said, `Well,
we're not supposed to tell you this, but it's going to win a big
medal, but it will be disqualified if it's not in a bottle.'''
</P>
<P>
   It was promptly bottled. It promptly won a four-star gold medal
at the fair.
</P>
<P>
   Hart: This winery is so unassuming it hasn't even gotten around
to paving its driveway off Rancho California Road, which made for a
spinning, splattering ride through the mud on a rainy day.
</P>
<P>
   Once inside, you're rewarded with a tasting room that is little
more than a corner of the actual winemaking operation, with
stainless-steel fermenting tanks and oak casks all around.
</P>
<P>
   The atmosphere is accordingly friendly, and the wines _
particularly the 1996 Syrah and 1995 Zinfandel _ were well worth
the mud bath.
</P>
<P>
   Mount Palomar: Plan your day so that lunch is a picnic here.
Follow either a dirt driving road or a walking path from the
parking lot to a hilltop collection of picnic tables at the edge of
a citrus grove. The view to the east of Temecula's rolling hills
won't disappoint you.
</P>
<P>
   Neither will the tasting room, where Terri Bennett cheerfully
held forth recently, offering a wealth of information about the
effect of El Nino, the traits of Temecula's soil and the vines that
flourish in it, and the winery's experimentation with such European
vines as sangiovese from Italy's Chianti region, sirah from
France's Rhone Valley, and cortese, the northern Italy varietal
that yields such a delightfully crisp white wine.
</P>
<P>
   If you forgot to pack provisions for your picnic, don't despair.
Mount Palomar has a fully stocked deli where you can order
sandwiches or pick through the shelves and refrigerator cases to
assemble your lunch piecemeal.
</P>
<P>
   Temecula Crest: Wine snobs beware of Gus Vizgirda and Jim Lyle,
who were playfully hosting the tastings at this picturesque winery
on the top of a hill.
</P>
<P>
   After taking a sip of Temecula Crest's 1997 Chardonnay, which
won a gold medal at the California State Fair, a patron furrowed
his brow and said, ``It's not as buttery as most.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We use oleo, actually,'' Vizgirda deadpanned. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
LODGING
</P>
<P>
   Temecula Creek Inn: If you're staying the night in the Temecula
Valley, do whatever you can to get a room here _ the other
accommodations in the region can't touch it for comfort and
serenity.
</P>
<P>
   It is tucked between a golf course and a steep bank that climbs
to the 15 Freeway, but surprisingly, no freeway noise bleeds
through the thick doors of the rooms. Inside are some clever
touches, including window shutters and closet doors constructed
largely of twigs. For maximal comfort, try to wangle your way into
a junior suite.
</P>
<P>
   The grounds include a seldom-used pool and spa, and on chilly
winter mornings the lobby features a fireplace that crackles with a
real-wood blaze, a giant basket of fresh apples and Los Angeles
newspapers (though none, strangely, from San Diego).
</P>
<P>
   Alas, availability can be at a premium, since the hotel has only
80 rooms, but Doug James of the front-office staff said there is a
plan to add 20 new rooms and upgrade the existing ones within the
next year.
</P>
<P>
   Information and reservations: (909) 694-1000.
</P>
<P>
   Loma Vista Bed and Breakfast: The location can't be topped _ in
the heart of the wine country, at the crest of a hill, surrounded
by grapefruit groves.
</P>
<P>
   The service is cheerful, too, notably in the case of Sheila
Kurczynski, who owns and operates the inn with her husband Walt _
when he isn't off in Long Beach attending to his custom-car
business, Alterdyne.
</P>
<P>
   The Loma Vista's rooms are decorated to correspond to various
wine varietals, and there is a bottle of sherry and basket of fruit
in each one.
</P>
<P>
   Staying at a b&AMP;b, however, is like dropping in on your aunt and
uncle, and this kind of accommodation isn't for everyone. The Loma
Vista wasn't without its shortcomings one night last month.
</P>
<P>
   At 5 a.m., a puppy began whimpering to get in at a downstairs
door. It was pronounced. It sounded almost human. It precluded any
hope of sleep for nearly an hour.
</P>
<P>
   The inn's hot tub, meanwhile, was no warmer than tepid _ an
acute disappointment on a rainy night after a long day of
sightseeing. But worse, the contents of the tub were a kind of
chlorine cocktail _ perhaps 50 parts water to 50 parts chemicals
(or so it seemed). It bleached the pigment right out of one
swimsuit and left skin reeking of chlorine _ no exaggeration _ for
two days.
</P>
<P>
   Phone: (909) 676-7047. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
DINING
</P>
<P>
   Baily Wine Country Cafe: This establishment has a reputation for
some of the best food in the Temecula Valley, and it proved worthy
of it during a lunchtime visit.
</P>
<P>
   Raves were voiced for the crab cakes, the baked brie and such
unusual dishes as butternut-squash soup.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, this restaurant is located not amid the rolling
hills of the wine country, or anywhere near the winery itself, but
in a strip mall in town, by a Mobil gas station, a mattress store
and a Round Table Pizza joint. Ambience takes a severe beating in
such environs.
</P>
<P>
   Also, while the bill of fare understandably includes a broad
selection of Baily wines, an unmistakable conclusion was reached:
What Baily puts on the plate is vastly superior to what it puts in
the bottle.
</P>
<P>
   Phone: (909) 676-9567.
</P>
<P>
   Temet Grill: The restaurant at the Temecula Creek Inn came
highly recommended, but hotel eateries are usually guaranteed a
steady stream of new customers and thus have no great compulsion to
lure repeat ones. The Temet Grill, unfortunately, fell solidly into
this category.
</P>
<P>
   The food _ with the exception of a perfectly prepared and
presented filet mignon _ was ordinary, while the service alternated
between inattentive and downright surly.
</P>
<P>
   When the wine order was taken, for example, our table of four
voiced a preference for a merlot that had been sampled just two
hours before at Hart Winery. The waitress contradicted us and
strongly suggested a merlot from Australia's Deakin Estate. When we
insisted on the Hart, she visibly turned up her nose before
stalking off to fetch it.
</P>
<P>
   Phone: (909) 694-1000.
</P>
<P>
   Cafe Champagne: In dramatic contrast to the Temet Grill, this
appendage of the Thornton Winery was friendly to a fault.
Unfortunately, it was also overwhelmed.
</P>
<P>
   A waiter promptly explained that they had been busier than
expected this Sunday evening and were regrettably out of all of
their specials. It was 7:03 p.m. _ that must have been some early
rush; that, or management planned poorly.
</P>
<P>
   As at the Temet Grill, a filet mignon entree got the highest
compliment at the table. The consistent superiority of beef at
these restaurants indicates that Temecula's cattle-ranch heritage
remains strong. (At the turn of the century, Walter Vail
established a sprawling, 87,500-acre spread in this valley, and his
family worked it for six decades.)
</P>
<P>
   Two cioppino entrees, meanwhile, looked no larger than appetizer
portions _ maybe the restaurant was nearly out of seafood, too, and
was stretching things.
</P>
<P>
   And the waiter, though personable and earnest, was obviously
flustered. He bustled away after taking entree and wine orders, not
bothering to ask if salads were desired (they were). And for one
guest, a promised side vegetable never materialized to accent an
entree.
</P>
<P>
   Cafe Champagne's ambience is warm and inviting. A portion of the
kitchen is open to view, and the air of the entryway is filled with
enticing smells of the cookery. It is also perched on a ridge,
affording nice views to the north for those fortunate enough to
secure window tables.
</P>
<P>
   Phone: (909) 669-0099.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-16-99 1745EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990316.0184 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-16 17:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2623 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IOC-SCANDAL-0317-COX     03-16 0790
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IOC-SCANDAL-0317-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    UNDER PRESSURE, EMBATTLED IOC EXPECTED TO OUST SIX MEMBERS AT
MEETING
 &HT;    EDs: Optional add at 500 words.
 &HT;    Moving in both the International and Sports categories.
 &HT;    By BERT ROUGHTON JR. 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAUSANNE, Switzerland _ Eager to put the Salt Lake City bidding
crisis behind it, the International Olympic Committee Wednesday is
expected to expel six members accused of improperly accepting cash
and gifts during the campaign for the 2002 Games.
</P>
<P>
   If the 91-voting members approve the expulsions, it would be the
first time in 105 years that the IOC has forced any of its members
to give up their positions.
</P>
<P>
   Each accused member will have 20 minutes to address his
colleagues before the committee votes. A two-thirds vote, which
will be taken by secret ballot behind closed doors, is needed for
removal. The accused members will not be allowed to vote.
</P>
<P>
   The members recommended for expulsion are Siuli Paul Wallwork,
Western Samoa; Agustin Arroyo, Ecuador; Jean-Claude Ganga, Republic
of Congo; Zein El Abdin Ahmed Abdel Gadir, Sudan; Lamine Keita,
Mali; and Sergio Santander, Chile.
</P>
<P>
   Most have said they did nothing wrong and some have challenged
the legitimacy of the investigations that have condemned them.
</P>
<P>
   Anita DeFrantz, the senior U.S. IOC member, predicted Tuesday
that the session would be an emotionally wrenching experience.
``It's going to be difficult,'' she said, describing her own
feelings as reminding the former Olympic rower of ``that flutter in
my stomach the way I did on the starting line.''
</P>
<P>
   But she nevertheless believes the membership will expel the six
members accused of violating their Olympic oaths. She said that the
IOC members, who have been given copies of the 55-page report by
the internal commission that investigated the Salt Lake City
allegations, should have all they need to expel their colleagues.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reports are very, very clear if you read the report,'' she
said. ``Their actions were without honor.''
</P>
<P>
   DeFrantz received a letter from Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz.,
reminding her that Congress may act if the IOC does not take strong
enough measures during this week's emergency session.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the strongest terms, let me communicate to you my hope that
the IOC will move quickly to adopt reforms necessary to provide
transparency and accountability to the IOC organization and
processes,'' he wrote. ``Without such independent action, the
demand from Congress to act will be irrepressible.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain noted that the IOC enjoys special tax status that allows
it to pay no taxes as well as allowing corporate sponsors to write
off the cost of their sponsorships. McCain has said before that
these advantages could be removed if the IOC doesn't clean up its
act.
</P>
<P>
   IOC officials hope the gravity of expelling its members coupled
with clear indications that it will enact important reforms will be
enough to forestall an assault in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Even though the IOC clearly has some resentment toward what it
considers the heavy-handed moralizing coming from the United
States, its leaders are aware of the importance to them of U.S.
television networks, corporate sponsors and now, politicians.
</P>
<P>
   Francois Carrard, the IOC director general, acknowledged that
the IOC is paying close attention to events in Washington. ``We
have been following and reading the recommendations which we got
from various sources,'' he said. ``We believe that the action which
is being undertaken now should be of the nature to satisfy those
who are considering certain measures.''
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Also Tuesday, IOC officials raised the prospect that Kim
Un-yong, the IOC member from South Korea who has received a severe
warning for his actions related to the Salt Lake bid, may not be in
the clear.
</P>
<P>
   Kim's case was left open by a special inquiry commission that
released its findings last week. Dick Pound, the commission's
chairman, said his panel needed more information to know if Kim was
aware that a $70,000 telecommunications job for his son in Utah was
underwritten by Salt Lake Olympic bidders.
</P>
<P>
   Kim has denied any wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
   DeFrantz, who is a member of the executive board, confirmed
Tuesday that further action could be taken. ``There is still an
open case,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Another leading member who received a stern warning, Australian
Phil Coles, arrived in Lausanne on Tuesday and said he would not
resign mounting pressure in Australia for him to step down.
</P>
<P>
   ``No way, mate,'' a weary Coles told a reporter who asked if he
would step down.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-16-99 1748EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
