<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990316.0188 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-16 17:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2630 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HEAVY-METAL-2TAKES-NY     03-16 0999
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEAVY-METAL-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
METAL, NOT ALL HEAVY: THERE'S BLACK-METAL, DEATH-METAL, TOO 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(dal) 
 By BEN RATLIFF   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ASBURY PARK, N.J. _ ``What's up, Jersaay!'' screamed Matthew
Barlow, the long-haired singer for the heavy-metal band Iced Earth,
at the dark throng before him under the vast ceiling of the
Convention Hall here. It was the first night of the first annual
March Metal Meltdown and the crowd of mostly white working-class
teen-agers, dressed almost to a one in black, collectively
shuddered in response; the insulation in the hulking old building
was not working very well.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a little song about a guy who walked the earth about
2,000 years ago who went by the name of'' _ Barlow paused, then
growled, ``Messiah!''
</P>
<P>
   Some in the audience wore white face paint with inverted black
crosses on their foreheads; most wore T-shirts with band names like
Bloodfeast, Incantation and Hypocrisy printed in dripping,
illegible logos. Contrary to what might be expected, there were
plenty of women in attendance; the grimmer sub-genres of metal have
a lot of female fans, perhaps because the lyrics are not usually
aggressively misogynist.
</P>
<P>
   The fans had come from Eastern seaboard suburbs to hear the kind
of blasphemous stuff that has been driving parents absolutely crazy
for 30 years, since the emergence of Black Sabbath: songs about
witches, bloodthirsty warriors, devil worship, graveyards and the
secret cabalistic codes of long-dead civilizations.
</P>
<P>
   Among the bands were some the audience might never hear again,
among them the Swedish black-metal group Dimmu Borgir, or the
Norwegian Viking-metal band Enslaved, which performed in old Norse
tunics. There were 100 bands in all, spread out on three stages,
across two days of metal. Nonmetal diversions included Jasmin St.
Claire, an adult-film actress with eyelashes like blackboard
erasers who functioned as occasional mistress of ceremonies, and
two World Wrestling Federation wrestlers play-acting mortal
aggression in silent battle. Death-metal, sex stars, wrestling: the
subculture seemed to be flourishing.
</P>
<P>
   Metal has evolved at a creeping pace, its various splintered
genres hanging on through waxing and waning demand in the
marketplace. Metal used to be easily recognized: scary, sludgy,
pummeling stuff lacking any social or political agenda. Its current
status is uncertain because it can be unclear what metal is. Punk
and hip-hop have body-checked it from both sides, resulting in a
successful hybrid that promoters call ``heavy music.'' (Note the
absence of the word ``metal,'' with its bad-for-business loner
connotations.)
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Top 10 rock band Metallica crusades on behalf of
its own obscure tastes in metal, recording songs by British bands
of the early '80s who soldier on in front of European and Japanese
audiences with a bit of new-found respect. A half-dozen other
sub-genres _ fans love to come up with new prefixes to attach to
the word ``metal'' _ have small but devoted followings.
</P>
<P>
   The idea for the March Metal Meltdown, the first underground
heavy-metal festival on the East Coast, grew out of the Milwaukee
Metalfest, a yearly ritual of pizza, beer and face paint that will
enter its 13th year this summer. The same Wisconsin-based promoter,
Jack Koshik, is behind both events; he compares them to the big
wrestling spectacles.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Milwaukee were Wrestlemania,'' he said, ``March Metal
Meltdown would be King of the Ring.''
</P>
<P>
   But March Metal Meltdown is clearly intended to grow into a
bigger moneymaker than Milwaukee, connecting new mainstream and old
underground metal as it does. The turnout, estimated by Koshik at
3,500, seemed slight for a festival with big-name headliners like
Sepultura and Biohazard; the Milwaukee festival, with far more
obscure bands, drew almost twice that number last year. The
festival was organized too late to run advertisements in the heavy
metal magazines.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the enormous stylistic range in the music played turned
away more fans than it lured. Performing in the festival were four
bands from the early '80s genre which has geekishly been termed
N.W.O.B.H.M., for New Wave of British Heavy Metal; some younger
new-metal bands like Spineshank and Madball that work on the line
between metal and hardcore punk; black-metal bands (black as in
dark and dismal, with haunted-house keyboard arpeggios and growled
vocals _ this is where the face paint comes in) and straight
meat-and-potatoes, hard and fast death-metal.
</P>
<P>
   Velocity and rhythm determined one's place along the spectrum of
metal fandom. The N.W.O.B.H.M. bands have an old-fashioned,
thrashing and rolling bar-band rhythm. The young new-metal bands
play a fast, whomping, unfunky version of funk with barbed-wire
guitar tone and no solos. The music by black-metal bands has a
slow, sloppy feeling, like walking through a pond of eyeliner.
Death-metal, the fastest, sprints by with double-timed bass drums
making your heart palpitate; the preponderance of the little
boomlets you feel in your chest makes the music sound arrhythmic.
</P>
<P>
   Each kind of rhythm produces a different fan, but the clearest
difference at Metal Meltdown was between the black-metal fans and
the hip-hop-inspired devotees of new metal. Black-metal fans are
pallid and withdrawn, letting the theatrical shows of bands like
Sweden's Dimmu Borgir stimulate their morbid inner fantasies.
New-metal bands, with their heavy-handed, hip-hop-inspired
drummers, evoke a bullyingly physical feeling, and accordingly,
some of its fans are high school jocks. As everybody knows, jocks
and raven-obsessed romantic poets don't mix. (``Saturday Night
Live'' devoted a long-running skit called ``Goth Talk'' to this
notion.) Yet here they were, their constituents commingling in the
middle of nowhere.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   Why Asbury Park? Koshik said that it was merely central, between
New York and Philadelphia and convenient for all the suburbs in
between. But an unintended benefit of putting March Metal Meltdown
in the connected theaters on the boardwalk was that the places
themselves felt incredibly heavy metal: formerly palatial, now
dark, crumbly, moody. (Bruce Springsteen and the E Street Band have
been rehearsing for a tour in the Convention Hall.)
</P>
<P>
   The theaters were full of floral-patterned ironwork and ancient
wooden doors. The structures have not been renovated or redesigned:
they have a raw look, with peeling paint and dim, fluorescent light
that threw a perfect hazy pallor on the crowd. And it was cold,
especially in the section between the two theaters where a third
stage had been built and record labels and fanzines had set up
their booths. For much of the weekend fans could see their breath
indoors.
</P>
<P>
   There is endless philosophical conversation in the culture of
heavy metal about whether the genre died and came back or whether
it had just been quiescent. The debate, in its various
trajectories, fills up most issues of underground metal fanzines
like Metal Core and Promethean Crusade, and festival musicians
chewed over the issue at news conferences.
</P>
<P>
   Billy Graziadei, the singer from the punk/metal hybrid band
Biohazard, took issue with the idea of metal's ever having gone
away. ``It's not re-emerging,'' he said. ``It's redefining. Metal
and heavy music have never died. The industry has wanted to make it
seem like it died so that maybe they could revive it.'' (He may
have been thinking about recent VH-1 ``Behind the Music'' and
``Where Are They Now?'' segments depicting the the waxing and
waning market shares of passe heavy-metal bands as personal drama.)
``But there's always aggression, always pressure in people, and
heavy music has been a way to release that energy.''
</P>
<P>
   The New Wave of British Heavy Metal bands did not have such
ponderous axes to grind, other than poking fun at ``heavy'' bands
whose members are half their age; now in their 40s, most were happy
to have been invited. These were bands that toiled in working-class
towns of northern England and Ireland in the early 1980s; a few,
like Judas Priest and Def Leppard, made it to stardom, but most did
not.
</P>
<P>
   Raven, which found some recognition in the early '80s, came from
Newcastle, England. ``In Newcastle, the only rock bands were Raven,
Fist and Venom,'' said Raven's bassist, John Gallagher. ``But all
over the country each town had one or two bands, and pretty much
all of them ended up coming to some kind of notoriety.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We played in a circuit of working men's clubs,'' he said.
``People who were over 18 could join these clubs to get cheap beer
and play bingo. So we'd come on stage and go, `Aargh!''' _
Gallagher bobbed his head and mimicked power-chording a guitar,
then jerked his head up _ ``and then say, `See you after the
bingo!' We'd come off, they'd have 20 minutes of bingo where you
could hear a pin drop and we'd go back on again and go, `Aargh!'''
</P>
<P>
   The uptick of interest in the genre in the United States results
partly from the influence of Lars Ulrich of Metallica, an early fan
of the music. He has endorsed these bands by performing versions of
their songs with Metallica, including ``Blitzkrieg,'' by
Blitzkrieg.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Hasselvander of Raven and Davey Bates of Sweet Savage agreed
that Ulrich's advocacy was the main reason they were playing at an
American festival. Sweet Savage is one of the ultimate cult bands
of metal: it made only two singles and a small number of tours
before it disbanded. For Metal Meltdown, they played to a small but
devoted audience in the Paramount Theater here on Saturday night;
those who knew the songs filled up the first few rows and the rest
of the crowd looked on with mild curiosity.
</P>
<P>
   There was talk that Dimmu Borgir, the headliner of Friday
night's concerts, had lip-synched its way through its set. But it
was hard to tell because the vocals of the lead singer, Shagrath,
were so heavily treated with echo and delay effects, as well as the
processed monster-growl that remains a trademark of the black-metal
and death-metal genres. There were cold echoes around Convention
Hall; it was unusually quiet between songs. (There was no beer
available on Friday, and the sound engineering had been a comedy of
errors.)
</P>
<P>
   ``This one deals with temptation,'' proclaimed spike-booted
Shagrath, keeping a game face behind the white paint. ``And it's
called . . . `Reptile'!'' ``Glowing eyes, staring eyes,'' he sang,
``manifest of evil presence/with entities swept in disease and
decay/a fall from paradise beyond redemption/wrathchild's
afterglow.''
</P>
<P>
   But two of the new bands delivered the best sets of the weekend,
perhaps auguring that metal is changing in a way that is not merely
a watering-down. Candiria, from Brooklyn, made its complicated
stop-start compositions skitter all over the place, even using some
jazz rhythms. And the Puerto Rican band Puya moved with striking
smoothness between metal and salsa, teaching a crowd uninterested
in dancing how to clap in Latin rhythm.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
