NYT-03-16-99 1800EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990316.0191 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-16 18:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2634 &Cx1f; ttg-z
a l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SWARTZ-COLUMN-$ADV23-     03-16 0914
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SWARTZ-COLUMN-$ADV23-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COLUMN: CENTURY OF THE WOMAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Tuesday, March 23)  
(Eds.: Please note that the word AT within parentheses has been
used in the end note instead of the symbol, which is
non-transmittable to many newspaper systems.) 
(mk) 
 By SUSAN SWARTZ   
 Santa Rosa (Calif.) Press Democrat   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Time is running out if you want to be named to one of those
lists of most important or influential women of the 20th century.
Unless you discover a cure for one of the horrible diseases or
become world famous overnight (having sex with a famous man doesn't
count), the spots are pretty much secured by the likes of Mother
Teresa, Margaret Sanger and Toni Morrison.
</P>
<P>
   Most will have to settle for being among the unsung or at least
getting their honors in smaller venues, which is OK except then you
don't get your photo taken by Annie Liebowitz.
</P>
<P>
   Is it too late to declare this the century of the woman? Not to
ignore the major achievements by men in the last 100 years, but men
did start out with the advantage and held it at least for the first
two-thirds. Women started out the century not expected to have much
of an impact.
</P>
<P>
   The 21st century will begin with a more level playing field,
except for pay discrepancies and a few other challenges. But women
have managed to catch up quite a bit in the last 100 years and, if
we're lucky, by the end of the next there may be no need for
separate lists.
</P>
<P>
   There are some things we won't have to worry about achieving.
Many of the ``firsts'' have been taken care of, although we're
still waiting for the first woman president. Many of the 20th
century's high achievers among women were first-timers. The first
woman Supreme Court justice and secretary of state; the first woman
to fly solo across the Atlantic; the first to go up in space.
</P>
<P>
   The ones who don't get on lists made less visible but
significant contributions to women's progress. The first woman
hired on a construction crew, the first woman to run a car
dealership. Ordinary firsts won't make you famous, though they
might have gotten you a feature story in your local paper.
</P>
<P>
   To win the kind of acclaim that gets you on lists of essential
women you have to do something outstanding in the fields of
science, politics or literature. You have to contribute to the
greater good in a lasting way, which explains why they often
mention Billie Holiday, because she changed the role of ``girl
singer'' from accompanist to star and introduced a whole new jazz
sound.
</P>
<P>
   It does not explain why Madonna gets named as one of the 100
most important women of the century.
</P>
<P>
   Some influential names don't court fame but win it anyhow. Anita
Hill's accusations against her former boss focused the country's
attention on sexual harassment. Betty Ford certainly didn't plan on
becoming an activist for substance abuse and breast cancer
awareness, yet when the first lady showed her vulnerability she
made it safe for others to get help.
</P>
<P>
   First lady Hillary Rodham Clinton shows up on
women-of-the-century lists. Monica Lewinsky does not.
</P>
<P>
   It's the women way back in the early 1900s that amaze the most.
That they could achieve anything besides dinner was a marvel,
considering how little society expected from them.
</P>
<P>
   Being educated was a risk. You might not find a husband if you
were too smart. You could be forced into an arranged marriage. You
were supposed to provide sex but weren't supposed to enjoy it, and
you had no choice in when to have your babies.
</P>
<P>
   Every March during Women's History Month there are stories about
women who defied social custom in order to use their talent and
brains. They struggled without advocates, the vote or unions. In
addition, they had to wear layers of annoying underwear and never
cut their hair.
</P>
<P>
   And they had a shorter time to get it done. Life expectancy for
women at the beginning of the century was 51, compared to 79 now.
</P>
<P>
   Even long after they were enfranchised, there were
gender-specific prohibitions for a woman who wanted more. Betty
Friedan got fired from her newspaper job for being pregnant.
Supreme Court Justice Ruth Bader Ginsburg was ridiculed by her law
professor for taking up a man's spot in class. Geneticist Barbara
McClintock's mother worried that her love for science would make
her unwelcome in society.
</P>
<P>
   But they all had their ways and they will translate well into
the next century. The legendary women of the 20th century, like
Oprah Winfrey and Billie Jean King, did not wait to be given what
they deserved. They were not shy, modest or repressed. They were
stubborn, spirited, smart and often loud.
</P>
<P>
   Ignoring the fact that Princess Diana keeps making
women-of-the-century lists, as do a number of movie stars, many
real achievers were not pretty, young or thin. They were not all
rich or white. They didn't set fashion trends, except for Amelia
Earhart's pleated trousers and Florence Griffith-Joyner's bicolor
running shorts.
</P>
<P>
   They were as crusading as Rachel Carson, as fearless as Dolores
Huerta, as tough as Shirley Chisolm.
</P>
<P>
   As to why Roseanne shows up on the same most-admired list as
Eleanor Roosevelt, it only proves that over the last 100 years,
women have also developed their sense of irony.
</P>
<P>
   (Susan Swartz is a columnist for The Press Democrat in Santa
Rosa, Calif. Her e-mail address is sfswartz(AT)pressdemo.com. This
story was distributed by the New York Times News Service.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
