<SLUG> BC-CHILD-CARE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSE DEMOCRATS AIM TO BOOST FEDERAL CHILD-CARE FUNDING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service Clients.)  
 By JENNIFER CORBETT DOOREN  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ House Democrats began a push Tuesday to help
moderate- income people pay for child-care costs by proposing to
boost federal funding for child-care subsidies and making more
families eligible for child-care tax credits.
</P>
<P>
   ``I repeatedly hear from my constituents that finding
affordable, high-quality, child care is virtually impossible,''
said Rep. Ellen Tauscher, D-Calif., chief architect of the
Democrats' child-care legislation.
</P>
<P>
   Day-care costs average $4,000 to $10,000 per child per year,
according to the National Women's Law Center.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation came under immediate attack from Republicans who
said states could put $3 billion of their unspent federal welfare
funds toward child care.
</P>
<P>
   ``The federal government will spend around $13 billion this year
on child care,'' said Rep. Nancy Johnson, R-Conn., ``Clearly,
states already have far more federal dollars for child care than
ever before (and) they have substantial funds at their disposal
that could be used to pay for child care.''
</P>
<P>
   The federal government began giving states money for child care
in 1997 as part of the Child Care Development Block Grant program,
which is funded at $3 billion annually.
</P>
<P>
   States are also allowed to allocate 30 percent of funds under
the Temporary Assistance for Needy Families (TANF) program for
child-care initiatives. The TANF program gives states $16.5 billion
annually for assistance programs for the poor. Both programs
replaced the federal government's welfare program that was scrapped
as part of 1996 legislation.
</P>
<P>
   Under existing programs, most of the money goes to very
low-income families who are just coming off welfare and does not
reach low- and moderate-income families who also struggle with
child-care expenses.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Ben Cardin, D-Md., said a family of three earning $18,000
does not qualify for a child-care subsidy in his state. Each state
sets income guidelines for who qualifies under the various
child-care programs, but in many cases families earning more than
$20,000 annually do not qualify for assistance.
</P>
<P>
   Tauscher's plan, which is backed by the Democratic leadership,
would increase funding for the Child Care Development block grant
by $7.5 billion over five years and require states to target the
money toward low- and moderate-income people who are not coming off
welfare.
</P>
<P>
   The bill would also:
</P>
<P>
   _Double the income limit to $60,000 for working parents to
become eligible for the Dependent Care Tax Credit. This credit
allows families to subtract up to $2,400 per child in child-care
costs from the amount of tax they owe, with a limit of $4,800 for
two or more children.
</P>
<P>
   _Allow all parents with children under 12 months to subtract up
to $1,500 in child-care expenses from their tax liability. This
credit would be available regardless of whether one parent stays
home.
</P>
<P>
   _Establish a tax credit for businesses to build or expand
child-care facilities. The credit would allow businesses to
subtract 25 percent of the cost from their tax liabilities, not
exceeding $150,000 annually. The bill would also allow five or more
small businesses to band together to provide child-care services
and receive federal and state matching funds.
</P>
<P>
   _Triple funding for a federal after-school program that provides
money for schools and community centers to help run after-school
programs. The program is currently funded at $200 million a year.
</P>
<P>
   House Minority Whip David Bonior, D-Mich., said improving access
to child care is a top priority for Democrats and they will
continue to press for the enactment of legislation ahead of next
year's congressional and presidential elections.
</P>
<P>
   During a House Ways and Means Subcommittee on Human Resources
hearing on child-care financing Tuesday, Johnson, the panel's
chairman, said funding for other programs would need to be cut in
order to pay for the Democrats' five-year, $24.6 billion plan.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this week the Ways and Means panel released a
Congressional Research Service report showing that states have $3
billion in unused TANF, or welfare funds. But many states,
including California and Texas, do not have any unspent funds.
</P>
<P>
   ``How could Congress justify cutting other programs or
increasing taxes to gives states yet more money when so much money
is going unused,'' Johnson said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
