<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAMAR ALEXANDER: ALL AMBITION, NO VISION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARIANNE MEANS  
 c. 1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Although he has been campaigning furiously since he
lost the Republican presidential nomination in 1996, former
Tennessee Gov. Lamar Alexander is preferred by only 2 percent of
Republicans surveyed in this week's USA Today/CNN/Gallup Poll.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the message there, he doesn't get it. When Alexander
finally made it official the other day that he meant to try again
for the big prize in 2000, it was no surprise.
</P>
<P>
   What it was, however, was a puzzlement. Why is he running?
</P>
<P>
   Or to put it another way: Why should we care?
</P>
<P>
   Alexander, 58, tried to get attention two years ago by wearing a
folksy plaid shirt, in the style of Gary Hart. You got the
impression he wanted to wear a sweater and carry his own garment
bag, but Jimmy Carter had already pulled that stunt.
</P>
<P>
   Since the plaid shirt didn't do anything for his popularity,
Alexander has now mercifully reverted to standard business attire.
But he has found no other way to distinguish himself from a crowded
GOP field in which the candidates all seem to echo the same themes,
formed by the same partisan cookie-cutter.
</P>
<P>
   Alexander is still saying the same things in much the same way
as he did in his 1996 race. If he has any understanding that the
issues and the country have moved on since then, he does not
indicate it. There is no evidence that new thoughts have percolated
in his brain.
</P>
<P>
   He does, however, have an instinct for the heat of political
battle, which he demonstrated recently by attacking the
front-runner, Texas Gov. George W. Bush, for his espousal of
``compassionate conservatism.'' It was a clever expression with
good campaign potential, and Alexander immediately tried to stamp
it out by scorning its message as ``weasel words.''
</P>
<P>
   Alexander is on the losing side of that one. Try explaining to
voters what's wrong with tempering basic GOP fiscal conservatism in
public policy with a little compassion for individuals. You can't
do it without sounding like a cold-hearted, right-wing ogre.
</P>
<P>
   Alexander, the former president of the University of Tennessee
and Education secretary in the Bush administration, also has tried
to claim the mantle of chief education advocate. He said recently
he was ``the only one'' among the GOP candidates who could
effectively push education issues. Oh?
</P>
<P>
   This is a man who wants to kill the Department of Education,
eliminating the primary voice on behalf of school children in the
Cabinet and downgrading the subject to the local level where it
will get less national attention. Even the GOP-controlled Congress
has backed away from trying to kill the Education Department. The
idea is politically dead.
</P>
<P>
   His other proposals to strengthen education also are familiar
GOP refrains, from taxpayer subsidies for private schools to an end
to ``race-based scholarships'' and a rejection of proposed national
grading standards. We may be forgiven if we fail to see how this is
supposed to identify him as a uniquely wonderful champion of the
nation's children.
</P>
<P>
   Alexander's campaign is mostly about running against
``obnoxious'' and ``arrogant'' Washington, which successful
presidential candidates of both parties have been doing for several
decades.
</P>
<P>
   Alexander lives in Tennessee. But as a former Cabinet officer,
White House assistant and aide to Sen. Howard Baker, he has little
credibility as a Washington ``outsider.'' And if foreign policy
becomes a major issue, portraying oneself as outside the
information loop might not seem like a strong qualification for the
presidency.
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore, the anti-Washington rhetoric has begun to wear thin
with voters, who didn't like the brief government shutdown and
don't want to get rid of the bureaucracy _ they just want it to be
smaller and function better.
</P>
<P>
   Alexander's remedy for Washington's ills doesn't address that.
</P>
<P>
   Instead he has stolen an idea from his mentor, Baker, an
otherwise sage statesman who long promoted the foolish notion that
in today's complex global community, Congress could revert to the
past and sit in session only half the year. During the other six
months members would return home as ``citizens,'' refreshing their
feel for daily constituent life and working for local companies. If
you believe this would not constitute a conflict of interest, I
have a bridge for sale.
</P>
<P>
   Of course Alexander is for cutting taxes, the GOP mantra.
</P>
<P>
   He says abortion is wrong but does not favor a constitutional
amendment to ban it, as the 1996 GOP party platform does. That puts
him in the pool of the wishy-washy on the subject, along with
George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   But Alexander's major problem is that he is stuck on tired,
stale issues and has nothing fresh to offer. In his announcement
speech, for instance, he lists term limits as one of his primary
goals.
</P>
<P>
   This is another concept whose time has come and gone. Perhaps he
has missed the anguish of GOP legislators who endorsed term limits
as candidates but now want to back out on their promise because
they have suddenly discovered the merits of seniority.
</P>
<P>
   Poor Alexander. He is all ambition and no vision.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
