<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRADY-WEAPONS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JAMES BRADY JOINS CONCEALED-WEAPONS VOTE FIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DONALD BRADLEY  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star   James S. Brady, the White House press
secretary who was shot during the 1981 assassination attempt on
President Reagan, came to Kansas City on Monday to implore Missouri
voters to reject a concealed weapons referendum on April 6.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Proposition B is poorly written and would jeopardize the safety
of everyone, Brady told an audience at St. Vincent's Family Service
Center at 3030 Troost Ave.
</P>
<P>
   ``The armed society that Proposition B creates is filled with so
many loopholes that it literally would allow convicted criminals to
carry hidden Uzi pistols into bars, stadiums and onto school
property,'' Brady said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think that is the kind of society the people of
Missouri want or need.''
</P>
<P>
   Brett Feinstein, a spokesman for Missourians Against Crime,
which supports the referendum, later took exception to Brady's
remarks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly, local law enforcement agencies who conduct the checks
can turn someone down and not issue a permit,'' Feinstein said.
``Nobody likes the fact that we live in a violent society. But
people have a right to protect themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   St. Vincent's child care center serves mostly inner-city
families. Before introducing Brady, who suffered permanent brain
injury in the 1981 attack, center director Sister Berta Sailer said
she polled staff and children to see how many had lost a family
member to gunfire.
</P>
<P>
   Of 70 staff members, 30 had lost a relative. Of 200 children,
the number was 50. Those who said ``yes'' wore black armbands.
</P>
<P>
   One little girl had an armband on each arm.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's lost two family members, and she's not even 3 years old
yet,'' Sailer said.
</P>
<P>
   Brady said the right to carry guns would send a bad message to
children.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't want our kids to believe that guns provide solutions
to every problem,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Feinstein disagreed with Brady.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody wants to see kids exposed to violence,'' Feinstein
said. ``But is it better that we allow people to be victims or that
we allow them to protect themselves?''
</P>
<P>
   Proposition B would allow mentally competent persons age 21 or
older to carry a concealed weapon if they've not been convicted of
a felony, if they're not known as a substance abuser and if they
have not displayed violent behavior in the past five years.
</P>
<P>
   After passing a background check, applicants would be issued a
three-year permit after 12 hours of firearms training.
</P>
<P>
   Proponents say the proposal would help law-abiding citizens
protect themselves and their families against violent criminals.
They reject arguments that more guns mean more gun deaths.
</P>
<P>
   Crime, the proponents say, has gone down in states that have
conceal-and-carry rights, mainly because criminals don't know who
has a gun.
</P>
<P>
   But Brady and doctors from Children's Mercy Hospital and Truman
Medical Center rejected those claims Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Crime is down everywhere, and it has gone down faster in states
without conceal-and-carry laws, said Denise Dowd, an emergency room
physician at Children's Mercy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Missouri's crime rate is down 22 percent over five years _
that's more than states where people are allowed to carry guns,''
said Dowd, who has researched the effect of guns on society.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's absurd why we would want to pass this.''
</P>
<P>
   Advocates of Proposition B are using a St. Louis area woman's
story that if she had carried a gun, she might have been able to
save herself from being raped.
</P>
<P>
   When asked to comment on the woman's contention, Dowd said the
question called for speculation.
</P>
<P>
   ``If she would have had a gun, she might be dead,'' Dowd
answered.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
