<HEADER>
A2655 &Cx1f; kan-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GRAIN-EXPLOSION-2NDTA     03-16 0621
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GRAIN-EXPLOSION-2ND </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKE-KAN   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICK ALM  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   performing other tasks. The federal safety agency in December
cited DeBruce with 36 federal safety violations in connection with
the tragedy and proposed fines of $1.7 million.
</P>
<P>
   DeBruce, which remains in business in Wichita and several other
U.S. locations, is contesting the federal safety agency's
allegations.
</P>
<P>
   In its 30-page complaint, OSHA neither cited nor mentioned
Industrial Maintenance.
</P>
<P>
   Federal safety officials in Kansas City and Wichita did not
return calls Monday.
</P>
<P>
   DeBruce founder and chief executive Paul DeBruce is careful not
to level blame directly at its maintenance contractor.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I know is, it wasn't our light, and that it was attached
to the (machinery) they were working on,'' DeBruce said Monday.
``It certainly is puzzling. It shouldn't have been there.''
</P>
<P>
   DeBruce, however, stopped short of saying use of that type of
light in a grain elevator violated federal standards.
</P>
<P>
   Nickel said her client thought the lamp met OSHA standards for
use in grain elevators.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the National Consumer Product Safety Commission
said tests and a consumer warning it issued in 1996 determined that
300-watt halogen bulbs could reach 970 degrees Fahrenheit.
</P>
<P>
   According to the National Electrical Code, cited in OSHA
grain-dust regulations, the ignition point for wheat and some other
agricultural dusts is 428 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Federal prosecutors in Wichita, meanwhile, are continuing to
investigate the explosion for possible criminal violations, a
spokeswoman for U.S. Attorney Jackie Williams said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The new civil lawsuit, filed by Carlos Amador and the families
of two workers who were killed, Jose Luis Duarte and Raymundo Diaz
Vela, asks for more than $75,000 in damages. Duarte worked for
DeBruce. Amador and Vela were employed by LSI Corp., a Wichita
company that supplies temporary agriculture industry workers.
</P>
<P>
   Under Kansas law, workers or their families cannot sue their
employers in cases of injury or death if they are eligible for
workers' compensation payments. Some states, including Missouri,
make exceptions in cases of negligence or willful acts, said Rupe,
the lawyer for Industrial Maintenance.
</P>
<P>
   Legislation is pending in Topeka to allow similar exceptions.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, Rupe said, ``Industrial Maintenance is a victim
of the Kansas workers' compensation system'' as affected families
search for deep pockets to sue.
</P>
<P>
   ``Employees of DeBruce have no other recourse except to
establish fault by non-employers,'' Rupe said. ``I would refer you
to the outcome of the OSHA investigation that supports what I
say.''
</P>
<P>
   In public statements, OSHA investigators have pointed to an
underground tunnel for grain conveyor belts as the likely spot
where the explosion originated.
</P>
<P>
   Investigator Vernon Grose told /{The Wichita Eagle/} last summer
that a seized bearing in that machinery caused friction and
generated enough heat to ignite grain dust.
</P>
<P>
   DeBruce officials take strong issue with that and argue that
grain was not being moved in that area at the time of the
explosion.
</P>
<P>
   Rupe acknowledged that the halogen lamp was the property of
Industrial Maintenance. It was being used that day by company
workers in the headhouse, a central control area near the top and
center of the nearly half-mile-long structure.
</P>
<P>
   But Rupe said OSHA investigators clearly determined ``the blast
did not start there.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides, Rupe added, the lamp fixture was both turned off and
unplugged at the time of the blast. His client's employees, he
said, were in another area of the elevator at the time.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
