<DOCNO> NYT19990316.0199 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-16 18:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2657 &Cx1f; kan-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RAIN-RETAIL-2NDTAKE-K     03-16 0832
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAIN-RETAIL-2NDTAKE-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
   
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   high-tourist areas.
</P>
<P>
   Chrysler Corp.'s 15,000-square-foot Great Cars Great Trucks
center in the Mall of America in Minneapolis is like a 365-day auto
show. The center, which is more interested in building brand names
than selling cars, features concept cars, a Dodge Viper that
customers can sit in, and interactive films on the history of
Chrysler and current technology. It is the second most popular
attraction at the mall and draws up to 8,900 customers on Saturdays
alone.
</P>
<P>
   Wish Superstore, an Atlanta clothing store and skateboarding
store, has a live disc jockey on weekends. Through the week,
customers can sit in a 1970s-style lounge area and watch talk shows
on a vintage white plastic television.
</P>
<P>
   Officials with Wish Superstore say the attractions keep people
coming in, but they caution that too much entertainment can have
customers playing instead of buying. It's a store, not a lounge.
</P>
<P>
   Along with attracting customers, the entertainment retailers may
have an edge in attracting employees, especially in tight labor
markets such as Johnson County, where unemployment typically is 3
percent or lower. While other restaurants have complained about the
lack of workers, Rainforest quickly hired 340 employees.
</P>
<P>
   Retail analysts said the sheer wonderment of concepts such as
Rainforest Cafe would draw people several times. Then the challenge
becomes how to attract repeat business.
</P>
<P>
   And now that theme restaurants are opening in Kansas City,
Indianapolis and other smaller markets, the novelty appears to be
wearing off.
</P>
<P>
   ``Entertainment retail is probably a trend that is on the
downturn right now,'' said Wilson of /{Chain Store Age/}. ``It was
the hot industry term two years ago; it's much less so now. I
wouldn't say the industry is very hot right now on theme
restaurants at all.''
</P>
<P>
   Theme restaurants seem to prosper more in high-tourist areas,
where they have a constant flow of new customers.
</P>
<P>
   NBA City, a basketball-theme restaurant, is being built at
Universal Studios' CityWalk entertainment district in Orlando, Fla.
It will be divided into a dining area, a merchandise shop, and a
recreation area where customers can shoot baskets and play trivia
games.
</P>
<P>
   The Walt Disney Co. plans to take one of its ESPN Zone concepts
to Times Square in New York. The operations combine a restaurant
and bar with a sports screening room and 10,000-square-foot arena
for virtual and actual games. Staff members will get briefings on
sports news before each shift, and place mats with current sports
information will be updated daily.
</P>
<P>
   But even heavy traffic doesn't guarantee success. Often it comes
down to the food. Many of the themed operations concentrate more on
what customers are seeing than what they are eating.
</P>
<P>
   Television City and Fashion Cafe, two theme restaurants that had
planned multiple locations, recently closed at Rockefeller Center
in New York, and work on David Copperfield's Magic Underground on
Broadway stopped nearly a year ago. In 1998, Hard Rock Cafe saw its
sales drop 11 percent for stores open at least a year, and its
operating profit slipped 19 percent.
</P>
<P>
   And Planet Hollywood, which has said it wants to be a tenant in
Kansas City's Power &AMP; Light District, said in January that it would
cut costs and revamp its menu because it expected sales to drop as
much as 25 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson predicted that the Overland Park Rainforest Cafe would
draw phenomenal crowds at first but would have problems sustaining
that traffic on a year-round basis.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rainforest is great when you look at it, it's fun, those
gorillas and the rain and everything like that, but that's really
not enough,'' Wilson said. ``The content, or the product, in
Rainforest is the food, and I think most people think that the food
hasn't lived up to it.''
</P>
<P>
   But a Rainforest spokesman noted that /{Restaurants and
Institutions/}, a trade publication, recently named Rainforest its
top winner in the ``themed restaurant'' category. The listing was
based on a nationwide survey of 2,500 households and criteria that
included food, value, merchandise and service.
</P>
<P>
   Jean Golden, director of corporate communications for Rainforest
Cafe, said the restaurant should not be lumped into the same
category as other themed operations.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're profitable and we have been since day one,'' Golden
said. ``We do not depend on people knowing a movie star's name or a
model's name. We feel we are not a fad and are very much a trend.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Kurt Barnard of Barnard's Retail Trend Report in New
Jersey sees the trend of themed restaurants waning.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a novelty that worked beautifully because everyone
rushed to see all those things,'' Barnard said. ``They were
tremendously interesting, but now many of them are coming on hard
times. Once you've been there and done that, why go back? There's
no novelty left.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
