<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GRAIN-EXPLOSION-2TAKES-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAWSUIT SAYS CONTRACTOR'S NEGLIGENCE CAUSED BLAST AT GRAIN
ELEVATOR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICK ALM  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   A new lawsuit alleges that a contractor's negligence caused the
fatal DeBruce Grain Co. elevator explosion last year near Wichita.
</P>
<P>
   The contractor, Industrial Maintenance Inc. of Wichita, was
hired in 1998 to repair DeBruce's grain-dust collection systems in
the huge elevator complex. Industrial Maintenance was named as the
sole defendant in the case, brought by one injured worker and the
families of two others killed in the June 8 blast.
</P>
<P>
   Industrial Maintenance ``failed to perform this maintenance in a
reasonably prudent manner, resulting in the ... explosion,'' the
lawsuit alleges.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for the company deny it did anything to contribute to
the blast.
</P>
<P>
   ``No way, no how,'' Alan Rupe, a lawyer for Industrial
Maintenance, said Monday. ``My client is without fault.''
</P>
<P>
   The new legal claim may lend support to a theory advanced by
DeBruce officials in recent weeks that a 300-watt halogen-light
fixture used by the contractor's employees might have generated
enough heat to ignite volatile grain dust. DeBruce officials said
the light was found later amid the blast debris.
</P>
<P>
   Specific acts of negligence were not detailed in the lawsuit,
filed Thursday in Sedgwick County District Court. The lawsuit also
did not specifically raise the halogen-light issue.
</P>
<P>
   Alisa Nickel, another Industrial Maintenance lawyer, said
federal safety investigators examined the halogen-lamp theory and
questioned company co-owner Randy Neises about it.
</P>
<P>
   The Occupational Safety and Health Administration discarded the
lamp, she said, after apparently determining the device was not a
factor.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, she added, if the lamp debris ``is not showing heat
damage or explosion damage, that just supports our belief that the
lamp had nothing to do with the explosion nor was in any way an
ignition factor.''
</P>
<P>
   Officials for DeBruce, which is based in North Kansas City, said
they retrieved the lamp debris last August, and on Monday they
released photographs.
</P>
<P>
   The plaintiffs are represented by former U.S. Attorney Randall
K. Rathbun of Wichita.
</P>
<P>
   ``There has been a lot of concentration on DeBruce,'' Rathbun
said. ``This case will be about others that DeBruce hired. This
company was hired to upgrade the dust suppression and collection
system, and they just didn't do their job.''
</P>
<P>
   Rathbun would not comment on specifics of the case or the
halogen light, saying details would come later.
</P>
<P>
   ``Only half the story is out there,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   DeBruce officials said Monday that Industrial Maintenance was
paid more than $60,000 for its rehabilitation work throughout the
elevator's grain-dust collection systems. That work was completed
in the months before the explosion.
</P>
<P>
   On the day of the blast, three Industrial Maintenance employees
were at the grain elevator performing other tasks. MORE
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
