A2659 &Cx1f; kan-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RAIN-RETAIL-2TAKES-KA     03-16 0684
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAIN-RETAIL-2TAKES-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MANY BUSINESSES OFFER RAZZLE-DAZZLE WITH THEIR RETAIL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOYCE SMITH  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's not enough anymore to provide good products at a good
price. More and more, retailers and restaurateurs are trying to
entertain their customers, too.
</P>
<P>
   An example of that trend, the Rainforest Cafe, opened recently
in Overland Park's Oak Park Mall. Customers do more than eat in a
trendy restaurant _ they experience a complete tropical rain
forest.
</P>
<P>
   Outside the restaurant is a roaring, animated crocodile, its
tail twitching in a threatening display. Parrots squawk a greeting
as customers pick up their ``passports'' to the restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   Inside is a 2,392-square-foot retail shop. Diners enter the
restaurant by walking under a 5,500-gallon saltwater aquarium
archway.
</P>
<P>
   They dine in a simulated forest with more than 2 million leaves
and a view of the night sky as it appears in South America.
Animated rain forest animals, such as thumping silverback gorillas
and trumpeting elephants, frolic nearby.
</P>
<P>
   Rain walls and cascading waterfalls lend soothing sounds until
there is a clash of thunder, and lightning strikes overhead.
</P>
<P>
   The Rainforest Cafe is an extreme example of the ``entertainment
retailing'' trend. The most popular are the theme restaurants built
around rock 'n' roll, supermodels, movies, wrestling, sports
superstars and even college sports.
</P>
<P>
   Marianne Wilson, senior editor of BEGIN ITAL Chain Store Age
BEGIN ITAL, a retailing magazine based in New York, said the growth
of electronic retailing, especially during the recent holiday
buying season, had forced retailers to make shopping and dining
more enjoyable.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to make the bricks-and-mortar store more of an
experience, more entertaining,'' Wilson said. ``That could mean
anything from having a great environment, real comfortable, having
wonderful service, or a more interactive, more stimulating store
environment that ties in with the products they sell.''
</P>
<P>
   Even before the Rainforest Cafe opened, Oak Park Mall customers
were checking it out. Their faces contained looks of amazement as
they watched the animated characters from afar.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've outgrown Chuck E. Cheese's, and this is something the
whole family can do together,'' said Amy Boothe of Lenexa.
</P>
<P>
   Boothe's daughter, Ashley, 6, was transfixed by the live parrots
and the animated crocodile.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's cool,'' Ashley said.
</P>
<P>
   Oak Park Mall also is home to the new Build-A-Bear Workshop,
which lets customers pick out fake animal skins and watch the bears
being stuffed and sewn. Zany Brainy offers authors' readings and
brings in live zoo animals.
</P>
<P>
   Galyan's Trading Co. at Town Center Plaza in Leawood has a
rock-climbing wall where customers can try out merchandise.
</P>
<P>
   Even small operations, such as Fritz's Union Station in Kansas
City, Kan., can draw customers and build their brand name through
entertainment retailing.
</P>
<P>
   Fritz's delivers meals on a toy train and track. Its new
location in the Crown Center Shops will expand on that with even
more bells and whistles, figuratively and literally. The
state-of-the-art system is still being designed, but could help
turn the restaurant into a franchise operation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a gimmick, but I know it brings people in; you can't get
in here on a holiday or Saturday,'' said Fred Kropf, co-owner of
Fritz's. ``It's such an attraction for a child, but also for
adults.''
</P>
<P>
   Beyond offering a good time, entertainment retailers are
desirable, especially in shopping centers, because they generate
longer stays in the centers and increased sales, according to the
International Council of Shopping Centers, a trade group in New
York. Typically, the longer customers are in a mall, the more money
they spend, according to the trade group.
</P>
<P>
   With that in mind, the five-story NikeTown in New York features
multiple rooms organized around specific sports, along with
interactive information on products and top athletes. All of the 12
NikeTowns are in high-tourist areas. MORE
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-16-99 1826EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
