</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-NOTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A RIVAL GAINS ON `FELICITY' 
TO RUSSIA WITH VIDEO CREW 
FRANKEN'S LAST CHANCE 
LOTS OF SCIENCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds.: Bylines follow notebook items.) 
(mk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Felicity,'' the WB drama about a young woman in her first year
in college, began last fall with a heliumlike burst of publicity, a
campaign that helped put its star, Keri Russell, on the covers of
Seventeen magazine and Entertainment Weekly and had the theme song
(sung by Madonna) playing in movie theaters everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   The show, scheduled at 9 p.m. Tuesdays to follow the cult
favorite ``Buffy the Vampire Slayer,'' seemed assured of becoming
the next giant hit among young people.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, a Tuesday night teen rival on UPN seemed likely to
struggle. ``Moesha,'' underpublicized and with no boost from any
hit show on its network (``Star Trek: Voyager'' and ``Dilbert'' are
UPN's only other hits), was in its fourth season and had new
competition from ``Buffy,'' ABC's ``Home Improvement'' and Fox's
``King of the Hill,'' all of which had moved to Tuesdays at 8.
</P>
<P>
   But Brandy, the pop singer who won a Grammy last month and stars
as Moesha, has kept her show steadily climbing. Indeed, ``Moesha''
has increased its audience since November while ``Felicity'' has
lost ground.
</P>
<P>
   ``Moesha'' averages a 2.5 household rating (each rating point
equals 994,000 homes) and a 2.4 rating among 18-to-34-year-old
women. But the latter number is up 33 percent from last year
(measured February to February).
</P>
<P>
   ``Felicity'' still has a larger audience, a 3.5 average
household rating and a 3.6 rating among women aged 18 to 34.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's doing fine, but it's clearly not the breakout hit they
had hoped for,'' Marc Berman, a media analyst with Seltel Inc. who
advises television stations, said of ``Felicity.'' As for
``Moesha,'' he said, ``on a network really having its problems,
it's holding its own, and that's pretty impressive.''
</P>
<P>
   But shed no tears for ``Felicity.'' WB is pleased; the show has
been picked up for a second season, starting next fall. Ms.
Russell's character will be in her second year of college.
</P>
<P>
   And Brandy, as Moesha, will go to college for the first time,
following, in that sense, in Felicity's footsteps.
</P>
<P>
   _ LAWRIE MIFFLIN
</P>
<P>
   Brokaw in Moscow
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A lot has changed in Moscow since Tom Brokaw scored
one of the biggest coups of his career in 1987 with his exclusive
interview with Mikhail Gorbachev, then the president of the Soviet
Union.
</P>
<P>
   But Brokaw is still at his post as anchor of NBC News, and this
week he will travel to Moscow to conduct another interview
milestone, the first American television interview with Yevgeny
Primakov, Russia's current prime minister.
</P>
<P>
   Brokaw said Tuesday that he hoped to conduct the interview
Thursday and to show portions of it on NBC's ``Nightly News''
Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   Brokaw said he had pursued the interview because of the
political and economic chaos in Russia and because he has known
Primakov for some time and has found him to be a fascinating
figure.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a guy who was around in the Brezhnev era and the
Gorbachev era,'' Brokaw said. ``Then he turns up as Boris Yeltsin's
head of the KGB. He goes on to be foreign minister and now he's
prime minister. Most people were stunned when he survived Gorbachev
to work with Yeltsin. Now he's in a position of management for the
first time, and he's working under a leader who is either limited
in what he can do or else totally incapacitated.''
</P>
<P>
   Beyond broaching the issue of Yeltsin's health, Brokaw said he
would ask Primakov questions in three main areas: ``Can anything be
done about the economic situation? What about the issue of the
so-called loose nukes? And then, the broad question of whither
Russia.''
</P>
<P>
   One difference between this interview and his 1987 encounter
with Gorbachev is the importance of the men involved, Brokaw said.
``Back then there was the sense that Gorbachev was a star of global
proportions,'' he said. ``But I have to say that when I interviewed
him I had no idea we were that close to the fall of communism.''
</P>
<P>
   _ BILL CARTER
</P>
<P>
   The Night to Be Funny
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Al Franken knows he has one last shot at making his
comedy series ``Lateline'' a candidate for survival on NBC. As of
Tuesday night, the show, a satire of both television news and
politics, had six episodes left in which to find a following
sufficient for NBC to bring it back for new episodes next fall.
</P>
<P>
   Franken, whose second book, ``Why Not Me?'' is a current best
seller, said he hoped that a shift to Tuesday night would
reinvigorate the series, which had languished on Wednesdays in an
earlier trial.
</P>
<P>
   ``At last I think we're in a place where people are looking for
comedy,'' Franken said.
</P>
<P>
   The show's producers struggled with the decision about which
episode to bring the series back with, although they knew the
highlight of their season was almost surely an episode now
scheduled for March 30.
</P>
<P>
   That one, with the guest stars Rob Reiner and Martin Sheen, is a
mock documentary in which Franken's character, Al Freundlich, is
asked to do a cameo role in a film Reiner is making.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rob lets him change one line for the sake of credibility,''
Franken said. ``He keeps suggesting changes until he ends up
destroying the movie.''
</P>
<P>
   NBC will measure ``Lateline'' against whatever new comedies it
develops when it decides in May what next season's schedule will
look like.
</P>
<P>
   _ BILL CARTER
</P>
<P>
   Scientific Leaning
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ PBS plans a new ``Science at Its Best'' block on
Tuesday nights starting this summer, Kathy Quattrone, PBS'
programming chief, said in a speech Tuesday before the New York
chapter of the National Academy of Television Arts and Sciences.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nova,'' PBS' longstanding science program, will move to 9 p.m.
from its traditional 8 p.m. slot and will be bolstered by a bundle
of new lead-in programs at 8.
</P>
<P>
   These will include a 10-hour series, ``The Life of Birds with
David Attenborough,'' ``Stealing Time: The New Science of Aging,''
``Savage Seas,'' ``The Secret Life of the Brain,'' produced by
David Grubin, and a new installment of ``The Living Edens.''
</P>
<P>
   _ LAWRIE MIFFLIN
</P>
</TEXT>
