<SLUG> BC-NIRELAND-MURDER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLICE COLLUSION IN A NORTHERN IRELAND MURDER WILL BE
INVESTIGATED 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 by JAMES F. CLARITY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   DUBLIN, Ireland _ The Northern Ireland police chief said Tuesday
that an independent police official from the British mainland and
agents from the FBI would investigate whether there was police
collusion in Monday's killing of a prominent Roman Catholic human
rights lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   The lawyer, Rosemary Nelson, 40, was killed by a car bomb placed
by a Protestant splinter group, the Red Hand Defenders. The group
is dedicated to destroying the Northern Ireland peace agreement
approved 10 months ago to end 30 years of violence in the British
province.
</P>
<P>
   The Catholic Irish Republican Army and the main Protestant
paramilitary groups have been observing a cease-fire while their
political representatives try to complete the agreement by this
Easter. Their work has been stalled by a dispute over disarmament
of the paramilitary groups, particularly the IRA.
</P>
<P>
   The chief of the Royal Ulster Constabulary, Ronnie Flanagan,
said that David Phillips, a police chief in Kent County, England,
and FBI investigators would work on the case and look into
accusations that the Northern Ireland police had themselves
threatened Ms. Nelson.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no evidence to substantiate collusion,'' Flanagan
said. ``There is no doubt about the professionalism'' of the
northern police force.
</P>
<P>
   Officials of Sinn Fein, the political wing of the IRA, responded
immediately that one British policeman could not be trusted to
investigate honestly the operations of another. They did not
mention the FBI.
</P>
<P>
   After the killing in the town of Lurgan, County Armagh, west of
Belfast, there were disorders in Catholic areas. But the North was
quiet Tuesday and political officials and police said it did not
appear that there would be more violent reaction.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Nelson was a leading advocate of Catholics accused of
terrorist offenses by the British government.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
