<SLUG> BC-GUSEWELLE-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CARS DON'T FLY THROUGH KCI GARAGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By C.W. GUSEWELLE  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star   It was a weeknight with not much
activity at the airport. The terminal where friends were arriving
on a flight from St. Louis was nearly empty.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Because leaving a car on the terminal drive isn't an option, I
pulled into the parking garage. The time stamped on my
machine-issued ticket was 7:45.
</P>
<P>
   The friends' flight was on time _ a few minutes early, in fact.
</P>
<P>
   ``Collect your baggage,'' I told them. ``I'll go get the car and
meet you in front of the terminal.''
</P>
<P>
   I hurried back to my parking place, in a convenient slot on the
surface level. When I slipped behind the wheel, the dashboard clock
read 8:05 _ still 10 minutes left of the allotted half-hour of free
parking.
</P>
<P>
   Exit arrows led down a ramp to the level below and straight into
a horrific jam-up.
</P>
<P>
   To get back on the terminal drive would mean negotiating a kind
of serpentine maze _ first a series of left turns, complicated by
cars merging from the right, then up another ramp to the
toll-takers' booths. But the line wasn't moving _ not moving at
all.
</P>
<P>
   A soup of exhaust fumes filled the underground parking area.
Drivers were stepping out and peering ahead to see if they could
determine the cause of the blockage. I left my car, walked along
the stalled line and around three corners, all the way to the
front.
</P>
<P>
   The problem was immediately apparent.
</P>
<P>
   Of four toll booths at the exit, only two were staffed. The
lanes to the other two were barred.
</P>
<P>
   When I got back to my car, the line _ maybe 50 or 60 vehicles
long _ still hadn't moved. It eventually did move, of course. Given
enough time, even mountains move. But for every car that made it
out, two or three more joined the queue. There was no guessing when
the nightmare might finally end.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, it was my turn at the pay station.
</P>
<P>
   ``What the devil's gone wrong?'' I demanded of the addled young
fellow in the booth.
</P>
<P>
   From his body language and tormented expression, I got an
impression that he might be close to going berserk.
</P>
<P>
   BEGIN BOLD``All these flights!''END BOLD he screeched.
</P>
<P>
   His eyes darted furiously back over the line.
</P>
<P>
   BEGIN BOLD``And people _ people losing their tickets.''END BOLD
</P>
<P>
   Lost tickets can't be helped, I suppose. But the evening's air
traffic was, if anything, uncommonly light. Anyway, flights are
scheduled, predictable. Planes don't just drop in unannounced to
dump their passengers.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got four booths,'' I told the toll-taker. ``And only
two are operating.''
</P>
<P>
   BEGIN BOLD``Right. Two empty. We've called for some help, but
nothing's happened. Nobody's come.''END BOLD
</P>
<P>
   The toll-taker wasn't at fault. He was just a cog in a broken
system, caught up, as we all were, in somebody else's failure.
</P>
<P>
   He ran my parking ticket through his machine. And put out his
hand for payment. I had been back at the car well before my free
half-hour had elapsed _ but that was at five minutes after 8. The
time now was 20 until 9.
</P>
<P>
   I paid, though, without complaint, as the drivers ahead of me
had done. Nobody wanted a discussion. What we wanted was BEGIN BOLD
out! END BOLD
</P>
<P>
   My friends still were waiting when I pulled up at last on the
terminal drive. They'd spent about as much time standing there in
the cold on the sidewalk as they had spent in the air between St.
Louis and Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   It's a small matter, I suppose. But a lot of people's time had
been wasted. They'd been inconvenienced for no reason and kept from
places they needed to be. And for good measure, some were made to
pay a fee just for waiting in line.
</P>
<P>
   Amazing, isn't it, how we somehow can manage to run a pretty
fair international airport when we can't run a parking garage?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
