<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-SETTLEMENT-ART-825&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOW JEWS TURN HOUSES INTO HOMES ON WEST BANK
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo and map are is being sent to NYT photo and graphic
clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
(888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By DEBORAH SONTAG   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ELI, West Bank _ From this entrenched Jewish settlement on a
bluff above the Palestinian territories, the vista is dotted for
miles around with what Israelis and Palestinians call ``facts on
the ground.''
</P>
<P>
   Almost every hilltop bears a scattering of mobile homes,
evidence of the continuing and willful expansion of the Jewish
presence in the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
   The hills are truly alive with the sound of hammers, buzz saws
and bulldozers as Israelis _ with the help of Palestinian laborers
_ dig into the land. They aim to sink their roots as deeply as
possible in the hope that the acres they occupy now will never be
turned over to the Palestinian Authority.
</P>
<P>
   ``When they built the hill, we climbed on up,'' said Oria
Levinstein, 17, whose family moved from Eli, which is almost
suburban, into a tin shack on a barren hillside nearby. ``We felt
like pioneers. At first it was horrible _ no water, no electricity.
But now we have our trailers, and it's gorgeous. Look at this view!
At night you see all the land of Israel. What, we should let the
Arabs have it?''
</P>
<P>
   For months, Palestinian leaders have criticized the growth of
Jewish settlements in the West Bank, particularly in the stretch of
rocky hills between the Palestinian cities of Ramallah and Nablus.
</P>
<P>
   And in the last few days, American diplomats have turned up the
pressure on Israel to contain the expansion, butting heads with the
Israelis in a war of words played out through the media. Last
weekend Dennis Ross, the American envoy to the Middle East peace
talks, in an unusual public rebuke, called increased settlement
activity ``very destructive to the pursuit of peace.''
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu, defying the
American criticism, visited a West Bank settlement and vowed, ``We
want it to be bigger.''
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday the American Embassy in Tel Aviv issued a pointed
statement in response. ``We have been troubled by Israel's
expansion of existing settlements well beyond their periphery,''
said Larry Schwartz, the embassy spokesman. ``These activities
prejudge and predetermine issues that were to be reserved for
permanent-status negotiations by changing realities on the
ground.''
</P>
<P>
   The embassy statement was issued as Ross was flying to Madrid to
see the Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat, in a meeting scheduled at
the last minute. Ross was expected to press Arafat to delay a
declaration of statehood beyond May 4, when the original
Israeli-Palestinian peace accord expires.
</P>
<P>
   Some Palestinian officials said they believed the American
criticism of Israel was timed to make Arafat more receptive.
</P>
<P>
   The most recent Israeli-Palestinian peace memorandum, negotiated
at the Wye Plantation in Maryland last fall, prohibits both sides
from taking unilateral actions to jeopardize their understanding.
The Americans, who brokered the agreement, see both a May 4
statehood declaration by Arafat and continued settlement expansion
by Israel as unilateral acts that would violate the Wye accord.
</P>
<P>
   The Israelis contend that they are expanding settlements based
on the natural growth of the 140 communities; they say the
settlements are theirs to expand until their future is decided in
the final-status negotiations, which have not yet begun. Indeed,
Foreign Minister Ariel Sharon counseled the settlers last fall to
make haste by ``grabbing hilltops'' before land was turned over to
the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   But the Americans and the Palestinians contend that the
expansion is carving out new Jewish communities, either by
occupying new land or by turning makeshift communities into more
established settlements by replacing trailers with houses.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we close our eyes to these facts on the ground, they will
become a reality we cannot negotiate away,'' Ahmed Qurei, the
speaker of the Palestinian Legislative Council, said at a recent
meeting. ``We cannot sit in our houses and watch the bulldozers.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, though, Palestinian protests have been restrained. When
one Palestinian legislator suggested forbidding Palestinian
laborers to work on the settlement projects, another scoffed,
saying, ``Not until they have an economic alternative, like our own
construction projects.''
</P>
<P>
   The American Embassy closely monitors settlement activity, but
does not release any data.
</P>
<P>
   But Israeli and American peace groups say 16 new settlements
have risen in the five months since the Wye accord was signed at
the White House. The trailer communities, blocks of white
rectangles atop the highest hills, are as conspicuous as the banks
of new house frames that stand beside the established communities.
</P>
<P>
   ``The system is very simple,'' said Mossi Raz, the general
director of Peace Now in Israel. ``The settlers go to a hill, most
of the time next to the settlement where they live and in some
cases outside the boundaries. They put up some trailers. They build
a road to the place. And nobody does anything about it, not the
police, not the army.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   For the last five years, the settler population has grown at a
rate of about 9 percent a year, to 170,000 Jews living amid
Palestinians in the West Bank and Gaza. Peace Now says the vacancy
rate in the established settlements hovers around 8 or 9 percent,
negating the argument that there is need to expand.
</P>
<P>
   But Pinchas Wallerstein, chairman of the Yesha Council, the
umbrella settlers' group, said the empty residences represent
natural turnover. He also said he hoped to see faster growth after
the end of this school year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope it will increase by 11 or 12 percent this year,'' he
said. ``But I don't know that there are a lot of people who will be
willing to pay $100,000 for a house in the middle of an area where
the political situation is unstable. I can give them a narrow
caravan, but if they want to live in a permanent house, they have
to pay for it.''
</P>
<P>
   Wallerstein discounted most of the new hilltop communities.
``They are not expansion,'' he said. ``They are very young fellows
or families who stay there to make a point, but the living
conditions are too difficult. There is growth in the settlements,
but it is not in the hills. What is important to us is to grow in a
way that connects areas of Jewish sovereignty.''
</P>
<P>
   He cited as an example a six-month-old outpost of four families
between Eli and Shilo, called Givat Harel, in an area at the center
of the West Bank that is experiencing the greatest growth.
</P>
<P>
   Eli is 14 years old and home to 400 families, both religious and
secular, about 20 percent of whom are new immigrants. A sign at the
foot of the hill promises houses ``With Cable!'' whose prices start
at $49,000. The town director, Lior Shtul, boasts of the short
commute to Jerusalem and Tel Aviv.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are those who come here for quality of life, and those
who come for that plus ideology,'' he said. ``Both ways, we grow.
We continue to build. This government comes and this government
goes, and nothing changes but what sits on the ground.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
