<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUNDAY-EARLY-BUDGET-NYT </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service will move the following
entertainment/arts articles this week for release Sunday, March 21,
1999. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ENTERTAINMENT &AMP; ARTS (Moved in `e' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FILM AND VIDEO &LR;
</P>
<P>
   RACHEL-GRIFFITHS-FILMS (Hollywood) _ Even before she made her
first movie, Rachel Griffiths' face was famous. She first realized
this back home in Australia while sitting in a Melbourne movie
house watching Martin Scorsese's 1991 remake of the thriller ``Cape
Fear.'' In it, Robert De Niro's oily convict stalks a teen-ager
played by Juliette Lewis, who has the same high forehead as Ms.
Griffiths, as well as the same full mouth, large eyes and short
dark hair. In the business of acting, such look-alike recognition
can be a minus when just starting out. But with a co-starring role
in the international hit ``Muriel's Wedding'' three years later,
Ms. Griffiths made the first big step toward helping the public
connect her own name to her face. For her role as Muriel's
party-girl sidekick, Ms. Griffiths took home her country's version
of the Oscar for best supporting actress and wound up with
theatrical representatives wrangling deals for her around the
globe. By Margy Rothlin. Photo.
</P>
<P>
   MONTENEGRO-OSCAR (Rio de Janeiro, Brazil) _ The first time it
occurred to Fernanda Montenegro that she could ever win an Academy
Award for best actress was at the Berlin Film Festival early last
year, before she and the film, ``Central Station,'' had won the
festival's top prizes. At breakfast one morning, the movie's
producer, Arthur Cohn, turned to her and said: ``You know, you're
going to get an Oscar nomination out of this.'' Since Cohn has five
Oscars of his own for foreign films and documentaries, his opinion
is not to be dismissed lightly. But the odds would seem to be
stacked against her. At age 69, Ms. Montenegro has acted in just
nine movies, and until ``Central Station,'' in which she plays an
embittered former schoolteacher who becomes a letter writer for
illiterate people in order to eke out a precarious living, only a
couple had been released in the United States. By Larry Rohter.
Photo.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; DANCE &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SHTICK-DANCE (New York) _ Talk about a tough crowd. Last fall,
the choreographer Danial Shapiro invited some friends and
colleagues to a preview of his new solo, ``Shtick,'' at the
Southern Theater in Minneapolis. Set to klezmer music and Henny
Youngman jokes, the dance was conceived as an upbeat sequel to his
1996 elegy about Jewish ghettos and concentration camps, called
``What Dark/Falling Into Light.'' With the first public performance
just two nights away, Shapiro was looking for a pat on the back,
and maybe a little constructive criticism. Instead he learned what
a lonely place the stage can be. By Christopher Reardon.
</P>
<P>
   BAHAI-CARNAVAL (Salvador, Brazil) _ In Salvador, the capital of
Brazil's state of Bahia, which has one of the richest carnival
traditions in the new world, all the connoisseurs of Bahia's
Carnaval have the same thing jotted down in their agendas: to
attend the start of the Ile Aiye parade. Ile Aiye (pronounced
Ee-leh Eye-eh) is one of the various carnival organizations, called
blocos, that sponsor floats and parades throughout the six-day
street festival that engulfs this city. But of all of them it is
perhaps the purest. Its percussion-and-voice band has refused to go
pop, sticking to the slow, stately Ijexa rhythms _ an African sort
of samba associated with the Afro-Brazilian religion of candomble.
It insists on walking through the streets rather than riding on a
sound truck the way other bands do. By Ben Ratliff.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THEATER &LR;
</P>
<P>
   RED-THEATER (New York) _ He is wry and witty, the very picture
of a promising young playwright, with his blue jeans, his black
leather jacket and his California cool. But in his mind's eye, he
is still clumsy and awkward, a gawky crow craving acceptance from a
tribe of graceful sparrows. And it is this metaphor, he says, that
best reflects his existence as a gay Chinese-American writer
struggling to succeed in a white world. ``It's how I see myself in
America, living on the periphery and longing to be in the midst of
it,'' said Chay Yew, 33, one of a handful of critically acclaimed
Asian-American writers actively working in the theater in this
country. ``It's like when you go to a bar,'' said Yew, whose newest
play, ``Red,'' opens on Tuesday at the Manhattan Theater Club Stage
2. ``You see all these guys. They're having a good time and you
want to be like them. But you know you never can. By Rachel L.
Swarns. Photo.
</P>
<P>
   CLOSER-THEATER (Undated) _ The British dramatist Patrick Marber,
34, new play ``Closer'' is a bitter, darkly comic prize-winning
English play about sex and longing. Underlying themes of betrayal
and competition are signified early on in a notriously ribald scene
in which two male strangers correspond in a cyberspace chat room,
one posing as a sexually hungry woman, the other happy to believe
it. The play, which won the triple crown in England _ the Olivier,
The Evening Standard and the Critics Circle awards _ opens on
Thursday at the Music Box Theater on Broadway. By Andrea Stevens.
</P>
<P>
   BLACK-WOMEN-PLAYWRIGHTS (Undated) _ While it is true that black
women playwrights are being produced in major Off Broadway and
regional theaters, they have yet to obtain the kind of consistent,
high-profile presence and voice accorded African-American women
today in popular music and fiction writing. The reasons offered for
why there is no female equivalent, for example, of the eminent
black playwright August Wilson on Broadway have to do not only with
the vagaries of an outsize talent but also the difficulties that
have always faced women _ but especially black and other minority
women _ in the theater. They include what has become a truism in
recent years, that straight plays do not attract Broadway
audiences, and that to do so successfully they have to offer broad
themes that mass audiences can relate to; that a number of small
theaters that nurtured talent, both black and white, have closed at
a time when government financial support for the arts is dwindling;
that there is a perception of artistic and financial risk in
mounting plays by blacks and women; that in the male-dominated
theater world, women have traditionally had difficulty finding
mentors and producers. By Felicia R. Lee. Photo.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CLASSICAL MUSIC &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SANTA-FE-MUSIC (Undated) _ What began as a New York appearance
by performers of the Santa Fe Chamber Music Festival has evolved
into a virtual weekend in the historic capital of New Mexico: a
three-day musical and cultural holiday, beginning on Thursday,
mostly within the confines of the Metropolitan Museum of Art. And
as befits Santa Fe, where controversy flows back through history to
the city's founding in 1610, the music is likely to be accompanied
by a note of political discord. By Lawrence B. Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ART &LR;
</P>
<P>
   DIEGO-RIVERA-ART (Cleveland) _ The big Diego Rivera
retrospective, organized by the Cleveland Museum of Art with the
Consejo Nacional para la Cultura y las Artes and the Instituto
Nacional de Bellas Artes in Mexico City, leans particularly on his
early years, before Rivera returned from Europe to Mexico and
started painting the murals for which he rightly became most
famous. The point: that the murals have obscured the value of his
previous work. By Michael Kimmelman.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TELEVISION &LR;
</P>
<P>
   TV-ITS-LIKE (Los Angeles) _ In the ceaseless civic sniping
between New York and Los Angeles, everybody always talks about the
weather, but nobody ever does anything about it. Until now. In what
at first appears to be a new skirmish in this culture war, the ABC
sitcom ``It's Like, You Know ...'' surveys the L.A. landscape _
where the people are as convertible as the cars they drive _ and
quickly runs up the flag of surrender. What charms beyond the
weather this city holds for its tired, its poor, its brain-dead,
non-softball-playing huddled masses are to be revealed,
elliptically, during a six-week trial run of ``It's Like, You Know
...'' beginning this Wednesday night at 8:30. By Bruce Newman.
</P>
<P>
   TV-RECKLESS (Undated) _ ``Reckless,'' is a production of Granada
Television presented last year on ``Mobil Masterpiece Theater,''
starring Francesca Annis, the acclaimed British stage actress, and
Robson Green, a heartthrob from northern England who is one of
Britain's most popular television actors. Ms. Annis is 54; Green is
34. The six-hour series, which also features Michael Kitchen as the
arrogant, philandering husband, was a huge hit in England. When it
was broadcast here in early 1998, The New York Times critic Caryn
James called it ``a deliciously tangled story of passion,
infidelity and civilized revenge.'' ``Reckless'' was such a success
that Granada made a two-hour sequel. ``Masterpiece Theater'' begins
rebroadcasting the original series on PBS next Sunday night,
followed by ``Reckless: The Sequel'' on April 18. By Jill Gerston.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ANTIQUES &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SUGIMOTO-ART-ANTIQUES (Undated) _ Most people view the things
they collect as a diversion from what they do for a living. But for
the Japanese photographer Hiroshi Sugimoto, 51, the traditional
Japanese art he collects is absolutely essential to the art he
creates: compelling images of seascapes, waxworks, life-size
Buddhas and the gilded interiors of motion picture palaces. While
Sugimoto's photographs are exhibited widely, the art he collects is
rarely displayed, even in his homes in Tokyo and New York. Now he
has lent three pieces to ``Crosscurrents: Masterpieces of East
Asian Art from New York Private Collections,'' an exhibition that
opens on Wednesday and remains through July 11 at the Japan Society
Gallery in Manhattan. By Rita Reif.
</P>
