<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-16 18:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2677 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AFRICA-FOSSIL-ART-749     03-16 0806
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AFRICA-FOSSIL-ART-749(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOLVING A 3.5-MILLION-YEAR-OLD, 3-D JIGSAW PUZZLE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Map is being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(kd) 
 By SUZANNE DALEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   STERKFONTEIN CAVES, South Africa _ Deep in the dark, dank
caverns here, Dr. Ronald J. Clarke, a man with a long list of
academic credentials, is at work.
</P>
<P>
   He is sprawled against a rock face, lying on an old camping
mattress, his tools scattered on a nearby ledge: a few sharpened
nail punches, some dental picks, Super Glue, a old jam jar full of
lacquer.
</P>
<P>
   With a rusting hammer and his tiny chisels, he tap, tap, taps,
gentle millimeter by millimeter, chipping the rock away from around
his discovery. Embedded in the stone is a skeleton perhaps 3.6
million years old _ a skeleton that may help answer some of the
enduring questions about human evolution.
</P>
<P>
   Already the skull has been exposed. The teeth, still shiny with
enamel, gleam under the spotlight an assistant holds. After a
morning's work, Clarke has cleared enough rock from the base of the
skull to insert a tiny pick.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look at that,'' he said, almost breathless with wonder.
Despite all the movement of rock around it, the delicate skull _
completely hollow _ has remained whole.
</P>
<P>
   Such work might try the patience of some. But Clarke uses words
like ``exciting'' and makes clear in a very polite way that he
would rather be chipping than talking. Behind his discovery _
front-page news around the world last December _ is a kind of
detective story that begins in a storage room in 1994 and included
an inch-by-inch search of a 30-foot-high cavern to look for a spot
about the size of a quarter that would match a piece of broken
shinbone.
</P>
<P>
   After the discovery, the international press descended here, the
experts debated and Clarke was distracted from the caves, where he
has worked for more than two decades. Nowadays he is back at work _
slowly, slowly trying to extract the precious skeleton, hoping that
his calculations, which led him to the conclusion that he had found
a truly whole skeleton will be borne out.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a bit worrying,'' he admitted, as he used a soft
artist's brush to push away the fragments left from his digging.
``It's a big responsibility to be telling the whole world that the
whole thing is in there. Now I've got to prove it.''
</P>
<P>
   There is nothing about the caves to announce the magnitude of
the find, which many scientists have likened in import to the
discovery of the famous ``Lucy'' skeleton in Ethiopia in 1974.
</P>
<P>
   The Sterkfontein caves are about a 45-minute drive from downtown
Johannesburg. There is a modest sign announcing the tourist
entrance, where there is a cheery little tea room that is not very
busy.
</P>
<P>
   Clarke's base of operation, a large tin-roofed shed with neatly
labeled boxes and tables full of prehistoric bones, is down an
unmarked gravel path. When the excavation is through, scientists
hope they will be able to match hip structure with leg bones and
brain capacity for the first time, and thus understand far more
about what this four-foot-tall creature was capable of.
</P>
<P>
   But Clarke does not even have the $170,000 he needs to keep his
operation going until the end of the year. As he was busy
unearthing the first bones of his discovery, he was also scrambling
for a job.
</P>
<P>
   After years at the prestigious University of the Witwatersrand,
Clarke was informed in early 1998 that his contract would not be
renewed. The decision was made by the head of the University's
paleo-anthropology research groups, Dr. Lee Berger, a flamboyant
32-year-old American regarded as an able fund-raiser for the
discipline, which is chronically in need.
</P>
<P>
   Berger did attend Clarke's news conference in December, praising
his colleague warmly and calling the discovery a ``fossil
comparable to no other.'' But later he refused to comment on his
role in Clarke's ouster from the university. In the past, he has
said that Clarke's skills were ``not so special'' and that his
methods were old fashioned and expensive.
</P>
<P>
   Clarke has since been hired by the Johann Wolfgang Goethe
University in Frankfurt, which has agreed to let him keep working
at Sterkfontein, a set of limestone caverns that have yielded
numerous fossils over the years. Witswatersrand officials say now
that they want to bring Clarke back to the university. They have
also set up a special committee to examine how best to administer
the research at the caves in the future.
</P>
<P>
   ``We consider the caves a unique resource and Dr. Clarke as
uniquely capable of continuing the work there,'' said Barry V.
Mendelow, the university's executive director of research.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The Sterkfontein caves have been an ideal time capsule. The
theory goes that the caves were a popular shelter 3.5 million years
ago, a place where many animals came to eat their prey, leaving the
bones behind. The caves also had small, concealed openings
perfectly suited for the unwary to fall into.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, as water dripped through the stone, the lime
deposited itself onto whatever debris and bones were inside,
encasing them in a rock-hard layer. More than 600 hominid fossils
have been found here, including the adult skull of an
Australopithecus africanus, which was found in 1947 and has come to
be known as Mrs. Ples.
</P>
<P>
   Until now, however, there has been nothing close to a complete
skeleton. The caves were mined for lime in the early part of the
century and much of the work at Sterkfontein has been sifting
through the debris the miners blasted out.
</P>
<P>
   The road to Clarke's discovery began with an academic's
question: Why were there no hoofed animals in the lower chambers of
the cave? He decided to look again at the bones taken from this
area, thinking they might offer an answer.
</P>
<P>
   What he found astonished him. Among the fossils thought to be of
animals was a foot bone that clearly belonged to a hominid. How it
had been misidentified he cannot understand. A further search found
more such bones, a discovery that was later nicknamed Little Foot.
It was significant because it showed a creature that could walk
upright, but still had the ability to climb trees.
</P>
<P>
   Three years later, Clark chanced to be looking in another
cupboard for some hominid fossils when he spied a box labeled
monkey bones. Inside, however, he found more mislabeled bones,
including a white bone that was the mirror image of Little Foot.
</P>
<P>
   He began to search through more bags of bones from the area
until he had found most of the creature's two feet, ankles and
shinbones, snapped off about halfway up. Such a discovery, Clarke
felt sure, meant that the rest of the creature still had to be in
the cave.
</P>
<P>
   But finding it seemed no easy task. The cave walls are jagged
and crumbling, and there is no natural light. He made a plaster
cast of one of the shinbones and sent his assistants with
flashlights to search for the cross section of its other half.
Amazingly, it took his aides, Nkwane Molefe and Stephen Motsumi,
only two days to find a match.
</P>
<P>
   Sitting in the mud in excruciating positions, the team scraped
and chipped, moving up the skeleton, until they came to a dead end.
The thigh bones were broken in half and went no further. After
studying the rock formations, Clarke finally deduced that a shift
of the rocks nearby had dropped the rest of the skeleton to another
level. But month after month went by without anything more being
found.
</P>
<P>
   Then, suddenly, the diggers began scraping at a bone _ the
skull.
</P>
<P>
   Inside the cave, Clarke is now looking for the vertebrae. He
says it will probably take him until the end of the year to get the
whole skeleton out.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be so cruel if it wasn't all there,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
