<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-PRESIDENCY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE MAN WHO CHANGED THE PRESIDENCY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LARRY SWINDELL 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Some believe that William Jefferson Clinton will be remembered
historically as a president who was impeached but not convicted.
Others say he'll be immortalized as a sex maniac. However he may be
recalled, Clinton may be most significant historically as the man
who changed the presidency, or caused it to be weakened.
</P>
<P>
   A recent and provocative major article in Newsweek considered
the likely effect of the Clinton impeachment on four disciplines:
the law, the media, the workplace and our children. The theoretical
findings were sufficiently interesting, but the presidency itself
may prove to be the institution most affected, most changed.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton is dazzling proof that a person may simultaneously be
remarkably intelligent and profoundly stupid. He should have known,
as we all do now, that privacy no longer exists in American life.
This is the Age of Information, technology is our new religion, and
it's too easy to get the goods on anybody.
</P>
<P>
   Remember the scene in ``Sleepless in Seattle'' in which Meg Ryan
employs a computer to research the Tom Hanks character she hasn't
even met, and immediately learns enough about him to know she loves
him?
</P>
<P>
   Considering what we are now learning about our president's
purple past, we may conclude that the Republicans really screwed up
in 1992. If they had done their investigative homework, they could
have neutralized early a Bill Clinton who surely was more
vulnerable than poor Gary Hart.
</P>
<P>
   They'll know better next time; they know better already.
Republicans and Democrats alike presently are probing
comprehensively the pre-gubernatorial, premarital, pre-everything
experience of one George W. Bush _ the one party seeking
affirmation, the other in quest of Achilles' heel.
</P>
<P>
   Henceforth it will be rather more difficult to secure a major
party's presidential nomination if the aspirant has a skeleton in
his closet or a bat in his belfry or a complex odyssey below his
belt line.
</P>
<P>
   Count on both party nominees in the 2000 presidential
sweepstakes being certified squeaky-clean. And after one of them
wins the election and takes office, he (she?) will be monitored as
never before.
</P>
<P>
   Compared, say, with passing muster to assume a Cabinet post or
other strategic federal function, it lately has been easier to
become president of the United States. Once nomination has been
secured, all it takes is pulling in more votes than your opponent.
</P>
<P>
   Federal appointments used to be rubber-stamped. What the
president wanted, the president got. The historical turning point
probably was Richard Nixon's failed attempt to get Clement
Haynesworth seated on the Supreme Court. The House and Senate
inhaled newfound power in that adventure and ever since have
relished investigating presidential choices for Cabinet, court and
top diplomatic positions.
</P>
<P>
   Those aspiring to the presidency now will be dissected, tracked
literally from birth _ perhaps not by lawmakers but certainly by
the media as well as by partisan interests.
</P>
<P>
   If our present information tools had been available then, would
Warren Harding, say, have been cleared for a presidential run? Or
even John F. Kennedy?
</P>
<P>
   Of relevance to all this is a new literary entertainment by
Richard Shenkman, a decidedly offbeat historian. His ``Presidential
Ambition'' is an account of how our bygone presidents ``gained
power, kept power, and got things done.'' It is a big parade of
presidents getting away, if not with murder (although some surely
have tried), with almost everything else _ but not in bourdoirs
primarily.
</P>
<P>
   Shenkman's White House saga is both an expose of presidential
skullduggery and a glorification of presidential chutzpah. Onward
from Thomas Jefferson, whose consummation of the Louisiana Purchase
certainly was unconstitutional, presidents often have abused their
power for what they believed was the good of the country.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew Jackson, James Polk, Abraham Lincoln, Grover Cleveland,
Woodrow Wilson, Theodore and Franklin Roosevelt, Harry Truman _
these now etched historically as superstar chief executives all
displayed strength by exceeding the specified boundaries of their
assigned role.
</P>
<P>
   They, and lesser presidents as well, also told lies. Their
prevarications were not always pragmatic, although they were rather
different in character from Clinton's lies. And there's no evidence
that Warren Gamaliel Harding ever had to lie about having fathered
an illegitimate child, because Harding was in his grave before the
fact was known.
</P>
<P>
   After Harding's somewhat shadowy and unexpected death in 1923,
Nan Britton _ his mistress in that well-known White House cloakroom
_ published a ``novel'' called ``The President's Daughter'' that
failed to gain for her such wealth as Monica Lewinsky surely will
attain.
</P>
<P>
   When our nation went ``back to normalcy'' for a Harding
administration that amounted to government by crony, the
president's raffish inner sanctum knew all about Britton. So did
Florence Harding, the wronged wife. But the American people
couldn't know _ primitive investigative journalism bypassed the
presidency because it was a sacred trust.
</P>
<P>
   It truly has been that. For more than 200 years, Americans have
beheld their presidency with awesome reverence, but that will
change _ is changing already.
</P>
<P>
   Expect future editions of Congress to hold presidential
aggressiveness firmly in check. In the new millennium, presidents
will be sorely challenged to gain power, to keep power and to get
things done. That will be the everlasting legacy of Bill Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   (Larry Swindell is books editor emeritus for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram and critic at large. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
