<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BELLSOUTH-AUDIT-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    FCC to phone companies: Show us the equipmentBy Michael E.
Kanell
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Billions of dollars in phone equipment is missing,
says the Federal Communications Commission.
</P>
<P>
   No it isn't and besides it doesn't matter, answer the regional
phone companies.
</P>
<P>
   The FCC has released an audit by its staff, which shows the
phone companies cannot account for about $5 billion of the $47
billion in ``hard-wired'' equipment that they have been carrying on
their books. The agency has announced no punishment, but suggests
that the companies write off the investment.
</P>
<P>
   BellSouth is listed by FCC auditors as having $721.2 million in
assets its cannot account for, about 3.3 percent of the asset toal.
The worst offender, according to the FCC, was Bell Atlantic, with
$1.56 billion, or about 11.6 percent of assets, ``missing.''
</P>
<P>
   BellSouth _ like the other target companies _ rejects the
audit's assertions.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is flawed, faulty and badly done audit that came to a bad
conclusion,'' said BellSouth spokesman Bill McCloskey. ``Even if we
wrote it all off, there would be zero impact on rates. We are under
price caps in all nine of our states.''
</P>
<P>
   Analysts too seemed unconcerned. Joseph Barthel of Fahnestock
wrote the audit is ``audit of the RBOCs is no serious threat to
their financial performance.'' He called it a ``ridiculous game of
'Gotcha!' at the FCC.''
</P>
<P>
   Analysts at Bear, Stearns &AMP; Co. wrote that the audit reports are
``a publicity, not a financial problem'' for the phone companies.
They too concluded that the audit should not affect prices for
phone service.
</P>
<P>
   But competitors say consumers should care.
</P>
<P>
   MCI WorldCom spokesman Joe Paluska said that even if rates
cannot rise, it may mean that BellSouth is reaping more profits
than are justified by its costs. ``These inflated investments were
used to develop those price caps.''
</P>
<P>
   The FCC has thus far taken no action on its staff report.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think the story is over,'' Paluska said.
</P>
<P>
   Michael E. Kanell writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
