A2686 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DOW-FUTURE-COX     03-16 0734
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOW-FUTURE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Cracking 10,000 _ What happens next?
 &HT;    By Tom Walker
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Okay, what next?
</P>
<P>
   Now that the Dow Jones industrial average has traded above
10,000 for the first time, investors would like to know if it will
close above that benchmark level any time soon, drop back or go
even higher.
</P>
<P>
   The answer is probably, ``All of the above,'' which leaves open
the matter of sequence.
</P>
<P>
   Big upward moves in stock averages tend to be followed by at
least small setbacks _ especially when the market passes one of
those historic milestones.
</P>
<P>
   The early history of the Dow's 1,000-point moves certainly is
not encouraging in that regard.
</P>
<P>
   The index plunged 42 percent in the two years following its
first close above 1,000 on Nov. 14, 1972, in the worst bear market
since the Great Depression.
</P>
<P>
   In 1987, the Dow closed above 2,000 for the first time on Jan. 8
and on Oct. 19 was down by 13 percent after the stock market's
worst crash ever.
</P>
<P>
   And the Dow's first close above 3,000 on May 30, 1991, was
followed by a 4.6 percent slide that didn't end until Dec. 12,
1991.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, however, the picture substantially improves. The Dow
has posted gains of as much as 25 percent (en route to 5,000), and
most recently, 10.7 percent (rising to 10,000 Tuesday before
falling back.).
</P>
<P>
   But every stock research report and mutual fund prospectus
contains a statement that past performance is no guarantee of
future behavior.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts are especially concerned that the Dow and the broader
S&AMP;P-500 indexes are the only ones making new highs, while the
Nasdaq composite and the Russell 2000 _ both of which contain lots
of smaller companies and technology stocks _ appear to be stalled.
</P>
<P>
   To market technicians, that is a sign the market lacks breadth.
</P>
<P>
   Interstate/Johnson Lane analyst Ricky Harrington calls the
performance gap between big and small stocks ``the market's most
serious weakness.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Currently, 48 percent of all New York Stock Exchange stocks
are down 30 percent from their most recent highs,'' said
Harrington. He argued that this is the kind of situation that
usually occurs at market tops _ from which stocks sell off.
</P>
<P>
   But Ralph Acampora, strategist and market technician for
Prudential Securities, believes the Dow _ and the market _ are on
the first leg of a new bull market that started last October when
the 1998 correction ended.
</P>
<P>
   According to Acampora, the significance of the Dow's rise was
not that it crossed 10,000 _ ``That's just a number,'' he said _
but that it was carried there by stocks of good quality.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bull markets start that way,'' said Acampora, who first
predicted that the Dow would reach 10,000 in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   The consensus among analysts is that as long as the economy
stays healthy, with minimal inflation and falling interest rates,
the stock market will continue to rise.
</P>
<P>
   This outlook is especially the case given the
``liquidity-driven'' nature of the market, as oceans of money flood
into stocks via individual mutual funds, 401(k) plans and other
pension systems. This in turn is being fed by the huge post-World
War II baby boom generation as it reached middle age with an eye on
retirement. Foreign investors add to the buying momentum.
</P>
<P>
   Total stock market assets in mutual funds rose from $245.8
billion in 1990 to $2.4 trillion _ an 876 percent increase _
according to the latest numbers from the Investment Company
Institute reports.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts see no reason to think this momentum will change,
barring some unpredictable outside event such as a Middle East war.
</P>
<P>
   It's no accident, they say, that the economy has expanded
without interruption over that same period that the Dow has gone
from 3,000 in April 1991 to where it is now _ the longest peacetime
expansion in U.S. economic history.
</P>
<P>
   The economy has given investors a relatively inflation free
environment of predictable growth that has made investing in common
stocks less risky _ as well as more attractive than bonds, whose
yields have steadily declined.
</P>
<P>
   In turn, the wealth created by rising stock prices has buoyed
consumer and investor confidence, supporting a spending spree that
has, in turn, fueled the economy's growth.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Walker writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution, Atlanta,
Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
