A2687 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DOW-HISTORY-COX     03-16 0479
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOW-HISTORY-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Dow average often mirrors events in U.S. history
 &HT;    By Tom Walker
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Dow rises, the Dow falls, the Dow remains unchanged, but
most of all, the Dow makes news _ and in the latest case, history.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow, of course, is the Dow Jones industrial average. Why it
should get so much attention is a matter of considerable debate,
between those who see the Dow at 10,000 as historic and those who
see 10,000 as ``just a number.''
</P>
<P>
   But even the Dow's detractors have to admit that, more than any
other Wall Street indicator, it has become synonymous with ``the
stock market,'' a fixture in the conversations of everybody from
taxi drivers to sales clerks to corporate chief executives to
presidents.
</P>
<P>
   Who talks about the S&AMP;P-500, or the Nasdaq composite?
</P>
<P>
   One reason for the Dow's singular status is its age. At 103
years, it is by far the oldest and best known of the world's stock
market indexes.
</P>
<P>
   And if nothing else, the Dow is a survivor. Consider the
publicity it has gotten in just the last few weeks.
</P>
<P>
   True, the index is comprises a mere 30 stocks in a universe of
some 10,000 public companies. For that and other reasons, the index
has been derided over the years as obsolete and misleading, not a
true barometer of investment trends.
</P>
<P>
   Tell that to the Dow.
</P>
<P>
   The index dates from 1896, the invention of Charles Henry Dow, a
founder of Dow Jones &AMP; Co. After a dozen years of experimenting, he
had settled on an index that averaged the prices of a dozen
railroad and manufacturing stocks.
</P>
<P>
   (Jones, incidentally, was Edward Davis Jones, who helped found
what is now Dow, Jones &AMP; Co., publisher of The Wall Street Journal,
whose staff maintains the index.)
</P>
<P>
   The Dow has been adjusted and revised constantly by Journal
staffers over the years, to 20 stocks early on, and in 1928 to 30
industrial companies.
</P>
<P>
   Over time, the makeup of the index was revised by adding
non-industrial stocks such as J.P. Morgan and Sears, to reflect the
range of the economy.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to its small size, critics of the index don't like
the way it works. As a price-weighted index, higher-priced stocks
have a greater impact on the average than do movements of
lower-priced stocks.
</P>
<P>
   Despite its faults, the Dow has become almost a universal
timeline of historical as well as economic events in the 20th
century. It has responded to war and peace, to booms and busts, and
survived crashes in 1929 and 1987 en route to 10,000.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1990s, the Dow has become an icon for a decade of
astonishing wealth and remarkable growth, marking with its
100-point and 1,000-point benchmarks the rise of Uncle Sam in the
post-Cold War world.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Walker writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution, Atlanta,
Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
