u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HAYES-AUCTION17-COX     03-16 1225
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HAYES-AUCTION17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Signing off: Hayes' last assets up for auction
 &HT;    By Michael E. Kanell
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Perched in a metal frame near the wall of the vast
room is a machine that has been used to test circuit boards coming
off nearby assembly lines.
</P>
<P>
   Although Hayes Corp. has not made modems for several months, the
tester is poised for work, one of many devices designed to run
continually whose lighted panels gaze unblinking at the empty
aisles between the rows of machines. The factory is still crowded
with machines, and the air is still filled with the drone of the
heating system. But gone are the hundreds of employees that once
churned out thousands of modems from these lines.
</P>
<P>
   On the tester's computer screen, there is a request for the
user's name. Someone has typed ``floor.'' Next to that is a space
for a password. But that is blank, as if a Hayes worker had started
to log on and then walked away.
</P>
<P>
   The Norcross, Ga.-based company is now defunct, its last assets
to be auctioned off starting at 10 a.m. today and continuing
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Interested bidders got a chance Monday and Tuesday to see the
offices, warehouse and factory, to preview the items they can bid
on this morning. What they saw was the residue of a 21-year
business.
</P>
<P>
   Co-founded by Dennis Hayes, a Georgia Tech graduate student, the
company went from garage operation to national player in a new
industry that paralleled the boom in personal computers. Analog
modems let PC users connect to each other or to the home office,
radically adding to the value of their desktop machines. As the
Internet was discovered, the shrill cry for connections sent modem
sales into the tens of thousands and then the millions.
</P>
<P>
   D.C. Hayes Associates became Hayes Microcomputer Products,
setting the technical standard for the industry. Sales ballooned,
even as rivals rushed into the fray, stealing shares of the growing
market.
</P>
<P>
   Hayes shrugged off the competition. Who cares about market share
when sales are jumping past $200 million a year? Hayes was a rising
star in Atlanta's growing high-tech constellation, employing about
1,200, and Dennis Hayes was repeatedly named entrepreneur of the
year.
</P>
<P>
   But costs surged faster than sales, losses mounted and in late
1994, Hayes officials called a press conference at Comdex to
announce they had filed for bankruptcy protection. In Chapter 11,
Hayes faced several buyout offers _ including a $140 million bid
from Diamond Multimedia.
</P>
<P>
   Dennis Hayes pleaded with the federal judge for the right to
keep his company and learn from his mistakes. He projected solid
sales growth and surrendered daily operational control. The judge
let Hayes reject the takeover efforts and sent the company out of
bankruptcy. For several quarters, the shiny predictions held, but
then the company stumbled again _ unable to overcome either market
confusion or strong competition from U.S. Robotics.
</P>
<P>
   In late 1997, Hayes announced a merger with Access Beyond, a
small Maryland company which specialized in connecting mobile
workers to the office. But the deal went sour. Contracts to build
new digital modems were still too small to turn the company around.
Sales of analog modems continued to lag, while Dennis Hayes feuded
with Access Beyond CEO Ron Howard, who had been tapped to run Hayes
Corp.
</P>
<P>
   In October, Hayes Corp. filed for bankruptcy protection again.
But this time, there was to be no triumphal emergence.
</P>
<P>
   In November, hundreds of workers were laid off and most of
manufacturing closed down. In late December, Howard and bankers _
already owed about $20 million _ disagreed about how to keep the
company funded. The plug was pulled, the funding ended, the rest of
the company shuttered.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the Hayes corporate offices have been largely emptied,
files and papers tossed into bins and carted away by employees of
Emerald Asset Management, which is conducting the auction. On some
walls, a few hangings remain. Many others are left studded with the
pegs that once held pictures and posters and charts. Scores of
chairs are clustered in odd places.
</P>
<P>
   Against one wall, a row of plants is lined, including several
small trees that loom around the doorway. On the counter is a
phone, unconnected. On a table is a pile of paper clips. Nearby,
stands a quartet of wine glasses, the reason for celebration long
forgotten. Hayes Corp. hardly looks like a company that churned out
millions of modems, the juggernaut that dominated the industry
during the 1980s. It hardly looks like a company at all.
</P>
<P>
   Except on the factory floor.
</P>
<P>
   Showing a visitor around the four-building Hayes Corp. campus,
R. Nuri Otus, president of Emerald Asset Management, waved a hand
at the assembly line and praised the company.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a very well-designed facility. That is why I'm
surprised no one came and bought Hayes. It has brand recognition.
It has quality recognition. Everything about Hayes was head and
shoulders above everybody else.''
</P>
<P>
   But no ``white knight'' emerged. Instead, the company's
intellectual and other assets have been put up for sale in an
attempt to raise the money needed to pay back Hayes Corp.'s
creditors.
</P>
<P>
   An auction in Manhattan disposed of some corporate pieces,
including some technology and overseas units. Howard and another
former executive bought one piece, a technology similar to that of
Access Beyond. But for the sell-off of hard assets in Norcross,
Emerald was contracted. One of the 10 largest asset management
companies in the nation, Emerald does about 30 auctions a year,
Otus said.
</P>
<P>
   Most are not business liquidations. Instead, Emerald is often
asked to sell unused or out-of-date machines by the likes of Apple
or IBM. Those clients, in good financial shape, just need to unload
inventory to empty warehouse space and clear the books.
</P>
<P>
   Coming to Hayes, on the other hand, is like walking into a ghost
town, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Otus nodded at the apparatus that remained and wondered why he
was selling much of it piecemeal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Somebody could walk in today and begin building modems within
a few weeks.''
</P>
<P>
   The auction is intended to raise money toward paying off the
staggering debt Hayes amassed as it went under. Many employees of
the corporation were also promised bonuses if they stayed after
Hayes hit trouble. When the final layoffs came, many also expected
the same kind of severance packages that were paid to previously
laid-off employees. Those payments were not made.
</P>
<P>
   So while bargains may be had here and there, that isn't the
auction's prime function, Otus said. ``It's not my job to give
bargains. It's my job to get as much money as possible.''
</P>
<P>
   How the money is dispersed is up to the federal bankruptcy court
in Delaware.
</P>
<P>
   Otus toted up the money expected from the auction, along with
that from previous sales of corporate assets and the trickle of
payments from former customers. Ex-employees should not assume they
will never get anything, but they should also be patient, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe the employees will see something. It won't be for
12, 24 or 36 months, but I do think they will see something.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael E. Kanell writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
