<HEADLINE>
CLINTON PROPOSES $70 BILLION IN DEBT RELIEF FOR POOR AFRICAN
NATIONS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOHN C. HENRY 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Calling for a new economic partnership with Africa,
President Clinton on Tuesday urged the international community to
expand debt-relief programs for impoverished African nations, a
proposal that could result in $70 billion worth of loans being
forgiven.
</P>
<P>
   In a speech opening a U.S.-Africa ministerial meeting in
Washington, Clinton suggested financing the additional debt-relief
partly through the sale of gold reserves held by the International
Monetary Fund. The president's remarks sent the price of gold to a
6 1/2-week low.
</P>
<P>
   Given the lack of congressional support for Clinton's African
initiative last year and wariness abroad for selling IMF gold to
provide debt relief, the prospects of winning support at home and
abroad for his proposal appeared to be a long shot.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal outlined Tuesday was similar to Clinton's plan,
unveiled during his four-nation tour of Central American last week,
to bolster the economies of emerging democracies and provide
additional markets for U.S. exporters.
</P>
<P>
   ``The more debtor nations commit to sound economic reforms, the
more creditor nations must be willing to forgive,'' the president
said. ``It is a principled and pragmatic approach, based on what
will work.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's proposal would expand a World Bank debt-relief program
called the Highly Indebted Poor Countries plan. Begun in 1985, the
program is designed to help relieve poor nations, mostly in Africa,
Central America and South America, of the debt they owe foreign
governments and international lending institutions.
</P>
<P>
   During his speech at the State Department, Clinton tried to
reassure government ministers from 46 African nations that he is
working to fulfill the promises he made during his historic
six-nation tour of the continent one year ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``For too much of this century, the relationship between the
United States and Africa was plagued by indifference on our part,''
Clinton said. ``We have been too separate and too unequal. We must
end that by building a better common future.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said that forgiving the debts of poor nations was
essential to their economic and political reform efforts. ``Our
goal is to ensure that no country committed to fundamental reform
is left with a debt burden that keeps it from meeting its people's
basic human needs and spurring growth,'' the president said.
</P>
<P>
   A cautionary note was sounded by Youssour Ouedraogo, foreign
minister for Burkina Faso and council chairman of the Organization
of African Unity. While endorsing debt relief, Ouedraogo said it
might be insufficient because economic growth experienced in most
African nations has not improved living conditions there.
</P>
<P>
   ``The results of growth, Mr. President, are still absorbed in
large part by debt repayment,'' Ouedraogo said. ``It is time then
to go to the heart of the matter, debt cancellation.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton pointed out that his budget proposal for 2000 includes
$237 million in debt relief for the poorest African nations. The
current budget includes $245 million in debt forgiveness.
</P>
<P>
   The president said that he will urge leaders of the world's
seven wealthiest, industrialized nations to forgive loans rather
than reschedule repayment of the debts, as is commonly practiced to
provide relief to debt-laden nations.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton pledged U.S. support, which must be cleared by Congress,
for gold sales by the IMF to help with loan forgiveness in Africa.
The IMF holds about $34 billion in gold at current prices. In
addition, the president said, the United States and other developed
nations would help finance the initiative.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after Clinton's speech, the price of gold for April
delivery fell to just under $284 an ounce in London, down $3.80.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
