A2701 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHINA-RICHARDSON-HNS &LR;      03-16 0703
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-RICHARDSON-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SECURITY BEEFED UP FOLLOWING SPY ALLEGATIONS, SENATE TOLD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ERIC ROSENBERG  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Clinton administration has beefed up security
at nuclear weapons facilities in the wake of allegations that a
U.S. scientist gave atomic secrets to China, Energy Secretary Bill
Richardson told a Senate panel Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Testifying before the Senate Armed Services Committee,
Richardson said his department now requires mandatory polygraphs
for all employees with access to sensitive information.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is significant because (only) one other agency does this,
and that is the Central Intelligence Agency,'' said Richardson.
</P>
<P>
   The Energy Department has taken other steps, including assigning
counterspies at all three major U.S. nuclear weapons labs to thwart
future spying, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Richardson added that the agency has doubled its
counter-intelligence budget while consolidating the spy-hunting
efforts in one office headed by Edward Curran, a 35-year FBI
veteran.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe that at our weapons labs, right now, we have strong
security procedures,'' Richardson said.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. John Warner, R-Va., chairman of the Armed Services
Committee, praised Richardson for moving quickly to tighten
security over nuclear secrets.
</P>
<P>
   ``It appears to me that the actions you personally have taken
during the brief period of your administration as secretary have
been timely and prudent,'' said Warner.
</P>
<P>
   Richardson, former U.S. ambassador to the United Nations, has
been energy secretary since last August.
</P>
<P>
   The department had long been lax in its supervision of the labs
and failed last year to file a congressionally mandated annual
report on the status of security at the facilities.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after taking over last summer, Richardson reinstated
background checks of all foreign visitors, a step the FBI had
recommended in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Richardson took that and other measures in response to
Presidential Decision Directive 61, an order issued by President
Clinton in February 1998 to boost security at the labs.
</P>
<P>
   The order was prompted by an FBI investigation detailing the
possible theft by China of U.S. nuclear warhead design secrets. The
alleged espionage took place in the 1980s. Richardson said the FBI
probe got under way in 1995. Other administration officials have
said it officially started in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   A computer scientist at Los Alamos National Laboratory in New
Mexico was fired March 8 after refusing to cooperate with FBI
officials. The scientist, Wen Ho Lee, a Taiwan-born American, has
not been charged.
</P>
<P>
   Richardson, who earlier Tuesday met with committee members for
more than two hours in a closed session, said the administration
won't know the extent of the damage from the alleged espionage
until the Central Intelligence Agency completes an investigation
next month.
</P>
<P>
   But, he said, the indications are that the spying may have hurt
national security. ``It's serious. It's inexcusable. Compromises
did happen,'' Richardson said. Intelligence experts say the
security breach may have allowed China to develop longer-range
missiles carrying more accurate multiple warheads.
</P>
<P>
   At the hearing Richardson defended a controversial program that
allows foreign scientists to tour the nuclear weapons labs, noting
the agency's current practice of conducting background checks on
the scientists.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday Sen. Richard Shelby, R-Ala., chairman of the Senate
Intelligence Committee, urged the administration to stop the
program for the time being.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our labs are not as secure as they should be,'' Shelby said.
The administration ``should put a moratorium on the exchange of
people coming into our labs and our scientists going to their labs
and perhaps giving them information,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   A report by the General Accounting Office, the congressional
investigative arm, concluded in 1997 that thousands of foreign
nationals had been allowed into Los Alamos and the Sandia National
Laboratories in New Mexico and California's Lawrence Livermore
National Laboratory. The report said scientists from China, Russia,
Iraq, Iran and Libya were among them.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
