<HEADER>
A2705 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NEWHART-COMENDY-ART-N     03-16 1236
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWHART-COMENDY-ART-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOB NEWHART _ STILL A STAND-UP COMIC
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo of Bob Newhart is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(dal) 
 BY JOHN BECK Santa Rosa (Calif.) Press Democrat   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   At 69, Bob Newhart is finally revealing one of his coveted trade
secrets to stand-up comedy _ call it an ode to the power of
porcelain.
</P>
<P>
   ``The best routines I ever wrote, I wrote in a john, I think,''
he says in his usual deadpan delivery. ``There should be a book on
it, but I think if someone researched it, most of the great ideas
since the beginning of time probably came out in the john.''
</P>
<P>
   Of all places, why the bathroom?
</P>
<P>
   ``Because there's nothing to distract you. If you've been in one
john, you've been in all the johns in the world. So your mind is
kind of focused.''
</P>
<P>
   Taken in context with the past 40 years of his career, this may
be one of the dirtiest jokes the comic has ever told in public.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Newhart, the buttoned-down, guy-next-door icon of American
comedy, using toilet humor? It might not make it to the stage, but
any appearance by Newhart promises to deliver plenty of fresh
insights to complement his tried-and-true bag of gags.
</P>
<P>
   He said his shows usually include one or two routines from his
old records. ``Some people show up for that and then it's just more
kind of observational about this world we live in and what a
strange place it is and how strange we are really. You know, stand
back and look at ourselves and see ourselves for the first time.''
</P>
<P>
   Imagine a round of psychotherapy with Bob _ sound familiar?
</P>
<P>
   Despite the time Newhart spent on television sitcoms, stand-up
comedy is an art form he never really left. Even while taping ``The
Bob Newhart Show'' in the 1970s, he still toured the comedy
circuit. ``Looking back, I still don't know how I did it, but we
would do three weeks (on the sitcom) and then be off two weeks and
I'd go to Vegas and play two weeks there and come back.''
</P>
<P>
   The sitcom business offered plenty of chances to hone his
stand-up shtick as he concocted a warm-up routine each week for the
live audience that watched the show.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't imagine ever not doing stand-up, as long as my health
holds up,'' he said. ``It's either the second greatest or the
greatest feeling in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   And the greatest? It depends on the person, maybe ``the laugh of
a child?'' he says, breaking into a wry chuckle that hints at other
possible contenders.
</P>
<P>
   As Newhart talks on the telephone from his mansion in Bel Air,
Calif., it's hard not to picture him gesturing on the other end _
the raise of a paranoid eyebrow, darting eyes, rubbing his weary
forehead as he rambles forth on one of his one-man phone
conversations conjuring the persona of Abe Lincoln's PR Man or Sir
Walter Raleigh's sarcastic boss or a rookie security guard who must
call his boss to report that King Kong is climbing the building.
</P>
<P>
   Newhart still remembers the night in 1964 when he dreamed up the
Kong routine while eating dinner with his wife and Carol Burnette
and her husband at the Top of the Sixes in New York:
</P>
<P>
   ``The way we were seated, I was looking at the Empire State
Building, and then it just came out. ... I was thinking about two
things that had happened to me and converging them on this one
event. Like I had always undergone those job-orientation programs
and nothing that they told you would happen ever happened. And then
I thought what would it be like if the night King Kong climbs the
outside of the Empire State building was the first night for a new
guard and he's got to call his boss and say, `A situation has come
up.' ''
</P>
<P>
   After completing Army service in the 1950s, Newhart worked as an
accountant and copywriter in his hometown of Chicago. Polishing his
act by taping ridiculous phone conversations with a friend, he
worked through the kinks of hit-and-miss stand-up routines,
learning to fluctuate between his comic persona and his real life.
</P>
<P>
   Even now the distinction is thin: ``There's a very slight change
in my voice so that it's Bob Newhart the stand-up comic, not Bob
Newhart the person. It's a schizophrenic kind of existence.''
</P>
<P>
   Riding a tide of nightclub laughs in the late 1950s, Newhart was
discovered by a Chicago DJ who introduced him to the head of talent
at Warner Brothers Records.
</P>
<P>
   The budding comic immediately connected with college kids when
he released his first album, ``The Buttoned-Down Mind of Bob
Newhart,'' in 1959 _ the first comedy album to hit No. 1 on the
charts. He cut seven more albums, eventually capturing the record
for longest simultaneous No. 1 and 2 album rankings on the
Billboard charts _ a feat he held for 35 years until it was broken
by Guns-n-Roses.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1960s, Newhart appeared on television shows like ``The
Entertainers'' and ``The Hollywood Palace.'' He landed parts in the
films ``Hell is for Heroes'' and ``Catch-22'' before launching
``The Bob Newhart Show'' in 1972.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish I could go back to the fun it was,'' he says. ``I loved
the process of a sitcom, coming in Monday and the script wasn't
quite right, and then Tuesday maybe a rewrite, and make some
suggestions on Wednesday, and then Friday you're there in front of
a live audience and it's working.''
</P>
<P>
   Newhart followed his debut show with an equally successful
eight-season run as Dick Loudon, the New York writer turned Norwich
innkeeper in ``Newhart.'' But by the early 1990s, his sitcom career
fizzled out with short-lived sitcoms like ``Bob'' and ``George and
Leo,'' in which he teamed up with Judd Hirsch.
</P>
<P>
   Now, he can't imagine doing another sitcom. ``You never say
never, but it takes so much out of you when the last two haven't
worked. You put so much of yourself into it and then to go through
that again. It's very emotional. Tuesday morning was always _ how
were the overnights? We're down a 10th of a point, we're up a 10th
of a point. You go through a whole year of that and you're pretty
much worn out.''
</P>
<P>
   An avid ``channel surfer,'' the immutable Newhart says the
original sitcom format vanished years ago with the loss of live
audiences.
</P>
<P>
   ``The one thing I lament _ they should find a different name for
sitcoms today because a sitcom to me was `I Love Lucy' and `The
Mary Tyler Moore Show' and `The Honeymooners,' all those great
shows with a live audience. ... If you listen today, it's all laugh
track. It's not a sitcom. They're non-audience sitcoms. That's the
easy way. You just do it. There's no one there. No one's testing
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Embarking on his latest project, Newhart is planning a
retrospective tour, showcasing highlights from the funniest moments
of ``The Bob Newhart Show'' and ``Newhart.'' It's a testament not
only to the endurance of his sitcoms, but to his dry, unsung sense
of humor that may have been overlooked by 1990s television
audiences, but continues to draw crowds to his stand-up
performances.
</P>
<P>
   Four years ago, he taped ``Off the Record,'' a video recording
of his live comedy routine. ``If you look at the audience, they're
like 35 to 40 years old, and it works in exactly the same places it
did 30 years before. That's what I find to be interesting _ some of
them weren't even born when I first recorded some of that stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   (John Beck writes for The Press Democrat in Santa Rosa, Calif.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
