<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-16 18:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2719 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EUROPE-ASSESS-2TAKES-     03-16 0911
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EUROPE-ASSESS-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEWS ANALYSIS: EUROPEAN CRISIS PAVES WAY FOR MORE ACCOUNTABILITY
</HEADLINE>
   (dal) 
 By ROGER COHEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRUSSELS, Belgium _ Long preoccupied with establishing a single
market, introducing a common currency, even talking bananas with
the United States, the European Union on Tuesday discovered that
its lack of attention to the theme of democracy could have
devastating consequences.
</P>
<P>
   Although the abrupt resignation early Tuesday of the entire
executive leadership of the 15-nation European Union was formally
linked to charges of fraud and gross mismanagement, it clearly
reflected a deeper malaise. As the size and power of a united
Europe has grown, the democratic accountability of its
Brussels-based leadership has not.
</P>
<P>
   ``Europeans have discovered that there is now real power in
Brussels, and they are saying they want more democratic controls,
more transparency, and more rigor,'' said Jean-Marie Guehenno, a
French diplomat and expert on European affairs. ``That is the true
significance of this collective resignation.''
</P>
<P>
   Jacques Santer, the 61-year-old Luxembourger who is president of
the European Commission, and his 19 fellow commissioners, quit
after a 144-page report by an independent panel of experts found
that the Union's $100 billion annual budget was mismanaged and said
that it was ``becoming difficult to find anyone who has even the
slightest sense of responsibility.''
</P>
<P>
   This amounted to an extraordinary accusation against the
officials responsible for upholding the treaties of the European
Union. But it reflected a growing perception that the
commissioners, who are appointed by national governments and
oversee a bureaucracy of 17,000 people, have enjoyed powers
inadequately balanced by democratic oversight.
</P>
<P>
   Their resignation ushered in what French President Jacques
Chirac called ``an unprecedented crisis.'' It comes at a time when
Europe's common currency, the euro, is still in its infancy;
decisive reform of the European budget is being discussed in
preparation for next week's meeting of European leaders in Berlin;
and trade frictions with the United States are intense.
</P>
<P>
   Tension and anger were apparent here on Tuesday in a city that
has often been derided for calling itself ``the capital of
Europe,'' but seemed vested at last with some of the cut and thrust
of big-power politics.
</P>
<P>
   Santer counterattacked vigorously, calling the experts' report
``distorted,'' vaunting his success in introducing the euro at the
beginning of this year, and saying the cases of fraud were old,
minor or unproven. He made it clear that he hopes to be reinstated
by national governments, along with other commissioners.
</P>
<P>
   But resorting to unusually blunt language, British Prime
Minister Tony Blair and German Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder made
their contempt for Santer clear as they spelled out a conviction
that a turning-point for Europe has been reached.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking in London, where he met Tuesday with the German
Chancellor, Blair said the former Luxembourg prime minister should
pack his bags and make way for a ``real political heavyweight.''
Schroeder waved away Santer's aspirations by saying that the
identity of a replacement would be discussed in Berlin next week.
</P>
<P>
   Blair's call for a ``political heavyweight'' appeared
particularly significant. Just four years ago, when Santer was
appointed, Britain seemed intent on imposing a political
lightweight in Brussels because it saw such an appointment as one
guarantee against strong moves toward European federalism.
</P>
<P>
   But since then, Britain has moved somewhat closer to Europe,
albeit cautiously, and has been in the forefront of new calls for
the development of a European defense arm. At the same time, with
the introduction of the euro, the Union has gained a new stature
and momentum that even Britain has been obliged to recognize.
</P>
<P>
   The current crisis seems to lie in the disparity between this
development of the Union into a powerful entity with its own
supranational currency and the absence of any meaningful reform to
increase democratic controls.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think this is the time to carp at the content of the
report,'' said Sir Leon Brittan of Britain, the commissioner
responsible for trade. ``What is needed now is comprehensive root
and branch reform of the Commission.''
</P>
<P>
   With vested interests strong, such reform would probably only be
possible with an extremely strong commission president. Among the
names being mentioned here were former German Chancellor Helmut
Kohl, former Spanish Prime Minister Felipe Gonzalez, former Italian
Prime Minister Romano Prodi, and the Secretary General of NATO,
Javier Solana of Spain.
</P>
<P>
   But the job is normally fiercely contested among member states,
and it appeared unlikely that any decision could be taken before
the Berlin meeting, at the earliest. The terms of Santer and the
other commissioners were supposed to run until the end of this
year.
</P>
<P>
   The report found commissioners hiring relatives, exercising
little control over budgets and, even, in the case of Edith Cresson
of France, the commissioner responsible for education and youth
programs, employing a home-town dentist and his son on large
salaries to do work for which they had no apparent qualification.
</P>
<P>
   In all, auditors have found close to $1 billion in European
spending for which there appears to have been no proper accounting.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Cresson's apparent contempt for mounting evidence against
her in recent months did much to fuel a sense of European outrage,
beginning in a European Parliament that long appeared laughably
powerless but now appears to be finding its teeth.
</P>
<P>
   ``The European Union has no constitution, so it advances and
changes in reaction to crisis,'' said Jonathan Eyal, a London-based
foreign policy expert. ``This is such a crisis and it will insure
that future commissioners are not fading national politicians for
whom a place has to be found somewhere. It also marks the arrival
of the European Parliament as a real force for democracy.''
</P>
<P>
   Many commissioners, like Ms. Cresson, or Neil Kinnock of
Britain, the former Labor Party leader, are major national figures
who have arrived at a point where they have little political future
in their own country. Like many of their predecessors, they have
come to Brussels to end their careers rather than build them.
</P>
<P>
   That now seems likely to change. So, too, will the importance of
June elections to the 626-member European Parliament, which was the
driving force behind the initial investigation after a Dutch
auditor first revealed the commission's long failure to tackle
fraud.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Commission must leave now and not in nine months time,''
the Parliament's president, Jose Maria Gil-Robles, said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   However, it was clear Tuesday that resistance to change would be
strong. Indeed, a cultural clash between a rigorous and reformist
northern Europe and a southern Europe that has been a major
beneficiary of European grants and subsidies appeared evident.
</P>
<P>
   The Italian and Spanish governments said Tuesday that the
commission should be allowed to complete its term, and Portugal
also gave guarded support for this position. Yves Thibault de
Silguy of France, the commissioner responsible for the euro, said
the report had merely revealed ``a few malfunctions'' and should
not obscure the Commission's achievements.
</P>
<P>
   But Scandinavian countries, traditionally vigilant over the way
tax money is spent, said the resignations should open the way for
sweeping reform, a position shared by Britain and Germany.
</P>
<P>
   ``The worst possible thing would be if the Commission was
reinstated,'' said Joachim Krauze, a German expert on European
affairs. ``For the first time, the commissioners have been shown
that they will be held responsible. They have to realize that
democratization is coming at a European level.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
