<HEADLINE>
JUDGE REFUSES TO BLOCK ENFORCEMENT OF PROP. 16 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK BLAUDSCHUN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The NCAA received another legal setback Tuesday when a federal
judge denied a request to delay the enforcement of a court order
wiping out minimum standardized test scores as a requirement for
freshman eligibility.
</P>
<P>
   US District Judge Ronald Buckwalter, who had issued the initial
order last week, denied the NCAA's request for a delay in a ruling
that technically could affect NCAA teams now participating in
postseason hockey and basketball tournaments as well as those just
beginning their spring seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Buckwalter's ruling last week struck down Proposition 16, which
required freshman athletes to have a high school diploma and a
minimum grade point average in 13 core academic courses, with the
GPA contingent on an indexed, sliding scale with scores on either
the Scholastic Assessment Test or the American College Test.
</P>
<P>
   Students scoring lower than 820 on the SAT or 16 on the ACT,
regardless of their other academic credentials, were ineligible for
the first year.
</P>
<P>
   Critics said using test scores to determine initial eligibility
was racially and culturally discriminatory.
</P>
<P>
   Buckwalter's ruling, prompted by four black athletes who filed
suit against the NCAA, supported that contention.
</P>
<P>
   The NCAA indicated it will appeal the decision, but the concern
is what happens now with teams that are still competing for
championships.
</P>
<P>
   Schools conceivably could use Prop. 16 athletes immediately if
they met the school's academic eligibility requirements.
</P>
<P>
   ``Each school has its own standards,'' said Boston College
basketball coach Al Skinner Tuesday. ``Each school has its own
mission. What's happening is that (the NCAA is) trying to make
everyone the same. That's just not the case.''
</P>
<P>
   Because the standards differ, some schools admit Prop. 16
students and some do not.
</P>
<P>
   Temple coach John Chaney, for example, has been a vocal critic
of Prop. 16. Would he now use a player who previously was declared
ineligible? A possible deterrent to such an action, though, is the
uncertainty of the appeal outcome. If the ruling were overturned,
schools using partial or non-qualifiers could be subject to
forfeiture of games and loss of revenue.
</P>
<P>
   Schools such as BC and Duke, who as a rule do not admit Prop. 16
athletes, would not be affected.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm happy for the ruling,'' said Skinner, ``because we all
felt test scores were not true barometers. What I thought was
unfair was not the initial ineligibility, but the loss of a year's
eligibility.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-16-99 1854EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
