<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUINS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRESSURE IS ON DAFOE _ ESPECIALLY ON THE ROAD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARVIN PAVE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- He's the last line of defense, the man who on occasion
has to make up for the mistakes of his teammates. But when Bruins
goalie Byron Dafoe gets beaten, the result shows up on the
scoreboard.
</P>
<P>
   Now, with his team in crunch time, vying for the eighth and
final playoff position in the Eastern Conference, and with the
Bruins in Toronto Wednesday to take on high-flying Mats Sundin,
Curtis Joseph, &AMP; Co. for the first time at the Air Canada Centre,
that pressure is magnified, especially on the road.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, down the stretch the goals become more important
and the starts of the games become more important,'' said Dafoe
after Tuesday's practice at Ristuccia Arena. ``(Earlier in the
season) there were times when it would take us a period to get into
a game, but we don't have time for that now and so as a goaltender,
you just have to be prepared from the drop of the puck and play
each period as if it were the start of overtime.''
</P>
<P>
   Dafoe, called ``our team MVP who gives us a chance to win every
night,'' by captain Ray Bourque, sports a 2.16 goals against
average and .923 save percentage (fifth best in the NHL) to go
along with seven shutouts (second best in the league). His
counterpart in the Toronto net, Joseph, is the man who has carried
the 37-25-5 Leafs into fourth place overall in the Eastern
Conference, according to Bruins coach Pat Burns.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're a confident team right now and Curtis Joseph is the
guy who's kept that club where they're at,'' said Burns.
</P>
<P>
   Joseph didn't have to work very hard the last time the Bruins
played in Toronto, Jan. 9, their last stop at Maple Leaf Gardens,
when Toronto ran out to a big first-period lead and blasted the
Bruins, 6-3.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were embarrassed,'' said Burns. ``I had to call a timeout
two minutes into the game, otherwise it would have been 10-0. We
didn't have Ray then, but now we have to go in and put that all
behind us and be confident.''
</P>
<P>
   And the Bruins don't have to do anything flashy to erase the bad
memories of that shellacking.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just have to be consistent,'' said Dafoe, ``just the like
the teams we're fighting with. It's pretty much us, the Rangers and
Florida, and we've got similar schedules. Every game is a must win
for us and for them. I'm not worried about our schedule. We can
beat any team in this league. We're trying not to look behind us,
but sometimes we have to.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I can say about our last game up here is that we weren't
ready and they were. They jumped right out at us, 4-0, in the first
15 minutes. Now it's a different story. We're playing for our
playoff lives right now. We don't care that it's a new building or
anything like that. We're looking for the 2 points. I don't care
where it is or who it's against.''
</P>
<P>
   Dafoe, more than any other Bruin (except backup netminder Rob
Tallas), will have some quick learning to do at practice.
</P>
<P>
   ``Generally, the new rinks are all very similar as far as the
boards and how the bounces are, but you never know,'' said Dafoe.
``We'll take some time to do some wraparounds at practice. It
sounds like it's an unbelievable building. So it'll be kind of neat
to play there.''
</P>
<P>
   He knows that getting some pucks past Joseph will be a challenge
for his teammates.
</P>
<P>
   ``He'll make the big save, and I think that's why they've done
so well this year,'' said Dafoe. ``He's allowed their offense to
take more chances because they expect him to make that big save on
a two-on-one or on a breakaway and he's done that all year for
them, and that's enabled their offense to explode.
</P>
<P>
   Dafoe says his adrenaline will flow a bit more with a quality
goalie like Joseph at the other end.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know it's going to be a tougher game against certain
goalies,'' he said, ``but Toronto has much more than him. We're
going against one of the best offenses in the league. You have to
be on your game from the get-go and you know you're going to be
facing more shots.''
</P>
<P>
   But, said defenseman Kyle McLaren, the Leafs will be facing a
pretty fair netminder as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``Byron has played well all year and he's really stepped up his
game the last few weeks,'' said McLaren. ``If we can help carry him
going into the last couple of weeks and build off him and get our
offense on a roll again, I think we're going to be OK.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins went through a spirited hourlong workout Tuesday at
the Wilmington practice arena before taking a 3 p.m. flight to
Toronto. Defenseman Don Sweeney was absent ``for personal
business'' according to Burns, but will play . . . The coach looks
at Boston's strong points as its power play, penalty killing (best
in the NHL), and goaltending, ``but we've got to get better
five-on-five,'' said Burns, whose team will have two days off after
the Toronot game before playing Saturday at home against San Jose .
. . The Bruins will have their eye on Sundin, Toronto's leading
scorer (24-44_68), said McLaren. ``They're a good team all around,
but Sundin's their main guy,'' he said, ``and if we can shut him
down and limit his opportunities, we'll have a good chance of
winning the game.'' . . . Winger Anson Carter on the last 16 games
of the season: ``Whether you win or lose, you have to put it behind
you and focus on the next game. Our veterans and our coaching will
be important. There's definitely a calming effect there, but I'm
also pretty excited. I like this time of year. This is the fun part
of hockey when all the games mean something.'' . . . Bourque said
the Bruins are as healthy as they've been all season, ``which
should help us bring our best game out there every night.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
