<SLUG> BC-INS-BUDGET-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARIZONA, TEXAS SENATORS DECRY CLINTON PROPOSAL NOT TO ADD MORE
BORDER AGENTS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By STEVE LASH 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Immigration and Naturalization Service chief Doris
Meissner said Tuesday that the Clinton administration will add no
new Border Patrol agents next fiscal year, incurring the wrath of
Texas and Arizona senators who said more are needed to stem the
flow of illegal immigrants and drugs through their states.
</P>
<P>
   Appearing before a Senate Appropriations subcommittee, Meissner
said President Clinton believes the current force of nearly 9,000
Border Patrol agents is adequate. She defended Clinton's proposal
by saying the Border Patrol would be strengthened not by more
agents but by Congress approving the president's proposed $50
million in enhancements, including high-tech cameras and tracking
systems.
</P>
<P>
   Meissner's call for no additional patrol officers in fiscal year
2000, which begins Oct. 1, follows her announcement last month that
INS plans to hire 1,000 new agents by Sept. 30. Texas will receive
500 of the new patrol agents, bringing to 3,933 the number of
officers on the state's border with Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   ``The administration has decided to take a breather for a
year,'' Meissner said in explaining the year-to-year shift in her
agency's hiring of patrol agents.
</P>
<P>
   But Sen. Kay Bailey Hutchison, R-Texas, and Sen. Jon Kyl,
R-Ariz., mocked Meissner's explanation and said 9,000 agents are
insufficient to thwart immigrants and drug couriers determined to
enter the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Hutchison, a subcommittee member, said Meissner's testimony
reminded her of 1997, when the INS chief also told the subcommittee
that the administration needed a breather. At that time, the
president proposed budgeting only 500 agents after Congress had
authorized 1,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``The border in Texas was a sieve,'' Hutchison said in
explaining her opposition to the president's request then. Clinton
increased his request to 1,000 agents, but only under heavy
congressional opposition, the senator said.
</P>
<P>
   Hutchison also disputed Meissner's view of INS technology,
saying that state-of-the-art cameras and tracking devices are no
substitute for having agents ready to respond when the technology
detects illegal immigrants. ``The chances of (agents) actually
getting there in time is not terrific,'' the senator said. She
urged Meissner to add more Border Patrol officers next year.
</P>
<P>
   Kyl, noting the non-stop flow of illegal immigrants coming
through Arizona, protested the president's refusal to endorse
additional agents. ``Nobody else at the border is taking a
breather,'' said the senator, who is not a subcommittee member but
attended the panel's hearing and questioned Meissner.
</P>
<P>
   The INS chief responded that Clinton's decision should be
interpreted not as an easing of border enforcement but rather as an
opportunity for the agency to improve the talents of its agents.
Nearly 48 percent of Border Patrol officers have fewer than three
years of experience, Meissner said.
</P>
<P>
   ``With a year of consolidation, INS will be able to ensure that
we maintain our current authorized strength, while continuing to
safeguard the highest standards of law enforcement professionalism
for this new workforce by building their experience and
effectiveness,'' Meissner told the Subcommittee on Commerce,
Justice, State and the Judiciary.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney General Janet Reno, Meissner's superior at the Justice
Department, gave the subcommittee a similar message during her
appearance before the panel last week.
</P>
<P>
   But Meissner, under questioning from Kyl, conceded that she had
urged the president to approve 1,000 new Border Patrol agents for
fiscal year 2000, but the White House balked. That admission drew
sympathy from Hutchison, who called Meissner ``a good soldier'' by
taking fire for Clinton's decision to seek no new agents.
</P>
<P>
   Meissner testified before the subcommittee in defense of the
president's proposed $4.27 billion budget for INS in fiscal 2000.
That funding would represent an 8 percent increase from the
agency's $3.9 billion budget for fiscal year 1999, which ends Sept.
30.
</P>
<P>
   The proposed budget includes $50 million to fund the Border
Patrol, $20 million to support enforcement of immigration laws
within the United States, $16.8 million to transport illegal
immigrants and $6 million to staff 87 positions at three new land
border ports of entry in Texas: Eagle Pass, Los Tomates and Laredo.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
