<HEADLINE>
CELTICS LOOK TO POTAPENKO'S BLOCKING ABILITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER MAY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- The newest member of the Celtics went through a 2
1/2-hour practice and film session Tuesday. Then came the hardest
part: meeting a sizable press corps that had coach Rick Pitino
wondering whether the playoffs had started.
</P>
<P>
   Before acquiring Vitaly Potapenko last week, the Celtics' two
biggest interior weaknesses were rebounding and shot-blocking. Now
that they have Potapenko, their two biggest interior weaknesses are
rebounding and shot-blocking. He's not known for either, but he is
a wide body who won't be moved around like a coat rack, which is
something the Celtics have lacked.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a very strong man,'' Pitino said. ``He also keeps his man
off the glass. This is one of our best acquisitions for the needs
of this basketball team.''
</P>
<P>
   Added general manager Chris Wallace, ``Yeah, we need to have
stronger rebounding and we need some shot-blocking, but this was
the best alternative that we could see on the horizon in terms of a
big body.''
</P>
<P>
   Potapenko turns 24 Sunday. He has been in the United States only
a little more than four years, the last four in Ohio and the last
two in Cleveland. (He still hasn't been to the Rock and Roll Hall
of Fame, but we won't hold that against him.) He grew up in Kiev
first as a volleyball player _ his sister still plays the sport _
and turned to basketball when his expanding size made that move a
wise decision.
</P>
<P>
   He is 6 feet 10 inches, weighs 273, and is Bunyanesque in
strength. Asked how much he bench-pressed, he grinned and said, ``A
lot.'' His father, Nikolay, is a 6-3 construction manager back in
Kiev and his mom, Anna, is a housewife. She's 5-7. He said his
paternal grandfather is 6-7 and there are some big aunts and uncles
as well. His sister is 5-11. He sees his parents at least once a
year, but added, ``I'm too busy to get homesick.'' He's single and
the possessor of a new, six-year, $30-something million contract,
but doesn't sound like the kind of guy who'll appear in the gossip
columns.
</P>
<P>
   He played for the Soviet Union's national junior team and for a
club team in Kiev while he attended Kiev State. (Honest.) A Wright
State bird dog got him to come to the Dayton school and he spent
two years there, working on his game _ he was all-conference both
years _ and his English.
</P>
<P>
   ``I picked most of it up at college,'' Potapenko said Tuesday at
the Celtics' practice facility at Brandeis University, of his
English, which is pretty good. ``I had a lot of tutoring lessons. I
had no other choice. No one spoke Russian there. So it made me
learn English faster.''
</P>
<P>
   He exploded on the NBA scene during the predraft camp in Chicago
in 1996. No one could match his strength and he showed a decent
offensive game around the post. Before the camp, he was seen as a
second-round pick. Agent David Falk then got him a trainer, and it
paid off: He ended up going 12th to the Cavaliers.
</P>
<P>
   He's aware of the Celtics' history and tradition, mentioning
Bill Russell and Bob Cousy as great players along with the Big
Three, whom he watched on television.
</P>
<P>
   ``I used to watch them a lot,'' he said. ``I'm proud to play for
this team. Very proud.''
</P>
<P>
   Don't look for a glass-eater against the Clippers, when ``V,''
as the Celtics call him, makes his first FleetCenter start as a
Celtic. He averaged only 3.3 rebounds a game in his first two
years; it's up a bit this year, mainly because of the increased
playing time he got after Zydrunas Ilgauskas's season-ending
injury. Over that same span, he blocked 62 shots in 160 games.
</P>
<P>
   But regardless what he does, you can't miss him. That's why he's
here.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Andrew DeClercq, the Celtics also gave up a No. 1
pick to get Potapenko, and Wallace explained how the deal works.
Boston has protection for the first three picks this year; the Cavs
must notify them of their intention 10 days before the draft. If
Cleveland passes this year, the pick is not protected in 2000. The
Cavs also can pass on that one, but they then have to take the
Celtics' 2001 pick . . . Former Celtics assistant Don Casey coached
his first game Tuesday as John Calipari's replacement in New
Jersey. He had no assistants; they all were fired along with Cal.
Casey has hired former NBA coaches Jimmy Lynam and Eddie Jordan as
assistants, but they won't join the team until Wednesday. Tuesday
Casey had scout Hal Wissel and former player/radio man Mike O'Koren
help him on the bench . . . Pitino on the Clippers: ``This team is
10 deep and as talented as anyone we can play. You look at teams at
how they are playing now. This team can beat you. They had Seattle
beaten and Portland beaten and they did beat Sacramento.'' . . .
Pitino said Paul Pierce re-sprained his right ankle Tuesday but was
OK. ``He's still not there physically, but he's 100 percent
mentally,'' the coach said. Pitino also preened a bit over
Kentucky's win over Kansas last weekend. He won a bet with Pierce
and the rook will have to wear a Kentucky shirt at Wednesday's
shootaround. ``I pointed out a graphic during the game that noted
Kansas had played Kentucky 21 times and it was 18-3 (for
Kentucky),'' said Pitino. ``I took advantage of his lack of
experience.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
