u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-MEDICARE-HNS &LR;      03-16 0714
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-MEDICARE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON TO UNVEIL OWN MEDICARE PLAN AS PANEL FAILS TO AGREE ON
PROPOSAL 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By GREG McDONALD 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton promised Tuesday to craft his own
plan this year to keep Medicare solvent as a bipartisan
congressional commission charged with overhauling the elderly's
government health insurance program broke up without reaching
agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Although Clinton praised the panel headed by Sen. John Breaux,
D-La., and Rep. Bill Thomas, R-Calif., for making a ``valuable''
contribution to the debate, he said he could not support its plan
to save Medicare by increasing competition among providers.
</P>
<P>
   The plan was endorsed by 10 of the panel's 17 members but did
not secure enough votes to be passed out of the commission.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said he would soon offer his own Medicare reform plan
that would include coverage for prescription drugs and use up to 15
percent of projected budget surpluses during the next 10 to 15
years to help keep the program afloat beyond 2009, when it is
expected to run out of money.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to make it clear that I believe we owe it to the
American people to make an agreement this year,'' he said. ``And
I'm going to do my dead level best to get it done.''
</P>
<P>
   While Clinton said the commission's work had produced some
``very strong elements'' that ought to be seriously considered as
part of a final Medicare package, he objected to a provision that
would raise the eligible age from 65 to 67.
</P>
<P>
   He also said the plan has the ``potential to increase premiums''
beyond normal inflation rates for seniors on fixed incomes and does
not provide for ``an adequate, affordable prescription drug
benefit.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But most important of all, it fails to make a solid commitment
of 15 percent of the surplus to the Medicare trust fund,'' Clinton
said. ``Even if all the changes recommended by the commission were
adopted, because of the projected inflation rates and health care
costs, it would not be sufficient to stabilize the fund.''
</P>
<P>
   Republican congressional leaders were quick to criticize the
president for not supporting the commission's work more fully. But
they gave little support of their own because of competing
GOP-sponsored proposals that are likely to be offered in Congress
over the next few months.
</P>
<P>
   Some Republicans also expressed little interest in trying to
address Medicare problems until Congress acts to preserve the the
Social Security program.
</P>
<P>
   For example, House Majority Leader Dick Armey, R-Texas, said it
was a ``crying shame'' that the commission adjourned after failing
by one vote to recommend a reform plan to Congress.
</P>
<P>
   But he acknowledged to reporters that few of the panel's
proposals would have been included in the 2000 budget Congress is
working on now because of the GOP's priority to shore up Social
Security.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our first job is to save every dollar of the payroll taxes for
Social Security ... and then give ourselves the time that it would
take to work out the legislative details of a (Medicare)
solution,'' Armey said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, he said it would have been ``nice'' to have the panel's
recommendation as a ``departure point'' for consideration as
Congress begins to look at other proposals, including the
president's and one Texas Sen. Phil Gramm hopes to unveil. Gramm
said his proposal will include additional assistance for
prescription drugs and will save $100 billion over 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   Although the 17-member commission fell short of the 11 votes
needed to recommend its reform plan, Breaux and Thomas said they
would likely act on their own to introduce it in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we've got is very important,'' Breaux said, predicting
that the commission plan could get 60 votes in the Senate. ``We've
changed the debate in a major, major way.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the commission plan, retirees would have been able to
choose from a list of coverage policies at different price ranges,
just like private health insurance companies offer. Drug coverage
plans would have been offered as well, but at additional costs.
</P>
<P>
   Breaux and Thomas insisted that raising the eligible age would
have helped keep Medicare solvent through at least 2017.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
