<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FORBES-ANNOUNCE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORBES, HAT IN RING, TAKES ANTI-TAX PLEDGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JILL ZUCKMAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CONCORD, N.H. _ After launching his presidential campaign on the
Internet Tuesday, Steve Forbes became the first candidate to sign
the state's famous anti-tax pledge, promising not to raise taxes
for individuals or businesses.
</P>
<P>
   But as he stood with his back to the state capitol and touted
his proposal to eliminate the current federal tax code and
institute a 17 percent flat tax, protesters from Boston began
chanting ``billionaires for Forbes'' and waving banners that said
``Tax cuts for me, not my maid,'' and ``Because inequality isn't
growing fast enough.''
</P>
<P>
   Aides to Forbes ripped some of the posters out of the
demonstrators' hands and tried to hustle them away from the
television cameras. The candidate himself dryly acknowledged
``those who are skeptical'' by saying they needed remedial
education.
</P>
<P>
   The subject of taxes has always inspired great passion in New
Hampshire, where there is no income tax and no sales tax. Most
state and local politicians here have felt compelled to sign the
well-known pledge, popularized by the late publisher of the
Manchester Union-Leader, William Loeb. Tuesday, Forbes said he
hoped all candidates for elective office would follow his lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will always be pressure, always be excuses, for imposing
more burdens on the people of New Hampshire,'' he said. ``In
Washington, they always have excuses on why they must impose more
burdens on all of the American people.''
</P>
<P>
   Chuck Collins, co-director of United for a Fair Economy, an
economic research group in Boston, said he and his protesters are
concerned that Forbes' proposals would lead to greater economic
disparities in the nation. Collins said the protest would be
repeated when Forbes arrives in Iowa later this week, and in other
cities around the country.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes' second run for the Republican nomination will be just as
heavily focused on taxes as the first. But as he continues to push
for a 17 percent flat federal income tax, the Granite State's
typical resolve against taxes is no longer quite so solid.
</P>
<P>
   An income tax bill was recently approved in the House with the
support of many Republicans representing poor school districts in
need of state dollars. The Senate could pass the measure, too, but
Governor Jeanne Shaheen, a Democrat, has promised to veto it.
</P>
<P>
   The issue seems to have galvanized Forbes, who plans to
demonstrate his disdain for taxes come April 15, when tax returns
are due. His campaign will stage a reenactment of the famous
``Stamp tax revolt of 1765'' in Portsmouth, replete with fife and
drums, as well as a casket in which to bury the federal tax code,
which Forbes calls ``corruptingly complex.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, Forbes placed fourth in New Hampshire, behind Patrick
J. Buchanan, Bob Dole and Lamar Alexander. His television ads,
however, nearly sank Dole's campaign here, and he drew great
interest for his conservative, economic themes.
</P>
<P>
   The multi-millionaire publisher has tried to broaden his appeal
during the last three years, also focusing on social issues, such
as a strong anti-abortion stance. And in this first-in-the-nation
primary state, he has courted activists and put together a seasoned
group of political strategists.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-16-99 1910EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
