<DOCNO> NYT19990316.0242 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-16 19:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2776 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-AFRICA-0317-C     03-16 0816
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-AFRICA-0317-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CLINTON CHIDES CONGRESSIONAL BLACKS TO COME TOGETHER ON AFRICA
TRADE BILL
 &HT;    Moving in both the (i) International and (w) Washington
categories.
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ With the Congressional Black Caucus deeply split
over how to increase U.S. trade with Africa, President Clinton
invoked the words of Abraham Lincoln Tuesday in calling on
lawmakers to rally around the White House approach.
</P>
<P>
   ''We cannot afford a house divided,'' Clinton admonished,
paraphrasing the powerful, Biblically-based rhetoric Lincoln used
to describe an American nation split by pro-slave and anti-slave
factions.
</P>
<P>
   ''Africa,'' said Clinton, ''needs action now.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton made the remarks during a 20-minute speech to delegates
attending the first-ever U.S.-Africa Ministerial. The meeting at
the State Department this week groups U.S. cabinet-level officials
with nearly 200 of their counterparts from 46 sub-Saharan African
states.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also called for the cancellation of some $70 billion in
long-term debt owed to wealthy nations like the United States by
developing countries, like those in Africa.
</P>
<P>
   He said he is seeking $237 million in African debt relief next
year, on top of the $245 million in such relief already contained
in this year's budget.
</P>
<P>
   ``The message I want your leaders to take home is this is a
partnership with substance backed by a long-term commitment,''
Clinton said. ''This is truly a relationship for the long haul.''
</P>
<P>
   High on the agenda is the goal of trying to link the
impoverished but resource-rich continent with the promise of the
global marketplace.
</P>
<P>
   A year ago next week, Clinton made an 11-day swing through
Africa, vowing to lift trade restrictions as a way to help promote
U.S.-Africa trade.
</P>
<P>
   The legislative vehicle for those changes, the so-called Africa
Growth and Opportunity Act, has stalled on Capitol Hill.
</P>
<P>
   The Act passed the House last February, 233-186, but then
languished in the Senate Finance Committee amid political haggling
over whether to attach additional free-trade legislation to the
bill.
</P>
<P>
   Now it's back before the House Ways &AMP; Means Committee, awaiting
a recommendation for a second vote by the new House elected last
November.
</P>
<P>
   The bill is controversial not because of race, but because it
touches on one of the most sensitive political issues of the era:
trade.
</P>
<P>
   And yet, many black members of Congress in an awkward position.
</P>
<P>
   Many, like Rep. John Lewis, D-Ga., want, in theory, to support
increased trade with Africa, but are reluctant to go along with
certain provisions of the growth and opportunity act because, like
any trade-expanding legislation, it's seen as threatening to some
of their traditional constituents in organized labor.
</P>
<P>
   Others, like Rep. James Clyburn, D-S.C., hail from southern
states where parts of the bill are opposed by influential textile
companies, which fear the bill could result in painful new
competition from low-cost African rivals.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis and Clyburn, both of whom are black, favor an alternative
bill put forth last month by Rep. Jesse Jackson Jr., D-Ill., the
son of the civil rights activist, the Rev. Jesse Jackson, who is
the special White House envoy for democratization in Africa.
</P>
<P>
   Among other things, the Jackson bill, called the Human Rights,
Opportunity, Partnership and Empowerment for Africa Act, or HOPE
for Africa Act, would treat textile imports differently from the
White House plan. It would also cancel the debt owed to the United
States by sub-Saharan African countries.
</P>
<P>
   ``The support for our bill is growing every day,'' said younger
Jackson's press spokesman, Frank Watkins, who said that, just three
weeks after its introduction, the bill already has 56 co-sponsors
-- backers willing to put their name on the legislation.
</P>
<P>
   Privately, White House aides grumble that Jackson's bill is
dividing the support for Africa trade liberalization, helping, in
effect, opponents of increased trade with Africa.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're empowering our opponents, who don't want to do
anything for Africa anyway,'' asserted one administration official,
speaking on background. ''It's infuriating the Africans and just
causing unnecessary divisions in the African-American community.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson's office responded, however, that his legislation is
picking up steam not because it's breeding divisiveness, but
because it addresses serious flaws in the administration's
approach.
</P>
<P>
   And, said Watkins, if the White House backed legislation,
sponsored in the House by Rep. Charles Rangel, D-N.Y., and 74
others, Republicans and Democrats, is defeated, that's fine.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is better to do nothing,'' said Watkins, ''than to pass
(the African Growth and Opportunity Act).''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
