<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-16 19:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2778 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IRELAND-CARBOMB-BOS &LR;      03-16 1173
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRELAND-CARBOMB-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORK OF CIVIL RIGHTS LAWYERS CHILLED IN WAKE OF BOMBING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELFAST _ Sitting in his Andersonstown law office Tuesday, Barra
McGrory was a jumble of emotions.
</P>
<P>
   He mourned his colleague, Rosemary Nelson, killed the day before
by a bomb planted by Protestant extremists. He admired her dogged
advocacy for human rights, and it sickened him to think what her
husband and three children were going through.
</P>
<P>
   And he couldn't help but wonder if he was next.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think every lawyer who's been involved in human and civil
rights work here feels the same way,'' said McGrory, one of the
leading defense lawyers in Northern Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   Nelson, 40, an outspoken advocate for Irish Catholic
nationalists who claim unequal treatment at the hands of Northern
Ireland's police, was killed Monday when a sophisticated bomb
planted under her car exploded. A loyalist paramilitary group
opposed to the Northern Ireland peace process claimed
responsibility.
</P>
<P>
   Nelson's murder cast a pall over St. Patrick's Day festivities
here and in Washington, where Northern Ireland's political leaders
have gathered for a White House party Wednesday with President
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   It also sent a chill through the legal community here, and it
revived unanswered questions about the unsolved murder of the only
other lawyer in Northern Ireland to have been killed because he
represented combatants in the conflict.
</P>
<P>
   Ten years ago, loyalist assassins broke into the home of Belfast
lawyer Patrick Finucane and shot him to death as he ate dinner with
his wife and children. Finucane had regularly defended Irish
Republican Army members.
</P>
<P>
   Finucane's murder came just days after a British cabinet
minister suggested that some lawyers were unduly sympathetic to IRA
members they defended. While the minister didn't single out
Finucane, his work as the busiest defense lawyer in Belfast made
him a target, colleagues say. Afterward, allegations surfaced that
some detectives had encouraged loyalists to kill him.
</P>
<P>
   The probe into Finucane's murder ended inconclusively, with no
charges, and in recent years Nelson had been an outspoken advocate
for a new investigation. She replaced him as the most high-profile
defender of Irish republicans who support the IRA and Irish
nationalists in general, including those in the town of Portadown
who have sought to block Protestant bands from parading through
their neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   That made her an enemy of the police. Nelson had charged that
police officers routinely harassed her, beat her and threatened to
kill her. Her complaints were the basis of a United Nations report
last year that criticized police and called for a new investigation
into Finucane's murder. Her complaints are also the subject of a
report by a civilian commission scheduled for release Friday.
Sources familiar with its contents say the report is highly
critical of the police.
</P>
<P>
   Members of Sinn Fein, the IRA's political wing, are claiming
that Nelson's murderers were assisted by police. Graffitti have
sprung up making the same allegation. Sinn Fein wants the Royal
Ulster Constabulary to be disbanded, saying the force, which is 93
percent Protestant, is irremediably biased toward unionists who
want to remain part of Britain.
</P>
<P>
   Those making the allegations, such as Sinn Fein councilor John
Dowd, have no hard evidence, but they pointed to circumstantial
evidence.
</P>
<P>
   First, they pointed to motive. Among Northern Ireland's
attorneys, none was more vociferous in criticizing the police than
Nelson. She had also embarrassed them, winning acquittals for IRA
suspects who were charged on flimsy evidence.
</P>
<P>
   Second, Dowd and others point to the sophistication of the bomb.
The group that claimed responsibility, the Red Hand Defenders, has
never displayed the capability of using a so-called ``tilt'' device
that detonates the bomb when a car slows down. Sinn Fein leaders
and others argue that the sophistication of the bomb shows that
either it was prepared by members of the larger loyalist groups
that claim to be honoring a cease-fire, or the killers had help
from rogue British agents who don't want the peace process to work.
</P>
<P>
   McGrory and most other lawyers aren't making allegations they
can't substantiate. But many believe the police are incapable of
carrying out an impartial investigation, so deep was the mistrust
between Nelson and the police.
</P>
<P>
   Sir Ronnie Flanagan, chief of the Royal Ulster Constabulary,
recognized the perception problem within hours of the murder. In an
unprecedented move, he asked that the investigation be controlled
by an outside law enforcement agency. Tuesday, David Phillips,
chief constable of the police in Kent, England, was appointed to
lead the probe. Flanagan also asked the American FBI to provide
forensics assistence.
</P>
<P>
   Flanagan said his move was ``no reflection'' on the integrity of
his officers. ``It's a reflection on the sensitivity I must show,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   McGrory was heartened by Flanagan's move, saying it ``shows how
far advanced the peace process is.''
</P>
<P>
   Already stalled by a dispute over the IRA's refusal to turn in
weapons and the unionists' refusal to form a local government until
the IRA begins disarming, the peace process was not helped by
Nelson's murder. Hardliners, including Duffy, who is free today
only because of Nelson's legal acumen, will be even more reluctant
to disarm, saying they need weapons to protect their neighborhoods
from loyalists like those who killed Nelson.
</P>
<P>
   For lawyers who challenge the system and the police, these are
scary days. McGrory was on the phone Tuesday to other lawyers. They
grieved for Nelson and her family, including her 8-year-old
daughter Sarah, who was at a nearby school and heard the explosion
that killed her mother.
</P>
<P>
   But Barra McGrory said they also compared notes about the
danger, about precautions. For McGrory, it was an unsettling case
of deja vu. Ten years ago, he remembers, his father, Paddy McGrory,
was the dean of the local defense bar. Although he was a man very
much against violence, he took to carrying a gun for protection in
the wake of Pat Finucane's murder.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Pat Finucane was murdered, a lot of lawyers comforted
themselves in that it was a one-off, that the revulsion that
followed made the targeting of lawyers off limits,'' Barra McGrory
said. ``But Rosemary's murder changes everything. People are
frightened. They don't know where this is going. This is an attack
at the very heart of democracy.''
</P>
<P>
   McGrory says it would be fitting if Nelson's murder led to a new
investigation into Finucane's killing. In the meantime, while he
doesn't consider himself brave, McGrory has no intention of giving
up his work. He will continue taking cases that anger the
authorities, using the law instead of violence as an instrument of
change.
</P>
<P>
   It's what his father would have done.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's what Rosemary would do,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
