<HEADLINE>
NORTH KOREA SAYS IT WILL ADMIT US WEAPONS INSPECTORS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By COLUM LYNCH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ North Korea agreed Tuesday to allow US inspectors
into an underground suspected nuclear weapons complex, ending a
diplomatic standoff that threatened to undermine American efforts
to halt Pyongyang's atomic ambitions.
</P>
<P>
   The United States, for its part, offered to grant crop
development assistance to the impoverished nation, which is facing
severe food shortages.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've just reached an agreement in New York with the North
Koreans on access to the suspect underground site at Kumchang-ni,''
US Secretary of State Madeleine K. Albright said in a statement
Tuesday. ``It will enable us both to confirm and monitor the
current and future use of the suspect site.''
</P>
<P>
   The accord has eased American anxiety prompted by intelligence
reports that the world's most secretive Communist government had
restarted a nuclear weapons development program it had abandoned in
1994 following an agreement by the United States to help the
country modernize.
</P>
<P>
   Last year US intelligence began suspecting the Koreans resumed
the operation after thousands of workers were detected on satellite
at the Kumchang-ni facility, which has been linked to its former
weapons program.
</P>
<P>
   Albright also announced that the Koreans had agreed to American
demands for talks aimed at limiting that country's missile
development program. Last summer North Korea launched a three-stage
missile over Japanese territory. The test alarmed American
intelligence agencies, who have since estimated that Pyongyang is
on the verge of perfecting a missile capable of striking Hawaii or
Alaska.
</P>
<P>
   But administration officials insisted the agreement was not a
direct food-for-access exchange. State Department spokesman James
P. Rubin said Pyongyang's action freed the Americans to approve a
``very modest potato project.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We did not agree to North Korean demands for ``compensation,''
Albright insisted. But ``removal of our suspicions concerning
Kumchang-ni would enable us to resume progress in our
relationship.''
</P>
<P>
   The accord permits an American arms control team to make
multiple visits to Kumchang-ni. The first visit will begin in May
of this year. A second trip is scheduled for May 2000. But a senior
US official said that the US obtained a commitment to conduct as
``many visits as necessary.''
</P>
<P>
   North Korea denied that it is developing nuclear weapons.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has nothing to with nuclear activities,'' said North Korean
Vice Foreign Minister Kim Gye Gwan. ``The site is related to
sensitive national security purposes.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement, which was struck between Kim and US envoy Charles
Kartman, came after three weeks of shuttle diplomacy in New York,
Washington and Pyongyang. A senior US official said it removes
``the boulder out of the middle of the road'' to improved relations
between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
   The cornerstone of US relations with North Korea is the 1994
Agreed Framework pact. That accord obliges the United States to
raise $5 billion, primarily from Japan and South Korea, to build a
pair of light water reactors in North Korea.
</P>
<P>
   The United States, meanwhile, has been supplying North Korea
with hundreds of millions of dollars in heavy fuel oil to power the
country's industry.
</P>
<P>
   In exchange, Pyongyang agreed to halt the development of nuclear
weapons.
</P>
<P>
   Over the past year, the North Korean leadership has periodically
threatened to break the accord, charging that the United States has
failed to meet its obligations to ease crippling economic
sanctions.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-16-99 1922EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990316.0249 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-16 19:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2794 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CARLYLE-RAVENOUS-LADN     03-16 1478
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CARLYLE-RAVENOUS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`FULL MONTY' WHETS ACTOR'S APPETITE FOR THE OFFBEAT  
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BOB STRAUSS  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Robert Carlyle is devouring the world.
</P>
<P>
   OK, that statement is a little overstuffed. But the 38-year-old
Scottish actor has swallowed up some prime roles recently,
including the next James Bond movie villain and the wastrel father
of Frank McCourt in the film adaptation of his best-selling memoir
``Angela's Ashes.''
</P>
<P>
   The former Glasgow house painter clearly is capitalizing on the
success of ``The Full Monty,'' in which he played a likable,
divorced dad who got his unemployed buddies to stage a male strip
show. The naughty-yet-empowering comedy gobbled up some $211
million worldwide, which made it the most successful British
production in history. It also was served a plateful of Oscar
nominations, including a surprise best picture nod, and won for its
musical score.
</P>
<P>
   By now you're wondering, what's with all the eating metaphors?
They're because, for all his obvious bankability, Carlyle chose to
take a year off after ``Monty'' madness to assess his career, then
resumed work with, of all things, ``Ravenous,'' a comic cannibal
western.
</P>
<P>
   Now, that's confidence. Or maybe it's just the kind of thing a
guy who really doesn't care about movie stardom does because it
intrigues him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would never, ever choose a project or turn a project down
because of what I thought it was going to do financially,''
Carlyle, a sandy-haired, compactly built man, says in a strong
Scottish burr. ``That's not the way for me to go about it. It's the
elements that are in place _ the director, script, cast _ that's
why I'll do any piece. Not because of what it may do, or may do for
me.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, a main element fell out of place soon after
``Ravenous'' started filming in the Czech Republic. Milcho
Manchevski, the acclaimed Yugoslavian director of ``Before the
Rain,'' was let go several weeks into production, stranding Carlyle
and an eclectic group of co-stars _ Guy Pearce (``L.A.
Confidential''), Jeremy Davies (``Saving Private Ryan''), Jeffrey
Jones (``Amadeus''), David Arquette (``Scream'') _ on snow-covered
mountain sets.
</P>
<P>
   Partly through Carlyle's urging, the English director Antonia
Bird, with whom he'd made the controversial ``Priest'' and two
other features, came to the rescue.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always like working with Robert because he's a chameleon,
and I think all great actors are chameleons,'' Bird says. ``He
always surprises me, his imagination and his ability to get under
the skin of a new character and show you something that you've
never seen before.''
</P>
<P>
   Interesting choice of words, under the skin, considering the
scenario on the, um, table. ``Ravenous'' is set shortly after the
1840s war with Mexico, at an isolated fort in California's Sierra
Nevada. A strange visitor, Carlyle's Colqhoun, stumbles into the
stockade with an alarming tale of getting lost in the snow with a
pioneer party, taking refuge in a cave and, when food supplies ran
out ...
</P>
<P>
   Before you can say Donner Party, Colqhoun has gone Weendigo on
the small garrison, deriving, like the Indian legend, supernatural
powers from consuming the flesh and blood of other humans. As if
this bizarre mixture of horror and history wasn't intriguing
enough, Carlyle adds that its implicit social satire _ a quality
that connects much of his work, from Ken Loach's class comedy
``Riff Raff'' to the trippy ``Trainspotting'' to ``Monty'' _ was
the project's main attraction.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't so much about playing a cannibal that was
interesting,'' he notes, relievingly. ``It was more the underlying
themes of the piece. The fact that it was set in California I found
very, very amusing, because the state is very identified with the
desire to have the body beautiful, with cosmetic surgery and the
live-forever kind of ethic. This guy is kind of the first
Californian, saying much the same stuff with a kind of twisted,
satiric voice.
</P>
<P>
   ``And it's a lampoon of expansionism and consumerism. As one of
the characters says, the country is stretching out its arms and
consuming all it can. Nothing much has changed, really, since those
times.''
</P>
<P>
   It was the discovery of social criticism in drama that first
inspired Carlyle to act. ``The catalyst was, a friend of mine gave
me a copy of `The Crucible' when I was 21,'' he recalls of Arthur
Miller's play about the Salem witch trials, which was considered a
thinly veiled attack on the anti-communist hysteria of the 1950s.
``I read this thing and I just thought, `How wonderful to be able
to talk about one thing but disguise it as sort of another.' In a
sense, that's what I've been doing my whole life ever since.''
</P>
<P>
   Carlyle attended drama school for three years and appeared in
amateur productions around Glasgow before moving up to professional
theater. In 1990, he started his own theatrical company, Rain Dog,
where he served as artistic director for five years and remains an
associate.
</P>
<P>
   Carlyle is quick to point out that, for all his commitment to
politically engaged work, he places a high premium on enjoying
himself, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``My way into the whole thing (of `Ravenous') was to try and
have as much fun as possible and savor that character,'' he says.
``This guy will not only eat your leg, he'll tell you why he's
doing it, so I tried to put the tongue firmly in cheek.''
</P>
<P>
   Carlyle describes ``Plunkett and MacLeane,'' an upcoming release
in which he plays an 18th-century British highwayman, as ``fun,
swashbuckling action.''
</P>
<P>
   As for ``The World Is Not Enough,'' in which he plays the
nemesis of Pierce Brosnan's James Bond, Carlyle cheerfully reports
that he's going for ``a blow-up-the-world villain rather than a
dominate-the-world one. He has a bullet in his head, so he's
actually dying from the beginning. That makes him very difficult to
kill, because he has no fear and, as a result of this injury, his
pain senses are closing down and he doesn't feel anything.
</P>
<P>
   ``So, he's sort of a slippery customer,'' Carlyle notes. ``It's
hard, though. You look at the people who have played these parts
through the years _ people like Robert Shaw, Christopher Walken,
etc. _ and in order to be a part of that group, I just have to try
and make it as memorable as possible.''
</P>
<P>
   There's a bit of ethnic pride involved in the assignment, too.
Before Carlyle and fellow Scot Ewan McGregor emerged from
``Trainspotting'' as major stars, original Bond Sean Connery was
pretty much Scotland's sole movie standard bearer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I used to go and see the Bond films with my father, and Sean
Connery was the only actor that sounded like me up there,'' he
recalls. ``The link between Connery and Bond and acting and Scots
is fundamental. It's like taking part in some kind of history piece
for us. It's part of your psyche.''
</P>
<P>
   Carlyle maintains a home in Glasgow with his wife, Anna, a
makeup artist. And, although he's Caledonian to the core, he tried
to bring a kind of Celtic cousin empathy to his portrayal of the
dissolute Irishman Malachy McCourt for the film version of
``Angela's Ashes,'' which co-stars Emily Watson and, like the Bond
film, will be released at the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very harrowing story,'' Carlyle concedes. ``Everyone
who I told I was playing the father said, `Oh, he was such a
bastard.' But of course the children, nor Angela, never had a bad
word to say about the guy their whole lives. His crime was that he
couldn't face his responsibilities, he couldn't accpet the fact
that he had children to look after. He was fond of drink, and that
took him off in a different world.
</P>
<P>
   ``So, what I tried to do with this part was to soften the
character to a certain extent, so it let the audience enter his
pain as well. It would be wrong, I think, to paint Malachy McCourt
as the villain of the piece. The villain of the piece, for me, is
the society that allowed that whole situation to exist.''
</P>
<P>
   Irish poverty in the first half of the century is truly a world
away from the millennial media stardom on the cusp of which Carlyle
now finds himself _ a world of hype, he hopes, he'll maintain the
good sense to navigate successfully.
</P>
<P>
   ``To say I was surprised by `The Full Monty's' success is an
understatement, really,'' he acknowledges. ``If I knew it was going
to be that big, I could make a living buying lottery tickets. You
just don't know about something like that, and when it becomes a
phenomenon, it kind of overtakes you.
</P>
<P>
   ``So, when it happened, I kind of held back from it. There's a
body of work, some 15 films, in Europe, and I didn't want to come
across to Los Angeles and be The Chap From `The Full Monty.' Not to
take away from that or detract from that in any way, but it just
ain't the sum total of who I am.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
