<SLUG> BC-MISSILE-BILL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHITE HOUSE AGREES TO LIMITED MISSILE DEFENSE PLAN 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By GREG McDONALD 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The White House agreed to a bipartisan compromise
plan Tuesday that would allow the development of a limited
missile-defense system if it does not conflict with efforts with
Russia to reduce nuclear weapons.
</P>
<P>
   The decision by the White House to embrace a compromise bill
offered by Senate Democrats and Republicans all but assured passage
in the Senate on Wednesday of a bill calling for the deployment of
a ballistic missile-defense system ``as soon as is technologically
possible.''
</P>
<P>
   The House was expected to take up a similar measure later this
week.
</P>
<P>
   The White House decision to back the development of what would
amount to a scaled-back version of the old ``Star Wars'' missile
defense plan, which followed years of opposition from Clinton. He
repeatedly had threatened to veto such a plan out of concern that
it would amount to a violation of the Anti-Ballistic Missile Treaty
with Moscow and cost too much to actually build.
</P>
<P>
   But an amendment adopted Tuesday by the Senate on a vote of 99-0
specifically tied development of the system to continued arms
reduction efforts with Russia and set no specific funding levels
for the project. The appropriations figures will be determined
later in the year if both the House and the Senate agree to move
ahead with development.
</P>
<P>
   The language also leaves the final decision on deployment up to
the president.
</P>
<P>
   The decision to reverse what amounts to a long-standing Clinton
administration policy followed on the heels of successful ballistic
missile tests in North Korea and Iran, and reports that China has
obtained U.S. technology that could help Beijing build more
accurate nuclear weapons.
</P>
<P>
   Those disclosures caused some Democrats to re-examine their
opposition to a missile-defense system. But they continued to
insist that their support does not extend to an expensive
``umbrella-like'' missile defense plan that was the focus of the
``Star Wars'' debate during Ronald Reagan's presidency.
</P>
<P>
   Democratic Sens. Mary Landrieu of Louisiana and Carl Levin of
Michigan, who joined with several Republicans to fashion compromise
language, said the bill the Senate will vote on Wednesday
recognized ``the threat'' of a missile attack from a rogue nation
is more real than ever before.''
</P>
<P>
   The bill will provide guidance for later appropriations and
development authorization. It contains no schedule.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Thad Cochran, R-Miss., chief author of the missile defense
bill, said the language tying deployment to offensive reductions is
a good idea.
</P>
<P>
   ``It strengthens the bill,'' he said, noting that ``defenses and
offensive reductions are not incompatible.''
</P>
<P>
   The White House embraced language in the bill that does not set
out specific funding for the project. Under a provision offered by
Cochran and Sen. Bob Kerry, D-Neb., appropriations for the project
will be determined year-by-year through normal budget channels in
Congress.
</P>
<P>
   As the Senate took up the missile defense bill Tuesday, Senate
Republicans were quick to draw attention to the latest reports that
China may have used U.S. technology pilfered from the government's
Los Alamos facility in New Mexico to enhance its missile guidance
and delivery systems.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today, the People's Republic of China has more than a dozen
missiles aimed at American cities,'' Senate Majority Leader Trent
Lott, R-Miss., said as the Senate began debate.
</P>
<P>
   He added that the lack of a national missile-defense system was
the ``Achilles' heel'' of the nation, leaving it vulnerable to
attack.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
