<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-16 19:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2800 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TECH-CONFERENCE-COX     03-16 0627
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECH-CONFERENCE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Advice offered on how to seek capital
 &HT;    By Mark Clothier
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ If everyone indeed has 15 minutes of fame,
entrepreneurs want theirs at venture capital forums, the singles
dance of financing. There, a handful of companies looking for money
pitch to crowds of investors looking to grow their money.
</P>
<P>
   How that 15-minute presentation is made varies according to
who's making it. Some hug the lectern and read slides; others prowl
the stage as if they prepped by watching late-night infomercials.
</P>
<P>
   Monday morning, Beverly McDonald, a partner with SocketPR, a
public relations firm, talked to about 30 people about how to
fine-tune that pitch.
</P>
<P>
   Some of them would be in the spotlight Tuesday pitching to this
week's Red Herring venture capital forum held at the same hotel.
</P>
<P>
   Others hope for a chance to pitch their companies next year.
They were a hungry and motivated audience.
</P>
<P>
   McDonald said the important part of the presentation is what is
said, not how it's said: content over technique.
</P>
<P>
   The goal, she said, is to sufficiently intrigue the money people
so they will talk to you afterward. The 15-minute presentation is
the first contact. If it goes well, it can lead to follow-up talks,
due diligence and ultimately, checks cut.
</P>
<P>
   If you have the choice between a good public speaker or a
passionate technology person, McDonald advised letting the best
public speaker make the pitch.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a lot of noise,'' McDonald said. ``We're looking for
ways to break through the noise.''
</P>
<P>
   To help, McDonald offered these tips for would-be presenters:
</P>
<P>
   _ Assume most in your audience are financial people, venture
capitalists or other types of investors. You don't want to clutter
your talk with too many details about money, but the venture
capitalists will look for some. A basic rule: If the numbers look
good, use them. If they don't, don't.
</P>
<P>
   _ Keep in mind the technology actually gets the least attention.
Most of the focus will be on your ability to get the product ready
for the market.
</P>
<P>
   _ Don't hide behind the lectern. At this point, you're selling
yourself. Get out from behind the lectern and let people see who
you are. Don't use slides as a crutch, and don't use slides riddled
with bullets.
</P>
<P>
   _ Bring a sample agenda that identifies the problem, tells what
your product is and tells how it solves the problem. What chance
does it have to grab a chunk of the market? Point out what makes
you different and say it simply. Don't demonstrate the product. If
you must, show one or two things that separate you from the
competition.
</P>
<P>
   _ Speak from your heart. You're putting everything on the line _
your home mortgage, your kid's college tuition. Tell the story of
how you developed the product. If you woke up in the middle of the
night and just had to get it on paper, say that. Let the audience
see your passion for your product and your company.
</P>
<P>
   _ Mention money and pricing model, even if you don't have one
yet. If you ignore it, the money people assume you don't realize
its importance. It's not just about your product, but how you're
going to get it to market and how you're going to service it. At
this point, the product is the least important thing.
</P>
<P>
   _ Finish early: It saves time to answer questions, get cards and
meet people. Take 10 or 12 minutes out of 15. For the most part,
you're looking for people in the audience who might not have that
day's schedule filled up. They will decide if they want to meet
with you in the first five minutes of your talk.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Clothier writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
