<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CNS-ORGAN-TRANSPLANTS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STILL ON THE LIFE-OR-DEATH WAITING LIST 
</HEADLINE>
   For use by New York Times Syndicate/News Service clients as
desired.  
 By ADAM KRAMER  
 c.1999Columbia News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Every day Michael Liebert lives with uncertainty. He
has been on the waiting list for liver and kidney transplants for
more than two years.
</P>
<P>
   As he waits, his body is slowly deteriorating. His eyes seem to
be sinking into their sockets and his skin is yellow from jaundice,
a symptom of liver failure.
</P>
<P>
   ``I handled the 15 years of dialysis well,'' said Liebert, 55,
who is president of his temple and working on procuring financing
for a Broadway musical. But now, a vein keeps narrowing near his
elbow and above the shoulder, causing excruciating pain.
</P>
<P>
   The fate of the New York City man, like that of 50,000 other
Americans awaiting organ transplants, may hinge on a new federal
policy that would change the way organs are allocated. Right now,
organs are distributed regionally _ meaning that a heart from a
donor in, say, New Jersey, would go to someone in that state even
if there were a patient in New York who needed it more.
</P>
<P>
   The result is a large disparity in waiting times between
regions, since some areas have fewer donors than others. According
to a government report released last month, patients in New York
City waited nearly 10 times as long for transplants as similar
patients just across the river in New Jersey - 511 days compared to
56.
</P>
<P>
   New federal regulations that were passed in April 1998 would
have corrected that by giving the sickest patients priority, no
matter where they live. But after public uproar, congressional
leaders and the Clinton administration agreed to a one-year
moratorium on implementing the new rules. By Oct. 21, 1999, the
Organ Procurement and Transplantation Network must present a new
policy for organ allocation to Health and Hospital Services, which
will go into effect 90 days later for livers, and one year later
for all other organs.
</P>
<P>
   ``The new allocation system will operate more fairly to reduce
the disparity and waiting times,'' said Charlotte Mehuron, director
of communications, Health Resources and Services Administration.
``It is a system based on a medical rationale and sound medical
judgement, not artificial geographic boundaries.''
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone agrees. The United Network for Organ Sharing, a
private non-profit group, has maintained the transplant waiting
list since Sept. 30, 1986; officials there say it works well.
``There is one waiting list,'' said spokeswoman Esther Benenson.
``First the transplant doctor looks locally for the organ, then if
there is not an organ, there is a regional search and then a
national one.''
</P>
<P>
   According to UNOS, the problem with the new government policy is
that some transplant centers take much sicker patients than others,
and some have many more patients. This would mean that they would
get the majority of organs, which in turn could force the closure
of smaller transplant centers. And if a patient does not live close
enough to a transplant center, they would have to move, causing
emotional and financial stress.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, some experts have argued that the sickest patients
are not always the best candidates for organ transplant because
they do not always have the strength to pull through the surgery _
meaning that the organ, which could have been used to someone with
a better prognosis, would be lost. According to an UNOS study, a
national list would cause 600 to 700 more people to die every year
than under the present system.
</P>
<P>
   The arguments on the allocation of organs would be moot if there
were enough organs for the people who need them. According to UNOS,
there were 50,047 people on the organ transplant waiting list last
year and 20,360 transplants were performed, while 3,916 people died
waiting. An estimated 12 people die every day while waiting for a
transplant, while every 16 minutes another name is added to the
waiting list, according to the non-profit Coalition on Donation.
</P>
<P>
   Liebert's problems started at birth, when a genetic disease that
destroyed his kidneys was diagnosed. Through 15 years of dialysis
and blood transfusions, he contracted hepatitis, which caused
cirrhosis of the liver. Organ transplants are his only option. But
until recently, no hospital would even consider a kidney transplant
on a patient with hepatitis B because of the potential side effects
_ liver cancer and the flaring up of the hepatitis. Therefore, he
has to spend three and one-half hours, three days a week, at the
hospital on a dialysis machine. He also has to go to physical
therapy three days a week in order to lead a somewhat normal life.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am a miracle of modern medicine,'' Liebert said. ``I have
real bad plumbing inside, and doctors said I wouldn't see my second
birthday.''
</P>
<P>
   The reasons for the lack of organ donations are threefold. Some
families hesitate for religious reasons _ even though most
religions allow for organ donation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are all for it,'' said the Rev. Brian McSweeney of the
Archdiocese of New York.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, many people believe that if they agree to donate a
loved one's organs, hospital officials will let that person die
instead of doing everything possible to save him _ which,
transplant officials insist, is not the case.
</P>
<P>
   ``They need to understand that everything will be done to keep
them alive,'' said Marilyn Winn, director of programs for the
National Kidney Foundation of Indiana chapter.
</P>
<P>
   The third reason for lack of organ donors is a bit of a
Catch-22. A person who signs an organ donor card does not get final
say on what happens to their organs. A hospital will not take the
organs even if there is a donor card, unless family members agree.
</P>
<P>
   ``For liability purposes a hospital needs to have the next of
kin sign off on a donation,'' said Maria Falcon, of the National
Kidney Foundation of New York. ``People need to have a witness when
signing an organ donor card, and say these are my wishes once I
die.''
</P>
<P>
   Added Mehuron, ``It is very heartfelt when people say, 'It was
comforting to know that their loved one continued on helping
another person to lead a productive life.'''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (EDITORS: Adam Kramer is a master's degree candidate at the
Graduate School of Journalism at Columbia University. There is no
charge for use of this story, but please send a tearsheet to Prof.
Wayne Svoboda, Columbia News Service, Graduate School of
Journalism, Columbia University, 2950 Broadway, New York, N.Y.
10027) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
