<HEADER>
A2803 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CNS-NEW-ITALIAN-THEAT     03-16 1139
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CNS-NEW-ITALIAN-THEATER </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN APPETITE FOR ITALIAN CULTURE 
</HEADLINE>
   For use by New York Times Syndicate/News Service clients as
desired.  
 By JEANINE PREZIOSO  
 c. 1999 Columbia News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Vitttorio Capotorto, a burly man with thick gray
hair, blue eyes and a Roman nose could be mistaken for an ancestor
of the Austrian Habsburg Dynasty that occupied 18th-century
northern Italy. But he is from Puglia, a region in the South, a
fact he hesitates to admit. While few contest the warmth and
natural beauty of Sicily, many northern Italians, and Americans,
believe southern Italy has no culture.
</P>
<P>
   And in America, Italian culture has been far too often
associated with ignorance and buffoonery, not to mention myriad
``Godfather'' imitations; a fact not lost on Capotorto. He blames
an initially poor, strictly blue-collar work ethic for a
malnourished Italian-American culture. He wants to fill the void
with his vision of theater.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem is Italian-Americans wanted to learn English,
work, establish themselves in society,'' Capotorto said. ``This
killed the other parts of the men and women.''
</P>
<P>
   Now he has plans for a multifaceted arts center. Capotorto, who
began putting on plays in Italian with Columbia University students
in 1997, now has a company of almost 13 working actors. But his
creative vision lacks a home. The performances are usually held in
high school theaters. The group, through the Department of Citywide
Administrative Services, is looking for its own space in midtown
Manhattan. Capotorto envisions a building large enough to house two
theaters, one for dance and theatrical performances, and the other
for film. He also envisions a cultural library, cafeteria,
conference room and exhibition space for art.
</P>
<P>
   Tucked away in a small office at the top of an old brownstone on
Restaurant Row in the theater district, is the home of La Bottega
Dell'Arte, the seed of what could become the Lincoln Center of
Italian performing arts in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Capotorto founded the company in 1997 as a theater experiment at
Columbia University. The 57-year-old Italian director, who speaks
little English, went to the Italian Department's acting chairwoman,
JoAnn Cavallo, and proposed establishing a theater group. She not
only agreed to his proposal but also asked him to teach a
three-credit course called the Italian theater practicum.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to do contemporary plays from southern authors,''
Capotorto said. ``Not that we want to ignore Machiavelli and
Pirandello.''
</P>
<P>
   A chance encounter brought Capotorto together with Vittorio
Lattanzi, a successful restaurateur. Capotorto invited Lattanzi to
his production of ``Le Bugie con le Gambe Lunghe,'' or
``Long-Legged Lies,'' by Eduardo De Filippo, playwright of things
Neapolitan, at Columbia's Casa Italiana, on Dec. 3, 1997. Impressed
with the turnout and with what he saw, and homesick for his own
culture, he offered to produce Capotorto's endeavors.
</P>
<P>
   ``I figured since he had such success with student actors, we
could do much better with real actors,'' said Lattanzi, 57, who
serves as the company's president.
</P>
<P>
   In May 1998, the company performed ``Long-Legged Lies'' again,
as the newly formed La Bottega Dell'Arte. In November, the company
put on three one-act plays by Italian playwrights. In December, a
production of Machiavelli's ``Mandragola'' followed a performance
of music, including a repertory of operettas, original dance and
theater.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no real center for the Italian performing arts in New
York, no real outlet,'' said Francesca Pennisi, 31, a coordinator
at La Bottega who recently got her Ph.D. from Yale University in
Italian language and literature. ``There's more an awareness of
cuisine and language. We want to expand people's vision.''
</P>
<P>
   Fred Gardaphe, professor of Italian studies at the State
University of New York at Stony Brook, said the theater had a
timely message. People are tired of the stereotypes and long for a
deeper understanding of Italian culture, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Italians are very good at repressing themselves,'' he said.
``If this theater allows the true Italian subconscious to come
through, it will succeed. If it does not just make people laugh,
but makes them think, it will succeed.''
</P>
<P>
   The next play will be ``Sabbia'' or ``Sand'' based on the life
of Nicolo van Westerhout, a turn-of-the-century Dutch composer who
was born and reared in Mola di Bari, Puglia, Capotorto's hometown.
Paolo Tartamella wrote the play; he is an Italian journalist who
works for America Oggi, the Italian daily newspaper. They are
scheduled to perform it in March at Brooklyn's New Utrecht High
School theater.
</P>
<P>
   While the creative side of the company is flourishing, the
administrative is less well-organized. La Bottega is searching for
an executive director and more money. The money they expected from
a fund-raiser held last December did not pan out.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our budget barely covers the cost of the shows,'' Pennisi
said. ``We need to organize from within. We need a viable business
plan before reaching out for fund-raising.''
</P>
<P>
   Marco Greco, 32, co-founder of the Belmont Italian-American
Playhouse, a small Bronx-based theater company, understands the
problems. He started his theater eight years ago and went out on
his own this year, after writing and performing a one-man play. The
success rate of starting a small theater company in New York is
about the same as the chances of opening a successful new
restaurant. Behind the scene seems to matter most, Greco said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not to knock the creativity, but you need some semblance of
administration,'' he said. ``I always tell anyone who's thinking of
starting a theater, whatever money you have in the bank, pay the
administrator. People want to receive a thank you note for the
money they donate. There has to be a genuine accountability for the
donations.''
</P>
<P>
   But Capotorto is focused on his mission. ``When Italian
immigrants came to the United States they were more concerned with
working to keep themselves alive.
</P>
<P>
   ``The mentality was one derived from the fear of starvation,''
he said. ``If there's one piece of bread, we don't think to split
it. I think, instead to take it all for myself. What became a
greediness of material desires manifested itself over the years
into an intellectual greediness. We must unite now.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (EDITORS: Jeanine Prezioso is a master's degree candidate at
the Graduate School of Journalism at Columbia University. There is
no charge for use of this story, but please send a tearsheet to
Prof. Wayne Svoboda, Columbia News Service, Graduate School of
Journalism, Columbia University, 2950 Broadway, New York, N.Y.
10027) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
