<HEADER>
A2804 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CNS-SURVEILLANCE &LR;      03-16 0911
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CNS-SURVEILLANCE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRIVACY, NEW YORK STYLE 
</HEADLINE>
   For use by New York Times Syndicate/News Service clients as
desired.  
 By ROSS FINLEY  
 c.1999 Columbia News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ If you live or work in Manhattan, you walk through
their line of vision every day. And even your most private actions
may not escape the thousands of silent observers that keep an eye
on you.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, the number of surveillance cameras in Manhattan
has increased dramatically, and New Yorkers appear to have scant
awareness of their presence. Places that used to seem like private
settings _ elevators, empty street corners or quiet parks _ have
become public thanks to monitoring by cameras.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's definitely been a major, major proliferation of video
cameras in the last five years,'' said Dov Hykind, a Republican New
York State Assemblyman who wants to open public hearings on the
issue of video surveillance.
</P>
<P>
   Although police officials insist the cameras help to fight
crime, Hykind and other critics raise questions on whether that
need outweighs the intrusion into the activities of unsuspecting
citizens. ``I think we need to take a much closer look at things,
and not wake up one morning and find out that wherever we walk,
wherever we stand, wherever we sit out there in the public there is
a camera trained on us,'' Hykind said.
</P>
<P>
   The New York Civil Liberties Union recently counted 2,397
cameras in Manhattan, with the greatest concentration in the
financial and theater districts.
</P>
<P>
   NYCLU volunteer Chris Johnson said that the goal was ``not a
matter of saying that it's right or it's wrong, but that some
discussion should take place.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year the NYCLU criticized New York police for installing
video cameras in Washington Square Park, which police said was a
strategy to curb the park's rampant drug dealing. Police say the
strategy has worked, and the cameras are still in place.
</P>
<P>
   The NYCLU, however, contends the cameras are an example of
unnecessary police encroachment on the lives of innocent people as
well.
</P>
<P>
   Surveillance cameras go unnoticed in many parts of the city.
Shoppers emerging on a recent day from the busy 7th Avenue and 34th
Street subway station just outside Macy's department store
expressed surprise that they were being observed by two cameras
visible one floor above them.
</P>
<P>
   When the camera was pointed out to him, passer-by Pierre
Elliott, 27, looked up and said: ``These are the slow beginnings of
a dictatorship. In five more years, they're going to be
everywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   Already, housing projects across the city are filled with police
cameras.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, we have about 500 cameras deployed'' in housing
projects, said Joseph Dunne, Chief of the NYPD's Housing Division.
He added that installation had begun on another 800.
</P>
<P>
   The cameras have been effective in preventing crime, he said,
and for aiding investigations. In the first seven months after
cameras were installed in Brooklyn's Albany projects, there were 12
arrests stemming from camera footage, he asserted. In Harlem's
Grant projects, crime has dropped 25 percent in the two years since
cameras began recording crack use, violent assaults, robbery and
vandalism.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think that this technology goes a long way to making public
housing what it was always intended to be,'' Dunne said, ``safe and
cheap housing for people who need a little help.''
</P>
<P>
   But in the workplace, fears that unsuspecting employees are
being videotaped using office bathrooms, or that street cameras may
tilt to see into apartment buildings have fueled criticism from
advocates for personal privacy.
</P>
<P>
   Doug Hill, President of FirstWatch, an Ottawa-based surveillance
firm, said that in his experience, court cases have determined that
in public places, people have little right to privacy. ``If you're
in public, you're fair game,'' he said. ``That even goes for public
washrooms.''
</P>
<P>
   Civil liberties aside, there is also the question of cost. Mark
Ventura, a security consultant, said that one camera typically runs
around $10,000, with installation.
</P>
<P>
   That would put city costs for watching millions of Manhattanites
at a minimum of $4 million if the NYCLU count is correct.
</P>
<P>
   Without confirming the figure, Dunne said, It is all ``money
well spent,'' and inevitable, Dunne said. ``We're lagging behind
many, many other municipalities and governments.''
</P>
<P>
   New York City is not the first place to embrace surveillance
cameras as a crime deterrent. Municipal governments in Britain,
like the town of Newcastle, have been monitoring city streets since
1992.
</P>
<P>
   But Hykind, a well-known conservative in the Assembly, is not
convinced that video surveillance should be so far-reaching. The
need for debate, he said, is demonstrated by his sharing a platform
with a group that he rarely aligns with on issues, the NYCLU.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the two of us _ us doing something together _ will
speak volumes of the fact that all of us should be concerned,''
Hykind said.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (EDITORS: Ross Finley is a master's degree candidate at the
Graduate School of Journalism at Columbia University. There is no
charge for use of this story, but please send a tearsheet to Prof.
Wayne Svoboda, Columbia News Service, Graduate School of
Journalism, Columbia University, 2950 Broadway, New York, N.Y.
10027) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
