<DOCNO> NYT19990316.0255 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-16 19:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2805 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CNS-LLAMAS &LR;      03-16 1111
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CNS-LLAMAS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR THE LOVE OF LLAMAS: BREEDING GROWS IN U.S. 
</HEADLINE>
   For use by New York Times Syndicate/News Service clients as
desired.  
 By AMY L. ANDERSON  
 c. 1999 Columbia News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ For Dana McCullough, it was something about
the calm, dewy-eyed gaze. ``The way they look at you,'' she said,
recalling her first encounter with a llama. ``They just fascinated
me.''
</P>
<P>
   McCullough, who now keeps a herd of 20 on her ranch in Elk City,
Okla., started out 11 years ago as an enthusiast with four llamas,
but quickly became an addict. ``They're like potato chips,'' she
said. ``You can't have just one or two.''
</P>
<P>
   Backstage at the Southwestern Llama Show here, McCullough runs
an industrial-size blow dryer over Kristi, a squirming,
chestnut-colored two-year-old. ``They're so observant,'' she said.
And curious. ``If I put something in the middle of the pasture,
they have to go check it right out.''
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone, she realizes, understands her hobby. ``Mostly
people ask: 'What do you do with llamas? What are llamas good for?'
'' One man, she said, wanted to know a bit more: ``How big are the
eggs they lay?'' McCullough shook her head. ``I guess he was
thinking they're ostriches.''
</P>
<P>
   Llama breeding is a growing industry in the United States. The
International Lama[cq] Registry, which tracks the animals'
pedigrees, listed more than 120,000 llamas in the United States at
the end of 1998, compared with approximately 40,000 in 1991. With
92 exhibitors from 25 states showing more than 400 llamas, the Fort
Worth show, which includes an auction, is the largest in the
country strictly for llamas, said the show's organizer, Carol Ann
Tallmon. Two larger shows also include alpacas, a smaller, slightly
woollier cousin of the llama.
</P>
<P>
   One of the oldest domesticated animals in the world, llamas can
be bred for their wool or as pack animals, and a bred female can
sell for $3,500 or more. Stud-quality males sell for $1,500 and up
and command anywhere from $100 to $5,000 in stud fees, said the
trade group's registrar, Jan Wassink. Still, many owners think of
their llamas more as pets, or even family members, than as
livestock. Whether it is the big, expressive eyes, the lush fur, or
the quirky, inquisitive personalities, owners display an attachment
toward their llamas that, to the uninitiated, might seem to border
on the obsessive.
</P>
<P>
   ``They kind of get to be like children,'' said Jerry Mitchell,
who has brought llamas to Fort Worth from Tuttle, Okla., for four
years. Mitchell, who started out five years ago with two llamas,
now has a herd of 30, but he cannot bring himself to sell any of
his animals just yet. ``I'd probably give her up before I'd give up
a llama,'' he joked, gesturing toward his adult daughter, who is
busy tending her own llamas.
</P>
<P>
   Back in the arena, a costume contest was under way. A llama in a
plastic cap peered through a shower curtain at the competition: a
turkey and a cowboy. Nearby, a medieval damsel was unwinding after
her turn in the ring. The next day's events were the halter
classes, where llamas were judged on their wool and their build
rather than their fashion sense.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the action, though, was back by the stalls, where llamas
pad behind their owners on rope leashes or stand with varying
degrees of patience as they were blow dried, combed and spritzed
with conditioner to make their fur soft and shiny.
</P>
<P>
   It takes two days to wash a llama, said Walter Cardenas, the
manager of American Llama Farm in Fort Worth. To thoroughly wet a
llama requires two painstaking hours of parting layers of wool with
one hand while working a hose with the other. Washing requires
about a half-gallon of shampoo _ Cardenas, like many breeders,
favors Suave because it's inexpensive _ and drying takes 24 hours,
including four hours of blow drying one morning and four the next
day, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Llamas may not enjoy baths, but Nell Graham, the owner of
Graham's Llamas, in Denison, Texas, said that her llamas
appreciated the grooming. ``They prance'' after being washed, she
said. Graham watched one of her llamas, Mistletoe, navigate an
obstacle course designed to simulate situations that a llama might
encounter on a trail. She smiled indulgently as Mistletoe, led by a
teen-age assistant, systematically refused to mount ramps, walk on
planks or back through an arrangement of poles. ``She says, 'I may
not do anything, but I look pretty,''' Graham concluded.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't imagine life without llamas,'' said Graham, who fell
in love with the animals at a petting farm in 1974. ``It keeps you
busy, and so many of my friends are llama friends.'' Llama rearing
is a full time job for her, but she scoffs at the idea of making
money at it. Shows, which have netted her a case full of ribbons
and llama-shaped trophies, are as much a social event as an
opportunity to promote her herd. ``I'm in it mostly for
enjoyment,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Even Hollywood may have discovered the animals' appeal: Disney
has announced plans for an animated film starring a llama. If some
owners are excited by the prospect, Mike Summers of Austin, Texas,
has reservations about the publicity. After the Disney movie ``101
Dalmatians,'' many families bought the dogs, only to give them away
after finding them too difficult to care for.
</P>
<P>
   ``I already have a Dalmatian that I got from the pound,'' he
said. ``My concern is the same thing might happen with llamas.''
</P>
<P>
   Llamas do at least have the advantage of being easy to get along
with. Like many owners, Summers regularly takes his llamas to
schools and nursing homes, where the animals demonstrate particular
solicitude for the elderly. ``Some of 'em almost get into bed with
them,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In the area set aside for llamas to be sold in the afternoon
auction, Monte and Leslie Dickman from Thedford, Neb., had two
llamas ready to greet prospective bidders. ``What always excites me
is a new buyer, '' Mrs. Dickman said. ``There's something about
being a new llama owner and experiencing the joy they give you.''
And, she added, ``llama people tend to be a really neat group of
people.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Dickman paused to look over her charges. ``How can we live
without llamas?''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (EDITORS: Amy L. Anderson is a master's degree candidate at the
Graduate School of Journalism at Columbia University. There is no
charge for use of this story, but please send a tearsheet to Prof.
Wayne Svoboda, Columbia News Service, Graduate School of
Journalism, Columbia University, 2950 Broadway, New York, N.Y.
10027) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
