<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-16 19:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2806 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CNS-NAIL-ART &LR;      03-16 1059
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CNS-NAIL-ART </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NAILED: MINI-MASTERPIECES AT THE TIPS OF WOMEN'S FINGERS 
</HEADLINE>
   For use by New York Times Syndicate/News Service clients as
desired.  
 By GEORGINA GUSTIN  
 c. 1999 Columbia News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Some people would call them the 10 greatest
masterpieces in New York's Metropolitan Museum of Art. They are
only about two and a half inches long, don't hang on the wall or
stand on pedestals, and are not rendered in marble or painted on
canvas. Their asking price is a modest $18 to $25.
</P>
<P>
   These works of art are on the tips of 20-year-old Desiree
Henry's fingers.
</P>
<P>
   Henry is a salesperson in the museum's gift shop and every two
weeks she goes to a salon in her native Brooklyn where she spends
up to two hours as a ``technician'' files, molds, paints and
stencils elaborate designs on her acrylic-reinforced nails. This
week, her nails were white with pinkish highlights, a stenciled
purple geometric design and stripes of silver glitter, but after
Henry's next visit to the salon, her constantly shifting digital
exhibit would change again.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't compare my nails with the art in the museum,'' Henry
said, modestly. ``But some people say they should be on display.''
</P>
<P>
   Like thousands of women across the country, Henry puts a great
deal of time, effort and money into her nails. According to a study
done by Nails Magazine, the nail industry's largest trade
publication, almost $6.3 billion was spent on services in nail
salons last year. And of the estimated 250,000 salons in the
country, 85 percent create what is known in the industry as ``nail
art'' for their clients.
</P>
<P>
   ``Technicians have been doing nail art for the last 20 to 25
years,'' said Cyndy Drummey, publisher of Nails magazine. ``But in
the last five or six years, we've really seen a boom.'' Drummey
believes this boom is the result of advances in nail art
technology. ``Once the nails got longer with acrylics in the last
20 years, and the colors got wilder, it gave rise to all the
possibilities with nail art.''
</P>
<P>
   Nail art, painstakingly rendered on the tiniest of canvasses,
can range from the relatively sedate to the stunningly bold. And
Drummey has witnessed the often-spectacular results at hundreds of
nail ``competitions'' held throughout the country where nail
technicians, most of them self-taught, have taken the developments
in the industry to new heights.
</P>
<P>
   ``You name it,'' Drummey said. ``I've seen entire jungle scenes
with animals and smoke, and a carousel with moving parts. You have
to see it to believe it.''
</P>
<P>
   Drummey explained the categories in which nail art competitors
are judged. ``At these competitions there is nail art and fantasy
nail art,'' she said. ``Nail art is done on the surface of the
nail,'' while fantasy nail art ``is literally bulding off that
platform.''
</P>
<P>
   Fantasy nail art, in which technicians use acrylic and
fiberglass to sculpt figures and shapes, yields some impressive,
even architectural results, but is not a practical adornment.
People whose nails receive fantasy treatment _ models on the
competitive circuit _ need help with everyday tasks like going to
the ladies room.
</P>
<P>
   Chesley Phillips, president of Nails of America, an 1,800-member
group that works to establish standards for the industry, attends
30 nail competitions a year. Phillips said some industry
professionals went from competition to competition trying to rack
up points for Nails magazine's ``Top 25'' nail technicians list.
``They travel around the country campaigning,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Nanda Khin, a 33-year-old salon owner from Windsor, Ontario,
Canada, has been one of the most consistent competitors on the nail
art circuit and often ends up on the Top 25 list. Windsor is a town
of 200,000 people about half an hour's drive from Detroit, the city
that Cyndy Drummey calls the nail art capital of the world. (Khin
insists that Windsor is in fact the true nail art capital. ``People
know you're if you're from Windsor,'' she said. ``They can tell by
your nails.'')
</P>
<P>
   But while Windsor may well be a paradise of nail art, there are
others. (The borough of Brooklyn is home to hundreds of nail-art
salons including Hope Nails, Happy Nails and Love Nail, as well as
the more ominously named Nail Attitude and Nail Trap.) And Khin is
easily lured across the border to nail competitions in the United
States, some of which are held thousands of miles away from her
home.
</P>
<P>
   The designs in Khin's nail art oeuvre range from tropical
landscapes to safari-inspired wildlife, but Khin attributes her
success on the nail-art circuit to her meticulous technique. ``I
like to be really, really neat,'' she said of her work. ``I look at
the nails I've done, and I know they're mine.''
</P>
<P>
   Nail art is also a point of personal pride for Desiree Henry,
who makes certain sacrifices not only to have her nails artfully
painted, but to live with such long nails. ``They sometimes get
caught in the register,'' she said. ``And sometimes I can't pick up
coins off the counter or the floor.'' And once, Henry said, she
slammed her front door on one of her nails and broke it.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you like them long, you adjust your lifestyle,'' Drummey
said. ``There are creative ways to avoid breaking them.'' (Some
methods include dialing the phone with the end of a pencil or using
devices specially designed to open cans or fasten buttons.) ``You
learn to do things with your knuckles,'' Drummey said.
</P>
<P>
   Monique Lowerey, another salesperson at the museum, insisted
that her two-inch nails, which she changes depending on her outfit
or mood, rarely interfere with her lifestyle. ``I don't know why
people say, 'How can you do things?''' she said. ``For me it's not
hard. It's nothing. I don't think it's a big deal.''
</P>
<P>
   But despite her lackadaisical attitude, Lowerey echoed a
sentiment felt by all nail art aficionados: Breaking a masterpiece
will really ruin your day.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (EDITORS: Georgina Gustin is a master's degree candidate at the
Graduate School of Journalism at Columbia University. There is no
charge for use of this story, but please send a tearsheet to Prof.
Wayne Svoboda, Columbia News Service, Graduate School of
Journalism, Columbia University, 2950 Broadway, New York, N.Y.
10027) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
