   The gym walls were painted orange, yellow, blue and covered with
murals painted by neighborhood kids, adding some warmth to its cold
feeling. Above the exit was a Police Athletic League sign, which
said, ``In some neighborhoods, kids have no PAL's except us.''
</P>
<P>
   Every January for the past 72 years, amateur boxers have
converged in gyms like this across the country with a single motive
_ to fight their way to stardom. A victory at one of the Golden
Gloves Tournaments qualifies a fighter for the nationals, and then,
with a bit of luck, Olympic glory.
</P>
<P>
   The tournament, the brainchild of then-Chicago Tribune sports
editor Arch Ward, who designed the amateur tournament to help youth
and promote competition, blossomed under the sponsorship of the
Chicago Tribune and The New York Daily News. Today, a newspaper, a
radio or television station, or a civic organization sponsors the
regional Golden Gloves tournaments throughout the United States.
</P>
<P>
   It has also been said that the real reason for newspaper
sponsorship of the tournament was to give papers a way to fill up
the sports pages during the winter months, after the football
season and before the start of baseball's spring training. More
important, the Golden Gloves provided amateur boxers with a venue
to showcase their skills and gave them hope of using boxing as the
means to escape poverty.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every year sitting at ringside, I can tell where the new
immigrants are coming from, just from their accents,'' said Bill
Farrell, a New York Daily News staff writer who has covered the
Golden Gloves for the past 13 years. ``In the 80's, the fighters
were from the West Indies, but in the past five years they are from
Mexico, West Africa, Central America, and Central Europe.''
</P>
<P>
   The number of boxers fighting in the tournament continues to be
strong: 500 registered for the most recent New York City
tournament, which divides the fighters into two divisions. The
novice class is for the fighters who have never fought in
competition, and the open class is for those fighters who have had
previous ring experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``In some areas amateur boxing is picking up, and in others it
is declining,'' said Ray Rinaldi, boxing trainer and New York State
Golden Gloves delegate. ``But throughout the country, with the
Olympics coming in a year, the number of kids signing up to learn
how box is increasing.''
</P>
<P>
   One thing that never changes is the crowd. Fans have not lost
their energy or the thrill of watching the matches hosted in their
community. Where else could a true fan sit at ringside and watch 10
fights for $10?
</P>
<P>
   ``Two bucks, I won the last fight!'' said a middle-aged man
dressed in a T-shirt, jeans, suspenders and mud-encrusted boots,
who was betting on the matches with his friend.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got the guy wearing the blue this fight,'' he said to his
friend who was wearing a sweater and jeans, with hair the color of
a smoker's hands stained with tar and nicotine.
</P>
<P>
   One row up, Eric Kelly, winner of the 1998 New York Golden
Gloves, junior Olympic under-19 championship, and one of the top
fighters in the United States at 156 pounds, was watching the
fights. He would be defending his title later in the tournament,
but in the meantime was attending all of the fights with his
father.
</P>
<P>
   ``We lost another one,'' said Kelly, referring to a fight in
which another boxer from his Bedford-Stuyvesant boxing club had
been defeated. ``We're zero for five.''
</P>
<P>
   Kelly, 18, is a personable and cocky high school senior, who has
been fighting since he was 10. He spends two hours a day, five or
six days a week, in the gym, then goes home and does sit ups and
push-ups.
</P>
<P>
   ``All Eric does is study and box,'' said Harold Kelly, Eric's
father. ``He has been real disciplined since he was a baby; it is
not taught. He has been good all his life, and gets supported 100
percent by his mother.''
</P>
<P>
   Eric's goals are simple if lofty: win the Golden Gloves, the
Nationals, Olympics and then turn pro. He is not one of the boxers,
as he says, who wants to box but does not want to put in the work
it takes to become good.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, Eric are you going to win another one,'' said an older
gentleman, pointing to the gold boxing gloves that hang around
Eric's neck, while fans went crazy watching fighter John Vargas's
head snap back from a straight right by Anthony Armstead, causing a
sound that resonated throughout the gym.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am determined and I want it,'' said Eric Kelly, over the
noise.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eric is a star, an absolute star,'' Farrell said. ``There is
no limit to his potential.''
</P>
<P>
   At 10:10 p.m., the last fight on the card was over. It was not
the best fight of the night. But on a night of some very good
amateur matches, it was quickly forgotten, as the crowds filtered
out into the cold Bronx night air, heading for home.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (EDITORS: Adam Kramer is a master's degree candidate at the
Graduate School of Journalism at Columbia University. There is no
charge for use of this story, but please send a tearsheet to Prof.
Wayne Svoboda, Columbia News Service, Graduate School of
Journalism, Columbia University, 2950 Broadway, New York, N.Y.
10027) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
