<SLUG> BC-CNS-DOG-LAW </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ATTORNEY FOR THE DALMATIAN: LAW, ON FOUR LEGS 
</HEADLINE>
   For use by New York Times Syndicate/News Service clients as
desired.  
 BY ERIK LINDEN  
 c. 1999 Columbia News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Sue Schacter says the love of her husband's life was
not her, but their dog, Sonny. And when her husband passed away,
she was not about to give up their beloved 11-year-old poodle.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's one of a kind,'' Schacter said of Sonny. ``And now he's
vital to my well-being.''
</P>
<P>
   But Schacter's lease clearly states that pets are forbidden. Now
her landlord is trying to evict her, even though Sonny has a clean
record. So Schacter did what any good New Yorker in trouble would
do. She hired a lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   Enter Karen Copeland, determined and pugnacious pet lawyer. She
is mounting a strong defense of Sonny, who she says, in legal
terms, is an ``emotional support assistant animal'' and therefore
has squatting rights.
</P>
<P>
   Copeland is one of a growing number of lawyers who defend people
and their pets. Pet law is a subspecialty of animal law, and
although few lawyers can support a private practice on dogs and
cats alone, these feisty attorneys are passionate about defending
animals.
</P>
<P>
   While New York City is not exactly farm country, it is often
called a zoo. Three million cats and dogs live on top of 7.5
million people, according to the American Society for the
Prevention of Cruelty to Animals. And with that kind of crowding,
there are bound to be conflicts. A dozen animal lawyers have come
to the rescue.
</P>
<P>
   Many of Copeland's cases concern squabbles between landlords and
tenants. Tenants always have a good excuse about why they need to
keep their loved ones. Like the couple who say their dog calms
their two children who have attention deficit disorder. Or the
woman who claimed her dog helped her quit smoking. Or the man with
AIDS who says his loving Rottweiler helps him cope.
</P>
<P>
   Manhattan-based lawyer Maddy Tarnofsky has become involved with
medical malpractice _ the four-legged kind. Tarnofsky recently
represented a client whose 9-month-old puppy died in surgery. A
settlement was reached before the case went to trial.
</P>
<P>
   In eviction cases, Tarnofsky said, landlords fail to realize
that pets can be vital to a person's mental and physical health.
But judges and juries do.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to jinx it,'' said Tarnofsky, who has been
practicing law for eight years, ``but I haven't lost one of those
cases yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Many lawyers who deal with pet cases are diehard animal lovers.
Wally Dingman, a lawyer based in Riverside, Calif., said he
considered police dogs part of his family. Dingman trains German
shepherds for Adlerhorst Police K-9 Academy, and he defends the
shaggy accused. One recent case involved an officer who was bitten
by a dog during a training exercise. The officer sued the academy
for personal injury, and lost, thanks to Dingman's defense.
</P>
<P>
   Some lawyers take things to the extreme, and the line between
animal defense and animals-rights activism can be blurry.
</P>
<P>
   ``My wife knows that if I ever see anybody abusing a dog, I'm
liable to do something that would get me in trouble,'' said
Dingman, who is also an editor of Dog Sports magazine. ``I view
that as one animal abusing another.''
</P>
<P>
   Adds Steve Logan, a Fort Lauderdale, Fla.-based lawyer: ``I
don't think I'd ever take up a case defending someone who's abused
an animal.''
</P>
<P>
   Even the controversial pit bull is seen as a victim of bad
press. Joel Zand, a New York City lawyer who operates a Web site _
www.doglaw.com _ said some breeds were unfairly maligned. Quoting
Martin Luther King, Zand said pets should be judged on the
``content of their character,'' and not on their particular breed.
</P>
<P>
   Some defenders do not even like the word ``pet.'' Gilda Mariani,
who chairs the New York City Bar Association's committee on legal
issues pertaining to animals, said the word ``pets'' implies
ownership. Mariani prefers the more general term ``animals''
instead.
</P>
<P>
   ``We cringe at the term 'pets','' said Mariani, who likens the
plight of animals to a group of people whose voices are never
heard. ``Animals are a discriminated sector.'' Mariani added that
as pet lawyers multiply, ``more people are looking at what we do as
something serious.''
</P>
<P>
   Pet lawyers also find new homes for pets when their owners die.
Manhattan-based lawyer Frances Carlisle encourages people to look
for a charitable organization to care for stranded pets.
</P>
<P>
   She also encourages other lawyers to join the cause. At a recent
seminar at the Association of the Bar of the City of New York,
Carlisle urged lawyers to take animal pro-bono cases. As she put
it: ``Helping animals has to be your passion, not a way of making a
living.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (EDITORS: Erik Linden is a master's degree candidate at the
Graduate School of Journalism at Columbia University. There is no
charge for use of this story, but please send a tearsheet to Prof.
Wayne Svoboda, Columbia News Service, Graduate School of
Journalism, Columbia University, 2950 Broadway, New York, N.Y.
10027) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
