<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-16 19:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2810 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CNS-CAFE-PHILO &LR;      03-16 1208
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CNS-CAFE-PHILO </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COFFEE OR NIETZSCHE? CAFE-GOERS TURN TO PHILOSOPHY 
</HEADLINE>
   For use by New York Times Syndicate/News Service clients as
desired.  
 By VIOLET LAW  
 c. 1999 Columbia News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONTCLAIR, N.J. _ Clusters of gleaming white mugs sat on each
table at Page One Cafe, most drained of every drop. A few cradled
cold coffee left by cafe-goers, who had come not for cafe-latte but
for the weekly philosophical discussion. The ceiling lamps were
hanging low, and the faces of the 22 attendees were aglow with the
sparks of intellectual inquiry: What is pleasure?
</P>
<P>
   ``Pleasure is a survival mechanism,'' said Mike Mendlovitz, 40,
a pizza-deliveryman, jiggling his mountain-boot-shod feet as he
reflected on the suicide of a friend who had lost his sense of
pleasure in life. A moment earlier, Dan Brenahan, 60, a network
analyst clad in a business suit, had hypothesized that pleasure
could be simulated just as easily as he had once suppressed pain
when he was badly injured as a child.
</P>
<P>
   Welcome to the cafe-philo, or philosophy cafe, a lay person's
forum for philosophical discussion that has sprouted up across
America in the last two years Boulder, Colo.; Chicago; Dallas; Los
Angeles; Minneapolis; New York; Philadelphia; San Francisco and
Washington. In most places, the cafe-philo was founded by
individual philosophers _ academic or amateur _ inspired by Marc
Sautet, a late Nietzsche philosopher, who launched the first cafe
in France in 1992. Although some groups meet in restaurants, the
typical venue in the U.S. for the cafe-philo is, no surprise, a
cafe, in observance of the French practice.
</P>
<P>
   The cafe-philo in Montclair was formed in September 1996 by
Chris Phillips, a former philosophy teacher whose mission is to
bring philosophy to everyone, from high school students to prison
inmates.
</P>
<P>
   ``Philosophy for so many decades has been confined to the
academia,'' said Phillips, 39, who now lives in San Francisco and
is spreading the seeds there. He calls the cafe-philo ``a church
service for heretics,'' yet observes that ``people need philosophy
like they need air and food and water.'' The Montclair cafe has
been going strong even in his absence.
</P>
<P>
   At every gathering, a moderator, usually the cafe's founder,
begins by posing an open-ended question to the handful of regulars,
as well as passers-by. In trying to respond to the question, the
cafe participants take turns pouring out their thoughts, and
sometimes their innermost feelings. Most speakers draw from
personal examples to illustrate their arguments, and a few
occasionally paraphrase words of notable writers and philosophers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those who can bridge the gap between day-to-day life and
philosophical thoughts will enjoy the cafe-philo,'' said Peggy
Willens, 37, a management consultant who had attended a cafe-philo
in Minneapolis where the topic was ``What should you do if your
friend is engaged in activities that are just plain wrong?''
</P>
<P>
   On a Thursday night at Le Poeme, a candlelit bistro in
Manhattan, moderator Bernard Roy, 54, a native of France and a
Baruch College philosophy professor, perched on a high stool with
chin in hand and listened attentively as one middle-aged man used a
boy-gets-girl story to underscore the fine line between selfishness
and unselfishness. Others cited author Ayn Rand's theories on ``the
virtues of selfishness.'' Roy's smiling, sparkling big eyes, topped
by silvery eyebrows, manifested a grandpa's patience in the group's
discussion.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a starvation for intellectual activities,'' Roy said.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Aaron Edison, 33, a filmmaker, agreed. He happened to walk into
Le Poeme that night and enjoyed the cafe-philo so much that he said
he would start attending regularly.
</P>
<P>
   ``The public dialogue has descended quite a bit over the past
year,'' Edison said. ``Any effort to rekindle that interest is
great.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Even though cafes-philo may be a creation of the late 90's,
cultural critics believe the idea behind them is not new. Alan
Olson, a professor of religion and philosophy at Boston University
and executive director of the Twentieth Century World Congress of
Philosophy, points to the Beat Generation's coffeehouses and the
Great Books clubs of the 60's as the progenitors of cafes-philo.
All these cultural institutions were founded on the idea of
engaging the public in philosophical discourse, he said.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The cafe satisfies ``the longing for the feeling that we had: We
count,'' said Sam Cresbi, who came of age in the 60's. She attended
the cafe-philo in Washington a few years ago and, she said, ``it
knocked my socks off'' _ so much so that she is now running her own
in Shepherdstown, W. Va., where she currently lives.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   ``In this period of prosperity and relative peace,'' Olson
added, ``people have the luxury of thinking about themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   In the same vein, Roy sees the emergence of cafes-philo in the
United States and other parts of the world, including England,
Israel and Hong Kong, as a direct outcome of the movement by some
contemporary philosophers to popularize philosophy.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, there is something special about the 90's.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're immersed in a self-conscious era,'' said Robert
Thompson, a keen observer of popular culture and director of Center
for Study of Popular TV at Syracuse University. ``So much of the
American life is subject to hyper-analysis.'' Overwhelmed by an
avalanche of media attention, Americans today, Thompson said, are
more used to analyzing issues.
</P>
<P>
   However, Stephanie Roth-Nelson, 49, a Boulder, Colo.-based
technical writer and cafe-goer, laments, ``With friends and family,
the discussion seems superficial. Everybody is so caught up with
the mundane day-to-day life.''
</P>
<P>
   Therefore, the cafe-goers also come to search for something more
universal. Jeremy Iggers, 47, who holds a Ph.D. in philosophy and
started the cafe in Minneapolis, thinks most participants miss
``the connection to other people.''
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of it has to do with the anonymity of modern life,''
said Iggers, a reporter for the Minneapolis Star Tribune.
</P>
<P>
   That may be why Sat Bhattacharya, 28, keeps coming back, despite
his hectic schedule as a Ph.D. candidate and instructor at Cornell
Medical School.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is less a sense of community in America,'' said
Bhattacharya, a native of India. ``Americans are more like
individuals.'' An avid attendee since last November, two months
after Roy founded his cafe-philo in Manhattan, Bhattacharya enjoys
both the company and the conversation of the diverse group at Le
Poeme.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is the multitude of philosophies that makes life
interesting,'' Bhattacharya said.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (EDITORS: Violet Law is a master's degree candidate at the
Graduate School of Journalism at Columbia University. There is no
charge for use of this story, but please send a tearsheet to Prof.
Wayne Svoboda, Columbia News Service, Graduate School of
Journalism, Columbia University, 2950 Broadway, New York, N.Y.
10027) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
