<TEXT>
<P>
   Columbia News Service provides feature stories from the New York
City area every week for your use as desired. There is no cost to
you. CNS stories are transmitted every week courtesy of The New
York Times Syndicate/NYT News Service.
</P>
<P>
   The stories are slugged  &UR; BC-CNS-keyword &LR;  and move in the ``l''
news category.
</P>
<P>
   They are edited by adjunct professors who are working
journalists at The New York Times, Newsday, the Associated Press
and The Wall Street Journal. The stories are written by degree
candidates at the Graduate School of Journalism at Columbia
University. All we ask is that you send us a tearsheet.
</P>
<P>
   So please, if you can, use our stories. Most of them are news
features that can be held until you have a pesky hole to fill.
</P>
<P>
   To send us a clip:
</P>
<P>
   COLUMBIA NEWS SERVICE
</P>
<P>
   GRADUATE SCHOOL OF JOURNALISM
</P>
<P>
   COLUMBIA UNIVERSITY
</P>
<P>
   2950 BROADWAY
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK, NY 10027
</P>
<P>
   Many thanks,
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &UR; Professor Wayne Svoboda (212-854-3837) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Columbia News Service &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; e-mail ws52 &LR; columbia.edu &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; web site http://cns.jrn.columbia.edu/ &LR;  This week's stories:
</P>
<P>
   BODY IMAGE _ A New York City photographer has a radical reply to
women with body image problems. She began persuading women who
typically cringe at the sight of themselves in a mirror to confront
their demons head-on with nude photo sessions.
</P>
<P>
   BOOK LOVE _ Megabookstores have successfully turned a little
Camus, coffee and conversation into a low-key, literate dating
scene.
</P>
<P>
   CAFE-PHILO _ Welcome to the cafe-philo, or philosophy cafe, a
lay person's forum for philosophical discussion that has sprouted
up across America in the last two years Boulder, Colo.; Chicago;
Dallas; Los Angeles; Minneapolis; New York; Philadelphia; San
Francisco and Washington.
</P>
<P>
   DOG LAW _ A growing number of lawyers are defending people and
their pets. Pet law is a subspecialty of animal law, and although
few lawyers can support a private practice on dogs and cats alone,
these feisty attorneys are passionate about defending animals.
</P>
<P>
   LLAMAS _ Llama breeding is a growing industry in the United
States. The International Lama[cq] Registry, which tracks the
animals' pedigrees, listed more than 120,000 llamas in the United
States at the end of 1998, compared with approximately 40,000 in
1991.
</P>
<P>
   GOLDEN GLOVES _ Every January for the past 72 years, amateur
boxers have converged in gyms across the country with a single
motive _ to fight their way to stardom. A victory at one of the
Golden Gloves Tournaments qualifies a fighter for the nationals,
and then, with a bit of luck, Olympic glory.
</P>
<P>
   NAIL ART _ Some people would call them the 10 greatest
masterpieces in New York's Metropolitan Museum of Art. They are
only about two and a half inches long, don't hang on the wall or
stand on pedestals, and are not rendered in marble or painted on
canvas. Their asking price is a modest $18 to $25. These works of
art are on the tips of 20-year-old Desiree Henry's fingers.
</P>
<P>
   NEW ITALIAN THEATER _ In America, Italian culture has been far
too often associated with ignorance and buffoonery, not to mention
myriad ``Godfather'' imitations; a fact not lost on Vittorio
Capotorto. He blames a malnourished Italian-American culture on an
initially poor, strictly blue-collar work ethic. He wants to fill
the void with his vision of theater.
</P>
<P>
   ORGAN TRANSPLANTS _ The fate of the 50,000 Americans awaiting
organ transplants, may hinge on a new federal policy that would
change the way organs are allocated. Right now, organs are
distributed regionally _ meaning that a heart from a donor in, say,
New Jersey, would go to someone in that state even if there were a
patient in New York who needed it more. The result is a large
disparity in waiting times between regions, since some areas have
fewer donors than others. The new guidelines would change that, but
not everyone thinks that is a good idea.
</P>
<P>
   SURVEILLANCE _ In recent years, the number of surveillance
cameras in Manhattan has increased dramatically, and New Yorkers
appear to have scant awareness of their presence. Places that used
to seem like private settings _ elevators, empty street corners or
quiet parks _ have become public thanks to monitoring by cameras.
</P>
</TEXT>
