<SLUG> BC-CNS-BOOK-LOVE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LITERATE ROMANCE: GETTING HITCHED IN THE AISLES 
</HEADLINE>
   For use by New York Times Syndicate/News Service clients as
desired.  
 By ROSS FINLEY  
 c. 1999 Columbia News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Michele Savage thinks about her wedding day, the children's
book ``Miss Spider Gets Married'' comes to mind. Ann Rice's
``Memnoch the Devil'' also rings clear in her memory. Both were on
display near the makeshift altar in the Barnes &AMP; Noble bookstore in
Columbus, Ohio, where she and her beau, Steven, were married.
</P>
<P>
   And it was only fitting that the couple had their wedding in the
store. After all, that is where Steven proposed, dramatically
interrupting a meeting of Michele's romance book club to announce
that he wanted to marry her.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were married between mystery and gay studies, which was
oddly appropriate,'' Savage said. The best man was gay.
</P>
<P>
   The Savages' storybook wedding is the ultimate example of how
the megabookstores have successfully turned a little Camus, coffee
and conversation into a low-key, literate dating scene. Borders
Books &AMP; Music now solicits customers not only with comfortable
sofas and cappuccino, but encourages singles to socialize.
</P>
<P>
   ``Certainly it's a thriving singles scene,'' said Daryl Mattson,
community relations coordinator for the sprawling Borders store at
the World Trade Center in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's sort of a cruising sensibility going on, with people
looking up and down'' perusing books and magazines, said David
Jetton, describing the scene at Barnes &AMP; Noble at 82nd Street and
Broadway.
</P>
<P>
   Among the strategies bookstore browsers employ _ choosing
reading material that they hope will attract like-minded partners
or spending time in a favorite specialty section.
</P>
<P>
   Mattson recently organized a singles' reading soiree titled
``Recruiting Love'' which attracted about two dozen singles from
the Wall Street community. A few people met and, true to form for
the clientele, exchanged business cards, he said.
</P>
<P>
   It's the relaxing atmosphere of a bookstore that makes people
feel comfortable, Mattson said. ``People feel weird going to a bar
alone, or going to a movie alone, but you can walk into a bookstore
alone and pretend you're just shopping, or just sit there alone and
no one's going to pass judgment.''
</P>
<P>
   ``First it was discos, then it was coffee bars, and now
bookstores,'' said Dierdre Kaduk, an actress who regularly visits
the Barnes &AMP; Noble bookstore and cafe at 82nd Street. While she has
yet to find Mr. Right, she often socializes with friends in the
store.
</P>
<P>
   Jetton first struck up a conversation about Tennessee Williams
and other gay playwrights with his partner, Dennis Schulz, last May
in Gryphon, a small bookstore on Broadway.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks later, they met again by chance in the Barnes &AMP; Noble
across the street. ``You can scan the entire floor'' from atop the
escalator, Jetton said. ``He spotted me and came to me.'' The two
went out for dinner that same night.
</P>
<P>
   For the bookstores, setting up an atmosphere conducive to casual
conversation has worked well as a sales strategy.
</P>
<P>
   ``The more comfort you give someone in a store, chances are they
will stay longer,'' said Helena Aalto, communications director for
the Chapters megabookstore chain in Canada. The average browsing
time in a comfortable megastore is ``a little short of one hour,''
compared to about 15 minutes in the more traditional mall stores
the chain owns, she said. More browsing time seems to yield more
books sold per customer, she added.
</P>
<P>
   But the sit-down-and-make-yourself-at-home approach to
bookselling can also produce some unexpected results. Bruce
Deachman, a freelance writer looking for an offbeat feature, tried
last year to see what it would take to get thrown out of the
Chapters in Ottawa. After spending nearly three weeks in the
aisles, trying everything from rolling coins at a wooden desk to
noisily fixing his broken telephone with a screwdriver, he was
finally asked to leave for practicing his golf putt in the sports
section.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my 19 days there, I didn't see many people buying stuff,''
Deachman said. But he said he did see a lot of free reading and
socializing.
</P>
<P>
   A Burlington, Ontario, couple, now married, ``just started up a
conversation'' one day in Chapters, recalled Kelly Kuus, store
manager. She said they returned within a year to have their wedding
photos taken _ in the romance section, of course.
</P>
<P>
   And customers are not the only ones meeting in bookstores. Beth
Reynolds, an editor in Ann Arbor, Mich., for Borders' Web site, met
her husband in 1994 while they were both clerks at a Borders store
in Pittsburgh. They married two years later. ``I originally thought
of working there because, of course, I would meet someone,''
Reynolds said.
</P>
<P>
   For the Savages, a bookstore wedding seemed inevitable, if
offbeat. But in spite of her happy ending, Michele Savage was blase
about encouraging romantic hopefuls who sip lattes and pretend to
peruse magazines while scanning the store.
</P>
<P>
   ``Go to a bookstore to read, and to buy books,'' Savage said.
``And if you happen to meet somebody, well _ that would be a happy
accident.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (EDITORS: Ross Finley is a master's degree candidate at the
Graduate School of Journalism at Columbia University. There is no
charge for use of this story, but please send a tearsheet to Prof.
Wayne Svoboda, Columbia News Service, Graduate School of
Journalism, Columbia University, 2950 Broadway, New York, N.Y.
10027) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
