<SLUG> BC-CNS-BODY-IMAGE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOCUSING ON SELF-ESTEEM: PHOTO SHOOTS FOR BODY IMAGE 
</HEADLINE>
   For use by New York Times Syndicate/News Service clients as
desired.  
 By KIM K. DIXON  
 c.1999 Columbia News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ For the first 25 years of her life, Ana battled with
the mirror.
</P>
<P>
   ``Getting dressed in the morning was an exercise in
self-torture,'' said the 27-year-old Cuban-American actress, who
asked that her last name not be used.
</P>
<P>
   Despite constant, and successful, dieting, Ana loathed every
nook, cranny and dimple on her body. She had been on Broadway and
in TV commercials but could not stomach looking at herself in any
of her roles.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was paralyzed. ... I couldn't have a conversation with
people without my body being in the background, right here in the
back of my head'' getting in the way of a normal life, Ana said.
</P>
<P>
   New York City photographer Ellen Turk has a radical reply to
this distinctly female predicament. Three years ago, Turk began
persuading women who typically cringe at the sight of themselves in
a passing mirror to confront their demons head-on.
</P>
<P>
   Clients willingly pose for a photo session in either their home
or Turk's in Brooklyn. The photos are artsy black-and-white stills,
culminating in nudes if requested. One is a woman lying on a bed,
askew and disheveled, on her stomach viewed from above. Another is
simply a profile shot of a woman peering in a bathroom mirror.
</P>
<P>
   ``I try to get at what's special, and everyone's got something
special,'' said Turk, a 50-ish woman with a pixie buzz haircut.
</P>
<P>
   ``The pictures they like capture something which contradicts the
idea they're not living up to some ideal of beauty,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Women for whom the mirror yields such power may be biologically
doomed to fail. A 1992 study in the International Journal of Eating
Disorders found that a woman's perceived ideal body weight was 13
to 19 percent lower than recommended by health experts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ninety five percent of women can't achieve their ideal,'' said
Terry Poulton, author of ``Fat Chicks: How the Diet Industry Makes
Women Hate Their Bodies.''
</P>
<P>
   Turk's solution is not cheap, at $450 a shot, which Turk said is
necessary to pay for the film, processing, printing, phone calls
and one photo session, which lasts about three hours.
</P>
<P>
   ``After a half an hour or so of talking and getting comfortable,
I shoot a few rolls of film,'' Turk said. ``And I've already spent
time talking to the woman, learning her story.''
</P>
<P>
   Her clients run the gamut from those with general body hate to
those with full-fledged eating disorders. Many have suffered
serious psychological trauma. Ana was sexually abused as a child
and had disordered patterns of eating for as long as she can
remember.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had this problem with my body image, so I thought what
better way to deal with it than to display it like a piece of
meat?'' said Ana, who admitted a feeling of horror at the first
sight of herself on Turk's film.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I first saw the pictures, I went crazy,'' Ana said. ``But
it was like a road accident, I couldn't stop looking and then
finally I got used to seeing what I thought was ugly. I got
desensitized to it.''
</P>
<P>
   Another Turk client, a New York City chiropractor, had a similar
reaction after her photo session with Turk last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was like a reprogramming of all the negative tapes in my
head,'' said the 42-year-old, who has despised her body since being
mocked as a child for her less-than-ideal size.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it was Ellen,'' the chiropractor said. ``She makes you
feel very comfortable and at ease.''
</P>
<P>
   But skeptical body-image and eating-disorder experts yell
caution.
</P>
<P>
   ``This method could be very dangerous by just scratching at the
surface,'' said Gerri DiBenedetto, a New York therapist who treats
eating disorders ranging from compulsive overeating to anorexia.
</P>
<P>
   She doubts that a one-time photo session with Turk can be a
cure-all for the deeply rooted eating and body-image disorders.
DiBenedetto and other experts argue that while the idea might seem
promising, women see themselves all the time and yet the
distortions persist.
</P>
<P>
   ``If she professes to help people with body-image problems,
she's trying to be a therapist, and then trying to cover herself by
saying, 'I advise people to get therapy,' '' said Dr. Denise
Heebink, a psychiatrist at New York Hospital's Eating Disorder
Program.
</P>
<P>
   Although Turk has no degree in psychiatry or therapy, she does
have a master's in special education. She also works with children,
using positive light.
</P>
<P>
   Turk does not profess to be a substitute for traditional
therapy, and admits her method is no science.
</P>
<P>
   ``For some, the need for self-perfection is so strong that I
have to screw up, it's a no win,'' she said. ``I can only do what I
can do.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (EDITORS: Kim K. Dixon is a master's degree candidate at the
Graduate School of Journalism at Columbia University. There is no
charge for use of this story, but please send a tearsheet to Prof.
Wayne Svoboda, Columbia News Service, Graduate School of
Journalism, Columbia University, 2950 Broadway, New York, N.Y.
10027) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
