<SLUG> BC-MA-PENSION-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BAY STATE MOVES PENSION FUNDS TO MELLON BANK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HIAWATHA BRAY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- For the first time since Massachusetts created its
Pension Reserves Investment Trust for state employees 16 years ago,
State Street Corp. will no longer act as the fund's custodian.
</P>
<P>
   State Treasurer Shannon O'Brien has appointed Pittsburgh-based
Mellon Bank to serve as custodian of the $25 billion fund.
O'Brien's decision was approved Tuesday by the state's Pension
Reserves Investment Management board, which oversees the fund.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Henderson, executive director of the PRIM board, said
Mellon was the strongest candidate in a field that also included
State Street, New York's Citibank, and Chicago's Northern Trust Co.
</P>
<P>
   Mellon entered the low bid, offering to oversee administration
of the fund for a $1.1 million annual fee, compared to State
Street's bid of $2.4 million, Henderson said. ``We found Mellon's
fee to be extremely competitive, but at the same time credible,''
he said. ``They can deliver very high quality services to us at
that level, without compromising quality.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Henderson said Mellon's Executive Workbench
computer network will make it easier for the PRIM staff to keep
tabs electronically on the trust's performance. ``We think that
product is probably a little bit ahead of the competition right
now,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The PRIM fund was established in 1983 to invest the pension
money of the Massachusetts State Employees' and Teachers'
Retirement systems, and other state and local government employees
in Massachusetts. State Street has served as custodian of the fund
since its inception. The bank had held onto the business through
four previous reviews by the PRIM board, which seeks new bids for
the custodianship every three years.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are extremely proud of the work we did on behalf of PRIM
for the past 15 years,'' State Street said in a statement issued
after the decision was announced. ``We wish Mellon the best of
luck.
</P>
<P>
   The PRIM board Tuesday also selected Blackrock Financial
Management Inc. of New York to manage its $1.3 billion portfolio of
fixed-income investments. The board also approved changes in its
asset allocation plan that will increase its investment in real
estate from 4 percent to 6 percent of the fund, and reduce its
stock investments from 47 percent to 45 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
