A2816 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DOW-FOUR-COX     03-16 0419
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOW-FOUR-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Retirement vehicles contain about 30% of stocks' value
 &HT;    By Hank Ezell
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Ordinary Americans, saving slowly and diligently for
their retirement years, helped push the Dow to 10,000 Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Retirement accounts such as 401(k) plans now hold close to $1.4
trillion worth of stocks, or a 10th of the total value of U.S.
stocks.
</P>
<P>
   Add to that the stock investments in individual retirement
accounts and traditional pension plans, and the total shoots to an
estimated 30 percent of the total market value.
</P>
<P>
   That concentration means the decisions of millions of individual
investors make a difference in the overall demand for stocks.
</P>
<P>
   As demand increases, so do prices.
</P>
<P>
   Americans have been deciding to buy more stocks. Studies of
401(k) plans _ the most common retirement savings plan _ show that
a growing percentage of those investments is in stocks.
</P>
<P>
   The 401(k) plans are popular with individuals because income
taxes are deferred on the money in them and because more Americans
are in their mid-career and later years, when they begin to pay
attention to retirement needs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, 401(k)s have had a significant impact,'' argued
Catherine S. McBreen. She is the chief retirement consultant for
the Spectrem Group, a respected data-gathering and consulting
company. ``It is more of a longer-term impact, but it's not what's
making the market go up and down day to day.''
</P>
<P>
   Much of the growth in total retirement plan holdings has come
from rising stock prices. The total might have grown faster, except
for the money that retirees have withdrawn from their accounts.
</P>
<P>
   Ted Benna, the Pennsylvania consultant known as the father of
the 401(k), believes the plans have had at least a modest impact on
the rising market. ``The 401(k)s are not the sole factor,'' he
cautioned. ``There's too much money, far beyond what's coming from
401(k)s. My suspicion is that there still must be substantial
volumes of foreign money coming into the market.''
</P>
<P>
   But the reliable habits of 401(k) investors have been a comfort
to the market. ``They have helped, simply because there is that
predictable, constant flow,'' Benna said. ``I don't know whether it
(retirement saving) is a big factor or just another factor. The
U.S. market remains a mystery to everybody.''
</P>
<P>
   Hank Ezell writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution, Atlanta,
Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
