<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CREDIT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INFLATION OPTIMISM HELPS TO PUSH 30-YEAR YIELD LOWER 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By ROBERT HURTADO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Bond yields dropped to their lowest point in three
weeks Tuesday, aided by optimism that inflation will not accelerate
and, to a lesser extent, by comments by Alan Greenspan, the Federal
Reserve chairman, suggesting that the central bank will not raise
short-term interest rates.
</P>
<P>
   The price of the 30-year Treasury bond rose 22/32, to 96 23/32.
The bond's yield, which moves in the opposite direction of the
price, fell to 5.47 percent, from 5.52 percent on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Donald Fine, chief market analyst at Chase Asset Management,
expects that Fed policy-makers will not change interest rates when
they meet March 30. ``The economy's impressive strength will
prevent the Fed from easing,'' he said, ``while the auspicious
inflation environment and global financial fragility argue strongly
against any policy tightening.''
</P>
<P>
   Fine also believes that bond yields will hover around 5.5
percent for a while as fears of a Fed tightening dissipate.
</P>
<P>
   Several reports Tuesday pointed to solid economic advances.
Housing starts declined just six-tenths of 1 percent in February,
to an annual rate of roughly 1.8 million units, after setting a
12-year high in January. The levels of both housing starts and
building permits in the first quarter are on track to significantly
exceed those of the fourth quarter, Fine noted. A tapering of house
construction is invariably a prelude to a slowdown in economic
activity, so the robust performance of starts and building permits
suggested continued momentum in the months ahead.
</P>
<P>
   Industrial production rose two-tenths of 1 percent last month
and manufacturing output also rose two-tenths of 1 percent _ its
fifth consecutive monthly advance.
</P>
<P>
   Greenspan spoke to the Independent Bankers Association of
America meeting in San Francisco, where his remarks seemed to focus
more on downside risks, providing only a marginal lift to the
market.
</P>
<P>
   Stocks also bolstered bonds as the Dow Jones industrial average
surpassed 10,000 points for the first time in intraday trading; it
closed lower, though, at 9,930.47. Traders speculated that some
investors switched their allocations from stocks to bonds.
</P>
<P>
   Gains could be limited in the days ahead, though, as several
corporate debt issues are expected to be priced. Fannie Mae, among
other borrowers, plans to sell as much as $13 billion of debt, and
AT&AMP;T Corp. expects to sell $5 billion to $6 billion in bonds.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
