<DOCNO> NYT19990316.0273 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-16 19:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2826 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DOW-MAGICMARK-COX     03-16 0449
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOW-MAGICMARK-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Dow reaches history, then drops back
 &HT;    (EDS: Moving in (a) General News and (f) Financial categories.)
 &HT;    By Tom Walker
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average finally topped 10,000 in the
first half hour of trading Tuesday, stayed about a minute and then
dropped back sharply and never challenged again.
</P>
<P>
   The benchmark index of 30 blue chip stocks reached an historic
10,001.78. By day's end, however, it closed 69.53 points below
10,000 and 28.30 points below Monday's all-time high.
</P>
<P>
   But that didn't stop Prudential Securities analyst Ralph
Acampora from exulting to reporters in a conference call: ``It's
exciting. It's America. We all should get up and sing `God Bless
America.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Acampora said stocks are in the earliest stage of a new bull
that began last October when the 1998 stock market correction
ended, and is being led by high-quality stocks such as those in the
Dow index.
</P>
<P>
   He reiterated an earlier forecast that the Dow would reach
11,500 before the end of 1999 ``if the market leadership stays with
quality.''
</P>
<P>
   Only a dozen Dow stocks closed with gains, the biggest being
Merck &AMP; Co., Boeing, Hewlett-Packard, Chevron and Eastman Kodak.
The big losers included American Express, Caterpillar, J.P. Morgan
and Disney. Coca-Cola and AT&AMP;T were unchanged.
</P>
<P>
   The broader market also declined on Tuesday, but the technology
loaded Nasdaq composite index posted a small gain on the strength
of positive news about semiconductor sales.
</P>
<P>
   None of the day's activities changed the conviction of traders
and analysts that the Dow will close above 10,000, and probably
this week.
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, mutual fund and other money managers are engaged
in end-of-quarter ``window dressing,'' where they buy winning
stocks to be fully invested with their clients' money,
Interstate/Johnson Lane analyst Ricky Harrington said.
</P>
<P>
   Also, Friday is a ``triple witching'' session, when the
expiration of futures, index options and individual stock options
often adds to trading and market volatility.
</P>
<P>
   This is not the first time the Dow has teased investors before
closing above an important level. It took six years to go from its
first trade above 1,000 to the first close above 1,000, on Nov. 14,
1972.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow crossed 3,000 several times in July 1990 but did not
close above 3,000 until April 17, 1991, and in 1994, it traded
within shooting distance of 4,000 for about five weeks in February
before closing above 4,000 on Feb. 23, 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Walker writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution, Atlanta,
Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
