<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JUAREZ-FACTORY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. FACTORY IS GETTING WORKERS OUT OF THE SLUMS
</HEADLINE>
 (EDS: Accompanies JUAREZ-KILLINGS) 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TIM MADIGAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CIUDAD JUAREZ, Mexico _ Each of the 14 plants General Motors
Chairman Jack Smith toured that day was a bright, bustling place
filled with thousands of focused employees.
</P>
<P>
   But to get from one GM plant to another, the American executive
was forced to drive through the colonias, sprawling communities of
cardboard shacks where ten of thousands of Juarez factory workers
lived in wretched poverty.
</P>
<P>
   On the trip back across the international bridge to El Paso at
the end of the day, Smith turned to Lee Crawford of Delphi
Automotive, the GM division that ran the plants.
</P>
<P>
   ``Crawford, you've got world-class plants and world-class
people,'' Smith said that day in 1992. ``And I don't want our
people to live in the conditions I saw today.''
</P>
<P>
   For Crawford, Delphi's executive director for Mexico and Central
America, Smith's statement was a mandate. Five years later,
neighborhoods of small but sturdy brick homes had sprouted near the
Delphi facilities _ places with heat, electricity and indoor
plumbing. Schools and stores were built nearby, and plans were made
to construct churches. Today, there are 5,500 such dwellings in
Mexican cities where Delphi runs factories, housing as many as
35,000 of the company's workers and their families. Delphi shares
small mortgage payments with its employees.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest gift they could ever give,'' employee Noel Monreal
told television reporters in 1997, the day he moved his family into
their new home. But such largess is rare in a city where 330
American-owned maquiladoras _ or ``twin factories'' _ now employ
230,000 people. Delphi's is the only factory-sponsored housing
program in the city. For most of the rest of the maquiladora
workers, factory wages amounting to $3 a day are insufficient to
escape the grimmest living conditions. Factory buses deposit
thousands of workers in the colonias, where after a day working
with the world's most sophisticated production equipment, employees
retire to homes with dirt floors and no electricity.
</P>
<P>
   The incongruity gives rise to frequent allegations of
exploitation, criticisms that have intensified in the past several
years. Critics say the factories and their owners are indifferent
to the slayings of young Juarez women. Many, if not most, of the
victims have been maquiladora employees.
</P>
<P>
   Industry officials have recently made overtures toward Juarez
feminist groups. Robert Urrea, the top executive for AMAC, the
largest Juarez maquiladora association, has joined the board of
directors of the Juarez rape crisis center that opened last month.
Maquiladora nurses will receive training as rape crisis counselors.
</P>
<P>
   But otherwise, the factories' most visible response to the
slayings has been plant posters urging employee caution while
coming to and going from work.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're really concerned about these tragedies, but the Chamber
of Commerce in Fort Worth or an association of bankers aren't
responsible for the security of the city,'' said Serbando Sarabia,
executive director of AMAC. ``We contribute a lot with salaries and
benefits in the city. We now have to demand security from our city
and state government.''
</P>
<P>
   The stance has been a public-relations disaster, one serving to
cast employee-friendly companies like Delphi, Juarez's largest
private employer with a work force of 20,000, in an even more
favorable light.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike most factories, which maintain strict security at their
plants, Delphi executives routinely guide journalists on long
tours. Recent visitors to one plant found an immaculately clean,
well-lit place with Mexican music piped in above the hum of
machinery.
</P>
<P>
   The company lunchroom, where workers receive two free meals each
day, resembled the interior of a new Luby's restaurant. Televisions
playing rock videos hung above the booths.
</P>
<P>
   And thousands of employees go home to the new dwellings built
near their plants, thus avoiding dangerous places in Juarez on the
maquiladora bus routes. Those new homes also have flushing toilets.
For thousands of Juarez factory workers, that remains an
otherworldly luxury.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
