<HEADER>
A2837 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-AUBURN-POHLMAN-CO     03-16 0931
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-AUBURN-POHLMAN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    This boy Tiger's got game
 &HT;    By Jack Wilkinson
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Once again, Auburn's trapping pressure worked
flawlessly. It was a perfect double team, one Bryant Smith
initiated as he passed through the revolving door. The senior
swingman reached back and stopped the door. On the other side of
the door, Auburn basketball publicist Chuck Gallina did likewise.
And there, trapped like a driveway rat and encased in glass, stood
Scott Pohlman.
</P>
<P>
   It was the only time anyone stopped the little guard all day.
</P>
<P>
   ''All they do is pick on me,'' a smiling Pohlman said once Smith
sprung him. ''All they do is pick on me.''
</P>
<P>
   If Auburn teases Pohlman, the Tigers also treasure him. Earlier
on Saturday in Indianapolis, he scored a career-high 28 points to
lead Auburn past Oklahoma State 81-74 and into the NCAA
Tournament's Sweet 16. The performance thrilled an RCA Dome crowd
of 30,318, particularly because Pohlman looks as if he would blend
in nicely with the Indiana state high-school playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   At least until the opening tipoff. ''Pohlman ran me to death,''
Oklahoma State point guard Doug Gottlieb said admiringly. The
slight sophomore guard from Roswell hit 11-of-17 shots from the
floor, 2-for-3 on three-pointers, and all four foul shots.
</P>
<P>
   In 32 minutes, Pohlman did not commit a single turnover. Not
even when, with Doc Robinson sitting out nearly five minutes after
getting his fourth personal midway through the second half, he
found himself at the point for one of the few times all season.
</P>
<P>
   ''The bigger key to the win was him playing the point,'' Auburn
coach Cliff Ellis said, ''because they had us where they wanted it,
and he responded.''
</P>
<P>
   With the shot clock winding down and Auburn clinging to a 74-72
lead, Pohlman drove across the lane and collided with Oklahoma
State's Brian Montonati. No foul was called, and Pohlman stuck a
pullup jumper with 0:51.9 left. When he made both ends of a 1-and-1
with 13 seconds to play, Auburn was bound for Knoxville, where the
top-seeded Tigers (29-3) will meet Ohio State in Thursday's
semifinals.
</P>
<P>
   There, Ohio State will learn that looks can be deceiving.
Robinson already knows what most opponents think when they spy the
6-foot-2, 160-pounder the Tigers call Opie.''Once they come out and
look over at him, they say, 'Look at this guy. He can't play. He
doesn't deserve to be out there. He looks like a ballboy.' But once
he start to hit threes and get in a rhythm, they know.''
</P>
<P>
   They know what opponents have discovered all of Pohlman's life:
He's got game.
</P>
<P>
   ''That's just Scott's mentality,'' Robinson said. ''I can kind
of feel it once he gets into his rhythm, and I look into his eyes
or he gives me that look.''
</P>
<P>
   Never mind that Pohlman looks like he could still be playing for
the Roswell High Hornets. He's the second-leading scorer, 12.3
points a game, on the winningest team in Alabama state history.
''He's always loved big games,'' said Pohlman's father, Ray, who
bought his son his first basketball goal at the age of 2, one with
a little metal arm below the basket that rang every time Scott
scored a basket. ''He's always liked the pressure of the big games.
That's kind of been his trademark.''
</P>
<P>
   It was at Roswell, where Pohlman led the Hornets to the state
Class AAAA championship in 1997. ''We'd go into games and look like
we were not gonna win,'' Pohlman said, referring to the Hornets'
slight appearances. ``We'd call ourselves the golf team.''
</P>
<P>
   Once on the court, Pohlman displayed a game forged in his
driveway. For Scott's 10th birthday, his father installed a
regulation 10-foot basket mounted on a plexiglass backboard. ''Kind
of unheard of in our neighborhood,'' Pohlman recalled. ''It was
pretty cool.''
</P>
<P>
   It also was a magnet for neighborhood kids and later Scott's
school teammates. They'd play for hours, often until late at night,
when the neighbors or Pohlman's parents would ask him to please
turn off the car radio, or the floodlight, or just stop shooting.
But Pohlman also spent hours alone, referring to a set of cards
that defined his shooting, dribbling and passing drills based on
Pete Maravich instructional tapes his father had bought.
</P>
<P>
   By his senior year at Roswell, Pohlman was prepared to attend
Pepperdine on a scholarship, especially after his official visit.
''Beaches and girls,'' he recalled, smiling. ''It'd be a hard place
to study. Might've joined the surf team.''
</P>
<P>
   But then Auburn called; a scholarship came open when a
junior-college signee was arrested and convicted of assault.
Pohlman changed his mind, preferring to play closer to home and in
the Southeastern Conference. Before he left for Auburn, his father
advised, ''Son, you're going to have to prepare yourself mentally
to come off the bench.''
</P>
<P>
   Ray Pohlman remember's his son's reply: ''He said, 'Dad, I'm not
going down to Auburn to sit on the bench.' Then, I knew he was
going to go to Auburn to play.''
</P>
<P>
   It took Pohlman one game to crack the starting lineup. Now, he
has helped put Auburn two wins from its first Final Four. That
could come Saturday, two days before Ray Pohlman's 55th birthday,
when his boyish-looking son might be the man once again.
</P>
<P>
   ''That's the way I've been all my life,'' said Pohlman. ''People
underestimate me. But I try not to let size matter. If they do
(underestimate), it's to my advantage.''
</P>
<P>
   Jack Wilkinson writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
