<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-16 19:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2838 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LASTDAYS-REMEMBER17-C     03-16 0537
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LASTDAYS-REMEMBER17-C0X </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Chilling tales of Hitler's `Last Days'
 &HT;    By Eleanor Ringel Gillespie
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service'
<TEXT>
<P>
   Life isn't beautiful in ``The Last Days,'' a searingly memorable
documentary about the Holocaust in Hungary.
</P>
<P>
   Produced by Steven Spielberg for his Survivors of the Shoah
Visual History Foundation and an Oscar nominee for best
documentary, ``Last Days'' shows us a particularly vile footnote to
Hitler's Final Solution. In the waning months of World War II, when
Der Furher's forces were crumbling, one would think the eradication
of more Jews would be the last thing on his mind. Instead, he
decided to enforce his implacable program of genocide in occupied
Hungary which, until that point, had been somewhat removed from the
appalling events occurring in neighboring countries. As one of the
five survivors who are the film's focus puts it, ``Judaism was our
religion, but we were Hungarians . . . We didn't believe the
stories of the refugees.''
</P>
<P>
   They should have.
</P>
<P>
   In six weeks, 438,000 Hungarian Jews were rounded up and put in
cattle cars. Told they were headed to work in a vineyard, another
survivor remembers secretly packing a bathing suit her father had
given her. Unfortunately, there wasn't much time for sunbathing at
Auschwitz or Buchenwald, which is where most of them landed.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps inevitably, some of ``Last Days''' stories and footage
are familiar. There are the obscene piles of corpses, the walking
near-dead whose skeletal bodies chilled the Allied liberators who
first discovered them, the appalling horror tales of ovens and
showers. Yet the documentary manages a unique focus by confining
itself to one small country and to five people who made it out
alive _ less, as they all point out, because of any resilience or
resourcefulness on their parts but because they were lucky. Very
lucky.
</P>
<P>
   Even ``luck'' can be a risky proposition. In one of the film's
eerier sequences, director James Moll introduces us to kindly Dr.
Hans Munch, a would-be Schindler who claims he used his experiments
at Auschwitz to help prolong lives. Confronted by a survivor who
wonders why her sister, one of Munch's lab rats, died in six months
under his supervision, the doctor looks distinctly less kindly and
decidedly more uncomfortable.
</P>
<P>
   It's moments like this that give Moll's 87-minute documentary
its special identity and impact among the mass of Holocaust
testimony. Tell future generations that 6 million died and they
have a statistic. Tell them about Tom Lantos, the only Holocaust
survivor serving in Congress and unimaginable horror is given a
human face.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Last Days'' says a kind of kaddish for the dead Jews of
Hungary. And it does so with respect, with honesty and, oddly
enough, with a kind of undiminished hope.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Last Days.''
</P>
<P>
   Grade: A-
</P>
<P>
   A documentary on the Holocaust. Directed by James Moll. Rated
PG-13 for extreme adult themes including genocide. At Toco Hills. 1
hour and 27 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: An extraordinary small-scale history lesson.
</P>
<P>
   Eleanor Ringel Gillespie writes for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
