A2841 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BUDGET-TEXAS-HNS &LR;      03-16 0882
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUDGET-TEXAS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS LAWMAKERS GRAPPLE WITH PROPOSED PROPERTY-TAX CUTS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOHN W. GONZALEZ 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Lawmakers said Tuesday they haven't found a way
to realize the $2 billion in property-tax cuts sought by Gov.
George W. Bush without short-changing Texas teachers and dashing
hopes for other forms of tax relief.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly halfway through the 140-day legislative session, members
of House and Senate committees predicted the projected $2.5 billion
surplus for 2000-01 would be more than devoured by a proposed $3
billion boost for education and at least $500 million in
miscellaneous tax breaks. They're hoping an increased revenue
estimate will save the day.
</P>
<P>
   Though Bush clings to his 1998 re-election promise to provide
some direct relief to property owners, ranking lawmakers said
Bush's best hope is for indirect relief in the form of higher state
payments to local school districts. Theoretically, districts would
have less need to increase ad-valorem property taxes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to put extra dollars in certain areas and they
will be considered tax relief, because otherwise the local property
taxpayers would have paid that,'' said Rep. Henry Cuellar,
D-Laredo, who serves on the House Appropriations Committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``The pressure is on us to put the majority of the dollars on
public education and higher education,'' Cuellar said.
</P>
<P>
   From a practical, not political, standpoint, bigger monthly
paychecks for teachers could be better than small reductions in
annual property taxes, said House Ways and Means Committee Chairman
Rene Oliveira, D-Brownsville.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thousands and thousands of teachers that are going to get a
significant pay raise _ that is a greater economic impact than
token property tax relief,'' said Oliveira, one of many lawmakers
who is convinced there won't be enough money left on the table for
Bush's full request.
</P>
<P>
   As for Bush's $2 billion property-tax relief objective, Oliveira
said, ``we can't reach that under any fiscal scenario that I see.''
</P>
<P>
   His conclusion is shared by Senate Finance Committee Chairman
Bill Ratliff, R-Mount Pleasant, who said it is ``probably
questionable'' whether Bush's full objective will be met, although
Ratliff and others caution that it's too early in the
budget-wrangling process to declare any notion dead.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this point, it's anybody's guess,'' said Rep. Harold
Dutton, D-Houston, vice chairman of the House Public Education
Committee that figures heavily into the equation. Dutton's
committee will sort through a stack of requests for teacher-pay and
retirement-benefit increases and program enhancements, and decide
how to divvy up about $1.5 billion a year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have more things in the hopper than we have money to do
them, which is always the case,'' Dutton said.
</P>
<P>
   Though teacher groups have pleaded for a $6,000 annual increase
to put them close to a national average, Ratliff and House
counterparts have poured cold water on that request.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no way we're going to get the $6,000 per teacher, but
if you talk about only $1,000 per teacher, you're talking about
$600 million over two years. That adds up in a hurry,'' Ratliff
said.
</P>
<P>
   Cuellar agreed, saying, ``we would love to do a $6,000 payraise,
but we just can't do it now.''
</P>
<P>
   Teachers won't be the only sector left asking for more.
Businesses seeking tax relief have endorsed proposals that would
cut billions from state income through tax-rate reductions, credits
and incentives. But a majority of the proposals could be doomed by
the agreed-upon emphasis on new education spending _ and an
informal, high-level agreement to cap those tax cuts at $500
million. Even so, the head of Ways and Means isn't ready to throw
in the towel.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not letting the Appropriations Committee or Senate Finance
Committee in any way designate or decide how much we should spend
or save in tax exemptions, tax credits and incentives,'' Oliveira
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we're going to have a collision course with the
appropriations-finance process. Hopefully it will be a minor
collision .... and hopefully it's not the Titanic,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The projected surplus presents a rare opportunity for lawmakers
to cobble together a package of sales tax and franchise tax relief,
Oliveira said. One popular proposal calls for a moratorium on sales
taxes on school-related items.
</P>
<P>
   Oliveira predicted sales-tax relief could top $300 million in a
stand-alone measure likely to reach the House floor in mid-April _
about the same time as the House version of the budget.
</P>
<P>
   ``The next thing we're going to look at is some (business)
franchise-tax exemptions or credits, and then we're going to leave
the research-and-development and job-training credits for the end,
as well as any possible property tax relief,'' Oliveira said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The property tax relief of $2 billion is the most difficult to
do,'' Oliveira said, emphasizing that he kept his own promise to
Bush to search for ways to implement Bush's plan.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, who is on vacation, wasn't available for comment Tuesday.
A spokesman said he remains confident that lawmakers will act in
the best interests of both students and taxpayers.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
