<P>
   CLINTON-MEDICARE (Washington) _ President Clinton promises to
craft his own plan to keep Medicare solvent as a bipartisan
congressional commission charged with overhauling the health
insurance program for the elderly failed to reach an agreement. By
GREG McDONALD. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-RICHARDSON (Washington) _ Energy Secretary Bill Richardson
tells a Senate panel the administration has taken numerous steps to
tighten security in the wake of allegations that a U.S. weapons
scientist gave nuclear secrets to China. The extent of the damage
from the spying won't be known until the CIA completes its probe
next month, he says. By ERIC ROSENBERG. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-AFRICA (Washington) _ Calling for a new partnership with
Africa, President Clinton urges the international community to
expand debt-relief programs for impoverished African nations, a
proposal that would result in $70 billion worth of loans being
forgiven. By JOHN C. HENRY. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   MISSILE-BILL (Washington) _ The White House agrees to a
bipartisan plan that would allow the development of a limited
missile-defense system if it does not conflict with arms-control
efforts between the United States and Russia. By GREG McDONALD.
(Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   CHILD-CARE (Washington)_ House Democrats push for a boost in
federal funding for day care and higher tax credits for
moderate-income families with children. By JENNIFER CORBETT DOOREN.
(Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   INS-BUDGET (Washington) _ The head of the Immigration and
Naturalization Service says the Clinton administration will add no
new Border Patrol agents in the next budget year, prompting
criticism from Arizona and Texas senators who said more are needed
to stem the flow of illegal immigrants and drugs across the border.
By STEVE LASH. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   FORBES-2000 (Concord, N.H.) _ Already running in cyberspace,
Steve Forbes appears in person at a New Hampshire rally to announce
his campaign for the Republican presidential nomination in 2000.
The magazine publisher had used his Internet site to kick off his
second bid for the nomination. By BENNETT ROTH.
</P>
<P>
   BUDGET-TEXAS (Austin, Texas) _ Texas lawmakers say writing the
state budget and another group contemplating tax-relief proposals
are on a collision course over how to divvy up a projected surplus
of at least $2.5 billion, key legislators said. Gov. George W. Bush
is waiting anxiously for the outcome. By JOHN GONZALEZ. (Already
filed.)
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL NEWS (``i'' category)
</P>
<P>
   ECUADOR-CRISIS (Quito, Ecuador) _ With the country paralyzed by
strikes, the currency losing value and politicians unable to
respond, some Ecuadoreans are calling for drastic measures.
Opposition leaders are demanding the resignation of President Jamil
Mahuad. According to politicians and diplomats, Mahuad and his
advisers have talked about closing the Congress and ruling by
decree, but so far have resisted the idea. By JOHN OTIS.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MEANS-COLUMN (Washington) _ Lamar Alexander, who has been
campaigning for two years, made it official last week that he is
running for the 2000 Republican presidential nomination. He's just
a blip in the polls, and his anti-Washington message is stale. He
is full of ambition, but his campaign lacks a punch. By MARIANNE
MEANS. (Already filed.)
</P>
