A2847 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-CUBS-WOOD-COX     03-16 0302
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-CUBS-WOOD-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    1998 top rookie Wood out for season
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAKE BUENA VISTA, Fla. _ Andres Galarraga. Moises Alou. Now
Kerry Wood.
</P>
<P>
   The National League on Tuesday lost for the season a third major
star, as Wood, the reigning Rookie of the Year and great hope of
the Chicago Cubs, was diagnosed with a torn ulnar collateral
ligament in his right elbow. An MRI exam in Chicago revealed the
damage, although the extent of the injury and the chances of
surgery could not be determined until further tests.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel for him,'' Cubs closer Rod Beck said. ``I think, as a
pitcher, everyone one of us (has been) in bed with an ache and a
pain thinking it's over.''
</P>
<P>
   Wood was in the middle of a disastrous camp. He already had been
hospitalized twice, for respiratory and intestinal illnesses, and
was making just his first start of the Cactus League season on
Saturday. He left the mound against Anaheim after throwing just 26
pitches and was sent back to Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   Wood, 21, was 13-6 in 26 starts last season with 233 strikeouts
in 166 2/3 innings and figured prominently in Cubs' hopes for their
first pennant in 54 years. He was sidelined with a tender elbow
most of the last month of the season but faced the Braves in Game 3
of the League Championship Series, allowing one run in a 6-2
defeat.
</P>
<P>
   ``A kid like that only comes around once in a while,'' Braves
manager Bobby Cox said. ``Even though he's the opposition, you sure
don't want to see him hurt. The game needs more young kids to come
along like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Stinson writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga. The Associated Press contributed to this article.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
