A2848 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-WOMENS-NOTES-COX     03-16 0615
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-WOMENS-NOTES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    NCAA Women's notebook: Top 16 teams to square off
 &HT;    By Wendy Parker
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ All 16 of the teams hosting NCAA women's subregional
sites won second-round home games Sunday and Monday, meaning each
of the four regionals will feature the top four seeds.
</P>
<P>
   But a number of the games were close, and, in the case of
Connecticut, the No. 1 seed in the Mideast, its second-round
contest Sunday was a downright scare. Xavier almost became the
women's equivalent of Miami of Ohio, Gonzaga and Southwest Missouri
State by leading the Huskies for most of the game before falling
86-84 in the final 7.1 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   The Musketeers could have gotten a return trip to Cincinnati for
the Mideast semifinals on Saturday, but a relieved full house of
10,027 at Gampel Pavilion watched freshman Tamika Williams sink two
free throws for the winning points.
</P>
<P>
   No freebies here
</P>
<P>
   Many of the top-drawing programs avoid disclosing how many
tickets they give away or discount during the regular season, but a
true gauge of the sport's fan base can be found in who turns out
for NCAA Tournament games.
</P>
<P>
   Although Tennessee has been averaging nearly 18,000 fans a home
game this season, only 9,907 _ easily a season low _ turned out at
Thompson-Boling Arena on Monday night to see Chamique Holdsclaw and
Kellie Jolly play their last home game. The Lady Volunteers rolled
in the second half to an 89-62 romp of Boston College, with
Holdsclaw tying her career high of 39 points. The low turnout
partly was because of a 9:30 p.m. starting time. But the NCAA
mandates an average ticket price of around $15 for tournament
games, and fans used to getting through the gates for $5 or less
might have decided to stay away.
</P>
<P>
   A number of schools did very well in their second-round games.
In addition to Connecticut, Iowa State had 11,719 for its win over
Oregon, Virginia Tech turned out 9,812 to see the Hokies defeat
Auburn, and Purdue brought in 9,501 to see the Boilermakers beat
Kansas.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia drew the poorest of the 16 host schools, with an
official crowd of 2,212 for Monday's 68-55 win over Southern
Methodist. The Lady Bulldogs still set a home attendance record
this season, averaging 3,199 for 14 games, including two in the
NCAA sub-regional.
</P>
<P>
   Sick of the Huskies?
</P>
<P>
   UConn is the Beast of the East, with its traveling media
entourage of 20 and regular coverage in the mainstream New York
media. But some coaches think that its national profile, as well as
that of Tennessee, crowds out almost everyone else.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's face it, ESPN is in Connecticut,'' Clemson coach Jim
Davis said.WOMEN'S NCAA TOURNAMENT
</P>
<P>
   EAST REGIONAL
</P>
<P>
   Saturday, at Greensboro
</P>
<P>
   Old Dominion (28-3) vs. Duke (26-6), 11:30 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee (30-2) vs. Virginia Tech (28-2), 30 minutes after the
first game.
</P>
<P>
   Monday: Semifinal winners.
</P>
<P>
   MIDEAST REGIONAL
</P>
<P>
   Saturday, at Cincinnati
</P>
<P>
   Connecticut (29-4) vs. Iowa St. (24-7), noon.
</P>
<P>
   Clemson (26-5) vs. Georgia (25-6), 30 minutes after the first
