<HEADER>
A2851 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NCAA-PROPOSITION16-CO     03-16 0513
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NCAA-PROPOSITION16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Judge declines stay in NCAA eligibility order
 &HT;    By Tony Barnhart
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NCAA schools have been left in a state of confusion over
freshman academic eligibility standards now that a Philadelphia
judge has refused to stay an order that the old rules discriminated
against blacks.
</P>
<P>
   On March 8, U.S. District Court Judge Ronald Buckwalter of
Philadelphia struck down the NCAA's Proposition 16, which does not
allow freshmen athletes to participate if they score lower than 820
on the SAT or 66 on the ACT. The NCAA asked for a stay of the order
so that some kind of academic guidelines would be in place while it
filed an appeal. On Tuesday Buckwalter said no and as of today
there are no minimum standards for incoming freshmen athletes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a mess, no doubt about it,'' said SEC Commissioner Roy
Kramer. ``Now we have to figure out what's the next step.''
</P>
<P>
   The very next step for the NCAA will be to continue the appeal.
The NCAA will seek a stay of Buckwalter's order from the Third
Circuit Court of Appeals but will appeal the case no matter what
the ruling.
</P>
<P>
   ``The NCAA's concern continues to be the welfare and protection
of student-athletes and the effect this ruling has on the
preparedness of freshmen for academics and athletics as they enter
Division institutions,'' said Cedric Dempsey, the executive
director of the NCAA. ``Our membership is left with many unknowns
about how to address eligibility standards.''
</P>
<P>
   The ruling creates numerous problems for the schools, but here
are just a couple:
</P>
<P>
   _ Technically, coaches will have no academic standard to use as
a guideline during the current spring recruiting period. In reality
they still have to use the old standard in case the NCAA eventually
wins on appeal.
</P>
<P>
   _ Freshmen athletes who were admitted to school this year but
were ineligible to play because they didn't meet the old standard,
are today technically eligible. But if the athlete participates in
one event, like this week's NCAA basketball tournament, he or she
forfeits a whole year of eligibility. And if the NCAA wins the
appeal, the school would have to forfeit the event in which the
athlete participated.
</P>
<P>
   ``My sense is that the judge never realized what kind of can of
worms he could open with this thing,'' said Kramer.
</P>
<P>
   The judge's ruling doesn't preclude the use of standardized test
scores, but does say there can not be a minimum score that cannot
be offset by other academic work. The NCAA Division I Board is
looking at a system that would allow a student to compensate for a
lower standardized test score with a higher grade point average on
13 college preparatory subjects.
</P>
<P>
   The NCAA's lawyers said this week that the earliest it could
establish new guidelines would be October. Other athletic officials
said it could happen sooner, given the urgency of the situation.
</P>
<P>
   Tony Barnhart writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
