<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-16 20:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2852 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WASTE-ECO-PARKS-ART-2     03-16 0964
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WASTE-ECO-PARKS-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WASTE BUSINESS BOOMS AS USES ARE FOUND 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., N.H., Miss., N.M.)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(dal) 
 By CLAUDIA H. DEUTSCH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Over a decade ago, Michael R. Daley was touring a plant that
burned old tires for energy when he learned that it paid haulers to
cart away gypsum, one of its byproducts. Daley was astounded:
Gypsum, he knew, is used in plaster, toothpaste, paints, even molds
for false teeth. So Daley set up shop near the plant to collect and
resell the gypsum.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, his company, Triad Energy Resources Inc., has grown
into a successful small enterprise, all by setting up next to
corporations and finding uses for their wastes. Triad makes soil
additives from the C &AMP; H Sugar Co.'s sugar-filtration byproducts in
Crockett, Calif. It turns leftover skins and seeds from Australian
wineries and fruit processors into fertilizer and compost. And it
is now contracting with fish processors in Oregon to turn their
detritus into fertilizer and fish food.
</P>
<P>
   ``If companies were smart, they'd all locate near sources of
waste,'' Daley said.
</P>
<P>
   Corporate America is, in fact, catching on. More and more
companies are buying their neighbors' wastes or selling their own.
And a growing number of economic development agencies and private
developers are building ``eco-industrial parks'' _ eco-parks for
short _ for this purpose.
</P>
<P>
   Some are doing it to attract jobs, others to reduce trash flows,
still others simply to make money. But all are working on the
principle that one company's waste can be its neighbor's raw
material. And they are taking advantage of the fact that many
wastes that cannot be recycled back to their original uses can
still be profitably used as materials for other products.
</P>
<P>
   ``A park that makes environmental and economic sense is an idea
whose time has come,'' said Dustin Bielagus, a developer who is
building an eco-park in Londonderry, N.H.
</P>
<P>
   Eco-parks are rising in Mississippi and Mexico. They are on the
drawing boards in Puerto Rico and Mesa del Sol, N.M. Dow Chemical
Co. is building one near its plants in eastern Germany.
</P>
<P>
   In California, local officials plan an eco-park in Oakland,
while the Cabazon Band of Mission Indians is looking for companies
to set up at its trash-to-energy plant near Palm Springs to extract
materials from the trash before it is burned.
</P>
<P>
   While the environmental movement spawned the idea of such
industrial symbiosis, it is no longer the primary force. ``People
realize that where materials are thrown out, there is money to be
made,'' said Kevin Taylor, coordinator of the California Materials
Exchange Program, a state group that brought Triad and C &AMP; H
together.
</P>
<P>
   There is money to be saved as well, added Reid Lifset, who edits
the Journal of Industrial Ecology. ``Companies are always looking
for cheaper ways to procure raw materials,'' he said, ``and the
more they hear about eco-industrial parks, the more light bulbs go
off.''
</P>
<P>
   The idea of selling and buying wastes is not new, of course. The
Environmental Protection Agency lists about 40
government-subsidized waste exchanges. But now more entrepreneurs
are becoming involved, charging companies for listing available
wastes or waste-product needs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Valuable waste materials should not be consigned to subsidized
exchanges whose funding can get cut,'' said William Sloan, who just
started Millennium Exchange Ltd., a for-profit, Web-based waste
exchange.
</P>
<P>
   Even the terminology reflects the private-sector thrust, said
Julie Rhodes, executive director of the Reuse Development
Organization, a clearinghouse for information about reusing
materials.
</P>
<P>
   ``People call them materials exchanges now, not waste
exchanges,'' she said. ``The whole idea is to think of waste as
having value.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, most existing exchanges ignore location when they match
waste sources with users. Factor in the cost of shipping waste, and
the economics of selling it becomes shaky. But put companies next
to one another, and the economics works.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a lot cheaper to transport used lumber from next door
than it is to truck wood down from a forest,'' said Ann Schneider,
director of recycling programs at the University of California at
Santa Cruz.
</P>
<P>
   That is the type of argument that the Energy Answers Corp., a
resource recovery specialist in Albany, is using to woo companies
to set up near the trash-to-energy plant it wants to install in Rio
Pedras, near San Juan, P.R. Patrick F. Mahoney, president of Energy
Answers, said he was close to persuading a paper company to reopen
an abandoned plant on the site because it could recycle waste paper
coming in and use cheap energy from the trash being burned. He said
he was also talking to steel and concrete companies about using
scrap steel from the trash and the fly ash that is left after
combustion.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can put the companies close enough to get the materials by
conveyor belt,'' Mahoney said.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the proselytizing, eco-parks are not an easy sell. When
a company is picking a site, a chance to lower disposal or
materials costs pales next to considerations like availability of
workers, taxes and nearness to customers. The sheer logistics of
figuring out the proper mix can be daunting.
</P>
<P>
   ``We thought we could handpick a perfect assortment of
businesses that would move right in, but it just doesn't work that
way,'' said Michael Krause, executive director of the Green
Institute, a nonprofit developer that just abandoned the idea of
using guaranteed waste exchange as a draw for an industrial center
it is building in Minneapolis.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   And even if the companies come, who is to guarantee that none
will move or change their products or go belly up?
</P>
<P>
   ``The minute one company changes its processes, the whole
industrial ecosystem gets screwed up,'' said Stuart L. Hart, a
professor of strategic management at the University of North
Carolina's Kenan-Flagler Business School.
</P>
<P>
   Not even environmentalists are unequivocal in their support.
Nancy B. Hirshberg, director of natural resources at Stonyfield
Farm Inc., fought to make waste exchange a requirement of the park
that Bielagus is building next to Stonyfield's yogurt plant in
Londonderry. But she is having second thoughts. ``Creating a market
for wastes could create a disincentive to eliminate them,'' Ms.
Hirshberg said.
</P>
<P>
   Bielagus acknowledges that his ideal tenant would generate no
waste. And Ned Hall, an executive vice president of AES Enterprise,
a company that operates power plants and will anchor the park, says
the park's green premise has not stopped local residents from
yelling, ``Not in my back yard.''
</P>
<P>
   All told, the numerous ifs and buts have created a Catch 22:
developers do not want to invest millions in setting up an eco-park
until they have successful models to follow, yet such models will
not dot the landscape until a few more pioneers take the plunge.
</P>
<P>
   ``It won't be a major trend until people see more good
examples,'' said Nabil Nasr, director of the National Center for
Remanufacturing and Resource Recovery at the Rochester Institute of
Technology.
</P>
<P>
   An example of sorts does exist in Kalundborg, Denmark, where
companies have been exchanging wastes for more than 20 years. But
Kalundborg was not built for that purpose; it had a lucky
confluence of companies that started to use one another's wastes
after environmental regulations banned their disposal methods.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kalundborg was a wonderful accident,'' said Edward
Cohen-Rosenthal, director of Cornell University's Work and
Environment Initiative.
</P>
<P>
   That accident may, in fact, have been replicated in Tampico,
Mexico, an industrial city in the Monterrey metropolitan area. Some
25 companies, all within a 40-mile radius, recently hired Bechtel
Corp.'s consulting arm to identify their wastes. Bechtel found 44
waste streams, and one chemical plant is already using a pigment
plant's waste ferric chloride as a water purifier, while a
manufacturer of industrial gases is exploring ways to use carbon
dioxide that is going up a smokestack.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are looking first to see what they can exchange among
themselves, and then for what kinds of companies they will woo,''
said Paul Worhach, a Bechtel senior engineer.
</P>
<P>
   Companies and developers in less industrialized areas do not
have that luxury. So they are plunging feet first into courtship.
</P>
<P>
   The Mississippi Economic and Community Development Department
recently wooed a power plant to its new Red Hills Ecoplex in
Choctaw County _ in the heart of lignite coal mining territory _ in
part by pointing out the availability of on-site coal and water.
</P>
<P>
   The plant will not start operating for two years, yet Robert T.
Smira, the agency's deputy director, said he is close to leasing
space to a brick maker that would use the clay left over from coal
mining. The mining company, which normally uses the clay to fill in
the holes its strip mines leave, will instead use the fly ash the
power plant spews out. More fly ash will go for building roads,
replacing the gravel that Choctaw now pays to haul in. And Smira is
also trying to interest a wallboard maker in the fly ash.
</P>
<P>
   That takes care of the solid stuff. Steady streams of water, at
various temperatures, flow in and out of power plants, too. The
eco-plex will have a greenhouse, a fish farm and a few food
processors, all either feeding water to the plant or taking it. The
greenhouse and a dry ice company will probably use the carbon
dioxide from the plant's stacks.
</P>
<P>
   That kind of everything-but-the-squeal setup attracted the AES
power plant to Londonderry. A sewage treatment plant nearby will
provide cheap water. Heated water coming out of the power plant
will be piped first to other factories that can extract some of the
heat, then back to the treatment plant. AES also expects to sell
steam it would otherwise vent to the air.
</P>
<P>
   In theory, it is an unbeatable system _ but no one knows how
many manufacturers will respond. Other eco-park developers feel
more comfortable casting a wider net for tenants, then offering
incentives for them to use one another's wastes.
</P>
<P>
   The Sustainable Technology Park Authority, a nonprofit
organization, is building an eco-park in Cape Charles, Va., that
welcomes any tenant that promises to operate along strict
environmental rules. As tenants move in, it will use lists of their
byproducts to woo others. But now it simply offers rent reductions
to companies that exchange wastes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We aren't setting up the whole park around that,'' said
Timothy E. Hayes, the agency's executive director. ``But we hope
that the availability of cheap materials will be an incentive to
come here.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
