<SLUG> BC-FBN-OWNERS-MEETINGS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Replay may finally win owners' approval
 &HT;    By Len Pasquarelli
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ Last year, as he walked into a session for the NFL
owners to decide the fate of instant replay, Mike Holmgren was a
man confident that proponents had the 23 votes necessary to
resurrect the system. But approval didn't happen.
</P>
<P>
   Holmgren thinks there are enough votes this year, but he's
taking nothing for granted.
</P>
<P>
   ``I about fell out of my chair (last year),'' Holmgren said.
``I'm taking nothing for granted. I know what everyone is saying,
but I'll believe it when I see them starting to put the
(television) monitors on the field.''
</P>
<P>
   Unless several owners are lying about their position on replay,
however, Holmgren has little to worry about this time around. A
spate of high-profile officiating gaffes during the 1998 season
seemed to convince all but the staunchest replay opponents that the
much-debated system is now a necessary evil.
</P>
<P>
   Although the annual meetings are running behind schedule _ some
agenda items slated for Monday morning weren't addressed until
Tuesday afternoon and committee sessions were going late into the
night _ the replay vote probably will be today. A straw poll
indicated only four teams opposed the system presented by the
committee. Two other teams are undecided. The addition of the
expansion Cleveland Browns means that replay needs 24 votes to be
approved, but most league officials think they have a vote or two
more.
</P>
<P>
   The system recommended by the committee is known as
challenge-based, with coaches able to review two plays per game. If
the original call is upheld, the challenging team is charged a
timeout. In the final two minutes of the second and fourth
quarters, replay can be triggered only by an official in a special
booth.
</P>
<P>
   Len Pasquarelli writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
