<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-TENNIS-NOTES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Inside pro tennis: U.S. tennis on comeback trail
 &HT;    By Todd Holcomb
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   When the new year broke, the USTA bragged that American-born
players had finished No. 1 on both pro tours for the first time
since 1981.
</P>
<P>
   The fact was, however, that American tennis had never looked so
bleak. There wasn't a young American without colored hair beads
showing any sign of matching Pete Sampras or Lindsay Davenport.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the picture has flipped. While Sampras and Davenport have
each been dropped to No. 2, American tennis is making an unforseen
comeback.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps it was veteran Todd Martin who led the charge. The
former No. 5 player fell out of the top 100 for a while in 1997
while battling shin and elbow injuries, but in the final five weeks
of last year, Martin went 14-4, losing three times to Sampras while
defeating five top-10 players. He's back at No. 10 after reaching
the quarters of Indian Wells, where he beat Marcelo Rios, and the
Australian Open.
</P>
<P>
   Another player presumed finished was Chris Woodruff, a top-30
player two years ago. Woodruff, 26, the former NCAA champ from
Tennessee, injured his right knee in December of 1997 while kicking
footballs with Richey Reneberg at Georgia Tech. He essentially sat
out 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Woodruff surged to the quarterfinals in Indian Wells
-- which actually had a stronger field than the Australian -- and
scored victories over Felix Mantilla, who had just beaten Sampras,
and sixth-ranked Tim Henman.
</P>
<P>
   Among young players, the USTA is most high on Jan-Michael
Gambill. A year ago, the 21-year-old came from outside the top 200
to beat Agassi, Henman, Mark Philippoussis and Alex Corretja, but
his appearance at the AT&AMP;T Challenge here last year revealed a
suspect clay-court game and net play.
</P>
<P>
   This year, his volleys have improved, and his two-handed
groundstrokes are among the biggest in the game. He's beaten Agassi
and Henman again, as well as Sampras this month in Scottsdale, in
becoming the only under-26 American with an ATP Tour singles title.
It propelled him to a career-high No. 31.
</P>
<P>
   On the women's side, Chanda Rubin has resurfaced after a 2
1/2-year slump that started with a hand injury just as she reached
No. 5 in the world. This year, she has beaten Martina Hingis and
was up a break in the third set on Steffi Graf last week. She's
back to No. 24.
</P>
<P>
   And finally, there's Serena Williams, on an 11-match winning
streak after titles in Paris and now Indian Wells, where she beat
Davenport and Graf. She's up to No. 16 and predicts that she'll be
there by the French Open in May.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T Challenge snags Woodies
</P>
<P>
   Jim Courier and Todd Woodbridge and Mark Woodforde, winners of
nine Grand Slam doubles titles, will play in the AT&AMP;T Challenge,
tournament owner ProServ announced Monday. The Woodies, who won the
Olympic gold medal for doubles in Atlanta, have won 53 career
doubles titles, the most of any active team. . . . The USTA Women's
Challenger of Norcross begins Sunday with qualifying at Racquet
Club of the South. Great Britain's Samantha Smith, ranked No. 55,
is the highest-ranked player in the field.
</P>
<P>
   New No. 1 not a fluke
</P>
<P>
   There are some misconceptions about Carlos Moya, the new No. 1
player on the ATP Tour. One is that he's just a dirt-baller.
Although the reigning French Open champion won two-thirds of his
matches on clay last year, he is proven on hardcourts, as well. He
has made the semifinals or better of the U.S. Open, the Australian
Open and the ATP Tour Championship. Granted, he was a first-round
loser at the Australian this year. It's also easy to forget that
Moya is a young, physically imposing player. He's the youngest
top-10 player at 22, just 2 1/2 months older than No. 11
Philippoussis, and he's 6-foot-3, 177 pounds. Sampras is listed at
only 6-1, 170. Moya is the first Spanish No. 1.
</P>
<P>
   Todd Holcomb writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
