<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-MCDONOUGH-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NFL OWNERS GIVE THE NOD TO THE JETS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By WILL MCDONOUGH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ He has a strong presence at these NFL meetings, but
the remarkable thing is, he is not here.
</P>
<P>
   There is no doubt the large shadow of Bill Parcells is hanging
over the American Football Conference.
</P>
<P>
   You could hear it in the voices of his peers Tuesday morning,
when the AFC coaches had their annual breakfast with the media as
part of the league meetings.
</P>
<P>
   Parcells was back on Long Island, continuing to retool his New
York Jets. The other AFC coaches were here, with their owners, even
though most of them would rather not be.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Jets will be the team to beat this year,'' said Jimmy
Johnson of the Miami Dolphins. ``Not only in our division, but in
all of football. I think they are as strong as any team in the
league.
</P>
<P>
   ``You put that playoff game they had in Denver (the AFC
Championship game) on a neutral field and I think you might have
seen a different result.''
</P>
<P>
   The Jets' AFC opponents agreed on one point: New York should be
the favorite to repeat as AFC East champion, in a year that the
division figures to be as tough as it ever has been.
</P>
<P>
   ``A year ago, we were sitting here at this same breakfast saying
New England was the team to beat, and they were,'' said Buffalo
Bills coach Wade Phillips. ``But all of that has changed. The Jets
have a heck of a football team, and they've done some good things
in the offseason to make them better. Wherever they felt they had a
problem last year, they went out and tried to fix it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Our division is going to be right there with the best,'' said
the Indianapolis Colts' Jim Mora, ``but the Jets will have the best
chance going in. They've done a good job there the last couple of
years putting a very good football team on the field.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just look at our division. The quarterbacks. Marino in Miami.
Bledsoe in New England, Flutie in Buffalo, Testaverde in New York,
and Peyton (Manning) with our team. Every team has the guy you need
to win, the quarterback.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess you would have to say that the team that won it a year
ago is the team to beat,'' said the Patriots' Pete Carroll. ``And
they've improved themselves. Steve (Atwater) should really help
them out. That became a salary cap thing for the Broncos, and they
couldn't keep him. Tom Tupa will help their punting, and this kid
Roman Phifer they picked up from the Rams is a good linebacker.
They're going to be tough.''
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, New England was picked as the team to beat, but of
the five teams in the AFC East, it seems to have slipped the most,
while the rest have improved.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're a good football team,'' said the Bills' Phillips. ``We
could have easily won 12 ballgames last year. Some games got away
from us at the end that easily could have been ours. But I guess
you could say that we won some that maybe we should have lost.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to have a better football team,'' said Johnson of
his Dolphins. ``We had a meeting last week in Miami and we had one
of these independent talent evaluators that we pay come in and take
a look at what we have done in our personnel, and size up with what
the other teams have done picking talent the last couple of years.
He thought we had done an excellent job, drafting fine football
players in the draft, and that the Jets had done a good job picking
up players in free agency.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson nearly quit at the end of last season, and when he
decided to come back, he promised he would take more time for
himself. But he already reneged on that.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm putting just as much time into it as I did before,'' said
Johnson. ``At the time I said I need more time off, I felt that
way. Then I took a little vacation and didn't go to some of the
bowl games. All the while I was away, I kept thinking I should be
at these games looking for more talent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year was the first time in my coaching career that I ever
felt that way at the end of a season. I didn't handle it well. Now
I'm back to where I was. This is what I want to do. I'm enjoying
it.''
</P>
<P>
   All of these coaches know that the most important thing next
season is finish with the best intradivision record. The Patriots
were 7-1 two years ago and won it. The Jets were 7-1 last year and
won it. This year, it will be hard for any team to get that good a
division record, but the one with the best figures to be standing
on top of the heap when the year is over. And right now, it looks
as though the championship banner once again might fly over the
Evil Empire to the South.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Will McDonough is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
