<SLUG> BC-MEDICARE-REFORM-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEDICARE REVAMP PANEL DISBANDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By AARON ZITNER AND ALEX PHAM  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Amid sharp philosophical divisions, a federal panel
charged with finding a way to stave off a financial crisis for
Medicare disbanded Tuesday after failing to gather enough votes to
make any recommendations to Congress.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, President Clinton, who had appointed four
members to the 17-member panel, said he will issue his own proposal
to revamp Medicare, which is due to run into severe financial
problems within a decade.
</P>
<P>
   Panel members, who include lawmakers and health policy
specialists, Tuesday fell one vote short of the 11 needed to
approve a plan to allow more Medicare beneficiaries to switch to
private health plans, with the government subsidizing the cost of
their premiums.
</P>
<P>
   Formed a year ago by Congress, the panel had been considered the
best hope to build momentum behind a bipartisan effort to
restructure Medicare, which now provides health insurance to 39
million senior citizens and disabled Americans. Despite the
commission's impasse, the panel's cochairman, Senator John Breaux,
Democrat of Louisiana, vowed to file legislation that would write
the panel's plan into law.
</P>
<P>
   The eight Republicans on the panel, joined by two Democrats,
supported the proposal, while all four of President Clinton's
appointees to the commission, and three Democratic lawmakers
opposed it. The partisan nature of the vote suggested that Medicare
reform could become a bitter issue in Congress during upcoming
elections. Democrats have made gains in past elections by arguing
that Republicans want to injure the popular health program.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking at the White House Tuesday, Clinton said the
commission's approach runs the risk of raising premiums for those
in the traditional Medicare program. He also criticized the
proposal for raising the age of eligibility to 67, from 65 today,
``without policy to guard against increased numbers of uninsured
Americans.'' He also said the commission's proposal to pay
prescription drug costs for poor beneficiaries did not go far
enough.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said he had instructed aides to begin work on a White
House Medicare plan that would use 15 percent of the projected
federal budget surplus to shore up the program and help fund a
broad prescription drug benefit. ``It is now incumbent on me to
present an alternative proposal . . . I'm going to do my dead-level
best to get it done,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Medicare is expected to run out of money as early as 2008, just
as millions of baby boomers begin to hit retirement age.
</P>
<P>
   Commission Republicans Tuesday sought to lay blame for the
deadlock on Clinton, whose four appointees voted against the plan.
Senator Phil Gramm (R-Texas), accused Clinton of passing up a
chance to achieve bipartisan consensus on reforming Medicare. ``We
have a president who had the opportunity to change American history
on Medicare, and he didn't have the courage to act,'' said Gramm.
</P>
<P>
   Breaux said he will introduce legislation based on the proposal
he unsuccessfully pushed before the commission. Breaux's proposal
would gradually raise the eligibility age for Medicare from 65 to
67 over 24 years; add prescription drug coverage for poor
beneficiaries who earn up to 135 percent of federal poverty
guidelines; require all Medicare supplemental insurance policies to
offer limited prescription drug benefits; shift a $3.6 billion
annual subsidy to the nation's medical schools from the Medicare
budget to the general federal government budget; and reduce
payments to hospitals and doctors.
</P>
<P>
   The most controversial element of the Breaux proposal, however,
is likely to be its plan to create a private market for health
maintenance organizations and other insurers to care for the
elderly. The government would pay 88 percent of the premium for
private coverage, while beneficiaries would pay the rest.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents of the proposal have argued that it will create a
two-tiered system where the poor can afford only inferior coverage
while the rich will be better off.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
