<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SURVIVORS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Survivor: `I could feel the heat'
 &HT;    By Anne Rochell Konigsmark
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOURBONNAIS, Ill. _ Jo Ann Lyons was eating a steak and a baked
potato Monday night in the dining car of Amtrak's City of New
Orleans train as it headed toward a stop in Kankakee, Ill., when
she heard a crash. The next thing she knew, her dinner was all over
her clothes, she was covered with glass and she was under the
table, trapped.
</P>
<P>
   ``My husband and I were just sitting there when everything
crashed to the ground, the cups and glasses,'' said Lyons, 62, a
retiree from Slidell, La. ``I was the last one they got. I was
blessed.''
</P>
<P>
   Lyons and her husband, Ray, were on a multitrain vacation around
the United States when the train that was supposed to take them
home slammed into a truck Monday night on a dark stretch of tracks
near Bourbonnais, Ill., 50 miles south of Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 196 passengers and 20 Amtrak employees on board, about 20
were teenagers from Clinton, Miss., and their chaperones returning
from a spring break ski trip to Quebec.
</P>
<P>
   One of the teenagers suffered a back injury, and three of the
chaperones were hospitalized, but no other serious injuries were
reported to group members.
</P>
<P>
   Jo Ann Lyons suffered broken bones, including a broken pelvis
that will keep her in traction for six weeks at St. Mary's Hospital
in Kankakee. Ray Lyons, 64, has a crushed chest and was in
intensive care Tuesday morning.
</P>
<P>
   As Jo Ann Lyons waited for rescuers to pry her out from under
the table, she realized other cars were on fire.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could smell the smoke, I could see the flames, I could feel
the heat,'' she said. ``I thought that was it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Lyons' trip began March 10 in San Antonio, Texas. From there
they traveled to Los Angeles, then north and finally east. The 19
1/2-hour trip from Chicago to New Orleans was to have been the last
leg of their trip.
</P>
<P>
   The worst part of the crash, Lyons said, was when she was
carried out of the train.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was cold, and dark, and scary,'' she said. ``There were
people crying. I hope I don't have to stay here. I want to go home
to Slidell.''
</P>
<P>
   Anne Rochell Konigsmark writes for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
