<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-TALKS-710&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SERBIAN TANKS ROLL INTO KOSOVO, THREATENING PEACE TALKS 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By CRAIG R. WHITNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ The Kosovo peace effort was on the verge of collapse
Tuesday as Serbia moved heavy tanks and thousands more troops into
the province at the same time that Serbian negotiators here
insisted on extensive changes to a draft peace agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Officials in Washington warned that the Serbs seemed to be
``bracing for war'' instead of preparing for peace with about
30,000 Serbian troops now in or poised near the province. The heavy
Yugoslav M-84 tanks that rolled into the province, in violation of
previous pledges, were the first to be seen in Kosovo in at least
five months, according to cease-fire monitors who began their
mission last October.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to raising new complaints about the content of the
peace agreement, Serbian negotiators here showed no signs of giving
in on their objection to a 28,000-member NATO peacekeeping force on
Serbian soil to police the accord.
</P>
<P>
   ``We shall sign the political agreement if they accept our
suggestions,'' the Serbian president, Milan Milutinovic, said on
emerging Tuesday afternoon from the French conference center, a
former hotel that was the German occupation headquarters during
World War II. The talks resumed there on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   But international mediators rejected any substantive changes to
the agreement. ``The talks are over,'' a Washington policymaker
said as Clinton administration officials convened a meeting to
discuss the next steps after the talks end, possibly as early as
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   As the talks faltered, the fighting in Kosovo continued Tuesday
in violation of an October cease-fire.
</P>
<P>
   French Foreign Minister Hubert Vedrine, co-chairman of the talks
with British Foreign Secretary Robin Cook, accused the Serbs of
backtracking and warned: ``The moment of truth is not far away.''
</P>
<P>
   The NATO allies have threatened to launch wide-scale bombing of
Serbian military targets unless the Yugoslav president, Slobodan
Milosevic, accepts the agreement. The Kosovo Albanian delegation to
the talks said on Monday that it was prepared to sign the accord as
negotiated in the first phase of the talks last month in the French
chateau of Rambouillet.
</P>
<P>
   Though the Albanians reacted warily when the international
mediators said they were willing to make ``technical adjustments''
to the agreement to get the Serbs to sign, and though some Albanian
commanders in Kosovo are threatening to keep fighting for
independence, the Serbs are now seen to be the main problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are today going back on certain aspects they appeared to
have accepted at the end of the Rambouillet negotiations, and they
still totally refuse civil and above all military guarantees on the
ground,'' Vedrine said of the Serbian side in a report to the
French Parliament this afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Another official close to the talks said that the Serbs had
demanded changes in up to 70 percent of the agreement, which would
provide political autonomy to the largely ethnic Albanian majority
population of Kosovo and commit NATO peacekeepers for a three-year
transition period. Alliance officials discussed military
peacekeeping arrangements with the Albanian delegates Tuesday
morning.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will come back and continue trying to get engagement going
Wednesday,'' said Philip T. Reeker, the chief spokesman for the
talks. ``The negotiators, with the full agreement of the contact
group, have reminded the Serb delegation and Milutinovic that only
technical adjustments could be considered, and that the purpose of
this meeting is simply to discuss implementation.''
</P>
<P>
   But the United States, Britain, France, Germany, Italy and
Russia, the six ``contact group'' countries that convened the
talks, have showed signs of disunity this week on the peacekeeping
force, which would be largely European and commanded by a British
general, with 4,000 American troops in a backup role.
</P>
<P>
   The five Western countries, all NATO allies, have insisted that
no settlement would mean anything without armed peacekeepers to
enforce it. But French officials have indicated that the
peacekeepers might not necessarily have to be an integral part of
NATO, and Russian officials in Brussels have said Russian soldiers
would only participate if a Russian general shared command.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Russian reporters covering the talks here said that the Russian
mediator, Boris Mayorsky, had told them Monday night that Moscow
had never approved the part of the draft agreement providing for
peacekeepers.
</P>
<P>
   The draft says that peacekeepers would separate the Serbian
military and police forces from the armed Albanian rebels, oversee
the withdrawal of all but 1,500 Serb troops from the province
within a year and provide security for Kosovo's two million people
until a new international conference convenes in three years to
decide whether the province should remain a part of Serbia.
</P>
<P>
   But according to an official who had seen the Serbian proposals
for changes, Milosevic was not prepared to accept provisions that
would allow the ethnic Albanian population to form its own police
force using former independence fighters.
</P>
<P>
   Nor would the Serbian proposals accept the draft's guarantee
that the more than 200,000 people displaced by a year of violent
clashes be allowed to return to their homes, the official said. The
Serbs also reject the idea that the international war crimes
tribunal in The Hague has a right to investigate the possibility of
war crimes in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``Paradoxically, their position could solidify the contact
group,'' an official said. ``Nobody can say the Serbs are being
reasonable and just want minor changes.''
</P>
<P>
   If the talks end in an impasse, a real possibility according to
their French hosts, it would probably take NATO about a week to
gear up for bombing. More than 400 American and European warplanes,
including American B-52's, stand ready to launch attacks against
selected Serbian military targets in Kosovo and beyond, and then to
destroy all of Serbia's sophisticated air defenses, if ordered into
action by the alliance's top civilian official, Javier Solana, the
secretary general.
</P>
<P>
   But officials in Brussels said he would only give the go-ahead
if he decided that there was a broad consensus that the Serbs were
the main obstacle to an agreement and that bombing might get
Milosevic to change his mind. Western embassy staffs would probably
be evacuated from Belgrade before any bombs started falling,
officials say, and the 2,000 civilian observers who have been in
Kosovo since last fall would also be brought out.
</P>
<P>
   Western officials charge that Serbia has blatantly violated the
terms of the Oct. 13 cease-fire agreement that provided for the
observers. Tuesday, monitors in Pristina, the capital of Kosovo,
said they had seen Yugoslav tanks and soldiers headed toward
fighting south of the city.
</P>
<P>
   Russia has always opposed any use of force to bring about a
settlement in Kosovo. Alliance officials in Brussels say that
bombing would probably wreck the attempts NATO has made to build a
constructive relationship with Russia since the end of the Cold
War.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
