<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NKOREA-NUKE-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. AND NORTH KOREA REACH ACCORD ON NUCLEAR INSPECTIONS 
</HEADLINE>
 (ART ADV: Graphic map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(wg) 
 By DAVID E. SANGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ After months of negotiations, North Korea agreed
Tuesday to allow the United States to inspect a huge underground
site that Washington suspects is the center of a renewed effort to
build atomic weapons.
</P>
<P>
   The deal includes some modest commitments by the United States
to continue food aid to North Korea, and to begin a pilot project
to help it grow potatoes to end to a famine that by some estimates
has led to the starvation of more than 3 million people in the last
few years. But the agreement leaves a number of issues still
unresolved.
</P>
<P>
   Chief among them is North Korea's continuing development of
ballistic missiles, some of which it has sold to Iran and Pakistan,
among other nations. Last week, former Defense Secretary William J.
Perry, who is conducting a complete review of American policy
toward North Korea, said that the country's ``long-range-missile
program itself suggests in parallel the development of a nuclear
weapons program.''
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, there are continuing suspicions, but no explicit
evidence, that North Korea may be hiding other elements of its
nuclear research and development program. And nothing in this
agreement requires the North to suspend test shots of its missiles,
like the one it sent over Japan last August that led Tokyo and the
Washington to press for the development of a missile defense system
in the Pacific.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's nuclear accord is the second the United States has
reached with North Korea since the two countries came perilously
close to military conflict in June 1994. The State Department
spokesman James Rubin said the latest accord would permit repeated
and regular American visits to the remote, mountainous site called
Kumchangri, about 25 miles Northwest of Yongbyon, the nuclear
research center that has been under constant inspection by the
International Atomic Energy Agency for five years.
</P>
<P>
   The American visits to the underground facility, which are
scheduled to start in May, would mark the first time the North has
allowed inspection beyond Yongbyon. They may be doing so because
the underground site was detected so early that it is still a huge
whole in the ground, with no signs that equipment has yet been
installed. The agreement permits regular visits after the initial
inspection, until the United States concludes that the facility
poses no threat.
</P>
<P>
   North Korea continues to deny that the site is intended for the
nuclear research or production, though in the negotiations they did
say it was designed for ``a sensitive military purpose.''
</P>
<P>
   The White House hopes that the accord will also quell a rising
movement in Congress to cut off fuel oil shipments to North Korea.
Under the 1994 accord, the United States committed itself to
provide 500,000 tons of oil to the North for a number of years, in
return for Pyongyang's agreement to freeze activity at the Yongbyon
plant, which appeared at the time to be only four or five months
away from producing five or six nuclear weapons.
</P>
<P>
   But Congress never provided more than partial funding for the
shipments. The future of the nuclear accord was thrown into further
peril last summer after intelligence reports about the existence of
the underground site surfaced in news articles.
</P>
<P>
   The site at Kumchangri was difficult to hide from American
satellites: thousands of North Korean military workers were
swarming over it each day, excavating a huge area under a mountain.
The shape of the excavation led experts to tentatively conclude
that the North's goal was to re-create the nuclear processing
facilities under round-the-clock inspection at Yongbyon.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans in Congress accused the State Department of
attempting to suppress news of the North Korean activity, and
charged that the huge new underground site proved that the North
Korean military was seeking to rebuild its bomb-making capacity at
a new, secret installation.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-16-99 2015EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990316.0296 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-16 20:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2880 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NKOREA-NUKE-ART-2TAKE     03-16 0504
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NKOREA-NUKE-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
  
 WASHINGTON: secret installation. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Politically, Tuesday's accord allows the administration to
certify to Congress in coming weeks that the North continues to
comply with the 1994 accord. Without that certification, Congress
would almost certainly have cut off the fuel oil, a move the
Pentagon feared would lead North Korea to resume its production of
plutonium, and create a new confrontation similar to the one that
led to the movement in the spring of 1994 of B-2 bombers and
anti-missile defenses to South Korea.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think we've contained an effort to break out of the
agreement,'' an American official said.
</P>
<P>
   The negotiations that ended Tuesday were led by Charles Kartman,
a longtime State Department expert on Korea, and by Kim Gye Gwan,
North Korea's vice foreign minister and a longtime interlocutor
with the United States on North Korea's nuclear projects.
</P>
<P>
   For months the talks were stalemated, with the North Koreans
initially demanding a $300 million payment by the United States for
a one-time visit to the nuclear site.
</P>
<P>
   ``We refused repeatedly to provide the kind of direct
compensation that they were seeking,'' said Rubin, the State
Department spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   But over months of talks, the more Kartman talked about access
to the site, the more the North Koreans talked about food aid. And
in the end, what they got was a promise that the current American
food aid program, which the State Department insists is for humane
reasons and is unrelated to the nuclear agreements, would continue.
</P>
<P>
   State Department officials said that a consortium of American
groups would announce the details of the potato program in coming
days, and that the Agency for International Development would
provide about 100,000 tons of food aid for North Korea to
compensate for the loss of crops during the two seasons it will
take to get a full potato harvest.
</P>
<P>
   That increase, though, has already aroused some critics of the
administration's policy. Rep. Benjamin A. Gilman, R-NY, who heads
the House International Relations Committee, said Tuesday, ``I am
concerned that the administration had to provide almost 600,000
tons of food aid to gain that access'' to the nuclear site.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is distressing that the North Koreans and other rogue
nations may begin charging the United States for ensuring
compliance with their international agreements,'' Gilman said.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, in a lunch with reporters, Perry declined to say
whether he would recommend more food aid in return for further
agreements with the North, particularly on missile proliferation.
But he talked at length about the human cost of the starvation
there, including stunted and orphaned children, and said that
making food aid a ``quid pro quo for achieving our aims'' was ``a
perfectly reasonable policy that I'm open to considering.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a country so weak that it could not fight a sustained
war,'' Perry said. ``But it is also a country so desperate that it
could lash out.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-16-99 2015EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
