<HEADLINE>
FINDINGS HELP BOLSTER COLLISION THEORY OF MOON'S ORIGINS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By MARK CARREAU 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Recent measurements of the moon's core bolster an
Apollo-era theory that the satellite formed from material ripped
away when the Earth was hit by a large object, planetary scientists
reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Readings taken by NASA's Lunar Prospector suggest the iron lunar
core comprises less than 4 percent of the satellite's total mass,
and perhaps less than 2 percent. The Earth's iron core comprises
about 30 percent of the planet's total mass.
</P>
<P>
   The unmanned, $63 million Lunar Prospector mission was launched
Jan. 6, 1998, and became the first NASA spacecraft to reach the
moon in more than 25 years.
</P>
<P>
   Past analysis of the lunar rocks and soil gathered in the late
1960s and early 1970s by the Apollo astronauts revealed a mineral
composition that suggests the moon and the Earth had a similar
origin. If they formed independently from the same materials,
though, the ratio of their cores to total mass should be
equivalent. Differences in their cores might suggest otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a critical finding in helping scientists determine how
the Earth and moon formed,'' said Alan Binder of the Phoenix-based
Lunar Research Institute, Prospector's chief scientist.
</P>
<P>
   Alex Konopliv of NASA's Jet Propulsion Laboratory in Pasadena,
Calif., presented the core measurements, made by gravity sensing
instruments on the probe, at this week's Lunar and Planetary
Science Conference at the Johnson Space Center in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Konopliv's findings and those of Lon Hood, a University of
Arizona researcher who is taking magnetic readings of the moon with
Prospector, place the diameter of the moon's core at between 140
and 280 miles.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of the collision theory believe the moon formed when
the Earth was hit about 4.4 billion years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``This impact occurred after the Earth's iron core had formed,
ejecting rocky, iron-poor material from the outer shell into
orbit,'' Binder theorized. ``It was this material that collected to
form the moon.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
