<HEADER>
A2883 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRAINWRECK-COX     03-16 0845
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAINWRECK-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Truck driver in Amtrak wreck held probationary license
 &HT;    By Anne Rochell Konigsmark and Marlon Manuel
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOURBONNAIS, Ill. _ The driver of a flatbed truck struck by an
Amtrak train in rural Illinois on Monday night, leaving at least 13
people dead and 119 injured, was driving with a probationary
license after three traffic violations last year, Illinois
authorities said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators in Bourbonnais, where the second-worst accident in
Amtrak's 27-year history occurred, said John Stokes of Manteno,
Ill., told them he didn't see any warning signals at the crossing
and tried to get out of the way of the oncoming train.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators were looking into whether the signal might have
malfunctioned, although emergency crews arriving shortly after the
accident said the warning lights were blinking and the gates were
partially down.
</P>
<P>
   Rescuers continued to search for at least three people presumed
to be missing, focusing primarily on a double-decker sleeping car
near the front of the train that was crushed and burned in the
derailment.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the Illinois secretary of state's office
confirmed that Stokes, 58, was driving on a probationary license
after he received three speeding tickets within a year. He was
scheduled to have his driver's license suspended Jan. 25, but got
the probationary license after completing a four-hour safety class.
</P>
<P>
   Cy Gura, a safety engineer with the National Transportation
Safety Board team, said the driver told investigators he didn't see
the train or flashing warning lights until he had already started
driving his truck, loaded with steel, across the tracks.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's very sad and upset. He felt he did whatever he thought he
could do to clear the train track but he didn't do it,'' Gura said.
</P>
<P>
   Amtrak officials said 196 people had bought tickets on the City
of New Orleans train, but it was unclear whether all had actually
boarded, leading to confusion about how many people might be
missing. The New Orleans-bound train also carried 18 crew members
and two off-duty Amtrak workers.
</P>
<P>
   Passengers included about 20 teen-agers and their chaperones
from Clinton, Miss., who were returning home from a ski trip to
Quebec.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, reports indicated 14 people had been killed, but a
National Transportation Safety Board official said at a news
conference Tuesday afternoon that the number of confirmed deaths
stood at 13.
</P>
<P>
   The City of New Orleans, a train made popular in the 1970s by a
song by that name recorded by Arlo Guthrie and written by Steve
Goodman, had been scheduled to arrive in New Orleans at 3:30 p.m.
Tuesday. The No. 59, as it also is known, makes a daily run from
Chicago with stops in Champaign, Ill., Memphis, Tenn., and Jackson,
Miss., among others.
</P>
<P>
   As emergency crews worked into the night Tuesday to find those
believed missing, hundreds of townspeople gathered to watch.
</P>
<P>
   The train departed Chicago at 8:03 p.m. Monday, three minutes
behind schedule. For reasons not immediately known, the train lost
35 minutes between Chicago and Homewood, where it arrived at 9:21
p.m., Amtrak officials said. The train left Homewood at 9:26 p.m.
bound for Kankakee. About 8 miles north of the station, the 14-car
train and its two locomotives struck a flatbed tractor trailer
truck loaded with steel used used to reinforce concrete.
</P>
<P>
   The cause of the accident was a ``truck in the wrong place at
the wrong time,'' said Randy Myers, an official with the
Bourbonnais Fire Department.
</P>
<P>
   Flashing lights and crossing gates were operating when emergency
personnel arrived at the scene of the collision in Bourbonnais,
Myers said.
</P>
<P>
   The truck was leaving a nearby Birmingham Steel Co. yard, though
receptionist said the driver did not work for the company. The
Associated Press identified the driver as John R. Stokes, 58, of
Manteno.
</P>
<P>
   Clark Garchwait, a manager at Blain's Farm and Fleet, a retail
hardware store the length of a football field away from the
accident, said the area is a combination of light industry and
farms.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rebar seems to be the biggest industry here,'' Garchwait said.
</P>
<P>
   In the song ``The City of New Orleans,'' Arlo Guthrie sings
that:
</P>
<P>
   ``The train pulls out at Kankakee/Ross along past houses, farms
and fields.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That would be pretty much what the area is like,'' said
Garchwait, who returned Monday to the store, which had been used as
a triage area. ``It is very flat. It's a cash crop area. Corn.
Soybeans.''
</P>
<P>
   The temperature was about 40 degrees with light snow on the
ground that had no effect on the accident, investigators said.
</P>
<P>
   The Riverside Medical Center treated 46 passengers. Thirty-four
were treated and released and 12 remained with more serious
injuries.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many were sleeping, totally relaxed and then tossed about,''
said Mary Thomson , a Riverside spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
   Konigsmark and Manuel write for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
