<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-16 20:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2884 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IRELAND-U.S.-AHERN-NY     03-16 0792
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRELAND-U.S.-AHERN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IRISH LEADER WHO GREW INTO ELOQUENCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: This story was eliminated earlier but has been restored.) 
(dal) 
 By JAMES F. CLARITY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DUBLIN, Ireland _ When he was campaigning for election as prime
minister in 1997, Bertie Ahern was disdained by many voters and
politicians as a lightweight who had risen from the working class
of Dublin and still spoke with a distinct North Side accent, which
turned ``th'' sounds into D's.
</P>
<P>
   He lacked gravitas, his detractors said, and would be something
of an embarrassment representing Ireland among better-spoken
presidents and prime ministers.
</P>
<P>
   Ahern acknowledged with some humor that he had trouble
pronouncing words like ``growth'' and brushed up his diction. He
won the election, narrowly, and when he meets President Clinton at
the White House on St. Patrick's Day, accompanied by Celia Larkin,
his partner of 10 years, his better-spoken opponents will be back
here, restless and relatively powerless in the parliamentary
minority.
</P>
<P>
   Ahern, whose tongue rarely fails him now, ignores what his
supporters call ``the chattering classes'' of Dublin 4, an affluent
and well-educated section on the South Side.
</P>
<P>
   When he returns home next week, Ahern, 47, may be on the verge
of making Irish history as the prime minister to preside at the
completion of the Northern Ireland peace agreement and the official
end to 30 years of sectarian violence in the predominantly
Protestant British province.
</P>
<P>
   But he may also be forced out of office and into an early
election by a growing corruption scandal involving some of his
allies in the Fianna Fail (Warriors of Destiny) Party.
</P>
<P>
   Before he left Dublin last week, he sounded distinctly
statesmanlike on the peace effort, saying:
</P>
<P>
   ``If the new agreement succeeds, it will see the two traditions
working together both in Northern Ireland and on the island for the
first time in 200 years. Every right-thinking person wants to see
the back of conflict for good and to create a new and happier
future for all.''
</P>
<P>
   Back home nobody is worrying about his accent or about the fact
that he is not married to his partner, Ms. Larkin. His 10-year
relationship with Ms. Larkin, a former Fianna Fail worker, has
never become a serious political issue here. But his other
political problems are real.
</P>
<P>
   To form a coalition government in 1997, he needed the support of
the smaller Progressive Democrats Party. The prospects for a full
five-year term were good. The economy was booming, and in a month
Ahern had helped broker a cease-fire by the Irish Republican Army.
</P>
<P>
   That paved the way for the accord in April to give minority
Roman Catholics in Northern Ireland added power and to give
overwhelmingly Catholic Ireland added influence in the affairs of
Northern Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   Then late last year, Ahern was suddenly reminded that political
trouble was as easy to find as the rain. Some of his party's most
prominent elected officials were accused of having taken huge
bribes from executives.
</P>
<P>
   One businessman, former Prime Minister Charles J. Haughey, who
had fostered Ahern's career and once called him ``the most devious
and cunning of them all,'' was shown to have amassed wealth,
impossible on an elected official's salary, including horses, a
yacht, a farm and his own island off the coast.
</P>
<P>
   Haughey, according to sworn testimony, had received nearly $3
million from Dunnes, the largest chain of department stores in the
country.
</P>
<P>
   His coalition partner, Mary Harney, leader of the Progressive
Democrats, which split from Fianna Fail 14 years ago over
corruption, said she might quit the government. That would lead to
an election well before the constitutional deadline of mid-2002.
</P>
<P>
   The majority of Irish people appear to believe that although
Ahern is personally honest and lives modestly, he must answer for
the past corruption of his party. Many people apparently feel that
as a high party official, and a professional accountant, he had to
have had some knowledge of what Haughey and other colleagues were
up to.
</P>
<P>
   A political consultant and a former ranking Foreign Ministry
official, Fergus Finlay, said to survive Ahern might have to find
another coalition partner in the next election.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bertie Ahern,'' Finlay said in an interview, ``has made a
genuine effort to clear up his party's act and turn Fianna Fail
into an organization other parties can do business with. But he's
trying to do all that without confronting the ghosts of his party's
past. And that's a recipe for failure.''
</P>
<P>
   Ahern would, of course, disagree. In the midst of the
disclosures about some of his former allies, he said: ``I am a
credible person. I am an honest person.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
