A2886 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JEWELL-SOURCES-COX     03-16 0546
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JEWELL-SOURCES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Reporters told to reveal sources
 &HT;    By Jay Croft
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The judge in Richard Jewell's defamation suit against
The Atlanta Journal-Constitution again Tuesday ordered reporters to
name sources for articles about the former Centennial Olympic Park
bombing suspect.
</P>
<P>
   Fulton County State Court Judge John Mather originally ruled
last April that the journalists must identify law enforcement
officials who gave them information about Jewell. But the
newspaper's attorneys refused. And Jewell's lawyers asked the judge
to rule in Jewell's favor without a trial and to hold the
newspaper's attorneys in contempt.
</P>
<P>
   Mather declined to do either Tuesday, but Lin Wood, Jewell's
lead lawyer, praised the latest court order and blasted the
newspapers for holding back information on sources.
</P>
<P>
   The newspaper's attorney, Peter Canfield, was out of town
Tuesday and could not be reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   Mather gave reporters 60 days to reveal sources or face possible
civil contempt, which can include being jailed until they name
names. The newspaper could appeal a contempt order if one is
issued.
</P>
<P>
   The Journal-Constitution was the first news organization to
report that Jewell was being investigated in the July 1996 bombing
that killed one woman and injured 111 people. The former security
guard at first was hailed as a hero for spotting the knapsack that
held the bomb. Months after the Games, he was cleared of any
wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
   Jewell sued the Journal-Constitution in January 1997, claiming
he was libeled ``in a series of false and defamatory articles which
portrayed him as an individual with a bizarre employment history
and an aberrant personality who was likely guilty.''
</P>
<P>
   Wood has said he is seeking tens of millions of dollars in
damages.
</P>
<P>
   The newspaper has insisted its reporting was fair and accurate.
Canfield said last year that disobeying the first court order was
essential for appeals. Further, the sources would be hurt if the
newspaper names them, Canfield said.
</P>
<P>
   Mather wrote Tuesday that he ordered the newspaper to name
sources ``in the interest of revealing the truth'' and said the
refusal to do so has complicated ``what is, in essence, a simple
case.''
</P>
<P>
   Mather wrote that reporters are not protected from naming their
sources when the reporters are parties to a lawsuit or criminal
case.
</P>
<P>
   That privilege extends only when reporters are not directly
involved in the case. Mather cited a March 8 state Supreme Court
decision that he said supports ``what is apparent'' in state law.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our press enjoys no greater constitutional freedom under our
First Amendment than any citizen,'' Mather said. ``A member of the
press . . . may not adhere to only those directives of the court
which conform to their subjective interpretations of the law.''
</P>
<P>
   Wood said Mather was giving the journalists a ``final
opportunity to obey the law'' before imposing ``extremely harsh''
penalties.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't test the accuracy and reliability (of the newspaper's
reporting) unless we talk to the sources,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Jay Croft writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution, Atlanta,
Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
