<HEADER>
A2888 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BAPTISTS-LYONS-COX     03-16 0751
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BAPTISTS-LYONS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Lyons resigns as Baptist leader
 &HT;    By Mike Williams
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. PETERSBURG, Fla. _ With a prison term looming for his
conviction on racketeering charges, a tearful Rev. Henry Lyons
apologized to African-Americans Tuesday and resigned as president
of one of the nation's largest black Baptist denominations.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to say to St. Petersburg, to Florida, to black
Americans all over this country that I'm just so sorry about all of
this,'' Lyons said, his voice choking with emotion. ``I'm truly
regretful. I hate that I hurt so many people.''
</P>
<P>
   Lyons, 57, was convicted two weeks ago in a Florida state court
of stealing some $4 million from corporations that wanted to do
business with the National Baptist Convention USA. Prosecutors
convinced an all-white jury that he spent much of the money on
luxury items for himself and three alleged mistresses. He faces up
to seven years in prison on the state charges.
</P>
<P>
   He is also due in court today on separate federal charges that
include extortion and income tax evasion. He is expected to accept
a plea bargain in hopes of winning a reduction in the 18-20-year
federal prison term he could face.
</P>
<P>
   Lyons tendered his resignation to the convention's board of
directors at a special meeting at his St. Petersburg church.
Although all but three of the 230 board members voted to keep him
as president, Lyons insisted on stepping down.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt I had to resign, I should resign and I did resign,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the board members stood steadfastly by Lyons throughout
his two-year ordeal, insisting he was a victim of
racially-insensitive media investigations.
</P>
<P>
   Their support didn't waiver with Lyons' resignation, as the
group discussed a motion to continue paying Lyons his $100,000 per
year salary for the next five years. The matter was referred to a
committee for further consideration.
</P>
<P>
   The board's vice president, the Rev. Stuart Cureton of
Greenville, S.C., was elevated to serve the remaining months of
Lyons' five-year term, which expires in September. But a scramble
to succeed Lyons in the powerful post began immediately, with
several candidates handing out press releases outside Lyons'
church.
</P>
<P>
   About two dozen opponents of Lyons held a news conference
outside the convention's headquarters in Nashville calling for a
new convention constitution to ensure that Lyons' successor be more
accountable. ``We will never again be subjected to one-man rule,''
said the Rev. Kenneth Whalum, minister of Mount Olive Baptist
Church in Memphis.
</P>
<P>
   The resignation caps a tumultuous scandal that began when Lyons'
wife set fire to a $700,000 waterfront home that Lyons had
purchased with Bernice Edwards, his co-defendant in the state trial
and the former director of public relations for the convention.
</P>
<P>
   Edwards was acquitted of all state charges, but still faces
federal charges of income tax fraud and extortion.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors in the state trial took several weeks to lay out
their case against Lyons, tracing a trail of huge checks from
credit card, insurance and funeral service companies that wanted
access to the convention's membership list.
</P>
<P>
   Lyons agreed to provide the list even though he knew there was
no such document and that ministers would be extremely reluctant to
release their rolls even to the convention, prosecutors argued.
</P>
<P>
   The paper trail also showed the money went for furs, jewelry,
expensive cars and other luxury items, which Lyons bought for
himself, his family, Edwards and two women who testified they had
affairs with him.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps most condemning was evidence that Lyons took most of a
$250,000 donation from the Anti-Defamation League, a Jewish group,
that was intended to rebuild black churches burned in a string of
arsons.
</P>
<P>
   Lyons later repaid that money, but by then criminal
investigations were well under way.
</P>
<P>
   Lyons gave his first extensive interview since his conviction to
ABC Television's Connie Chung Monday night. He apologized in the
broadcast, saying he felt he had ``disgraced the black community
and black America.''
</P>
<P>
   He also admitted spending the money on luxuries, saying ``I was
like a kid at the fair, and just wanted to go out, touching and
tasting everything, kind of running without a great deal of control
in my life.''
</P>
<P>
   Mike Williams writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-16-99 2021EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990316.0303 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-16 20:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2889 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUSSIA-NUKE-2NDTAKE-N     03-16 0791
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-NUKE-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 MOSCOW: were continuing. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Strapped for cash and eager to maintain a modicum of cooperation
with Washington, Iran is just one issue where the Russians are
hoping for a breakthrough.
</P>
<P>
   A compromise has already been worked out concerning 16 advanced
IBM computers the Russians obtained in 1996 in violation of
American export controls.
</P>
<P>
   The Russians obtained the IBM computers using Moscow-based
middlemen and installed them in the closed nuclear city of
Arzamas-16, a design center for Russia's nuclear arsenal.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration initially asked that the computers be
returned. Under the compromise, the computers have quietly been
moved from a military site to a civilian site within the closed
city: a building used by Sberbank, a government bank.
</P>
<P>
   The IBM computers are to be used for civilian purposes, such as
the development of commercial software, according to the new
arrangement.
</P>
<P>
   The compromise plan was overseen by Siegfried Hecker, the former
director of the Los Alamos National Laboratory, who visited Russia
to help put it in place.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe there will be sufficient access, physically or
electronically, to assure ourselves that the computers are for
civilian use,'' Hecker said in a telephone interview.
</P>
<P>
   American officials hope to work out a similar arrangement for an
SP-2 IBM computer, which American officials suspect has also been
delivered to Arzamas, to be used in a high-performance computer
system from Silicon Graphics, which is at the Russian nuclear
design center at Chelyabinsk.
</P>
<P>
   There has been progress on other some fronts, as well. Russian
and American officials hopes to conclude arrangements that would
facilitate the sale to international companies of billions of
dollars worth of low-enriched uranium derived from Russian nuclear
warheads. Negotiations were conducted in 1993 but an agreement has
been thwarted by commercial and legal problems.
</P>
<P>
   The Russian government has also made encouraging statements
about the need to pass the START-2 treaty, slashing strategic arms.
</P>
<P>
   Iran, however, has been the most contentious issue, and the
Russians are eager to see the sanctions lifted. If they are not
removed, the sanctions would deprive Nikiet of several million
dollars worth of work, a considerable setback for the cash-poor
institute.
</P>
<P>
   ``The contracts which we have had have been suspended,'' Adamov
complained. ``Those which were prepared have not been signed, and
the partners who work with us are scared and are avoiding
discussions.''
</P>
<P>
   The United States, however, also has an interest in resolving
the issue. Nikiet, which designed the type of reactor involved in
the accident at Chernobyl, is working to improve the safety of
Russia's nuclear power complex, a task Washington has supported.
</P>
<P>
   One American-financed project that was suspended as a result of
the sanctions involves the installation of the special display
system in Russian reactors to help pinpoint the cause of a nuclear
accident.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Energy Department officials have been so worried about the
safety implications that they secretly appealed to the White House,
asking that some exceptions be made to the sanctions so that
important safety work could go forward, American officials said.
</P>
<P>
   (OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</P>
<P>
   Russia has also taken some steps to cut off contracts on the
sale of missile technology to Iran, but much more needs to be done,
American officials said.
</P>
<P>
   One big issue is whether Nikiet has, in fact, stopped its
contacts with Iran, as Adamov contends it did.
</P>
<P>
   Explaining the past contacts, Adamov said Nikiet had prepared a
contract for the sale of a research reactor to Iran. The Mendeleyev
Institute, he insisted, has provided some basic unclassified
information to Iran on heavy water technology, while recommending
that Iran purchase a light-water reactor.
</P>
<P>
   Adamov said the Russian government had rejected his proposal to
sell the research reactor to Iran and that Nikiet no longer has
dealings with the Iranians. That, he insisted, should lay the basis
for an agreement in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do believe in American pragmatism,'' Adamov said. ``This is
a chance to check if these people are pragmatic, though I am afraid
of some angry people in the State Department. They are somewhat
narrow-minded.''
</P>
<P>
   A senior American official said that Washington needed to
confirm that the contacts had really been broken off before
sanctions were lifted.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not going to accept this on face value,'' the official
said. ``They will have to provide assurances that they have really
cut this relationship off. There is a lot of heavy lifting to do
between now and the Primakov meeting.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
