A2892 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PATIENTS-RIGHTS-NYT &LR;      03-16 0837
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PATIENTS-RIGHTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CURBS ON MANAGED CARE STILL DIVIDE TWO PARTIES
</HEADLINE>
   (dal) 
 By FRANK BRUNI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Of the issues likely to draw serious attention from
Congress this year, managed health care would seem to be
particularly ripe for action. Republicans and Democrats agree that
Americans need guarantees of better treatment from health plans and
that most voters would applaud steps in that direction.
</P>
<P>
   But to say the two parties have that much in common is not to
say they see eye to eye. As lawmakers begin anew this year to try
to craft _ and, perchance, to pass _ a patients' bill of rights,
many of the same obstacles that tripped them up in previous years
again stand in their path.
</P>
<P>
   The parties remain split by philosophical differences about how
extensively the federal government should regulate insurers, who
are poised to marshal at least as many millions of dollars and
hundreds of lobbyists to block the legislation as they have in the
past.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps just as significant, members of both parties are already
engaged in intense political gamesmanship, each side intent on
snaring credit for any bill and suspicious of the other's desire to
actually enact a law.
</P>
<P>
   When a Senate committee headed by James Jeffords, R-Vt., starts
hammering out the details of a bill on Wednesday, the degree of
consensus and the depths of division between the parties should
become abundantly clear.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is the first test of the new Congress on health care,''
Sen. Edward M. Kennedy of Massachusetts said after that panel, the
Committee on Health, Education, Labor and Pensions, held a hearing
into the issue last week.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy, the committee's senior Democrat, said that the steps
the majority Republicans had proposed were pathetically
insufficient and that Democrats would try to amend any Republican
bill that failed to do enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're enacting a law,'' Kennedy said at the hearing, ``not a
sieve.''
</P>
<P>
   Foreshadowing the friction to come, Jeffords offered a droll
retort. ``It looks like we'll have an interesting markup next
week,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans and Democrats alike have introduced comprehensive
bills, and Kennedy and other Democrats will use the committee
process this week to try to tweak the Republican effort under
consideration so that it incorporates provisions and language
favored by Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican and Democratic bills give patients expanded ways
of appealing an insurer's refusal to cover treatments, promote the
ability of patients under managed care to use the nearest emergency
room and permit doctors to discuss with patients their full range
of options.
</P>
<P>
   But while Republicans would leave initial judgments about the
medical necessity of treatments in the hands of health maintenance
organizations and other insurers, Democrats would empower patients'
doctors to make those decisions, subject to some federal
guidelines.
</P>
<P>
   And while the Democrats' plan would apply to all Americans with
private insurance, the Republican bill would affect only the
covered employees of fully self-insured companies. In addition, the
Democrats would make it easier and more fruitful than under current
law for patients to sue managed care providers for denial of
treatment. Republicans oppose such a liability provision,
forecasting an increase in the expense of health coverage that
might force businesses to scale back what they offer employees.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe the best thing we can do is make sure a patient is
cured,'' Jeffords said in an interview. ``They'd rather have a good
lawsuit.''
</P>
<P>
   In the House, some of the same points divide Democrats and
Republicans, but a slightly different contest is taking shape.
While Democrats and some Republicans are pushing for a
comprehensive bill, the Speaker, J. Dennis Hastert, has tentatively
signaled an interest in passing a series of more limited bills that
isolate specific proposals.
</P>
<P>
   Although Hastert has not fully committed to that approach, aides
said that by teasing out those aspects on which both parties agree,
he could make sure that some legislation passes, inoculating House
Republicans against charges of do-nothingism.
</P>
<P>
   But even some members of Hastert's own party dislike that
strategy.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem is, we'll run out of time before we get to the
hard parts,'' said Rep. Charlie Norwood, R-Ga., who has introduced
a comprehensive bill similar to Democratic proposals. ``And if we
don't get to any of the hard parts, you're not going to get any
congratulations for the easy parts.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite their disagreements, many Republicans and Democrats have
expressed real hope for legislation this year, tracing their
optimism to the early beginning of the debate. But they must get
past the logjams inevitably created by addressing any issue as
intricate as this.
</P>
<P>
   ``They say it takes seven years to produce legislation that is
complex,'' Norwood said with an audible sigh. ``This is complex,
and we're only in our fifth year.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
