<SLUG> BC-BRAZIL-ECON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRAZIL STOCKS DEFY RECESSION'S DAMAGE
</HEADLINE>
   (dal) 
 By SIMON ROMERO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAO PAULO, Brazil _ After spending much of 1999 so far
straddling the line between pessimism and panic, Brazilian markets
are staging a cautious rally that may be the first sign the
economy, Latin America's largest, is starting to creep its way out
of recession.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, the benchmark Bovespa stock index, the main
barometer of investor sentiment, moved into positive territory
measured in U.S. dollar terms. And when measured in the Brazilian
currency, the real, stocks have risen 57 percent in two and a half
months.
</P>
<P>
   The last two days have been notable, with the Bovespa index
gaining 8.77 percent on Monday and a further 2.35 percent on
Tuesday, to close here at 10,658.39.
</P>
<P>
   The real, which spent much of January and February battered by
concern over a possible return in Brazil to the turbulent times of
hyperinflation, has strengthened nearly 15 percent in the last two
weeks to settle in New York Tuesday at 1.87 to the dollar.
</P>
<P>
   The improvement is partly the result of investor optimism after
pledges by foreign financial institutions to renew credit lines
totaling about $23 billion to Brazilian borrowers over the next six
months. The foreign banks acted after pleas by the new president of
this country's central bank, Arminio Fraga, a former fund manager
for George Soros.
</P>
<P>
   Lending rates, though, remain extremely high by world standards.
On Tuesday, Bloomberg News reported, the overnight futures contract
for May rose to 42.06 percent from 41.49 percent on Monday. Bonds
were mixed, with the widely traded C bond yielding 16.04 percent.
</P>
<P>
   But the signs that inflation may not be accelerating as fast as
once feared have helped alleviate some investor concerns. ``We're
witnessing a shift in sentiment from very dark forecasts to a
scenario of a long, slow recovery,'' said Octavio de Barros, chief
economist here for Banco Bilbao Vizcaya. De Barros, like most other
economists at large banks, said he saw the brunt of Brazil's
economic difficulty occurring in the first half of the year, with a
recovery, if an anemic one, starting late this year or early in
2000.
</P>
<P>
   Banks' willingness to keep lending to some companies came on the
back of an endorsement last week by the International Monetary Fund
of the government's plan to narrow the budget deficit. The IMF
agreed to provide a $9.3 billion installment from its $41.5 billion
aid package, some of which the central bank can spend to combat
currency speculation. ``There's a realization in the markets that
the recession we're experiencing is preparing us to emerge
stronger, with a more vibrant export sector and improved public
accounts,'' said Fernao Bracher, president of Banco
BBA-Creditanstalt, in a telephone interview from Paris.
</P>
<P>
   The Brazilian currency, though recently improved, has lost 35
percent of its value since the government abandoned market support
for it two months ago. Yet the severity of the recession brought on
by devaluation is one of the main reasons why some analysts foresee
resumed growth so soon. Dampened activity _ with economists
forecasting output to shrink as much as 6 percent in the first
quarter _ should translate into lower consumer demand for most
goods, keeping inflation in check.
</P>
<P>
   The likelihood that inflation will not gallop out of control, as
it did in the early '90s, when price increases of 60 percent a
month were common, allows consumers and companies to plan with more
certainty. The government's pledge not to let salaries be regularly
adjusted for inflation provides additional assurance, said Julio
Ziegelmann of BankBoston.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it is too early to tell whether the new-found optimism on
trading floors foretells any change in the bleak economic reality
that many Brazilians are expected to confront in coming months.
</P>
<P>
   Unemployment, hovering near a record at 8.4 percent, is seen
rising as high as 10 percent in the next few months. And according
to a study by Marcio Pocmann, an economist at the University of
Campinas, per-capita income should fall 6.4 percent this year,
steeper than declines in recessions in the '80s and early '90s.
</P>
<P>
   ``The stock market is not that accurate an indicator,'' said
Guido Mantega, an economist affiliated with the opposition Workers
Party. ``People are getting poorer.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
