<SLUG> BC-RENO-COUNSEL-LAW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RENO TO ANNOUNCE OPPOSITION TO RENEWAL OF INDEPENDENT COUNSEL LAW 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By DAVID JOHNSTON and DON VAN NATTA Jr.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Attorney General Janet Reno has decided to announce
at a Senate hearing on Wednesday that the independent counsel
statute is ``structurally flawed'' and should be abandoned, a
striking reversal from her past embrace of the 21-year old
Watergate-era reform law, government officials said on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``After much reflection, we have decided reluctantly to oppose
reauthorization of the act,'' said a final draft of written
testimony that Reno had prepared to deliver at a Senate
Governmental Affairs Committee hearing.
</P>
<P>
   During her six years as attorney general, Reno's position on the
law has hardened as she tried to carry out the statute, and she has
come to view it as rigid, unwieldy and unfair, law enforcement
officials said. In a more personal sense, Reno's shift on the law
illuminates a rite of passage for the Miami prosecutor who was
tossed with little preparation into the brutal combat over politics
and law in the nation's capital.
</P>
<P>
   The officials said Reno had often watched in frustration and
anger at what she viewed as serious prosecutorial abuses committed
during inquiries led by several independent counsels, including
Kenneth Starr, and had concluded that some of these investigations
had spun out of control.
</P>
<P>
   More than any other single issue, the debate over independent
counsels has defined Reno's tenure at the Justice Department. The
law requires Reno to refer cases to outside counsels, chosen by a
three-judge panel, whenever there are specific and credible charges
of criminal wrongdoing against any one of about two dozen top
officials in the executive branch of government, including the
president and vice president.
</P>
<P>
   At first, some of Reno's aides hoped the law might work as it
was designed to keep the Justice Department out of political
controversies. Instead, the aides said the law has had the opposite
effect, repeatedly plunging Reno into raw partisan battles that
left her deeply scarred and undercut her image of integrity.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there was just a constant frustration on her part as
she tried to apply the statute, which she came to view as nothing
more than a rigid set of rules that sometimes defied common
prosecutorial sense,'' said one former Justice Department official,
who spoke on condition of anonymity. ``That frustration was
compounded by the fact that some of the special prosecutors that
were appointed ended up taking a very simple, narrow issue and
turned it into a long, drawn-out investigation that often seemed to
stray from the original mandate.''
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, for the first time, Reno will publicly express her
dissatisfaction with the law, echoing themes voiced two weeks ago
by her deputy, Eric H. Holder Jr. He announced at a House hearing
that the Justice Department was opposed to renewing the statute
when it expires on June 30. Holder said that cases now referred to
independent counsels could be handled by career prosecutors at the
Justice Department.
</P>
<P>
   In applying the statute, which gives the attorney general the
sole authority to decide whether an independent counsel should be
appointed, Reno has found herself buffeted between Republicans in
Congress and Democrats in the Clinton administration. Republicans
hammered her for what they viewed as bias in her refusal to refer
to an independent counsel the swirl of campaign finance issues that
arose from the 1996 Clinton re-election campaign.
</P>
<P>
   But Democrats also expressed unhappiness and frustration with
Reno. They complained that she timidly acquiesced to Republican
demands when she sought appointments of independent counsels to
investigate Cabinet officers like Mike Espy, the former agriculture
secretary; Henry Cisneros, the former housing secretary; Alexis
Herman, the former energy secretary; Bruce Babbit, the interior
secretary, and Ron Brown, the commerce secretary who died in a
plane crash in Croatia.
</P>
<P>
   Initially, Reno endorsed the law. When she testified before the
Senate Governmental Affairs Committee in May 1993, she strongly
urged Congress to renew the legislation. She said that it was
preferable for disinterested, outside prosecutors, free from the
taint of politics, to conduct investigations of high-level
administration officials.
</P>
<P>
   ``While there are legitimate concerns about the costs and
burdens associated with the act, I have concluded that these are
far, far outweighed by the need for the act and the public
confidence it fosters,'' Reno testified.
</P>
<P>
   Reno quickly discovered that the law provided little respite
from political controversy. In July 1994, one day after President
Clinton signed the bill reauthorizing the law, Reno asked the
appointing panel of three appellate judges to reinstate Robert B.
Fiske Jr., who had been selected by Reno as chief Whitewater
prosecutor.
</P>
<P>
   Aides at the time said Reno was surprised and dismayed when the
three-judge panel dumped Fiske and instead appointed Starr. ``She
thought a good deal of Fiske,'' the former Justice Department
official said. ``There was no question that in our mind Fiske was
independent, and we did not think it was necessary for Starr to be
appointed.''
</P>
<P>
   A month after Starr took over the Whitewater inquiry, the panel
named Donald C. Smaltz to investigate Espy. Reno's decision to seek
an independent counsel in that case was a highly technical one
because there was no evidence that Espy had performed any favors
for the gifts he was accused of accepting from companies regulated
by the Agriculture Department, law enforcement officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Reno and her aides assumed that Smaltz's inquiry would be
concluded in a matter of months. But Smaltz built up a large
prosecutorial office and, in August 1997, his prosecutors charged
Espy in a 39-count indictment.
</P>
<P>
   Reno was deeply displeased by Smaltz's tactics, the officials
said, concluding that no career federal prosecutor would have ever
subjected Espy to such scrutiny. In December 1998, four years after
Smaltz's appointment, a jury acquitted Espy of all charges.
</P>
<P>
   Reno became especially frustrated with Starr's tactics as the
Lewinsky investigation progressed. Reno, and several senior Justice
Department lawyers, the officials said, became troubled by what
they viewed as possible violations of Justice Department guidelines
by Starr's prosecutors, from his decision to require Secret Service
agents to testify before a grand jury to allegations of leaks of
grand jury material to reporters. She has now decided to
investigate those tactics.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-16-99 2033EST &QL; 
