u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LONNIEHOLLEY-BJT-ADVI     03-16 0389
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LONNIEHOLLEY-BJT-ADVISORY-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   The following stories are part of four-part series on Lonnie
Holley, the Alabama folk artist who has endured nothing but trouble
since he was one of the stars of the Olympic Arts Festival in 1996.
Holley, one of the South's most important folk artists, has known a
world of trouble in his 49 years. But nothing has prepared him for
the random misfortunes that have bedeviled him like Job over the
past couple of years. This is a story about a man who has struggled
against great odds to make his art and to keep his family together.
</P>
<P>
   All stories moving Wednesday. WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   Please call Cox News Service at 404-526-5456 if there are any
questions.
</P>
<P>
   LONNIEHOLLEY-PART1 _ COLUMBIANA, Ala. _ We start with Holley's
arrest, then back up and tell the story of how he got there.
(Auchmutey, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) 90.
</P>
<P>
   LONNIEHOLLEY-PART2 _ HARPERSVILLE, Va. _ We look at Holley and
his family and their current troubles. Holley has raised five
children by himself, and by all accounts did a great job against
the odds. But in recent years, his kids have had all manner of
problems. And it could get worse. (Auchmutey, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) 58.
</P>
<P>
   LONNIEH0LLEY-PART3 _ BIRMINGHAM, Ala. _ We look at Holley's
career in the context of the world of folk art. The reasons for
folk artists' struggles are complicated but the results are the
same: renowned, respected artists who wouldn't qualify for an auto
loan. We also look at the efforts of various dealers and do-gooders
to help him and his family. (Auchmutey, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) 50.
</P>
<P>
   LONNIE-HOLLEY-PART4 _ We sort out the endings, happy and
otherwise. The first good news, it seemed, Holley had gotten in
years was that juvenile authorities had been so impressed with
Holley's 16-year old son Kubra that they took it upon themselves to
nominate him for the Alabama School of Fine Arts, a magnet program
in Birmingham for gifted children from across the state. While
oldest son Ezekial appears headed for prison, and third son A.J.
for juvenile boot camp. And Holley? He'll probably plead guilty to
reduced charges and get probation, and he's finally painting again.
(Auchmutey, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) 30.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
