<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-16 20:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2909 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRAIN-CRASH-ART-2TAKE     03-16 1071
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAIN-CRASH-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
13 KNOWN DEAD, 114 HURT, 4 MISSING IN AMTRAK CRASH 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ill., Miss., La., Minn., Fla., Ala., Md.)  (See also TRAIN-SCENE, TRAIN-SAFETY) 
(ART ADV: Photos are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Graphic/locator map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By PAM BELLUCK   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOURBONNAIS, Ill. _ They were just settling in for the night,
comfortably ensconced in the first-class double-decker sleeper car
of a train with a famous name, The City of New Orleans. They had
boarded in Chicago, just 90 minutes before, and their train, its
legend celebrated in a popular American folk song, was due to pull
into New Orleans in the late afternoon of the next day.
</P>
<P>
   But in a single horrifying instant, everything changed. At 9:55
p.m. CT Monday, Amtrak's City of New Orleans smashed into a
semi-trailer truck at a railroad crossing in this rural town about
55 miles south of Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   By Tuesday afternoon, 13 passengers had been found dead, all of
them in the sleeper car. Officials said Tuesday night that four
people were unaccounted for. There were no signs they were alive.
</P>
<P>
   In what was being called one of the worst accidents in Amtrak's
history, the train derailed and the first five cars were mangled,
twisted like empty soda cans. Flames burst out, visible from miles
away.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not sure at this point I can collect my thoughts enough to
tell you what was going through my mind,'' said Michael
Harshbarger, chief of the tiny Bourbonnais fire department. ``I
don't think I've ever seen anything quite like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Officials were releasing few details about the dead, whose
bodies were being kept in an old lumber company warehouse turned
makeshift morgue. They confirmed, however, that four of those
killed were a woman, her grandchild and two other children, all
from Nesbit, Miss.
</P>
<P>
   The woman, June Bonnin, was a cancer survivor in her late 40s
who had opened a bed and breakfast with her husband while she was
still recovering. She was traveling with her granddaughter, Jessica
Whitaker, 12, two of the girl's friends and her daughter, so that
the girls could shop in Chicago at a store that carried American
Girl dolls and their accessories, which feature historic details.
The daughter, Ashley Bonnin, who is Jessica's aunt, was injured in
the crash and hospitalized in Kankakee, a few miles south of here.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Bonnin was among 114 people who were injured, at least 11
critically, authorities said. They were rescued along with the rest
of the train's surviving 216 passengers and crew members. Among
those passengers was a group of 20 teen-agers from Mississippi and
their chaperones, returning from a ski trip to Canada.
</P>
<P>
   The truck driver, who was driving on a probationary permit after
his license had been suspended because of speeding tickets, was
heading east across the train tracks when the train hit. His truck
was packed with heavy steel bars from a nearby steel factory. He
was routinely treated and released, officials said. The collision
shattered the trailer section of the truck.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of the day Tuesday, rescue crews that had rushed here
from miles away were still combing through the tangled metal,
hampered by piles of crushed debris and the need to make sure the
wreckage would not shift and endanger the rescuers themselves.
</P>
<P>
   The once-gleaming sleeper car had been slammed up onto one of
the train's two locomotives. It was broken down the middle and
ravaged by fire, Harshbarger said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The interior is filled with debris from the fire, and it's
necessary to search through that debris to find victims,''
Harshbarger said. ``It's simply a matter of digging with the gloved
hand, turning pieces of debris over in order to find someone.''
</P>
<P>
   Don Allen, 80, who was traveling with his wife from their home
in Winona, Minn., to visit their son in Florida, described the
frightening confusion of the accident.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was this violent jerking motion and all of a sudden we
just stopped and the lights went out,'' said Allen, who was riding
in one of the last of the train's 14 cars and had just settled down
to read a book. He heard a loud, grating noise and then, he said,
``All we could see was the smoke.''
</P>
<P>
   The crash was one of the deadliest in Amtrak's 26-year history.
The worst was a 1993 crash that killed 47 people when a train
plunged into a bayou near Mobile, Ala. In 1987, two trains collided
near Chase, Md., killing 16.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators from the National Transportation Safety Board
arrived Tuesday morning. In addition to investigating the accident,
the board will coordinate efforts to help the families of the dead
and injured, as it does after plane crashes.
</P>
<P>
   The truck driver, John Ralph Stokes, 58, of Manteno, Ill., a
town near the accident site, had had his commercial driver's
license suspended in January because he had received three speeding
tickets in 12 months, said David Druker, a spokesman for the
Illinois secretary of state's office.
</P>
<P>
   However, since this was Stokes' first suspension, he was able to
take a safety class and receive a temporary probationary permit.
Barring any problems, he would have received his regular license
back on March 25.
</P>
<P>
   ``The man was driving legally,'' Druker said.
</P>
<P>
   Kenneth Wykle, the administrator of the Federal Highway
Administration, said the agency would investigate the
safety-compliance record of the company Stokes was driving for,
Melco Transfer Inc. of Peotone, Ill.
</P>
<P>
   No one answered the door or the telephone at Stokes' house on
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier Tuesday, Cy Gura, a safety engineer with the National
Transportation Safety Board, told The Associated Press that Stokes
had told authorities that he did not see the train or warning
lights until he had already started driving across the tracks.
Later Tuesday afternoon, safety board officials would not confirm
that account.
</P>
<P>
   Amtrak's chairman, Wisconsin Gov. Tommy Thompson, held a press
conference Tuesday to say that he had been briefed on the
investigation and believed that the truck driver was trying to beat
the train by driving around the crossing gates.
</P>
<P>
   ``The engineer said he saw the lights flashing, he saw the
barriers down, and then he saw the truck stop and try to get around
it,'' Thompson said.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Illinois Central Railroad, which manages the
railroad crossing, said the crossing was equipped with gates, two
signal lights and a bell, which were functioning properly Monday
night, based on an analysis of a computer chip that records the
previous 3,000 times the crossing equipment functions.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have every confidence that they were working last night,''
said the spokesman, Jack Burke. He said the blinking lights begin
to flash five seconds before the gates come down, and that the
gates start to come down about 26 seconds before the train gets to
the crossing. He said it would not have been possible for the truck
to get trapped by the closing gates, because the gates would have
hit the truck and broken.
</P>
<P>
   There have been three previous fatal accidents at this railroad
crossing, in 1964, 1968 and 1988. State officials say that is a
relatively good safety record, given the number of trains that
cross the intersection _ about 40 a day, traveling at speeds
between 25 and 79 mph.
</P>
<P>
   Jolene Molitoris, administrator of the Federal Railroad
Administration, said Tuesday that the crossing was considered a
good intersection. The agency's records indicate that the road
crossing the tracks is angled to give drivers a clear view of
oncoming trains.
</P>
<P>
   A City of New Orleans train passes this way every night, pulling
out of Chicago at about 8 p.m. It makes a few stops in Illinois,
stops in Memphis, Tenn., and virtually turns into a local train in
Mississippi, until it reaches New Orleans at 3:30 p.m. the
following day. Another City of New Orleans train makes the same
trip in reverse every day.
</P>
<P>
   The City of New Orleans was the main northbound train of the
great black migration from the South in the 1940s and 1950s. And it
was celebrated in a folk song written by Steve Goodman and made
famous by Arlo Guthrie. The song croons about men dealing cards in
the club car, mothers rocking their sleeping babies and the train
``passin' towns that have no names, freight yards full of old black
men, and the graveyards of rusted automobiles.''
</P>
<P>
   The chorus _ ``Good Morning America, how are you?'' _
memorialized the romance of the railroad age.
</P>
<P>
   The modern-day City of New Orleans is a comfortable ride,
especially in the sleeping car, where passengers have a
``hospitality hour,'' a morning paper delivered to them, and a
24-hour on-call attendant who can ``order you a night-cap if
wished,'' Amtrak's literature says.
</P>
<P>
   National Transportation Safety Board officials said they had
interviewed the truck driver and the train engineer and sent the
train's black box to Chicago to be analyzed. They plan to retest
the crossing gates and lights and the sensor on the tracks that
trips the gates.
</P>
<P>
   They said the investigation was complicated by the presence of
two cars on the side tracks, one full of steel and the other full
of furnace residue from a steel plant. The cars had been struck in
the derailment and were making the search for evidence more
difficult.
</P>
<P>
   Also, for the first time in a railroad accident, the safety
board deployed a counseling team to work with the survivors, an
approach adopted after a fatal airline crash in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, in a stiff winter wind, rescue workers clambered on
top of the up-ended and fractured train cars, searching for any
glimpse of the missing.
</P>
<P>
   Some had worked all night, helping the survivors.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people were coming off the train searching for their
family members,'' said Karen Brzezicki, a firefighter and paramedic
for the Bourbonnais Fire Department who was one of the first
workers on the scene. ``That was the hardest part, people searching
for their children. This is one of those things you don't want to
see and you hope you never have to see again.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
