u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MINORITY-INVESTING-CO     03-16 0565
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MINORITY-INVESTING-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Online magazine targets minorities
 &HT;    By Tammy Joyner
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ During her 20-plus years as a broker, Deardra
Green-Campbell said she rarely saw minority investors and often had
to explain how the stock market worked and what investments would
be best for them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I spent three quarters of my time educating clients,'' the
investment consultant said recently. The 1993 U.S. Census Bureau
survey of household assets estimated only 6 percent of blacks and
Hispanics own stocks or mutual funds.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been unable to find anything updated, so I would have to
make the assumption that not much has changed.''
</P>
<P>
   Campbell hopes to make improvements to those numbers.
</P>
<P>
   She launched an online investment magazine this month to help
blacks, Hispanics, native Americans and other neophyte investors
navigate the stock market, considered one of the greatest
wealth-building sources around.
</P>
<P>
   The site (http://www.investedmagazine.com) debuted March 1 and
is believed to be the first of its kind.
</P>
<P>
   ``What sets us apart is our educational approach to the
market,'' said Campbell, who conducts seminars and classes on
investing. ``Most of the (educational investment) sites make the
assumption that the reader has at least a basic understanding of
the markets. We don't. Everything we write is designed to help the
reader understand the concept or strategy we're presenting, but
also how to apply that concept or strategy to their personal
life.''
</P>
<P>
   As a black woman, ``investment education is something I'm
personally and professionally committed to,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   As a former vice president at Charles Schwab and Dreyfus Service
Corp., Campbell said, ``I know that investment returns are what
have made a lot of the wealth in this country. But in order to be
successful at investing, you have to understand the market and how
to balance investment returns with investment risks.''
</P>
<P>
   People not used to investing ``often don't understand that risks
can be managed and as a result ... we shy away from market-type
investments, and then we miss out and instead settle for 2.5
percent from the local banks,'' Campbell said.
</P>
<P>
   Minorities have made tremendous economic strides this decade,
Campbell noted in her first ``From the Editor's Desk'' article on
the Web site. She cited a recent University of Georgia study that
found during the past nine years, the after-tax income for black
people rose 73 percent, outperforming the 56.7 percent gain for all
other Americans. But, she goes on to say, blacks' net worth _ the
best gauge of actual wealth _ still falls short of whites'.
</P>
<P>
   The Web site has features on investing in Africa and the best
companies for minorities to invest in.
</P>
<P>
   It will also include regular articles on investments such as
stocks, bonds and mutual funds. It also highlights investment
strategies, individual investors and industry professionals.
Subscribers can post questions on a message board, answer each
other's questions and talk about investing in general.
Subscriptions are $5.95 a month or $15 a quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically, it's to help establish a community of people with
like-minded goals,'' Campbell said.
</P>
<P>
   Tammy Joyner writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
