<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-10K-STOCKS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOW'S 10K RUN  
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By RUSS WILES  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ Now that the Dow has peeked above the 10,000
threshold, investors are wondering whether the milestone will mark
a temporary ceiling.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're getting close to an intermediate top, and in that sense,
10,000 might be a psychological barrier,'' said Arthur Stockton of
Stockton Trust in Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average, a barometer of the share
prices of 30 of America's most prominent companies, resembled a
pole vaulter at a track meet Tuesday. It cleared its first attempt
at 10,000 shortly after the opening bell at 8:21 a.m. Arizona time,
reaching 10,001.78, then scratched on all successive jumps.
</P>
<P>
   It finished down 28.30 points at 9930.47.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's trading session brought back memories of the Dow's
first crossing of the 1,000 mark three decades ago. It did so on
four separate days in early 1966 but failed to hold any of those
gains for more than a few hours.
</P>
<P>
   The market then spent the next 6{ years moving sideways and
lower, before finally rallying to close above 1,000 for the first
time on Nov. 10, 1972.
</P>
<P>
   Investment observers point out that the economy is in better
shape today than in the late 1960s, when government spending on the
Vietnam War was starting to push up inflation and interest rates.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're in a darn favorable environment right now,'' Stockton
said. ``There's just not much bad news out there.''
</P>
<P>
   There are other differences between '99 and '66.
</P>
<P>
   Back then, Baby Boomers were still in high school, grammar
school or preschool, and their parents were spending money on food,
clothing and other consumer goods rather than investing it.
</P>
<P>
   Now, members of the huge Boomer generation are moving into prime
investing years in their 40s and 50s, and their buying of stocks
and mutual funds has pushed the market higher.
</P>
<P>
   ``The lack of faith in Social Security makes us more concerned
about retirement planning, and that fuels our investments in 401(k)
plans and other accounts,'' said Fred Lynn of F.A.L. Capital
Management, a Scottsdale investment firm.
</P>
<P>
   Workplace 401(k) retirement programs and even individual
retirement accounts have played a big role, bringing adults of all
ages into the stock market by offering tax incentives and other
benefits. Neither type of program existed a generation ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been in the 401(k) plan since Day One,'' said Kelly L.
Cook, 27, of Chandler, who works at the Finova Group in Phoenix.
``I can't afford not to be.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the costs of investing have come down drastically
since the 1960s, making it more economical for a larger number of
people to get started. For example, the government deregulated
brokerage commissions in 1975, giving birth to a vibrant discount
business that today is reinventing itself with cut-rate fees on
Internet trading.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're at the beginning of the electronization of trading that
has created a lot more participation by the general public,'' said
Pejman Hamidi, who writes an online trading newsletter for Polar
Analytic Services in Mt. Clemens, Mich.
</P>
<P>
   Even more important has been the explosive growth of mutual
funds, which have enabled millions of investors to participate in
the market with greater convenience, more affordability and reduced
risks compared with owning individual stocks.
</P>
<P>
   Mutual-fund assets have swelled more than 100-fold, from less
than $50 billion in the 1960s to more than $5.7 trillion today,
eclipsing even bank deposits.
</P>
<P>
   The economic backdrop also has been an exceptionally good one
for stocks. The nation's prosperity has been on a general uptrend
since the Persian Gulf War ended in 1991. Today's economic climate
is marked by steady growth, moderate interest rates, low
unemployment and scarce inflation.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow's hitting 10,000 is ``an indication that things are
going right with the economy,'' said Susan Filson, senior portfolio
manager at Harris Trust Bank in Scottsdale.
</P>
<P>
   Low interest rates, in turn, have fueled liquidity-driven
buying. That's a fancy way of saying that investors are
transferring cash from low-yielding bonds, money-market funds and
bank accounts into the stock market in search of greater gains.
</P>
<P>
   The challenge for investors is to determine whether today's high
stock prices are justified _ the Dow is up more than 6,000 points
just since the end of 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Lynn thinks so, in light of the productivity gains being
achieved by American companies through the increased use of
technology.
</P>
<P>
   Phoenix money manager L. Roy Papp goes a step further, arguing
that the technological breakthroughs of the past decade and a half
could be more significant than those of the Industrial Revolution.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since the development of the personal computer in 1982, we
have had only one year of recession,'' Papp said. ``Something is
different.''
</P>
<P>
   Technological improvements help to explain why the big stocks in
the Dow average, which includes the likes of IBM, General Electric
and Hewlett Packard, have fared so well in recent years. Large
corporations are more likely to have embraced computerization,
which has helped them cut costs in an era of low inflation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Large companies have had really good earnings growth,'' said
Rose Papp, co-manager of the Papp mutual-fund group in Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   Last year during a talk to investors in Phoenix, fund manager
Art Bonnel predicted that the Dow would hit 20,000 by the year
2007. Today, he suspects that forecast might be too low.
</P>
<P>
   mergers and acquisitions have reduced the number of large stocks
in which to invest, Bonnel says, yet the public continues to pour
more cash into the market. Meanwhile, inflation remains low, the
political environment is reasonably stable and technology continues
to spur productivity gains.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you put it all together, it's a perfect environment for
stocks,'' said Bonnel, who runs the San Antonio-based United
Services Bonnel Growth Fund. ``If you haven't ventured into the
market yet, I'd recommend doing so, because this market's going a
lot higher.'' &QL; 
Russ Wiles can be reached at 444-8616 or at russ.wiles(at)pni.com. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
