<HEADER>
A2930 &Cx1f; tta-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RENAULT-NISSAN-2TAKES     03-16 0894
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RENAULT-NISSAN-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RENAULT OFFERS TO BUY 35 PERCENT SHARE OF NISSAN 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By EDMUND L. ANDREWS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   FRANKFURT, Germany _ In one of the biggest gambles that a
European car company has ever taken, Renault SA of France on
Tuesday offered to buy 35 percent of Nissan Motor Co., Japan's huge
but deeply troubled producer of cars and trucks.
</P>
<P>
   If Nissan accepts the offer, which could be worth as much as $4
billion or even $5 billion, the deal would mark a rare incursion by
a foreign company into the inner sanctum of Japanese industry. It
would also transform Renault from a smallish European producer to
one of the world's biggest players.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts and industry executives said such a deal carries
enormous risks. Renault has been unsuccessful in previous efforts
to move overseas, and it is not dominant in Europe. Nissan has lost
money for five years and is believed to have lost more than $1.5
billion in 1998. A turnaround is nowhere in sight.
</P>
<P>
   Nissan also has more than $30 billion in total debt, much of it
difficult to identify because it lies with affiliated companies and
is not part of Nissan's official balance sheet.
</P>
<P>
   And there are major questions about control. Though Renault
would gain several board members and be able to veto major
decisions, it would not necessarily have the power to dictate
strategy or dismiss top executives.
</P>
<P>
   Just last week, DaimlerChrysler AG walked away from a deal with
Nissan. At the time, Daimler executives complained that Nissan did
not have an adequate turnaround plan and would require too much
attention to be worth the trouble.
</P>
<P>
   But even after Daimler snubbed Nissan, Renault's chairman, Louis
Schweitzer, said he was still interested. In a brief statement on
Tuesday night after a meeting of Renault's board of directors, the
company said it was ``convinced of the merits of a strategic
alliance'' and would now enter exclusive negotiations with Nissan.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement, Nissan said it would proceed with the
negotiations. ``We will work out conditions for forming an alliance
in the days ahead so that a conclusion can be reached by the end of
this month,'' said Yoshikazu Hanawa, president and chief executive
of Nissan.
</P>
<P>
   Renault did not mention the price it had offered. At Nissan's
current market capitalization of about $10 billion, 35 percent of
the company would be worth about $3.5 billion. A variety of sources
said that Renault was prepared to pay a premium for the Japanese
company. French news agencies, quoting unnamed government and labor
union sources, said the company is offering 32 billion French
francs, just over $5 billion, for 35 percent of the company.
Renault would install three of its executives, led by Schweitzer,
on Nissan's board.
</P>
<P>
   Renault shares fell 5.45 percent, or 1.93 euros, to 33.47 euros
($36.80) in Paris. Nissan shares rose 19 yen, or 4 percent,
bringing their gains to 18 percent in the last two days. Nissan's
American depositary receipts rose 31.25 cents, to $7.4375 on
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   A big question for Renault is, why? Nissan, once extolled as a
prime example of an unstoppable Japanese company in books like
David Halberstam's ``The Reckoning,'' is a corporate basketcase
today, hobbled by high costs, staggering debts and a nightmarish
recession in its home market. It is also extremely difficult to
understand, because it has so many entangling ties to other
companies.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, Renault has bounced back from losses of $1 billion
in 1996 to booming sales and profits last year. Thanks to its
popular line of new cars and minivans, Renault earned about $1.4
billion on $40 billion in sales in 1998, and has built up a
substantial cash cushion.
</P>
<P>
   But Renault, in which the French government owns 44 percent of
the stock, remains a smaller player in a field increasingly
dominated by giants like Daimler-Chrysler, Ford, Toyota and General
Motors. About 85 percent of Renault's cars are sold in Europe, and
most of those are in France itself. It has little presence in the
United States and virtually none in Asia.
</P>
<P>
   Company executives, speaking on condition of anonymity, offered
several reasons for their interest in Nissan.
</P>
<P>
   As Japan's second-biggest car company after Toyota, they argue,
Nissan would give Renault a powerful presence in Asia as well as in
the United States. Renault could in turn provide Nissan with a
strong base in Europe, where it currently has little market share,
as well as in Latin America. In combination, the two companies
would be the world's fourth-biggest carmaker with 4.8 million
vehicles built, ahead of Volkswagen AG.
</P>
<P>
   Schweitzer was also attracted by Nissan's line of products.
While Renault derives most of its sales from small and midsized
passenger cars, which Nissan also builds, the Japanese company also
produces sport trucks, light trucks and luxury cars.
</P>
<P>
   Renault executives see other potential benefits. They like
Nissan's factory in Smyrna, Tenn., which is one of the world's most
modern. And they see opportunities for profits from reorganization:
Nissan currently uses 29 separate manufacturing ``platforms'' _ a
car's basic engineered underpinning _to build about three million
cars a year. Most other companies have consolidated scores of
different models into fewer than half that many platforms.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   But the dangers and uncertainties are at least as formidable as
the attractions. In teaming up with Nissan, Renault would be trying
to direct a company that has long been at the very heart of the
Japanese economy. Though Ford has owned 33.4 percent of Mazda for
several years, Nissan is a much bigger company and Renault would be
seeking much greater management control.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Renault would probably not obtain full control. Under
Japanese rules, by buying more than 33 percent of a company's
stock, an investor would obtain a veto right over major decisions
like mergers, acquisitions and new security offerings.
</P>
<P>
   But unless Nissan makes specific legal concessions on management
issues, Renault would not have an automatic right to set
compensation levels, reshuffle manufacturing or branding strategy
or install new management.
</P>
<P>
   ``It takes 51 percent to control the board,'' said Tetsuya
Morimoto, an expert in corporate law at the Tokyo office of White &AMP;
Case. ``Thirty-three percent does not stop the other party from
running the business.''
</P>
<P>
   Automobile analysts said on Tuesday that there is no guarantee
an alliance of the two companies would produce a new powerhouse.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nissan is not a strong player, and Renault is not the
strongest player in its market either,'' said Christian
Breitsprecher, an automobile analyst at Deutsche Bank in Frankfurt.
``Getting two basically weak companies doesn't necessarily create a
stronger player.''
</P>
<P>
   Renault's track record with foreign partners is mixed at best.
It bought American Motors Corp. in 1981 only to see the company
plunge into disarray before Chrysler came along and bought it. It
reached an agreement to acquire AB Volvo of Sweden in 1993, but the
deal collapsed when both shareholders and Volvo managers rebelled
over provisions that would have given the French government a veto
over key decisions.
</P>
<P>
   Renault does own the big American producer of heavy
tractor-trailer rigs, Mack Trucks, and that business has been
successful. Renault has made it clear that part of its interest in
Nissan Motor carries over to Nissan Diesel, the loss-making truck
company in which Nissan Motor owns a 40 percent stake. It was not
clear on Tuesday night whether Renault's offer includes a separate
capital infusion into Nissan Diesel or would simply amount to an
indirect stake through Nissan Motor.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
