<SLUG> BC-GAMES-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Pirates Cost Software-Makers Plenty
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; By Benny Evangelista &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c 1999, San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
The growing popularity of cheaper CD-ROM recorders in homes could
be costing computer game, educational and reference software-makers
nearly $1 billion in lost sales, according to a survey being
released today.
</P>
<P>
   And 12 percent of home computer owners admitted having at least
one unauthorized copy of a CD-ROM, predominantly computer and video
game titles, according to the survey to be released during the
first full day of the Game Developers Conference in San Jose.
</P>
<P>
   Piracy already is a major threat to the $6.3 billion video and
computer game industry. Douglas Lowenstein, president of the
Interactive Digital Software Association, on Monday told a group of
some 300 game company executives at the conference that pirates who
copy and sell games cost the industry an estimated $3.2 billion in
lost international sales last year.
</P>
<P>
   But the new survey, conducted by Merrill Research &AMP; Associates
of San Mateo, is the first to focus on a relatively new phenomenon
of ``casual copiers'' _ PC owners who copy games and other software
for themselves, their relatives or their friends.
</P>
<P>
   ``Consumer casual copying reared its head because of the cheap
CD-Rs that hit the streets in the last couple of years,'' said
Brian Dunn, vice president of computer software copy protection for
Macrovision Corp., which sponsored the survey.
</P>
<P>
   Merrill Research general partner Joe Wheeler said the firm last
month surveyed 301 home PC owners, ages 15 to 59. While only 6
percent owned CD recorders, another 32 percent knew someone else
with such a device.
</P>
<P>
   Among copied titles, 47 percent were of computer and video games
and 29 percent were of educational software. Another 24 percent
were copies of reference or personal business software.
</P>
<P>
   Copyright laws allow consumers to make backup copies of
software. However, it's illegal for people to copy a game or
software they don't own or to give it to someone else. Lowenstein
also noted that it's rare that anyone would need a backup copy of a
CD-ROM game.
</P>
<P>
   The casual copying phenomenon is tied to the growth in sales of
CD-R devices, which have come down in price from $1,000 or more to
as low as $200. About 600 million CD-ROM recorders were sold in
1998, a 165 percent increase from the year before, according to the
International Recording Media Association, an industry trade group.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the cost of blank recordable CD-ROMs has dropped to
less than $1 each.
</P>
<P>
   Another recent poll by the MTV cable network showed about 50
percent of young adults were planning to buy a CD-R.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, anyone can be a pirate,'' Dunn said.
</P>
<P>
   Macrovision is trying to sell game-makers new software designed
to prevent copying. The company is one of two in the world offering
such encryption technology for game-makers, Lowenstein said.
</P>
<P>
   Lowenstein said he has not had a chance to examine how Merrill
Research arrived at its revenue loss estimate. But he said the
survey should be taken seriously by the game industry, which now
uses copyright protection technology on only a few titles.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whether it is $1 billion or $200,000, there is a problem,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   The IDSA has in the past year stepped up enforcement of
commercial game piracy.
</P>
<P>
   However, ``It's awfully difficult for the industry to go into
the bedroom and try to run down individuals who are using CD-Rs to
copy at home,'' he said. ``That why the emphasis needs to be on
what we are going to do to help ourselves. You've got to do what
you can to protect your product.''
</P>
<P>
   The Game Developers Conference will host a panel discussion on
new CD-ROM protection techniques today. The 13th annual conference,
which runs through Friday at the San Jose Convention Center, is
expected to draw about 7,000 game industry professionals.
</P>
</TEXT>
