<HEADLINE>
FORBES OUTLINES PROGRAM IN ANNOUNCING BID FOR PRESIDENCY 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By BENNETT ROTH 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CONCORD, N.H. _ Steve Forbes, the wealthy publisher whose deep
pockets caused heartburn for Republican presidential candidates in
1996, said Tuesday he will again make a bid for the White House and
intends to air television ads beginning next month.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes made his announcement both on the Internet and at an
outdoor rally in front of the New Hampshire state capitol, where he
outlined his program that included reforming the tax code,
privatizing Social Security and beefing up defense spending.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes claimed to be the first candidate in U.S. history to
announce his campaign on the Internet. But Lamar Alexander, another
candidate repeating his 1996 attempt at the Republican nomination,
made his announcement on the Internet four years ago.
</P>
<P>
   In the Web site announcement, the 51-year old candidate pledged
to run a vigorous campaign despite polls showing him lagging far
behind other Republicans, including Texas Gov. George W. Bush and
former Red Cross chief Elizabeth Dole.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today marks the beginning of a national crusade to restore
Ronald Reagan's vision of hope and prosperity for all Americans. I
don't believe in business as usual _ and I surely don't believe in
politics as usual,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes, who catapulted onto the national political scene four
years ago with his promotion of the flat tax, again stressed the
need for tax reform calling the tax system ``an abomination.``
</P>
<P>
   ``It's too complex, too corrupt. It's a playground for
special-interest lawyers, lobbyists and lifetime politicians,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   But faced with criticism that the flat tax disproportionately
benefits the wealthy, Forbes this time would allow taxpayers to
choose either the flat tax or the current system. He did not
elaborate how such a system would be paid for or administered.
</P>
<P>
   While Forbes has increasingly tailored his message to court the
religious conservatives _ repeatedly asserting his opposition to
abortion _ he only briefly touched on those issues in his
announcement addresses Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   He said Republicans should not abandon the anti-abortion plank
in the party platform crafted by Reagan. But adopting a more
conciliatory stance to compete in the crowded GOP field, Forbes
said that anti-abortion forces need to persuade their adversaries.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't come across as trying to ram something down people's
throats,'' he said in a town-hall meeting taped Tuesday for later
broadcast on WMUR-TV in New Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   While political observers give Forbes little chance of winning
the GOP nomination, the chief executive of a publishing empire can
cause mischief for the leading candidates because of his enormous
wealth. Some Republican leaders fear a repeat of 1996 when Forbes
damaged front-runner Bob Dole by running millions of dollars of ads
in key primary states slamming the Senate leader and weakening his
general-election position.
</P>
<P>
   As he did last time, Forbes is expected to rely on his personal
fortune and contributions and forgo federal matching funds and the
contribution limits that go with it.
</P>
<P>
   By officially filing his candidacy with the Federal Election
Commission rather than establishing an exploratory committee, as
Bush and Dole and others have done as a preliminary step, Forbes is
now free to begin a full-scale campaign, including a media effort.
He plans a more elaborate announcement later in the spring.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes said he is now preparing for an ad campaign, targeted to
run before the end of April. However, the candidate would not say
where the ads would run or whether they would target certain
candidates. ``We're going to be running commercials advocating our
positions,'' he told the Houston Chronicle. ``I believe in
utilizing every tool possible.``
</P>
<P>
   Forbes also said that while he never has attacked anyone
personally, he looks ``forward to a vigorous debate with the
candidates.'' He said it would be unwise for the leading candidates
to avoid debates or participation in the early primaries.
</P>
<P>
   ``Voters resent being taken for granted. They don't like
candidates posturing as emperors,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes also claimed that he is better positioned this time
because he has started much earlier and been spending the years
since the last election building grass-roots organizations to back
up what will likely be an expensive broadcast war.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes has tapped a number of political operatives who worked
for presidential candidate Pat Buchanan in 1996, including the head
of Buchanan's New Hampshire operation and his media consultant.
</P>
<P>
   ``My impression is he's a more experienced candidate. He'll have
a stronger grass-roots effort,'' said Ken Eagan, executive director
of the New Hampshire Republican Party.
</P>
<P>
   But Dick Bennett, a Manchester-based pollster, said that Forbes
must overcome negative perception among voters here that he is
trying to buy the election. Bennett said many voters were turned
off when Forbes swamped the airwaves here before the 1996 primary.
</P>
<P>
   ``They didn't like seeing him whenever they flipped the
channels,'' he said. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
