<SLUG> BC-DEL-MURDER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUDGE ORDERS DEATH PENALTY IN '96 KILLING BY EX-LAWYER
</HEADLINE>
   (dal) 
 By MICHAEL JANOFSKY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WILMINGTON, Del. _ Addressing the defendant as an ``angry,
sinister, controlling and malignant force,'' a state judge on
Tuesday ordered that Thomas Capano, a once prominent and wealthy
Delaware lawyer, be executed for the murder of a former mistress
three years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The decision by Judge William Swain Lee of the Delaware Superior
Court affirmed a jury's recommendation in late January that Capano,
49, be put to death, rather than serve a life sentence without
parole, for killing Anne Marie Fahey, a scheduling secretary for
Gov. Thomas Carper. The same jury found Capano guilty of
first-degree murder on Jan. 17.
</P>
<P>
   Lee set June 28 as the date for execution by lethal injection,
but it is unlikely that it will occur then. A death sentence in
Delaware leads to an automatic appeal, and lawyers for Capano said
they would file one.
</P>
<P>
   Capano also faces a wrongful-death civil suit filed by Ms.
Fahey's family.
</P>
<P>
   Capano, who has been in prison since his arrest in November
1997, will join 17 other inmates awaiting execution in Delaware,
one of 38 states with a death penalty.
</P>
<P>
   While Lee's decision was widely expected _ even by Capano, his
lawyers said _ his withering 12-minute summation of the three-month
trial stunned many in the crowded courtroom, which included members
of the Fahey and Capano families.
</P>
<P>
   As Capano sat before him, Lee condemned him as an arrogant bully
who ``systematically and contemptuously degraded all those who
participated in the proceedings,'' a clear reference to Capano's
outburst and sneers, which led to frequent admonitions from the
bench.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tom Capano does not face judgment today because family and
friends failed him,'' Lee said. ``He faces judgment because he is a
ruthless murderer who feels compassion for no one and remorse only
for the circumstances in which he finds himself in. He is a
malignant force, from whom no one he deems disloyal or adversarial
can be secure.''
</P>
<P>
   Capano betrayed no emotion as the judge affirmed the jury's
recommendation of the death sentence. Before he left, he turned to
his 76-year-old mother, Marguerite, who uses a wheelchair, and said
quietly, ``I'll be all right. I love you.'' She wept, and was
comforted by relatives.
</P>
<P>
   The trial had been stunning in its force, gaining national
attention for its revelations, defensive strategies adopted by
Capano and in the end, the emotional trauma to Ms. Fahey's family
and the Capanos.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors said that Capano shot and killed Ms. Fahey on June
27, 1996, after her efforts to break off a two-year affair with
him. Shunning his lawyers' advice, Capano took the stand in his own
defense and admitted he elicited the help of his brothers, Louis
and Gerard Capano, who later testified against him, to dump her
body in the Atlantic Ocean. Her body was never recovered.
</P>
<P>
   In later testimony, he accused another former lover, Deborah A.
MacIntyre, of committing the murder in a jealous rage, a contention
that Ms. MacIntyre denied on the stand.
</P>
<P>
   In the penalty phase of the trial, Capano refused to express
remorse or plead for his life, other than to ask the jury to
consider the feelings of his mother, his four teen-age daughters
and his former wife, Kay _ which Lee said was the ultimate act of
selfishness.
</P>
<P>
   Leaving the courthouse on Tuesday, Ms. Fahey's family had little
to say. But it was clear they had been heartened by Lee's remarks.
</P>
<P>
   ``He summed up in 12 minutes what we have felt for 33 months,''
said Ms. Fahey's sister, Kathleen Fahey-Hosey.
</P>
<P>
   Capano's lawyer, Joseph S. Oteri of Boston, said of the judge's
remarks, ``I have never heard anything like that in all my life.''
But his co-counsel, Eugene Maurer of Wilmington, said the judge had
to justify the death penalty by characterizing Capano ``as a
miscreant.''
</P>
<P>
   Ferris Wharton, the state prosecutor, called Lee's summation
``an extraordinarily eloquent statement,'' and told reporters ``it
showed that not just poor people are convicted of these kinds of
crimes.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
