u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEDICARE-PANEL-2TAKES     03-16 0454
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDICARE-PANEL-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
  
 WASHINGTON: any recommendations. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Senate Republican leader, Trent Lott of Mississippi, said
Clinton ``chose to kill the Medicare commission's bipartisan
recommendations one-half hour before the commission was scheduled
to meet.'' But Barry Toiv, a White House spokesman, said Clinton
did not try to influence commission members ``one way or the
other.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton appointed four of the 17 commission members. All four
voted against the Breaux-Thomas proposal, though two of the four
said they saw some merit in it.
</P>
<P>
   One of the Clinton appointees, Professor Stuart Altman of
Brandeis University, said Breaux's plan did too little to find
additional revenue for Medicare and to guarantee affordable drug
coverage.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do need more money in this program,'' Altman said. ``We
need it sooner rather than later.''
</P>
<P>
   Another commission member, Laura D'Andrea Tyson, the former
chairwoman of Clinton's Council of Economic Advisers, said she
supported efforts to inject competition into Medicare. But she said
such competition could never produce enough savings to solve
Medicare's financial problems.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. John Dingell, D-Mich., acknowledged that the commission was
influenced by politics, but he declared: ``Thank God for it. That's
the exercise of free men and women doing the business of their
government.''
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, he said, ``the proposal before us would convert
Medicare from a universal guarantee to a government voucher for
private insurance.''
</P>
<P>
   Breaux disagreed. ``This proposal is not a voucher program,'' he
said. ``It is not an end to Medicare as an entitlement.''
</P>
<P>
   The chairmen of the House Ways and Means Committee and the
Senate Finance Committee said they would hold hearings on the
Breaux-Thomas proposal. And Breaux said the full Senate would
probably support much of the proposal. But the outlook for action
in Congress is murky, unless Republicans agree to Clinton's
proposal to use some of the projected budget surplus for Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas said the proposal to earmark some of the surplus for
Medicare was a bookkeeping gimmick. ``The President's proposal is
likely to create a public misperception that something meaningful
is being done to reform the Medicare program,'' Thomas said.
</P>
<P>
   Many health policy experts say Medicare will eventually need
additional revenues, beyond the current sources of money, which
include premiums paid by beneficiaries, workers' payroll taxes and
general revenues from the Treasury. But Newt Gingrich, who as
speaker of the House named four commission members, insisted that
his appointees promise not to vote for tax increases. And the
commission did not seriously consider tax increases.
</P>
</TEXT>
