<SLUG> BC-GROW-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Column: Getting A Handle on Patenting
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; By Peter Sinton &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; c 1999, San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Question: &LR;  I believe I have a couple of items that I may be able to
patent and wonder how best to go about the patenting process.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Answer: &LR;  You might start by curling up with a good primer like
``Patent It Yourself'' by San Francisco patent attorney David
Pressman (Nolo Press, 7th edition, 420 pages, $45). Even if you
decide to consult with a patent attorney (about $200 an hour and
up), you are probably well advised to go through a self-help book
like Pressman's to get a handle on the complex patenting process.
</P>
<P>
   In essence, Pressman advises inventors to start out with a clear
record of the creation process. That means writing about and
drawing a rough sketch of each invention. Sign and date these early
records and have them witnessed by two persons such as friends,
neighbors or co-workers.
</P>
<P>
   If you can, build and test your design and again keep careful,
signed and dated written records.
</P>
<P>
   Consult with potential buyers, professors, friends and others
about the commercial potential. It's hard to get a patent but even
harder to make a commercial success of it. Pressman figures only
about three out of every 100 patents make money.
</P>
<P>
   Along the way, you need to conduct a search to see if your
invention is patentable. You can hire a professional to do this
search or go to a patent depository library like the one on the
fifth floor of San Francisco's main Civic Center library.
</P>
<P>
   For a less complete computer search, you can go to two Web sites
_ &LR;  www.uspto.gov  &LR; and  &LR; www.patents.ibm.com  &LR; _ but these only go
back to 1974. There also is some general information on patents and
patent law at these sites.
</P>
<P>
   If you feel you can get a patent on your inventions and believe
someone will buy it, the next step is to prepare and file an
application with the U.S. Patent Office. The application requires a
$380 filing fee along with detailed drawings and descriptions. A
professionally prepared application for a simple device can easily
cost $3,000 to $5,000.
</P>
<P>
   After you file your patent application, &UR;  &LR; you might want to sell
or license your invention to a company. Pressman advises against
hiring invention developers, who tout their ability in getting
companies to buy new products. &UR;  &LR; ``Their track record in getting you
more money than they take is practically zero,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Filing Conundrums
</P>
<P>
   Q: My wife and I are self-employed and run a consulting business
out of our home. Previously, we've divided the income and filed a
Schedule C, but I understand the IRS wants us to file as a
partnership (Form 1065). If we do that, how do we handle the two
home-office deductions?
</P>
<P>
   A: If the two of you are involved in the same business and split
the income 50-50, you can continue to file one Schedule C (the form
for sole proprietors) and two Schedule SE forms to properly report
self-employment tax, according to CPA Mary Kay Foss of the Danville
firm of Marzluft, Giles, Tulis &AMP; Foss. The IRS treats married
couples as one person for many tax purposes, but each of you has to
pay your share of the 15.3 percent self-employment tax.
</P>
<P>
   If your businesses are separate, you can file two forms of
Schedule C and two for Form 8829 for home office deductions. One
Schedule C can be filed if one spouse is the proprietor and the
other is an employee. In that situation, a Form W-2 will be
required for the employee-spouse.
</P>
<P>
   If both of you file as a partnership, you can still claim
office-in-home deductions. Form 8829 is used for Schedule C filers
only. A partnership would require all of the same information on
your own schedule.
</P>
<P>
   If you rent your home offices to the partnership, you need to
pay rent at the going rate per square foot in you neighborhood. No
sweetheart deals are allowed. What you pay in rent must then be
reported as income on your individual income tax returns.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever your arrangement, you should have it in writing, Foss
suggests. If you are a partnership, you should split income based
on the ratio of ownership. Note that Schedule C filers only report
income and expenses while partnerships must go through the added
step of preparing a balance sheet to report business assets and
liabilities.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Send small-business questions to  &LR; entrepreneurs(at &LR; 
 &LR; sign)sfgate.com &LR;  or to Peter Sinton, Grow a Business column, 901
Mission St., San Francisco, Calif., 94103
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
