<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-16 21:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2946 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WATER-SFCHRON &LR;      03-16 1421
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WATER-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Turning Water Into Gold
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; By Peter Sinton &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c 1999, San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
Indian Wells Water Co. is putting a new twist on the bottled water
business.
</P>
<P>
   The Sonoma startup is trying to carve out a niche in the
thriving $4.3 billion U.S. water market with a distinctive pitch to
consumers who may want to improve the economic lot of American
Indians while slaking their thirst.
</P>
<P>
   The company is making an unprecedented attempt to market bottled
water as a purely American Indian enterprise. That means tapping
springs on tribal lands, building bottling plants there, hiring
local residents and returning profits to American Indians.
</P>
<P>
   Indian Wells hopes customers will find its efforts a refreshing
notion in a market dominated by such large, well-known players as
the Perrier Group, Suntory and McKesson HBOC Inc.
</P>
<P>
   The company, which started selling its water in San Francisco
last month, still has a ways to go before it reaches its goal of
turning water into gold on Indian reservations. To date, Indian
Wells is bottling water from a natural but non-Indian source in
Sedona, Ariz.
</P>
<P>
   The company, though, has lined up significant American Indian
support. For example, the Mille Lacs Band of Minnesota's Ojibwe
tribe last May invested $10 million for a 40 percent stake in the
company.
</P>
<P>
   Indian Wells also has various agreements with the Mille Lacs and
five other American Indian tribes, including the Washoe near Carson
City, Nev., to develop springs and build bottling plants. And it is
looking for one more tribe in Southern California to complete its
network of strategically located sites of water supply around &LR;   &LR; the
country.
</P>
<P>
   Although markets and convenience stores are swimming in bottled
water, Indian Wells chief executive Jim Stevens believes that
``cause marketing will help position the product.''
</P>
<P>
   Stevens, 51, knows something about selling water. In 1976, he
helped introduce Perrier to the United States. He then became chief
operating officer for the world's largest bottling company,
Coca-Cola Enterprises, and chief executive of Suntory Water Group,
the second-largest U.S. water company.
</P>
<P>
   ``The goal is to help American Indians develop a new economic
template besides casinos,'' said company President Brian McCarthy,
53. The former rear admiral in the Naval Reserve's Defense
Logistics Agency started Indian Wells a decade ago as a business
that delivered purified tap water to homes and offices.
</P>
<P>
   Then three years ago, he got out of that business and created a
new company that would be true to the Indian Wells name and sell
bottled water from Indian springs.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, McCarthy recruited Stevens, who still lives in Atlanta,
to develop the concept. While talking to tribes about potential
sources of water, they approached European investors, who love both
bottled water and Indian lore, about sources of capital.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't think we could find the money in Indian country, so
we pursued more traditional finance methods,'' said McCarthy. But
the 3,000-member Mille Lacs surprised him and Stevens when they
expressed an interest in investing in Indian Wells. The Ojibwa band
already operate two profitable casinos in central Minnesota, about
80 miles from St. Paul, and have been a pioneer in plowing profits
back into development.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our strategy has been to become less casino dependent and
diversify into other industries that will benefit the band, create
jobs for members, help the surrounding community and have an impact
on Indian country beyond the Mille Lacs,'' said Kenneth Mimmack,
commissioner of corporate affairs for the tribe.
</P>
<P>
   ``We looked at getting into bottled water ourselves but realized
we had no experience or marketing ability,'' he added. ``That's
what we liked about Indian Wells.''
</P>
<P>
   With its investment, the band took two positions on the
startup's seven-person board to help ensure that Indian Wells
remains true to its mission.
</P>
<P>
   ``The goals are good,'' agrees Richard Trudell, a Santee Sioux
who directs the American Indian Resources Institute in Oakland and
is an Indian Wells director. The startup's bottling plants will be
located on American Indian lands and each will be operated and 60
percent owned by the American Indian tribe.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is important for the 1.6 million American Indians living on
more than 550 federal reservations to diversify their economic
efforts, and to do so in a way that protects our resources,''
Trudell said.
</P>
<P>
   But finding springs with sufficient flow and acceptable mineral
content has sometimes been a challenge. The first few tests of
Mille Lacs water sources proved marginal at best, so the search
there continues.
</P>
<P>
   However, Indian Wells has found a suitable spring on
Narragansett Indian Tribe lands near Charlestown, R.I., and plans
to spend $7 million to $9 million to build a bottling plant there
within six months. CEO Stevens said this plant could supply the
entire Northeast market with 10 million cases of bottled water a
year and generate $70 million or $80 million.
</P>
<P>
   Each participating tribe will receive all of the profits
generated by its bottling plant, 60 percent in cash and 40 percent
in Indian Wells stock. McCarthy and Stevens hope to make money from
marketing and distribution charges as well as appreciation of the
company's shares.
</P>
<P>
   The two executives are aware that establishing commercial
ventures on Indian lands involves special sensitivity. For example,
there may be problems getting members of the Squaxin Island Tribe
in Washington state to work at the plant because they like to go
clamming together at certain times of the year. To compensate for
those absences, the company realizes it will need to build up
sufficient inventory of bottled water.
</P>
<P>
   Indian Wells still has a long way to go before water rivals the
billions of dollars generated by casinos on American Indian
reservations or becomes as successful a venture as the more than
$50 million in sales generated by actor Paul Newman's popcorn,
salad dressing and other food lines, which benefit nonprofits.
</P>
<P>
   McCarthy and Stevens also face formidable competition in the
U.S. water business.
</P>
<P>
   The $1.3 billion U.S. Perrier Group, which is owned by Nestle,
is the largest contender with 75 springs and 18 brands including
California's Calistoga and Arrowhead. Suntory Group is second
largest and McKesson is third with its Alhambra, Sparkletts and
Crystal brands.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, Coca-Cola announced plans to roll out its U.S. brand
of bottled water called Dasani. Instead of tapping natural springs,
Coke will turn on the tap and use reverse osmosis to filter and
purify the water before adding minerals for taste. Five years ago,
Coke's main soft-drink rival, PepsiCo, began selling its Aquafina
brand.
</P>
<P>
   There also are plenty of small players. For instance, Crystal
Cream &AMP; Butter Co. of Sacramento has been selling bottled water
from Sierra springs since 1992.
</P>
<P>
   It's easy to see why companies see water as such a strong
selling point. Mike Newell, vice president for Crystal Cream, said
the profit margins of his company's water business are several
times fatter than the milk business' thin 2 percent returns.
</P>
<P>
   The sales growth in the water business also is far higher than
milk or sodas. John Sicher, editor of Beverage Digest, reports that
the $57 billion soft drink business is growing at about 3 percent a
year while the $4 billion bottled water business is growing 8
percent a year overall and the small bottle segment growing about
20 percent a year.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the competition, Indian Wells, with only 10 employees,
believes it has an important edge. Stevens points to surveys
showing 78 percent of consumers are more likely to buy a product
that is associated with a cause they care about, and 66 percent
would even switch brands.
</P>
<P>
   Indian Wells picked the Bay Area as its second market after
Arizona to sell bottled water. Last month, the Indian Wells brand
started to show up on independent grocery store shelves in San
Francisco and Marin. The firm is also planning radio commercials
featuring American Indian actor Michael Greyeyes.
</P>
<P>
   The distributor of Indian Wells bottled water is pleased with
sales so far. ``We've had an outstanding penetration rate,'' said
Don Saccani, whose Anchor and Mariner distribution companies also
deliver Anchor Steam, Miller and some other beers, soft drinks and
Calistoga water. ``In less than two months, 35 percent of the 1,250
stores we serve are taking Indian Wells.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-16-99 2110EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
