<SLUG> BC-MCDOUGAL-TRIAL-NYT </SLUG>
  
 McDOUGAL TRIAL SEES MRS. CLINTON'S VIDEOTAPE  
(sw) 
 By STEVE BARNES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LITTLE ROCK, Ark. _ Hillary Rodham Clinton, appearing Tuesday on
videotape in the trial of a woman who once was her business partner
in the Whitewater real estate deal, testified that she had little
knowledge of the development company's financial transactions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never seen these documents before and I have no
information about them,'' Mrs. Clinton said when prosecutors for
Kenneth Starr, the independent counsel, presented copies of loan
papers in the name of her husband, taken out in the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never spent any significant time at all looking at the books
and records of Whitewater,'' Mrs. Clinton said at another point in
her previously secret grand jury testimony, which was given at the
White House last April 25.
</P>
<P>
   Her testimony came in the trial of Susan McDougal, who is
charged with criminal contempt of court and obstruction of justice
for refusing to answer questions about Whitewater transactions,
including some that were nearly identical to those posed to Mrs.
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. McDougal, her former husband, James McDougal, and Jim Guy
Tucker, who was then governor of Arkansas, were found guilty of
fraud in 1996 in connection with a series of interlocking
transactions, including a $300,000 loan in 1986 to Mrs. McDougal
that an Arkansas businessman testified he granted to her at Bill
Clinton's urging.
</P>
<P>
   In the trial now under way, the focus has been on a $27,600 loan
made in 1982 in Clinton's name by an Arkansas savings and loan
controlled by James McDougal, who has since died, and a $5,081.82
check written in 1983 by Mrs. McDougal with the notation, ``Pay off
Clinton.''
</P>
<P>
   Starr's prosecutors have long contended that part of the 1986
loan to Mrs. McDougal was improperly diverted to the Whitewater
real estate partnership. They maintain that other funds from the
loan were similarly laundered to largely retire the loan made in
Clinton's name.
</P>
<P>
   As a defense witness in 1996, President Clinton denied any
knowledge of the loan to Mrs. McDougal and said he had never
borrowed money from Madison Guaranty, McDougal's savings and loan
company. When McDougal began cooperating with prosecutors after his
conviction, he reversed himself and contradicted Clinton on both
points, according to an FBI agent who testified last week. It was
with McDougal's guidance, said the agent, Michael Patkus, that
investigators found the $27,600 loan in Clinton's name.
</P>
<P>
   The cashier's check, recovered in 1997, does not bear Clinton's
endorsement, however, and Starr's staff has acknowledged that
Clinton may have been unaware of the loan, as the president's
lawyers have suggested.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know anything about this,'' Mrs. Clinton was heard to
say on Tuesday about the loan. ``So far as I knew,'' she testified,
McDougal saw to the Whitewater partnership ``until the very end.''
</P>
<P>
   All the more reason for Mrs. McDougal's cooperation, say
prosecutors, who note that she is the only member of the original
Whitewater partnership to not have testified about the loans and to
whether Clinton was truthful in his testimony.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton also disputed a bit of conventional wisdom about
the relationship between the two couples in the partnership,
replying, when asked if she and her husband were social friends
with the McDougals, ``No, we were not.''
</P>
</TEXT>
