<HEADLINE>
COMPUTER SALES HEAD FOR SLUMP THIS FALL, SOME ANALYSTS SAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By REBECCA ROLWING  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ Many businesses will quit buying computers as the new
millennium approaches to avoid adding to system problems that may
be created by the arrival of Y2K, market research shows.
</P>
<P>
   The growth in the number of computers shipped is expected to
drop from 16.96 percent in the third quarter to 7.59 percent in the
fourth quarter, according to Cahners In-Stat Group, a high-tech
market research firm with offices in Scottsdale.
</P>
<P>
   The fourth quarter is typically the strongest period of growth
for personal computer shipments, but problems the arrival of the
next millennium may cause is expected to result in a drop this
year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a risk management approach that most sane (information
technology) managers will want to take to survive through January
first,'' said Martin Goslar, who directs the Internet commerce and
PC market services for Cahners In-Stat.
</P>
<P>
   The downturn should be brief.
</P>
<P>
   However, the situation could mean good news for consumers.
Manufacturers may slash prices in an effort to keep inventory low.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some deals might be available that weren't there before,''
Goslar said.
</P>
<P>
   The research firm spoke to information technology managers in a
cross section of businesses before predicting the downturn.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is highly likely that in the fourth quarter, we're going to
have a lockdown to some degree,'' Goslar said.
</P>
<P>
   Contributing to the computer sales slump is that the businesses
will be spending their technology budgets on making sure their
systems are Year 2000 compliant. That will leave less money
available for buying new computers.
</P>
<P>
   The fourth quarter stall is expected to trickle into other areas
as well, affecting sales of items such as networking equipment. &QL; 
Rebecca Rolwing can be reached at 444-8305 or
rebecca.rolwing(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
