<SLUG> BC-BKC-OHIOSTATE-AUBURN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Little OSU shoot to slay goliath Tigers
 &HT;    By Susan Vinella
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLUMBUS, Ohio _ Jason Singleton is used to standing on the
basketball court and looking up.
</P>
<P>
   That's the position Ohio State's 6-foot-5 power forward has
found himself in frequently this season. Singleton will be there
again on Thursday, when the fourth-seeded Buckeyes face top-seeded
Auburn in the South Regional semifinals of the NCAA tournament.
</P>
<P>
   The Tigers (29-3) boast a starting frontcourt with a 7-foot
center in Mamadou N'Diaye and a 6-7 power forward in Chris Porter,
the Southeastern Conference's player of the year. Their reserves go
6-7 and 6-5.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're a big team and they want to go crash the boards,'' OSU
point guard Scoonie Penn said. ``We have a problem with that
because we're undersized.''
</P>
<P>
   Auburn ranked fourth nationally in rebounding margin during the
regular season, grabbing 44 per game while giving up 34.8. In their
first and second round NCAA games, the Tigers grabbed an average of
10 more rebounds per game than their opponents and scored a total
of 40 points from second-chance shots.
</P>
<P>
   ``My biggest fear is their ability to rebound on offense,'' Ohio
State coach Jim O'Brien said. ``That's been one of our obvious
deficiencies this year and it seems like one of their strengths.
That's going to be a real concern.''
</P>
<P>
   To compensate for the disadvantage he'll have against a taller
opponent, Singleton said he'll have to be smarter and quicker.
He'll study more film to learn Porter's tendencies in an effort to
anticipate them on the court.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll just try to use my intelligence, my quickness and wit,''
Singleton said.
</P>
<P>
   Equally as important for Ohio State is keeping 6-11 center Ken
Johnson in the game. The Bucks tallest player, Johnson is a
terrific shot blocker who can alter a game. But he's also prone to
foul trouble. With him on the bench, OSU shrinks significantly with
6-7 forward George Reese as his replacement. And its defense
becomes more conservative.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Kenny's not in foul trouble and he's blocking shots, we
can take a lot of chances out there,'' Penn said. ``We can get in
the passing lanes a little bit more. We can play our pressure
defense even more.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Brien continues to stress to Johnson that he doesn't have to
block every shot. That sometimes, positioning himself for rebounds
is more important than trying to swat balls away. Johnson said he's
trying to play smarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I have to do is stay confident, stay on the ground and
time shots well,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Penn, who, in a fluke, grabbed 12 rebounds in OSU's second round
rout of Detroit, doesn't expect to finish with similar numbers
against Auburn. But he knows if OSU hopes to pull off the upset,
his taller teammates will have to be aggressive on the boards.
</P>
<P>
   ``I figure if we can keep those guys off of second shots, we'll
have a good chance of winning the game,'' Penn said. ``That's their
biggest thing, rebounding.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've seen them go up and down (the court in transition). But I
feel we can play that way and we can really change the whole tempo
of the game.'
</P>
<P>
   Susan Vinella writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
