<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OHIO-SCHOOLFUNDING-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Phillis calls on Ohio to change school funding policies
 &HT;    By Lynn Hulsey
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ About 325 Ohio school districts are too wealthy
to get special state help but struggle to make ends meet with local
tax dollars, according to William Phillis, executive director of
the Ohio Coalition for Equity and Adequacy of School Funding.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Phillis brought that message to the Ohio Statehouse
atrium, in what he said will be a series of similar news
conferences across the state.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Milburn, spokesman for Gov. Bob Taft, said the state has
made major commitments to education in the last few years and the
governor has proposed spending a record $13 billion on schools in
the state's 611 districts over the next two years.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people in the education community want a blank check
from the state,'' Milburn said. ``The governor believes that we
have to have accountability for the massive amount of dollars that
we're investing in education.''
</P>
<P>
   Phillis' group, a coalition of Ohio school districts,
successfully sued the state over its school funding system, which
was found unconstitutional by the Ohio Supreme Court in 1997. In
February, a Perry County Common Pleas judge said the system remains
unconstitutional, despite changes enacted last year by the Ohio
Legislature. The state plans an appeal.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the state's recent funding changes benefited the state's
poorest districts, funneling more money to disadvantaged pupils and
targeting crumbling school buildings.
</P>
<P>
   Phillis argues that the state is ignoring the needs of most
school districts.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is this group of districts in the mid-wealth range that
are emerging as the new poor,'' said Phillis.
</P>
<P>
   By his definition ``mid-wealth'' districts are those where the
community's per pupil property valuations range from $56,559 to
$113,371, which would include the majority of the Miami Valley's 61
school districts.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's happening here is that the whole system is grossly
underfunded,'' Phillis said during a phone interview after the
meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Huber Heights, which has a per pupil property valuation of
$66,394, is one local struggling district. It faces a $3 million
projected deficit by June 30, 2000 without additional revenue or
cuts. Seven efforts to get voters to approve a new operating levy
have failed since 1991 and the district is on the May ballot with a
6.5 mill continuing levy, said Cheryl Dale, the district's central
office coordinator.
</P>
<P>
   ``The system is flawed, therefore it causes us to rely on our
property owners to make up any gaps in funding,'' said Dale. ``Its
getting harder and harder to get voters to say yes on these
levies.''
</P>
<P>
   Lynn Hulsey writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
