<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CZECH-MAGAZINE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MITTELEUROPA LOSES JOURNAL SOROS BACKED
</HEADLINE>
   (dal) 
 By STEVEN ERLANGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PRAGUE, Czech Republic _ The post-Communist world's sole
magazine devoted to analyzing the region's own transformations is
dead, a victim of the Russian financial crisis, bad management and
the shifting priorities of its main supporter, the financier George
Soros.
</P>
<P>
   The monthly, Transitions, founded in 1994 and based here, has
published its last issue and will lay off its small staff at the
end of the month, its publisher, Jan Urban, said Tuesday in an
interview.
</P>
<P>
   Although its circulation was less than 8,000, much of its
readership was in the countries of the former Soviet bloc. The
magazine and its Web site, which are in English, were one of the
few common strands to link the professional, scholarly and
political elites of the former Communist bloc.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a loss in every way,'' said Jiri Pehe, a former
journalist and political adviser to President Vaclav Havel. ``It is
the only journal of its kind reporting on developments in Central
Europe and the former Soviet Union that is actually read by the
people living there.''
</P>
<P>
   Jefim Fistein, former editor in chief of a Czech daily, Lidove
Noviny, said Transitions was the lone magazine to attempt
comparative studies of development in the region on issues like
privatization, human rights, the treatment of minorities and crime.
It helped leaders avoid mistakes made by other countries, and it
also provided journalists and scholars in the region a chance to
write for a wider audience.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a very convenient tool, not only for the Easterner, who
gets little information from his own press about his neighbors, but
for the Westerner, too, whose knowledge about the region is even
lower than here,'' said Fistein, now assistant director of
broadcasting for Radio Free Europe and Radio Liberty.
</P>
<P>
   Urban, a well-known former dissident, said that without the
magazine ``there will be no real bridge from the emerging
English-language elite, pro-democracy and pro-free-market, to the
West and to each other.''
</P>
<P>
   Urban said he had underestimated the difficulty of finding
alternative financing when Soros told him that he would cut back
his yearly grant to the magazine.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our circulation was rising, and we were getting 300,000 visits
a month to our Web site,'' he said. ``It's not that the magazine
was unsuccessful. But we were not able to finance it in the long
term.''
</P>
<P>
   Marketing directors of foundations and companies are hard to
sell on a diffuse readership in 75 countries, Urban said, adding,
``We didn't have time to convince the corporate world of this
venture's importance in the long run.''
</P>
<P>
   After 10 years, ``the region is less sexy, and it's very
complicated to report on transitional nations,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This region is underreported in the Western media generally,''
Urban added.
</P>
<P>
   But others at the magazine and elsewhere said that Urban was not
extremely business minded or entrepreneurial and that he did too
little to raise money or earn it.
</P>
<P>
   The president of the Soros Foundations and the Open Society
Institute, Aryeh Neier, said in a telephone interview from New York
that Soros simply did not want to finance forever an expensive
magazine of small circulation.
</P>
<P>
   The magazine had evolved from a research report of Radio Free
Europe and Radio Liberty. Soros had subsidized it as part of the
Open Media Research Institute. When that closed in 1997, the
magazine was published by another independent foundation. But Soros
still provided most of the support, and the magazine became more
journalistic, attractive and lively.
</P>
<P>
   Soros agreed to give it $1 million in 1998, with the grant
declining by $250,000 a year, to push the magazine to be
self-sustaining. But Urban had secured less than $100,000 in new
financing for 1999.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would like to see it have other sources of revenue,
primarily advertising and subscriptions,'' Neier said. ``But there
hasn't been enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would have adhered to our initial commitment of $750,000,
if they could have made it at that. But they said they couldn't.''
</P>
<P>
   But he also implied that in view of the business plan of the
magazine, Soros had lost confidence in its future. Alternative
proposals were made to reduce the scope of the magazine. But Soros
offered $250,000 for this year in a telephone call to Urban this
month.
</P>
<P>
   Others at the magazine said they believed that Soros, having
lost much money in the Russian financial collapse, reneged on his
pledge and doomed the magazine.
</P>
<P>
   Neier denied that. ``The Russian crunch hurt a lot,'' Neier
said. But even before that, he said, Soros had told the foundations
that he would cut back by half on grants from 2001 and revert to
the levels of 1993 to 1997.
</P>
</TEXT>
