<SLUG> BC-GOODYKOONTZ-COLUMN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPEAKING OF SNAKES, ARIZONA'S THE PIT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL GOODYKOONTZ  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX The prevalence of shamrocks, the green beer, the
ridiculous claims that someone way back on your mother's side was
Irish _ really, O'something or O'other _ can mean only one thing:
It's St. Patrick's Day.
</P>
<P>
   St. Patrick is famous for driving the snakes out of Ireland and
into the ocean, where they drowned. How he did this depends on whom
you talk to: He either beat a drum, rang a bell, led them with a
wooden staff or got rid of them by preaching an especially moving
sermon.
</P>
<P>
   Except that he didn't. You can't get five words into this legend
without some know-it-all blurting out that Ireland never had snakes
in the first place. The ``snakes'' are just a symbol of pagan
beliefs, he'll tell you. It's all metaphorical.
</P>
<P>
   These kinds of people ruin everything. Don't even get them
started on Santa Claus.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the case, Ireland is snake-free. So in the spirit of
the day, let's credit St. Patrick with doing the job.
</P>
<P>
   But could it really happen? Are there any modern-day saints in
our midst? Could anyone rid Arizona of snakes? For instance, would
an especially potent sermon do the trick?
</P>
<P>
   ``Because snakes can't hear, I doubt it,'' said Tom Taylor of
the Arizona Herpetological Association. That probably rules out the
drums and bells as well; the staff, presumably, remains a viable
option. Though Taylor knows of others. &QL; 
150 degrees of separation
</P>
<P>
   ``They don't like water,'' he said. ``You could have a giant
flood, I guess. Maybe wash 'em all out. Maybe have our annual
hundred-year flood.''
</P>
<P>
   If that didn't work, there's always the desert heat.
</P>
<P>
   ``Turn the furnace up a little bit,'' Taylor said, ``maybe have
it be 150 degrees. That would eliminate them, and probably anything
else _ probably you and me.''
</P>
<P>
   No one wants that. What's the point of ridding the place of
snakes if we're not around to enjoy their absence?
</P>
<P>
   Wes Patrick claims some insider knowledge on the subject.
</P>
<P>
   ``St. Patrick was my great-great-great-great-uncle,'' said the
non-sainted Patrick, owner of Critter Control, a company that
specializes in trapping animals.
</P>
<P>
   The lineage claim is a load of blarney. But seriously, Patrick
said, a cold snap would rid the state of snakes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Move Arizona to the Antarctic,'' he suggested, ``because the
cold would either make them hibernate forever or make them leave.
You'd have to change the climate.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe, but the only foolproof way to get rid of snakes is to
eliminate their food source, he said, and with all the furry little
critters running around in Arizona, that's unlikely. Still, that's
how.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what my great-great-great-great-uncle would have done
if he hadn't been such a great preacher,'' Patrick said.
</P>
<P>
   Our gift to LA
</P>
<P>
   Har. He knows a sermon wouldn't work.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not the kind I would deliver, anyway,'' he said. ``I know I've
heard people pray for them to leave. I've heard people cuss them.''
Neither worked.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Organ, a dispatch supervisor for Rural/Metro Fire
Department (which removes snakes from yards), liked the idea of the
staff, although he sounded like he had St. Patrick mixed up with
the Pied Piper.
</P>
<P>
   ``Instead of chasing them into the sea . . . I would probably
just have them follow me into the LA basin,'' he said. ``They've
got to go somewhere, and what better place than LA?''
</P>
<P>
   A good start. The leftovers can slither their way to Washington,
D.C.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, some question the saintliness of the whole idea.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why would you want to get rid of them?'' asked Gavin
Gallifant, owner of First and Last Pest Control. ``They're
incredible rodent feeders. If we did that, we'd be overpopulated
with rodents. I know the serpent has a bad rap, but they actually
are very beneficial to the environment. I wouldn't do it. That's
the bottom line.''
</P>
<P>
   You've got to admire him for sticking to his principles. But
don't hold your breath for St. Gavin's Day anytime soon. &QL; 
Bill Goodykoontz can be reached at 444-8828, or at
bill.goodykoontz(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
