<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK TIMES CORRECTIONS FOR WEDNESDAY, MARCH 17
</HEADLINE>
 Eds.: These corrections will appear in The New York Times on
Wednesday. Days and dates refer to the original article's
transmission by the New York Times News Service, and may need to be
adjusted by NYT clients.)  
(gc) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BC-SALMON-PROTECTION-NYT (moved on Monday, Mar. 15)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Monday, Mar. 15,
about threats to Pacific salmon misstated the planned
classification of the fish. Federal officials proposed to declare
that eight of nine wild salmon types in the Pacific Northwest would
be listed as threatened species. Only one type, not all, would be
listed as endangered. The Endangered Species Act allows officials
more time to develop protections for species listed as threatened
than it does for those with the more serious classification of
endangered.
</P>
<P>
   BC-LOS-ALAMOS-SECURITY-NYT (moved on Thursday, Mar. 10)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Thursday, Mar. 10,
about security concerns at Los Alamos National Laboratory referred
incorrectly to the case of Julius and Ethel Rosenberg, who were
executed in 1953 for espionage. They were convicted of having
conspired with David Greenglass, an engineer at Los Alamos, not of
having acted as couriers for two other workers at Los Alamos _
Klaus Fuchs and Ted Hall _ who spied for the Soviet Union.
</P>
<P>
   BC-SPAIN-FILM-NYT (moved on Monday, Mar. 15)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Monday, Mar. 15,
about a scandal in Spain's film industry misidentified the party in
a dispute who apologized. A producer, Andres Vicente Gomez, called
a director, Jose Luis Garci, a coward for not attending the Spanish
film academy's annual awards ceremony in January, and Mr. Vicente
Gomez apologized the next day. It was not Mr. Garci who apologized.
</P>
</TEXT>
