<SLUG> BC-TRAIN-SAFETY-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WRECK-SITE CROSSING CONSIDERED STATE OF THE ART 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ill., Conn., Texas, Ind.)  (See also TRAIN-CRASH, TRAIN-SCENE) 
(ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By MATTHEW L. WALD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The federal government says it has been working
hard since 1991 to reduce the chances of train-vehicle collisions
like the one Monday night in Bourbonnais, Ill., but the railroad
crossing there was one the government said had already been fixed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It had the best we've got,'' said Jolene Molitoris,
administrator of the Federal Railroad Administration.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Molitoris said the Bourbonnais crossing had gates, lights
and a computerized system designed to ensure that warning lights
flash and the gates come down 25 to 30 seconds before a train
arrives, regardless of its speed. If gates come down more than 30
seconds in advance, drivers may gradually become convinced that the
warning system is crying wolf and that they have time to go around.
</P>
<P>
   The improvements in Bourbonnais cost about $150,000 five years
ago, making it one of the best-equipped of the approximately
260,000 grade-level railroad crossings in the country, Ms.
Molitoris said. Only about 62,000 crossings, fewer than 40 percent,
have any active warning system _ gates, lights or bells.
</P>
<P>
   The federal Transportation Department is testing systems that
are more difficult to circumvent. One, in Mystic, Conn., has gates
that come down over all four lanes of the road, so a driver cannot
cross the double yellow line and drive around them.
</P>
<P>
   In this fiscal year, the Transportation Department is providing
$154.8 million to states to improve crossings. A flashing signal
system can cost $60,000, and a gate across a single lane can cost
$15,000. An overpass or tunnel costs millions of dollars.
Improvements are made by local or state highway departments, or the
railroads themselves, not the federal government.
</P>
<P>
   The Transportation Department is trying to reduce the number of
crossings so that improvements can be concentrated on those that
remain.
</P>
<P>
   ``The best crossing is the one that doesn't exist,'' said Warren
Flateau, a department spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   When the federal government began its campaign in 1991, there
were more than 290,000 grade-level crossings, but by this year,
33,000 of them had been closed. The goal is to eliminate at least
another 30,000.
</P>
<P>
   The strategy is working, officials say. Last year there were 422
deaths in crossing accidents, down one-third from five years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The small towns around Chicago, long a railroad hub, are ground
zero for such accidents. Seven high school students died in 1995 in
Fox River Grove when a train plowed into the back of their school
bus while it was stopped for a traffic light, its rear hanging over
the tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 3,030 accidents at public railroad crossings counted by
the Federal Railroad Administration in 1998, 175 were in Illinois.
Only two states had more, Texas, with 282, and Indiana, with 178.
Amtrak was involved in 139.
</P>
<P>
   The numbers are gradually improving; in 1995, there were 4,154
such accidents, more than a third more than in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   According to the Federal Railroad Administration, the number of
train-vehicle collisions is falling in Illinois, too, down 15
percent since 1996.
</P>
<P>
   The agency has tried a variety of tactics to reduce collisions.
In an effort to improve law enforcement, it has arranged for police
officers to ride in the cabs of freight trains, so they can see how
many drivers or pedestrians dash across the tracks in front of
them.
</P>
<P>
   After the Fox River Grove collision, the Illinois Legislature
set a minimum fine of $500 or 50 hours of community service for
drivers or pedestrians who cross in front of trains.
</P>
<P>
   Passenger trains running at 79 mph can take more than a mile to
stop; freight trains travel at slower speeds but they typically
have more cars, and can take just as long or longer to stop. Making
trains stop faster is difficult, so many locomotives have been made
more conspicuous by the addition of ``ditch lights,'' a set of
headlights at the lower left and right, to join the traditional
cyclops eye mounted near the top.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
