<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FINLEY, GREENE HAPPY WITH DEBUTS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, Ariz. -- Chuck Finley and Todd Greene both were in a
particularly good mood after playing in Tuesday's game against the
Chicago White Sox at Tempe Diablo Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   And with good reason.
</P>
<P>
   Finley (muscle strain upper back/neck) made his first start of
the spring on the mound and Greene (bad right shoulder) made his
first appearance at catcher. Both said they came away feeling good.
</P>
<P>
   ``Did Greenie tell you the joke I told him?'' Finley asked
reporters. ``I told Greenie that we got a letter from Disney today
saying if we didn't get in a game by today they'd cut off our
workman's comp.''
</P>
<P>
   Finley made 24 pitches in one inning. He struck out the first
two batters he faced, gave up a single to Jeff Abbott, then got
Paul Konerko on a grounder to short.
</P>
<P>
   ``The good thing about it is I walked on the field and I walked
off the field under my own power,'' he said. ``I planned on
throwing all fastballs but the way my fastball was in the 'pen, I
didn't think I'd get too far. My split was there, my curveball was
decent, so I said heck, why not use them all.''
</P>
<P>
   Finley's opening day start is still a question, but he says as
long as he is ready to jump in the rotation the first time around,
he'll be happy.
</P>
<P>
   ``The good thing is it's not like I've been shut down, I've been
throwing,'' he said. ``I can make steps forward because I'm not
that far behind.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Greene caught three innings. Although he was charged
with a passed ball, he blocked a couple balls in the dirt and
picked a runner off first base. One runner tried to steal on him,
but he lost the handle of the ball and didn't make the throw to
second.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way I feel now I could catch tomorrow,'' Greene said. ``I
don't think that would be wise at this point because I don't
necessarily have to be ready. ... My legs are more sore than my
shoulder, so that's good.''
</P>
<P>
   The one play that tested his shoulder came in the third inning
when a pitch from Jarrod Washburn was in the dirt. Greene blocked
the ball and threw to first to catch the baserunner Abbott leaning
too far off the bag.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't feel it at all,'' Greene said. ``That's the throw I
would think would bother it, because it was an off-balance throw.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way it feels I don't think I'll have any problems. I'll
have the normal aches and pains, but I don't think I'll have
anything that will keep me from catching.''
</P>
<P>
   Angels manager Terry Collins called it a big day, but cautioned
there is still a ways to go.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're starting to mend,'' he said. ``Getting those two guys
out there was really nice but we can't get carried away. We have to
realize it's the first step of two weeks left in camp. It's still a
matter of how we come out of here and what kind of shape they're in
by the end of camp.''
</P>
<P>
   Troy Glaus played all nine innings at shortstop in Tuesday's 4-3
loss the the White Sox. He played four innings on Sunday at short
in a split-squad game, but Collins didn't get a chance to see him
then.
</P>
<P>
   Glaus, who was a shortstop at UCLA, looked comfortable there but
did make one error.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to take time to get used to it,'' Glaus said.
``Reading the ball off the bat, things like that. But I played
there a long time. If I didn't, it would be a different story. ...
As many things you can do on the baseball field is going to help
you chances of making the team.''
</P>
<P>
   Rex Hudler, the ex-Angel and new colorman on Angels broadcasts
for KCAL-9 and Fox Sports West, is in town to work on some mock
broadcasts. He took in Tuesday's game from the press box, but
obviously still has quite a bit of player in him.
</P>
<P>
   When the Angels' Randy Velarde led off the first inning with a
home run, Hudler had trouble controlling himself in a place where
cheering is not allowed: ``Oh, baby, he got around on that one!
That-a-way RV!''
</P>
<P>
   After being told the press box rules, Hudler apologized.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels will wear green caps today for St. Patrick's Day. ...
The Milwaukee Brewers will visit the Angels today in Tempe. Tim
Belcher will start for the Angels against the Brewers' Rafael Roque
at 12:05.
</P>
</TEXT>
