<SLUG> BC-MEDICARE17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    MEDICARE COMMISSION FAILS TO ADOPT PLAN
 &HT;    480&AMP;add.
 &HT;    By LARRY LIPMAN
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Torn by profound differences over what the
government's role should be in providing health care for seniors, a
bipartisan commission ended its 15-month mission Tuesday without
adopting a plan to reform Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   The 17-member panel voted on recommending a proposal to
Congress, but fell one vote short of the 11 votes required.
</P>
<P>
   The plan would have dramatically transformed the Medicare
program from one in which the government pays for health care to
one in which the government provides ``premium support,'' helping
people buy private health coverage.
</P>
<P>
   The plan also would have gradually raised the eligibility age
from 65 to 67, matching the Social Security eligibility age.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's action is likely to become the first step in a process
that could consume much of the rest of this congressional term.
Although the commission's plan will not be formally recommended to
Congress, it had the support of three members of the Senate Finance
Committee _ which writes Medicare law _ and was co-sponsored by the
chairman of the House Ways and Means health subcommittee, which
also has jurisdiction over Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   ``I fully intend to take this document, which a majority of the
commission supports, and introduce bipartisan legislation to begin
moving this through the legislative process,'' said Sen. John
Breaux, D-La., the panel's chairman and author of the plan.
</P>
<P>
   Three hours before the final roll call was taken, President
Clinton predicted the outcome and said he would offer Congress his
own Medicare reform proposal.
</P>
<P>
   The president said he hoped for action before the end of the
year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Medicare is too important to let partisan politics stand in
the way of vital progress. I believe if we make the hard choices,
if we work together, if we act this year, we can secure Medicare
into the future,'' Clinton said in a Rose Garden statement.
</P>
<P>
   Medicare, which covers nearly 39 million elderly and disabled
beneficiaries, is expected to run out of money for its hospital
insurance trust fund in 2008, about the time that the first of 77
million baby boomers start to become eligible for coverage.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of the Breaux plan predicted it would slow the
increase in Medicare costs over the next decade and allow the
program to continue operating until 2013 or 2017.
</P>
<P>
   They also claimed the plan would foster competition among
insurance companies and managed care groups, giving Medicare
beneficiaries a greater choice of health coverage offering a wider
range of benefits. Another part of the plan would have extended
prescription drug coverage to those at or near the poverty level.
</P>
<P>
   But critics of the plan warned that it ran the risk of excluding
the oldest, sickest and poorest Medicare beneficiaries from
enhanced managed care coverage while costing them considerably more
than they would pay under the current program.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   They argued that those risks were not worth it for a plan that
would not significantly extend the solvency of the Medicare
program.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said the plan ``falls short'' because raising the
eligibility age without ensuring insurance coverage for those over
55 could increase the number of uninsured Americans.
</P>
<P>
   He also said he was concerned about the potential for
significant premium increases, and criticized the panel for not
embracing his plan to earmark 15 percent of the projected federal
budget surplus over 15 years _ about $700 billion _ to shore up the
Medicare program until 2020.
</P>
<P>
   The commission was supposed to have completed its work by March
1, but delayed a final vote until this week in a last-ditch effort
to forge a compromise.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
