</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HARVARD-ANGST-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHOULD HARVARD MAKE SURE ITS STUDENTS GO OUT AND PLAY?
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(dal) 
 By JULIE FLAHERTY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAMBRIDGE, Mass. _ For the first time anyone here can remember,
Harvard College is wondering whether it should find a way to get
students out of their rooms and away from their books to _ gasp _
relax and socialize.
</P>
<P>
   A survey by The Harvard Crimson, the student newspaper, brought
the question to the forefront last month when it asked
undergraduates something that many of them seemed to be too busy to
think about: their happiness.
</P>
<P>
   Among other things, it found that 64 percent of the students
said they stayed in their rooms at least every other weekend to do
homework, with about 45 percent saying they would like to stay in
less often.
</P>
<P>
   Almost half of the 211 men and 210 women surveyed said they had
two hours of free time a day, or less. But even those minutes are
not stress-free; about the same number said they often felt guilty
about the way they spent that free time. And 36 percent said that
while at Harvard they had never had a romantic relationship that
lasted more than a week.
</P>
<P>
   The telephone survey, conducted over a weekend using a list of
undergraduates selected at random from the student directory, arose
from a widespread feeling that something was missing from campus
life.
</P>
<P>
   While many institutions of higher education, including Harvard,
are playing a growing role in regulating students' behavior outside
class _ with restrictions on fraternities, alcohol consumption and
late-night parties _ the Crimson survey raises a question on the
other side of that trend: Does a college have a responsibility to
make sure its students go out and play?
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, the Harvard administration is divided on the
issue.
</P>
<P>
   Archie C. Epps III, the dean of students, said he had tried for
years to tell students that misery was not a required course.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would like to see people slow down and smell the roses, if
you would,'' Epps said, ``and take a moment to enjoy the charm of a
Harvard building, and also reflect on those things that could
produce a philosophy of life.''
</P>
<P>
   He said Harvard owed its students fulfillment, and not just
academically. More play space, for starters: His dream is to bring
a barn from New Hampshire, put it on the quad, and turn it into a
disco on the weekends.
</P>
<P>
   Students may have become so harried and competitive, Epps
continued, that they are afraid to start relationships. ``It's
hard,'' he said. ``Maybe they kind of frighten each other. It's
sort of a look right, look left, who's going to win?''
</P>
<P>
   Harry R. Lewis, the dean of Harvard College, agreed that times
have changed; when he was an undergraduate in the 1960s, no one
complained about such things.
</P>
<P>
   So Lewis said he was surprised that students would turn to the
institution to provide a quote-unquote social life, and he added
that the term itself had a code meaning: ``Going to a party where
there is alcohol _ that is social life.''
</P>
<P>
   Some students hear about the parties at their friends' colleges
and expect the same sort of life style, Lewis said. He told The
Crimson that attending Harvard was ``a rare and precious
privilege'' that should not be wasted. And he pointed out that
Harvard had increased its financial aid budget last year, in part
to give more free time to students who would otherwise have to get
a paying job.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond that, Lewis said, dragging students out of their rooms
does not need to be a priority.
</P>
<P>
   Many undergraduates agree. Some are happy, some are miserable,
and some are happy being miserable. About 13 percent said the
success of their Harvard experience was not contingent on their
being happy.
</P>
<P>
   Jung E. Oh, a junior, told The Crimson: ``The place expects me
to work hard, and I do, and I like it. For me, academic intensity
brings happiness.''
</P>
<P>
   Benjie Flusberg, a sophomore, said that he knew people who did
nothing but study, but that he was not sure what the college could
do for them. ``The only thing the school could do is give less
homework,'' Flusberg said.
</P>
<P>
   Even if Harvard offered more dances and parties, there is no
guarantee that students would abandon their studious ways.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really a conundrum,'' said James Y. Stern, a writer of
The Crimson's survey article. ``There's not much you can do to
force people to have a good time. It stems from how competitive the
world of Harvard has become. You just get people who are
hyper-driven at the age of 17.''
</P>
<P>
   Epps said that just getting students to assess their life style
was a good start.
</P>
<P>
   ``Often,'' he said, ``they don't realize until they look back on
their freshmen and sophomore years and say, `What was that all
about?'''
</P>
</TEXT>
