<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-NUKE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NUCLEAR LAPSES KNOWN IN '96, ADMINISTRATION AIDES NOW SAY
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By JEFF GERTH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In late 1996, months earlier than previously
acknowledged, a senior Clinton administration official ordered that
security measures at the nation's nuclear weapons laboratories be
quickly strengthened, but his orders were largely ignored or
delayed, administration officials said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Until now, senior administration officials had said that they
first learned of the security lapses at the labs in the summer of
1997 and took prompt action.
</P>
<P>
   But eight months earlier, in November 1996, Charles Curtis, the
deputy secretary of energy, ordered a series of security measures
to be carried out on a strict timetable over the next several
months, the officials said.
</P>
<P>
   But those measures were not taken, the officials said, despite
the warning in the department's annual security review for 1996
that the Energy Department was ``at greater risk of becoming a
victim of espionage than at any time in its history.''
</P>
<P>
   Officials said Tuesday that this inaction was largely owing to a
change in leadership at the Energy Department. Federico Pena became
secretary of energy in March 1997 and Curtis left office one month
later.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm looking into this possible lapse,'' Bill Richardson, who
succeeded Pena last year, said in a telephone interview Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The timing of the administration's response to security concerns
at the Los Alamos nuclear weapons laboratory and other weapons
plants has become a political issue following reports that the
White House, the FBI and the CIA did not respond quickly to
allegations that China had stolen an important piece of nuclear
technology from Los Alamos in the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   Pena said in an interview Tuesday that he learned about Curtis'
unsuccessful effort to alert his department to security problems at
the weapons labs just this week, nine months after he left office.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first time I heard about this plan was two days ago. What
happened here?'' he said. ``This is a serious issue that should not
have fallen through the cracks.''
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't until July 1997 that Pena was briefed on Energy
Department findings that China had stolen valuable nuclear secrets
from Los Alamos National Laboratory in New Mexico in the 1980s and
that overall security measures at the weapons labs needed
significant bolstering.
</P>
<P>
   Those briefings led to a presidential directive in February 1998
and subsequent changes by Pena and his successor, Richardson.
</P>
<P>
   White House spokesman Joe Lockhart said no one at the White
House was aware of the Curtis directives until the steps leading up
to the presidential directive, and that the president's orders
``went well beyond what Curtis did.''
</P>
<P>
   Last week, President Clinton said his administration had
promptly addressed the security problems at the weapons labs. ``The
record is we acted aggressively,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials say they know of no security breaches
that resulted from the failure to adopt Curtis' directives in a
timely fashion.
</P>
<P>
   But other administration officials and some in Congress say the
administration acted too slowly. They say the administration and
some of the labs feared that too much security would get in the way
of efforts to use weapons labs to deepen ties with countries like
China by encouraging scientific visits aimed at improving nuclear
safety. It was not until last fall, for example, that background
checks on foreign visitors to the weapons labs were reinstated, two
years after Curtis directed just that, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, under sharp questioning from senators, Richardson
defended the steps his agency has taken since last fall to combat
the theft of secret material from the nation's nuclear weapons
laboratories.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe we have successfully addressed this problem,''
Richardson said at a hearing of the Senate Armed Services
Committee. ``I believe we have strong security procedures in
place.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. John W. Warner, R-Va., who heads the committee, praised
Richardson for taking ``timely and prudent'' measures. But Warner
added, ``I cannot say the same about the administration over a
longer period of time.''
</P>
<P>
   The issue of security at the weapons labs is decades old. A 1988
study by the General Accounting Office, the investigative arm of
Congress, found lax controls over foreign visitors. A follow-up
study nine years later found things had gotten worse.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, lab experts found the first indications that China had
stolen secrets on miniaturizing nuclear bombs from Los Alamos in
the 1980s. The White House was told about this evidence in April
1996 but took no action.
</P>
<P>
   Seven months later, Curtis summoned the directors of the weapons
labs to a meeting with top Energy Department officials in
Washington on Nov. 21, 1996, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   At the meeting Curtis ordered a series of actions affecting both
the labs and top Energy Department officials.
</P>
<P>
   They included, officials said, the following: creating a new
tracking system for foreign visitors, revising guidelines to insure
background checks for foreign visitors, increasing
counterintelligence training for officials at the labs and the
Energy Department, preparing annual security reviews and requiring
labs to critique their own security programs.
</P>
<P>
   The self-critique was completed on time, but many of the others
lagged as Curtis became a lame duck. A few weeks after the meeting
the Pentagon sponsored a visit by China's defense minister to one
of the weapons labs without receiving proper clearances, officials
said.
</P>
<P>
   Pena says he talked to Curtis this week and ``he remembers
telling me that I should get a general brief on the espionage
matter and counterintelligence issues,'' but Pena said he doesn't
remember any such conversation.
</P>
<P>
   Curtis, now a Washington lawyer and the administration's current
choice to be nominated for secretary of the Air Force, declined to
discuss the matter Tuesday when reached by telephone.
</P>
<P>
   After Curtis left in 1997, his counterintelligence plan became
``an orphan,'' one official said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We couldn't get an order requiring the labs to report to
counterintelligence officials when the Chinese were present,'' the
official added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
