<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ECUADOR-CRISIS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOME URGE DRASTIC MEASURES AS CRISIS GRIPS ECUADOR 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: A tilde is needed over second n in El Nino)  
 
By JOHN OTIS 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   QUITO, Ecuador _ With their country paralyzed by strikes, their
currency losing value and their politicians so far unable to
provide relief, some Ecuadoreans are calling for drastic measures
to end the chaos.
</P>
<P>
   In the face of what has been called Ecuador's worst economic
crisis in 70 years, opposition leaders are demanding the
resignation of President Jamil Mahuad, who took office seven months
ago.
</P>
<P>
   Military officers are reportedly discontent, although the armed
forces have largely stayed out of politics since democracy was
established 20 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Mahuad, a bookish economist who graduated from Harvard, has
grown weary of clashing with legislators, who have blocked key
bills designed to put the moribund economy back on track.
</P>
<P>
   According to politicians and U.S. Ambassador Leslie M.
Alexander, Mahuad and his advisers have considered closing the
Congress and ruling by decree. But, so far, they have done nothing
more than talk about the idea. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; ``Yes, that has been discussed,'' said Alexander, who spoke
with Mahuad at the presidential palace Monday.
</P>
<P>
   But no matter how attractive the notion of closing the Congress
might be, ``I think that enough level-headed people understand that
it is not an option,'' Alexander said.
</P>
<P>
   The ambassador insisted that Ecuador's democracy is ``alive and
well.''
</P>
<P>
   On the streets of Quito and other cities Tuesday, however, the
scene looked more like anarchy.
</P>
<P>
   Thousands of taxi drivers blocked roads for the second straight
day to protest steep increases in gasoline prices ordered by Mahuad
as an emergency measure to raise government revenue.
</P>
<P>
   Irate truckers joined the strike, as Indian groups blocked
sections of the Pan-American Highway, the principle north-south
route connecting Ecuador with Peru and Colombia.
</P>
<P>
   Transportation and commerce in many cities were brought to a
standstill, though some people moved about on foot and bicycle.
Some deputies were unable to get to the congressional building to
discuss emergency legislation demanded by Mahuad.
</P>
<P>
   The nation's banks reopened Monday following a five-day shutdown
ordered by the government. But many customers were furious when
they found out that their savings and checking accounts had been
partially frozen for up to a year to prevent capital flight.
</P>
<P>
   Falling oil prices, severe flood damage from the El Nino weather
pattern last year and government spending have resulted in a budget
deficit equal to 7 percent of the gross domestic product.
</P>
<P>
   Mahuad has tried to raise taxes, cut spending, privatize state
institutions and reach an accord with the International Monetary
Fund. But most of the measures have been blocked by populist
legislators. The dispute has eaten away at Mahuad's support and has
prevented Ecuador from receiving up to $800 million in financing
from the IMF.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no reason why we could not authorize for Ecuador an
aid package that is proportionally as strong as it was for Mexico a
few years ago and for Brazil now,'' IMF Director Michel Camdessus
said on Ecuadorean television. ``The only thing that keeps us from
doing it now is the fact that there is no unity in Ecuador behind
an emergency program.''
</P>
<P>
   The gridlock has led to speculation that Mahuad could stage a
so-called ``self-coup'' by closing the Congress and temporarily
ruling by decree.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Luis Mejia, a deputy allied with Mahuad, called on
the Congress to close itself down. And during call-in programs on
Ecuadorean radio stations, a handful of people endorsed the idea.
</P>
<P>
   ``Either he reaches an accord with the Congress or he has to
pull off a self-coup,'' said Enrique Galarza, dean of public
administration at the Catholic University in Quito. ``There is no
other way out.''
</P>
<P>
   In neighboring Peru, President Alberto Fujimori assumed
authoritarian powers for eight months in 1992 to combat guerrilla
violence and to sidestep obstructionist legislators. Venezuelan
President Hugo Chavez, who attempted to overthrow the government in
1992 as a junior army officer, has threatened to close his
country's Congress if it blocks his reform program.
</P>
<P>
   But analysts contend that such drastic moves require grass-roots
support and collaboration from the armed forces, which Mahuad
apparently lacks. A recent poll put Mahuad's job-approval rating at
16 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Paco Moncayo, a centrist congressman and a former head of the
armed forces, said that a military uprising is also extremely
remote.
</P>
<P>
   Although he believes that military leaders have no stomach for
inheriting the nation's economic mess, Alexander said that there
are rumblings within the institution.
</P>
<P>
   ``The military is feeling the same frustration as the people on
the street,'' the U.S. ambassador said. ``They want things to
change.''
</P>
<P>
   Fueling the protests against Mahuad is what one Western diplomat
described as Ecuador's tradition of ``political cannibalism.'' The
country has had four presidents in the past 25 months. Such
instability has given hope to protesters that Mahuad will step
down.
</P>
<P>
   But unlike former President Abdala Bucaram _ who had lost
virtually all of his support when he was forced from office in 1997
_ Mahuad retains the backing of businessmen and the upper-middle
class.
</P>
<P>
   Some say that drastic measures can be avoided if Mahuad forms an
alliance with other parties.
</P>
<P>
   The president's center-right Popular Democracy Party lacks a
majority in the 121-seat Congress and had counted on the support of
the right-wing Social Christian Party. But the Social Christians
ended up blocking many of Mahuad's bills.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most (politicians) recognize that they've got to reach some
kind of accommodation,'' the Western diplomat said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
