<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GAMBLER-DEATH-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FLASHY LAS VEGAS GAMBLER WAS KILLED, DID NOT COMMIT SUICIDE,
AUTHORITIES SAY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service Clients) 
By BARRY SHLACHTER 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   After stashing $4 million in silver in an underground vault near
Las Vegas, the son closest in character to legendary Texas gambler
Benny Binion died when someone gave him a lethal dose of heroin and
a prescription tranquilizer, Xanax, authorities say.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's revelation by a Nevada coroner was the latest twist in
a mystery that has been slowly unraveling since the girlfriend of
55-year-old Ted Binion reported finding his lifeless body on Sept.
17.
</P>
<P>
   A reward for his killer was immediately raised to $100,000 from
$25,000 by his brother, Jack Binion, executor of his estate.
</P>
<P>
   Ted Binion was born in North Texas where his flamboyant father
still had many admirers, including Billy Bob Barnett who erected a
$150,000 statue of Binion outside Billy Bob's Texas, the
self-described World's Largest Honky-Tonk. The statue was shipped
to Las Vegas in 1988, a year before the elder Binion's death from
natural causes at 83.
</P>
<P>
   Yesterday, investigators would not say how the drugs were
administered to Ted Binion, or whether they had a suspect in his
death. Heroin was found in Binion's stomach, although he was known
to have smoked the drug before reportedly kicking the habit earlier
in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are numerous scenarios,'' Clark County Coroner Ron Flud
said on Tuesday. ``We're not to the point we're going to comment on
any of the scenarios.''
</P>
<P>
   The girlfriend, ex-topless dancer Sandy Murphy, 27, and three
others were arrested on charges of stealing Ted Binion's buried
treasure two days after his death. Jack Binion said one of them,
Richard Tabish, 33, was romantically linked with Murphy. Tabish, a
twice-convicted felon, built the underground vault. All have denied
the charges.
</P>
<P>
   Ted Binion had the vault constructed on his Pahrump, Nev., ranch
after losing an 11-year battle to keep his gaming license. It was
finally revoked a year ago because of his friendship with
underworld figure Herbert Blitzstein, the victim of a
gangland-style killing in January 1997, authorities say.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, he and his brother Jack sold their share of the $80
million Horsehoe gaming empire to a sister, Becky Behnen, following
a drawn-out feud.
</P>
<P>
   Like his father, Ted Binion's life had it's breathtaking ups and
downs.
</P>
<P>
   While brother Jack and sister Becky were said to have their
father's gambling business acumen, it was Ted who inherited his
larger-than-life Texas personna.
</P>
<P>
   ``I started learning (the gaming business) when I was 12,'' Ted
Binion told The Wall Street Journal three weeks before his death.
</P>
<P>
   In 1947, Benny Binion brought his family to Las Vegas from the
Fort Worth-Dallas area, as legend had it, with $2 million packed in
a suitcase. He had run an illegal, but rarely prosecuted, gambling
operation at the Top of the Hill Terrace speak-easy, built on an
unincorporated patch between Fort Worth and Arlington _ now a
Baptist seminary _ and another gaming club in west Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   Nicknamed ``The Cowboy,'' he served prison time for bootlegging
during Prohibition and for tax evasion in the 1950s. &QL; 
(Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
