<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-16 21:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2980 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CALIF-CLASSROOMS-ART-     03-16 0954
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CALIF-CLASSROOMS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMID CLAMOR FOR COMPUTER IN EVERY CLASSROOM, SOME DISSENTING
VOICES
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(dal) 
 By TOM ZELLER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Zenobia Barlow remembers when the frenzy over computers in the
classroom came to California. As director of the Center for
Ecoliteracy, a nonprofit foundation in San Francisco, she had long
shepherded money to elementary schools seeking to involve students
in hands-on science projects like local creek-bed restoration and
organic gardening.
</P>
<P>
   But by 1996, Ms. Barlow says, more and more parents and teachers
were telling her: ``This is nice. But where are the computers?''
</P>
<P>
   Although grade schools, especially in well-off suburbs, had long
used the computer as a teaching tool, more and more were coming to
rely on it; for many students, escaping the classroom was looking
less like a sojourn to the local watershed and more like an
afternoon spent staring at a screen.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was this increasing pressure in the earlier and earlier
grades for children to be involved with computers,'' Ms. Barlow
recalled.
</P>
<P>
   That was when her center hired William L. Rukeyser, a
51-year-old consultant who had done public relations for the
California Department of Education, to found Learning in the Real
World, a nonprofit organization that has become a rallying point
for those who would like to take the steam out of the drive to
computerize classrooms.
</P>
<P>
   At a time when conventional wisdom holds that computers and
technology are as essential to schools as blackboards and libraries
_ when President Clinton trumpets his goal of ``connecting every
classroom in America to the Internet by the year 2000'' _
Rukeyser's organization is the skunk at the garden party.
</P>
<P>
   It has blanketed news organizations, lawmakers, school systems
and parent groups with phone calls, faxes, reprints of articles and
slickly produced brochures asking if connecting ``every classroom
in America'' to the Internet makes sense. This year, it has awarded
$54,000 in grants for research into how computers are affecting
education, especially in the early grades, and whether they are
being overemphasized. Rukeyser says the group gets its money from
its parent, the Center for Ecoliteracy.
</P>
<P>
   ``So many programs were being slaughtered by this perception
that if it didn't involve computers, it wasn't worth anything,''
Rukeyser said. ``I quickly realized that there was this tremendous
faith that computers were in fact some plaster saint that would
save the day.'''
</P>
<P>
   Rukeyser's group is fighting a powerful tide. In just six years,
the number of computers in public schools has more than doubled, to
7.4 million in 1998. Spending on instructional technology from
kindergarten through grade 12 rose sharply as well, to more than $5
billion last year from $2.1 billion in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   But dissenters like Rukeyser are beginning to make their voices
heard, with even supporters of educational technology acknowledging
that they may have a point.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hope we're reaching a point of maturation in all this,''
said Dr. John Bosco, a professor at Western Michigan University who
is chairman of the Consortium for School Networking, a nonprofit
group that promotes technology in schools. ``We're beginning to see
that it is not magic, and that there are things done in the name of
information technology which are either foolish or wasteful.''
</P>
<P>
   Bosco added that educators and researchers were starting to ask
more sophisticated questions about computers' role in the
classroom.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem is that both proponents and opponents are looking
for the magic fountain,'' he said. ``They're looking for a study
which would demonstrate that computers do good things for learning,
but I can tell you that's never going to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Linda Roberts, director of the Office for Educational Technology
in the federal Department of Education, agreed that computers and
Internet connections were ``simply the starting point,'' but she
added, ``I think there is sufficient evidence out there right now
to support the investment that we're making in technology.''
</P>
<P>
   One of Learning in the Real World's grant recipients, Dr. Larry
Cuban, a professor of education at Stanford University and the
author of ``Teachers and Machines: The Classroom Use of Technology
Since 1920,'' agrees.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no question that computers have an initial novelty
effect,'' Cuban said. ``The kid gets immediate feedback _ can in
effect talk to the computer, and the computer responds. This whole
issue of a human-machine interaction is very engaging for kids. But
how long it lasts depends a great deal on the teacher's use of it
and the particular software.''
</P>
<P>
   Cuban and three other researchers plan to use the money from
Learning in the Real world to investigate just what it is that
teachers and students are doing with the computers that are
provided for them. Cuban in particular will be focusing on computer
use in preschools and kindergartens _ precisely the age level,
Rukeyser and Ms. Barlow say, at which children might be better off
planting seeds and digging in the dirt, rather than surfing the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, Rukeyser says he will continue to make phone
calls, send faxes and show up at events like last month's
Conference of the Consortium for School Networking in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically, our approach to all this is that we're skeptical,''
he said. ``We're not pushing our own brand of solution, and we're
not saying that the emperor has no clothes. We're just asking, Is
his tie on straight and do his socks match?'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
