<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-REVOLUTION-HARKES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HARKES HEADED TO REVOLUTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- John Harkes seems to fit in well in Foxborough. With
the US national team and D.C. United, he has lost only once in
regulation time in 12 matches at Foxboro Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Now he hopes to continue his success as a member of the
Revolution.
</P>
<P>
   The Revolution Tuesday announced the acquisition of Harkes, who
had played three games on loan to Nottingham Forest in England
before suffering a calf injury. Harkes will join the team for
training Monday in preparation for its Major League Soccer season
opener at Miami March 28.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything was going well here, I had a good rapport with the
fans and was getting some good writeups,'' Harkes said from the
Village Hotel in Nottingham Tuesday night. ``But I tore my calf
muscle against West Ham and time was running out on the loan. The
manager wants me to stay and play to the end of the season with the
option to take me on full-time, but I don't think that is in my
best interests. I want to get back and commit 100 percent to the
Revolution.''
</P>
<P>
   Though Harkes turned 32 early this month and is likely past his
prime, the Revolution are hoping his experience and winning habits
will help elevate the team. The Revolution have failed to win a
playoff game in three years and had the league's worst record last
season.
</P>
<P>
   ``New England is the team I wanted to go to,'' Harkes said.
``Foxboro Stadium is a great atmosphere and one of the best venues
I've played in in 11 years with the national team.''
</P>
<P>
   Harkes became available when D.C. United's player budget
exceeded the salary cap. He was considered expendable, but other
teams were reluctant to acquire him. Though Harkes is among the
most accomplished US players of his generation, his stock fell
after he was dropped from the national team before the '98 World
Cup. Many coaches were discomfited by his clashes with former US
coach Steve Sampson.
</P>
<P>
   But Revolution player-coach Walter Zenga did not hesitate to
court Harkes, who was acquired for two draft choices.
</P>
<P>
   ``Walter wants to have me in the center of midfield,'' Harkes
said. ``If he needs me on the right or left, I'll do whatever it
takes to help out the club. Right now, I want to concentrate on
being healthy and settling into the club.
</P>
<P>
   ``I look forward to starting fresh with a new club in a great
area with passionate fans and good people running the club who want
soccer to succeed.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Revolution have some good personalities and all we have to
do is jell together. We have to look at ourselves individually,
what we can do to make the team work. Fortunately, I've had success
and won a lot of things and my experience and enthusiasm will
hopefully come across.''
</P>
<P>
   Harkes made his international debut in 1987 and was captain of
the US national team until clashing with Sampson last year. He has
long been ambitious and outspoken, making his way into Sheffield
Wednesday's starting lineup at age 23 and remaining in England's
Premier League until the start of MLS in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had the opportunity to return to the Premier League and that
is an opportunity you can't turn away from,'' Harkes said. ``I
wanted to challenge myself and I've shown I can play at this level
in an attacking game, at a faster pace, and against the best
players in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Harkes's national team days ended abruptly, but he seems
rejuvenated by his latest England sojourn.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was difficult with the way I've represented the country for
so many years as an ambassador for the game,'' Harkes said. ``Steve
knows what happened, he made some bad choices and it's unfortunate
because we lost and the country lost.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a little setback, but with Bruce in there injecting
some new blood and combined with some veterans, the future looks
good. Bruce has done the right thing with younger players and it
should have been done years ago.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
