<SLUG> BC-TRAIN-SCENE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A LEGENDARY TRAIN'S WORST NIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ill., Miss., La., S.C.)  (See also TRAIN-CRASH, TRAIN-SAFETY) 
(mk) 
 By DIRK JOHNSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANKAKEE, Ill. _ The passenger train had just swept across the
snowy farm fields, passing a tall white grain elevator, and was
headed, a bit late, for its stop in Kankakee, an old railroad town
where the whistle echoes like a lullaby every night.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whistle, the clanging, it's a good noise,'' said Dennis
Brady, 57, who lives in Kankakee, ``a noise that's supposed to be
there.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, there was silence. And then came the sound of sirens.
</P>
<P>
   ``It happened so quickly, we didn't have time to be scared,''
said Don Allen, 80, a passenger who was unharmed. He stood in the
parking lot of a motel here Tuesday with his wife, Lois, ready to
resume a trip to see their son. ``We didn't know how bad it was
until this morning.''
</P>
<P>
   Hearing the terrible sounds of tons of metal slamming together
and seeing flames shoot into the sky, workers at a nearby
Birmingham Steel plant raced to the side of the tracks, trying to
pull passengers from the wreckage.
</P>
<P>
   The authorities said that at least 13 people had died and that
four others were believed to be missing in the wreckage, a charred
and twisted heap of steel along the Illinois Central tracks, about
50 miles south of Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   The train, the storied City of New Orleans, had traveled about
50 miles of its scheduled 934-mile journey, with several stops in
smaller cities in Mississippi.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is one of the great name trains of the 20th century,''
said H. Roger Grant, a history professor at Clemson University, and
the author of several books about rail travel.
</P>
<P>
   From the 1920s through the 1940s, the train was known for its
highbrow clientele and top-shelf amenities. Then the train became
better-known for its working-class passengers, many of them blacks
who had moved from the Mississippi Delta to industrial centers like
Chicago during the great migration that followed World War II.
</P>
<P>
   The City of New Orleans becomes virtually a local train in
Mississippi, with stops in Jackson, Yazoo City, Brookhaven, McComb
_ places where almost everyone has a friend or a relative living in
Northern cities like Chicago or Milwaukee.
</P>
<P>
   The singer Steve Goodman wrote a ballad about the train in 1970,
``The City of New Orleans,'' that makes reference to the old
freight yards in Kankakee, just a few miles from the site of the
wreck:
</P>
<P>
   ``All along the southbound odyssey, the train pulls out of
Kankakee,'' passing ``freight yards full of old black men.''
</P>
<P>
   But the rail yards have not been a big employer here for
decades. And Amtrak closed the Kankakee station in the early 1990s,
although the passenger train stops in the town four times a day.
</P>
<P>
   People like Brady, who have ridden the City of New Orleans,
speak of the wondrousness of riding the rail through the spine of
so many Midwestern and Southern towns, seeing the inside of places
that go unseen from the airplane, and even from cars, which
generally stick to the expressways that go around cities.
</P>
<P>
   ``You see another world when you take the train,'' said Brady.
``Unfortunately, we never took it all the way to New Orleans. We're
like everybody else these days, I guess. We're in too much of a
hurry to get where we're going.''
</P>
<P>
   Kankakee, a city of about 30,000 people, has been struggling to
re-invent itself in recent years, tearing down dilapidated old
buildings and courting developers of office complexes. The towns of
Bourbonnais and Bradley, meanwhile, have increasingly become
bedroom communities for Chicago commuters.
</P>
<P>
   The train wreck was just down the road from a strip of stores on
state Highway 50, just off Interstate 57.
</P>
<P>
   The brilliant sunshine on this late winter day gave these cities
an incongruously cheerful look Tuesday. There were people hanging
clothes to dry on clotheslines, and games of basketball being
played at hoops over garages.
</P>
<P>
   As people gathered in shops and restaurants Tuesday, there were
expressions of sorrow, as well as thanksgiving that apparently no
local people had been on the train.
</P>
<P>
   People who work at the hospitals here, Riverside and Provena-St.
Mary's, had been working through the night.
</P>
<P>
   Moments after the wreck, a call was issued to all doctors,
nurses and other staff workers at St. Mary's to report immediately
to the hospital, said Becky Wilder, a spokeswoman for the hospital.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had physicians running from their cars in the parking
lot,'' Ms. Wilder said. ``Within a half-hour, we had 150 doctors at
the hospital. I've never seen anything like this.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
