<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMF-GOLD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOLD PLUNGES AFTER CLINTON SUGGESTS SALES BY THE IMF
</HEADLINE>
   (dal) 
 By JONATHAN FUERBRINGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The price of gold plunged Tuesday after President Clinton
suggested that the International Monetary Fund should sell some of
its gold reserves to help reduce the debt burdens on the world's
poorest nations.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal is not new, but had been set aside several years
ago, in part because of the opposition of Germany. But after the
election of the new chancellor, Gerhard Schroeder, the sentiment
changed, opening the way to put the plan back on the table.
</P>
<P>
   Then French President Jacques Chirac suggested Monday that
France could support IMF gold sales for the same cause, aligning
another major player _ and one-time opponent _ behind the sales.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the sharp drop in gold's price on Monday and Tuesday
seemed to indicate that a lot of investors had forgotten that
selling IMF gold was a possibility, although the United States has
supported sales for some time and other countries had brought up
the subject again recently.
</P>
<P>
   ``The strange thing is that the IMF story wasn't fully in the
price,'' said Philip Klapwijk, a managing director of Gold Fields
Mineral Services Ltd. of London, which produces some of the most
closely watched research on gold.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sales are quite probable, but in the future,'' he said.
``There is a lot of preparation that would be required.''
</P>
<P>
   The price of gold for April delivery on the New York Mercantile
Exchange fell $3.70 an ounce, or 1.3 percent, to $283.90. On Monday
it dropped $5.80 an ounce. From its recent high of $295.50 an ounce
Thursday, the price of gold is off 3.9 percent and not that far
from the 19-year low it hit in August.
</P>
<P>
   What this proposal will do for the longer-term price of gold is
uncertain, but it does not look positive.
</P>
<P>
   IMF gold sales would require approval of Congress and of other
nations in the IMF. In addition, the IMF would be expected to sell
the gold in the most orderly fashion possible, if the plan was
approved, to limit its impact. And it would be some time _ maybe a
year _ before gold sales could occur.
</P>
<P>
   However, the threat of the sale would hang over the market,
making it harder for good news to lift the price. The threat of
gold sales by the world's central banks has had a negative impact
on the price of gold over the last several years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was surprised the amount of impact merely the speculation
had'' on the price of gold, said George Milling-Stanley, manager of
gold market analysis at the World Gold Council.
</P>
<P>
   The IMF has about 103 million ounces of gold and under the
Clinton administration proposal about 5 percent, or 5.2 million
ounces, would be sold. That is equal to about 6 percent of total
mine production.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton and Chirac said the money from gold sales should be used
to expand a program of debt relief for a group of 41 of the world's
poorest countries, know as Highly Indebted Poor Countries, or HIPC.
With the additional money from gold sales, the countries in that
group could be expended to 50.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, who made his proposal before a group of African
government officials, including representatives of highly indebted
countries, said he wanted ``extraordinary relief for countries
making extraordinary efforts to build working economies.''
</P>
<P>
   Traders said that some other downward pressure on gold came from
the fact that big speculators who had been betting that the price
of gold would fall had just recently backed off those positions.
That buying back of gold is what helped push the price up about $8,
to $295. With this negative news, there was an opening for them to
sell again. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
