<HEADER>
A2991 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-APPLE-SFCHRON &LR;      03-16 0528
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-APPLE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Developers to Get Apple Source Access
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; By Jon Swartz &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c 1999, San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
Joining the free-software movement, Apple Computer yesterday
introduced a new version of the Macintosh operating system for
servers and said it will allow developers access to the new
software's blueprints via the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   With the move, Apple becomes the first major computer company to
offer software designers some of its programming code secrets. The
computer-maker hopes the software giveaway will inspire more
developers to craft applications based on its Mac OS server
software.
</P>
<P>
   Just as significant, it marks the biggest endorsement yet of
``open source'' computing, in which companies and organizations use
the Net to enlist volunteer programmers and accelerate software
development.
</P>
<P>
   The tactic has been employed to particular success by supporters
of Linux, an operating system for business computers that poses a
challenge to Apple's server technology. Developers can download
Linux for free, customize it and distribute it. The program is
widely used by Internet service providers, PC makers and Web
developers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're hoping the software eventually runs on all kinds of
computers,'' Steve Jobs, Apple's interim CEO, told a gathering of
reporters and employees at the computer-maker's Cupertino campus.
``We're putting our source code and the intellectual property out
there for everyone to see.''
</P>
<P>
   Apple's decision is as competitively driven as it is benevolent,
observers said. The venerable computer-maker is butting heads in
the server market with Windows NT and different versions of Unix,
including Linux.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; ``There are societal and corporate advantages for Apple
here,'' said Richard Doherty, research director of Envisioneering
in Seaford, N.Y. ``It is making elements of its great technology
available to the public, and it is seeding the use of its operating
system.''
</P>
<P>
   Apple also said it's considering opening up some of its other
software code, though officials declined to comment further.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think more companies will make open source available,''
Avie Tevanian, Apple senior vice president of software development,
said in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   Silicon Graphics and Sun Microsystems said they are considering
making portions of their Unix operating systems available as open
source. Netscape and Apache have already opened up programming code
for the creation of Web browsers and server software, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   But don't count on Microsoft to come around anytime soon,
industry observers note.
</P>
<P>
   ``Microsoft does not have the mind set,'' Doherty said. ``Mr.
(Bill) Gates will never admit to bending to pressure. They may
volunteer code for Windows 95, but who wants buggy software?''
</P>
<P>
   Components of Mac OS X Server software are available at
 &LR; www.apple.com &LR; . Mac OS X combines features from the current Mac OS
and Next Computer's Rhapsody operating system. Apple acquired Next
in late 1996. The server software is a precursor to a major
overhaul of the Mac OS later this year.
</P>
<P>
   In related news, Apple reduced the price of its $999 Mac OS X
server to $499 for most users.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
