A2992 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHEVRON-SFCHRON &LR;      03-16 0456
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHEVRON-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Chevron Plans To Move Unit, Cut 100 Jobs
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; By Rebecca Smith &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c 1999, San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
Chevron Corp. said yesterday it will move its 321-person pipeline
unit to Houston by the end of the year, eliminating 100 jobs along
the way.
</P>
<P>
   The relocation of the pipeline unit from offices in San Ramon,
Bakersfield, Salt Lake City, New Orleans and Woodlands, Texas, is
expected to save $15 million next year.
</P>
<P>
   The San Ramon office, which currently serves as the corporate
headquarters of the pipeline unit, employs 62 in management
positions and office staff while the Bakersfield field office
employs 20 in management and operations positions.
</P>
<P>
   Plans call for the consolidation of all of the unit's offices
into a single facility in Houston by the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Fred Gorell, a spokesman for Chevron, said no information is
available yet on the number of employees who will be relocated and
which jobs will be phased out.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a difficult decision but one that is necessary to
allow Chevron to remain competitive over the long term,'' said Jeet
Bindra, president of Chevron Pipe Line Co.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Chevron said it would relocate its chemical company
from San Ramon to Houston, slashing 300 positions.
</P>
<P>
   More cuts and transfers are expected. Late last year, Chevron
Chairman Kenneth Derr said the firm will eliminate up to 1,000 jobs
in 1999 and reorganize operations with an eye toward reducing
yearly expenses by $500 million.
</P>
<P>
   The reductions are stimulated, in part, by low oil prices. The
company's net earnings plunged 39 percent in 1998 as a consequence
of oil prices that fell by half.
</P>
<P>
   Though crude oil prices have firmed this month, rising to around
$14.50 a barrel, the company continues to look at ways to
consolidate operations and cut costs. It has been trimming
expenses, systematically, since 1991. Total reductions, to date,
exceed $2.4 billion.
</P>
<P>
   It makes sense to move the pipeline unit to Texas, company
spokeswoman Dawn Soper said, because most pipeline employees
already are in Texas. The unit is responsible for managing the
transportation of crude oil, natural gas, petroleum and chemical
products through nearly 9,000 miles of Chevron pipeline in the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   Not all of Chevron's changes are taking jobs out of the Bay
Area. Last month, the oil firm said it will shift its La Habra
advanced technology unit to San Ramon in Contra Costa County. That
unit has 330 positions, though not all are expected to survive the
transfer.
</P>
<P>
   The Bay Area remains home for the greatest concentration of
Chevron workers. It has more Chevron employees, at 8,200, than the
No.2 and No.3 areas combined, Houston and Southern California.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-16-99 2142EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
