u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WOMEN-INCOME-BOS &LR;      03-16 1035
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WOMEN-INCOME-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORKING WOMEN FUELING FAMILY INCOME IN NEW ENGLAND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Servi clients)  
 By DIANE E. LEWIS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- Gains made by working women have fueled a dramatic
growth in family income in New England, evidence that women have
made significant strides in the labor force.
</P>
<P>
   Between 1983 and 1997, the real earnings of married couples with
college degrees in New England rose 45 percent, from $70,079 to
$101,780, much of that gain due to the increased earning power of
married women. Additionally, the real median income of middle-class
New England families grew one-third faster than national family
income.
</P>
<P>
   Married women working today are better educated, are higher
paid, hold better jobs, and are working more hours than ever
before, according to a study released to the Globe Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are enormous increases in New England, and they are
mostly due to the labor force involvement of wives, whose
educational attainment is rising,'' said economist Paul Harrington
of Northeastern University's Center for Labor Market Studies, who
authored the study in conjunction with Thomas Kochan of the Work
and Employment Institute at the Massachusetts Institute of
Technology.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, mothers are now working an average of 1,600
more hours per year than they did in 1983.
</P>
<P>
   Barbara Marx should know. A vice president at Fidelity
Investments, she has always worked full time. And she has continued
to do it with two children, putting in 12 hours at the office each
day before factoring in the commute, and relying heavily on a
``tremendous support system.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I have been working since before my kids were born,'' said
Marx. ``I have worked forever.''
</P>
<P>
   As the second and third generation to enter the work force in
large numbers, married women with children are now an integral part
of the middle-class wage gains that have fueled New England's
bustling economy. Between 1983 and 1997, for example, the median
earnings of married working mothers rose 77 percent, accounting for
almost two-thirds of the real income gains of such dual-earner
households. By contrast, men in such households experienced an
income gain of just 9.8 percent. In dollar amounts, however, the
median pay for men continued to be twice as much as for women.
</P>
<P>
   During the same period, married couples with some college or
post-secondary training saw their incomes increase 22.3 percent, to
$68,080 from $55,684.
</P>
<P>
   Lisa Wood, 39, a senior partner at the law firm of Nutter,
McClennen &AMP; Fish, acknowledged that if she stopped working today,
her family's lifestyle would change substantially. ``But that being
said, I would never do what I do, in terms of having a very
demanding job, for the money,'' she said. ``You have to have
passion for your work.''
</P>
<P>
   MIT's Kochan, president of the Industrial Relations Research
Association, said the percentage of married women entering New
England's labor force has increased from just under 70 percent to
nearly 80 percent over the 15-year study period. The study examined
New England and the nation as a whole, but did not look at other
regions of the country.
</P>
<P>
   The region's labor shortage, and the increased demand for
workers in such fields as financial services and high technology,
have helped professional women entering the market garner
top-paying jobs.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, experts say, working mothers' increased hours
and bigger job responsibilities are having a profound effect on
family life. ``Women are getting better jobs and their income is
now crucial to the family, but, by and large, the family has not
restructured to support working women,'' said Joan K. Peters,
author of ``When Mothers Work: Loving Our Children without
Sacrificing Ourselves.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Those who can afford it are outsourcing some of their
responsibilities to nannies, to cleaning people, to daycare,'' said
Peters, ``but they are doing that because the woman's
responsibilities at home are still not being shared equally between
men and women.''
</P>
<P>
   Even when men and women are equal partners at home, both now
face the demand of the 50- to 60-hour work week as well as the
ongoing perception among employers that leaving early to pick up a
child or attend a school conference is largely women's work. Peters
calls this situation a hidden fault-line, and she said it has led
to increased stress and anxiety among working women with children.
</P>
<P>
   In releasing their report, both Harrington and Kochan said they
are hoping to generate dialogue and solutions for working parents
whose job responsibilities are preventing them from meeting their
families' needs. Their paper, titled ``Building a Family Centered
Labor Market Policy,'' will be presented Monday at a Northeastern
University conference.
</P>
<P>
   Marx, who describes herself and her husband, an Internet
consultant, as ``equal partners,'' said they have managed by
relying on a support system of service providers, friends, and
family members. ``No matter what age your children are, if you are
working full time it is difficult, and you need a tremendous
support system,'' Marx said. ``It definitely helps if your partner
is oriented toward family, which my husband is. It also helps to
have an army of people and baby sitters.''
</P>
<P>
   Nationally, about 5.5 percent of 54 million households of
married couples currently rely on the wife to bring home the bulk
of the family paycheck, federal statistics show. Among these
dual-earner families, 22 percent of wives now earn more than their
husbands, up from 18 percent in 1987 and 4.4 percent in 1970.
</P>
<P>
   When New York-based Catalyst examined women's pay in a study of
461 female vice presidents or top executives at Fortune 1,000
companies two years ago, it found that 75 percent were primary
earners and 64 percent were married with children.
</P>
<P>
   Constance Armstrong, executive director of the Boston Club, has
noticed the changes. ``Typically, a woman is in management for 10
years before she joins the Boston Club,'' she said. ``Now, we are
seeing women coming in at younger ages. That implies to us that
women are achieving higher management positions at younger ages.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-16-99 2145EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990316.0369 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-16 21:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2996 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PHILADELPHIA-ORCHESTR     03-16 0901
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PHILADELPHIA-ORCHESTRA-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
346-9867.)
</HEADLINE>
  
 AN ORCHESTRA OUT ON A LIMB, TOUTING THE 20th CENTURY  
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)(bl) 
 By ANTHONY TOMMASINI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The directors of the Philadelphia Orchestra were not pleased to
read the headline over a recent article in The Philadelphia
Inquirer about plans for the orchestra's 1999-2000 centennial
season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Phila. Orchestra Will Leave Old Masters Behind,'' the headline
said. From a public relations standpoint, the subheading was even
worse: ``In its 100th season every piece will be from the 20th
century.''
</P>
<P>
   What? No Mozart or Brahms? Every program devoted to 20th-century
music? Not surprisingly, the orchestra's office was flooded with
calls, faxes and e-mail from irate concertgoers who feared an
entire season of tuneless, jarringly dissonant works.
</P>
<P>
   But those incredulous callers have been finding out that there
is less to fear than first imagined. During its centennial, the
Philadelphia Orchestra will offer its subscribers only works
composed during the orchestra's lifetime, which exactly encompasses
the 20th century. But that applies only to the subscription series,
which consists of 121 performances of 44 programs. The orchestra
will also present 20 nonsubscription concerts of 15 programs
(galas, holiday concerts and such) with works by Handel, Beethoven,
Tchaikovsky and other not-completely-banished old masters.
</P>
<P>
   Still, technically speaking, the Philadelphia Orchestra's
regular subscribers will face a season of music from this century,
a programming concept that no other American orchestra has tried.
</P>
<P>
   The idea is not to survey 20th-century music, but to represent
100 years of the music that the Philadelphia Orchestra has been
associated with, including the world premieres of works like
Bartok's Piano Concerto No. 3 (in 1946) and monumental compositions
championed early on by the orchestra, like Stravinsky's ``Rite of
Spring,'' which Leopold Stokowski conducted in its American
premiere in 1922.
</P>
<P>
   Philadelphia Orchestra president Joseph Kluger said he realized
that for many people, the very label ``20th-century music''
conjured up ``a stereotype of music that is by definition 12-tone
and/or atonal, and harshly dissonant.'' He was quick to point out,
however, that the 20th century is filled with ``popular and
accessible'' works, the ``kind of music that people beg for all the
time.''
</P>
<P>
   Rachmaninoff, Sibelius and Ravel are generously represented on
the subscription programs, as are Scriabin, Faure, Mahler, Poulenc,
Prokofiev and Copland _ composers who go down easily even with
timid listeners. Music by important composers like Varese,
Lutoslawski, Takemitsu and an under-40 American, Aaron Jay Kernis,
is being performed. However, there is an absence of works by those
names that mainstream audiences, however unfairly, have come to
fear, like Milton Babbitt, Elliott Carter, Pierre Boulez and
Karlheinz Stockhausen.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gurrelieder,'' a sprawling early work by Schoenberg, another
audience-intimidating name, will be performed; but this sumptuously
scored music is ``really very Romantic,'' said Simon Woods, the
orchestra's artistic administrator.
</P>
<P>
   ``The paradox,'' he added, is that ``though this is a daring
idea, the programming is, if anything, rather conservative.''
</P>
<P>
   Then just how daring can the idea be? The orchestra's directors
contend that the programming must be judged not in the context of
earlier eras, when concerts of new works were the norm, but against
today's more backward-looking mentality.
</P>
<P>
   In the 19th century, all orchestras were essentially
contemporary music ensembles, playing mostly new or recent works.
</P>
<P>
   The Philadelphia Orchestra's plan is being greeted in some
circles as a ``gutsy and timely move,'' to quote The Philadelphia
Daily News.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, in emphasizing that the old masters would be left behind,
that teasing Philadelphia Inquirer headline did pinpoint what is
arguably daring about the orchestra's centennial season. Its
20th-century programming may not be that challenging, but by
depriving subscribers of their beloved Mozart and such, the
orchestra is making a statement about the richness of this century,
and risking retribution.
</P>
<P>
   The suggestion for a 20th-century season originated with the
orchestra's music director, Wolfgang Sawallisch, which may surprise
those who know the 75-year-old German-born conductor as a man
comfortably steeped in the European classical music heritage. Once
the idea was broached and approved, the process of winnowing down
the repertory began. ``I was very impressed by Sawallisch's
willingness to make value judgments,'' Kluger said, ``and to select
works that are worthy of surviving into the next century.''
</P>
<P>
   The orchestra's choices are nonetheless likely to draw criticism
from some musicians and the more adventurous concertgoers. The
Philadelphia has not been noted for its advocacy of the century's
more challenging composers, innovators who have clearly earned a
place in the 21st century. In the last decade, there have been
attempts to correct this with premieres of single works by Luciano
Berio, Mario Davidovsky, Olivier Messiaen and Ralph Shapey. These
works are significantly absent from next season.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The Philadelphia Orchestra's more telling act of commitment to
its era may be its centennial commissions: eight composers have
been asked by the orchestra to create works to be performed over
the next three seasons. The 1999-2000 season will offer two: ``One
Heart Beating,'' for vocal soloist, chorus and orchestra, by
Hannibal, the Texas-born composer who first came to attention as a
jazz trumpeter, and the Eighth Symphony by the Finnish composer
Einojuhani Rautavaara. Eight new works over three years may seem
like a lot, but in a less placid musical culture than today's,
eight new works in one season would not be overdoing it.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, the New York Philharmonic, which no one has ever
accused of being a hotbed of radicalism, will present six newly
commissioned works next season. And, in honor of the centenary of
Copland's birth, the Philharmonic will perform almost all his
orchestral works over three weeks in the fall.
</P>
<P>
   Excluding past masters does not necessarily make a program more
challenging. For example, by any measure, the Philadelphia's first
subscription program is pretty easygoing: Stravinsky's
``Pulcinella'' (a charming pastiche of music by Pergolesi),
Shostakovich's spirited First Piano Concerto and three popular
works by Ravel, including the mega-popular ``Bolero.''
</P>
<P>
   All from the 20th century, yes. But compare this program with
three concerts that Esa-Pekka Salonen, the conductor of the Los
Angeles Symphony, offered last season, which grouped symphonies by
Haydn with recent works by the visionary Hungarian-born composer
Gyorgy Ligeti. In a way, Salonen's musically provocative mixed
programs were, in terms of marketing, more risky.
</P>
<P>
   Kluger speaks ardently about the role of an orchestra in
educating its audience. A balancing act is required between shaping
and following public taste, and it is getting harder. Subscription
sales are down at every major American orchestra, although this
probably has more to do with life style issues than programming.
Most busy people do not want to commit to a weekly night at the
symphony.
</P>
<P>
   Ten years ago, Kluger said, the Philadelphia Orchestra sold
about 85 percent of its seats to subscribers and 5 percent to
single-ticket buyers; this season, those figures are 67 percent to
subscribers, 17 percent to single-ticket buyers. So far this
season, overall attendance is good, roughly 85 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Hometown praise has bolstered the management's morale. An
editorial in The Philadelphia Inquirer was almost giddy: ``Bravo to
the orchestra leadership willing to take a leap of faith and brand
itself as fresh and contemporary,'' it said, adding, ``Bravo to the
musicians who are willing to show that this fading century's music
can be melodic and rewarding, creating more than an atonal
headache.''
</P>
<P>
   Other musicians are trying to show audiences that gritty works
by Sessions, Babbitt, Lutoslawski and Shapey can be beautiful in a
bracing way that reflects a dynamic, tumultuous century.
</P>
<P>
   At the very least, the Philadelphia Orchestra's announcement has
provoked controversy and gotten people talking. And apathy, Kluger
said, ``is the biggest challenge orchestras face today.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
