<HEADLINE>
NFL OWNERS VOTE LOS ANGELES IN AGAIN, IF . . . 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ They have no firm financing agreement, no stadium
plan, no apparent political support, no sure owner and no solid fan
base but the city of Los Angeles has two things. It has TV sets and
because of that it now has the NFL's 32nd franchise.
</P>
<P>
   The league's 31 owners voted the city a provisional franchise
29-2 Tuesday, on the third day of the annual owner's meetings. But
owners were so unsure of Los Angeles' willingness or ability to
sustain a team that the move is only for six months and hinges on
several conditions, including the approval of a stadium site,
selection of one of two competing ownership groups and proof the
business community will ``actively support the re-establishment of
a successful NFL franchise in the greater Los Angeles area.''
</P>
<P>
   This decision, opposed by Buffalo owner Ralph Wilson and Oakland
owner Al Davis, left Houston businessman Bob McNair in limbo, which
is where he's been since this process began. Despite having the
financing in place to buy an expansion team and both the money and
the necessary approvals to erect a stadium with the full backing he
needs politically, McNair was told Tuesday he is out in the cold if
L.A. can get hot behind the return of the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   If this does not make sense to you, remember this is a league
with teams in Jacksonville, Fla., Nashville, Tenn. and Green Bay,
Wisc. but none in Los Angeles or Houston, the nation's second
largest TV market and fourth largest city.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's absurd to have this process pit the fourth largest city
in the country against the second largest market in a league that
has the Tennessee Titans,'' remarked sports agent Leigh Steinberg,
who is working with the group headed by Ed Roski and Eli Broad, who
intend to refurbish the L.A. Coliseum as the new team's home
against the league's wishes. ``Los Angeles has more people come to
a traffic jam than go to any Tennessee Titan game.''
</P>
<P>
   Be that as it may, Houston at least temporarily lost out to Los
Angeles if the city and either the Roski-Broad group or a competing
one headed by Hollywood mogul Michael Ovitz that is trying to build
a stadium in Carson, Calif., a suburb east of Los Angeles, can
satisfy 24 owners that it has the money, power and political clout
to bring the NFL back to Los Angeles after the market lost two
teams - the Rams and Raiders - in the past decade.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of every 15 individuals in the United State lives within
90 minutes of the Coliseum,'' Roski said after the announcement.
``We feel we have the financial capability to do the transaction
and a viable stadium plan.''
</P>
<P>
   If he does, it's news to owners like Denver's Pat Bowlen, who
voted for the proposal but made clear if Los Angeles does not meet
the NFL's requirements by Sept. 15 the franchise would be awarded
to McNair.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we're looking for is a stadium situation like Houston's
in Los Angeles,'' Bowlen said. ``We haven't seen any financial
plan. What financial plan? They may have a financial plan but but
we haven't seen it.''
</P>
<P>
   What they have seen is the second largest TV market in the
country living comfortably without NFL football for years. There
was no hue and cry when the Rams and Raiders left southern
California and there has been no real demand for a team to return,
a fact that has worried the league as a generation of L.A. kids
grow up without attachment to any NFL team.
</P>
<P>
   Expansion committee co-chairman Jerry Richardson acknowledged as
much when he conceded, ``It's the league's obligation to rekindle
that passion in Los Angeles. It wouldn't be helpful to rekindling
the passion if we gave the franchise to Houston.''
</P>
<P>
   True enough, but McNair has met every criteria outlined by the
league while the competing Los Angeles groups have not. Yet for at
least the next six months, he must sit on the sidelines while the
NFL plays ball with a reluctant Los Angeles market.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel having a deadline established is something we'd hoped
for,'' McNair said, doing his best to put a bright face on at least
temporary defeat. ``Six months is better than 10 months (another
proposed timetable). It's been clear there's a feeling the LA
market could not be ignored. There are now conditions that have to
be met. The league can set any rules or standards they wish but
they have gone on record with Sept. 15 (as L.A.'s deadline).
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't feel shafted. The world isn't fair. I never have gone
into anything expecting things to be fair. There's a preference for
L.A. That's clear. What's also clear is there's a lot more passion
for football in Texas than in Los Angeles so we'll see how it plays
out.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Commissioner Paul Tagliabue announced he had fined San Francisco
49ers owner Edward DeBartolo, Jr. $1 million and suspended him for
another year from running the team for his involvement in an
alleged scheme to buy the state of Louisiana's final riverboat
gambling license. DeBartolo has agreed to testify against former
Louisiana Gov. Edwin Edwards, claiming Edwards extorted money from
him in exchange for a favorable license application. If DeBartolo
violates the terms of the suspension he could be fined an
additional $4 million and be forced to continue watching his
sister, Debroah DeBartolo York, control the 49ers...With only five
dissenting votes, it was decided that the annual Thanksgiving Day
games will remain in Detroit and Dallas...No decision was announced
on the sale of the Redskins for $800 million to Howard Milstein and
Daniel Snyder but rumors persisted that the owners will block the
sale, claiming the offer lacks sufficient capital investment by the
two entrepreneurs. Some of the older owners want to see the club go
to John Kent Cooke, son of the late Redskin owner Jack Kent Cooke,
who in his will ordered the team be sold to finance college
scholarships for the needy. Cooke bid $700 million but Milstein's
higher offer to the trust set up to sell the team had to be
accepted. Word was Monday night that the issue, which may well lead
to law suits, had blown up and Milstein was out but Tagliabue
insisted the issue would be discussed Wednesday pending a report
from the Finance Committee...Instant replay will also be voted on
Wednesday and approval is expected but not yet assured. Cincinnati
and Arizona will definitely oppose it and the Jets are a likely no
vote. The Giants and Chiefs have long opposed replay's return but
remain on the fence and inscrutable Al Davis, who has opposed any
past plan that cost his team timeouts, refused to say how he is
leaning.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-16-99 2155EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
