<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-MISSILE-1STLD-WRITETHRU-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATE CALLS FOR MISSILE DEFENSE SYSTEM AFTER DEMOCRATS DROP
OPPOSITION
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Subs to add new 17th graf with comparisons to Reagan's Star Wars
program; see also RUSSIA-NUKE, CHINA-NUKE)   (wg) 
 By ERIC SCHMITT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The White House and Senate Democrats abandoned
their longstanding opposition on Tuesday to a politically popular
bill that calls for a national defense against limited long-range
missile attacks.
</P>
<P>
   The actions all but assure overwhelming approval of the overall
bill, which declares it to be United States policy to field an
antimissile system against ballistic missile threats from rogue
nations like North Korea and Iran as soon as ``technologically
possible.''
</P>
<P>
   The administration dropped its threatened veto by President
Clinton after the Senate passed a compromise amendment that
Democrats say insures that any antimissile system will not
interfere with arms-control negotiations with Russia.
</P>
<P>
   A final vote in the Senate is expected on Wednesday. The House
is scheduled to debate and likely pass a similar, bipartisan
missile-defense bill on Thursday. While neither bill authorizes a
specific system or appropriates money to build it, the measures, if
enacted, represent the government's most forceful support for the
policy.
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials said that the Senate compromise defuses
a potent national security campaign issue that Republicans could
have wielded against Democrats, and tries to finesse a nettlesome
issue before the Russian Prime Minister Yevgeny Primakov visits
Washington next week.
</P>
<P>
   Russia has long opposed an American antimissile system, and
conditioned further reductions in its nuclear arsenal on
Washington's compliance with the 1972 Anti-Ballistic Missile
Treaty. Fielding an antimissile system would require changes in
that pact, and Russia's leaders have expressed alarm in recent
months over the revived plans.
</P>
<P>
   The compromise amendment, passed 99 to 0, asserts that the
United States will continue to negotiate cuts in Russia's nuclear
forces, which Democrats interpret as language that is inextricably
linked to the ABM Treaty. But Republicans rejected any explicit
language that would have tied deployment of an antimissile system
to adherence to the treaty.
</P>
<P>
   Critics said that by failing to incorporate language that would
specifically protect the treaty, the overall measure could face
opposition from Russian leaders and the Russian parliament, which
is considering ratification of the second strategic arms reduction
treaty known as Start-2.
</P>
<P>
   But the administration appeared satisfied with the compromise.
</P>
<P>
   ``If this were the final bill, we'd accept it,'' Robert Bell, a
senior national security official at the White House, said Tuesday
night.
</P>
<P>
   The action marks a significant departure for Senate Democrats,
who twice last year narrowly blocked the same measure from coming
to the Senate floor, and for the White House, which had wielded a
veto threat, arguing that it was bad policy to deploy such a costly
system based only on technological merit.
</P>
<P>
   The measure has since picked up bipartisan support in the wake
of missile tests in the last year by North Korea and Iran, and
recent disclosures that China may have stolen nuclear secrets from
an American weapons laboratory that would enhance Beijing's
long-range missile fleet.
</P>
<P>
   ``This bill recognizes the threat is real and that the world has
changed,'' said Sen. Mary Landrieu, D-La., who helped broker the
compromise amendment with Sen. Olympia Snowe, R-Maine.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In January, the administration began to backpedal. The White
House announced it was asking Russia to renegotiate the ABM treaty
to permit a limited national missile defense.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Defense Secretary William Cohen and the Joint
Chiefs of Staff testified to Congress that the administration was
pledging $6.6 billion over the next six years to build a network of
radar and interceptor missiles.
</P>
<P>
   That commitment increased the budget for a national missile
defense to $10.5 billion between now and 2005. The administration
has said it would decide next year whether to build an antimissile
system _ perhaps based in Alaska or North Dakota, or on ships _
that would be ready by 2005.
</P>
<P>
   That type of anti-missile system is a far cry from President
Ronald Reagan's ``Star Wars'' vision to use lasers in space as a
shield against nuclear attack. Even on a smaller scale, the current
program remains burdened by technological problems that some
experts view as impossible to overcome.
</P>
<P>
   Even as senior U.S. officials sought to calm Russian fears and
explain that the system was intended to protect against outlaw
nations, the unity of Senate Democrats was fracturing so badly that
leaders expressed concern they would not be able to muster 33 votes
to sustain a presidential veto.
</P>
<P>
   So Democrats negotiated two amendments that are vague enough for
both sides to interpret them the way they want. The first, which
also passed 99 to 0, assures that any money to be spent on a
missile system would go through the regular congressional
appropriations process. The second was the arms control amendment.
</P>
<P>
   The amendments were embraced both by Sen. Thad Cochran, R-Miss.,
one of the bill's chief sponsors, and Sen. Carl Levin, D-Mich., one
of its chief foes.
</P>
<P>
   But arms control advocates, who fear that fielding a missile
system will undermine nuclear weapons cuts, criticized the
negotiating. ``The Senate has taken a sow's ear, put a little rouge
on, slapped on some lipstick, and produced a sow's ear,'' said John
Isaacs, president of the Council for a Livable World, an arms
control advocacy group.
</P>
<P>
   Before striking the compromise, Democrats and Republicans argued
bitterly over the legislation. ``A national missile defense can't
protect us from a low-flying cruise missile launched by a third
world despot or from a terrorist who plants a bomb under a
skyscraper in lower Manhattan,'' said Sen. Byron Dorgan, D-N.Dak.
</P>
<P>
   But Sen. Fred Thompson, R-Tenn., said: ``It's time for Congress
to wake up and act. The technology to develop and deliver nuclear
and other weapons of mass destruction is widely available and
spreading rapidly.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
