<SLUG> BC-BKC-MIAMI-OHIO-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Miami coach a quiet 'warrior'
 &HT;    By Marty Williams
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   OXFORD, Ohio _ Everyone is praising Charlie Coles but Charlie
Coles.
</P>
<P>
   He coached brilliantly in guiding Miami to back-to-back upset
wins over Washington and Utah in the first two rounds of the NCAA
tournament, but he avoids the limelight the way he avoided
defenders when he averaged 42.1 points a game as a senior at Yellow
Springs Bryan High School.
</P>
<P>
   The RedHawks are in the Sweet 16 for the first time and will
face defending national champion Kentucky in the Midwest Regional
semifinals in St. Louis on Friday, but the 57-year-old Coles swats
at compliments as if they were pesky mosquitoes.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I was 35 years old, this would probably have really gone to
my head,'' he said Tuesday at Millett Hall. ``But now, it can't go
to my head. I've been coaching for 34 years. If I started feeling
good about myself, people might say, 'Gee, what took you so long?
You're not real clever if it took you all this time to win two
(NCAA) ball games.'''
</P>
<P>
   But while Coles hesitates to speak for himself, others are quick
to offer personal testimonies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coach Coles is a warrior,'' said point guard Rob Mestas. ``He
showed that when he came back from cardiac arrest (in a
Mid-American Conference tournament game last year at Western
Michigan) and took us to the conference championship (this season).
</P>
<P>
   ``He literally put his life on the line to come back and coach
us,'' Mestas said. ``How can you not have respect for someone who
does that?''
</P>
<P>
   Senior co-captain Damon Frierson said the reason Coles'
strategies and adjustments worked so well in New Orleans was
because the players have such confidence in him.
</P>
<P>
   ``We couldn't have been better prepared for those two games.
Even when things weren't going well, we would go to the bench and
he would explain how we could fix the problem. And he was right
about everything he said.''
</P>
<P>
   Coles still refused to budge. ``I just don't think of it like
that. I see it like this: you can tell your players to do this or
do that, but it doesn't mean anything unless they want to do it and
can do it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was very proud after we beat Washington and Utah,'' he
admitted. ``Our players did what we wanted them to do and they
adjusted well. That's good from a coaching point of view because we
certainly told them to make those adjustments. But the thing that
gives you the most pride is that they did it during the game, in
the face of unbelievable pressure.''
</P>
<P>
   When asked how his team can beat Kentucky, Coles returned to
form.
</P>
<P>
   ``The strategy for this game is simple. We have to try to keep
it close so we can have a chance. How we're going to do that, I
don't know.'' But regardless of what Coles was saying to the media
on Tuesday, Mestas and Frierson know the players will be getting
something a little more concrete as they prepare to face the
Wildcats.
</P>
<P>
   And they'll believe what he tells them because they're convinced
he believes in them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coach Coles is a great motivator and a great X's and O's
guy,'' Mestas said, ``but he's more than that. We can talk to him
about anything. He worries about other things in our lives besides
basketball.''
</P>
<P>
   Added Frierson, ``You don't have to be with coach Coles very
long before you feel you've known him all your life. He's the kind
of guy a player dreams about having as his coach.
</P>
<P>
   Marty Williams writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
