<DOCNO> NYT19990316.0383 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-16 22:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3015 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEX-CARNIVAL-INSPECTI     03-16 0730
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEX-CARNIVAL-INSPECTIONS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Keel bill to authorize local inspectors at carnivals
 &HT;    By Scott Greenberger
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ George Lane would have given anything not to be
at the Capitol on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   A year ago this Friday, Lane watched in horror as his
15-year-old daughter, Leslie, was thrown to her death from an
amusement park ride at the Austin-Travis County Livestock Show and
Rodeo. Steeling himself against his grief and nervousness, Lane
stood up Tuesday to urge a House committee to stiffen safety rules
for such rides.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm here for the love of this lady,'' Lane said as he showed a
portrait of Leslie to state legislators and a phalanx of television
cameras.
</P>
<P>
   Nine people, including the owners and operators of the ride,
maintenance workers and insurance inspectors, were indicted on
murder charges last September in Lane's death.
</P>
<P>
   Spurred by the incident, lawmakers are weighing legislation
filed by Rep. Terry Keel, R-Austin, and Sen. Gonzalo Barrientos,
D-Austin, which would for the first time allow Texas law
enforcement officials to inspect and immediately shut down unsafe
rides. Rather than create a system of state inspections, Texas
would continue to rely on inspectors hired by insurance companies.
</P>
<P>
   Lane, along with several carnival ride and amusement park
operators, testified in favor of the bill. But Lane also referred
to it as ``a start'' and suggested that he'd prefer that the state
do its own inspections.
</P>
<P>
   Lane declined to talk to reporters after the hearing _ ``I'm
holding it in as best I can right now,'' he said _ but his lawyer
confirmed that he'd like the legislation to go further.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously leaving the inspection procedure to the insurance
companies didn't work for Leslie Lane,'' said Chris Elliott. ``We
see state and or local inspections as an extra hammer to hold over
these ride operators' heads.''
</P>
<P>
   Some critics of the Keel bill also have questioned whether law
enforcement officers have the expertise to identify potential
problems.
</P>
<P>
   Keel notes that the insurance companies, which don't want to pay
large claims, have a financial incentive to make sure rides are
safe. Under current Texas law, ride operators must be able to prove
that they have insurance and that the ride is inspected at least
once a year. Insurance companies can choose their own inspectors,
as long as they meet certain standards of education and experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no better incentive than the pocketbook,'' Keel said.
</P>
<P>
   His bill would supplement that system by allowing law
enforcement officials to inspect and immediately shut down rides
they deem unsafe. Under current rules, law enforcement officers or
Texas Department of Insurance officials must get a court order to
close a ride. Keel says that many problems, such as broken lap bars
or an intoxicated operator, are obvious.
</P>
<P>
   The bill also would toughen sanctions for failing to comply with
the insurance and inspection rules, making jail time a possibility
in addition to fines.
</P>
<P>
   Keel said people overestimate the effectiveness of state
inspections.
</P>
<P>
   ``You'd end up having state inspectors come out, inspect it,
bless it , say it's safe and it would become unsafe and the
operator would point to the fact that they complied with the
minimum inspection requirements,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In the absence of federal regulations, amusement park rules vary
greatly from state to state. Arkansas and Florida use state
inspectors to check rides at every setup, while Hawaii uses state
inspectors every six months. Nevada leaves it up to city code
inspectors, and Missouri and North Dakota have no safety
requirements. Some states perform inspections but do not require
insurance.
</P>
<P>
   Keel says his analysis of safety records in other states
convinced him that relying on insurance company inspections is
preferable to a state inspection system.
</P>
<P>
   ``Texas actually has a pretty good mechanism in place now,''
Keel said. The problem is it isn't complemented by any type of
governmental oversight or deterrence. When you couple these two
prongs, we have the best bill in the United States, in my
opinion.''
</P>
<P>
   Scott Greenberger writes for the Austin American-Statesman,
Austin, Texas. E-mail: sgreenberger(AT)statesman.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
