<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-16 22:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3017 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SEATTLE-SALMON-ART-NY     03-16 1079
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SEATTLE-SALMON-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEWS ANALYSIS: FOR THE SAKE OF SALMON, THE PEOPLE OF SEATTLE FACE A
BURDEN
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(dal) 
 By SAM HOWE VERHOVEK   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ In a sense, what is most remarkable about the federal
government's announcement on Tuesday that it would list nine types
of salmon under the Endangered Species Act, a move that will force
new building restrictions and raise taxes across the Seattle area
and elsewhere in the Northwest, is how little controversy it has
stirred _ so far, anyway.
</P>
<P>
   But this new application of the law, the broadest in terms of
both geography and the effect on a human population in the
statute's 26-year history, is almost certain to become a test of
the willingness of an entire urban region to pay large sums of
money and perhaps even sacrifice some growth for what has become a
political battle cry: the control of ``sprawl.''
</P>
<P>
   The effort to restore the once-vigorous runs of the Puget Sound
chinook and other salmon is really a cause that combines elements
of a customary environmental crusade with those of the more recent
drive against rampant growth _ the kind of concern that tops Vice
President Al Gore's ``livability agenda,'' which he hopes to make a
centerpiece of his presidential campaign. Restoring the salmon will
entail cleaning up the waterways that snake all over the Puget
Sound region, promoting and preserving green space and open space,
limiting the creep of suburbanization _ all the kinds of things
that people seem to clamor for in public opinion polls.
</P>
<P>
   Those polls indicate overwhelming support here for doing
whatever is necessary to save the salmon, which are running at a
fraction of their historic peaks. A big rally on the eve of the
long-awaited listing drew Seattle's mayor and other top local
officials, all in support of the fish. ``What's good for salmon is
good for people,'' one placard said.
</P>
<P>
   But the effort could well mean measures that may not prove so
popular, particularly in the long run. Fertilizer use could be
banned in some areas, and residents' use of water could be limited.
And it will cost hundreds of millions of dollars, perhaps more, to
preserve crucial land.
</P>
<P>
   So what now seems a popular move could well prompt a severe
backlash against the Endangered Species Act and those state and
local officials who must now adopt the needed restrictions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Really, what's involved here is that for the last 100 years,
as we developed out here, we sort of forced the salmon to adjust to
us,'' said William D. Ruckelshaus, a Seattleite who served as
Administrator of the Environmental Protection Agency in the Nixon
and Reagan administrations and now heads a business round-table
group on salmon. ``Well, now we have to figure out how to adjust to
the salmon. At this juncture, there is tremendous enthusiasm for
that, enough political support to cause politicians here to feel
comfortable in taking some pretty extraordinary steps.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it could all evaporate,'' Ruckelshaus added. ``It could
turn into a fight and a struggle. I don't think it will, but it
could.''
</P>
<P>
   Others say there is reason to be more skeptical.
</P>
<P>
   ``The old Clinton slogan was `putting people first,' and now the
Gore slogan is `putting salmon first,''' said Alex Castellanos, a
Republican political consultant, referring to Gore's advocacy of
salmon restoration and his recent promise of $100 million in
federal aid as part of what he and the president called ``a new
partnership for salmon recovery.''
</P>
<P>
   The general idea ``sounds good to people, so of course they'll
say they're for it,'' Castellanos said. ``Even so, here's what
always happens: The best day is the first day it's announced. After
that, when you get to putting the price tags on it, there's just a
steady, steady erosion. After a while, people begin to ask, `Well,
what else could you do with this money?' What if the question
becomes, Do you save salmon or do you save seniors?''
</P>
<P>
   And even if pubic support does hold, still others wonder whether
the salmon runs can really be nursed back to health. The
Seattle-Tacoma region already has nearly 3 million people, and it
continues to grow; some projections call for a population growth of
1 million in the next 25 years.
</P>
<P>
   But at a briefing on Monday, the King County Executive, Ron
Sims, a Democrat who is a strong proponent of salmon restoration
plans and a potential candidate for the Senate next year, said
economic growth and saving the salmon were not incompatible.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not going to tear down the Seafirst bank building and
replant it with Douglas fir _ the key will be to make sure we're
smarter with the land mass that's available,'' he said. ``This area
is going to have to become greener.'' But if it grows by 1 million
people, it's hard to see where and how it could become greener.
</P>
<P>
   Under provisions of the species act, local officials must work
in the coming months to develop plans for restoring the salmon runs
and, if there is no improvement, local governments and eventually
even private citizens could face federal sanctions for failing to
protect the fish.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, the key to a successful protection effort may be
that all parties involved feel they are affected equally.
</P>
<P>
   ``If people are convinced that this whole thing really is a
partnership, that everybody is doing their fair share, then I think
you could continue to see a lot of support,'' said Robert E.
Gogerty, a consultant here who has advised both businesses and
political candidates. ``But if they think they're bearing the brunt
of it, then you could see a rebellion.''
</P>
<P>
   Curiously, precisely because salmon restoration will be
undertaken across such a wide region, it may actually prove more
palatable than other listings that have affected a much smaller
number of people.
</P>
<P>
   ``What may be somewhat unique about the salmon listing is that
it is likely to spread the cost of recovery fairly broadly,'' said
Michael Bean, chairman of the wildlife program of the Environmental
Defense Fund. ``The act has often been the source of controversy
because while the public at large benefits from conservation, it
was not uncommon for only one or a few landowners or industries to
bear a disproportionate share of the cost when a species was
listed.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
