<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-16 22:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3019 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FLEET-DIVEST-BOS &LR;      03-16 1211
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLEET-DIVEST-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FLEET-BANKBOSTON DEAL ENTAILS MASSIVE BRANCH SELLOFF 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LYNNLEY BROWNING  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- In what industry experts say could be one of the
largest bank divestitures in US history, Fleet Financial Group Inc.
and BankBoston Corp. plan to sell off approximately 270 branches
across New England _ including some 200 Fleet branches in
Massachusetts _ as part of their $16 billion merger.
</P>
<P>
   Under the plan, detailed Tuesday by sources familiar with the
merger, a combined Fleet-BankBoston would retain nearly all of
BankBoston's 301 branches in Massachusetts, the 215-year-old bank's
traditional stronghold.
</P>
<P>
   The new company, which will initially be called Fleet Boston
Corp., would sell nearly all of Fleet's in-state branches.
</P>
<P>
   Fleet Boston also proposes to sell around half of BankBoston's
64 branches in Connecticut and nearly all of its 45 branches in
Rhode Island, where Fleet dominates. After the proposed
divestiture, the company will have around 1,580 branches.
</P>
<P>
   ``This would appear to be the largest single market bank
divestiture ever in a major merger,'' said Christopher Bellini, a
banking lawyer at Gibson Dunn &AMP; Crutcher in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   The issue of which branches would be sold was so contentious
that it nearly derailed the merger agreement last weekend. Sources
close to the transaction said Fleet initially agreed to sell nearly
all its Massachusetts outlets but then reconsidered, proposing that
BankBoston branches be sold instead.
</P>
<P>
   But BankBoston prevailed, saying that unless the new company
kept most of its branches in Massachusetts, the merger was off.
According to sources, BankBoston felt that its legacy as the
nation's oldest bank, founded in Boston, was at stake.
</P>
<P>
   Both Fleet and BankBoston, which are combining to form the
nation's eighth largest bank, have so much overlap in
Massachusetts, Connecticut, and Rhode Island that they must sell
branches to avoid violating antitrust laws. Fleet, New England's
largest bank, is dwarfed by BankBoston in the Massachusetts market
but dominates in other New England states.
</P>
<P>
   The proposed divestiture will allow other banks, including those
outside the region, to bid for branches and potentially assemble
enough outlets to pose a competitive threat to Fleet Boston.
Whether a serious challenge emerges, however, is an open question.
</P>
<P>
   Some observers say that Fleet Boston's divestiture plan may
signal a new chapter in banking consolidation, in which regulators
allow mergers that utlimately decrease competition.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it sets a precedent,'' said one senior New York
banking lawyer who declined to be named. ``This would essentially
be the first time that Justice has ever permitted a single bank to
dominate a single market.''
</P>
<P>
   Fleet and BankBoston executives acknowledge privately that they
hope to sell branches to lots of bidders, preferably smaller banks,
to avoid opening the door to a new competitor. Already several
local banks, including Citzens Financial Group Inc. and US Trust,
have expressed interest.
</P>
<P>
   ``Will the divestiture be to one big entity or divided up in
parts to smaller competitors? That is the big open question,'' said
Gregory Lyons, a partner in Boston-based Goodwin, Procter &AMP; Hoare's
banking practice.
</P>
<P>
   Fleet offcials said all banks were welcome to bid.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our divestiture plan is subject to revisions and approvals by
federal and state regulators,'' said Fleet spokesman Jim Mahoney.
``But we believe these are attractive franchise opportunities and
that major companies will bid for them.''
</P>
<P>
   ``At this point, we are open to all bidders, whether they are
large or small banks, whether they are inside or outside the
region,'' Mahoney said.
</P>
<P>
   Out-of-state banks expected to bid include giant NationsBank
Corp., based in Charlotte, N.C., according to analysts.
</P>
<P>
   Many small, local banks are interested in buying branches.
</P>
<P>
   ``The community banks would absolutely like to be part of the
bidding process, especially if they can buy branches on an
individual basis'' said Gene Graham, executive vice president of
the Community Bank League of New England, which represents about
118 small institutions. ``But we don't want to have to be required
to purchase a minimum of, say, 20 branches.''
</P>
<P>
   Fleet Boston's divestiture proposals are just that _ proposals.
And the numbers are still approximations, to be approved by
regulators. The two banks, which presented their divestiture plan
to the Justice Department and Federal Reserve officials three weeks
ago, said they are confident that regulators will approve the
proposal later this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were frankly surprised at how receptive they were to the
plan,'' one company source said, adding that officials from both
state bodies spent one week reviewing the plan and offered no
criticism. ``If they'd had reservations, they would have said, `You
go forward at your own peril.' ''
</P>
<P>
   No matter what the regulators decide, however, Fleet and
BankBoston say their deal cannot be broken.
</P>
<P>
   If regulators decide Fleet Boston must get rid of twice as many
deposits and branches in order to comply with antitrust laws, the
merger agreement must still go ahead _ even if it becomes more
costly to Fleet.
</P>
<P>
   Fleet initially wanted a so-called ``regulatory-out clause'' in
the merger contract _ a provision stipulating that Fleet could
renegotiate the agreement's price if regulators demand more costly
divestitures.
</P>
<P>
   But sources close to the merger said BankBoston insisted on an
agreement that could not be adjusted if regulators require more
assets to be divested. The reason, sources said, was that
BankBoston feared that if the deal unraveled it could find itself
open to a takeover by a big out-of-region bidder _ a scenario
BankBoston was keen to avoid.
</P>
<P>
   Getting Fleet to agree to a final deal that could not be
renegotiated under any conditions kept executives from both banks
up all last weekend in New York before signing a final deal on
Sunday, according to sources.
</P>
<P>
   Fleet Boston plans to hold three auctions _ one for Fleet
branches in Massachusetts, which have around $7.5 billion in
deposits; one for BankBoston branches in Connecticut, which hold
$1.5 billion in deposits; and one for BankBoston branches in Rhode
Island, which have $2.5 billion in deposits. Auctions may or may
not have multiple bidders, sources said.
</P>
<P>
   While Fleet Boston is expected to cut approximately 5,000 jobs
and close two dozen branches, staffers at divested branches are
expected to keep their jobs when the outlets are sold.
</P>
<P>
   In order to pass regulatory hurdles, Fleet Boston also proposes
to sell $13.6 billion in deposits, or about 20 percent of its
combined $71 billion in deposits.
</P>
<P>
   Fleet Boston Corp. will earn from $0.10 to $0.15 for each
deposit dollar it sells, giving it a profit of up to $2 billion
from divestiture. In a separate sale, Fleet Boston Corp. will also
sell off around $2.5 billion in loans to small and mid-size
businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the prospect of divestiture has ``every banker in
town ringing our phones off the hook,'' said an executive at one of
the to-be-merged banks.``They're all looking for a leg up.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-16-99 2204EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
