<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-16 22:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3022 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-R-CONGRESS-BUDGET-ART     03-16 0842
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-CONGRESS-BUDGET-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOP BUDGET PLAN CUTS TAXES BUT SUPPORTS EDUCATION AND MILITARY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating to correct art note)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(sw) 
 By RICHARD W. STEVENSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Republicans laid out a budget proposal on Tuesday
that makes good on their promises to cut taxes and increase
spending on the military and education, but at the cost of deep
cuts elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Their plan is the Republican response to the budget proposal
sent to Congress last month by President Clinton, and like the
White House plan, it makes shoring up Social Security the nation's
top fiscal priority in a period of emerging surpluses.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican plan was introduced on Tuesday in the Senate
Budget Committee, and a similar version is to be taken up on
Wednesday by the House Budget Committee. While it is likely to
prove no more than the opening Republican negotiating position, it
makes clear that the surplus will not mute the debate over how to
capitalize on the nation's prosperity.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Pete Domenici, the New Mexico Republican who is chairman of
the Senate Budget Committee, said the plan would provide a tax cut
next year of $15 billion and possibly more if the strong economy
continues to generate higher-than-expected tax revenues.
</P>
<P>
   The tax cuts would grow to $778 billion over the next decade.
That is enough for the tax-writing committees in the House and
Senate to choose among a variety of tax-cutting options, but
probably not enough, Domenici acknowledged, for the 10 percent
across-the-board reduction in income tax rates that Republicans had
hoped to make the centerpiece of their agenda.
</P>
<P>
   Seeking to blunt attacks from Clinton and Democrats in Congress
that Republicans are shortchanging Medicare, Domenici said his plan
would set aside $133 billion over the next decade to cope with a
variety of contingencies, including the possibility that an
overhaul of Medicare would require an infusion of money.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal would increase Pentagon spending by $18.2 billion,
to $290 billion, reflecting an insistence among Republicans on
rebuilding what they see as a dangerously run-down military.
</P>
<P>
   In an attempt to neutralize a traditionally Democratic issue,
the plan calls for a $3.3 billion increase in federal spending on
education next year, to a total of $103 billion.
</P>
<P>
   But to allow the spending increases on the military and
education while also meeting another bedrock Republican pledge _ to
remain within the tight spending limits set out in the 1997
bipartisan budget deal _ the plan would require slashing spending
on a wide array of other programs.
</P>
<P>
   To stay under the cap on programs that receive annual
appropriations _ $536 billion for next year _ the plan requires
discretionary spending cuts of $14.7 billion next year, which some
members of both parties said could well prove politically
impossible. The plan would require even bigger cuts in the two
subsequent years: $15.4 billion in 2001 and $22 billion in 2002.
</P>
<P>
   The plan, if it is adopted by both the House and the Senate,
would not become law but would be the guideline for the annual tax
and spending bills Congress will take up this year. It is not
binding but suggests specific cuts that the appropriations
committees could consider in reconciling the demand from both
parties for new and expanded programs be financed with the painful
discipline of the spending caps.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal suggests that spending on environmental programs,
for example, be reduced to $21.5 billion next year, from $23.9
billion this year. It would reduce spending on science, including
NASA, to $18 billion, from $18.8 billion this year. It would shrink
spending for agriculture to $14.3 billion next year, from $16.8
billion, and would not renew billions of dollars in emergency aid
Congress gave farmers last year.
</P>
<P>
   Domenici called the plan ``a good start on wisely and
effectively using projected surpluses into the next century.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Budget Committee's senior Democrat, Sen. Frank
Lautenberg of New Jersey, attacked the proposal, as did the White
House.
</P>
<P>
   ``In order to fund an irresponsible and exploding tax cut, it
fails to commit a single penny to securing Medicare and it requires
discretionary cuts in the first few years that could not
realistically be put together without serious reductions in key
areas like education, health and environment,'' said Gene Sperling,
the administration's economic policy adviser.
</P>
<P>
   Domenici said he hoped the committee would complete work on the
plan this week and send it to the Senate floor for a vote next
week. Last year, Domenici feuded over budget priorities with his
counterpart in the House, Rep. John Kasich, R-Ohio. But this year,
the two men are working closely together to keep the party united
as they head into months of negotiations with the White House on
taxes, spending, Social Security and Medicare.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-16-99 2209EST &QL; 
