<SLUG> BC-BUSINESS-TRAVEL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS TRAVEL: A YOUNGER BREED TRAVELS THE WORLD
</HEADLINE>
   (dal) 
 By JOE SHARKEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ruth Stanat talks fast, but this probably comes naturally for
someone who has visited more than 100 countries on business in the
last couple of years.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no time anymore!'' she gasped the other day from her
office in Fort Wayne, Ind. ``I just jumped off the plane from
Geneva, and I hit the deck running. I can't even look at the
schedule. Back and forth to San Francisco for two hours! I recently
had a meeting in Washington, which I had to leave in the middle of,
to go to Montreal.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Stanat, 51, is the president and founder of SIS
International Research, a business planning and market research
company with offices in 18 countries. A former senior executive at
Chase Manhattan Bank and the Mars Corp., Ms. Stanat has also
managed to write two books, often working on airplanes or in
airports. The most recent is ``Global Jumpstart: The Complete
Resource for Expanding Small and Midsize Businesses,'' with Chris
West as co-author (Perseus Books, 1999).
</P>
<P>
   While never leisurely, business travel has become more frantic
with the accelerating speed of globalization, Ms. Stanat says. She
chuckles now to think that she was once able to ``drag my kids all
around the world'' and even enjoy an occasional carefree weekend in
London. Now, especially with cellular phones and the Internet, she
says, it's always a business day somewhere.
</P>
<P>
   One of the consequences of this is that business travel is
increasing in both volume and pace. ``With the good economy,
companies want their people on the road,'' said Christine Levite, a
vice president at American Express. American Express estimates that
U.S. companies spent $175 billion on travel and entertainment in
1998, up from $165 billion in 1997. And it is no accident that a
lot of those faces in departure lounges are looking younger these
days.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rather than just sending someone to Paris, a company will now
send someone to four or five other countries in the European Union,
and possibly to Prague and Budapest, too,'' Ms. Stanat said.
``After about 10 days of this, most people are totally burned out.
Companies are throwing so many young people out on the road because
kids are resilient. They're usually not strapped down with
families, and, hey, maybe it's their first time in Paris. They're
willing to fly coach.''
</P>
<P>
   But there are limits even to youthful patience on the road.
</P>
<P>
   The scene: Newark International Airport, AMR's American
Airlines, Gate 30, last Thursday night. Flight 1535 to Miami has
already been rescheduled five times from its original 6:20 p.m.
departure time. There being few social lubricants as effective as
adversity in the face of a common enemy, strangers have begun
gathering in knots, muttering darkly to one another about what they
say is a lack of reliable information about their flight, which
American agents maintain has been delayed by that hardiest of
excuses, ``bad weather in Dallas.''
</P>
<P>
   At 9 p.m., after still another delay, Robert Rossi, a burly
28-year-old real estate salesman from Summit, N.J., who says that
he travels 40 to 50 times a year on business, decides that he isn't
going to take it anymore, not silently at least.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why do they keep lying to me?'' he bellows, raising both arms
and addressing the crowd. ``They threatened to call the police
because I'm complaining!''
</P>
<P>
   Once, fellow travelers would have kept their eyes downcast at
such a scene, like subway riders avoiding a panhandler. But Rossi's
outburst actually elicits general approval from the crowd. One
frustrated passenger puts in: ``I'd call this a fly-by-night
operation, but they aren't even doing that.'' Says another: ``I
just came in from in Dallas. The weather is fine in Dallas, just a
little overcast.''
</P>
<P>
   Around 9:30, a group of Port Authority police officers, alerted
to potential rebellion, is summoned to the departure gate. ``There
must be 15 police officers with clubs,'' marvels Joe Abelleira, a
marketing executive with the Cordis Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Calm restored, the plane finally arrives for a 10:58 departure
that will put passengers into Miami around 2 a.m. Oddly, the
official reason for the late flight has now changed, at least on
the American Airlines automated telephone flight-information
system, which insists that ``air-traffic control delays'' were
responsible for the problem with Flight 1535. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
