<HEADLINE>
A GENERAL WILL ADMIT TO ADULTERY
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Wash.)  (nk) 
 By STEVEN LEE MYERS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A retired two-star general who briefly served as
the Army's deputy inspector general has agreed to plead guilty to
eight counts of misconduct stemming from adulterous relationships
he had with the wives of four subordinate officers, his lawyer said
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The officer, Maj. Gen. David R.E. Hale, reached an agreement
with Army prosecutors on the eve of his court-martial, which was
scheduled to begin Wednesday at Fort Lewis, Wash. The Army had
charged him with 17 counts of misconduct, but in exchange for the
guilty pleas it agreed to reduce the charges and impose a lesser
sentence, which was not made public Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Hale had served only four months as deputy inspector general
when his request to retire last February was granted by the Army,
even though the wife of a subordinate had filed a complaint
accusing him of an improper sexual relationship.
</P>
<P>
   The Army's handling of the case led to accusations of a double
standard that allowed senior officers to escape punishment for
wrongdoing while junior officers or enlisted personnel faced
vigorous prosecutions.
</P>
<P>
   The furor over the case prompted Defense Secretary William Cohen
to order changes in the military's retirement policies, barring
officers accused of misconduct from retiring until charges against
them are resolved.
</P>
<P>
   Under the Uniform Code of Military Justice, Hale had faced a
maximum sentence of 11 years in prison if convicted at
court-martial. However, under the agreement announced Tuesday,
Hale's lawyers and Army prosecutors have already agreed to limit
his sentence.
</P>
<P>
   Hale, 53, must appear in Fort Lewis on Wednesday before the
presiding officer of the court-martial, who will review the plea
agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Hale, who had adamantly maintained his innocence, wanted to
bring the case ``to a swift conclusion,'' his lawyer, Frank J.
Spinner, said in remarks to reporters at Fort Lewis on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Spinner emphasized that while his client admitted having
adulterous relationships and lying about them, both violations of
the code of military justice, he denied committing ``any
nonconsensual sexual offense.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the agreement, Hale has agreed to plead guilty to making
false official statements by lying to the Pentagon's deputy
inspector general and conduct unbecoming an officer and gentleman
for having an ``improper relations, while married'' with the wives
of four subordinates, for denying that to one of the husbands and
for misleading the Army's inspector general once the accusation
surfaced.
</P>
<P>
   The Army dropped charges of making false statements, unbecoming
conduct and obstruction of justice, including one count that
charged him with threatening one of the women that he would testify
against her in a child custody case.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The charges against Hale grew out of the accusations of
Donnamaria Carpino, whose husband was a colonel at the NATO base at
Izmir, Turkey, where Hale served as deputy commander of all NATO
ground forces for southeastern Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Carpino accused Hale of trumping up adultery charges against
her husband and then promising not to pursue them if she agreed to
have sex with him. At the time, Hale was divorcing his wife of 30
years.
</P>
<P>
   An investigation by the Pentagon's inspector general, Eleanor
Hill, concluded that the relationship between Ms. Carpino and Hale
was consensual, not coerced. That investigation also detailed a
``pattern of inappropriate behavior'' involving the other women, as
well as misuse of travel expenses.
</P>
<P>
   Even though he agreed to plead guilty to some of the charges
before the court-martial could begin, Hale still, technically, will
have faced a court-martial. As such, he will be only the second
Army general to face court-martial since Congress enacted the
Uniform Code of Military Justice in 1951.
</P>
<P>
   The other case occurred in 1952, when Maj. Gen. Robert W. Grow,
the military attache in Moscow, was tried on charges of dereliction
of duty after his diary was stolen from a hotel room in Germany and
published by East Germany's Communist government.
</P>
</TEXT>
