<SLUG> BC-SOC-GALAXY-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CIENFUEGOS ENDS HOLDOUT _ FOR NOW
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRED J. ROBLEDO  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA -- Midfielder Mauricio Cienfuegos reported to Galaxy
training camp Tuesday, ending his holdout -- at least temporarily
-- without warning and much to the surprise of coach Octavio
Zambrano.
</P>
<P>
   Even though Cienfuegos practiced for the first time in
preparation for Saturday's season opener against Colorado, his
problems with the league are far from over.
</P>
<P>
   Cienfuegos said he acted in good faith by reporting to camp, but
that if his contract isn't re-worked by Friday, he'll fly back to
El Salvador and miss the season opener.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't make a decision to come back to the team by showing
up today,'' Cienfuegos said. ``The league wanted us (he and fellow
holdout Raul Diaz Arce of San Jose) to report to our teams so that
we can negotiate. That's all we're doing, doing our part. Now maybe
they will hold up to their end of the bargain and get this
settled.''
</P>
<P>
   Ivan Gazidis, the executive vice president of player relations
for the MLS, said he was hoping to speak with Cienfuegos' agent,
Corey Clemetson, so the two sides could begin talks.
</P>
<P>
   Gazidis did say, however, that if Cienfuegos' position is to
report to camp solely for the purpose of negotiations without an
intent to play, that's not an good act of faith in his book.
</P>
<P>
   ``First of all, it's definitely a positive development to see
him in camp,'' Gazidis said. ``But if Mauricio returns again to El
Salvador, it would show he reported solely to get what he wants.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's important to us that he plays in games; that's what he's
being paid for. Good faith means adhering to your commitment and he
has a contract to play now and that's the bottom line.''
</P>
<P>
   As Clemetson has said all along, Cienfuegos said he feels his
$103,000 contract is an insult compared to what he believes other
marquee players are earning.
</P>
<P>
   ``Knowing what we know and our value to the league is the reason
we want to sit down and discuss our contracts,'' Cienfuegos said.
``The maximum of $250,000 is an illusion. There are many players
making more than that.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of these players (with high contracts) haven't produced
as well as we have. There are players getting way above the
maximum, yet they're not producing the way we are, so there has to
be a way to compensate us better.''
</P>
<P>
   Cienfuegos was very disappointed with the 15-percent raise the
league offered during the first round of negotiations a few weeks
ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``What they offered me amounted to a tip, as you call it in the
United States,'' Cienfuegos said, comparing MLS' offer to a
gratuity at a restaurant. ``I'm willing to meet them halfway, but
they have to be willing to meet with me halfway.''
</P>
<P>
   If the worst-case scenario plays out and he returns to El
Salvador, Cienfuegos would ask the league to shop him around.
</P>
<P>
   ``My career doesn't end here,'' Cienfuegos said. ``If it doesn't
work out, I'd like them to put a price on my exchange and loan me
out somewhere. I'm not ready to retire.''
</P>
<P>
   Clemetson says the decision to play is up to Cienfuegos and Diaz
Arce.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are ready to play,'' Clemetson said. ``Whether they play
this week really depends on the efforts of the league at this
point.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they (the league) step up and give them a great, brand new
contract, then the league is true to their word and we can resolve
this. But if it's their intention to get them in camp and use their
names for the purpose of getting ready for the start of the season,
I don't think that's going to work.''
</P>
<P>
   Zambrano, who sat down and spoke with Cienfuegos, believes
everything will be worked out by Saturday. He also said Cienfuegos
appeared in top shape.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think so; I think Mauricio is a competitor and he will be
with us Saturday,'' Zambrano said. ``This thing has been eating him
alive. At the end of the day he wants to play and he knows this is
his job.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the eyes of everyone, if the league comes through with a
reasonable offer on (par) with offers that other players are given
with (Cienfuegos) relevance, I believe Mauricio will accept it. And
I do believe he deserves to be paid with that elite group.''
</P>
</TEXT>
