<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-16 22:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3032 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-MODESTI-COLUMN-LA     03-16 0879
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-MODESTI-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHEFFIELD'S COMPLAINTS GETTING HAIRY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   VERO BEACH, Fla. _ The player with the ear-lobe jewelry and the
``sensitive'' label, back with his team earlier than expected
following an excused absence, was asked Tuesday if it had been a
time for soul-searching.
</P>
<P>
   ``Soul-searching?'' he replied incredulously. ``Man, I don't
know where you get that from. I know who I am.''
</P>
<P>
   Who, Dennis Rodman?
</P>
<P>
   Well, no. Gary Sheffield is no Rodman, nothing that extreme. For
one thing, there's no crying in baseball.
</P>
<P>
   But Sheffield (begin ital)is(end ital) a player with the talent
to make or break the Dodgers' season if his self-absorption _ about
matters as trivial as personal grooming _ don't distract them or
him.
</P>
<P>
   Which, maybe, it just did.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, the day after he left the Dodgers' spring-training camp,
Sheffield was quoted musing about retirement, apparently expressing
frustration over a slow-to-heal throwing shoulder, a 1-for-15 start
in exhibition batting and _ worse _ his switch to left field and
the team policy against facial hair.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody took the retirement talk seriously, certainly nobody who
remembered Sheffield's similar venting at a bleak moment early in
the Florida Marlins' 1998 season, to which Marlins general manager
Dave Dombrowski replied, essentially, ``So retire!''
</P>
<P>
   Nor was there anything wrong with Sheffield's worry about the
shoulder, which threatens to keep him out of the April 5 season
opener.
</P>
<P>
   But when he made an issue of the position change, which he'd
originally approved, and the grooming rules, which are hardly
unique, he went over the line separating the introspective players
from the selfish.
</P>
<P>
   And when he returned to Dodgertown on Tuesday and declined
opportunities to put the left-field and facial-hair questions to
rest, he turned this into the latest fire that manager Davey
Johnson must put out.
</P>
<P>
   As Sheffield spoke to a circle of about 10 reporters in the
clubhouse, teammates were spotted rolling their eyes at the scene.
Some of those Dodgers later issued colorful no-comments.
</P>
<P>
   The surprise might be it took Sheffield _ the last holdover from
the seven-player trade headed by Mike Piazza _ 10 months in Los
Angeles to live up to his reputation.
</P>
<P>
   Until now, he'd been a sweetheart with management, teammates and
reporters. After writing last May that Sheffield was physically and
emotionally fragile, I'd come to doubt my words.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gary's reputation preceded him here,'' Dodgers president Bob
Graziano said Tuesday. ``(But) when he came over, I thought the
reputation was about somebody different.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers like Sheffield, and love his 42-homer, 120-RBI
power, and so they're unusually sympathetic in the wake of his
recent statements.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're here to support him and help him,'' general manager
Kevin Malone said. ``He knows my door is always open.''
</P>
<P>
   Malone added: ``I like players that have their own opinions and
say what they think. I myself am like that.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody deals with (trouble) in different ways,'' first
baseman Eric Karros said. ``Maybe it's easier for him to deal with
it by talking about it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I would hate,'' Graziano said, ``for people to judge Gary
based on comments he made one day last week.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers know the reason for Sheffield's two-day leave was
innocent, and believe the four-time All-Star has earned special
treatment.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, there are a lot of players who've earned it but don't
need it quite as badly as he does.
</P>
<P>
   For their part, what the Dodgers need is Sheffield to move from
right field, Raul Mondesi's natural position, to left. It's one of
those good-of-the-team sacrifices that should come naturally to a
player with a Marlins World Series ring.
</P>
<P>
   To Sheffield, it's an issue. He refers to himself as ``an
All-Star in right field,'' missing the point that he's really an
All-Star hitter with lesser credentials as a fielder.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers' no-beards rule, revived by Johnson and Malone, is a
problem to Sheffield because he says he has sensitive skin.
</P>
<P>
   On top of that, Sheffield complained that management has failed
to address the grooming issue in a meeting with players. He said,
``Everything's about respect.''
</P>
<P>
   Right now, it sounds more like it's about a guy with a bad
shoulder and a worse spring training batting average taking it out
on a small target.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gary's a guy who speaks his mind, what's on it at any
particular time,'' said Dombrowski, Sheffield's former GM. ``He can
hit, though.''
</P>
<P>
   He can, anyway, if his head and heart are in it.
</P>
<P>
   As of Tuesday, he was saying things like, ``I'm not going to
play unless I'm 100 percent (healthy),'' which hardly rings with
commitment.
</P>
<P>
   At 30, he's a player whose greatest seasons came with .500-range
teams in San Diego (1992) and Florida (1996).
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers, with a World Series in their plans, need a big year
from Sheffield. They need a hitter who'll carry them in those
inevitable stretches when nothing else goes right. They need a new
Piazza.
</P>
<P>
   But the way things are going with Sheffield, what they've got is
another reason to regret trading away the Piazza they had. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
