<P>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following photos are part of tonight's
New York Times Photo Package, moving 03/16/99. Photo clients will
automatically receive these photos via AP's PhotoExpress or may
download them from either the Wieck Photo Database in Dallas at
972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at 305-448-8411.
Non-clients can make individual purchases by calling (888) 603-1036
or 212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT27) CROCKETT, Calif. -- March 16, 1999 -- WASTE-ECO-PARKS-3,
3-16 -- Triad Energy Resources is a pioneer in developing
eco-industrial parks, where industrial byproducts are turned into
raw materials for other uses. Sifted material from sugar byproducts
is used as a soil enricher, adding calcium phospahte and creating a
better consistency. (Anne Dowie/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT26) CROCKETT, Calif. -- March 16, 1999 -- WASTE-ECO-PARKS-2,
3-16 -- Triad Energy Resources is a pioneer in developing
eco-industrial parks, where industrial byproducts are turned into
raw materials for other uses. In processing sugar, material rich in
organic matter has long been discarded. In the operation shown
here, the material is sifted to remove rocks that were added as
landfill, producing a fine soil. (Anne Dowie/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT25) CROCKETT, Calif. -- March 16, 1999 -- WASTE-ECO-PARKS-1,
3-16 -- Michael R. Daley, president of Triad Energy Resources, is a
pioneer in developing eco-industrial parks, where industrial
byproducts are turned into raw materials for other uses. ``If
companies were smart, they'd all locate near sources of waste,'' he
says. (Anne Dowie/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT24) POMPANO BEACH, Fla. -- March 16, 1999 -- TEN-PRODIGY-2,
3-16 -- Monique Viele working on her serve Tuesday at the Palm Air
Country Club courts in Pompano Beach. At 14, she has become a
disgruntled tennis prodigy whose equally disgruntled parents, Rick
and Bernadette, have vowed to sue the WTA Tour if it persists in
preventing their daughter from turning professional and hanging out
her shingle, and her star, right now. (Gary I. Rothstein/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT23) POMPANO BEACH, Fla. -- March 16, 1999 -- TEN-PRODIGY-1,
3-16 -- Monique Viele, center, with her father, Richard, and her
mother, Bernadette, on Tuesday. The family moved to Florida to help
the daughter's tennis career. (Gary I. Rothstein/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT22) NEW YORK -- March 16, 1999 -- NY-DIALLO-DA, 3-16 --
Robert T. Johnson, the Bronx District Attorney, tries to maintain a
strong bond with his constituents, attending countless community
events. He recently met with women concerned about victims' rights.
(Michelle V. Agins/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT21) NEW YORK -- March 16, 1999 -- CHESS-BLACK-GRANDMASTER,
3-16 -- Maurice Ashley, newly minted grandmaster, explaining a
position. In the clubby, eccentric world of chess, Ashley is known
for his straightforwardness, clarity and determined playing style.
``It's not significant to me to be the best black chess player in
the world,'' he says. ``But it is sweet to be the first.'' (Librado
Romero/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT20) SEATTLE -- March 16, 1999 -- SEATTLE-SALMON, 3-16 --
Protesters rallying at Pike Place Public Market in Seattle on
Monday night in support of placing nine species of salmon on the
threatened list. The listing, which was announced Tuesday, is
expected to have broad consequences for the residents of the
Seattle area. (Larry Davis/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT19) NEW YORK -- March 16, 1999 -- MARKET, 3-16 -- New York
Stock Exchange traders celebrating the Dow's breach of the
10,000-point barrier Tuesday. But it reversed its early climb and
ended the session lower. (Ruby Washington/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) WASHINGTON -- March 16, 1999 -- CONGRESS-BUDGET, 3-16 --
Sens. Frank R. Lautenberg, D-N.J., left, and Pete V. Domenici, the
New Mexico Republican who is chairman of the Senate Budget
Committee, confer during Tuesday afternoon's committee hearing.
Republicans laid out a budget proposal that makes good on their
promises to cut taxes and increase spending on the military and
education, but at the cost of deep cuts elsewhere. (Justin Lane/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) CAMBRIDGE, Mass. -- March 16, 1999 -- HARVARD-ANGST,
3-16 -- Almost half of Harvard students surveyed say they have two
hours of free time a day, or less. In the library of Pfozheimer
House on a recent Friday evening, Aric Christal, left, and Brian
Joseph crack the books. (Evan Richman/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) MIAMI -- March 16, 1999 -- BAPTISTS-LYONS, 3-16 --
Connie Chung talks with the Rev. Henry Lyons In an exclusive
interview for ABC News' ``20/20.'' Lyons, the nationally prominent
black minister from Florida who was convicted this month on charges
of racketeering and grand theft, stepped down Tuesday as president
of the National Baptist Convention USA. ``With tremendous
dignity,'' says his attorney, Grady Irvin, in describing Lyons'
announcement. (Todd Anderson/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) ELI, West Bank -- March 16, 1999 --
ISRAEL-SETTLEMENTS-1, 3-16 -- Uriya Levinshtein, front, her sister
Emuna and their parents moved from an established settlement in Eli
to a trailer nearby. Settlers and opponents argue: Is this a ``new
settlement'' or ``natural expansion''? (Rina Castelnuovo/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) OFRA, West Bank -- March 16, 1999 --
ISRAEL-SETTLEMENTS-1, 3-16 -- New Jewish homes near Ofra, on the
West Bank. Some Jews hope that larger settlements - they call them
``facts on the ground'' - will give them rights to more land, but
both Palestinians and Americans are angry. (Rina Castelnuovo/New
York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) BOSTON -- March 16, 1999 -- ONBUSINESS-COLUMN-BOS, 3-16
--- Terry Murray, left, and Chad Gifford at a press conference
announcing the merger of Fleet Financial Group and BankBoston Corp.
at the Park Plaza Hotel in Boston. A number of smaller local banks
were positively gushing about the prospect of getting a chance to
acquire some of the $13 billion in deposits that will have to be
divested to meet antitrust concerns. (Pat Greenhouse/Boston Globe
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) BOSTON -- March 16, 1999 -- MUSIC-ALI-BOS, 3-16 ---
Tatyana Ali, of the sitcom ``Fresh Prince of Belair,'' talks with
her mother, Sonia, during a break at a recent photo shoot in
Boston. She is managing to combine the unthinkable: the music
industry, Hollywood, and Harvard. ``I want to finish on time,''
says Ms. Ali, 20. ``I'll do five classes my sophomore year and
summer school this summer.'' (Pam Berry/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) BOURBONNAIS, Ill. -- March 16, 1999 -- TRAIN-CRASH-2,
3-16 -- Rescue crews combing through the wreckage of Amtrak's City
of New Orleans on Tuesday. The train struck a truck and derailed
shortly after 9:30 p.m. Monday. At least 14 people were killed and
four others were missing and feared dead. (Todd Buchanan/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) BOURBONNAIS, Ill. -- March 16, 1999 -- TRAIN-CRASH-1,
3-16 -- A rescue crew member combs through a twisted, charred rail
car Tuesday, with little hope of finding survivors after Amtrak's
City of New Orleans struck a truck and derailed shortly after 9:30
p.m. Monday. At least 14 people were killed and four others were
missing and feared dead. (Todd Buchanan/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) NEW YORK -- March 16, 1999 -- PHILADELPHIA-ORCHESTRA,
3-16 -- Wolfgang Sawallisch conducts the Philadelphia Orchestra,
which will perform works from its first 100 years. Joseph H.
Kluger, the orchestra's president, says he realizes that the label
``20th-century music'' often conjures up ``a stereotype of music
that is ... atonal, and harshly dissonant.'' But, he is quick to
point out that this century also has its share of ``popular and
accessible'' works. (Ozier Muhammad/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) NEW YORK -- March 16, 1999 -- STUDENT-OSCAR, 3-16 --
Keiko Ibi, who received a Master of Fine Arts from New York
University last year, with two of the people in her Oscar-nominated
documentary, Selma Wernick and Harold Gordon. ``It's really
surreal,'' Ms. Ibi, 32, says of the nomination of her film, ``The
Personals: Improvisations on Romance in the Golden Years,'' and the
flurry of telephone calls and E-mail media interviews it has
spawned. (Linda Rosier/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) ASBURY PARK, N.J. -- March 16, 1999 -- HEAVY-METAL-2,
3-16 -- Fans enjoying the music during ``March Metal Meltdown'' in
Asbury Park. Contrary to what might be expected there were plenty
of women in attendance; the grimmer sub-genres of metal have a lot
of female fans, perhaps because the lyrics do not usually carry a
sexist aggressiveness. (Nicole Bengiveno/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) ASBURY PARK, N.J. -- March 16, 1999 -- HEAVY-METAL-1,
3-16 -- Matthew Barlow of Iced Earth at ``March Metal Meltdown'' in
Asbury Park. Metal has evolved at a creeping pace, its various
splintered genres hanging on through waxing and waning demands for
it in the marketplace. (Nicole Bengiveno/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) NEW YORK -- March 16, 1999 -- AMISH-COOKING-2, 3-16 -- In
