<HEADLINE>
LOS ANGELES TENTATIVELY AWARDED AN NFL TEAM
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Texas)   (nk) 
 By THOMAS GEORGE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ Los Angeles was awarded the National Football League's
32nd franchise by an overwhelming margin Tuesday at the owners'
annual meeting. There were, however, several conditions.
</P>
<P>
   The league stipulated that a stadium site, financing and support
from the Los Angeles business community must be in place by Sept.
15. If not, Houston would receive the franchise.
</P>
<P>
   The stadium options include a refurbished Los Angeles Memorial
Coliseum or new stadiums in either in the city of Carson or in
Orange County. The decision also opened the door for various
ownership groups to surface in Los Angeles and bid for the new
team, which is projected to begin play in 2002.
</P>
<P>
   The vote for Los Angeles was by 29-2. The Buffalo Bills and
Oakland Raiders reportedly voted against the resolution.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fortunately, the league had an interesting dilemma,'' said
Jerry Richardson, the Carolina Panthers owner who is chairman of
the league's expansion committee. ``We have two attractive markets
in Houston and L.A. and one only one franchise. The way I see it,
we've tightened up the window.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the expansion committee will visit sites in Los Angeles
in the next three weeks and recommend to the league where a stadium
should be built.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are talking about the greater L.A. area, and that gives us
a window to go anywhere,'' Richardson said. ``But given the time
constraints, I just can't see any other sites being selected in
L.A. other than the Coliseum, Carson or, remotely, Orange County.''
</P>
<P>
   Richardson said he would be surprised if other groups in Los
Angeles did not surface that would like to buy the team.
</P>
<P>
   It was clear the league was not ready to grant the franchise to
the two groups in Los Angeles who have long been in the race and
who came here hoping that one of them would leave with the team.
Businessmen Ed Roski and Eli Broad head one group that wants the
team to play in the Coliseum and Hollywood mogul Michael Ovitz
wants the team and have it play in Carson. The owners agreed that
too many questions _ stadium financing, parking and ancillary
development _ remained to award the franchise Tuesday to either
group.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to see a very viable stadium proposal; we haven't seen
that yet,'' said Pat Bowlen, the Denver Broncos' owner.
</P>
<P>
   ``If L.A. doesn't get its house in order, this franchise is
Houston's,'' said Dan Rooney, the Pittsburgh Steelers' owner.
</P>
<P>
   When Rooney was asked if the owners were concerned that Al
Davis, the Raiders owner, might sue as he has threatened because he
believes he still owns rights to the Los Angeles market, Rooney
answered, ``It's not a factor as far as we're concerned.''
</P>
<P>
   Houston businessman Bob McNair has a strong bid with stadium
proposals in place in Houston, but the league wants to pursue Los
Angeles first because of the size of the market and because ``it is
the entertainment capital of the U.S. and maybe the world.''
</P>
<P>
   McNair was gracious in accepting the delay, adding: ``We feel we
have a deadline we can work with and something to hope for. It's
something we can deal with. We look forward to the opportunity of
going forward and seeing what the ultimate outcome will be.''
</P>
<P>
   The meetings continue Wednesday to vote on the sale of the
Washington Redskins and on the return of instant replay for the
1999 season.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In other action Tuesday, Commissioner Paul Tagliabue announced
that Eddie DeBartolo, the San Francisco 49ers' owner who was
suspended last year for gambling ties and for his felony plea as a
result of them, has been fined $1 million and suspended through the
1999 season. DeBartolo can resume control of the 49ers in February
2000, Tagliabue said, if DeBartolo complies with an order he
signed. It says he will not conduct himself in ways detrimental to
the league. If he does, he will fined an additional $4 million,
Tagliabue said.
</P>
<P>
   Tagliabue said there was strong sentiment among the owners to
keep the Thanksgiving Day games in Detroit and Dallas. He said
several franchises wanted the game in their cities to build their
own tradition on that day, but that most said the games should stay
in Detroit and Dallas.
</P>
</TEXT>
