<SLUG> BC-COCA-COLA-EARNINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
$1.2 BILLION BILL AT COKE RAISES EYEBROWS
</HEADLINE>
   (dal) 
 By CONSTANCE L. HAYS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In 1998, a grim year for the Coca-Cola Co., one bright spot was
the United States, where case volume sales rose a healthy 6
percent. But that appears to have come at a high price.
</P>
<P>
   In its annual report, distributed last week, Coca-Cola disclosed
that it spent more than $1.2 billion on ``direct support for
certain marketing activities'' for its largest bottler, Coca-Cola
Enterprises, which handles the bulk of Coca-Cola's volume in the
United States in addition to sales in several countries in Western
Europe. Coca-Cola controls about 42 percent of Coca-Cola
Enterprises, which was spun off as a separate, publicly traded
company in 1986.
</P>
<P>
   The expenditure, nearly twice what Coca-Cola spent on the
bottler the year before, included $899 million for marketing and
$324 million for vending machines and other equipment. It far
outstripped the $640 million spent last year for marketing at all
other bottlers in which the company holds equity stakes, the report
noted.
</P>
<P>
   The amount takes on added significance when compared with
Coca-Cola Enterprises earnings for 1998: just $141 million, on
revenue of $13.4 billion. Operating income was $869 million, but
that dwindled rapidly once the company paid $701 million in
interest and $56 million in taxes.
</P>
<P>
   James S. Chanos, who runs Kynikos Associates, a money management
fund in New York, said the marketing expenses that Coca-Cola has
absorbed for Coca-Cola Enterprises were ``an increasingly important
part of the revenue for C.C.E.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The company's cash flow over the last two years, without these
payments from the parent, would have declined,'' said Chanos, whose
company is a ``short seller,'' betting that the share price of
Coca-Cola Enterprises will decline.
</P>
<P>
   The marketing costs were keenly felt over at the Coca-Cola Co.,
which turned in one of its most lackluster performances in years in
1998. With volume flat or declining in Russia, Japan, South Africa,
Germany, Brazil and other key markets, the company's earnings fell
15 percent, from $4.1 billion in 1997 to $3.5 billion.
</P>
<P>
   ``The marketing was up 49 percent, and the infrastructure
spending was up 71 percent,'' said Caroline Levy, a beverage
analyst for Schroder &AMP; Co., who removed Coca-Cola Enterprises from
her recommended list last fall and has a neutral rating on
Coca-Cola. ``If they hadn't spent that money, their earnings would
not have been as badly hit last year.''
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Coca-Cola, Mark Preisinger, played down the
marketing expense, saying that the territory covered by the bottler
grew with acquisitions made during 1998. ``There is nothing new
here except that there is substantially greater territory within
C.C.E.,'' Preisinger said, adding that marketing expenses are
determined in the early part of every year. ``This is money we
contribute to drive the business.''
</P>
<P>
   But a closer look shows that the marketing expenses rose 25
percent even when the bottlers acquired during 1998 are figured in,
and amount to 24.9 cents a case, up from 20 cents in 1997.
Coca-Cola Enterprises bottled about 3.6 billion cases of soft
drinks last year, up from 3.4 billion in 1997. Over all, in the
United States, volume grew to 4.47 billion cases. Worldwide, 15.8
billion cases were sold last year, a increase of 900 million cases
over 1997.
</P>
<P>
   The increase in marketing spending has much to do with a long
price war between Coca-Cola and its big rival, Pepsico, in
supermarkets, where prices have been abnormally low for more than
two years in many areas of the country.
</P>
<P>
   Marketing takes many forms at Coca-Cola, ranging from discount
coupons handed out in local supermarkets to sponsorship of
community events to more sophisticated tie-ins with Coke products
like the Coke card. The company distributed more than 40 million of
the cards last spring and summer, offering discounts at bowling
centers, amusement parks and other entertainment sites with the
purchase of a Coca-Cola, all to drive sales.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's certainly something that benefits the system,'' said
Laura Asman, a spokeswoman for Coca-Cola Enterprises. ``The direct
support is a natural function of the franchise system and the
Coca-Cola Co. sharing in the investment in our system.''
</P>
<P>
   Coca-Cola executives have said they plan to reduce spending on
marketing this year, said Andrew M. Conway, an analyst for Morgan
Stanley. ``That's not negative for CCE if pricing improves in
supermarkets,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Coca-Cola Enterprises is one of 11 major bottlers for Coca-Cola.
Coca-Cola's chief financial officer, James E. Chestnut, was named
to the Coca-Cola Enterprises board last month.
</P>
<P>
   In a reflection of the sluggish sales of Coke products around
the world, Coca-Cola's equity income from all bottlers it has made
investments in fell markedly last year. In 1997, the company
reported $155 million from such bottlers, which account for more
than half of Coca-Cola's volume around the world. But last year,
equity income plummeted to $32 million, a decrease of 79 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
