<SLUG> BC-SEC-DISCLOSURE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEC CONSIDERS TIGHTENING RULES ON COMPANY DISCLOSURES
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By MELODY PETERSEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Concerned that some investors may be getting key stock
information before the rest of the market, federal securities
regulators are considering tightening disclosure rules so that
companies will be forced to announce news to all investors at the
same time.
</P>
<P>
   Harvey J. Goldschmid, general counsel at the Securities and
Exchange Commission, said Tuesday that commission lawyers were
reviewing situations in which companies might have given
information to certain analysts and investors before it was
available to the public. Regulators are worried that some investors
have been able to profit by getting the information first, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The regulators' review, which is expected to take eight or nine
months, could result in new disclosure rules for public companies.
The commission may require, for example, that companies issue news
releases with any significant new information that they plan to
tell analysts or certain investors at invitation-only meetings or
during conference calls that are not open to the public, Goldschmid
said.
</P>
<P>
   But the commission's lawyers are proceeding carefully, he said,
because they do not want any new rule to reduce the amount of
information that companies are now willing to provide to analysts
and the public. ``That would not be healthy,'' Goldschmid said.
</P>
<P>
   In recent speeches, SEC Chairman Arthur Levitt has criticized
companies for selectively disclosing key information to certain
investors. Levitt has pointed out, for example, how some corporate
executives often call their favorite stock analysts to discuss
earnings results before the numbers are released to the public.
</P>
<P>
   Most companies try to disclose new information to all investors
at the same time. But sometimes, it is not immediately clear how
significant the new information is.
</P>
<P>
   In January, for example, the stock price of the General Motors
Corp. rose the same day that it told analysts at an invitation-only
meeting about its plans to increase the production of pickups and
sport utilities, which are among the company's most profitable
products. But Mark Tanner, a company spokesman, said the same
information could have been derived from detailed production
schedules that the company had already distributed to the public.
``It was only highlighted at the meeting with analysts,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Tanner said General Motors' policy was to disclose news to the
entire market at once. ``We're very judicious about it,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-16-99 2238EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
