<HEADER>
A3050 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SLUM-LAW-AZR &LR;      03-16 0916
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SLUM-LAW-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOUGH ANTI-SLUMLORD LEGISLATION APPROVED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PAT KOSSAN  
 and WILLIAM HERMANN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ A law designed to root out slumlords, along with the
blight and crime they bring to neighborhoods, passed the
Legislature on Tuesday and is on its way to Gov. Jane Hull, who is
expected to sign it.
</P>
<P>
   The bill passed its last hurdle when the House approved it on a
42-13 vote, with five not voting.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation requires property owners or agents to register
with the county assessors' offices, increases penalties for
landlords who don't clean up their property, and gives cities and
counties new powers against owners of property used for criminal
activity.
</P>
<P>
   It makes Arizona's anti-slumlord law one of the toughest in the
nation, but it might be an idle threat if cities and counties don't
have the political will to enforce it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've closed some of the loopholes slumlords had to bypass
city ordinances and prosecution,'' said Rep. Ken Cheuvront, the
central Phoenix Democrat who helped work the bill through a
minefield of opposition. ``It's up to the cities to utilize this
statute and up to the neighbors to put forth the pressure.''
</P>
<P>
   Neighborhood activists say cities, towns or counties must
establish a partnership with law enforcement and back up the new
law with money budgeted to hire an adequate number of inspectors to
respond to neighbors' complaints.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's time for cities and counties to step up to the plate and
do their share, including me,'' said Maricopa County Attorney Rick
Romley, who has committed time and money to help neighbors salvage
their streets and property values.
</P>
<P>
   The law strengthens existing property codes in Phoenix, Glendale
and Tempe, and it's expected to encourage the adoption of codes in
other cities, including Mesa, where council members plan to ask
voters to approve a housing maintenance code in the March 2000
elections.
</P>
<P>
   ``If voluntary compliance doesn't happen,'' Romley said, ``we
have to make sure there's a place for neighbors to reach out to.''
</P>
<P>
   The bill was created and championed by Romley; Phoenix City
Councilman Phil Gordon; a Slumlord Task Force of county and federal
prosecutors, police, and housing inspectors; several Republican and
Democratic lawmakers; and a well-organized group of neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   But it also got a boost from an unlikely source: Sherwin
Seyrafi, who faces city, county and federal charges stemming from
his substandard rentals.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sherwin Seyrafi turned out to be the best thing we had,''
Romley said, laughing. ``He put a face in the newspaper, on the TV
cameras, of who we were talking about when we mentioned the owners
of these slum properties.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it had been some poor old guy who couldn't really afford to
fix up a place, that would have been different. But Seyrafi could
have fixed them up, and refused to. His expensive suits, arrogant
attitude . . . that got to people.''
</P>
<P>
   It may have been Seyrafi's public legal battles that convinced
the Arizona Multihousing Association to stop years of lobbying
against the neighbors and their demands that something be done
about slumlords and the crime their properties breed. The group not
only stopped fighting but began helping with the legislation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not going to walk away since the law is done,''
association spokesman Wayne Kaplan said. ``We hope this is the
beginning of a journey of cooperation with cities, neighborhoods
and homeowners to deal with issues.''
</P>
<P>
   Romley and others note that long before there was Seyrafi, long
before the Slumlord Task Force, there were neighborhood activists.
</P>
<P>
   ``What happened in the last year was they (the politicians) saw
it,'' said Donna Neill, who founded a statewide neighborhood
association and fought for years to bring politicians into her
neighborhood to see the problems firsthand. ``It was in the
newspaper, it was on TV. It came right in front of them. They had
to deal with it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now we have to see what happens. We have to protect it and
amend it and make it stronger. We must see the cities turn the
state law into proper regulations.''
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Alma Williams, an east Phoenix neighborhood leader,
stood in Karl Baker's front yard looking at the place on the other
side of Baker's chain-link fence where sewage once pooled and
leaked onto his property. The small, shabby apartment building next
door once was owned by Seyrafi.
</P>
<P>
   It has a new owner, but before the law passed, the new owner
didn't have to worry about citations the city wrote to Seyrafi. If
slum properties weren't cleaned up by a new owner, city inspectors
were forced to open a new case, a new investigation and write new
citations to defend in court each time the property changed hands,
which happens often with substandard properties.
</P>
<P>
   But the new law changes that.
</P>
<P>
   ``If this law works, if the owner sells it _ then violations are
supposed to follow the property,'' Williams said. ``It's one of the
biggest hopes we have.''
</P>
<P>
   But Williams is cautious about the new slumlord law, worried
that it could be undermined or circumvented by politicians
unwilling to make it work.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now we have a lot of tools in the law, but do you have
enforcement?'' she asked. Without relentless and expensive
enforcement, slums will persist, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tell neighborhood leaders: Don't listen to what politicians
are telling you; follow the money,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
