<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-16 22:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3051 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AMFAR-AD-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      03-16 0813
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AMFAR-AD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADVERTISING: AIDS, THE WAR THAT ISN'T OVER, GAINS SOME NEW
MARKETING GENERALS
</HEADLINE>
   (dal) 
 By STUART ELLIOTT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A giant agency company is enlisting in the fight
against AIDS to battle not fear or ignorance but a perception that
the fight is finished.
</P>
<P>
   Young &AMP; Rubicam Inc. in New York is joining the American
Foundation for AIDS Research, known as Amfar, in what is intended
to be a comprehensive, multimedia communications program. The goal
is to counter a growing belief that AIDS is no longer as much a
menace to public health as it seemed before the introduction of
treatments like protease inhibitor drugs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Very simply, we want to attack this complacency issue,'' said
Edward H. Vick, chief operating officer at Y.&AMP; R., because despite
recent progress, ``AIDS is still a problem _ and could be a bigger
one.''
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Vick said, ``we want to raise the level of
visibility for Amfar'' and raise donations, now at $18 million to
$22 million a year, by focusing on Amfar's support of clinical and
biomedical research as well as AIDS prevention. So the campaign
carries this new theme: ``We've bought time. More research will buy
answers.''
</P>
<P>
   Vick joined the Amfar board at the behest of a member, Alan D.
Schwartz, who is also on the board of Y.&AMP; R.; Schwartz is executive
vice president and senior managing director at the Bear Stearns
Cos. Employee volunteers from four units of Y.&AMP; R. are
collaborating on the pro bono campaign, contributing advertising,
direct marketing, corporate identity and public relations work that
ranges from low-key commercials to a distinctive redesigned logo
that adds the words ``AIDS research'' under the Amfar acronym.
</P>
<P>
   Those contributions from Y.&AMP; R. Advertising, Wunderman Cato
Johnson, Landor Associates and Burson-Marsteller will be
supplemented by outdoor and transit posters from Kenneth Cole
Productions in New York, the fashion retailer, which has been
donating ads to Amfar as part of its long-running cause-related
marketing efforts.
</P>
<P>
   Television and radio networks, magazines and outdoor advertising
companies have agreed to donate more than $2 million worth of
commercial time and ad space for the campaign. But Y.&AMP; R. and Amfar
are seeking additional commitments worth at least $3 million to
further expand the campaign's reach.
</P>
<P>
   ``This epidemic is not going away any time soon,'' said Jerome
J. Radwin, executive vice president and chief executive at Amfar in
New York, ``so we needed to sustain a long-term communication
effort.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Ed said that's exactly what he can bring to the table,'' he
added, ``and that has made an enormous difference to us.''
</P>
<P>
   In the campaign, the Y.&AMP; R. volunteers decided that Amfar ought
to be treated as a brand.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a little odd to think of an organization like that,''
said one volunteer, Peter C. Diamond, vice president and account
director at Young &AMP; Rubicam New York, a unit of Y.&AMP; R. Advertising.
</P>
<P>
   But the branding approach was chosen because the idea is to
``make sure Amfar stands for something,'' he added, and because
previous pro bono campaigns ``lacked a cohesive, unified image.''
</P>
<P>
   Radwin described the campaign's premise as ``a very, very
difficult balancing act.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The success we've had with biomedical research gives us every
reason to believe that it will provide solutions,'' he said, ``but
we have to get people to understand we're not there yet.''
</P>
<P>
   So, a print advertisement, showing a discarded, tattered AIDS
ribbon, carries the headline ``Apparently, the AIDS virus is so
smart it can convince people that it's no longer a threat.'' And
the TV commercials talk about the future for people who have the
virus that causes AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   One spot declares that an HIV-positive child can ``look forward
to new sneakers, summer vacations, a later bedtime.'' Another spot
asserts that an HIV-positive mother can ``look forward to seeing
first steps, going to school plays, sharing the big popcorn at the
movies.''
</P>
<P>
   In both instances, those lists of upbeat expectations end with
the phrase ``and eventually, getting AIDS.'' That's when the new
theme appears on screen.
</P>
<P>
   The media that have agreed so far to donate time and space are
the broadcast networks ABC and CBS; the cable channel Lifetime; CBS
radio; TDI, the outdoor advertising company, and Entertainment
Weekly, Esquire, People and Sports Illustrated magazines.
</P>
<P>
   Other nonprofit organizations that have benefited from pro bono
campaigns by Y.&AMP; R. include UNCF/The College Fund, formerly the
United Negro College Fund.
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether he was worried about becoming involved with a
cause like the fight against AIDS, which many Americans still
stigmatize, Vick replied: ``I'm not concerned about anybody's
reaction. It could be worse; you could represent a political
candidate.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
