<HEADLINE>
DON'T CALL IT FRISCO; CALL IT DR PEPPER
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds: This story also moved in the ``a'' national news file)  
 By LEAH GARCHIK  
 c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   San Francisco has ``put out feelers to advertisers'' to attract
an official corporate sponsor, says a story gleaned by
 &UR; Doug Johnson &LR;  from Monday's Los Angeles Times.
</P>
<P>
   The Times'  &UR; Roy Rivenburg &LR;  said that after Huntington Beach
signed with Coca-Cola to be that city's official beverage, city
administrators heard from counterparts in San Francisco, Long Beach
and Cleveland inquiring about the contract. Coke pays $300,000 a
year to put its logos on Huntington Beach's lifeguard towers, trash
bins and other city property. Board of Supervisors President  &UR; Tom
Ammiano  &LR; says the city as a whole hasn't made any inquiries, but
individual departments _ Park &AMP; Rec, for example _ may have looked
into sponsorship.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; HOW TO KEEP LOVE ALIVE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Peta Wilson &LR;  told Men's Fitness what she likes in a man:
``Vulnerability. I like it when a man wears his heart on his sleeve
_ and it's OK if he wipes his nose on it now and again.''
</P>
<P>
   As to what other women like, the magazine offers this advice,
from sex expert Dr.  &UR; Joy Davidson &LR; : ``Remember her name.''
</P>
<P>
   P.S. If ``he inquired how you felt about the hypocrisy of the
Republican Party during the impeachment trial of  &UR; President &LR; 
 &UR; Clinton &LR; ,'' says Seventeen magazine, he has a crush on you.
</P>
<P>
   P.P.S. Twelve out of 20 Glamour magazine staffers playing the
board game Death Is Not an Option would rather go to bed with
 &UR; Jesse Ventura &LR;  than  &UR; George W. Bush Jr. &LR; ; eight chose the
Bush-ster. When it came time to choose between  &UR; Newt Gingrich &LR;  and
 &UR; Jesse Helms &LR; , one staffer insisted on death.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MOVIEMAKERS REWRITING HISTORY &LR;
</P>
<P>
   British sticklers are unhappy with Universal Studios' plan for a
World War II movie about Americans who captured a piece of
 &UR; Hitler &LR; 's encryption equipment and were able to break Nazi codes.
What's irking the British, explains the BBC, is that the feat was
actually accomplished by the British Navy.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Charles Baker-Cresswell &LR; , whose father commanded the Royal Navy
destroyer that captured the machine, called the movie's twisting of
history ``typical. ... We've seen this time and time again.''
Universal says that the movie, with  &UR; Harvey Keitel  &LR; and
 &UR; Jon Bon Jovi &LR; , will not be advertised as fact but as fiction
``based on real events.''
</P>
<P>
   The British Navy's official response is that ``it is
unfortunate, but it is not the first time, and I am sure it will
not be the last, that Hollywood has distorted history.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FLASH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Tom Wolfe  &LR; is going to be spending five weeks or so as a
visiting scholar in the graduate program in journalism at Stanford
University's Department of Communication. He'll be there ``to take
a look at campus life,'' said a representative for his publisher,
Farrar, Straus &AMP; Giroux, in preparation for a novel ``set in the
world of education.''
</P>
<P>
   In gratitude for the chance to observe, Wolfe may teach or
lecture while he's on campus, said the his  &LR; publisher, but the
position offers no financial recompense or living provisions.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Betty Currie &LR; , presidential gate-keeper, earns about $60,000
a year, reports the Washington Post, so some of her pals have
established a Betty Currie Legal Expense Trust Fund. (Ask for a
raise, Betty; it's not fair that  &UR; Linda Tripp &LR;  pulls down more than
$90,000.)
</P>
<P>
   _ Since  &UR; Michael Roizen &LR;  claims in his book, ``RealAge: Are You
as Young as You Can Be?'' (Cliff Street; $25), that flossing teeth
daily makes your Real Age 6.4 years younger, and a happy sex life
can make your RealAge six years younger, &UR; Betsy Nolan &LR;  wonders
whether she can get 12 years out of doing both things at once.
</P>
<P>
   _ There's still time to sign up for Clothing Optional
Cross-Country Ski Night, the Full Moon Package on March 31 and
April 1 at the Snowvillage Inn in Mount Washington, N.H. Self
magazine says that naked skiers are given flashlights and cassette
tapes with such selections as ``Moon River'' and ``By the Light of
the Silvery Moon.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Former Boston Globe columnist  &UR; Mike Barnicle &LR; , who left after
being accused of fabricating stories, has been hired by the
</P>
<P>
   New York Daily News to write a weekly opinion column that will
run on Sundays.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHO SAID WHAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm smarter than people give me credit for. I have a light
personality and a deep-thinking brain.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Goldie Hawn in More magazine.
</P>
