A3054 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-DODGERS-NOTES-LAD     03-16 0640
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHEFFIELD'S MOOD DOESN'T IMPROVE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   VERO BEACH, Fla. _ Gary Sheffield is frustrated. His right
shoulder hurts, he's struggling with his move from right to left
field and he's unhappy with the way the Dodgers' reinstituted the
facial hair policy.
</P>
<P>
   The team hoped the two days off for family business would help
Sheffield, but on Tuesday, he was still unhappy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to play if I'm not 100 percent,'' said
Sheffield, who then talked about retiring. ``I always feel like
that when I get injured. Is it worth it to take your body through
what I have to take my body through just to get on the baseball
field? Everybody can look at it and say it's a lot of money, but
everything in life isn't about dollars and cents.
</P>
<P>
   ``(The thought of retirement) comes and goes, but it's one of
those things that until I get healthy it's going to stay on my
mind, and you never know. You might react to certain things. I
guess I have to leave an open mind both ways.''
</P>
<P>
   Dodgers manager Davey Johnson said he's scaling back Sheffield's
work until the shoulder feels better. Sheffield, in the second year
of a six-year, $61 million contract, isn't expected to play for the
next few days.
</P>
<P>
   Normally a right fielder, Sheffield has played five games in
left field this spring. He's had limited chances and made one
error.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really didn't feel like I was accomplishing anything out
there,'' Sheffield said. ``I went two games without getting a ball
hit to me so I didn't learn anything that day. I played well one
day, so I have to build on that.''
</P>
<P>
   He was also concerned about the facial hair policy. Last year
the team relaxed the rules but decided to reinstate them during the
offseason. Team officials talked to players individually, but
Sheffield would like them to address the players as a group.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think out of respect, out of playing 11 years, they will
eventually address the team about the issue,'' Sheffield said.
``One-on-one they have, but I feel if you're going to address it,
sometimes it's better to address the team....
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to have facial hair and the rest of the guys
won't. I'm going to abide by the rules.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson and Dodgers general manager Kevin Malone said Sheffield
hasn't contacted them about his issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've talked to Gary a lot lately and he hasn't expressed
anything to Davey or I,'' Malone said. ``His only concern is that
his shoulder is not feeling well and he's a little uncomfortable in
left field. Other than that, there's no other issues that I'm aware
of.''
</P>
<P>
   Osuna setback: The Dodgers were taking it slow with right-handed
reliever Antonio Osuna's comeback from elbow surgery, but it hasn't
helped.
</P>
<P>
   Osuna had his bullpen outing cut short Tuesday and was
complaining about elbow soreness. Johnson was hoping to have Osuna
available for opening day, but that's looking less and less likely.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson said he hoped to use the one-time Dodgers closer in a
spring game late in the week.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm usually optimistic about things, but I don't know where
we're at,'' Johnson said. ``I feel discouraged about things and I
know so does he.''
</P>
<P>
   Roster cuts: The first large chunk of roster cuts were announced
Tuesday without surprise. The Dodgers optioned outfielder Hiram
Bocachica and pitchers Arnold Gooch, Mike Judd, Steve Montgomery
and Ricky Stone to Triple-A Albuquerque, pitchers Eric Gagne and
Luke Prokopec were optioned to Double-A San Antonio and pitcher
Randy Galvez was optioned to Single-A San Bernardino.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers also reassigned pitchers Dan Hubbs, Matt Herges,
Matt Jarvis and Gavin Osteen, infielders Pete Rose Jr. and Jason
Thompson and catcher Hector Ortiz to their minor-league camp.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
