<DOCNO> NYT19990316.0415 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-16 22:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3061 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOX-TITLE-FIGHT-460&AMP;A     03-16 0714
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-TITLE-FIGHT-460&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REFEREE CALLS LEWIS WINNER
</HEADLINE>
  (See related BOX-BERKOW-COLUMN) 
 (nk) 
 By RICHARD SANDOMIR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Arthur Mercante Jr., the referee in Saturday's
controversial draw between Lennox Lewis and Evander Holyfield, said
Tuesday that he felt Lewis was the clear victor.
</P>
<P>
   ``He took the fight to Evander,'' Mercante said of the 12-round
fight at Madison Square Garden. ``If I were scoring, I'd have given
Holyfield three rounds. Lewis wanted it so bad. And Evander, he
really wasn't focused and into the fight. His mind looked like it
was somewhere else.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we should go back to the old days and let the referee
score the fight. If they need his card, they should use it.''
</P>
<P>
   The judges' decision in the heavyweight unification bout has
inflamed the boxing world and led Manhattan District Attorney
Robert M. Morgenthau to agree to a request by City Council Speaker
Peter Vallone on Tuesday to investigate the fight.
</P>
<P>
   The New York state Athletic Commission launched an investigation
on Monday. Mercante will testify at a hearing to be held Thursday
by state Sen. Roy Goodman. A second hearing, by state Attorney
General Eliot Spitzer, is set for Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is just a crime for the sport I've been around all my
life,'' said Mercante, whose father, Arthur Sr., is a legendary
referee.
</P>
<P>
   Mercante said Holyfield's best round was the third, the one in
which he predicted he would knock Lewis out. ``But then he laid off
and Lennox took it right to him,'' Mercante said. ``I think Lennox
could have done more. He'd throw three or four punches, then tie
up, and I'd have to say, `Come on, guys, let's go.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Larry O'Connell, one of the three judges, scored the fight a
115-115 draw, but was quoted this week as saying that he was wrong.
Eugenia Williams, who scored the bout, 115-113, for Holyfield, has
vigorously defended her scoring. The third judge, Stanley
Christoudoulou, voted for Lewis, 116-113.
</P>
<P>
   Mercante said his father kept copious notes of the fight from
his seat at the Garden and scored the fight for Lewis, 9 rounds to
3.
</P>
<P>
   Also at the fight was Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., a fight fan who
has sponsored legislation to regulate boxing.
</P>
<P>
   McCain said Tuesday that Lonnie Ali, the wife of Muhammad Ali,
called to tell him that ``Muhammad is indignant and wants me to do
something about it because it was a disgrace to boxing.''
</P>
<P>
   Three years ago, Congress passed legislation co-authored by
McCain to strengthen health and safety measures for boxers.
</P>
<P>
   He has also reintroduced a bill, the Muhammad Ali Boxing Reform
Act, to reform the sanctioning organizations, protect boxers from
exploitation by promoters and require financial disclosure by the
organizations and promoters. An identical bill passed the Senate
last year but died in the House.
</P>
<P>
   ``Saturday's fiasco could help it pass the House,'' McCain said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   McCain, who is seeking the Republican presidential nomination in
2000, said he might amend the Ali Act to prohibit sanctioning
organizations from choosing judges. The World Boxing Council,
International Boxing Federation and World Boxing Association did so
for the Holyfield-Lewis fight.
</P>
<P>
   ``The judges being selected by the alphabet soup folks is not
acceptable,'' McCain said. ``It should be the state boxing
commissions who choose the best qualified people.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain also said the promoters should not pay the judges. The
Holyfield-Lewis judges were paid $5,150 each, with the money coming
from Don King, the promoter, through the sanctioning bodies.
``Judges should be completely independent,'' he said. ``The money
should could come out of the gate, not the promoter.''
</P>
<P>
   One provision of McCain's bill would limit options between
boxers and promoters to one year. If the law were in place, he
said, it might prevent King, Holyfield's promoter, from a role in
the expected rematch.
</P>
<P>
   Mercante said that after the fight, Panos Eliades, Lewis'
promoter, screamed from ringside at the New York state Athletic
Commission members about the judges. ``I had to intervene,''
Mercante said. ``I said, `The commission didn't appoint the judges,
the sanctioning bodies did.' ''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
