<SLUG> BC-NJ-POLICE-PROFILING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COURT WON'T PERMIT DELAY IN N.J. RACIAL PROFILING CASE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By ROBERT HANLEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HACKENSACK, N.J. _ A New Jersey appeals court refused Tuesday
night to give the administration of Gov. Christie Whitman more time
to appeal a judge's ruling in 1996 that state police tolerated a
``de facto policy of racial profiling'' on the southern half of the
New Jersey Turnpike.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, the state attorney general, Peter Verniero, said
publicly for the first time that his office was considering
dropping the appeal, as civil rights lawyers, black ministers and
some Democrats have been demanding for weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Verniero said in an interview that his final decision on the
fate of the appeal awaits completion of the racial profiling aspect
of his office's broad investigation of a variety of state police
practices, including trooper discipline, promotion, training, and
the department's handling of complaints from the public.
</P>
<P>
   Verniero said after the ruling by a three-judge panel of the
appellate division of New Jersey Superior Court that he hoped to
complete the review into racial profiling as quickly as possible
because, he said, he wants to base a final decision on the appeal
on as much information as possible. ``We may withdraw from the case
depending on what the review shows,'' he said. ``We do have
concerns about these issues. We've always acted appropriately. I
have been second to no one in wanting to get to the bottom of these
allegations because they trouble me greatly as chief law
enforcement officer of the state.''
</P>
<P>
   Verniero's office has spent several months preparing its appeal
of the 1996 ruling. In it, Judge Robert Francis of the state
Superior Court found that a disproportionate number of black
drivers on the southern half of the turnpike were being pulled over
by troopers searching for narcotics. Although he did not find that
state police had a formal policy of profiling, he said the
department's superiors had tolerated what amounted to a policy of
racial discrimination through indifference.
</P>
<P>
   Arguments on the state's appeal have been scheduled for April
28.
</P>
<P>
   On March 5, Verniero's office asked the court for a four-month
delay in the hearing, contending that it needed additional time to
conclude its investigation. Critics of the Whitman administration,
including civil rights lawyers who pressed the case before Francis,
charged that Verniero was seeking the delay to avoid defending
state police on the eve of hearings by the Senate Judiciary
Committee into his nomination to the state Supreme Court. Those
hearings are scheduled for May 6.
</P>
<P>
   Critics also questioned the Whitman administration's objectivity
in conducting an investigation of profiling at the same time it was
denying the existence of the practice in its appeal of Francis'
decision.
</P>
<P>
   In its ruling Tuesday night, the three-judge appeals court panel
refused to grant the four-month delay. The two-paragraph ruling
gave the attorney general's office an option of asking the court
that will hear the appeal to delay its decision until Verniero's
staff reaches a decision on whether to drop the appeal.
</P>
<P>
   William Buckman, a civil rights lawyer who helped assemble the
statistics that led to Francis' decision, praised the court for
rejecting the extension Verniero wanted.
</P>
<P>
   ``It strips politics out of the process at least for the time
being,'' Buckman said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
