A3064 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-DODGERS-BELTRE-LA     03-16 0709
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-BELTRE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DODGERS HOPE BELTRE IS THE ANSWER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   VERO BEACH, Fla. _ The Dodgers are doing everything they can to
take the pressure off Adrian Beltre.
</P>
<P>
   Manager Davey Johnson awarded him the third baseman's job, short
of Beltre booting every grounder from now until March 31. They
don't need him to be their offensive catalyst and, if actions speak
louder than dollars, consider this: General manager Kevin Malone
spent $124 million on free agents in the offseason but never
contemplated pursuing a third baseman because of his confidence in
Beltre.
</P>
<P>
   ``He may have been rushed last season,'' Malone said. ``I was
sold on this guy's ability from when I saw him (last season). I've
been around enough quality, young players in Montreal to know this
guy was a keeper. He has the potential to be an All-Star.''
</P>
<P>
   Potential? That's baseball talk. However, Beltre's numbers from
last year speak of something else. In his first big-league action,
he hit .215 and made 13 errors in 74 games.
</P>
<P>
   Beltre _ who has four years of professional experience despite
being only 20 _ isn't naive enough to think his status as the No.1
third baseman is a sure thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't prove it here,'' Beltre said of spring training. ``I
have to prove I can play in the big leagues. I have to prove I can
stay here.''
</P>
<P>
   On a club of veterans, some with reputations of being ornery
when players don't make the necessary plays, Beltre is a player
with undeniable tools and a calm demeanor. He's been that way since
playing on the rocky fields of Santo Domingo, Dominican Republic,
where a quick glove and smart reflexes keeps you from getting
drilled in the teeth on a bad hop.
</P>
<P>
   Beltre impressed teammates in spring training with his fielding,
especially pitcher Kevin Brown. Brown went as far as to compliment
Beltre after Beltre made a nice bare-handed play on a slow roller
recently against the New York Mets.
</P>
<P>
   There were glimpses of his talent, although he didn't show the
form that made him a .305 hitter during his three-plus seasons in
the minor leagues. Worse, being called up to the majors as the
replacement for an injured Bobby Bonilla, he let his hitting affect
his fielding.
</P>
<P>
   Beltre said the Dodgers tweaked his batting stance last season
and everything else crumbled.
</P>
<P>
   ``They changed my batting stance and that was the principal
thing I had trouble with,'' Beltre said. ``They told me to keep my
body up and close my feet. It didn't work. I think I had such a
tough time last year that if anything happens this year, I can
handle it.''
</P>
<P>
   Just to make sure Beltre is comfortable, fellow Dominican Jose
Vizcaino has been tutoring him, helping prepare him for the ups and
downs of the major-league season.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a (kid) so I've been telling him what to expect, that
he's got to be smart,'' Vizcaino said. ``He's a good kid and he
listens. It makes it easier for him because he has somebody
there.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers have lots of somebodys this year. They've got
starting pitching (six to be exact) and they've got veteran hitting
(Gary Sheffield, Eric Karros, Raul Mondesi). They know what to
expect with the exception of the bullpen and third base.
</P>
<P>
   Beltre appears to be the solution at third. The only real
question about him is in what season will he become the magnificent
third baseman his talent says he should be. It's not supposed to
happen this season. All Johnson wants is solid play in the field
and a .250 average. On this team, with this lineup and this
pitching, that should be enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted him to know that he has time,'' Johnson said. ``I
want him to get his timing down in the field and his timing down at
home plate. That's the key. Anything I can do to help him relax,
I'll do it. He's been fine, expressing his talents and relaxing.''
</P>
<P>
   Beltre has his own expectations, citing confidence from his play
in the Dominican Winter League. Beltre hit .301 with 10 homers and
37 RBI and was named the league's most valuable player.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to hit .250,'' Beltre said. ``If I hit more than
20 homers and have more than 70 RBI and hit the ball hard, that
will be good.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
