<HEADLINE>
TURNING OIL RIGS INTO FISHING REEFS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEITH LAIR  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONG BEACH -- A state bill to turn oil rigs into fishing reefs
is in the works and could generate millions of dollars for wildlife
and fishing projects, American Sportfishing Association president
Mike Hayden says.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know that new reefs would improve the water ecosystem,
improve the habitat, the fishing and provide economic benefits,''
said Hayden, a former Kansas governor and former assistant
secretary at the Department of Interior.
</P>
<P>
   ``ASA believes that there is sufficient scientific evidence
demonstrating rigs-to-reefs is sound public policy. We recognize
that the cautious environmental community desires further
scientific studies to demonstrate that the program is good for
California.''
</P>
<P>
   There are 27 oil platforms between Point Arguello, near Lompoc,
and Huntington Beach. Some of the platforms are 890 feet tall and
in 740 feet of water. When the wells run dry, the oil company must
dismantle the platform. Four platforms already have been abandoned
and dismantled and the oil production from the other platforms is
expected to decline over the next several decades.
</P>
<P>
   United Anglers of Southern California, which recruited ASA in
this project, would like the platform's bases to be left alone,
creating an artificial reef made up of mounds of debris. The shells
would provide new habitat for sea cucumbers, prawns, crabs, mussel,
plumose, anemones and bat stars. Rockfish and perch feast on those
animals and would benefit by an expanded food chain.
</P>
<P>
   The point of the proposal by UASC and ASA is that if it costs
the oil companies $100 million to remove a platform -- a figure
Hayden says is realistic for some of the smaller platforms -- the
companies could remove all but the platform base. The state and oil
companies would then split the savings from the project, with the
state money going to an independent commission that would designate
funds for wildlife, fishing and hunting projects.
</P>
<P>
   Hayden says if the estimated expense was $100 million and the
actual cost was $60 million, the newly formed commission and oil
companies would split the $40 million difference -- the platform
owner giving the commission $20 million.
</P>
<P>
   Environmental groups and commercial fishing trawlers have
objected to the proposal. Trawlers say the reefs will ruin their
nets.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our idea is controversial, but we think it will benefit the
fish,'' UASC president Tom Raftican said. ``In the long run, it
would provide more fish for the trawlers and the sportsman.''
</P>
<P>
   Of the four platforms that have been dismantled, none of the
shell mounds has been removed. ASA conservation network director
Daniel Frumkes says the state's Lands Commission has an agreement
with the oil companies that those companies must return the sea
bottom to its natural state.
</P>
<P>
   ``They can't remove habitat,'' he said. ``At these shells, the
resources have yet to suffer.''
</P>
<P>
   Hayden and Raftican both say all they are really interested in
is getting all sides to begin dialogue.
</P>
<P>
   ``This would provide fish habitat forever,'' Hayden said. ``But
it's clearly controversial, and all we want is discussion with
others. This is now the time to do it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
