<HEADLINE>
SAMARANCH'S FUTURE RESTS WITH IOC VOTE ON EXPULSIONS
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Utah, Arizona)   (dal) 
 By JERE LONGMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAUSANNE, Switzerland _ A vote to ratify the expulsion of six
delegates of the International Olympic Committee on Wednesday will
essentially be a referendum on Juan Antonio Samaranch.
</P>
<P>
   Samaranch, the president of the badly tarnished IOC, has been
lobbying delegates to affirm the expulsions and has phoned
corporate sponsors, promising them that real change is on the
horizon. But any sweeping reforms appear impossible if the
committee cannot oust the six members accused of most seriously
violating the rules of propriety involving Salt Lake City's bid to
win the 2002 Winter Games.
</P>
<P>
   ``If those who are clearly guilty are not thrown off, I would
have real concerns about the credibility of the IOC after that,''
said James Easton, a delegate from the United States, who has said
he may resign if the expulsions are not carried out.
</P>
<P>
   The 11-member executive board has called for the expulsions of
Augustin Arroyo of Ecuador, Zein El Badim Ahmed Abdel Gadir of
Sudan, Jean-Claude Ganga of Congo Republic, Lamine Keita of Mali,
Sergio Santander Fantini of Chile and Paul Wallwork of Samoa.
</P>
<P>
   A two-thirds vote by the 91 attending IOC members (61 votes)
will be necessary to ratify the expulsions, which were proposed by
the executive board in January. A failure to carry out the
expulsions of any or all of the accused delegates would be seen as
a repudiation of Samaranch and could force him to resign before his
term ends in 2001, Olympic officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The IOC also finds itself under heavy pressure from the outside
to reform itself quickly, particularly from sponsors who spend $40
million or more to underwrite the Olympic movement and from the
U.S. Congress. This week, the committee is expected to change the
way cities bid on the Olympics and to appoint an ethics commission
and a reform commission to examine such proposals as democratic
elections and term limits for IOC delegates, and open financial
records and open meetings.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., who heads the Senate committee on
commerce, science and transportation, has threatened to revoke the
IOC's tax-exempt status in the United States. He is also
considering the rerouting of billions in NBC television money from
the IOC to the U.S. Olympic Committee. McCain will hold a hearing
in Washington on April 14.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, McCain sent a letter to Anita DeFrantz, the senior
IOC member from the United States, which said, ``In the strongest
terms, let me communicate to you my hope that the IOC will move
quickly to adopt reforms.'' Without such independent action, McCain
said, ``the demand for Congress to act will be irrepressible.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We must put on the fire water, not petrol,'' said Mario
Pescante, an IOC member from Italy, calling for expulsions and
immediate reform. ``The situation is delicate. If the situation
continues, we risk losing sponsors. If you blend politics with
sport, this is the end.''
</P>
<P>
   As the Wednesday vote approached, rumors abounded of back-door
deals and plots and a palace revolt by officials who may want to
succeed Samaranch. Dick Schultz, the executive director of the
USOC, said in January that he believed that some IOC officials
appeared to be attempting to oust Samaranch. That theory gained
some currency this week when The Associated Press reported that
Samaranch had begun to express his concerns about a revolt from the
inside.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm hoping people are not mixing personal prestige into this
problem, but there may be some of that,'' said Gerhard Heiberg, a
delegate from Norway.
</P>
<P>
   A vote of confidence for Samaranch by the IOC assembly is set
for Thursday, but that is expected to come easily, considering that
Samaranch appointed most delegates.
</P>
<P>
   ``The real vote of confidence is what we do,'' said Richard W.
Pound of Montreal, who headed the IOC's investigation of the Salt
Lake City scandal.
</P>
<P>
   One investigation that remains open is that of Kim Un Yong, a
powerful delegate from South Korea who has been censured for
allegedly arranging for jobs for both his daughter and son through
the Salt Lake City bid committee. He has denied any wrongdoing.
However, IOC officials said Monday that Kim could still face a vote
of expulsion on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   There has also been some dissatisfaction within the IOC that a
warning, not expulsion, was given to Phil Coles of Australia, who
has been accused of both offering and receiving improper trips
regarding Salt Lake City and Sydney's bid to win the 2000 Summer
Games.
</P>
<P>
   Heiberg of Norway said it was possible that delegates could call
for a vote on expulsion from the floor during Wednesday's assembly,
if they believed that some members had received preferential
treatment.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they are equally guilty, I think they should receive the
same punishment,'' Easton said of Kim and Coles.
</P>
<P>
   Anxiously awaiting the outcome of Wednesday's and Thursday's
meetings are corporate sponsors, most of whom are located in the
United States. While the IOC cannot be reformed in two days, a
framework for reform is necessary, said Susan Rosenberg, a
spokeswoman for one sponsor, United Parcel Service.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to see movement and a clearly defined timetable for
reform, so we can hold them accountable to change,'' Rosenberg
said. ``It's important that a clear message be sent by the actions
they take that they are committed to serious change.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
