<HEADLINE>
GIULIANI SAYS SHOOTING COVERAGE SKEWED POLL
</HEADLINE>
   (See related NY-DIALLO-D.A.) 
(nk) 
 By DAN BARRY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Mayor Rudolph Giuliani blamed partisan politics and
an ``obsessive media concern'' Tuesday for the results of a New
York Times poll released this week that showed a sharp drop in his
job-approval rating and a widespread belief among the city's black
and Hispanic residents that the police routinely use excessive
force against them.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking to reporters at the Waldorf-Astoria Hotel, he suggested
that the numbers were skewed because of the way the news media and
various black leaders have responded to the shooting death last
month of Amadou Diallo, an immigrant from West Africa. Four white
police officers killed Diallo, who was unarmed, with a flurry of
bullets while he stood in the vestibule of his Bronx apartment
building.
</P>
<P>
   Black leaders immediately denounced the shooting as indicative
of a Police Department that too readily assumes that black people
pose a threat. After some sporadic demonstrations, the leaders
recently began daily protests of civil disobedience.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor characterized statements by the protesters about
police attitudes as inaccurate and partisan, and he said the
statements were repeated in a ``media frenzy'' that distorted
reality and affected the perceptions reflected in polls.
</P>
<P>
   That is why, Giuliani suggested Tuesday, the Times poll showed
his job-approval rating plummeting to 42 percent, from 63 percent
only five months ago. That is also why, he said, the poll indicates
that fewer than a quarter of all New Yorkers think that the police
treat blacks and whites in an equally fair manner; that nearly 90
percent of black residents think that the police often engage in
brutality against blacks and that one of every three blacks has
felt danger in the presence of a police officer.
</P>
<P>
   As he has since the Diallo shooting, Giuliani emphasized that
statistics have shown a sharp reduction in incidents of excessive
force among the city's police officers, to the point that the
department is among the most restrained in the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``If 70 or 80 percent of the people believe that police officers
in New York City are brutal too often, that's a misperception,''
the mayor said. ``It is driven by a very effective partisan
political campaign, and the fact that there's been an obsessive
concern in the media about it.''
</P>
<P>
   He then used the Waldorf-Astoria, where a guest was killed over
the weekend, to illustrate his point about the ``obsessive media
concern'' _ a phrase he repeated _ that has been shown to the
police shooting of Diallo.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look, we're in a hotel that two days ago, three days ago, had
a horrible murder take place,'' he said. ``If you spent the next
five weeks covering that murder, you would convince people that
there was a murder problem in the city of New York, even though
murder is down by 70 percent.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-16-99 2314EST &QL; 
