<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-DIMAGGIO-HIGHWAY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLITICAL BRAWL OVER JOE DIMAGGIO HIGHWAY
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By CLIFFORD J. LEVY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Gov. George Pataki agreed Tuesday night to rename
the West Side Highway after Joe DiMaggio, but his announcement was
partly overshadowed by new tensions with Mayor Rudolph Giuliani,
suggesting that relations between the two men are so strained that
they have trouble concurring on whether to put up a few street
signs.
</P>
<P>
   In the days after DiMaggio's death last week, the governor had
withheld support for the mayor's plan to rename the West Side
Highway, saying that he wanted first to consult with the Yankees
and DiMaggio's family.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday night, Pataki said for the first time that he would sign
legislation to change the name of the West Side Highway, which runs
from Battery Place in lower Manhattan to 72nd Street along the
Hudson River. Lawmakers are expected to approve the bill later this
week.
</P>
<P>
   To save money, the measure calls for a ceremonial, not official,
name change. In other words, signs along the highway would not be
replaced, but signs would be added declaring that it now honors
DiMaggio. The state had estimated that an official name change
would cost several million dollars.
</P>
<P>
   But while the governor was publicly lauding DiMaggio, he was
said to be privately furious over what his aides called efforts by
the mayor to embarrass Pataki over the issue. The dispute was the
latest in an escalating feud that began in the 1994 gubernatorial
election, when Giuliani crossed party lines and endorsed the
Democratic incumbent, Mario M. Cuomo, who lost to Pataki.
</P>
<P>
   The governor's ire Tuesday night was focused on a letter that
DiMaggio's lawyer wrote to Giuliani, which was circulated Tuesday
afternoon around the Capitol.
</P>
<P>
   In the letter, the lawyer, Morris Engelberg, assails the
governor for not acceding to the renaming of the West Side Highway,
while also questioning his motives. ``To use Joe DiMaggio's name to
further any political objective is inappropriate,'' Engelberg
wrote, ``and to attempt to do so at this time _ so soon after his
death _ is, in our opinion, in extremely poor taste.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked about the letter, Pataki told reporters that Engelberg was
``grossly misinformed.'' The governor's spokeswoman, Zenia Mucha,
suggested that the Giuliani administration had orchestrated the
letter to pressure the governor and hurt his reputation. She noted
that Pataki had never opposed the West Side Highway plan, but had
merely called for more discussion before approving it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's beyond comprehension why anyone would want to play
politics with this man's memory,'' Ms. Mucha said.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani and Engelberg on Tuesday night both denied the
suggestion by Pataki aides that there had been cooperation on the
letter.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking to reporters at City Hall, Giuliani sought to calm the
quarrel. He praised the governor for supporting the plan and seemed
to imply that Engelberg had misunderstood the matter.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no politics in this,'' Giuliani said. ``This is out of
respect for Joe DiMaggio, which the governor and I both have.''
</P>
<P>
   In a telephone interview, Engelberg said he wrote the letter
after reading articles about the debate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't speak to anyone before I wrote the letter,''
Engelberg said. ``I'm not looking for publicity. I just wanted to
protect Joe's name and image, not throw him into this political
arena.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
