<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-16 23:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3195 &Cx1f; tth-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SALMON-ENDANGERED-SPI     03-16 1335
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SALMON-ENDANGERED-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NINE NORTHWEST SALMON SPECIES LISTED AS ENDANGERED, THREATENED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By HEATH FOSTER  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ The federal government Tuesday stepped in to do what
the Northwest has failed to do: bring wild salmon back from the
brink of extinction.
</P>
<P>
   Now state and local leaders must start making good on their
promises.
</P>
<P>
   The National Marine Fisheries Service listed nine struggling
salmon sub-species in Washington and Oregon, including the once
bountiful Puget Sound wild chinook, as threatened or endangered
under the Endangered Species Act.
</P>
<P>
   The much-anticipated listingwill force state and local
governments, foresters, farmers, land and home owners, and even big
city apartment dwellers to make financial sacrifices to reverse
more than a century's worth of environmental degradation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Over the last hundred years as people have moved out here and
developed this part of the country, we've forced the salmon to
adjust to us,'' said Bill Ruckelshaus, leader of a partnership of
Washington corporations and environmental groups monitoring the
salmon-saving efforts. ``This will force us to adjust to the
fish.''
</P>
<P>
   Political leaders from Seattle, King, Snohomish and Pierce
Counties, state government and Indian tribes crowded before the
microphones Tuesday to assure Uncle Sam of their commitment to
restoring the natural habitat and pristine waterways that once
allowed salmon to thrive.
</P>
<P>
   They hope that by pledging stringent new regulations on how much
water their communities use and how much asphalt and concrete is
laid down for new homes and businesses, they can prevent the
federal government from imposing even more draconian measures in
the thickly populated Puget Sound. They're desperate to avoid the
kind of economic paralysis that hit the Olympic penninsula and the
timber industry with the 1990 listing of the spotted owl.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think people understand what (the National Marine
Fisheries Service) did to us today,'' said King County Executive
Ron Sims.
</P>
<P>
   But politicians may not be able to keep some of the promises
they made Tuesday once their constituents take a hard look at the
utility rate hikes and land-use restrictions they're proposing.
</P>
<P>
   Pivotal to Washington's success in keeping federal regulators at
bay is Governor Gary Locke's salmon recovery plan. The $201 million
proposal, designed to give salmon the cool, clean water they need,
is in deep trouble.
</P>
<P>
   Locke's plan would sharply tighten restrictions on water use for
farmers and surburbanites alike, and crack down on illegal
withdrawals. His proposed ``Forest and Fish'' plan, negotiated over
months by the timber industry, state and federal government, and
some tribes, would put 15 percent of existing commercial timber
land permanently out of production. Locke is calling for adding 180
new state employees to enact the recovery effort, shortening salmon
fishing seasons, and forcing developers and private landowners to
expand protection of wetlands and stream-sides.
</P>
<P>
   The first-term governor's ambitious proposal includes the kind
of dramatic, science-backed measures the federal fisheries agency
likes to see. But it's hard to find a Democrat or Republican from a
rural district who is backing the plan.
</P>
<P>
   It is said that average salmon must travel through 28 different
government jurisdictions to reach its spawning grounds.
</P>
<P>
   Rural lawmakers complain Locke's plan concentrates too much on
the fish habitat in Washington, and not nearly enough on the
environment at sea where salmon spend most of their lives. It does
nothing to address the sea lions, terns and Canadian fisherman
capturing Washington salmon, they say.
</P>
<P>
   And it exacts too much flesh from farmers and homeowners without
clearly spelling out how much sacrifice will be enough, they say.
Small timber land owners depending on their property to finance
retirement or a college education shouldn't be forced to give up
land, they say, for vaguely defined fish recovery goals.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Chandler, co-chair of the House Agriculture and Ecology
Committee, hails from Grant County, whose dry land was transformed
60 years ago by the Columbia Basin irrigation project into
sprawling fields of beans and peas. He said Locke's demands that
farmers give up water would rob them of their hopes of ever
expanding their operations.
</P>
<P>
   ``The governor's plan is centered on taking water from people,''
he said. ``Do that, and you turn off the economy's tap too.
Agriculture is the number one industry in this state, employing the
most people.''
</P>
<P>
   Environmentalists are casting stones at Locke's plan too. They
say the Forest and Fish plan doesn't protect enough stream-side
forest land to guarantee salmon will recover.
</P>
<P>
   Curt Schmidt, Gov. Gary Locke's top salmon adviser, cautioned
that with six weeks of the session left, it's premature to predict
the plan's demise.
</P>
<P>
   Chandler, Rep. Jim Buck, co-chair of the House Natural Resources
Committee and Dave Mastin, co-chair House's Salmon Restoration Task
force, all rural Republicans, said they're confident they'll
deliver a plan that will satisfy federal regulators.
</P>
<P>
   But what happens if the Legislature's salmon package lacks the
teeth that the federal government requires?
</P>
<P>
   It may deter federal lawmakers' efforts to get Washington the
money it needs to enact its plans. For instance, Sen. Slade Gorton,
chair of the U.S. Senate Interior Appropriations Subcommittee, is
seeking $210 million more than the $100 million President Clinton
promised for West Coast salmon recovery. Gorton said last week that
it's essential that the Legislature do its share if it wants
federal help.
</P>
<P>
   Environmental groups and Indian tribes are standing by, ready to
sue to protect salmon where the state does not.
</P>
<P>
   ``If governmental entities don't step up to the plate to protect
society from a species becoming extinct, (litigation) will
happen,'' said Ed Zuckerman, executive director of the Washington
Environmental Alliance for Voter Education.
</P>
<P>
   Such suits would invite federal judges in to dictate exactly how
much salmon protection is enough.
</P>
<P>
   Other states have lived to regret the fact that they opened the
door for such lawsuits. In Massachussetts, an environmental group
sued the state, claiming it had shirked its responsibilities under
the Endangered Species Act by not banning fishing nets that were
catching an endangered species of whale. They won, and state was
prevented from granting permits for the nets.
</P>
<P>
   In Florida, Volusia County was sued by an environmental group
for failing to adopt an ordinance to dim beach-front lights that
were leading nesting sea turtles into the path of oncoming cars.
That case is now awaiting a ruling from the U.S. Supreme Court. At
issue is whether local governments have an obligation to use their
powers to save endangered species.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Johnston, a Seattle attorney who specializes in endangered
species law, said environmental groups in Washington could sue the
state for not leaving enough enough water in streams for salmon.
Such a victory could force lawmakers to enact water-use
restrictions they are balking at now.
</P>
<P>
   Johnston said the federal government can also take direct
enforcement action against governments, businesses and even
individuals deemed to be harming fish with their actions. But
proving that fertilizing a lawn or washing a car is harming a fish
in court isn't easy, and Johnston said that's the path the
fisheries agency is least likely to pursue, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Federal fishery officials inisted Tuesday that they're thrilled
with the cooperative spirit they've seen so far in local and state
political leaders.
</P>
<P>
   But Rolland Schmitten, assistant administrator of the agency,
warned, ``please don't mistake our desire to partner as a lack of
commitment. We will (protect the fish) even if we have to do it
alone.''
</P>
<P>
   P-I reporter Michael Paulson contributed to this report.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
