<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-16 23:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3196 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-DIALLO-DA-ART-2TAK     03-16 0857
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-DIALLO-DA-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DIALLO CASE TESTS BRONX PROSECUTOR
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(dal) 
 By AMY WALDMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ For Robert T. Johnson, the Bronx district attorney,
1996 was a trying year. In March, a police officer, Kevin
Gillespie, was shot and killed, and a former convict was arrested
for his murder. Convinced that Johnson, who previously stated that
he would not seek the death sentence, would not pursue it in this
case, Gov. George E. Pataki removed him from it.
</P>
<P>
   Seven months after the stunning ouster, the trial of Francis X.
Livoti, a police officer accused of killing Anthony Baez with an
illegal choke hold, concluded with an acquittal. Again, Johnson was
under fire, this time from the Baez family, some members of the
public and, more subtly, from the judge in the case, all of whom
suggested his office had bungled the prosecution. In one year, the
district attorney found himself accused of being both soft on
police killers and soft on the police.
</P>
<P>
   But 1999 may make 1996 seem easy. The killing of Amadou Diallo
by four police officers, who fired 41 rounds at the unarmed African
immigrant in the vestibule of his apartment house late one night
last month, has presented Johnson with the most politically charged
case of his 10-year tenure.
</P>
<P>
   While it is a grand jury, which is now hearing evidence in the
shooting, that will decide whether to bring charges against the
officers, Johnson and his prosecutors will decide which charges the
jurors consider _ and shape how they see the case.
</P>
<P>
   In a city of distinctive prosecutors, Johnson, up for
re-election in November, is neither crusader nor publicity hound.
Nor does he seem to trim his sails according to the political
winds.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, it would be difficult for Johnson, the only black
district attorney in the state, to miss the emotions swirling
around the Diallo case. Protesters pressing for an indictment rally
outside the Bronx County Courthouse almost daily. Johnson declined
an interview request by saying that he did not want to talk about
the Diallo case _ and these days, all conversational roads lead
there.
</P>
<P>
   In the last decade, Johnson's constituents have endured the
worst of the crime wave and felt the relief of crime's subsequent
plummet. But that drop has been coupled with high-profile cases of
alleged police abuse. For Bronx residents, and for the city as a
whole, the Diallo case is evolving into a referendum on how
government handles the misdeeds of the police _ and Johnson's
actions are the first test.
</P>
<P>
   Some police officers, more likely to see the Diallo shooting as
a tragic byproduct of aggressive crime-fighting, fear that the
officers will fall victim to political forces.
</P>
<P>
   For Johnson, good relations with the police are crucial: his
office relies on them to investigate cases and serve as witnesses.
District attorneys know that if they are perceived as being unfair
to the police, securing cooperation for subsequent investigations
of police conduct will be much harder.
</P>
<P>
   ``Prosecutors are in a no-win position when they try to
prosecute police officers,'' said Joel L. Blumenfeld, a Queens
judge who more than two decades ago supervised a young Bronx Legal
Aid lawyer named Rob Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, 51, grew up in an era when the problem for minorities
in the city was not overly aggressive policing but the lack of it.
He was raised in the Amsterdam housing project in Manhattan, and
moved to the Bronx at 16. For several years, he lived in the
Soundview section, where Diallo also lived. Johnson's mother still
lives there.
</P>
<P>
   He is not a born politician, or even, very much, a bred one.
Slim and youthful-looking despite graying hair, he can slip in and
out of a room unnoticed. He and his second wife, Dianne T. Renwick
_ a Supreme Court justice in Bronx Civil Court _ live near Pelham
Bay Park just south of the Westchester County border in the Bronx
with their two young children.
</P>
<P>
   The district attorney ascended not through party politics but
through the Bronx criminal justice system. It was a fast rise.
After finishing City College in 1972, Johnson went to New York
University Law School and then became a defense attorney in the
Bronx Legal Aid office.
</P>
<P>
   He soon switched sides, going to work as a prosecutor under
Mario Merola, the colorful Bronx district attorney. In 1985,
Johnson became the head of Merola's narcotics bureau. The next
year, Edward I. Koch appointed him to the Criminal Court bench.
Then Merola died, and the fight to replace him threatened to tear
the Bronx Democratic Party, whose nomination is tantamount to
election, apart. Johnson was brought in as a neutral Democratic
candidate and won.
</P>
<P>
   Former assistants describe him as a hands-on manager who
frequently drops in on courtrooms to watch his assistants in
action. He is considered tough on crime, pushing hard, for example,
for mandatory one-year minimum sentences for defendants caught with
loaded, unregistered guns.
 &UR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  (MORE)
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Johnson's friends and colleagues say his toughness couples with
a commitment to addressing crime's root causes, something of an
old-fashioned concept these days. They point to his willingness to
consider treatment alternatives for low-level drug offenders.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson has an unusually strong bond with his constituents. He
shuns the media but attends countless community events. He drives
himself around the Bronx, declining to be chauffeured, and
residents often approach him on the street to discuss problems or
pass on information.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson's battle with the governor over the Gillespie case may
not have played well with other public officials, but it does not
seem to have hurt him with his constituents. Community leaders say
he earned respect for standing up for his principles.
</P>
<P>
   Those who disagreed with him thought differently. ``It was
typical Rob _ this is my view and you're not going to budge me,''
said Paul Schectman, Pataki's former criminal justice coordinator.
</P>
<P>
   In the Livoti case, Johnson was accused by the Baez family and
others of applying the law indifferently. ``I was very
disappointed, from the beginning, in the way the entire case was
investigated _ which was not vigorously,'' said Susan M. Karten,
the lawyer who represented the Baez family.
</P>
<P>
   The original indictment was thrown out because of a clerical
error. When Officer Livoti finally went to trial, he was acquitted
by a judge who decried the ``nest of perjury'' he saw in testimony
from the police. It was the prosecution's duty to have sorted it
out, he implied. Livoti was later convicted on federal civil rights
charges.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson's defenders point to his success in winning a conviction
against Livoti for applying a choke hold in another case.
</P>
<P>
   That case, and Johnson's largely unsuccessful attempt to
prosecute officers from the 48th Precinct for brutality and
corruption, prompt some officers to say he is too aggressive in
prosecuting the police _ ``not pro-cop,'' in one officer's words.
But the district attorney's bigger problem is that the Bronx
residents who comprise his juries do not trust the police.
</P>
<P>
   Since Johnson has been in office, his conviction rate in jury
trials has never been above 70 percent and has usually hovered
closer to 60 percent. The citywide average, in contrast, has
usually been above 75 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Some defense lawyers blame incompetence or high turnover in
Johnson's office. But many lawyers and judges in the Bronx said the
conviction rate in jury trials reflected the skepticism of Bronx
jurors. And the shooting of Amadou Diallo, they said, can only make
things harder for Johnson.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-16-99 2322EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990316.0431 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-16 23:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3201 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-IRISH-WRITER-NYT &LR;      03-16 0924
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-IRISH-WRITER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHEN IRISH EYES ARE SMILING MALICIOUSLY
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By RANDY KENNEDY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ One of the dangers with interviewing Sean Kelly is
that you might find out what your name means, if it happens to be
Irish. (From the Gaelic, Kelly translates as something like
``sacred prostitute.'' Kennedy means ``ugly head.'')
</P>
<P>
   You will also probably hear more than you want about the Irish
saint whose day this is: First of all, he was not Irish but
Welsh-Italian; his given name was not Patrick, it was Succat; he
was not even the first Christian missionary to visit Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   But history and green beer aside, Kelly kind of likes St.
Patrick's Day. ``I think because it's the original day in America
when people celebrate their other roots,'' he said Tuesday. ``It's
a festival of immigrants. If there's anything good to be said in
its behalf, I guess it would be that.''
</P>
<P>
   Kelly, a soft-spoken man with a somewhat devilish glint in his
eye, has made his way through a lot of occupations in 58 years _
child quiz-show star, radio actor, advertising copywriter,
substitute professor of Victorian literature, founding editor of
National Lampoon, ill-fated writer for ``Saturday Night Live,''
children's book and television writer.
</P>
<P>
   But pondering and alternately embracing and disparaging Irish
culture and Roman Catholicism has been a lifelong occupation. So
when he recently got together with a friend and Irish-American
collaborator, Rosemary Rogers, they decided it was time to put some
of their collective arcana into a book, ``How to Be Irish (Even if
You Already Are).''
</P>
<P>
   They hope the book makes them some money, of course, but it also
conforms nicely to an important philosophical concept for Kelly _
the sucker punch.
</P>
<P>
   His first experience with this concept came at Loyola High
School in Montreal, where he grew up. Kelly, who viewed high school
less as a place to learn than as a place to drive Jesuits crazy,
was hauled one day to the dark, imposing offices of the rector, the
Rev. Gerald F. Lahey.
</P>
<P>
   The rector, an expert on the Jesuit poet Gerard Manley Hopkins,
told the young Kelly that he had great _ even Hopkinsesque _
potential as a writer, if only he could overcome his attitude
problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was flattering,'' Kelly recalled. ``But even at that age I
knew: I was being sucker-punched.''
</P>
<P>
   One way or another, it was a lesson that would stick with him:
give the people something they don't expect.
</P>
<P>
   When he got a job with an advertising agency, for example, one
of his television spots for Canadian National Railways was 58
seconds of ``any kind of footage of crashing planes and people
picking through rubble. And then at the end the screen goes white,
and rain, and through the night _ whoosh _ a train zips past. And
then `Canadian National Railways' on the screen. No voice-over.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They couldn't air it, but it was a great commercial,'' Kelly,
beaming, said at home in the Cobble Hill section of Brooklyn, where
his almost-7-year-old son, Mac, bounded around upstairs. (Kelly's
wife is Patricia Todd, editor in chief of trade paperbacks at Simon
&AMP; Schuster.)
</P>
<P>
   Even as a writer of children's books, he can't help himself. One
of his books, ``Boom Baby Moon,'' is a sweet-looking attack on
baby-boomer excess and the bedside standard ``Goodnight Moon.''
</P>
<P>
   A children's book it is not:
</P>
<P>
   Goodnight intercom in my crib
</P>
<P>
   Goodnight fireproof feeding bib
</P>
<P>
   The slim Irish book looks like one of those funny, impulse buys
that book stores always put near the cash registers. And it is
funny, with a kind of National Lampoon slapdash approach, but
inside there are quotations from many unfunny people, like Edmund
Spenser and Benjamin Disraeli, and discussions of things like
William Butler Yeats' brief dalliance with Ireland's Facist Party.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's what I think I used to do as a teacher,'' he said.
``Which is that it would appear that `You've really lucked out,
kids, because you've got your long-haired, dope-sucking maniac as
your English teacher.' And then a couple of weeks later, you're
actually doing it. You're trying to crack Culture and Anarchy.''
</P>
<P>
   As a longtime freelance writer (``I'm much too sensitive to get
a job,'' he says) Kelly is a mind-boggling generalist.
</P>
<P>
   In 20 minutes of conversation, one can end up learning a little
about Aquinas, discovering that a certain movie director smokes a
lot of marijuana, and finding out about the San Patricios, Irish
soldiers who deserted the U.S. Army during the Mexican-American War
and joined the Mexican side.
</P>
<P>
   He says his deep knowledge of things Irish has always been so
much a part of him that writing about it seemed strange.
</P>
<P>
   He was born on his grandfather's farm in Cushing, Quebec, but
raised in a part of Montreal so Irish ``that I probably didn't meet
anyone who wasn't Irish until I was a teen-ager.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It was like living in a shtetl,'' he said. ``I had no idea
that there was an alternative to it.''
</P>
<P>
   His father, Charles Kelly, was a draftsman for RCA Victor, who
met his mother, Grace Whelehan, when he helped out with the haying
on her parents' farm. ``Of course she became Grace Kelly when she
married my father.''
</P>
<P>
   Now that he is done with the Irish book, he is not sure what
subject to tackle next. But then the phone rang.
</P>
<P>
   ``Guy said we could do the Taco Bell book, you know, about the
Taco Bell chihuahua,'' he said afterward. ``Now let's see ... what
kind of money do you ask for to write the chihuahua book?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-16-99 2323EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
