<HEADLINE>
KINGS' LAPERRIERE DOES THE LITTLE THINGS 
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROGER PHILLIPS  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Once upon a time, an 18-year-old forward scored 44
goals and chipped in 96 assists in a season playing for
Drummondville in the Quebec junior league.
</P>
<P>
   It was only six seasons ago, but it might as well have happened
in another lifetime for Kings center Ian Laperriere.
</P>
<P>
   In 206 games as a King, the 25-year-old Laperriere has posted
somewhat less impressive numbers: 18 goals, 41 assists and 59
points, a far cry from his Gretzkyesque final season of junior
hockey in 1992-93, when he had 140 points in just 60 games.
</P>
<P>
   In his 206th game as a King, Monday night's important 4-0
victory over Ottawa, Laperriere did all the little things, as
usual.
</P>
<P>
   On one notable second-period shift, he stole the puck from a
Senator, was held, dropped to the ice, got up, was knocked down
again, battled for the puck from his knees, somehow got it to
linemate Nathan LaFayette, got the puck back, was checked, threw a
punch at Ottawa defenseman Lance Pitlick that was not seen by
referee Don Koharski, then took a punch from Pitlick and dropped to
the ice as if he'd been struck by the Mike Tyson of a decade ago.
</P>
<P>
   This last bit was witnessed by Koharski, meaning Laperriere had
done his job by drawing a penalty, and Blake scored the Kings'
first goal on the subsequent power play. For good measure, with the
outcome decided late in the game, Laperriere pummeled Ottawa's Bill
Berg so thoroughly that only a Lewis-Holyfield judge would have
failed to give Laperriere the decision in that bout.
</P>
<P>
   Mention Laperriere's name, and Blake breaks out in an instant
smile.
</P>
<P>
   ``He does it all the time,'' Blake said. ``He's done it all year
long. The kid loves to play.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Laperriere, ``I love to be on the ice, playing hockey,
practicing. I just want to skate and have fun.''
</P>
<P>
   It was following his impressive career in junior hockey that
Laperriere, a native of Montreal, became typecast as a defensive
specialist.
</P>
<P>
   Chosen by St. Louis in the seventh round of the 1992 draft,
Laperriere had 13 goals and 27 points for the Blues in 37 games
during the 1995 lockout season. But midway through the following
year, the Blues traded Laperriere to the New York Rangers, who had
a different plan for him.
</P>
<P>
   ``They thought I was just a fourth-line guy, and that was it,''
said Laperriere, who next will perpetrate his unique brand of
mayhem Thursday night when the Kings play host to the Mighty Ducks.
``You don't decide what you're going to play. They decide what
you're going to play. They saw more my physical play than my
skills, and decided I was going to be a physical player.''
</P>
<P>
   When the Kings acquired him from the Rangers later that same
season in a multi-player trade, their plan for Laperriere didn't
change.
</P>
<P>
   ``He just wants to play,'' Kings coach Larry Robinson said. ``I
wish all the guys had his attitude. He wears his emotions on his
sleeve.''
</P>
<P>
   Assistant coach Jay Leach added, ``One day, I said to Ian, `What
makes you go?' He said, `If I don't do this, then I'm back in
Canada, working for General Motors.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Of his willingness to accept the role that now appears to be his
destiny, Laperriere said, ``It's from my parents, both my parents
but more my dad (Michel). He never forced me to work hard, but he
said, `If you work hard, you get what you want.'
</P>
<P>
   ``He also drilled in me that if you practice hard, you play
hard. And I'm not a Donald Audette or a Luc Robitaille. If I want
to stay in the league, I've got to work hard.''
</P>
</TEXT>
