<HEADLINE>
GALAXY, FIRE THE ONES TO BEAT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRED J. ROBLEDO  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The two biggest guns in the Western Conference of
Major League Soccer -- Los Angeles and Chicago -- should again
battle for the top spot.
</P>
<P>
   The Fire, which captured the MLS Cup and U.S. Open Cup title in
its inaugural season in 1998, seems destined to repeat. The bulk of
its roster is in place, most noticeably foreigners Peter Nowak
(Poland), Lubos Kubik (Czechoslovakia), Jerzy Podbrozny (Poland)
and Roman Kosecki (Poland), collectively known as the ``Eastern
Bloc.''
</P>
<P>
   The defense centers around Kubik, who led defenders in scoring
and could be the most skillful defender in the league. Both C.J.
Brown and defensive midfield specialist Chris Armas have earned
U.S. National team appearances because of last year's showing,
along with goalkeeper Zack Thornton, who boasted a league-low 1.17
goals-against average.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we have a very good mix of players,'' said Fire coach
Bob Bradley. ``We need to remember what went into last season and
do our best to work together again and see what happens.
</P>
<P>
   The Galaxy set every record imaginable last season, including
best record (24-7) and most goals (85). They have tinkered with
their lineup and could start seven players under than age of 25.
L.A. still is trying to obtain the one crown jewel that has eluded
the franchise -- an MLS championship.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas City should improve with the acquisitions of goalkeeper
Tony Meola and defender Alexi Lalas.
</P>
<P>
   The most disappointing team in 1998, the Wizards went from a
scoring machine that captured the 1997 regular-season title to a
last-place finish in 1998. Don't expect coach Ron Newman, the
winningest coach in American soccer history, to be in the cellar
again.
</P>
<P>
   The Wizards added proven American veterans Lalas and Meola, both
of whom played big roles for the American team during the 1994
World Cup.
</P>
<P>
   Dallas, which finished 15-18 last season, will try to avoid the
injuries that plagued midfielders Leonel Alvarez and Jason Kreis
and striker Dante Washington most of last season.
</P>
<P>
   If those three are healthy, goalkeeper Mark Dodd -- along with
solid contributors Jorge Rodriguez, Mark Santel, Mickey Trotman and
late-season acquisition Oscar Pareja -- could make the Burn a
dangerous opponent.
</P>
<P>
   Colorado reached the 1997 MLS championship as the fourth seed in
the West. But until its back line figures out a way to keep
opponents away from the net, the Rapids will have problems.
</P>
<P>
   Colorado ranked 12th in MLS (allowing 69 goals, an average of
2.16 per game) last season and has given up 187 goals in three
seasons -- the most of any MLS team.
</P>
<P>
   To help out, the Rapids acquired defender Matt McKeon from
Kansas City, allowing veteran Marcelo Balboa and Peter Vermes to
move the middle of the central defense.
</P>
<P>
   Here is a quick glance at the Western Conference and projected
order of finish:
</P>
<P>
   agl,8.6,9 CHICAGO FIRE &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Head coach: Bob Bradley.
</P>
<P>
   1998 finish: 21-12 (56 points), second in the West and MLS Cup
champions.
</P>
<P>
   Top returning scorer: Ante Razov (10 goals, 9 assists).
</P>
<P>
   Top returning players: Peter Nowak, Chris Armas, Lubis Kubik,
C.J. Brown and goalkeeper Zack Thornton.
</P>
<P>
   Key acquisitions: Dema Kovalenko.
</P>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES GALAXY &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Head coach: Octavio Zambrano.
</P>
<P>
   1998 finish: 24-8 (68 points), first in the West.
</P>
<P>
   Top returning scorer: Cobi Jones (19 goals, 13 assists).
</P>
<P>
   Top returning players: Welton, Robin Fraser, Mauricio
Cienfuegos, Carlos Hermosillo, Clint Mathis.
</P>
<P>
   Key acquisitions: Tony Soto, Zak Ibsen.
</P>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY WIZARDS &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Head coach: Ron Newman.
</P>
<P>
   1998 finish: 12-20 (32 points), sixth in the West.
</P>
<P>
   Top returning scorer: Preki (10 goals, 13 assists).
</P>
<P>
   Top returning players: Mo Johnston, Uche Okafor.
</P>
<P>
   Key acquisitions: Alexi Lalas, Tony Meola, Chris Henderson.
</P>
<P>
   DALLAS BURN &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Head coach: David Dir.
</P>
<P>
   1998 finish: 15-17 (37 points), fourth in the West.
</P>
<P>
   Top returning scorer: Jason Kreis (9 goals, 8 assists).
</P>
<P>
   Top returning players: Dante Washington, Chad Deering, Jorge
Rodriguez, Leonel Alvarez and goalkeeper Mark Dodd.
</P>
<P>
   COLORADO RAPIDS &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Head coach: Glenn Myernick.
</P>
<P>
   1998 finish: 16-16 (44 points), third in the West.
</P>
<P>
   Top returning scorer: Paul Bravo (11 goals, 8 assists).
</P>
<P>
   Top returning players: Marcelo Balboa, Ross Paule, Wolde Harris,
Marcus Hahnemann.
</P>
<P>
   Key acquisitions: Jorge Dely Valdes, Anders Limpar, Matt McKeon,
Ian Feur.
</P>
<P>
   SAN JOSE CLASH &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Head coach: Brian Quinn.
</P>
<P>
   1998 finish: 13-19 (33 points), fifth in the West.
</P>
<P>
   Top returning scorer: Ronald Cerritos (13 goals, 12 assists).
</P>
<P>
   Top returning players: Eddie Lewis, John Doyle.
</P>
<P>
   Key acquisitions: Raul Diaz Arce, Scott Bower, Richard
Mulrooney, Jimmy Conrad.
</P>
</TEXT>
