<HEADLINE>
MUSEUM IS TOLD TO HOLD AUSTRIAN ART
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By JUDITH H. DOBRZYNSKI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A state appeals court ruled Tuesday that the Museum
of Modern Art cannot return two Egon Schiele paintings to Austria
until a criminal investigation into their ownership is concluded.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling reversed the decision of a lower court, which had
allowed the museum to return the paintings, which it had borrowed
from the Leopold Foundation in Vienna.
</P>
<P>
   Manhattan District Attorney Robert M. Morgenthau is examining
charges that the paintings, confiscated from Jews by the Nazis, had
improperly made their way after World War II into the private
collection of Dr. Rudolf Leopold, a Viennese ophthalmologist, who
later sold them to the Leopold Foundation, financed by the Austrian
government.
</P>
<P>
   The Modern, which had borrowed the works for a huge Schiele
retrospective, had moved to quash a subpoena, and last May Acting
Justice Laura E. Drager of state Supreme Court in Manhattan had
granted its motion. She ruled that the works were protected from
seizure of any kind by New York state's 30-year-old Arts and
Cultural Affairs Law and that the subpoena was in effect a seizure.
</P>
<P>
   But Tuesday the appeals court ruled that the law did not apply
to criminal proceedings like Morgenthau's investigation. The court
disagreed with the contention of the Modern and other museums that
the law was intended to maintain the free flow of art without any
concern about legal challenges.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one disputes that intent,'' the ruling said, ``but it is
not contended, nor could it be, that the public interest is served
by permitting the free flow of stolen art into and out of the
state.''
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore, the ruling said, a subpoena requiring the Modern to
produce the paintings for the grand jury investigation does not
constitute ``seizure'' of them. It said that there was ``no
evidence'' in the subpoena that ``the two paintings will be sought
to be retained in custody.''
</P>
<P>
   After the ruling, Morgenthau said he felt ``vindicated.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We will continue to proceed with our investigation to see if a
crime or crimes have been committed,'' Morgenthau added. ``And the
paintings will stay at MOMA while the grand jury continues its
investigation.''
</P>
<P>
   At the Modern, Glenn D. Lowry, the director, called the ruling
``deeply troubling and disappointing.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This issue is a very important one that goes far beyond the
fate of the Schieles,'' Lowry said.
</P>
<P>
   The museum said it would appeal the decision.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
