<HEADLINE>
CREW, UNITED DRAW ATTENTION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRED J. ROBLEDO  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   There's no question, on paper at least, that two-time MLS Cup
champion D.C. United should be the class of Major League Soccer's
Eastern Conference again. Even so, the hottest ticket -- and the
hungriest team -- will be the Columbus Crew.
</P>
<P>
   The Crew's steady rise over the years (fourth in 1996, third in
'97 and second in '98), coupled with its new 22,500-seat
European-style soccer-specific stadium, should give the city of
Columbus a team to get excited about.
</P>
<P>
   The new stadium, which is set to open May 15 when the Crew plays
host to New England, will feature a much wider field than the
narrow confines of Ohio Stadium. That will give strikers Brian
McBride and Stern John, the best forward tandem in the league, more
room to operate.
</P>
<P>
   John, a native of Trinidad and Tobago, emerged from nowhere last
season to lead the league in scoring (26 goals, 5 assists, 57
points). He'll join McBride, Columbus' career scoring leader and
arguably the best striker the U.S. has to offer.
</P>
<P>
   Defensively, the return of veteran Mike Lapper from
reconstructive knee surgery and the arrival of the versatile Matt
Kmosko should bolster the Crew's back line.
</P>
<P>
   The question for United, obviously, is how will it do now that
Bruce Arena has left to coach the U.S. National team? How will this
franchise react after losing the Alan Rothenberg Trophy to Chicago
in the MLS Cup championship?
</P>
<P>
   The good news is that new coach Tom Rongen has proven
credentials after guiding Tampa Bay to the best record in the
league during MLS' inaugural season.
</P>
<P>
   United is still solid all-around, boasting striker Roy Lassiter
and Jaime Moreno on the front line.
</P>
<P>
   The league's top playmaker, Marco Etcheverry, returns, as does
1998 Rookie of the Year Ben Olsen, who has spent some time with the
U.S. National team recently.
</P>
<P>
   How this team does following the departures of U.S. veteran John
Harkes and Tony Sanneh depends on the additions of Diego Sonora and
Jason Moore.
</P>
<P>
   Bora Milutinovic, regarded as one of the best coaches on the
planet, has the task of trying to bring the New York/New Jersey
MetroStars their first winning season.
</P>
<P>
   Milutinovic, who has taken three teams (including the United
States in 1994) to the World Cup, took over the coaching reins late
last season. The MetroStars were swept in the opening round of the
playoffs by Columbus, however.
</P>
<P>
   Milutinovic went to work in the offseason, acquiring Costa Rican
standout Roy Myers and former Kansas City Wizards Mark Chung and
Mike Ammann.
</P>
<P>
   Eduardo Hurtado, the team's top striker, returns, as does
midfield presence Tab Ramos. The MetroStars lost a group of proven
veterans in Alexi Lalas, Giovanni Savarese, Diego Sonora and
goalkeeper Tony Meola.
</P>
<P>
   Here is a quick glance at the Eastern Conference and projected
finish of teams:
</P>
<P>
   agl,8.6,9 COLUMBUS CREW &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Head coach: Tom Fitzgerald.
</P>
<P>
   1998 finish: 15-7 (39 points), second.
</P>
<P>
   Top returning scorer: Stern John (26 goals, 5 assists).
</P>
<P>
   Top returning players: Brian McBride, Thomas Dooley, Brian
Maisonneuve, Andy Williams.
</P>
<P>
   Key acquisitions: Matt Chulis, Matt Kmosko.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON D.C. UNITED &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Head coach: Thomas Rongen.
</P>
<P>
   1998 finish: 24-8 (55 points), first.
</P>
<P>
   Top returning scorer: Jaime Moreno (16 goals, 11 assists).
</P>
<P>
   Top returning players: Marco Etcheverry, Roy Lassiter, Eddie
Pope, Jeff Agoos, Ben Olsen.
</P>
<P>
   Key acquisitions: Diego Sonora, Jason Moore.
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK/NEW JERSEY &QC; 
METROSTARS &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Head coach: Bora Milutinovic.
</P>
<P>
   1998 finish: 15-17 (39 points), third.
</P>
<P>
   Top returning scorer: Eduardo Hurtado (11 goals, 15 assists).
</P>
<P>
   Top returning players: Tab Ramos, Mike Sorber, Mike Petke.
</P>
<P>
   Key acquisitions: Mark Chung, Roy Myers, Mike Ammann.
</P>
<P>
   MIAMI FUSION &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Head coach: Ivo Wortman.
</P>
<P>
   1998 finish: 15-17 (35 points), fourth.
</P>
<P>
   Top returning scorer: Diego Serna (11 goals, 9 assists).
</P>
<P>
   Top returning players: Carlos Valderrama, Leo Cullen, Jeff
Cassar.
</P>
<P>
   Key acquisitions: Roberto Gaucho, Mario Gari, Jay Heaps, Dusty
Hudock.
</P>
<P>
   NEW ENGLAND REVOLUTION &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Head coach: Walter Zenga.
</P>
<P>
   1998 finish: 11-21 (29 points), sixth.
</P>
<P>
   Top returning scorer: Joe-Max Moore (7 goals, 15 assists).
</P>
<P>
   Top returning players: Mike Burns, Ted Chronopoulos, Imad Baba.
</P>
<P>
   Key acquisitions: John Harkes, Dan Calichman, Walter Zenga.
</P>
<P>
   TAMPA BAY MUTINY &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Head coach: Tim Hankinson.
</P>
<P>
   1998 finish: 12-20 (34 points), fifth.
</P>
<P>
   Top returning scorer: Mauricio Ramos (9 goals, 9 assists).
</P>
<P>
   Top returning players: Steve Ralston, Jan Eriksson.
</P>
<P>
   Key acquisitions: Alejandro Sequiera, Jefferson Gottardi, Scott
Garlick.
</P>
<P>
   -30-
</P>
