<HEADLINE>
INSTANT DECISION 
STILL DIZZY FROM `CAROUSEL'? 
JUST A CALDOR GUY FROM LEVITTOWN
</HEADLINE>
   (dal) 
 By JAMES BARRON with JOE BRESCIA   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Don King, the boxing promoter, was in the greenroom, waiting for
his turn in the guest's chair on the public-television interview
program ``Charlie Rose'' on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   On a television monitor he watched a segment being videotaped
with Leah Rabin, the widow of Yitzhak Rabin, who was assassinated
in 1995; their daughter, Dalia Rabin-Philosof, and their
granddaughter, Noa Ben-Artzi Philosof.
</P>
<P>
   They were talking about the Yitzhak Rabin Center for
International Studies in Tel Aviv and their campaign to raise $40
million for the center's educational programs for children of all
ages and backgrounds, including Palestinians and other Arabs.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately for the center, it was a long segment.
</P>
<P>
   King called down to his driver and told him to bring up the
checkbook. King wrote out a check for $10,000 and gave it to Mrs.
Rabin as she came out of the studio.
</P>
<P>
   ``He does things like that,'' King's spokesman, Howie Evans,
said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Still Dizzy From `Carousel'? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Drama League benefit on Monday provided more
drama than anyone had bargained for.
</P>
<P>
   As the mezzo-soprano Audra McDonald was finishing singing a
tribute to the Broadway-boosting talk-show host Rosie O'Donnell,
Miss McDonald fainted and tumbled off the stage in the ballroom at
the Pierre Hotel.
</P>
<P>
   She landed squarely on Miss O'Donnell's table.
</P>
<P>
   Someone called 911. Barbara Walters, who had been in the
audience, began delivering a medical bulletin over the
public-address system, telling the audience that an ambulance was
on its way and that Miss McDonald was up and walking. Miss Walters
went on to report that Miss McDonald had hyperventilated, then
fainted. Careful correspondent that she is, Miss Walters added,
``She also fainted for her audition for `Carousel,' and then won a
Tony.''
</P>
<P>
   Miss McDonald was admitted to Lenox Hill Hospital. Her manager,
Carol Yaple, said Tuesday that Miss McDonald had been released
after the tests were negative, though she was sore from the fall.
</P>
<P>
   Back at the benefit, Swoosie Kurtz and F. Murray Abraham read
from the script of ``Grease'' in the best Olivier or Barrymore
upper-crust accents. And Mary Tyler Moore, Diane Sawyer, Katie
Couric and Liz Smith danced in a number from ``Cabaret.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I was so self-conscious,'' Ms. Smith said later. ``I'm not a
performer. I don't know why they asked me. They just know I'm a big
ham.''
</P>
<P>
   Just a Caldor Guy From Levittown &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ One can take Billy Joel out of Long Island, but one
can't take Long Island out of Billy Joel. As he made clear
backstage at the Rock and Roll Hall of Fame induction ceremony at
the Waldorf-Astoria on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   First he praised his hometown of Levittown, the Long Island
community whose cookie-cutter houses were lampooned in the Malvina
Reynolds folk song as ``little boxes made of ticky tacky.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm from Levittown,'' he said after he was inducted. ``This is
not supposed to happen to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Then Joel, who turned ``Uptown Girl'' into a top-of-the-charts
hit, proved that he is no uptown guy. Madison Avenue? Not his kind
of place.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like shopping in Caldor's,'' he said. ``I know they're going
out of business. But they're having great sales now.''
</P>
<P>
   Not anymore. The Caldor in Bridgehampton, about 15 miles from
Joel's house in East Hampton, closed on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
