<SLUG> BC-FBN-EXPANSION-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LA AWARDED NFL FRANCHISE _ WITH A CATCH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN LYONS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ The city of Los Angeles was awarded the NFL's 32nd
franchise Tuesday, scheduled to begin play in 2002. But the
measure, approved by a 29-2 vote by league owners, comes with a
catch: The would-be ownership group must tighten up its financial
and stadium plans in six months or the expansion franchise will be
awarded to Houston billionaire Bob McNair.
</P>
<P>
   The league acknowledged Tuesday McNair has a proposal that is
more advanced than that of the two prospective Los Angeles
ownership groups. But the ``attractiveness,'' of the Los Angeles
market gave it a decided edge over Houston.
</P>
<P>
   ``You just can't deny the dynamics of the Los Angeles market, it
has the second-largest television market and it is the
entertainment capital of the United States, if not the world,''
said Carolina Panthers owner Jerry Richardson, who served on the
expansion committee as stadium committee chairman. Los Angeles is,
``a great place to host Super Bowls. I'd like us to go there for
more Super Bowls, but only when there is a team there.''
</P>
<P>
   Buffalo's Ralph Wilson and Oakland's Al Davis were the owners
who voted against the resolution.
</P>
<P>
   The league will begin deciding on an ownership group for the Los
Angeles franchise next month, when members of the expansion
committee meet to visit the two stadium sites, and check on the
involvement of the business community with each ownership effort.
</P>
<P>
   Yet officials close to the situation have said the league will
award the Los Angeles franchise to real-estate mogul Ed Roski and
construction giant Eli Broad. Roski and Broad already have an
exclusive agreement with the LA Coliseum for two years. They plan
to spend more than $350 million to make the facility
state-of-the-art. Such construction, Roski said, could be completed
before the 2002 season was to begin.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got a project together, the venue is great, and our
ownership team we've put together is ready to move forward,'' Roski
said. ``We're ready to go. They (NFL) would just like to come to LA
and spend some time to see how things are.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the other prospective ownership group, headed by
Hollywood superagent Michael Ovitz, has made preliminary plans to
build a $350 million stadium on a waste dump site in Carson, Calif.
They would still have to deal with the cleaning up of hazardous
wastes at the site, and highway infrastructure. Such a venture
would not be expected to be completed until after the 2002 season
began.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Los Angeles city councilman Mark Ridley-Thomas was in
Phoenix on Tuesday declaring his municipality was ready to get
behind the Roski-Broad ownership group.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're behind (Roski-Broad) and we believe (Ovitz) will join
forces with the people who are ready to make this happen,''
Ridley-Thomas said. ``And if Ovitz doesn't join with the program,
the show will continue to go on.''
</P>
<P>
   For now, that show has been postponed in Houston. It could be
canceled if the Los Angeles ownership group comes through before
the league imposed Sept. 15 deadline, or if no team decides to
relocate to Houston before McNair's exclusive rights agreement with
the City of Houston to build a partially public funded stadium ends
on Jan. 31, 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're still in this thing,'' McNair said, ``but certainly
there is a preference for Los Angeles. There is still a lot to be
done in LA There is not as much passion for football there is there
is in Houston.''
</P>
<P>
   The league is expected to vote on instant replay and the sell of
the Washington Redskins on Wednesday, the last day of the owners'
meetings.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
