<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Falcons add Bishop to line
 &HT;    By Len Pasquarelli
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ The Atlanta Falcons added depth and created
competition on their offensive line Tuesday, reaching agreement in
principle with unrestricted free agent guard Greg Bishop in a
two-year deal believed to be worth about $4 million.
</P>
<P>
   A fourth-round draft choice of the New York Giants in 1993,
Bishop started the past 64 games. He has played both left tackle
and right guard for the Giants and will be used at guard by
Atlanta. Richardson said the addition of Bishop will have no effect
on the future of incumbent starting right guard Gene
Williams.Expansion race
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles is in, at least for now, but Houston is not
necessarily out yet as the league voted Tuesday to add a 32nd
franchise for the 2002 season. By a 29-2 vote, owners approved a
resolution that gives Los Angeles until Sept. 15 to meet
predetermined criteria, including a stadium site, financing for the
facility and evidence of support from the business community. ``If
we get the issues resolved, then Los Angeles will have the
expansion franchise,'' said Denver owner Pat Bowlen, a member of
the finance committee. ``If not, we move on to Houston, which seems
to have its house in order.''
</P>
<P>
   Notable
</P>
<P>
   Commissioner Paul Tagliabue confirmed he has suspended 49ers
owner Ed DeBartolo for the '99 season and fined him $1 million for
his role in a scheme to get a gaming license in Louisiana with
ex-Gov. Edwin Edwards. ... Thanksgiving Day games will remain in
Detroit and Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
