<SLUG> BC-NJ-MEADOWLANDS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
$212 MILLION MAKE-OVER FOR MEADOWLANDS
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By CHARLES V. BAGLI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ Even as the Nets and Devils develop
plans for new arenas elsewhere in the state, the New Jersey Sports
and Exposition Authority on Tuesday proposed building a new $212
million home for the teams in the Meadowlands and replacing the
existing arena with a giant entertainment complex.
</P>
<P>
   The proposed basketball and hockey arena would be built
alongside Giants Stadium, while the 18-year-old Continental
Airlines Arena would be demolished. As part of creating what the
Sports Authority called a ``sports epicenter,'' the new retail and
entertainment complex would feature halls of fame, sports
restaurants like ESPN Zone, movie theaters and retailers like Nike
Town that allow patrons to try out the sporting goods.
</P>
<P>
   Even though the Sports and Exposition Authority, a quasi-public
agency that runs the sports complex, made an elaborate presentation
in describing its effort, the plan serves mainly as the
Meadowlands' opening bid in determining a future home for the Nets
and the Devils.
</P>
<P>
   It comes a week after John McMullen, the owner of the Devils
hockey team, released his own plan for a $350 million hockey arena
and entertainment complex in Hoboken. Raymond Chambers and the
other new owners of the Nets have said they intend to move the
basketball team to a new arena in Newark as part of a plan to
revive the state's largest city.
</P>
<P>
   ``There'll be discussions with the two franchises to see whether
this vision is part of their future,'' said Dennis R. Robinson, the
authority's president. ``I think this plan creates the ultimate
sports and entertainment destination that would benefit all the
teams. It's up to them.''
</P>
<P>
   If the Nets and Devils leave the Meadowlands, Robinson said that
the Sports Authority would still demolish the Continental Airlines
Arena and develop the retail and entertainment complex.
</P>
<P>
   Howard J. Rubenstein, a spokesman for the Nets, declined
comment. McMullen was out of town and could not be reached for
comment.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson said that Gov. Christie Whitman's first goal was to
insure that New Jersey remained home to the Nets and the Devils, as
well as the Giants, the Jets and the MetroStars soccer team, all of
which now play in the Meadowlands.
</P>
<P>
   In recent months, the Nets have tried to woo McMullen, but he
has steadfastly resisted any notion of moving the Devils to Newark.
Still, there are ample political and economic reasons for the teams
to cooperate, be it in Newark, Hoboken or the Meadowlands.
</P>
<P>
   Sports analysts say that an arena is economically viable only
when it is used by more than one team.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, it is unlikely that Whitman would provide
state aid for more than one arena. Although each project would
involve at least some private financing, the teams and the Sports
and Exposition Authority want the state to provide highway and
other transportation improvements.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't build two single-team arenas; the governor's pretty
firm about that,'' said Raymond H. Bateman, chairman of the
authority.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
