u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-FUNDRAISER-CO     03-16 0503
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-FUNDRAISER-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Just another meal at Gary's house
 &HT;    By Paul Reid
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEWALL'S POINT, Fla. _ Not since Aretha Franklin last dined
alone, has so much soul sat down to dinner.
</P>
<P>
   Willie Gary. The Rev. Jesse Jackson. Cris Carter of the
Minnesota Vikings. William Graves, bishop. The Drifters. They all
came to dinner at Gary's house.
</P>
<P>
   The house _ 50 rooms, three kitchens, 14 bathrooms and a worn
Bible in almost every room _ belongs to Stuart attorney Willie Gary
and his wife, Gloria. Gary has trod a long road from a shoeless
childhood in a two-room sharecropper's shack to his Sewall's Point
mansion. Tuesday night his path crossed with that of the president
of the United States. Bill Clinton came to dinner.
</P>
<P>
   So did some 250 Democratic party partisans who ponied up $2,500
apiece to join Gary and Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   These Democrats live large. Put a tent over Gary's patio Tuesday
night, and you'd have a revival meeting. Politics meets partying on
the St. Lucie River.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, Republicans enjoy life, but when you have Jesse Jackson
over there and Willie Gary here and William Jefferson Clinton in
the middle of the room, you have yourself a party.
</P>
<P>
   This guy lights up a room. The smile, the presence. He can shake
hands to his right, talk straight ahead and make eye contact to his
left. He's good. That's Willie. Gary.
</P>
<P>
   The President isn't half bad, either, at working a crowd. And
Tuesday night he was on. He's so good, he could walk into a
Republican caucus and walk out with endorsements.
</P>
<P>
   He and Gary spoke for more than 30 minutes and the crowd
responded, first with a scattering of ``Amen'' and then with more
and then, almost as one, as first Gary and then the President
sermonized on growing up poor.
</P>
<P>
   The speeches came after a dinner of roast beef with bernaise
sauce, asparagus, roasted potatoes and popovers stuffed with
chicken, all garnished with a sprig of thyme. White rose
centerpieces graced the tables and Turning Leaf merlot flowed
freely.
</P>
<P>
   Think what you will about the man and his politics, Bill Clinton
has a genius for working a crowd. And like it or not, working a
crowd is part of a president's job, whether it's a crowd of 200 or
200 million. You gotta move them. And does he ever. The Drifters
got this crowd primed and Willie Gary got them on their feet, but
Bill Clinton knocked them down.
</P>
<P>
   This is a man whose every secret has been aired in the public
square. With grace and good humor, he moved through Gary's home,
chin up, smile in place. If most presidents don't have much of a
private life, he has none. He was on display, X-rayed by 200 pairs
of eyes. More than a few people whispered, ``How does he do it?''
</P>
<P>
   Gary said that the President was among friends. And, Gary said,
he can count on this man as a friend long after he's out of office.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Reid writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
