<SLUG> BC-NY-BUDGET-NYT </SLUG>
  
 ALBANY DEMOCRATS URGE 4.6% BUDGET INCREASE  (dal) 
 By RICHARD PEREZ-PENA   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ The Democrats who control the Assembly called
Tuesday for a 4.6 percent rise in state spending, more than double
the increase Gov. George E. Pataki has proposed, setting the
boundaries for another fierce budget fight.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki assailed the Democrats' plan as irresponsible, raising
the prospect that like last year, he might veto most of the money
the Legislature adds to his proposed budget. Pataki has proposed a
$72.66 billion budget for the fiscal year that starts April 1,
while the Assembly Democrats describe their plan as $2 billion
higher.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the difference lies in the Democrats' rejection of
Pataki's proposed cuts in health care and education. Assembly
Speaker Sheldon Silver said his house's plan ``rejects the
devastating cuts that would have been funded on the backs of our
children and on the backs of working families and senior
citizens.''
</P>
<P>
   After an 8 percent increase in the budget last year, when he was
running for re-election, Pataki has called for a 1.8 percent rise
this year, vowing to keep the increase within the rate of
inflation, despite a $2 billion surplus.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats charge that the governor is trying to impress
conservatives in other states as he looks toward a possible
campaign for national office next year.
</P>
<P>
   The plan released Tuesday is just the Democrats' opening bid,
but the gap between it and the governor's proposal fed a growing
resignation here to the prospect of a late budget for the 15th
straight year.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki; Joseph L. Bruno, the Republican majority leader of the
Senate, and Comptroller H. Carl McCall, a Democrat, all predicted
Tuesday that a budget would not be passed by April 1.
</P>
<P>
   When asked about the Democrats' plan, Pataki said, ``We have not
seen anything to remotely justify the level of spending we're
seeing from the Assembly.''
</P>
<P>
   But Silver, a Democrat from Manhattan, said tax revenues were
growing so quickly that his plan would set aside $1 billion from
the current surplus for future needs and still run up an additional
$1.3 billion surplus next year.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate's Republican majority has not released a detailed
budget plan, but Bruno said Tuesday that his house would seek about
$800 million, or 1.1 percent, more than the governor, putting the
two houses $1.2 billion apart.
</P>
<P>
   Budget negotiations between the two houses are stalled on the
fundamental question of how much money is available, and have not
yet even touched on how it will be spent. Silver said he would name
members of budget conference committees on Wednesday, leaving just
two weeks in the fiscal year for the committees to strike deals.
</P>
<P>
   Until 1997, the governor and the two legislative leaders met
privately to reach a compromise budget. Then last year, the
Legislature met in conference committees to hash out a budget
publicly, without the governor.
</P>
<P>
   But Pataki demonstrated, by broad use of his line-item veto
power, that the new process had freed him from the need to
compromise, increasing his power over the budget.
</P>
<P>
   Silver says he remains committed to conference committees, which
rank-and-file Assembly members enjoyed because it gave them more
say in the process. But aides say he is still searching for a way
to avoid a repeat of last year, slowing talks with the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   The April 1 deadline carries new weight this year, because the
law passed in December that gave state officials a pay raise also
requires that legislators' salaries be withheld as long as the
budget is late. If the budget is more than a few weeks late, the
delay in being paid could present a serious hardship for many
lawmakers, adding to the pressure to reach a settlement.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
