A3234 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDIT-NY-POLICE-NYT &LR;      03-16 0549
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-NY-POLICE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: THE POLICE AND THE CITIZENS
</HEADLINE>
   (dal) 
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Wednesday, March 17:
</P>
<P>
   The civic muscle that holds New York City together suddenly
feels taut, strained by the danger of communities fracturing along
racial lines. The shooting of an unarmed West African last month by
four white policemen has focused these tensions among New Yorkers,
not only in the ordinary street and subway encounters but also in
official settings like One Police Plaza, where former Mayor David
Dinkins, Rep. Charles Rangel and others invited ceremonial arrests
on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Rudolph Giuliani labeled the Dinkins demonstration a
``great publicity stunt'' by his unappeasable political foes. But
he needs to look past the symbolism of these protests to the
substance behind them. There he will find a major test of mayoral
leadership that will weigh heavily in judgments about the success
of his administration.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani's first term was marked by a remarkable decline in
crime. But his second has seen a disturbing spike in tension
between police and the minority community and a sharp polarization
in black and white attitudes toward the police. A New York Times
poll released Monday found that nearly 9 out of 10 black residents
believe that the police often engage in brutality. Almost
three-quarters of the whites interviewed, by contrast, approve of
how the mayor is handling crime.
</P>
<P>
   This racial polarization is not an invention of the media nor a
public-opinion hiccup generated by a few publicity-seeking
activists. It is a serious civic lament that requires both private
and public leadership from the mayor. Giuliani's aides say that the
mayor has been working hard to defuse the issue in private. He has
publicly expressed regret about the shooting of Amadou Diallo, the
unarmed West African killed in a spray of 41 bullets on Feb. 4. He
has also given speeches admonishing police and police cadets to be
respectful to civilians.
</P>
<P>
   Even a task force report on police-community relations issued
after the torture of Abner Louima while in police custody has
survived the mayor's early mocking to become the structure for a
number of recent changes at the Police Department. Police
Commissioner Howard Safir now says that 84 percent of the task
force recommendations under his department's control have been
started or fully launched. Those changes include more diversity
training for police and focusing on how officers deal with the
public, as well as more contacts between police and community
leaders and extra programs for young people. A $10 million
recruitment drive aimed at city residents is expected to increase
the numbers of minority police.
</P>
<P>
   All these steps are positive, but something larger is needed. We
urge Giuliani to undertake a high-profile public campaign designed
not to refute his political rivals but to calm a diverse and
anxious city. He has moved in that direction with his speeches to
police and his demand that officers abandon the ``disrespectful
attitude'' that feeds charges of brutality and racism. But
sometimes true leadership requires bigger gestures, both as a way
of protecting a political legacy and a matter of calming tensions
of the moment. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
